<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE ARE NO GUARANTEES WHEN IT COMES TO JOB SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few days after the Teamsters and Associated Wholesale Grocers
reached an agreement that allowed the union workers to return to
their jobs, I received a plaintive note.
</P>
<P>
   The man who wrote would not be returning to the AWG warehouse.
He'd read the economic tea leaves earlier in the year, when the
company announced its intention to outsource management of its
warehouse operations. He'd foreseen labor strife and possible job
loss and elected to look for another job.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly found work elsewhere and thought he'd done a good
thing. But the labor impasse was broken after a few weeks, and his
former work mates got their jobs back, with back pay and raises.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately he regretted his move and asked if he could get his
job back, too. Yes, he was told, but because you quit, you've lost
your seniority and the preferable workhours that come with it.
You'll have to start over at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   So much for trying to plan ahead and ensure a steady income, he
ruminated.
</P>
<P>
   On a grander scale, this week's Justice Department announcements
dooming the WorldCom-Sprint merger may be causing similar second
thoughts among Sprint workers who have already jumped ship on the
expectation that their post-merger futures were rocky.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no sizable Sprint exodus, but a smattering of key
executives, would-be entrepreneurs and folks looking for what they
thought was a surer opportunity have left. Too much remains up in
the air to second-guess the wisdom of any departure.
</P>
<P>
   Workers who stayed the course, in both the AWG and Sprint
situations, have been buffeted by change, too. For them as well,
too much remains up in the air to second-guess the wisdom of
hanging tight.
</P>
<P>
   There is no blueprint, no right answer, no sure path to
financial and emotional security. Career choices and the outcomes
of those choices are as varied as the individual worker and the
individual circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional career advice says we should always have a Plan B
in mind. It says that we are responsible for our own paycheck
security, that the paternal corporation is dead. It says we should
plan ahead and leap before we are pushed.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no guarantee that if we leap, we won't regret it.
There's no calendar that dictates the exact right time to change
jobs. There's no promise that a new job will be better or more
profitable than the old one.
</P>
<P>
   Workers struggling with ``Do I stay?'' or ``Do I go?'' decisions
need to ask the kind of question that Ann and Abby ask their letter
writers. When someone asks the columnists for advice about staying
in or leaving a relationship, they often respond, ``Are you better
off with him/her or without him/her?''
</P>
<P>
   In love lives, as in work lives, the answer almost never is
known until after the choice has been made.
</P>
<P>
   That may frustrate people who want quick, clear direction, but
that's the way it is. The best any worker can do is research
options, weigh the ups and downs of either choice, and then work
hard to validate the choice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
