<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-INQUIRY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS BUREAU SEEKS MORE INFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Just when you thought all the questions had
been asked and answered, the Census is back.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Census Bureau sent questionnaires to 120 million
households, got 65 percent of them back and has since reached 99
percent of the rest of American families, it wants even more
information.
</P>
<P>
   About 700,000 households around the country, including some in
the Kansas City area, are receiving letters informing them they
would receive a ``supplementary'' questionnaire called the American
Community Survey.
</P>
<P>
   It covers the same social and economic topics included in the
long form of the regular Census.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials want to conduct that survey every year,
eventually replacing the long form. Fewer people would be
inconvenienced at one time, but the government would get a better
picture of the changing nation, instead of a snapshot every 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Census Bureau publication, ``Communities can use
the data to track the well-being of children, families and the
elderly; determine where to locate new highways, schools and
hospitals; show a large corporation that a town has a work force
the company needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Community Survey is being tested in 31 sites
nationwide, but if Congress approves it would be expanded to reach
every county by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The regular Census, conducted every 10 years, has two parts. One
is a simple head count to determine the number of seats each state
has in the House of Representatives. That is accomplished with the
short form and would continue once a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The other part, the long form, is used to distribute federal
money for housing, education, health and other programs. This year,
the amount is $185 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But spending decisions made in 1999 were based on data collected
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get under-counted, you're a loser throughout the
decade,'' regional Census Director Henry Palacios told The Star in
an interview this spring.
</P>
<P>
   With the annual survey, the government can extrapolate from a
sample of data collected each year to make spending decisions. The
survey can be changed, with questions added or deleted, to reflect
social and political trends.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 1 percent of the households that received a Census
short form this year also will be asked to fill out the additional
survey. No one who was randomly picked to receive the long form
this year is supposed to be tapped for the supplementary survey.
</P>
<P>
   Each month, a sample of households will be selected from a
master address file to receive the survey. If approved for full
implementation, 3 million households would be surveyed each year.
No household is supposed to be surveyed more than once every five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Census, participation in the American Community Survey
is mandatory. Answers are confidential. As with the regular Census,
households that do not respond will be contacted by Census workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
