<HEADLINE>
U.S. WILL PROVOKE SADDAM BEFORE ELECTION, EX-UNSCOM HEAD PREDICTS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 600-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By KIM SENGUPTA  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The new United Nations commission for arms
inspection in Iraq is likely to be used by the U.S. government to
trigger a confrontation with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein in the
run-up to the November presidential elections, a former U.N.
inspector claimed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Ritter, who resigned from the previous UNSCOM, said it was
commonly recognized in Washington and New York that the new
mission, under the chairmanship of Hans Blix, has no realistic
chance of being allowed into Iraq while sanctions and air strikes
by American and Britain continues.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq's blocking, he maintained, would be used by Washington as
an example of non-compliance to the U.N., leading the way to an
escalation of bombing without the U.N. Security Council being asked
to vote on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The former U.S. Marine Intelligence Colonel left his post with
UNSCOM in August 1998 after complaining that information covertly
gathered by the U.N. was turned over to the U.S. by the team's
chief Australian Richard Butler, and used in the bombing campaign
Operation Desert Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter was in London to address the inaugural meeting of the
Great Britain Iraq Society. The man once accused by the Iraqis of
being a CIA spy, now believes that the sanctions against Iraq are
doing nothing to damage Saddam's regime and only victimizing the
civilian population.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Independent Ritter accused the U.S.
government of hypocrisy, and Britain of acquiescing to this.
</P>
<P>
   He said that both government's knew Iraq did not now possess the
capability for using weapons of mass destruction, but the Clinton
administration was still pursuing a cynical policy for short-term
political gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new commission, UNMOVIC, will not be allowed into Iraq in
August, a month of primaries and three months away from the
election. You have got a vice president, Al Gore, trailing behind
in the polls and what better way to appear tough and switch
attention away to a so-called foreign threat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.N. Security Council did not vote on Desert Fox and we
can expect the same thing to happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. would not like to take unilateral action; it needs
Britain to give it in appearance of something multilateral,'' said
Ritter. ``And sadly, when the U.S. says jump, Tony Blair asks `how
high?'
</P>
<P>
   ``The ironic thing,'' he continued, ``is that the longer the
inspectors stay away from Iraq, the more time the hard-liners there
have to rebuild their weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intelligence services of the U.S., Britain and Israel
realize this, but there is nothing they can do while the U.S.
administration wants to keep Iraq as the whipping boy they can
wheel out at times of domestic difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritter has held extensive talks with congressmen in Washington.
He said: ``Both Republicans and Democrats accept the current policy
on Iraq is a mess. But it seems little will be done this side of
the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritter's strident criticism has led to the U.S. government
launching a FBI investigation into allegations that he had supplied
Intelligence to the Israelis. On the subject, Ritter said: ``That
started in 1996 and is still going on. It has cost me $120,000 in
legal fees so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``After endless requests the FBI finally agreed to meet me last
month. I am not demeaning their investigation, it is a very serious
issue, but I have nothing to hide.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
