<HEADLINE>
ALL BELCHER WANTS IS EQUAL TREATMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Umpire Mike DiMuro again refused comment Wednesday one
day after ejecting Anaheim Angels pitcher Tim Belcher from
Tuesday's game in the second inning, saying only that he filed his
report with the major-league office.
</P>
<P>
   Plate umpire DiMuro called a balk on Belcher after fake pickoff
attempts to third and first. The ruling was that Belcher crossed
the imaginary 45-degree line and stepped more toward home than
third, thus the balk. Belcher was ejected almost immediately after
running to confront DiMuro.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher and manager Mike Scioscia argued that Belcher did
nothing to deserve an ejection. But crew chief Brian Gorman said
Wednesday that arguing a balk is means for an automatic ejection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's frustrating in my mind is that pitchers
aren't afforded the same equality in arguing with the umpires as a
hitter is,'' Belcher said. ``That's always bothered me. A hitter
can see 16 pitches, bitch and complain on 13 of them and stay in
the game. A pitcher does it and the ump says, 'Get back on the
mound and pitch. Shut your mouth.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Why am I not allowed to disagree with a call? I'm not making
gestures and complaining on every pitch. They can do it, why can't
I?''
</P>
<P>
   __ Team meeting: Scioscia says he is not big on team meetings,
but he held one before Wednesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more of a communication guy, I talk to these guys every
day,'' Scioscia said. ``We went over a couple things, nothing huge.
I just wanted to refresh some things, go over some things. It was
not a chew-out meeting. The effort is there. It's just keeping
everybody on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said his chat centered on focusing on fundamental
baseball, things like playing aggressive defense and improving
situational hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We addressed some focus issues, some individual defense
issues, how we're going to approach the next six weeks,'' Scioscia
said. ``We want to make sure we're prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Defensive dropoff: With Jim Edmonds in center, Gary DiSarcina
at shortstop and Randy Velarde at second base, the Angels defense
up the middle used to be one of the best in the league. Now,
because of injuries and trades, it's Garret Anderson in center,
Benji Gil at shortstop and Adam Kennedy at second.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia, though, says it's unfair to compare Anderson with
Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could put Willie Mays out there and some people still
might like Jim Edmonds,'' he said. ``No one expects Garret to do
what Jim Edmonds did. But Garret has potential to be an outstanding
center fielder. For a guy that hasn't played out there a lot at the
major-league level, he's making strides every day.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Hatcher returns: Hitting coach Mickey Hatcher returned to the
team Wednesday after missing Tuesday's game so he could be with his
daughter, who had back surgery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
