<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUACKENBUSH-QUITS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARTHQUAKE VICTIMS FAULT COMMISSIONER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOMINIC BERBEO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ The resignation of Insurance Commissioner
Chuck Quackenbush was greeted with muted cheers Wednesday at the
epicenter of the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge Earthquake victims were glad to see Quackenbush leave
but skeptical whether his resignation would help settle their
insurance claims or whether he would be prosecuted for his charged
misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Allison, for example, said in only 10 seconds most of her
life was destroyed, yet six years later she hasn't been able to
piece it back together. She blames Quackenbush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm living with no hot water, no central heat in a tagged
house unfit to live in, for the past six years,'' said Allison, who
is battling her insurer for more than $749,000 for repairs on her
Northridge home damaged in the Jan. 17, 1994, temblor. ``I've lost
custody of my children. I don't know how much worse it could get.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with stories like Allison's and growing evidence that he
profited politically by reportedly misusing $12.45 million of
insurance settlement funds, Quackenbush resigned Wednesday,
effective July 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the decision Mr. Quackenbush has made is the
right one,'' said Assembly Speaker Bob Hertzberg, D-Van Nuys. ``The
facts gathered by this committee make clear that the commissioner
can no longer claim the public trust necessary to continue serving
in office.''
</P>
<P>
   The resignation prevents state legislators from impeaching
Quackenbush, but civil and criminal charges may still be pursued.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad because a lot of what (Quackenbush) has done can't be
undone,'' said George Kehrer, executive director of Community
Assisting Recovery Inc., which helps hundreds of quake victims who
say their claims were mishandled by insurers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the bright side is now the department can focus on the
real problem and figure out how to create restitution for people in
the Valley whose claims were mishandled. There were hundreds of
millions of dollars that could have gone toward restitution.''
</P>
<P>
   The scandal stems from the Insurance Department having
threatened insurance companies with $3.7 billion in fines for
mishandling thousands of Northridge Quake victim claims.
Quackenbush let a half-dozen insurers settle their cases by paying
a total of $12.45 million to the newly created California Research
and Assistance Fund, which then aired television public service
announcements for quake preparations featuring Quackenbush.
</P>
<P>
   The insurers, many of whom say they simply followed
Quackenbush's directive to pay into the fund, had little comment
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a difficult situation for all parties
involved,'' said Allstate Insurance spokesman Justine Schmidt.
``Allstate stands ready to do what we can to facilitate a smooth
transition as a new commissioner takes office.''
</P>
<P>
   Ric Hill of Woodland Hills-based 21st Century Insurance said the
company was ``looking forward to working with whomever the governor
and Legislature decide to appoint as the next commissioner.'' He
declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Messages left with other insurers were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is some of the best news I've heard in months,'' said
Rick Bennett, who lives at the Devonshire Village Condominiums in
Northridge, which sustained heavy damage in the magnitude-6.7
quake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The insurance companies no longer have an ally sitting up
there in Sacramento,'' Bennett said. ``I hope this means we'll see
thousands of mishandled cases reopened, including ours. But we want
to see him behind bars also, because what Mr. Quackenbush did was
worse than murder. What he did impacts tens of thousands of
homeowners.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandi Webb, a former Simi Valley City Council member who
launched a recall drive against Quackenbush earlier this month,
said more than 10,000 people downloaded a recall signature form
from the Web site of her group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a race between him quitting and us recalling him,''
Webb said. ``I'm surprised he lasted this long.''
</P>
<P>
   The Attorney General's Office announced Wednesday that it will
look into whether Quackenbush can be held personally liable for
repaying the $12.45 million in insurance settlements.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
