u s BC-BKN-DRAFT-NYT &LR;      06-29 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS GO TO HIGH SCHOOL TO GET MILES
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Most of his fellow draftees were pressing their
shirts and nervously waiting for their dry-cleaned suits to arrive
at the hotel. Darius Miles spent the anxious hours before Wednesday
night's NBA draft like most teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played Super Mario Brothers with my best friend,'' Miles
said. ``Video games, movies. Anything to kill the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids, they're so impatient. Miles had to wait only 18 years and
8 months to become the highest-drafted high school player. Taken
third by the Los Angeles Clippers before a few thousand stunned
fans at the Target Center, Miles stole the attention and thunder
from many of the other well-known prospects.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the Cincinnati power forward Kenyon Martin went No.
1 to the New Jersey Nets, and the Vancouver Grizzlies plucked
Stromile Swift out of Louisiana State as the second pick.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls chose Marcus Fizer of Iowa State, the power forward
who was thought to be going to the Clippers with the third pick, at
No. 4. Florida's Mike Miller went No. 5 to the Orlando Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's Cincinnati teammate, DerMarr Johnson, was taken No. 6
by the Atlanta Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing development of the night involved the Magic,
who dumped two of their lottery picks _ Nos. 10 and 13 _ and two of
their players to create salary cap room for the beginning of the
free-agent signing period that begins July 1. Tim Duncan and Grant
Hill may be pipe dreams no longer.
</P>
<P>
   Keyon Dooling, the No. 10 pick, was sent to the Clippers along
with Derek Strong and Corey Magette for a future first-round pick.
And the rights to the Magic's pick at No. 13, Courtney Alexander,
the nation's leading scorer out of Fresno State, were dealt to
Dallas for a future first-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   The draft again had a young flavor. After Martin, 10 straight
underclassmen were taken. DeShawn Stevenson became the 11th player
in the last five years to go straight from high school to the NBA
when the Washington Union (Fresno, Calif.) senior was selected 23rd
by the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of St. John's Erick Barkley at No. 28 by the
Portland Blazers broke the record for underclassmen selected in the
first round of the draft. Eighteen were picked, breaking the mark
of 17 set in the 1996 draft.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a record seven players born outside the United
States were drafted in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Garnett had been the highest-selected prep player when he
was taken fifth in 1995, but the 6-foot-9-inch, 217-pound,
wafer-thin Miles surpassed his idol, who plays for the hometown
Timberwolves. Walking to the podium with a radiant smile, Miles
wore an oversized gray suit and a gold hoop earring. He was so
excited about the selection, he hugged Stern and patted the
commissioner's graying thatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if I have a couple of good years, you guys will say
that's the greatest high school player ever to get picked,'' said
Miles, from East St. Louis High (Ill.), who became the 14th player
in the modern era to go straight to the NBA from high school. He is
the 10th high school player since Garnett was taken in 1995 to be
drafted in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's entrance was almost as electrifying. The highlight tape
rolled before he strode toward the podium in a Nets baseball cap.
Ducking inside for strong layups, rejecting shots or taking
alley-oop passes and throwing them down maliciously, he looked
great on celluloid.
</P>
<P>
   With Martin unable to work out for teams because he broke his
leg three months ago during the NCAA tournament, video was all the
Nets had to go on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenyon was the best player in the draft,'' Miles said. ``He
worked hard for four years in college. I'm just a high school
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   A teary-eyed Martin said: ``These last three months have been
outrageous for me _ knee-rehabbing and all that stuff. It's been
unreal. When they called my name it was like a sigh of relief. I
worked so hard for four years, and now I guess it's panning out for
me. I can't stop now. I have to get better from here and just move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, the consensus player of the year, became the third
senior chosen No. 1 overall in the past four years and the first
player from Cincinnati to be taken with the first pick. Oscar
Robertson was a territorial choice of the Cincinnati Royals in
1960, and thus was not eligible to be selected by any other team.
</P>
<P>
   Miles talked of how much a fan he was of Garnett and Chris
Webber, his two favorite players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at K.G. a little more because he was in the same
situation as me, and he went through the same things,'' Miles said.
``He's a great man and a great player. Hopefully, I can be a lot
like him.''
</P>
<P>
   He also did not say anything disparaging about the Clippers, the
losing franchise that has jaded some of the brightest and youngest
NBA stars over the past two decades. ``I think the Clippers are a
good, young team,'' he said. ``I feel we can develop as the years
go on, and hopefully we'll be a playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   If Miles beaming or Martin crying in the green room did not
qualify as the draft's most touching moments, then Mateen Cleaves'
going to Detroit as the seventh pick a few months after he led
Michigan State to the national title did.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves, a 6-2 guard, joined Morris Peterson, taken 21st by
Toronto, as the second group of teammates to be selected in the
first round after Martin and Johnson. ``I had to pinch myself when
we won it all, and I have to pinch myself now,'' Cleaves said.
``Seems like a fairy tale, me going home to Detroit. I'm going to
have to place a call to Grant and tell him to stay. I'd be honored
to be his teammate.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Mihm, the 7-foot Texas center, was taken seventh by the
Bulls, and the Michigan freshman Jamal Crawford was selected eighth
by the Cleveland Cavaliers. Shortly afterward, the two teams
swapped picks. The Bulls traded the rights to Mihm and an
undisclosed amount of cash for Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10, the Houston Rockets selected Minnesota
center Joel Przybilla. The Gophers sophomore, who quit school amid
the university's academic scandal, received a chorus of boos before
he took the podium to meet Commissioner David Stern. He was later
traded to Milwaukee for Jason Collier, the Bucks' No. 15 pick.
</P>
<P>
   Speedy Claxton of Hofstra was taken No. 20 by the 76ers. The
5-11 point guard wowed scouts at the pre-draft camps, including his
breathtaking two-handed dunk in Chicago last month that stunned the
gathering of general managers and coaches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 0033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
