<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-FUTURE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT FACES FALLING SHARE PRICE, GROWING QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo. _ As Sprint Corp. sifts through the remains of
its proposed sale to WorldCom, the questions on most people's lips
are: What happens to the company next, and how will it prop up its
sagging stock price?
</P>
<P>
   Many shareholders hope William T. Esrey, Sprint's chairman,
finds another suitor to buy the company. Sprint shares plunged
almost 10 percent on Wednesday, closing at 52 and 203//256, as
investors digested the news that they wouldn't be getting the
promised $76 a share for their Sprint holdings anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   The stock that tracks the company's wireless business, Sprint
PCS, fared a little better, dropping 4 percent, reflecting the loss
of the premium that WorldCom would have paid to PCS shareholders in
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, WorldCom shares rose 4 and 7//8 to 44 and 9//16.
Investors were apparently relieved, because they thought an
expensive deal with Sprint would put an anchor on WorldCom
earnings, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the drop in Sprint's stock Wednesday may have come as
traders who invested in Sprint betting the deal would go through
unwound their positions.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tom Burnett at Merger Insight, however, Sprint's
stock could possibly trade as low as the mid-40s before investors
settle in and wait for the next deal to happen.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom and Sprint have not officially called off their
marriage yet, but to go forward they would have to make a valid
argument for the merger in court, observers say. The temptation is
probably there, considering the speed at which the long-distance
market is being opened to the regional Bell companies.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Bell, for example, hopes to get approval Friday to
enter Texas' long-distance market, and on Wednesday asked Missouri
regulators to let it provide long-distance to customers in that
state.
</P>
<P>
   But considering the time, expense and uncertainty of the outcome
of a court case, they companies won't likely go that route,
observers say.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Justice's lawsuit seeking to block the
WorldCom-Sprint deal, filed Tuesday, ``effectively means the deal
will not go through,'' said Tim Horan, an analyst with CIBC World
Markets, in a research report.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union joined the Department of Justice on
Wednesday, announcing that it was formally blocking the deal, even
though the companies withdrew their application to merge on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   European competition commissioner Mario Monti explained that his
agency ``felt compelled'' to act as the companies have yet to
formally cancel their merger agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Many expect the companies to formally announce that they're
scrapping their deal later this week, or after the Fourth of July
holiday, and then hold a conference call with analysts to reassure
Wall Street about their prospects going forward.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of the deal is a big blow to Esrey. A former
investment banker, he reportedly engineered the WorldCom deal in
the first place, playing WorldCom Chief Executive Bernard J. Ebbers
off BellSouth Corp. to win a premium most analysts thought huge at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey could have pointed to that premium as the crowning
achievement of a successful 15-year stint at the helm of Kansas
City's largest private employer.
</P>
<P>
   And he certainly feels the financial pain of the deal's
collapse. He personally owns or has options on hundreds of millions
of dollars worth of Sprint stock.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the deal is collapsing, Esrey is also watching a flow
of senior executives leaving Sprint with millions of dollars in
vested stock options in hand.
</P>
<P>
   So how much pressure does he face to bring about another merger?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not under any extreme pressure, not enough to do
something desperate,'' Burnett said. ``There will be plenty of
traffic between Atlanta and Germany'' to assess interest from
potential suitors BellSouth and Deutsche Telekom, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the stock holds in the 50s, he'll have time to right the
ship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Righting the ship probably means selling the company eventually,
analysts say. But that may not come for months as Esrey explores
his options.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Comack, an analyst with Guzman &AMP; Co. in Miami, doubts
that BellSouth is still interested in a Sprint deal, despite its
$100 billion bid for the company in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have changed,'' he said. BellSouth has ``entered into a
joint venture with SBC for wireless services and established a
partnership with Qwest, who will haul their long distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've moved on and are going out with someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, some say a deal with Deutsche Telekom will face
difficulties. The German government still owns a large chunk of the
former state monopoly, and any bid for an American company would
doubtless raise hackles in Washington. One senator, Fritz Hollings
of South Carolina, has already proposed legislation barring such a
foreign purchase. If Telekom is allowed to bid, it might prefer an
alliance with Qwest, as that company owns part of KPN Qwest, a
fast-growing Internet backbone in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Others point to less traditional partners for Sprint, along the
lines of the Time Warner//America Online merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who it would be exactly, but the options that are
out there are kind of exciting,'' said John Hoffman, a former
senior vice president with the company. ``Sprint's always been a
trailblazer, an innovator. Now may be the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
