<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-PROTESTORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAPD PROTESTS PLAN FOR DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Staff Writer Rick Orlov contributed to this report.) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Warning they expect violent protests at the
Democratic National Convention in mid-August, top LAPD officials
urged the City Council on Wednesday to rescind its plan to turn
over Pershing Square to up to 50,000 demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Police are braced to make mass arrests of renegade protesters
and anarchists and prepared to get backup from 40 other local
enforcement agencies and the National Guard if needed, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fully expect to be involved in mass arrests and civil
disturbance,'' said LAPD Cmdr. Tom Lorenzen, head of the DNC
Planning Group. ``We anticipate a level similar to that which we
saw in Seattle, if indeed not more intense.''
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle during the World Trade Organization meeting, police
arrested 660 people as 50,000 protesters, many of them anarchists,
caused $2.5 million in damage to downtown businesses. National
media captured scenes of protesters smashing storefronts, blocking
city streets and defying officers clad in riot gear and armed with
rubber bullets and tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   Lorenzen and Police Chief Bernard C. Parks warned the council
that anarchist groups already are planning to demonstrate before
the convention, which will be Aug. 14-17 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Parks told the council that city, state and federal law
enforcement agencies have been planning for a year for the
convention and will be prepared to protect the delegates, other
visitors and residents.
</P>
<P>
   He said the city can ask the Sheriff's Department to mobilize
more than 40 police agencies in the county if necessary and that
the governor can be called upon to send the National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Parks and Lorenzen showed the council an 11-minute video of
scenes from violent protests in other cities this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city may regret that it ever voted to bring this
convention here, because you invited a lot of things here that you
didn't think about,'' said Councilman Hal Bernson of Granada Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Parks and Lorenzen told the council that 6,000 LAPD officers
have been trained in mass arrests and crowd control and that
commanders and top-ranking officials will be dispersed throughout
the city to make on-the-spot decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But Parks also urged the council to reconsider last week's
designation of downtown's Pershing Square as a demonstration zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our No. 1 mission here is to make sure that the people who
live and work here continue to have free access to their city,''
Parks said. ``We believe it is a major problem for us,
security-wise, to create a formalized demonstration area.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the City Council agreed to a demand by Councilwoman
Jackie Goldberg to designate Pershing Square as a protest area
before she cast the deciding vote for a $4 million city bailout for
the convention.
</P>
<P>
   But with several members saying they had security concerns, the
council voted Wednesday to forward the Pershing Square matter to a
newly created ad-hoc committee on the Democratic National
Convention, which will be chaired by Councilman Alex Padilla of
Pacoima.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg agreed to send the issue to the committee but scolded
her fellow council members for what she called ``underhanded and
cheap'' tactics.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the protests in Seattle and in Washington, D.C.,
during an International Monetary Fund meeting earlier this year,
Los Angeles civic leaders and merchants have questioned the choice
of Pershing Square, which is in a congested downtown area adjacent
to the jewelry district.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Mayor Richard Riordan offered assurances that
the police will be able to handle any demonstrations during the
convention as he defended their actions at the disturbances
following the championship victory by pro basketball's Los Angeles
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were absolutely right,'' Riordan said of the LAPD
decision to not immediately step in. ``If you compare us with other
major cities that have won major championships ... we had 11 minor
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the restraint shown by officers, we stopped the violence
from escalating. We had a strategic plan and it worked. The problem
is TV focused on a few bad things but didn't show the overall
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan also said the city is prepared in other aspects for the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a wedding and we have made preparations (for) ...
cleaning up the city,'' Riordan said. ``We have people from the
flower mart who will be putting out millions of flowers on the
streets. Los Angeles will be the most beautiful bride the world has
ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
