<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSROOM-DOWNSIZING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SHOWS TRADEOFF IN REDUCING CLASSROOM SIZE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Students in smaller classes outperformed their
peers in larger settings but teacher quality has deteriorated since
the state reduced primary grade class sizes, a study released
Wednesday shows.
</P>
<P>
   A consortium of educational research groups studying the
four-year-old program found that the number of California students
in reduced-size classes who performed at the national median or
greater was about one to four percent higher than the number in
larger classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a small increment, but it is significant,'' said George
Bohrnstedt, senior vice president for research at American
Institutes for Research.
</P>
<P>
   Groups conducting the state-commissioned study, which cost
$500,000, include the American Institutes for Research, RAND and
Policy Analysis for California Education.
</P>
<P>
   The state's class-size reduction program, launched in 1996, pays
districts $800 per student enrolled in a class of 20 or fewer in
kindergarten through third grade.
</P>
<P>
   The program was implemented quickly, according to the study, and
by last year, more than 92 percent of California students in
primary grades were in classes of 20 or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   But that progress has come at a cost, the study found. As
districts scrambled to fill the new classrooms created by
class-size reduction, they resorted to hiring more underqualified
teachers without full credentials, or with less education and
experience.
</P>
<P>
   They also found the problem of underqualified teachers went
beyond the grades where class-size has been implemented. Because
there are better-paying professions and high demand for workers in
other industries, finding qualified and experienced teachers for
all grade levels grew more difficult for schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tight labor market in California and the competition for
workers is having its toll on qualification of teachers at the
secondary level as well,'' Bohrnstedt said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Unified School District board member Valerie Fields
said that while the district did implement class-size reduction in
those lower grades, right now the district's space shortage is a
more important concern. The district needs to build at least 150
more schools during the next decade to accomodate a surge in
enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Facilities is a higher priority because we're stuck at this
point,'' Fields said. ``It's hard to reduce class size any more
because we don't have any place to put them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, recalling her days as a teacher in some West San Fernando
Valley schools, she said reducing class size makes a ``huge
difference'' in student achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Since the state reduced class sizes, the percentage of fully
credentialed teachers statewide in kindergarten through third grade
dropped to 86.6 percent last year, down from 98.2 percent in 1995,
according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   Becki Robinson, a vice president of United Teachers Los Angeles,
argued if districts would offer better salaries, more teachers
would stay in the profession, reducing the need to hire
underqualified personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If salaries were higher, you'd have people who are now going
into other professions (choose teaching),'' Robinson said.
``Because teaching does not pay them enough to support their family
in the way they'd like to be able to support their families.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7941 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      06-29 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL INDEPENDENCE ISN'T OFTEN ACHIEVED THROUGH A QUICK FIX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Americans prepare to celebrate Independence Day, many might
be well advised to stop a moment and reflect on what it takes to
gain financial independence.
</P>
<P>
   Last Independence Day, many stock investors no doubt thought
their financial independence would be secured by a euphoric Nasdaq
market that was making them richer by the week, at least on paper.
That was then. This is now.
</P>
<P>
   Dreams of early retirement may remain realistic for some, but
many others have been brought back to unpleasant reality by the
gut-wrenching price plunges suffered by high-tech and dot-com
stocks since the March massacre. The worst appears to be over, but
confidence is still shaky as all stock markets continue to back and
fill.
</P>
<P>
   Drat. Just when a carefree financial existence seems within
reach, the economics gods intervene to remind us that gaining
financial independence isn't as easy as a bull market makes it
appear.
</P>
<P>
   So, how do you achieve financial independence?
</P>
<P>
   Slowly.
</P>
<P>
   It has been said that compound interest is the one true miracle
of human existence. The best example is how much you would
accumulate if you saved a penny today, and doubled the amount saved
each day for a month. A penny today, 2 cents tomorrow, 4 cents the
day after, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Before reading further, try to imagine what a nest egg would
grow to if a penny investment doubled every day for a month:
$10,000? $100,000? Half a million dollars? A million dollars?
</P>
<P>
   Most people guess far too low when confronted with this
question. The answer is $10 million. What makes this staggering
amount so difficult to fathom is that with barely a week to go in
the month the sum still wouldn't have grown to $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   But, such is the phenomenon of exponential growth.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it's unlikely any of us will find an investment that
doubles our money every day. However, even modest compounded
interest rate yields will create impressive gains over a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Financial independence doesn't have to depend on a highflying
stock market, either. A story concerning Groucho Marx, who is said
to have lost a bundle in the stock market, is instructive. After
losing a considerable fortune in stocks, Marx began putting all his
money in Treasury securities because they were the safest
investment on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Back when Treasuries yields were historically low, a friend
chided Marx, saying, ``Treasuries don't pay anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They do if you've got enough of them,'' Groucho replied.
</P>
<P>
   How do you get enough of any form of savings or investment?
</P>
<P>
   Each and every time you receive money in any form, you put some
of it away where it can benefit from compound growth.
</P>
<P>
   During the 20th century, those who put their money in stocks did
better on average most of the time than those who put their money
elsewhere. But those who weren't comfortable with stock market risk
also did quite well for themselves _ well enough, certainly, to
have retired with a reasonable degree of financial independence.
</P>
<P>
   The habit of thrift has succumbed to consumption for many
Americans in recent years, but achieving financial independence
always has more to do with deferring gratification than picking a
hot stock or hitting the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   It all has to do with setting goals and sticking with your plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 0039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
