<SLUG> BC-SOUTHWESTERN-BELL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHWESTERN BELL AGAIN SEEKS TO PROVIDE LONG-DISTANCE IN
MISSOURI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Southwestern Bell Telephone Co. went back to
Missouri regulators Wednesday asking for permission to sell
long-distance services to its local telephone customers throughout
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bell has filed for such approval before and come up short in
proving to regulators at the Public Service Commission that its
local markets were open to competition _ the condition it needs to
meet before being allowed to offer long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it has since addressed the problems regulators
found, evidenced by Texas regulators' approval of the company's
application to offer long-distance service to customers in that
state.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Justice has approved the Texas application,
and the company expects that the Federal Communications Commission
will give its final approval Friday. If it does, Texas will become
the second state in which a Bell company is allowed to offer
long-distance service, after Bell Atlantic in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of long-distance competition by the regional Bell
companies was one point given in favor of letting WorldCom acquire
Sprint _ the deal the Department of Justice sued to block Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Bell had to pass a 14-point regulatory checklist to
get approval in Texas. That checklist assessed the company's
ability to process orders for service and repairs in a timely
manner and the capacity of operational support systems.
</P>
<P>
   Bell is required to resell parts of its network to competitors,
and regulators want competitors' customers to get the same service
as Bell's customers.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of the company's operational support systems was
independently tested in Texas, and the company says they are the
same ones used for Missouri, Kansas and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   The staff at the Missouri commission has recommended hiring
Ernst &AMP; Young to validate that the data being collected by
Southwestern Bell to measure its performance are accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Bell says local-service competition in the state
already is robust. It reports that it has dozens of competitors in
its local markets in Missouri _ 16 that have their own equipment
and 22 that resell Bell services. Collectively, it says, those
competitors serve 287,000 access lines, or 9.7 percent of the
overall access lines in its territory.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of those lines are business customers, but Bell
contends that competitors are serving customers out of 90 percent
of its wire centers, meaning they are not just concentrated in big
cities while ignoring rural customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Service Commission has yet to set a procedural
timetable, but an action might be taken on the matter by Dec. 1.
The matter would then go before the Justice Department and the FCC,
which makes the final determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally, if they meet all the standards, they should get
in'' long-distance, said Martha Hogerty, Missouri's public counsel.
``But we have to be careful to make sure they meet the standards,
and once they're in that there are strict penalties there to
prevent backsliding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
