<HEADER>
A7945 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-TIFFANY-MISSING-KAN &LR;      06-29 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIFFANY-MISSING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIVES AWAIT WORD ON MISSING GIRL LINKED TO ROBINSON
INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Tiffany Stasi's biological grandmother poses
the most modest of requests of the teen-ager that authorities
suspect to be the long-missing girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want her to know we're here, we're her family, and we
love her,'' said Pat Sylvester. ``I don't want to disrupt her life;
I just want to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany disappeared when she was just a 4-month-old baby and her
mother, Lisa Stasi, was only 19. According to investigators'
reports, Lisa Stasi was lured from a battered women's shelter by
John E. Robinson Sr., who is accused of being a serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   The young mother has not been seen for 15 years. Neither, at
least by the name she was given at birth in Kansas City, has
Tiffany.
</P>
<P>
   But now sources familiar with the investigation surrounding
Robinson say detectives believe a teen-ager being raised by a
family known to the murder suspect could be Tiffany.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Wednesday they have yet to go to her father,
Carl Stasi, asking for medical evidence to confirm the girl's
identity. He declined an earlier request for a blood sample,
routinely made to relatives of the missing women tied to Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not feel comfortable saying we know who that young lady
is,'' said Capt. John Meier, a Lenexa police officer working on the
Robinson case. He added that authorities wanted to be careful not
to raise false hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Stasi has talked earlier about yearning to see his
daughter, but on Wednesday referred questions about Tiffany to his
attorney. The attorney could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Stasi's aunt, Karen Moore, last saw the young mother
shortly before she met Robinson, who then was promoting what turned
out to be a bogus program for unwed mothers. Lisa was separated
from Carl at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, investigative reports compiled at the time said, made
promises of job training and housing. Later he would tell
detectives she left suddenly for Denver with a new boyfriend. He
produced typewritten letters with her signature, but family members
have said she did not type and that the tone of the letters did not
strike them as authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Moore recalled a young woman in late 1985 eager for a brighter
future and who saw hope in what Robinson promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was real excited and thought she was going to start a new
life for her and her daughter,'' the aunt said. There was no hint
that she might voluntarily give up her child.
</P>
<P>
   Now Moore longs to see the child again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these (adoptive) parents of Tiffany's were victims, we
can't change the past,'' she said. ``We can't destroy this little
girl's life by taking her away. We just want her to know how many
people are here that love her.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore is curious about the neighborhood where the girl lives,
the parents who have her in their care and the life she leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all just so concerned about her,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvester, the grandmother who has never seen more than pictures
of Tiffany as an infant because she lived in a different state,
learned in The Kansas City Star Tuesday that authorities had strong
leads about her granddaughter's whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years she had trouble maintaining that her daughter
was still alive, but, for whatever reason, nurtured the thought
that Tiffany was in good hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always assumed that the baby would be OK and prayed that
it was raised in a good family,'' she said. ``Anytime a baby is
taken, I don't know, I just think that a family will take care of
her and love her.''
</P>
<P>
   Sylvester hates to contemplate that the people raising her
granddaughter might have a connection to the man suspected in her
daughter's disappearance. And she's had enough tragedy in her life:
a husband who died while Lisa was still in elementary school, a son
who committed suicide, and a daughter and grandchild gone for 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to wait and find out if this is Tiffany,'' she
said. ``We can only pray.''
</P>
<P>
   Angela Moore, Karen's daughter and a cousin of Lisa Stasi's who
lived with her for six months, joined the family in an evening of
prayer about Tiffany this week. That produced a poem.
</P>
<P>
   ... For the sight, just one small peek
</P>
<P>
   For the answers, we all seek.
</P>
</TEXT>
