<HEADER>
A7946 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     06-29 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BROKEN LEGS CROSS PATHS ON NETS' DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The shattered leg never healed the way
it had to, but you got the impression Wednesday that Jayson
Williams was suffering more from a broken heart. When the Nets
announced his retirement via conference call, the man who talked
nonstop and without peer for much of the previous decade was not on
the line, or even in state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jayson's in Arizona,'' said Rod Thorn, the Nets' new
president, who didn't add that Williams was said to be shopping for
a winter home in Phoenix. Strange, but true: 10 years ago, Williams
was drafted by the Suns, a New York kid who didn't hide his
displeasure and later lobbied his way east.
</P>
<P>
   Most retirees tend to participate in their own valediction, but
the Nets were never good with secrets, the word was already out and
the team apparently had to clear one broken leg from the roster to
make room for another.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be a closure about it,'' Thorn said, before
opening up Wednesday night's draft by selecting Williams'
frontcourt replacement in recuperation, the University of
Cincinnati's Kenyon Martin.
</P>
<P>
   It was, even after taking the source into account, a strange
sequence of events, making official such sobering news hours before
the Nets would invite season ticket holders into the Meadowlands
Champions Center to share in their good lottery fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Good, not great. As it was the last time the Nets landed the
first pick in the NBA draft, there was no player to name this
lottery after. Eerily enough, it was also a decade ago when David
Stern stood up at the Jacob Javits Center to announce, ``With the
first pick of the 1990 draft, the New Jersey Nets select Derrick
Coleman.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year retrospective on that pick is a rousing
whoop-de-damn-do. Coleman came with character questions that were
answered soon enough. Besides Martin's broken right leg _ which the
team doctors have examined and are swearing on a stack of old Nets'
yearbooks will not be a problem _ there is the issue of his tepid
performance before his senior season, in which he averaged 18.9
points and almost 10 rebounds. As late as Martin's junior year, the
numbers were 10 and 7. ``You're talking about a young man who got
better every year,'' Thorn said, providing _ what else? _ the
sanguine spin.
</P>
<P>
   There are scouts who claim that with the exception of the truly
gifted, the Tim Duncans, rating an experienced college big man has
become a most daunting task. ``By the time he's a senior, the
question is, `Who is he playing against?''' one scout said
Wednesday. ``Most of the really good players have already gone. A
kid like Martin is 22 years old playing against guys who are either
much less talented or 18 year-olds whose bodies are not as
developed. How does he do when everyone is at least as talented and
big?''
</P>
<P>
   We'll see, but it's a shame the Nets had the vacancy in the
first place. Williams, a power forward, was the team's
center-by-default until he was injured during the 1998-99 season.
The mishap was a classic Nets' disaster, Williams entangled with
the newly-acquired Stephon Marbury, the lockout-shortened season
already lost. While everyone including his mother tended to the
point guard, Williams rolled over in agony, comforted by the
front-row ticket holder Danny Aiello.
</P>
<P>
   Some people thought Jayson Williams was more actor than player.
It would be hard to dispute that it was more fun to listen to him
than to watch the Nets' teams he anchored. Yet it is equally
important to remember that the Nets acquired Williams for two
second-round draft picks, as a replacement for the immortal Terry
Mills. He was more than a late-blooming rebounding force. He became
that rare contemporary athlete who wanted to tell everyone how
fortunate he was.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, a Nets' official related a story by
telephone about how a young boy with cancer had visited the locker
room, right after a chemotherapy treatment. While meeting some of
the players, he turned nauseous and, in trying to keep from
vomiting, began to choke. While the other players backed away,
Williams realized what was happening, swept the boy into his arms
and nearly knocked John Calipari down on his way to the trainer's
room.
</P>
<P>
   The line went quiet, and, after a few seconds, I realized the
official was quietly weeping.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had that effect on people. He could make you laugh or
cry. He was no heralded star but he was a steal. With the first
pick in the entire draft, you hope for something more than a
rebounder with heart, but if Kenyon Martin ever fills Jayson
Williams' shoes, the Nets should be thrilled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
