<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 YOU CAN DUCK, BUT YOU CAN'T FLY  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Chuck Quackenbush is stepping down in order to
avoid testifying.
</P>
<P>
   He needs to be verrry careful when he steps down, because that's
a very squishy mountain of bull doo he's stepping down from.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush will avoid any potentially unpleasant scolding from
our state's legislators by copping the traditional playground
basketball mea culpa plea of ``My bad.''
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Quackenbush has vowed to ``devote the rest of my
life to finding the real cheaters.''
</P>
<P>
   The scandal is a severe blow to Quackenbush's political career.
With the systematic lying and cheating now on his record, the only
job he has a chance of landing is president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It's an interesting glimpse into politics. So far, the only
person who has been reprimanded or accused of a crime is
whistle-blower Cindy Ossias, who will probably lose her job because
she was the only honest, honorable and courageous person in the
insurance commissioner's office. Take a lesson, kids.
</P>
<P>
   Since insurance companies could have been fined up to $3 billion
for screwing earthquake victims, and Quacky let 'em off the hook
for $12 million, they paid 1/250th of what they should have paid.
That's a quarter of a cent on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   How could Quackenbush afford to give such great discounts?
Volume, volume, volume.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S OFFICIAL: Everyone who reads this paper is aware that when
hatters went mad, it was due to mercury poisoning, not inhalation
of glue fumes, as I first wrote, nor lead poisoning, as
subsequently stated here.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is a rare correction correction, and it can be fun and
educational for all of us.
</P>
<P>
   Hatters (they make men's hats; milliners make women's hats)
rubbed mercury into the felt hats to aid in the shaping and
finishing. Inhalation of the mercury fumes, and mercury absorption
through the skin of the hands, eventually led to loss of motor
control, drooling, severe twitching and other bad stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hayward says that if you were to drink a shot of mercury
and stand still for a while, the stuff would come out the bottoms
of your feet. That trick will either kill you or get you a great
laugh at a party, whichever comes first.
</P>
<P>
   WHY BIG STARS never starve to death:
</P>
<P>
   About 9 p.m. last Saturday, the restaurant 23 Ross Common in
Ross got a call. Table for eight? Sorry, can't do it? Oh, it's for
Sean Penn and friends? Come on in.
</P>
<P>
   So Penn (a ``23'' regular), Jack Nicholson, Kevin Spacey,
producer Peter Allen and four others took over a corner of the
restaurant and stayed 'til way past closing time.
</P>
<P>
   They ate everything chef-owner Bob Montuori knows how to cook,
and when the other customers had gone, they broke out cigars and
port. Nicholson picked up the tab.
</P>
<P>
   The big scoop: According to one of the group, the big four are
``working on a project together.''
</P>
<P>
   WHILE SLAVING away on a Stairmaster at the gym, Barbara Weiss
glanced at the TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jean Claude Van Damme was rolling around with a bad guy who
was clutching a hypodermic syringe. The closed caption read,
`Yelling and strunting.' Do you know what that means?''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, that's what I'm doing after five minutes on the
Stairmaster.
</P>
<P>
   I understand Van Damme does all his own strunts.
</P>
<P>
   YET ANOTHER true-life, TV-related adventure:
</P>
<P>
   Jessie Gordon was doing a crossword while watching TV when a
mouse ran to the middle of the living room rug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured if I scared him, he'd run away and show me where he
got in. I threw my pen at him _ and knocked him out cold!
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran and got an empty coffee can and piece of cardboard, and
as I was dumping him outside, he looked around as if to say, `What
the hey?' Now I know how he got out, but not how he got in.''
</P>
<P>
   And you named the mouse Steve Young, right?
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, I phoned Young the other day to tell him how
gracefully I thought he handled his going-away ceremonies. And
Steve commented, ``I retired from  &UR; what? &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   FANS RIOTED in Los Angeles when the Lakers won the NBA title,
and officials expressed concern over the LAPD's ability to handle
riots at the upcoming Democratic national convention.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Day wonders, ``Why are they worried about riots? The
Democrats are nominating Al Gore, for God's sake. Who's going to
riot over that? The Cardboard People from Planet Corrugated, where
Gore is a deity?''
</P>
<P>
   Your point is duly noted, Terry, but police presence will be
vital at the convention. Cops will drive around with lights
flashing and sirens blaring, trying to keep people awake.
</P>
<P>
   THE DREADED glassy-winged sharpshooter is invading Northern
California, threatening the wine industry.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of financial devastation, this is the most dangerous
insect to hit the state since the classy-wingtipped sharpdresser,
more commonly known as Chuck Quackenbush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
