<HEADER>
A7956 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-ABORTION-POLIT     06-29 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-ABORTION-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: REACTIONS TO ABORTION RULING REFLECT POLITICAL
STRATEGIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 2nd, 16th grafs to clarify)  
(With SCOTUS-ABORTION) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The strikingly different reactions to the Supreme
Court's ruling on abortion Wednesday underscore how Vice President
Al Gore is trying mightily to catapult the court into a
front-and-center issue in the presidential campaign, while Gov.
George W. Bush wants the matter to fade from the political horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the court announced its 5-4 decision striking down
Nebras- ka's ban on the type of abortion that opponents call
partial-birth abortion, Gore upended a planned talk in Blacklick,
Ohio, about the environment and energy, and instead opened his
remarks by warning that the unexpected closeness of the vote
demonstrated the importance of electing a president who would pick
justices who would protect abortion rights. He said nothing about
the late-term abortion procedure addressed by the court.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Bush made no mention of the broader makeup of the
court, though he did upbraid the justices for not upholding the
right to ban what he called ``the brutal practice'' of late-term
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The contrasting strategies _ and remarks from the two rivals _
reflect differing political imperatives. The Bush strategy is to
make the abortion issue go away, and, for his campaign, the timing
of Wednesday's ruling is not propitious. The last thing the
Republicans want one month before their nominating convention is
another spectacle that turns rancorous over abortion. Not only
that, the ruling comes as Bush is mulling over whether he dares
pick a running mate who favors abortion rights and how he can
finesse the issue in the party platform.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore wants to do whatever he can to keep the matter alive _
and paint Republicans as riven by internecine squabbles over
abortion. Gore officials have been waiting gleefully for months in
anticipation of Wednesday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst news that the Bush campaign could get,''
said Ann Stone, national chairwoman of the Republicans For Choice
PAC. The closeness of the court ruling, she said, gave Gore a fresh
hook to declare that abortion rights may be endangered, and to
shore up his sagging support from women.
</P>
<P>
   Richard N. Bond, the former Republican Party chairman who for
years has counseled the party to not let itself split over
abortion, said the best thing Bush could do was to keep a low
profile on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll try to paint Bush as risky, extremist, out of touch,
intolerant,'' Bond said of Democrats. ``I don't think Bush is going
to take the bait on this. What can a presidential candidate do
about a Supreme Court decision?''
</P>
<P>
   As if on cue, Gore put out fresh bait. He seized on the ruling _
and another that gives states greater leeway to restrict
anti-abortion demonstrations outside health clinics _ and tried to
reignite the abortion issue in the Republican Party. For months, in
speech after speech, Gore has warned that religious conservatives
like Patrick Buchanan and Jerry Falwell would ratify prospects for
the bench if Bush is elected.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Wednesday: ``The next president will nominate at least
three and probably four, perhaps four, justices to the Supreme
Court. One extra vote on the wrong side of those two issues would
change the outcome and a woman's right to choose would be taken
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Gore recalled that Bush has said he respects
Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, both of whom were
dissenters in the decision Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Air Force II on Wednesday night on a flight from Columbus,
Ohio, to New York, Gore stepped up his attack, asserting that Bush
was determined to overturn Roe vs. Wade, which affirms a woman's
right to an abortion. ``His views about choice are really quite
extreme,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was also on script, asserting at a news
conference here that the court's stand on abortion was ``very much
in the balance, depending on what appointments are made in the next
four years.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no surprise that Bush, in his remarks, failed to mention
the prospect of vacancies on the Supreme Court. While conservative
groups have trumpeted the balance of the court as a high-stakes
voting issue, Bush almost never raises it on the stump. He does not
want to put off moderate and swing voters who may support abortion
rights. He also knows, perhaps, that usually only the most partisan
voters think about the makeup of the court.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bush told supporters in Cleveland, ``I hope to be able
to come up with a law that meets the constitutional scrutiny. And,
unlike Al Gore, I pledge to fight for a ban on partial birth
abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling is discouraging for Bush and many Republicans
not only because it gives Gore another rationale to talk about the
court. In addition, the Republicans' embrace in the last few years
of eliminating late-term abortion allowed the party to maintain its
anti-abortion position in a way that is more palatable to many
voters than suggesting overturning the Supreme Court's
constitutional rationale allowing abortion. Even many Democrats who
favor abortion rights tell pollsters they object to late-term
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   But with Wednesday's decision, it may be difficult for
politicians like Rep. Rick Lazio, a Republican who is running for
the U.S. Senate from New York, to declare that he favors abortion
rights but voted to prohibit some late-term abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will no longer be credible for politicians to claim to be
pro-choice while supporting these abortion bans,'' said Janet
Benshoof, president of the Center for Reproductive Law and Policy,
which represented the doctor in the Nebraska case.
</P>
<P>
   Another complication is that some Republicans have already begun
debating whether they should keep language in the party platform
that applauds efforts ``to sign into law an end to partial birth
abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to energizing Democrats, Wednesday's ruling may
embolden conservatives, some of whom want Bush, like Gore, to turn
it into a rallying cry to discuss the court itself. But in their
determination that Bush capture the White House, they are reluctant
to press him to be outspoken on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like him to aggressively criticize the decision and to
say how important it is that we have judges who respect innocent
human life,'' said Phyllis Schlafly, the prominent anti-abortion
advocate. Asked if Bush should raise the abortion issue more, she
said, ``I don't know that he has to make it the first thing he
talks about at every stop. There's so much to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bill Graves of Kansas put it this way: ``Many Republicans
are prepared to put aside differences on abortion and other issues
in exchange for the greater good _ the election of George Bush as
president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
