<HEADER>
A7958 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-CLINTON-CONFERENCE-SF     06-29 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONFERENCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CLINTON USES BULLY PULPIT TO EXTOL GORE AT PRESS CONFERENCE  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, with just over half a year
remaining in his own presidency, spent the better part of an
hourlong news conference Wednesday advancing Vice President Al
Gore's bid to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton dismissed Gore's sagging poll numbers, defended him
against allegations of campaign finance wrongdoing and insisted
that the vice president's association with the ``bogus'' scandals
of his own administration will do him no harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still more likely than not that he will win,'' Clinton
said in response to repeated inquiries about Gore's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   The news conference in the White House East Room was Clinton's
first in three months and covered a range of topics from relations
with Cuba to the high price of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he supports the concept behind a GOP bill to lift a
trade embargo on food and medicine sales to Cuba, but rejected the
suggestion of normalizing relations with the Caribbean republic.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he supports trade with regimes in China, North Korea
and Russia, yet not Cuba, Clinton angrily recalled the downing of
two planes belonging to an anti-Castro group over Cuba in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of these other countries you mentioned, none of them _ none of
them _ by order of the leader of the country killed, murdered ...
two airplanes worth of people,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was lukewarm to the suggestion that the federal
government repeal an 18-cent-per-gallon gasoline tax to compensate
for soaring prices, saying that to do so, congressional leaders
would have to decide what highway projects they would be willing to
do without.
</P>
<P>
   With just a few months left before Congress adjourns for the
year, Clinton urged passage of his own legislative priorities,
including a patients' bill of rights, a $2 an hour minimum wage
increase, gun control laws, hate crime legislation and more money
for schools.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign of his own dwindling presence in the national
political spotlight, the reporters kept returning to questions
about the campaign between Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to doubts often expressed by Democrats about Bush's
intellect, one questioner asked Clinton how important ``command of
facts and plain old brain power'' are to the job of being
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a dead-bang loser, isn't it,'' Clinton said with a
laugh. ``No matter what I say, I'm in a big hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton passed on the opportunity to knock Bush, saying: ``I
don't think it's so much a question of intelligence, generically.
... I think it's much more a question of curiosity and willingness
to learn what you think is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared confident and relaxed for most of the midday
event, however he grew defensive when someone asked whether Gore's
slip in the polls might in part stem from his association with the
administration's scandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me remind you that a lot of these ... so-called scandals
were bogus,'' Clinton said, specifically mentioning the charges
against Mike Espy, the former secretary of Agriculture, and Henry
Cisneros, the former Secretary of Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you all know that the Whitewater thing was bogus from day
one,'' he added pointedly. ``So the word `scandal' has been thrown
around here like a clanging teapot for seven years.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made no mention of the Monica Lewinsky scandal, which
led to Clinton's impeachment in 1998. No reporters brought it up.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Gore did the right thing last week in releasing the
123-page transcript of his testimony with Justice Department
attorneys regarding Democratic Party fund raising in 1996 and
expressed doubt that a special prosecutor is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Lavishing praise on the vice president, Clinton said ``no person
in the history of the republic has ever had the positive impact on
this country as vice president than Al Gore has had.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton recounted the difficulties that previous vice
presidents, including Richard Nixon in 1960, Hubert Humphrey in
1968, and George Bush in 1988, had emerging from the shadow of the
president. But he said that after this summer's political
conventions, Gore and Bush will emerge as the ``main players on the
stage of American political life.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon and Humphrey each lost their elections.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he has made any decisions about what to do after he
leaves the White House in January, Clinton said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll run for the school board someday,'' Clinton said.
``That's about the only thing I can imagine doing. I don't have any
other plans. I just want to be a good citizen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
