<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7959 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-QUACKENBUSH-RESIGNS-S     06-29 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUACKENBUSH-RESIGNS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALIFORNIA INSURANCE COMMISSIONER RESIGNS UNDER PRESSURE  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush resigned
Wednesday to avoid testifying under oath about using money from
insurance company settlements for his own political activities.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush did not receive any deals in exchange for his
resignation _ which is effective July 10 _ and a criminal and civil
probe by the Attorney General is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either through intention or neglect, the Department of
Insurance committed unacceptable abuses of power during Mr.
Quackenbush's tenure as commissioner,'' said Assemblyman Jack
Scott, D-Pasadena, chairman of the Assembly Insurance Committee.
``I take no joy in the ruin of a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush's capitulation ended a months-long legislative
investigation into the activities of his department.
</P>
<P>
   Hearings conducted by the Assembly Insurance Committee revealed
that Quackenbush coerced insurance companies into paying $12
million to nonprofit foundations he created. The payments allegedly
allowed the insurers to avoid paying as much as $3.7 billion in
fines for improperly handling policyholders' claims after the 1994
Northridge earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   The payments to the foundations were used to promote the
Republican commissioner's own political agenda, and none of the
money went to earthquake victims.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush, 46, was one of only two statewide-elected
Republicans, and his demise is a blow to the GOP's prospects in
future state elections.
</P>
<P>
   He sent a letter announcing his resignation to Secretary of
State Bill Jones _ the other statewide-elected Republican _ shortly
after noon Wednesday. The letter said simply, ``I hereby resign my
position as insurance commissioner of the state of California
effective July 10, 2000.'' He left his lawyer's office without
commenting to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis has the authority to appoint a successor, who
will then need to be confirmed by both houses of the Legislature.
That individual will serve out Quackenbush's term, which ends in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Davis released a statement promising to ``name someone of
unquestioned integrity, with the ability and experience to restore
credibility to this important office.``
</P>
<P>
   Still pending is Attorney General Bill Lockyer's criminal and
civil probe of the operations of the department and foundations
Quackenbush established.
</P>
<P>
   ``No deal was offered by my office to Mr. Quackenbush, and none
is contemplated,'' Lockyer said. ``Our investigation of the
Northridge insurance settlements and related Department of
Insurance actions will continue without delay. If crimes have been
committed by anyone associated with these actions, my office will
take action to see to it that they are prosecuted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sacramento County district attorney's office is also
investigating the matter, and the Fair Political Practices
Commission may investigate Quackenbush's use of campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer has shut down one of the earthquake foundations and
frozen its assets. The civil lawsuit filed against Quackenbush on
behalf of taxpayers demands the return of the money diverted from
the general fund and into the foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the victims of the earthquake will ever see restitution
for their claims is unclear. There is a movement in the Legislature
to reopen all claims, but how any payments might be made has not
been determined. Quackenbush's lawyer said Wednesday that the
commissioner did not do anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done nothing criminal or illegal,'' said Donald Heller, a
prominent Sacramento defense attorney. ``Mistakes were made, as he
fully admitted. But he felt that in light of the level of this
controversy and the paralyzing effect it has had on the Department
of Insurance, he was left with no choice but to resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush's resignation came two days after a senior
department official testified that he was told to make a $4 million
settlement with a title insurance company because the commissioner
``needed $4 million for a media buy.''
</P>
<P>
   The official, Robert Hagedorn, said he was told by two members
of Quackenbush's executive staff that the insurance chief made the
demand.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Insurance Committee then told the two staffers _
Norris Clark and Brian Soublet _ that they would be given immunity
and forced to testify, said Assemblyman Fred Keeley, D-Boulder
Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Both men confirmed to the committee that they were in the room
when Quackenbush made the statement in March and would have
testified to the fact before Quackenbush took the stand Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As these facts became known, Republicans in the Legislature told
Quackenbush that resignation was the only way to avoid impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Assembly Republican leader Scott Baugh of Huntington
Beach told state Sen. Jim Brulte, R-Rancho Cucamonga, that he heard
Quackenbush would plead the Fifth Amendment to avoid
self-incrimination in Thursday's planned testimony.
</P>
<P>
   If Quackenbush did so, Baugh told Brulte that GOP Assembly
members would move to impeach.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something this egregious happens on your watch, you can't
walk away from it unsullied,'' said Republican Assemblyman Ken
Maddox of Garden Grove, the vice chairman of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Grounds for Impeachment
</P>
<P>
   Because Quackenbush had previously denied any knowledge of the
foundations' operations, admitting now that he had any knowledge
would also have been grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Brulte met with Heller and said that if Quackenbush
was considering resigning, he should do so before the Assembly's
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Heller said Wednesday the comments Quackenbush made about
needing the money for a media buy were not what they seemed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That testimony was correct as to what was said, but there was
a far greater context,'' Heller said. ``It is consistent with what
he has said in the past about seeking to do outreach to underserved
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Heller said Quackenbush never planned to take the Fifth
Amendment. He also said the commissioner plans to cooperate with
Lockyer in any way he can.
</P>
<P>
   The July 10 resignation date was chosen to allow Quackenbush
some time to finish up some business, some of which would not be
able to be accomplished over the holiday weekend, Heller said.
</P>
<P>
   Many hope to see a successor named quickly, because one of
Quackenbush's top aides _ Michael Kelley _ would be left in charge
once he is out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on our hearings, I have no confidence in him,'' Keeley
said. Speculation on possible appointments by the governor began in
earnest Wednesday. Some thought Davis would not want another
elected official to be given such a prominent spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This governor would be more likely to appoint a caretaker than
an elected official,'' said one lawmaker who asked for anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   One Capitol insider said, ``The governor probably does not want
competition for insurance industry campaign contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other names have surfaced as possible appointments to
the post.
</P>
<P>
   One is U.S. Rep. Gary Condit, D-Ceres, who is close to Davis and
has created a state political action committee for a possible run
at statewide office.
</P>
<P>
   Another is state Sen. Patrick Johnston, a moderate Stockton
Democrat with nearly 20 years of legislative experience on a
variety of insurance issues.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston is leaving the Legislature in December because of term
limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the governor asked, I'd be honored to serve,'' Johnston
said. ``In the little world of the Capitol, the names people think
of are people that work here, but it's a big state.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Jackie Speier, D-Hillsborough, has previously
expressed interest in the job, but Wednesday said she didn't know
if she wanted the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do know the job I will do is work to reform the department
through the Legislature, and I really haven't thought much farther
than that,'' said Speier, chairwoman of the Senate Insurance
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee intends to hold more hearings,'' she said.
``We're going to transform that department into one of the best in
the nation as it relates to consumer protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Assembly Insurance Committee also promised that
reform would take place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merely changing the occupant of the office is not enough if
there are structural conflicts of interest inherent in the
office,'' said Assemblyman Tom McClintock, R-Northridge. ``There is
a need for substantial institutional reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Greg Lucas contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
