<HEADER>
A7961 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-MEXICO-LABASTIDA-SFCH     06-29 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-LABASTIDA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANDARD-BEARER FIGHTS TO PRESERVE PRI POWER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ To understand why Francisco Labastida may soon
rule Mexico, one has to understand what he is not.
</P>
<P>
   He's not a rabble-rousing populist, and he's not an Ivy
League-educated technocrat. He's not corrupt (at least as far as
anyone seems to know); he is not a member of any of the governing
party's quarreling factions, and he's not an enemy of anyone in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, he has been chosen by the world's most
long-lasting political machine, the Institutional Revolutionary
Party (PRI), to be its leader.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's national elections, if the public opinion polls are
correct, he could eke out a razor-thin victory to become Mexico's
next president.
</P>
<P>
   He is the man of the machine. To tens of millions of Mexicans,
that is reason to vote for him _ or against him.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Graciela Urroz and her co-workers at a Labastida rally
in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI knows how,'' Urroz said. ``It has the experience, it
helps the average people get ahead. That's why most people support
him, er, whatshisname?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Labastida,'' a friend chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labastida, right, I trust him. He's the best candidate by
far.''
</P>
<P>
   Urroz and her companions are government workers from Mexico
state, just outside the capital city. They had been bused to a
recent PRI rally in Mexico City's central Zocalo square by their
union, which is tightly linked to the PRI and has turned out its
members to vote for the party since before most of its current
members were born.
</P>
<P>
   But squeeze your way 10 yards through the tightly packed crowd
in the Zocalo and ask the guy selling chewing gum about Labastida.
He grins and hisses, ``I'm just working here. I'm not one of these
 &UR; acarreados. &LR; '' The slang word, used only by PRI opponents, is
loosely translatable as ``trucked-in-ones,'' or ``rent-a-crowd.''
It refers to the PRI's practice of coercing vast numbers of people,
ranging from government workers and union members to peasants, to
attend its rallies and vote for its candidates.
</P>
<P>
   A special congressional commission has filed dozens of
complaints with Mexico's attorney general, charging that the PRI is
illegally using federal programs to gain support and is turning
some government workplaces into virtual campaign headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Independent election monitors say Labastida's recent rise in the
polls _ he was behind in some surveys until a month ago and is now
ahead by a few percentage points in most _ is due to the PRI's
reliance on such coercive measures.
</P>
<P>
   At the Mexico City rally, Labastida rushed through a short
speech emphasizing that the PRI, and only the PRI, could guarantee
``change with direction'' _ controlled, cautious change rather than
the destabilizing lurches that he said would take place under
opposition rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either we all go forward, correcting what hasn't worked and
making changes with direction so that people live better, or we'll
all go backward. I have no doubt. Never backward, no way, never,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's voice, a reedy tenor, excited almost no one in the
crowd, but it did the trick. Although Mexican intellectuals and
political analysts _ most of whom openly or covertly support his
opponents _ disparage him as a wooden campaigner lacking in
charisma, Labastida has been effective on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   His speeches are carefully crafted for audiences ranging from
Mexico City bankers to Oaxaca Indians to Veracruz oil workers, and
they carry a sense of competence and earnestness.
</P>
<P>
   In smaller, more informal settings, Labastida can be even more
engaging and impressive. Drawing on his background as a lifelong
bureaucrat and politician _ a government economist, governor of
Sinaloa state and Cabinet minister in charge of the Agriculture,
Energy and Interior departments _ he can switch topics
extemporaneously from child nutrition to farm supports to oil
exploration, mixing minute details with broad rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   As a man of the PRI system, he is frequently savaged by
opponents as yesterday's hack. ``Labastida represents the worst of
the official party system, a network of corruption, repression and
arrogance,'' said leftist challenger Cuauhtemoc Cardenas in a
typical attack.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas and other critics say Labastida's background shows
little evidence that he would carry out bold reforms as president.
</P>
<P>
   For example, during his 1998-99 stint as Interior secretary, a
position that directs the government's powerful systems of
patronage and political and police control, his accomplishments
were gradual and piecemeal. His pressure for clean voting produced
local elections free of major claims of fraud, but he failed to
solve the standoff in the southern state of Chiapas, where
Zapatista guerrillas have been holed up in the jungle since their
1994 rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also point out that drug violence, including car
bombings and assassinations, intensified in Sinaloa state during
his 1987-92 tenure as governor. But Labastida contends that not
only did he fight the drug traffickers, they even shot up his car
and tried to kill him. Because he had received death threats, the
PRI named him ambassador to Portugal when his term as governor was
over to get him out of harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida and his advisers have read enough polls to realize
that after 71 years of often-corrupt, authoritarian PRI rule, most
Mexicans want change. Some of the advice has come from U.S.
campaign strategists such as James Carville, President Clinton's
former adviser, whom the PRI hired to help poll voters and shape
political messages.
</P>
<P>
   Like Democrats in the United States, Labastida has focused on
the issue of education, saying he will lengthen the grade school
day by two hours daily and raise teachers' salaries. Taking a page
out of Cardenas' campaign manual, Labastida has constantly
criticized President Ernesto Zedillo's free-market, free-trade
policies, saying he would concentrate on supporting domestic
industries rather than exports.
</P>
<P>
   If much of this agenda echoes the old, nationalist PRI,
umbilically linked to government largesse and power, Labastida is
eager to reinforce the impression. While the reform-oriented
Zedillo repeatedly has advocated a ``healthy distance'' between the
party and the presidency, Labastida calls for a ``healthy
nearness.''
</P>
<P>
   On the streets, this sort of rhetorical ``change'' seems to play
well. ``Whatever he says, I love it,'' Urroz said as the Mexico
City rally broke up. ``It's what we need.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 0119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT &LR;      06-29 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGERS MAUL YANKEES, 13-6 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ If their names were not Jeter, Cone, O'Neill, Williams
and Torre, no one would take them seriously anymore. If not for all
their World Series rings, they would be written off as contenders.
</P>
<P>
   This is what would be said about the New York Yankees, if not
for the pedigree: their pitching is terrible. They cannot catch the
ball. Their offense is sterile. This is what would be said about
the Yankees: they stink.
</P>
<P>
   They have the big names, however, the rings, the pedigrees and,
even after games like Wednesday night's, in which Detroit crushed
four homers among eight extra-base hits and destroyed the Yankees,
13-6, you figure that it is only a matter of time before they
rebound and at least play adequately. But with each successive
defeat, they are moving closer to being defined by this prolonged
slump.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Ford made his fourth professional start for the Yankees on
Wednesday night and lasted only two batters into the third inning,
and by then the score was one-sided, another game lost. The Yankees
have dropped 26 of their last 41 games, and are three games out of
first place in the American League East, behind the Toronto Blue
Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is a rookie. Andy Pettitte will start Thursday on only
three days' rest, and the Yankees do not know who will pitch Friday
_ they are hoping Jason Grimsley can step in as an emergency
starter _ or on Saturday or Sunday; maybe Orlando Hernandez and
Roger Clemens, or maybe not. Ramiro Mendoza will miss at least two
more weeks, and David Cone is healthy but he has not won since
April 28.
</P>
<P>
   This is the state of the Yankees' pitching staff. In the 40
games leading to Wednesday night's defeat, the Yankee pitchers
allowed 378 hits and 160 walks in their last 3502/3 innings, an
average of 1.53 runners an inning. They accumulated a 5.03 earned
run average.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers got much worse Wednesday night. Detroit's Tony
Clark lined a two-run double in the first inning. Brad Ausmus
tripled to right field to lead off the second, and manager Joe
Torre elected to position the infield in, in an attempt to pinch
off the run.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, the Yankees played their infield back with a
runner at third in the 11th inning, and as a result, the winning
run scored on a soft grounder hit to shortstop. But with the
infield in Wednesday night, Juan Encarnacion dumped a blooper over
second, the ball falling between second baseman Chuck Knoblauch and
right fielder Paul O'Neill. Ausmus scored, and O'Neill, disgusted,
threw the ball into the ground furiously.
</P>
<P>
   Two more runs scored in that inning. The Yankees trailed by 5-0,
their frustration was heightened and, really, the best they could
hope for at that point was that Ford could get back on track and
pitch a few more innings and save the bullpen from early abuse.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford did not do this. Clark smashed a home run to open the
third inning, and after Ford walked Dean Palmer, Allen Watson was
summoned from the bullpen. The left-handed Watson was crucial to
the Yankees last season, after being acquired in July, but this
year he has struggled. He walked Ausmus with one out before
Encarnacion launched a three-run homer, and after Deivi Cruz's
single, Luis Polonia lined a home run into the bullpen in right
field.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
