<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 METS WIN 7th STRAIGHT GAME AS ROCKER AND BRAVES LOOM  
 By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The purpose of the roof that went up over the bench
in the visitors' bullpen at Shea Stadium on Wednesday night was not
to protect the Florida Marlins relievers. It is a Rocker Roof, and
when the New York Mets are host to the Atlanta Braves on Thursday
night, it will shield the notorious John Rocker from harm.
</P>
<P>
   Before that happens, though, the Mets had one more meeting with
the Marlins prior to their four-game showdown with the Braves, who
hold a two-game lead over them in the National League East. And so
the first reliever to emerge from the left-field fortress Wednesday
night was Ricky Bones; the Mets should not expect Atlanta's
relievers to be so generous.
</P>
<P>
   Called in with the bases loaded and his team holding a two-run
lead in the sixth inning, Bones could not halt a sudden outbreak of
wildness and sloppy play that helped the Mets earn their seventh
victory in a row, 6-5, before a crowd of 37,252.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Penny, the Florida starter, had walked three of his last
four hitters, the last walk forcing in a run, when Bones was
summoned. But Bones walked Derek Bell to bring in a run, and then
got Mike Piazza to ground toward the hole between short and third.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Andy Fox could not field the ball, and the Mets tied
the score at 4-4 on the error. Mark Johnson then lashed a two-run
single to left that gave the Mets a 6-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose two-run homer was a crucial blow in Monday's
victory over the Marlins, was making his first start since being
recalled from Triple-A Norfolk. He was a late addition to the
lineup, starting because of lingering soreness in the right
shoulder of third baseman Robin Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, who injured the shoulder diving for a ball on Sunday,
acknowledged the soreness before the game but said it was unrelated
to off-season surgery. Ventura walked as a pinch-hitter in the
sixth inning and was replaced by a pinch-runner, pitcher Mike
Hampton. Venture is listed as day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura was resting because of injury, but two healthy Mets
regulars did not start.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, when Manager Bobby Valentine met with reporters
and was asked about the Braves, he seemed bemused. The Marlins were
Wednesday night's opponent, he said. Protestations aside,
Valentine's lineup was obviously more fit for fourth-place Florida
than first-place Atlanta. Edgardo Alfonzo and Todd Zeile were out
of the lineup for routine days off.
</P>
<P>
   Either one could have been used in the fourth inning, when the
Mets had the bases loaded and one out and Valentine let his
starter, Bobby J. Jones, hit for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Jones struck out, and then the leadoff hitter, Melvin Mora,
grounded into a force-out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets trailed by 3-1 at that point because of a bases-empty
home run by Cliff Floyd and a two-run shot by Mike Lowell.
Florida's first hitter in the fifth, Paul Bako, stroked a double
and scored on a single by Luis Castillo, increasing the Marlins'
lead to 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was coming off his best start of the season, an
eight-inning, one-run victory over Pittsburgh. He allowed four runs
on seven hits in six innings Wednesday night, but evened his record
at 3-3 when the Mets broke out for five runs in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Penny struck out the first two hitters in the sixth, but he
walked Benny Agbayani and allowed a single to Kurt Abbott. Ventura
then walked, and Mora's walk brought the Mets within 4-2, before
Bones entered, and the Mets went ahead for good.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins provided a scare in the seventh, when Preston Wilson
laced a two-out, run-scoring single off Dennis Cook to cut the
Mets' lead to 6-5. Pat Mahomes relieved Cook _ who tossed a towel,
shook his head and muttered to himself on the bench but escaped the
jam by getting Lowell to fly out.
</P>
</TEXT>
