<HEADER>
A7966 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-MEXICO-FOX-SFCHRON &LR;      06-29 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FOX-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICK CHALLENGES MEXICO'S LONGTIME RULING PARTY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUANAJUATO, Mexico _ Late last year, when Vicente Fox needed to
hire a manager for his presidential campaign, he did something
shocking.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking with age-old Mexican political tradition, he didn't
fill the position from among his top aides or longtime associates.
Nor did he pick one of his political party's experienced campaign
operatives. Instead, Fox, a former manager of Coca-Cola's Mexico
operations, went to a corporate headhunter.
</P>
<P>
   After dozens of interviews, he chose Pedro Cerisola, a top
executive for Telefonos de Mexico, the national phone company.
Cerisola had never met Fox, had no election background and was
completely unknown in politics.
</P>
<P>
   The result? By nearly all accounts, Fox's campaign has been
well-run and flexible, boosting Fox to his current position near
the top of most polls and at the top of at least one.
</P>
<P>
   All this, his backers say, is an example of what sort of
president Fox would be _ efficient and beholden to no one. After 71
years of political cronyism and corruption under the Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI), they argue, Mexico needs a new way of
doing things.
</P>
<P>
   But that also scares many people, for whom Fox remains
unpredictable, an opportunist who talks out of both sides of his
mouth. His opponents _ Francisco Labastida of the PRI and
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of a left-of-center coalition _ lambaste him as
``arrogant,'' ``reactionary,'' and even as ``a traitor to the
motherland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign has functioned with a great deal of tolerance,
and that's why it makes others so nervous,'' Cerisola said
recently.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the truth of the matter, it's clear that Fox has been
able to create an unusual political alliance that includes more
than his party, the pro-Catholic, conservative National Action
Party (PAN), and the centrist Green Ecologist Party of Mexico,
which together have formed a coalition dubbed Alliance for Change.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Fox has sidelined the two parties' political apparatus,
surrounding himself with prominent left-of-center intellectuals _
like well-known writer Jorge Castaneda, a former Cardenas adviser _
and a few longtime aides. Wags say he is now more  &UR; Foxista  &LR; than
 &UR; PANista.  &LR; At times, his about-faces have been astonishing:
</P>
<P>
   -- He has abandoned his earlier proposals to privatize the
government oil and electrical monopolies, which are viewed by most
Mexicans as jewels of national pride.
</P>
<P>
   -- He has endorsed the so-called San Andres accords, which were
signed by a congressional panel and the Zapatista rebels in 1996
but have been blocked by President Ernesto Zedillo (and by
Labastida during his stint as Interior secretary). The accords
would give vast new rights to the downtrodden Indian groups that
make up about 10 percent of the country's population.
</P>
<P>
   -- He has pledged to name opposition officials to key Cabinet
ministries, such as Energy and Social Development, and to keep most
incumbent PRI bureaucrats in their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   -- He has tacitly repudiated the PAN's conservative social
agenda. In virtually every speech, he embraces equality for women,
opposes religious education in public schools, opposes further
restrictions on abortion and supports gay rights. ``The Alliance
for Change is not against strip-teases, naked people, and even less
against the gay community,'' blared one of his coalition's recent
newspaper ads. ``The Alliance for Change is against lies, hypocrisy
and double standards. We are against those who throw rocks and then
hide their hand: cowards.''
</P>
<P>
   Many political pundits throw up their hands in response. ``Fox
tries to be all things to all people,'' said Lorenzo Meyer, a
prominent analyst and historian who supports Cardenas. ``He's all
over the map in a way that can only be called opportunist.''
</P>
<P>
   For clues to how Fox really would govern as president, many look
to his record as governor of Guanajuato state from 1996 to 1999.
The state, located about 150 miles northwest of Mexico City, is
chugging along in much the same way as other nearby PRI-run states:
Maquiladora assembly plants are spreading everywhere, unemployment
is dropping, social statistics are improving mildly, yet most
people are still struggling on low incomes.
</P>
<P>
   So was Fox's government really different from a PRI government?
Yes, but not too dramatically. His record includes the following:
</P>
<P>
   -- Fox's constant world travels to pitch Guanajuato as an
investment location paid off, bringing about $3 billion in new
industrial facilities. General Motors, Procter &AMP; Gamble, Celanese,
Reebok and Nestle built new plants, and unemployment dropped to 2.4
percent, the second-lowest rate in Mexico. He opened state offices,
or mini-embassies, in Hong Kong, New York, Los Angeles, Dallas and
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   -- He named several PRI leaders to top state positions. He also
allowed corrupt, conservative, PRI-run unions to keep their hammer
lock on the state's workers _ thus keeping factory wages low, a key
incentive for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   -- By increasing education spending and taking a tough stand
against the PRI-controlled teachers' union, he helped raise school
performance and graduation rates and lower adult illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
   -- He helped Guanajuato emigrants in the United States bring
their savings back to start small factories in their hometowns. For
example, his government matched funds sent by Guanajuatans in Napa
County to set up a successful clothing plant in Timbinal in the
southern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   -- He provided thousands of computers for school classrooms and
spearheaded a joint program with Microsoft Corp. to train
university students in software development. Fox hopes the program
will turn Guanajuato into ``Silicon Valley South.''
</P>
<P>
   When describing this complex record, Fox's backers say that in
Mexico, where political dogma and intolerance are all too common,
it should simply be called pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox's agenda is ensuring the democratic transition from the
PRI, not enacting a partisan program,'' said Adolfo Aguilar Zinser,
a left-of-center, independent federal senator who is one of Fox's
top campaign advisers. ``His government will be a gradual process,
integrating many different points of view into consensus on the
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But many backers and opponents alike say that if Fox is elected
president, his government would be severely divided between
centrist  &UR; Foxistas  &LR; and conservative  &UR; PANistas. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Between Fox's campaign team and the PAN there is very little
in common, and this could become very complicated once in
government,'' said Carlos Castilla Peraza, a longtime PAN leader.
``Would he try to govern without the party that put him in power?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 0123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
