<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7973 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-ABORTION-SCOTUS-SFCHR     06-29 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-SCOTUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SUPREME COURT RULINGS FAVORS ABORTION RIGHTS  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A sharply divided Supreme Court overturned
Nebraska's ban on so-called partial-birth abortion Wednesday,
saying it puts an ``undue burden'' on a woman's constitutional
right to terminate a pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The decision _ the most important Supreme Court statement on
abortion in eight years _ handed a victory to pro-choice advocates
who argued that efforts by Congress and 30 states to ban such
procedures were part of a sophisticated campaign to undermine the
court's landmark 1973 Roe versus Wade ruling guaranteeing the right
to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-to-4 ruling in Stenberg versus Carhart struck down the
Nebraska ban on the grounds that it was too vague and could be used
by prosecutors to intimidate physicians performing other types of
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The court also said the ban failed to allow any exceptions even
if a physician deemed a procedure necessary to protect the mother's
health, as the court required in Planned Parenthood versus Casey in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Although the decision is expected to overturn other similar
state bans, the court's deep division is likely to stir up the long
and bitter fight over abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said Wednesday that the narrow 5 to 4 ruling thrusts
the issue into this year's presidential campaign, given that the
winning candidate could name as many as four new Supreme Court
justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This court is always just one vote away from overturning the
basic right to choose,'' said Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif. ``If the
next president appoints more anti-choice justices, this basic right
could be taken away at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee,
opposes bans on the procedure, while his Republican opponent, Texas
Gov. George Bush, favors them. Both campaigns issued statements
reaffirming those positions Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion foes coined the term partial-birth abortion to describe
a procedure performed after 19 weeks of pregnancy in which a fetus
is partially delivered feet first and then the physician punctures
and drains the skull that remains inside the uterus.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen G. Breyer wrote for the majority that
prosecutors could use the Nebraska ban to criminalize a much more
common procedure performed between 12 and 24 weeks, in which part
of a fetus is dismembered or collapsed as it is pulled through the
birth canal.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those who perform abortion procedures using (that) method
must fear prosecution, conviction and imprisonment'' under the
Nebraska ban, Breyer wrote. ``The result is an undue burden upon a
woman's right to make an abortion decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Justices John Paul Stevens, Sandra Day O'Connor, David Souter
and Ruth Bader Ginsburg joined the majority; Chief Justice William
Rhenquist and Justices Anthony Kennedy, Antonin Scalia and Clarence
Thomas dissented.
</P>
<P>
   The opinions reflected strong emotions on both sides, with
unusually bitter dissents.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, joining the majority, dismissed the ``gruesome''
language used by opponents of the procedure, noting that it could
equally describe procedures that the Nebraska ban would still
permit.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional right to abortion established by Roe versus
Wade, Stevens wrote, ``makes it impossible for me to understand how
a state has any legitimate interest in requiring a doctor to follow
any procedure other than the one that he or she reasonably believes
will best protect the woman in her exercise of this constitutional
liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   To ban one procedure as ``infanticide'' while permitting an
equally gruesome alternative, he said, ``is quite simply
irrational.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalia, dissenting, said he hoped the court's decision would one
day reside in the infamous company of the Korematsu ruling
upholding Japanese internment camps and the Dred Scott decision
declaring all slaves and their descendants to be noncitizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The method of killing a human child _ one cannot even
accurately say an entirely unborn human child _ proscribed by this
statute is so horrible that even the most clinical description of
it evokes a shudder of revulsion,'' Scalia wrote. Requiring states
to permit a procedure if a physician deems it necessary to protect
a mother's health, he argued, ``is to give live-birth abortion free
rein.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who joined in upholding Roe versus Wade eight years
ago, said the ruling denies states the capacity to ensure that
medicine remains ``cognizant of the dignity and value of human
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Raschke, a staff attorney for the pro-choice Center for
Reproductive Law and Policy, said the decision was a ``clear-cut
victory,'' but she expected abortion foes to continue trying to
attack abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Carroll, legislative analyst for the California ProLife
Council in Sacramento, said Wednesday's ruling ``only temporarily''
sets back the move to ban the controversial procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this country will continue to put up with
virtual infanticide,'' Caroll said. ``It will just take us longer.
... We have to win a presidential election. There will be a
different court someday.''
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate have voted three times to ban such
late-term abortions. Two bills were vetoed by President Clinton. A
third has passed just short of the votes needed in the Senate to
override a veto.
</P>
<P>
   Raschke said Wednesday's opinion ``exposed the deception behind
these so-called partial-birth abortion bans,'' which she said use
language that appears to ban one procedure but in fact would be
interpreted to cover many others.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Crosby, an attorney with the Northern California office
of the American Civil Liberties Union, warned that Justice
O'Connor's separate concurrence ``sounds an ominous note'' because
it said if Nebraska's ban had been more specific and allowed a
health exception, it should have stood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's decision opens the door to dangerous experiments with
bans on safe abortion,'' Crosby said. ``I think it's clear ... that
the right to reproductive choice is far from secure.''
</P>
<P>
   But pro-life groups, following Justice Scalia's argument, said
the court's insistence on allowing this procedure if a physician
deems it necessary to protect the mother's health opens the door to
abortion by any means at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a radical expansion of the abortion right, expanding
that right outside the womb to include the killing of a child who
is but two inches from full delivery outside the mother's body,''
said James Bopp Jr., general counsel for the National Right to Life
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate 6 to 3 opinion, the Supreme Court also ruled that
states can restrict anti-abortion demonstrations outside health
clinics, upholding a 1993 Colorado ``bubble'' law banning unwanted
`'sidewalk counseling'' of abortion patients.
</P>
<P>
   The majority opinion by Justice John Paul Stevens said
Colorado's law does not deny free speech but only limits its
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   (The cases are Stenberg, Attorney General Of Nebraska, et al.
vs. Carhart, No. 99-830, and Hill et al. vs. Colorado et al., No.
98-1856.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
