<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7974 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-SCOUTS-SCOTUS-SFCHRON     06-29 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOUTS-SCOTUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SCOUTS' RIGHT TO BAR GAYS UPHELD  &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A deeply divided U.S. Supreme Court dealt a setback to the gay
rights movement Wednesday, ruling that the Boy Scouts of America
can exclude gays from its organization.
</P>
<P>
   By a 5-to-4 vote, the justices ruled that a New Jersey
anti-discrimination law requiring the Scouts, a national
institution for 90 years, to include gays as scout leaders and
members would violate the group's First Amendment rights of
``expressive association,'' the right of a group to choose members
who share an ideology or a set of values.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled against James Dale, an assistant scoutmaster in
New Jersey who was ousted from the organization after his troop
learned from a newspaper article that he is gay.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is one of only a handful of cases that the court
has taken up that deal with gay rights. The justices have
repeatedly refused to hear challenges to President Clinton's
``don't ask, don't tell'' policy on gays in the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't come along as far as we thought we had,'' said Matt
Coles, director of the ACLU's Lesbian and Gay Rights Project.
``They seem to be saying that if you don't like gays, then the
First Amendment gives you the right to discriminate against them,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned that the practical effect of the decision may
be limited to private organizations that espouse values and views.
``It's a bad decision,'' he said, ``but it's not something that
people should regard as a tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision is consistent with a 1998 California Supreme Court
ruling allowing Scouts to ban gays because the organization is not
a business subject to the state's anti-discrimination laws.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's decision, the majority noted that the Scout Oath
requires a member to strive to be ``morally straight'' and
``clean,'' values that the group says are inconsistent with
homosexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``A state requirement that the Boy Scouts retain Dale would
significantly burden the organization's right to oppose or disfavor
homosexual conduct,'' wrote Chief Justice William Rehnquist. But he
cautioned that ``we are not, as we must not be, guided by our views
of whether the Boy Scouts' teachings with respect to homosexual
conduct are right or wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision divided the justices along ideological lines, with
conservatives ruling in favor of the Scouts and liberals siding
with Dale.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice John Paul Stevens said there
was no evidence that the Scouts organization was exercising any
expressive association, because it had adopted no clear policy
against gays. The Scouts' mission statement makes no mention of
sexual orientation, and scouts are advised to seek guidance on
sexual matters from religious leaders, Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   The Scout's requirement that a member be morally straight and
clean ``is a far cry from the clear, unequivocal statement
necessary to prevail on its claim,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional right ``is not a freedom to discrimination at
will,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Scouts issued a statement saying the group is pleased with
the ruling, which allows it to stand by its membership policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision affirms our standing as a private association
with the right to set its own standards for membership and
leadership,'' the Scouts said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The group says that while it makes no attempt to discover the
sexual orientation of its members, ``we believe an avowed
homosexual is not a role model for the values espoused in the Scout
Oath and Law.''
</P>
<P>
   James Dale, now 29, said he was saddened by the decision.
``People don't join the Boy Scouts because they're anti-gay,'' he
said. ``People join the Boy Scouts because they want acceptance,
they want community.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he still believes that the Scouts have a lot to offer.
For 12 years, he said, ``they taught me to respect and defend the
rights of other people.''
</P>
<P>
   But with this decision, Dale said, ``I think the Boy Scouts are
making themselves extinct, and that's a very sad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale's attorney, Evan Wolfson of Lambda Legal Defense and
Education Fund, said the Boy Scouts are out of step with most other
youth organizations, including the Girl Scouts, which have no
anti-gay policy. He said he was heartened by Rehnquist's disavowal
of any endorsement of the group's anti-gay policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this case is going to open the floodgates of
discrimination,'' Wolfson said. He predicted that as a result of
the discriminatory practices, the Scouts will lose members, as well
as the support of public schools and other organizations that
sponsor individual troops.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokeswoman for the Scouts said the organization, which
has 6.2 million members, is the largest youth organization in the
nation and has grown by 7 percent during the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   George Davidson, the attorney for the Scouts, said he doubts
that the decision will reduce membership, because cases challenging
the Scouts' anti-gay policy have been widely publicized during the
past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The case, he said, was not a defeat for gay rights, but a strong
endorsement of freedom of association. ``This really is a great
victory for all Americans,'' Davidson said. ``The issue is the
right of organizations to decide their own policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale joined the Scouts in 1978 when he was 8 and eventually rose
to the rank of Eagle Scout. In 1989, he became an assistant
scoutmaster.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, a newspaper identified him as a leader of a gay
student group at Rutgers University. The Boy Scouts promptly
revoked his membership.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Dale filed a state discrimination claim, saying the
organization illegally removed him based solely on his sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   A trial judge dismissed the lawsuit, but an intermediate
appellate court reinstated Dale's claim. The New Jersey Supreme
Court also ruled in his favor, finding that the Scouts' policy
violated a state law barring discrimination by private groups open
to the public.
</P>
<P>
   (The case is Boy Scouts of America et al. vs. Dale, No. 99-699.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
