<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-PORTUGUESE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIDGEPORT JOURNAL: PORTUGAL'S FANS CHEER A DISTANT HOME TEAM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Mass.)  By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. _ As the game stretched into its second
overtime on Wednesday, the curses streaming out of the dusty men
inside Clube Portugues Vasco da Gama on James Street grew more
anguished.
</P>
<P>
   This was the point in the match at which men like these, almost
all of them Portuguese immigrants, hands thick as slabs of ham and
faces like creased leather, forgot about jobs, wives and children
and began to pray for the 12 sweat-drenched players on the
television, the pride of their nation: the Portuguese national
soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   In a soccer stadium in Brussels, the Portuguese were battling
the bigger, more experienced French in the semifinal match of this
year's European Championship. Here in Bridgeport, home to the
largest Portuguese community in Connecticut, about 200 men (and
exactly two women) were staring at three televisions that were
carrying the game live.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our Super Bowl,'' said Jaime Jorge, of Trumbull, a
marketing executive for a car-rental company who, like everyone
else here, took the Wednesday afternoon off to come to Vasco da
Gama, an 80-year-old soccer club with about 600 members. ``If you
watch the game at home, you're not going to ride that roller
coaster of emotion,'' said Jorge, who, at 31, was one of the
youngest in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Ribereiro, 52, an electrical contractor, said he had been
coming to the club about five days a week since he arrived from
Coimbra, Portugal, in 1982. ``This is the point where we all get
together,'' he said, finishing off a pork-chop-and-onions sandwich.
``We have this center and the church,'' Our Lady of Fatima, where
priests still say Mass in Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20,000 Portuguese or their descendants live in and
around Bridgeport, rivaling the two larger communities in Newark,
N.J., and in New Bedford, Mass. They began arriving in the first
decades of the 20th century, mainly from the northern region near
Chaves, and started new lives hauling in fishing nets, pounding
railroad ties and punching timecards in Bridgeport's factories.
</P>
<P>
   The Vasco da Gama soccer club, like the 15th-century Portuguese
explorer for whom it is named, is a point of reference and extreme
pride for the men and women who gather here several nights a week
and know one another by first name.
</P>
<P>
   The bar is made, they will tell you, of imported brown
Portuguese marble. Two glass cases on the wall are crammed with
trophies, team photographs and banners from other Portuguese,
Italian, Polish and German soccer clubs around the region.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Matos, 48, who normally spends Wednesday afternoons building
swimming pools, had not missed a Portuguese game since the European
Championship began last month. The team had surpassed expectations,
winning all four of its matches thus far. Matos, who immigrated in
1967, said his boss had no choice but to let him and his colleagues
take time off on game days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell him, `We got a soccer game, we gotta watch it,'''
Matos said, his hair, T-shirt and jeans coated with a fine layer of
cement dust. ``He gets mad, but what's he gonna do? We've got five
guys on the crew.''
</P>
<P>
   And the crew was here, watching the game. As the match
progressed, the cigarette smoke hovering over the marble bar grew
dense, the men more vociferous. Finally, in the 20th minute, a
Portuguese striker rocketed a shot past the French goalkeeper, and
Clube Vasco da Gama erupted with shouts of ``Golo!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gonna win, 2 to 0,'' claimed Matos, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second half, the French began attacking the
Portuguese goal, and the members of Clube Vasco da Gama, most of
them standing up, grew agitated. ``Onde esta penalto?'' the older
men would cry when a Portuguese player was tackled without a call
from the Austrian referee. They bellowed curses when the French
finally scored in the 52nd minute. But hope pulsed through
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the younger men said that if the team won, they planned
to drive across town and wave the Portuguese flag in front of a
social club for French people.
</P>
<P>
   As the second overtime wound down, the members of Vasco da Gama
twisted their bodies with every missed shot. The game finally
slipped away when a Portuguese defender was called for a penalty
kick. Seconds later on the field in Brussels, the French captain,
Zinedine Zidane, kicked and scored, winning the game, 2-1. Inside
Vasco da Gama, men turned away or hung their heads in silent agony.
A few began heated arguments over the referee's fatal call.
</P>
<P>
   Their prayers unanswered, the men's jobs, their wives and their
families came zooming back into focus. Heading out into the sunny
afternoon, many men talked with one another amiably, but with a
noticeable air of having missed winning the state lottery by a
single digit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take it easy,'' Matos, the swimming pool builder, told a
visitor. There was always the next game, the next tournament, the
next chance for Portuguese soccer glory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
