<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS TALENT EXCITES BAYLOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN KEARNS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Clippers ended up on top. And
that's not a punch line.
</P>
<P>
   With a flurry of activity, the Clippers set themselves up with
seven new players, including 18-year-old high-schooler Darius Miles
and three more in a trade for almost nothing with the Orlando
Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Clippers have an NBA team that's loaded with potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's as much talent as we've ever had,'' said Elgin
Baylor, the Clippers vice president of basketball operations. ``We
have some terrific athletes on this team. . . . I think we
assembled a lot of talent.''
</P>
<P>
   After taking Miles with the third overall pick, the Clippers
acquired guard Corey Maggette, power forward Derek Strong and the
10th pick, Missouri point guard Keyon Dooling, from the Orlando
Magic for a future first-round pick. With the 18th pick overall,
the Clippers took DePaul guard Quentin Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just so fortuitous,'' said Jeff Weltman, Clippers
director of player personnel. ``You couldn't dream it up any
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Weltman had been part of the Clippers brass that scouted the
6-foot-9, 215-pound Miles since he was a high school junior.
Despite not having Miles in for a workout, Baylor said the Clippers
knew enough about him to make the pick.
</P>
<P>
   Miles was surprised. The closest he has been to Los Angeles is
Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy the team picked me up,'' Miles said. ``That means
they want me, because they picked me at No. 3 and I'm a high school
player. I'm glad to play for someone who wants me.''
</P>
<P>
   Miles said he will move his family to Los Angeles, including his
cousin, his mother Ethel and her boyfriend. Miles likes to compare
himself to Minnesota's Kevin Garnett, who also entered the NBA out
of high school in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a similar player to Lamar Odom,'' Baylor said. ``He's
slightly built. He's got great skills. He can run and jump and he's
still a kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at his upside, there is a great upside. When you
visualize him playing with Lamar, those two guys together. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   While the Clippers have had problems keeping top draft picks,
the new collective-bargaining agreement means the newly drafted
players will sign five-year-contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Trade rumors had the Clippers dealing Miles to the Magic for
Marcus Fizer, but Chicago ruined those plans by taking Fizer
fourth, one pick before the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   But the Magic was willing to deal anyway, and the three-player
trade was practically a gift for the talent-starved Clippers. If
the Clippers are in the lottery again next year, they won't have to
give up the draft pick until 2002 at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic fire sale came as the team looks to make a run at free
agents Tim Duncan, Grant Hill and Tracy McGrady and wanted to clear
room under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   The deal landed Maggette, who averaged 8.4 points last year as a
rookie, and Dooling, the point guard the Clippers needed. Dooling,
another draft pick whose stock rose in draft workouts, averaged
15.3 points and 3.7 assists per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people underestimate me as a shooter and a
playmaker,'' Dooling said. ``I think I can bring some ability as a
point guard.''
</P>
<P>
   The final first-round selection was Richardson, who had been
projected as a lottery pick but fell to No. 18. Projected as a
shooting guard, the 6-6, 225-pounder averaged 17 points and 9.8
rebounds last season as a sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   The new players already bring a family feel. Richardson roomed
with Miles in Chicago before the draft, grew up in Illinois playing
against Maggette and he roomed with Dooling at an all-star camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a special situation we've got here with the
Clippers,'' Richardson said. ``I'm coming out here with a lot of my
friends. I like the way things look. We can be up and coming. I
think it's the sweetest situation.''
</P>
<P>
   With the first pick of the second round, the Clippers took Marko
Jaric, a 6-7, 200-pound shooting guard who plays in Italy. In
addition, the Clippers traded point guard Eric Murdock to the
Dallas Mavericks for power forward Sean Rooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been a wonderful day,'' Baylor said. ``We've been
able to get a few veteran players in Strong and Rooks. We are very
talented and very athletic. I look at our team, we are pretty deep
at every position.''
</P>
<P>
   What's left for the Clippers is to name a new coach. Baylor
didn't say how close the team is but said that there might be some
candidates interested in coaching the new talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now. you take a look on the talent on this team, and a
lot of people would like to coach this team,'' Baylor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
