</P>
<P>
   RACE-PAPER (Akron, Ohio) _ Carl Chancellor and Bob Dyer were
part of a team of reporters for The Akron Beacon Journal that had
explored the racial attitudes of this city of 215,000 people. Their
series earned the paper the Pulitzer Prize. The Beacon Journal also
tried to lead by example. Shortly after the series ended, it
introduced a lineup of columnists reflecting ``the perfect
demographic,'' as Dyer put it. They included a black woman and a
white woman as well as Chancellor, who is black, and Dyer, who is
white. The paper, it seemed, had become a proud model of racial
enlightenment. Which made it all the more startling when, just a
year later, the jubilation began to fade _ for the men and the
newsroom. By Dana Canedy. 6,240 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT110-116 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
For a special price, nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   PRESCHOOL-GRADUATION (Hartsdale, N.Y.) _ Preschool graduations
are taking on all the trappings of similar events on college
campuses _ the caps and gowns, the diplomas, the grandparents
flying in from overseas. At a time when pressure to achieve comes
younger and younger, it only makes sense that each step takes on
more moment. As transitions go, the one to kindergarten might not
seem so rough, but preschools across the country say they want to
ease it by marking all that has come before. By Kate Zernike. 1,100
words.
</P>
<P>
   CHESAPEAKE-COMPACT (Rose Haven, Md.) _ Three states sign a new
compact to repair the tattered ecology of the Chesapeake Bay, the
vast resource of 64,000 square miles and a watershed population of
15 million that has slowly been on the mend. It has been 18 years
since the first compact, now considered a model for
intergovernmental cooperation, and the new pact sets such ambitious
standards as a 10-fold increase in oysters, the restoration of blue
crabs and a 30 percent cut in suburban sprawl development that is
the latest threat undermining the bay. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
