<P>
   RUMOR-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ An analyst spreads a rumor that
one company is about to buy another one, and the stock of the
target company soars. The rumor proves to be false, and the stock
price falls back. The chain of events has occurred countless times.
But now something different has happened. The analyst _ a
well-known Wall Street veteran _ and the brokerage firm that
employed him have been censured and fined by the New York Stock
Exchange. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTIONS-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ Economics now offers two
distinct approaches to predicting election outcomes. One has its
roots in macroeconomics, examining how national economic
performance affects voting. The other is grounded in
microeconomics, using a real financial market in which participants
can place their bets on the election results. By Hal R. Varian.
</P>
<P>
   M&AMP;M-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ What does the word ``plain''
insinuate? Dull, bland, simple, ordinary, boring? That is how the
marketing executives at M&AMP;M/Mars see it, anyway. So, after 46
years, the company has decided to change the name of its Plain
variety of M&AMP;M's candy _ you know, the one without the peanuts _ to
what it hopes is a more appetizing moniker: Milk Chocolate. By
Courtney Kane.
</P>
