<HEADER>
A7988 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCI     06-29 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LANDSLIDE IN VOTE REQUIRING DONOR DISCLOSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, June 29:
</P>
<P>
   When the House finally voted on Wednesday morning to require
secret campaign slush funds to disclose their donors, the margin of
victory was huge. It was hard to remember that this very bill was
narrowly defeated two weeks ago and belittled by foes as something
the public did not care about. In trying to combat this supposedly
unwanted measure, Rep. Tom DeLay and the Republican leadership
cooked up a sham alternative that was so punitive toward unions and
violative of the privacy rights of nonpolitical groups that their
own members could not swallow it. In the end, DeLay had no choice
but to get out of the way and allow a vote on reform or be
stampeded by fellow Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The measure passed by the House in a post-midnight session
Wednesday would stop a new, particularly indefensible form of
campaign abuse _ the spread of tax-exempt groups created under
Section 527 of the tax code to raise money from secret sources and
spend it on campaign ads. DeLay has created his own secret groups
and harvested uncounted sums for the campaign. Some supporters of
Gov. George W. Bush paid for ads attacking Sen. John McCain in
March, but they were eventually found out. A spectrum of groups
from the Sierra Club to various right-to-life organizations were
also raising money for ads under the Section 527 rubric.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is due to vote on the bill Thursday, and a similar
lopsided tally is possible. A nearly identical measure was already
approved, 57 to 42. But some senators who voted no last time under
pressure from Trent Lott and Mitch McConnell are now worried about
being punished in November by voters who have begun to pay
attention to campaign reform as an issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate needs to act quickly, since every day of delay
guarantees that more truckloads of secret money will be harvested
by the slush fund organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The rush to be on the right side of this issue proves several
things. When there is a clear up-or-down vote on campaign reform,
reform wins. Opponents have to resort to trickery to avoid a vote,
because they know that lawmakers cannot afford to be against
something desired by the public. The other lesson is that
bipartisanship can carry the day against an entrenched Republican
leadership. DeLay and Lott have always looked petty and high-handed
in opposing sound reform backed by a broad spectrum of the members
of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Three Republicans _ Reps. Christopher Shays of Connecticut,
Michael Castle of Delaware and Lindsey Graham of South Carolina _
came together to work with the Democrats, led by Martin Meehan of
Massachusetts, to make an unbeatable combination. Lloyd Doggett of
Texas, a Democrat who at times tried to use the issue for partisan
advantage, played a constructive role in the end. In the Senate,
McCain has gotten crucial support from another Republican, Olympia
Snowe of Maine. They have joined in their efforts with two
Democrats, Russell Feingold of Wisconsin and Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, campaign reform will not go away. It will be
important to remember that the bill requiring disclosure of secret
slush funds was dismissed two weeks ago by many reputable pundits
and lawmakers as having no chance. It now could be signed by
President Clinton in the next couple of weeks. The same ``experts''
have also said that a soft-money ban _ ending the practice of huge
unregulated sums contributed by corporations, unions and rich
donors to political parties _ also has no chance. If everyone feels
that way, the leaders should let there be an up-or-down vote. If
that happens, reform will win again. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
