<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SCOTUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE COURT EXITS, IN CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, June 29:
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ended its 1999-2000 term Wednesday with a
burst of important rulings that could reverberate into the fall
elections. The rulings involved a range of contentious social and
political issues _ abortion rights, public aid to parochial schools
and the civil rights of gay people.
</P>
<P>
   On a positive note, a sharply divided court reaffirmed a woman's
right to choose the safest method of abortion throughout pregnancy
by striking down Nebraska's ``partial-birth abortion'' law and, by
extension, similar laws enacted by 30 other states.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the day's other 5-4 decision, holding that the Boy
Scouts have a constitutional right to exclude gays, was a
disappointing departure from a proud line of high court precedents
erasing discrimination in public accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow margins in both cases serve as reminders that this
remains a court in considerable ideological turmoil over
fundamental questions of liberty. So, too, did the court's 6-3
ruling allowing the use of taxpayer money to buy computers and
other instructional material for religious schools. Apart from the
particulars of each case, the narrowness of the decisions also
reminds us that the next president will have the power to change or
reinforce the court's present disposition with only one or two
changes. Here is a brief look at Wednesday's major decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``PARTIAL-BIRTH ABORTION.'' The majority opinion written by
Justice Stephen Breyer and joined by Justices Sandra Day O'Connor,
David Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and John Paul Stevens affirmed a
lower court ruling overturning Nebraska's ban on the rarely used
procedure known as ``partial-birth abortion.'' This is the phrase
invented by pro-life groups to stigmatize all abortion procedures,
not only in late term but those commonly used before fetal
viability. These more common procedures have long been protected
under Supreme Court precedents, which the new ruling strongly
reaffirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously missing from the majority was Justice Anthony
Kennedy, who helped write the court's 1992 decision reaffirming the
right to abortion. This switch does not bode well for future cases.
However, the ruling vindicates President Clinton's repeated veto of
Congressional attempts to impose a similar national ban. It also
undercuts the strategy of politicians to claim to be pro-choice
even as they support the ``partial birth'' bans the court has now
ruled to be unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGIOUS SCHOOL AID. In a 6-3 decision, the court upheld a law
that requires public school districts to share equipment in a
``secular, neutral and nonideological'' way with students enrolled
in private schools. This is a relatively inoffensive result that
does not tell us how the court will vote on far more politically
charged cases involving tuition vouchers that are percolating up
the legal system. Four justices in the majority _ Chief Justice
William Rehnquist, Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas and Anthony
Kennedy _ made plain their approval of broad taxpayer support of
religious schools. But the two justices who voted with them,
O'Connor and Breyer, filed a separate opinion strongly objecting to
such wholesale breaching of the wall between church and state.
</P>
<P>
   GAY SCOUTS. The court reached one of its lowest moments of the
term when it ruled in favor of the Boy Scouts' right to exclude gay
members. The four dissenters _ Stevens, Ginsburg, Breyer and Souter
_ did not challenge the principle that an organization cannot be
forced to adopt an unwanted message. But the dissenters correctly
noted that the Boy Scouts had failed to show that admitting gays
was fundamentally incompatible with the organization's core
mission, the test the court has traditionally applied to groups
trying to escape an anti-discrimination law.
</P>
<P>
   James Dale, the excluded Eagle Scout, deserved better. So did
the rest of the nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0047 </DOCNO>
