<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CUBAN-BOY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ELIAN GOES HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, June 29:
</P>
<P>
   Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old boy found off the Florida coast
last Thanksgiving Day, returned home to Cuba on Wednesday night
after the U.S. Supreme Court rejected an emergency request from the
child's relatives in Miami to keep him in the United States. It was
the proper legal conclusion to a bitter family dispute that dragged
on for months and drew international attention. The high court was
right not to take the case because there were no important issues
of law that had not been resolved by lower courts.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times editorial page opposed the predawn raid in
April by federal immigration agents to remove Elian from the home
of his Miami relatives as an unwarranted use of force against
citizens who were behaving in a recalcitrant but not violent
manner. But we have supported the father's right to regain custody
of the child and to decide where he should live. The relatives had
no business blocking the return of the boy to his father simply
because they equated paternal custody with delivering him to Fidel
Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Despite pandering by politicians to the passions of Miami's
Cuban-American community and despite intense community anger over
the raid, there was no deadly violence. The legal system provided a
rational process and has now produced a just outcome. All the
parties were allowed to make their arguments in court, with the
federal judges ruling that in this case only the parent could speak
for the young boy in making an asylum decision.
</P>
<P>
   Elian may yet find his way to a normal childhood in his country.
The image of the Cuban-American community in Miami, however, has
suffered because of its belligerence in disrupting familial ties
between father and son. The posturing by Miami's elected leaders in
refusing to aid federal authorities was insupportable. Miami city
politics have become more divisive than ever.
</P>
<P>
   On the national scene, the anti-Castro lobby has hurt its
message by seeming to use a child as a political prop. Perhaps most
harmful to that cause is that many Americans came to sympathize
with Elian's father and became more aware of America's outdated
policy of isolation toward Cuba. It is perhaps not surprising that
just one day before Elian's flight home, the House Republican
leaders agreed to end four decades of sanctions on food sales to
Cuba. The saga of this Cuban child helped to hasten that shift in
policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7995 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLAN     06-29 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ... CORRECTS GREEN STAT TO FINALS, NOT PLAYOFFS... 
LAKERS WAIVE GOODBY TO A.C., DRAFT MADSEN
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Just nine days removed from the glow of
their championship moment, the Los Angeles Lakers began the
retooling process Wednesday with two promising additions and one
painful subtraction.
</P>
<P>
   The net result: The only player to contribute to the Lakers'
last three championships probably won't be around for a fourth.
</P>
<P>
   A.C. Green, who started every regular-season and playoff game at
power forward last season, was waived just hours before the NBA
draft. The Lakers then selected his potential replacement, drafting
Stanford big man Mark Madsen with the 29th pick.
</P>
<P>
   They also acquired swingman Cory Hightower, the 54th overall
pick, in a trade with San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision to cut ties with Green _ who left the Lakers
after winning two titles in the 1980s, then returned last season
and helped restore ``Showtime'' _ made the biggest waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decisions like this are most difficult, particularly when you
have the utmost respect for a true professional like A.C. Green,''
said Lakers executive Jerry West, who added that moves like this
are ``what I most despise about this part of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was not unexpected. Green will be 37 in October and was
due to make $1.9 million next season if the Lakers did not cut him
by Saturday. Releasing Green will save money and give the Lakers
room to sign a younger, more athletic power forward.
</P>
<P>
   Their payroll also is perilously close to the $55 million
threshold that will trigger the league's luxury tax in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something we felt we had to do in order to remain more
flexible going forward, also knowing that we're going to be facing
a potential tax,'' West said. ``And as I stated before, our job is
one of trying to assemble a team that not only can be competitive
on the court but also stay within the guidelines of what our owner
wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Green was traveling and unavailable for comment, but agent Marc
Fleisher said Green understood the decision. Green does not intend
to retire, and both Fleisher and Laker officials suggested he could
even return to the Lakers, albeit for less money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very, very loyal to the Lakers,'' Fleisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Green averaged 5.9 rebounds in the regular season but slipped to
3.3 rebounds in the Finals and surrendered most of his minutes to
Robert Horry. Green and Horry were an adequate tag team, but the
Lakers were hurt in the playoffs by more athletic forwards, from
Sacramento's Chris Webber to Portland's Rasheed Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   They hope to find the answer in the free-agent market, using
their $2.25 million salary-cap exception. Last summer they
unsuccessfully dangled the exception in front of Charles Oakley and
Lorenzen Wright.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can get a very attractive player as a free agent
with our midrange exception,'' West said. ``If not, we can always
go back to A.C. Green and see if there's some interest on his part
coming back here. But my best guess is we're going to look for help
in the free-agency market.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who they get, the Lakers hope to see an immediate
contribution from the 6-foot-9, 240-pound Madsen, who played four
years for the Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited about having this guy,'' West said. ``He's a
tough, hard-nosed kid. I think he has an opportunity to play right
away. . . . And my best guess is he will be a tremendous crowd
favorite here. This guy plays really hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Madsen averaged 12.2 points and 9.4 rebounds as a senior. His
nickname, ``Mad Dog,'' says everything else _ he's aggressive and
physical, attributes the Lakers sorely need.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need physical players in basketball,'' coach Phil Jackson
said, ``and you need players that are willing to put their body on
the line, to take charges, to plug the lane, to do other things
that are important for a ballclub to keep the opponents away from
penetration. And that's one of the things I think this young man
has demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still has to play within the framework of how we play as a
team, and how his enthusiasm ignites us or brings us to that level
is important.''
</P>
<P>
   That enthusiasm was evident in a brief conference call with
reporters. Madsen, a lifelong Lakers fan, put an exclamation point
at the end of every sentence and said he ``jumped about 10 feet in
the air'' when the Lakers picked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how excited I am right now to be joining such
a first-class organization,'' said Madsen, whose grandparents live
in Long Beach. ``I love Southern California, I love the area, and I
absolutely love the Lakers. I grew up watching the Lakers and I
just think the world of coach Phil Jackson _ I've read his books
and I'm just so excited to be joining the Lakers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers did not have a second-round pick but obtained
Hightower _ who played two years at Indian Hills City College in
Iowa _ from the Spurs in exchange for second-round picks in 2001
and 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 0156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7996 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-POLO-LADN-(SLANG)     06-29 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-POLO-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JET LAG BOTHERS HUMBERT; HE STARS ANYWAY VS. CROATIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMITOS, Calif. _ His primary role on the U.S. National
Water Polo team is to set up himself up in the front of the
opponents goal and, with the opposition pummeling him from on top
and under the water, get a good scoring opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the easiest of roles for Chris Humbert, or any other
two-meter man, even with a good night's sleep. But it becomes
downright excruciating when just over 24 hours you stepped off a
plane following a 14-hour flight and your body clock says it's
about five in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Humbert, who stepped off a jet on Tuesday after finishing off a
professional season in Greece, looked pretty darn fresh, even
though he admitted otherwise afterwards, while scoring five goals,
including the game-winner and the clinching goal in an 11-9 triumph
over Croatia before 1,000 in the UPS International Cup at the U.S.
National Aquatic Center on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired and jet-lagged,'' said the 6-foot-7, 225-pound
Humbert, who is perhaps the world's best player at his position.
``It's about five in the morning Greece time.''
</P>
<P>
   Humbert was at the team's opening 7-7 tie with Australia on
Tuesday, but he didn't suit up. It wasn't difficult on Wednesday to
see the impact he makes when in the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big presence in the two-meter for sure,'' said U.S.
head coach John Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   The winning goal, which came at 4:40 left, came when Humbert
fought for position, took a nice entry pass from Gavin Arroyo and
somehow snuck the ball past Croatian goalkeeper Goran Volarevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea how I did that,'' said Humbert, who converted
five of 7 shot attempts. ``I'll have to watch the tape and see. I
was just trying to throw it toward the cage. There was a lot of
luck there.''
</P>
<P>
   The clincher came with 1:25 left when Humbert fired the ball
into the cage on a 6-on-5 advantage to give the U.S. (1-0-1) its
sixth goal in 10 man-advantage situations. Humbert had created the
man advantage by drawing an ejection.
</P>
<P>
   However, Croatia (1-1-0) wasn't done. With 50 seconds left
Robert Lynn committed a four-meter foul to create a penalty shot
for Croatia. The attempt by Dubravko Simenc got past U.S.
goalkeeper Dan Hackett but stayed out of the cage by striking the
bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't get a whisker on it,'' Hackett told his teammates
moments later.
</P>
<P>
   The bar was also Hackett's friend with 11 seconds left on a shot
by Ivo Ivanis. Hackett also kept the ball out of the net more
traditionally by blocking nine shots during the game, including
several in key situations.
</P>
<P>
   The other U.S. goals were scored by Arroyo, Lynn, Tony Azevedo,
who converted a penalty shot but missed on all three attempts from
the field, Chi Kredell, Chris Oeding and Brad Schumacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is I'm pleased how well we played today after
(Tuesday's game),'' said Vargas, who praised the two-meter work of
Humbert, Kyle Kopp and Ryan Bailey. ``We're trying to be tournament
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the most important tournament games will come in
September in Sydney and the U.S. will open play against Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't forget (Wednesday's game), we'll try to learn from
it,'' Vargas said. ``It's more important to win at the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia 12, Team UPS 6: It wasn't a sharp performance by the
tournament favorite, but Yugoslavia (2-0-0) had plenty to get past
Team UPS (0-2-2). Jerry Smith and Omar Amr had late goals for Team
UPS to make the score more respectable. Team UPS, which is made up
of young American players, will play the U.S. National team tonight
at 8:30.
</P>
<P>
   Italy 10, Australia 5: Marco Gerini had eight saves and Leonardo
Sottani scored three times to push Italy (1-1-0) past Australia
(0-1-1).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
