<HEADLINE>
HILL BRIGHTENS ANGELS' FOCUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Anaheim Angels manager Mike Scioscia held a team
meeting before Wednesday's game against the Seattle Mariners,
reminding his players it's a long season and that it's important to
come to the ballpark every day with a consistent approach.
</P>
<P>
   But what keyed the Angels' 3-2 win on this night simply was good
pitching, the kind of pitching they will need to contend in the
American League West.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hill (4-4) returned from a seven-week absence caused by a
strained rib-cage muscle, and held the Mariners to one run and four
hits in six innings to earn the victory. Shigetoshi Hasegawa and
Troy Percival (19th save) combined for the final three innings to
close it out before 32,581 at Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   The victory snapped the Mariners' winning streak at seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing six innings was something Hill did only twice in his
eight starts this season before his injury. He was still throwing
ha sixth, hitting 94 mph on the radar gun, when he had to face the
heart of the Mariners lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Facing Alex Rodriguez, Edgar Martinez, John Olerud and Jay
Buhner in the inning, Hill gave up only a walk to Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels fared only slightly better against Mariners starter
Jamie Moyer, though they had their chances. With one out in the
first inning, the Angels loaded the bases with a single and two
walks for Garret Anderson, who grounded into a force play at
second. Anderson barely beat the relay to first, allowing Benji Gil
to score and give the Angels a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus followed with a single to center field to drive in Mo
Vaughn for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hill kept the lead at two until Martinez homered with one out in
the fourth inning, cutting the Angels' lead to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had a chance to get the run back and increase their
lead in the fifth after Gil tripled, Vaughn was hit by a pitch and
Tim Salmon walked to load the bases with one out for Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer got ahead in the count, 0-2, but Anderson fouled off five
pitches with two strikes. Anderson eventually struck out swinging
at a 75-mph changeup on a 2-2 count. Moyer then struck out Glaus to
end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson had yet another chance with runners in scoring position
in the seventh. The Angels had already scored once in the inning on
Gil's RBI double. Gil went to third when center fielder Mike
Cameron lost Vaughn's fly ball in the sky for a single, but Salmon
struck out for the first out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson then grounded into an inning-ending 1-6-3 double play,
the 15th double play he's grounded into this season, fourth most in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   Despite taking a season-worst 6-game deficit in the AL West into
Wednesday's game, Scioscia repeated what he has said all season _
that his club should focus on itself and not what other clubs are
doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our season depends on how we play, not how other teams play,''
he said. ``We as coaches talk every day about being patient. This
club has come a long way. It has a high ceiling. It has to reach a
certain level and play on a consistent basis.''
</P>
<P>
   But will it be good enough to win a division that has teams like
Oakland and Seattle that are putting together long winning
stretches?
</P>
<P>
   ``If winning this division takes winning 90 games, we have to
make sure we win 91,'' Scioscia said. ``If we win 95 and somebody
else wins 105, that's pretty much out of our control.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning 90-plus games is something Scioscia, his staff and the
front office have believed his club could do since spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this team in a special light a lot of people don't,''
Scioscia said. ``There is a lot of talent. You look at what some of
these players have gone through the last three or four years. They
do respond to adversity. There have been some good years and some
hard years. There's a feeling deep down inside they can win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
