<SLUG> BC-BBN-NUDODGER-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-YANKEE COMES THROUGH FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It took less than a week for the players to give
Jim Leyritz some guff. He arrived in a trade for Jose Vizcaino, the
Los Angeles Dodgers lost five in a row, and Leyritz's most
productive time at home plate came in cameo catching appearances.
</P>
<P>
   However, Leyritz figured his opportunities would come, and he
got one of them with two outs and two on in the ninth inning
Wednesday. He came through like it was the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz's single into the left-field corner scored Shawn Gilbert
from second and gave the Dodgers a 5-4 win over the San Diego
Padres at Dodger Stadium. It was the second consecutive night the
Dodgers won with a two-out single in their last at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real clutch hitter and everyone knows what he's done
with the Angels and Yankees and Padres with so many clutch hits,''
Dodgers right fielder Shawn Green said. ``I think everyone in the
park thought he was going to do his job, and he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz was 0 for 4 with a walk in four games, and when he
joined the club, the Dodgers went on a season-long five-game losing
streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept telling them, 'Maybe it's me, maybe it's me,' and they
were riding me a little bit, too,'' Leyritz said. ``It made me feel
good, but at the same time the ballclub was playing good, and to be
able to come back and me being able to contribute, you feel good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nice thing about being back over here in the National
League and with this ballclub is going to be that opportunity to
get that one at-bat maybe a day. Mentally, it makes you a lot more
prepared coming to the ballpark. I'm really starting to enjoy
myself again.''
</P>
<P>
   Having Leyritz come through with the game-winning hit is the
exact scenario the Dodgers thought about when they acquired him
from the Yankees last week for Jose Vizcaino. He's made a career of
hitting huge homers in the postseason and he's relishing the role
of being a pinch-hitter for a National League manager who loves to
double switch.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz's presence also puts the matchups in the Dodgers' favor,
something manager Davey Johnson only dreamed of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Padres manager Bruce Bochy) was between a rock and hard
spot,'' Johnson said. ``He left me to control the matchup because
he knows if he brings in (right-hander Carlos) Almanzar, I'm going
to go with (lefty Dave Hansen). I burned three guys to win it
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Chad Kreuter started the game-winning rally by drawing a walk
off reliever Steve Montgomery (0-1). Gilbert pinch-ran and moved to
second on Alex Cora's single to right. Pinch-hitter Todd Hundley
flew out to center, but Leyritz hit Kevin Walker's 1-2 pitch into
the left-field corner for the win.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers bench would have been nearly depleted had Leyritz
not gotten the hit.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Adams (3-3), plagued by stiffness in his right shoulder,
pitched two perfect innings of relief for the win. Todd
Hollandsworth and Eric Karros each hit two-run homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was big for our bullpen to keep the rest of the guys in the
bullpen out of the game,'' Adams said. ``Guys needed some rest
because we've been getting a lot of work lately, so to have one guy
go in there and pitch and give the rest of the guys the day off is
huge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
