<HEADER>
A7999 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     06-29 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMAL CRAWFORD GETS A FRESH START WITH THE BULLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wheeling and dealing and milking the system is a punishable
offense when you're a so-called student-athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jamal Crawford about that.
</P>
<P>
   Last season at Michigan, the Wolverines freshman was
investigated and suspended by the NCAA for allegedly accepting a
car and some jewelry from a family friend.
</P>
<P>
   The violations tussle sent Crawford, Michigan's high scorer,
running for the NBA draft, where he was one of 29 high-school
players or college underclassmen up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. This is now. And in the big, rich world of the
NBA, it's all good when it comes to wheeling and dealing.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night in Minneapolis at the scene of the 2000 NBA
draft, not only was Crawford the surprise pick by Cleveland at the
unexpectedly high No. 8 spot, the 20-year-old guard out of Rainier
Beach was immediately used as leverage.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, an NBA team using a kid as a bargaining chip in a
draft-day deal that lets team officials act on their dark and
devious impulses.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out everyone's looking for some easy money.
</P>
<P>
   Just moments after Crawford was plucked from a sea of young and
restless NBA wannabes, the Bulls turned around and traded their No.
7 pick, 7-foot center Chris Mihm, to Cleveland for Crawford _ and
some cold, hard cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago told me they were going to take him at No. 7, but they
wanted to make Cleveland feel like they were going to take Mihm to
get money out of the deal,'' Crawford's agent Aaron Goodwin said.
</P>
<P>
   Shenanigans aside, this draft-day tango will soon be forgotten.
It won't matter how Crawford got to Chicago. All that will matter
is what happens once he gets there, because he was such a high
pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to be drafted, always wanted to shake David
Stern's hand. To go this high _ the highest to ever go out of the
state of Washington _ that's just a dream for me, and I'm just
going to get a fresh start in Chicago,'' said Crawford, who was
accompanied by his father, Clyde, and his toddler son, Eric.
</P>
<P>
   All eyes are on young guns like Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   He and other talented basketball players are somehow being used
as the reason basketball at the college and pro level is undergoing
such an upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Crawford had no idea about the tricks Chicago
was playing on Cleveland by drafting Mihm and then bartering for
Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   He even said he was going to wear a red suit, thinking the Bulls
liked him. When they passed him by at the No. 7 pick, Crawford
thought nothing about it, figuring he could get used to playing in
Cleveland with the likes of Shawn Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they told me I was traded, I thought they were joking,''
Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford was the first guard taken in this year's draft _
probably the right call.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who saw St. John's Erick Barkley throw away the Red
Storm's NCAA tournament chances knows that Crawford was a better
pick. The Trail Blazers took Barkley at No. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Alexander and Keyon Dooling were rated higher earlier
this spring, and there were always questions about how Mateen
Cleaves' game would translate to the NBA. Khalid El-Amin went in
the second round, and wound up in Chicago with Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   But Crawford went first Wednesday night because he went to
Chicago for a pre-draft camp and blew away the competition, blew
away his detractors and blew away the scouts.
</P>
<P>
   His game is silky smooth, and he let that show. He handles the
ball very well with those long fingers, and can lull defenders into
a trance with his dribble before slashing to the hoop or letting
fly a jumper.
</P>
<P>
   He also has excellent court awareness, a benefit no doubt from
years of playing with fellow Seattle hoopsters like Doug Christie,
Jason Terry, Shammond Williams and Gary Payton. He displayed the
kind of confidence and calm that made him far less of a gamble than
originally forecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say I'm the best, but I think I was one of
the best. I'm not going to say I'm better than them, but I'm not
going to say they're better than me, either,'' Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I just showed my overall versatility. I shot NBA
3-pointers, 9-for-10. I showed that I can handle the ball as a pure
point guard at 6-foot-5. I think that's pretty rare. ... After
Chicago, my name just took off a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   In the post-Jordan NBA, as the league seeks to redefine itself
and come to terms with a steady influx of younger players, the
meter is running on the young guns.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, to his credit, has never let criticism or tough times
deter his effort to get better at his game. If he had an advisor in
Barry Henthorn, who may have steered him wrong on money issues,
Crawford has had just as many solid boosters within the Sonics
organization, who let him know he was on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   It also says something about the young man that between the
limbo state he was in during his NCAA suspension and his decision
to go pro, he raised the level of his game so no one could doubt
his talent.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Crawford was an example of what's wrong with college
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Next, considered too green, too young for the draft, Crawford
was an example of what's wrong with the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Wednesday night, Crawford was good enough for one team to
pick him No. 8, then trade him for the No. 7 pick.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about about moving up the charts with a bullet.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey
</P>
<P>
   can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
