<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS' WIN STREAK ENDS AT 7 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sinatra occasionally had to clear his throat.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway frequently had writer's block.
</P>
<P>
   Freud sometimes had bad dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Who, then, can say that the Mariners weren't going to lose one
eventually?
</P>
<P>
   It's just that they don't think they should have lost this one.
Handcuffed by the pitching of Anaheim starter Ken Hill and the
Angels bullpen, the Mariners saw their seven-game losing streak end
in a 3-2 loss Wednesday night at Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   Given the number of hits they've had lately, it's been a tribute
to the pitching and defense that the Mariners came into Wednesday
night with any kind of winning streak. In their last four games,
they have just 22 hits, an average of 5{ per game. To get three
wins out of that is amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Putting a winning recipe together out of few ingredients becomes
harder each successive day. It had to come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   It did Wednesday night, with Seattle collecting just six hits.
Two of them were monster homers by Edgar Martinez and Alex
Rodriguez, but both came with the bases empty, and the offense
beyond that was as dry as the Sahara. Seattle was fortunate that
Oakland lost 5-3 at home to Texas, so the Mariners remain just
one-half game out of first place in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losses aren't easier to take just because you've won a bunch
of games in a row,'' Rodriguez said. ``We feel we could have won
this one. But it's not like we blew it. They just beat us with good
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to us to come out (today) with better energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill had plenty of energy stored up. He'd spent the last six
weeks on the disabled list, but in his first start in the majors
since May 6, Hill looked as if he'd been in an extended groove.
Gifted with a 2-0 lead in the first inning, he allowed just one run
_ Martinez's homer _ in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their pitchers pitched well,'' manager Lou Piniella said.
``There are just times you have to give the other side credit.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Piniella and the Mariners were more than
willing to give losing pitcher Jamie Moyer credit. If you didn't
know the final score, you might have thought Moyer had won.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-run first inning that could have been worse than it
was, Moyer settled down and held the Angels at bay for the next
five.
</P>
<P>
   That was particularly true in the fifth, when nothing more than
Moyer's sheer force of will got the Mariners home without a run
being scored. The Angels loaded the bases with one out for two of
the biggest boppers on the roster _ Garret Anderson and Troy Glaus.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer matched up with Anderson in what was as much a battle of
wills as it was a battle of skills. The Anaheim center fielder
fouled off pitch after pitch, but Moyer kept throwing strikes.
</P>
<P>
   After eight pitches, catcher Joe Oliver came out to the mound,
if only to give Moyer a break. Then, on the 10th pitch of the
at-bat, Moyer snuck a pitch past the flailing Anderson. Moments
later, Moyer struck out Glaus, too, stranding all three runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``That fifth inning defines Jamie,'' fellow starter Aaron Sele
said. ``He was in a jam, and he fought his way out. Their guy,
Anderson, was battling, too, but Jamie kept coming with quality
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a gamer, and guys like that are in short supply.''
</P>
<P>
   The other side has some gamers, too, even if the Mariners have a
nice edge in the standings as the West is currently constituted.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, first-year Angels manager Mike Scioscia held a
team meeting, after which he was quick to point out that he was
impressed with his club's competitive spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the desire in these guys to kick butt,'' Scioscia said.
``It's something you want to see in your team. They come out with
the passion to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The young but improving Angels needed a win to keep pace with
Seattle and Oakland, and they got it in the form of six strong
innings from Hill, who was making his first start since coming off
the disabled list. Troy Percival finished up an impressive evening
for Angels pitchers by throwing a scoreless ninth for his 19th
save.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen Hill a lot over the years, so not much he does is
going to surprise us,'' Rodriguez said. ``But for a pitcher coming
off the disabled list, he was able to throw his fastball at speeds
six or seven miles (per hour) apart, and that was surprising. One
would come in at 87 and another at 94.''
</P>
<P>
   The speed game was evident in the Mariners' bullpen, too. Brett
Tomko threw hard and relatively loose in his first inning since
June 6 _ he came off the disabled list Saturday _ and Jose Paniagua
and Jose Mesa continued to dominate.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua threw yet another scoreless inning of relief in the
eighth. He's allowed just one run this month and one run, in fact,
in his past 16 games. During that time he's lowered his ERA on a
glacial scale, trimming it from 6.97 on May 19 to 3.99.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa followed Paniagua by throwing a scoreless ninth. It was
another in a string of strong efforts by Mesa, who has allowed
three earned runs in 13 innings in June, an ERA of 2.08 for the
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a lot of nice pitching, particularly from Paniagua and
Mesa late and Moyer,'' Piniella said. ``But their pitchers didn't
give us any runs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
