<HEADER>
A8003 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-MUGABE-JOKES-INDEPEND     06-29 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUGABE-JOKES-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUGABE: HERO TURNED DESPOT AND NOW, FIGURE OF RIDICULE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Analysis...ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 575-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MARY BRAID  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ To see how far President Robert Mugabe, one-time
national hero of Zimbabwe, has fallen you had only to attend the
opposition's recent election rallies. It could be measured in the
raucous laughter that followed the numerous, and sexually risque,
``Bob and Grace'' jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The gags about President Mugabe and free-spending Grace, four
decades his junior, whom he married in 1996, lost something in
translation from Shona to English. But the biting sarcasm, that
even a few years ago few would have dared express in public,
survived.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians _ come-standup comedians _ who worked the crowds
linked the president's political and private sins, and concluded
that Mugabe's kleptomaniac tendencies were so ingrained that he had
even felt compelled to steal Grace, another man's wife.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone had dared tell the old man about the daily ridicule,
he might have wondered when, and possibly even why, the rot set in.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that over twenty years Mugabe allowed his
overriding greed for power to cloud his judgment and distance him
from his people.
</P>
<P>
   During the weeks of pre-election, state-sponsored violence, many
ordinary Zimbabweans concluded that Bob loved power more than his
country, and perhaps he always had.
</P>
<P>
   It all started so well. In 1980, when Mugabe became prime
minister, after his successful bush war against the minority white
regime of Ian Smith, he was largely adored and the former British
colony he inherited was in healthy shape.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy hardly mattered after the common black enemy _
colonialists and white racists _ was defeated, and Mugabe was feted
at home and overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The president had made his own sacrifices for the cause. He
spent ten years in jail, separated from his first wife Sally,
courtesy of the Smith regime, and was inside when their
four-year-old son _ their only child _ died.
</P>
<P>
   And to be fair, Mugabe, who acquired several degrees in jail,
set about improving the conditions of his downtrodden people. He
poured money into education even when the international monetary
institutions disapproved.
</P>
<P>
   The irony, some Zimbabweans say, is that by creating an informed
population, he was educating himself _ in the long term _ out of
power.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe was always authoritarian but throughout his reign his
greed for power just kept growing. He made laws, amended the
constitution and massacred rivals to increase his control and that
of his party, ZANU-PF.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe became a one-party state, run by ZANU and its corrupt
cronies, where dissent was discouraged, sometimes brutally.
</P>
<P>
   When the much-loved Sally Mugabe died in 1992 so did some of the
public's affection for her husband. Grace's arrival - along with
the revelation that Mugabe had fathered a child by her when Sally
was still alive _ just added to public disillusion.
</P>
<P>
   Demands for multiparty democracy began to emerge in the late
1980s, championed by trade union leader, Morgan Tsvangirai, who
would, a decade later, form the Movement for Democratic Change _
and challenge Mugabe. But it was the economic disaster Mugabe
presided over during the 1990s that created the mass clamor for
political change.
</P>
<P>
   With his back against the wall, Mugabe acted like a dinosaur. He
harked back to a bush war that meant little to a new generation,
and spouted now meaningless Cold War rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   And when he tried to play his last card _ the racist one _ and
blame white farmers for the country's ills, few Zimbabweans bought
it. Many just laughed at the old man, hero turned despot and now
figure of fun. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 575-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
