r a BC-NAPALM-GIRL-FORGIVES-     06-29 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPALM-GIRL-FORGIVES-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM'S `NAPALM GIRL,' PHOTOGRAPHER MEET WITH QUEEN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 575-word ``separate-buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald
Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``a''
domestic/general news file.)  
 &HT;    
 By TOM BUERKLE  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   LONDON _ Standing next to the museum display, the warm eyes,
generous smile and smooth complexion of Phan Thi Kim Phuc make it
hard to believe she is the same person as the girl in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone old enough to remember the Vietnam War, the
photograph of the naked 9-year-old girl running toward a camera
screaming in agony as napalm burned her flesh is seared into the
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Her image has become a symbol of the barbarity of war that
transcends debate about the rights or wrongs of U.S. intervention
in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Its iconic status also serves as a constant reminder to Kim Phuc
of the day in June 1972, when a U.S. commander ordered South
Vietnamese planes to drop napalm near her village in the Central
Highlands of South Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the pictures and the documentary,'' she said, referring
to a film that was made of her life three years ago. ``That makes
me remember all the time. I saw the airplane. I saw the fire. I got
burned. I was so scared and crying and running out of the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   But far from trying to avoid the memories, Kim Phuc is proud of
the photograph and wants to see it exposed to future generations.
``Let the world see how horrible wars can be,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph, along with shots of the bombing and her initial
rescue by a television film crew, is going on display as part of a
$75.2 million extension of London's Science Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The new Wellcome Wing opens to the public next week, but Kim
Phuc and Nick Ut, the Associated Press photographer who took the
pictures and helped save her life, were in London Tuesday for a
formal opening of the extension by Queen Elizabeth II.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Phuc is not overtly political, perhaps understandably. After
being used as a propaganda tool by the Vietnamese government, she
defected with her husband, Bui Huy Toan, during a refueling
stopover in Canada on a flight from Moscow to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to have freedom myself, and build my family,'' she
said. The couple live in Toronto with their two boys, Thomas, 6,
and Stephen, 3.
</P>
<P>
   She is happy to be an anti-war symbol, though. She was named a
goodwill ambassador for the United Nations Educational, Scientific
and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) three years ago, and she has
established the Kim Foundation, which trains doctors and supplies
artificial limbs to help child victims of land mines in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to move on to help each other,'' she said. ``I really
want to say, `Thank God I'm alive.' I want to forgive the people
who caused my suffering. I did.'' She laid a wreath at the Vietnam
Memorial in Washington in 1996 _ ``and so I am free from hatred and
bitterness.''
</P>
<P>
   Ut, who took up a camera after his brother was killed as an AP
photographer, didn't hesitate to help 28 years ago. After shooting
the Pulitzer-Prize photo, he doused Kim Phuc's body with water and
drove her to a hospital. And he has kept contact through her
painful recovery, which included 17 operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saved my life,'' Kim Phuc said of the man she calls Uncle
Ut. ``He's wonderful, isn't he. I'm so grateful that he didn't only
do his job, but he's a human being helping another.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 575-word article from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
