<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 10:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8084 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN02-COX     06-29 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Court was right in backing Miranda
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   That hissing sound you heard a few days back was the air going
out of a hope long pumped up on the political and social right that
if only the Miranda ruling could be wrestled back before a
conservative Supreme Court like the current one, it would be
overturned and that would show the crooks and liberals -- pretty
much one and the same _ a thing or two.
</P>
<P>
   Oops. Steered through the Virginia-based 4th Circuit Court of
Appeals, made genial to such notions by Presidents Reagan and Bush,
the issue was indeed forced back to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   The happy result is a ruling that not only doesn't reverse
Miranda but fastens it into law more firmly than ever -- written by
no less than Chief Justice William Rehnquist, a root-and-branch
legal conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist's emphatic presence in the majority was especially
deflating on the right. He had often said that if he had been on
the court at the time, he would not have voted for the Miranda
ruling, which advised criminal suspects of their rights to stay
silent and to legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
   But Rehnquist is more a straight-arrow conservative than a
reactionary activist like Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence
Thomas, who were left sputtering together in volatile dissent. A
true legal conservative bows respectfully, though not slavishly, to
precedent.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was not, precisely, Miranda, but rather a law Congress
passed in panicky overreaction two years later attempting to
nullify the ruling. The law was widely counted so constitutionally
crippled that no administration ever wasted time trying to enforce
it.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, as Rehnquist reminds us, can't just vote away
unpopular constitutional findings, and the 1968 statute could be
held valid only if the Supreme Court were prepared to scrap
Miranda. Rehnquist made plain it would do no such thing.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling ought to give pause, but won't, to the various
ideological throwbacks _ from radio ranters to hyperventilating
activists _ who make political and financial livings out of never
letting a potent demagogic issue die.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda, to those ends, was vilified as coddling criminals and
making life impossible for cops, when in practice it shored up the
criminal justice system by making it fairer and by forcing a sharp
improvement in police work and prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   Similar eternal campaigns are organized around efforts to send
women and doctors to prison for having and performing abortions and
to put Christian religious services back in public classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   All that is possible. The next president probably will name
three, maybe four, justices, and a change of just one Supreme Court
vote would start dismantling lawful abortion. And if the next
president appoints Scalia-Thomas look-alikes, as much George W.
Bush's constituency wants, we could be thrown into full legal
free-fall.
</P>
<P>
   How much better, as Rehnquist suggested, just to let sleeping
dogs lie _ especially the ones that have been dozing for more than
a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8099 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN02-CO     06-29 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Fidel re-nurtured
 &HT;    For release July 2, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Every once in a while, the Cuban-American community here
is smitten by erroneous reports that Fidel Castro has died. No such
thing. After 40 years of total control of Cuba, he is as alive as
ever.
</P>
<P>
   He's got his Elian back, he's got the Republican-led U.S.
Congress pushing through legislation to ease segments of the
embargo, he's got the Miami exile community in the most depressed
(and foul) mood it's even been in.
</P>
<P>
   There is a Rasputin quality to Fidel Castro. He can mesmerize
you into believing that he is a paternalistic messiah,
self-anointed to lift the values and lives of the world's oppressed
peoples.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he is one of the world's greatest oppressors.
</P>
<P>
   Many can be swayed by the sight of hundreds of thousands of
mothers in Havana marching in support of the return of Elian
Gonzalez, or of that entire school of children at the airport last
Wednesday to welcome Elian home.
</P>
<P>
   But there are cold, harsh truths about the rule of Fidel Castro,
truths that reach beyond just the thousands who take to rafts in
search of greater economic opportunity, truths that penetrate the
walls of his prisons where dissenters are incarcerated, where many
of the basic freedoms Americans take for granted (and celebrate
Tuesday) do not exist at all.
</P>
<P>
   It is granted that the Cuban exiles, particularly those that
dominate Miami, sometimes can be their own worst enemies, that many
of the things they say and do hurt their cause more than help it.
Certainly, the Elian Gonzalez saga was one of them; wrong battle,
wrong battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   But to those of us who have lived among them all these years,
there is a greater understanding, a better knowledge of what drives
their passions. No paramount ruler since Adolf Hitler has been able
to enchant both his people and others as has Castro.
</P>
<P>
   For four decades, he has taken advantage of the embargo first
imposed upon him by the Eisenhower administration, plus a series of
military and political foibles by John F. Kennedy, to blame all his
failures on U.S. policy. Nevermind that for the first three
decades, the Soviets were his sugar-daddies who kept him well-armed
but poorly fed and industrialized. Nevermind that since the Soviet
collapse, other nations have moved in and gone into joint venture
with Castro in re-establishing Cuba as a tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the help he has received from elsewhere, the island
still is dominated by 1957 Chevys; i.e., nothing has trickled down
to the people.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the exile community often exaggerates the hardships of
Castro Cuba; they really aren't starving to death down there,
they're just not eating as well as those over here. And education
has improved since the Batista years; so have medical facilities.
</P>
<P>
   But Cuba remains a closed society; no dissension, no free
enterprise, justice denied, no free press and only recently, a
slight lifting of religious oppressions.
</P>
<P>
   The Elian period, where Miami's exiles came out looking loony to
the rest of the United States, has given new verve to Castro. He,
as did Khrushchev decades ago, speaks with new bravado of burying
American capitalism, of continuing the crusade against us.
</P>
<P>
   And now, elements of the embargo are about to be lifted which
Castro will tell his people is a victory for their cause, when in
truth it is nothing more than lobbying American farmers and
pharmaceutical companies trying to create a new market for their
goods.
</P>
<P>
   How much has Castro left us incoherent and irrational? On the
day that Elian was returned to Cuba, exiles here continued (and
accelerated) their condemnation of the Clinton administration,
saying the return was but an effort by Clinton to improve relations
with Castro. At the same precise time, their hated Clinton was
standing at his podium in the White House saying that there never
could be a normalization of Cuba during his administration because
of the murder of Cuban-American fliers near Cuba several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This twisted discord, not goods, is what feeds the Rasputin of
the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8100 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV02-C     06-29 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: GATES HITS THE E-BOOK CIRCUITS
 &HT;    Moving in the (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Bill Gates, the squire of Redmond, where
Microsoft Corp. makes its home, has no use for computer manuals.
</P>
<P>
   Gates says the software programs that have made him a rich man
since he co-founded the company 25 years ago are much too complex.
The stuff that follows in the wake of Windows, he vows, will be a
lot more simple to use. It will also respond to intuitive voice
commands, making manuals superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   Until that day, Microsoft will beef up its digital help
materials, making them accessible both within individual programs
and on line.
</P>
<P>
   Gates concedes that manuals are often useful to folks of a
certain age who learn best by turning the pages of a book. But he
is not alone in suspecting that quite a few of them are peddled to
bolster computer piracy, a fact of life in our cybertimes.
</P>
<P>
   In his new guise as Microsoft's chief software architect, Gates
dotes on all other kinds of books. All he asks, quite simply, is
that they be electronic books and that they run on Microsoft
software.
</P>
<P>
   E-books, as they are called in the publishing trade, are a hot
topic nowadays. Following the pioneering lead of Stephen King and
Michael Crichton, some authors salivate at the delectable prospect
of publishing directly on the Web without the need of hiring an
agent or having to kowtow to an imprint that offers the standard 10
percent royalty on sales.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, for most people reading on line is still no fun,
even if have great computer monitors. While mine are as good as
they come, nearly all of my non-research reading is done by turning
the pages of ordinary books.
</P>
<P>
   Gates thinks he's got a better idea. It's based on a device
known as a PC Tablet, which appears to be a major upgrade from the
$500 e-readers that Microsoft now markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we call ClearType,'' Gates said the other day in
the course of a drill he had staged for outsiders on where the
company wants to go tomorrow. ``When we talk about having the
quality of paper, can you believe how paper-like those fonts are?''
he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``So this is an electronic book, and I can read along and see a
character,'' Gates went on in his best schoolmaster manner.
``Here's 'Baker,' a character that's introduced at this point. (To)
remind myself of when the character was introduced, it's simply a
matter of highlighting, tapping and it's done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, and I can look up a word in as simple a manner as tap on
the word, tap on lookup, I see definitions for 'stretched,'
'stretching,' et cetera,'' Gates continued. ``A third tap and I'm
back reading with no visual artifacts, no clutter.''
</P>
<P>
   Without much of a stretch, it seems as if Web print-on-demand
models and e-books are likely to shake up a business model that has
essentially remained static since post-Victorian times.
</P>
<P>
   If Charles Dickens, the Victorian-era novelist who first wrote
his ``books'' for newspapers, were to come back to life, it no
doubt would be as a Web author. And Bill Gates, no doubt, would
soon be signing him up for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
