<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8127 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COURT-ABORTION-BOS &LR;      06-29 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-ABORTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT STRIKES DOWN NEBRASKA LAW BARRING PARTIAL-BIRTH ABORTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reflecting the nation's deep and emotional schism
over abortion, the US Supreme Court Wednesday narrowly restated its
27-year-old affirmation of the right to choose by ruling that a
Nebraska law banning so-called partial-birth abortions is
unconstitutional and puts an undue burden on a woman's liberty to
end a pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The closely watched decision, the court's most important on the
issue in eight years and one sure to resound in the upcoming
presidential campaign, jeopardizes as many as 30 state laws enacted
to outlaw certain abortion procedures and could derail Congress's
effort this year to pass a partial-birth bill.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen Breyer, writing for the 5-4 majority, said
Nebraska's law was unconstitutional on two counts: It lacked any
exception for protecting a woman's health, and it raised
``substantial obstacles'' to a woman obtaining a second-trimester
abortion because the wording of the ban was too broad and vague.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aware that constitutional law must govern a society whose
different members sincerely hold directly opposing views,'' Breyer
wrote, ``this court, in the course of a generation, has determined
and then redetermined that the Constitution offers basic protection
to the woman's right to choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Breyer was joined by Justices John Paul Stevens, Sandra Day
O'Connor, David H. Souter, and Ruth Bader Ginsburg. Dissenting were
Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Anthony Kennedy,
Antonin Scalia, and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion-rights advocates marked a double victory as the court
in a separate case upheld 6-3 a Colorado law that prohibits
protesters, leafleters and ``sidewalk counselors'' from approaching
within eight feet of a patient attempting to enter an abortion
clinic, saying a protest-free ``bubble'' does not violate
free-speech rights. Rehnquist sided with the majority in this case.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on partial-birth abortions, which Thomas deplored
from the bench as ``grievously wrong'' and morally indefensible,
brought both drama inside the chamber on the last day of the high
court's term and angry warnings from opponents on the plaza outside
that the ruling will not stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 5-4 decision reflects a radical expansion of the right to
abortion,'' James Bopp, general counsel of the National Right to
Life Committee, told reporters. ``The question before the country
is whether we are going to tolerate a system of invented rights to
abortion, and that question is going to be answered in large part
by the election in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates and foes of abortion rights both seized on the court's
action to remind voters that the next president is likely to name
one or more Supreme Court justices during his term, and that
nominee could easily tip the court's balance on abortion. Abortion
opponents took heart because Kennedy, who voted with the court
majority in the 1992 case of Planned Parenthood v. Casey, which
said states can place ``no undue burden'' on a woman seeking an
abortion, switched sides and dissented in the Nebraska ruling in
Stenberg v. Carhart.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential candidates weighed in, too. Texas Governor
George W. Bush, the presumptive GOP nominee and an opponent of
abortions rights, said he was ``disappointed'' by the ruling and
``unlike Al Gore, I pledge to fight for a ban on partial-birth
abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's spokesman, Chris Lehane, said the vice president supports
a woman's right to choose, including the right not to be forced to
undergo life-threatening abortion procedures. Lehane said it was
``particularly disturbing'' that Thomas and Scalia, who Bush had
called model justices, dissented from the opinion.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who twice has vetoed partial-birth abortion
bills, said during his news conference that he had ``pleaded with
Congress'' to include exceptions for the life and health of the
woman in its legislation. ``I think the court decision is clearly
the only decision it could reach consistent with Roe v. Wade,''
Clinton said, naming the 1973 landmark case that first affirmed
abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   The partial-birth case was brought to the high court by Dr.
LeRoy Carhart, a retired Air Force surgeon who began performing
abortions 1988 and runs a women's health clinic in Bellevue, Neb.
Carhart challenged the state's 1997 law, arguing that it was so
restrictive that 90 percent of the 5,000 abortions performed in the
state each year would be threatened. Under the law, physicians
convicted of performing outlawed abortion procedures would lose
their medical licenses and be subject to 20 years in jail and
$25,000 fines.
</P>
<P>
   After a federal district and appeals court ruled in Carhart's
favor, Nebraska Attorney General Don Stenberg brought the case to
the Supreme Court, where it was argued in April. Carhart, who was
at the court Wednesday, said he felt vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer's opinion hinged, in large part, on an affirmative answer
to the clinical question of whether dilation and extraction, or
D&AMP;X, a second-trimester abortion procedure in which a doctor pulls
a fetus feet first through the birth canal and then crushes its
skull and empties its contents, is ever medically necessary to
protect the mother's life. ``We recognize that D&AMP;X may be safer for
some women,'' Breyer wrote, adding that decisions on appropriate
procedures must be made by doctors, not legislators or courts.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor suggested that if Nebraska's statute had banned only
the D&AMP;X procedure and included an exception for the life and health
of the mother, ``the question presented would be quite different
than the one we face today.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said his colleagues were missing the point. He said
Americans are so repulsed by these procedures, which he called
tantamount to infanticide, that they have supported bans in 30
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``From reading the majority's sanitized description, one would
think that this case involves state regulation of a widely accepted
routine medical procedure,'' Thomas wrote. ``Nothing could be
further from the truth. The most widely used method of abortion
during this stage of pregnancy is so gruesome that its use can be
traumatic for even the physicians and medical staff who perform
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8131 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ELIAN-HOME-BOS &LR;      06-29 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-HOME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER SEVEN TUMULTUOUS MONTHS, ELIAN GOES HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old boy who survived a harrowing
journey at sea seven months ago only to be cast into the center of
an international diplomatic storm, waved goodbye to America
Wednesday and returned to Cuba in the arms of his father.
</P>
<P>
   The Gonzalez family took off in a chartered jet from Dulles
International Airport at 4:41 p.m., several hours after the Supreme
Court rejected a final appeal by the child's Miami relatives and
just 41 minutes after a lower-court injunction prohibiting Elian's
departure expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very happy to be going home,'' Juan Miguel Gonzalez
told a crowd of reporters shortly before leaving the US with his
son. During his brief statement, most of which he delivered in
Spanish, the elder Gonzalez also thanked the American people for
their support and said he hoped the United States and Cuba could
achieve ``friendship'' in the future.
</P>
<P>
   On the tarmac of a small airport in Havana, where they arrived
about three hours later, Elian and his father were greeted by the
boy's four grandparents and a group of other relatives as hundreds
of flag-waving schoolchildren sang patriotic songs and chanted:
``Elian! Elian! Elian!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The little absent prince is coming back to his homeland,'' a
state television commentator said during the ceremony, which was
broadcast live across the island. Elian, who seemed to grow
comfortable with the ominpresent TV cameras and adoring crowds
outside his home in Miami, appeared far more shy as he waved
tentatively to the crowd in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   President Fidel Castro _ who has frequently accused his critics
in the United States of exploiting Elian, even as he has used the
boy to try to score political points of his own _ did not attend
the homecoming reception.
</P>
<P>
   The protracted custody battle over Elian captured Americans'
imaginations, seemingly as much because it involved a charismatic
child who had survived against enormous odds as because of the
emotional Cold War rhetoric that framed it. The case also grew in
prominence because it provoked heated debate about an array of
controversial issues, ranging from the 41-year US trade embargo
against Cuba to the fairness of American asylum procedures to the
role of fathers in their children's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most starkly, the ferocity of the tug-of-war over Elian
demonstrated to the rest of the country the deep hatred and
distrust Cuban-Americans feel toward their homeland's communist
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the home of Elian's great-uncle in Miami's Little Havana
section, where Elian spent most of his time in this country,
protesters wept Wednesday, denounced President Clinton for having
sided with Castro on the legal resolution to the case, and
expressed concern about the boy's fate in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sad to see this young child go back . . . to a
country that's going to deprive him of his basic freedoms,'' said
Ninoska Perez, an official of the Cuban American National
Foundation. Ramon Saul Sanchez, president of the Democracy
Movement, said in a separate phone interview that he believed the
Clinton administration had orchestrated Elian's repatriation during
``secret dealings'' with the Castro government.
</P>
<P>
   During a press conference before Elian's departure Wednesday,
the president said it would have been ``fine with me'' if Juan
Miguel Gonzalez had decided to defect to the United States with his
son _ as Cuban-American officials had repeatedly suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I wish it had unfolded in a less dramatic, less traumatic
way for all concerned?'' Clinton added rhetorically. ``Of course I
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian's appearance on the world stage was a gripping and
wrenching story from the start.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, her boyfriend, and a dozen other would-be refugees
fled Cuba last Nov. 22 in a motorboat that sank as it approached
Florida several days later. Elian was found floating on an inner
tube off the coast of Fort Lauderdale on Thanksgiving Day, one of
just three Cubans to have lived through the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   After the boy spent several days hospitalized, the Immigration
and Naturalization Service granted temporary custody of the boy to
his great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez. Elian's father quickly demanded
that his son be returned to him in Cuba, however, and the tug of
war began _ with most Cuban-Americans in Southern Florida backing
Lazaro Gonzalez and Castro supporting the Clinton administration.
The Miami relatives refused to follow INS orders that they give up
custody of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno took an unusually high-profile and
hands-on approach to the case, illustrating both the Clinton
administration's political sensitivity toward the influential
Cuban-American community and Reno's personal interest in a
melodrama that was playing out in the city where she grew up and
spent most of her professional career.
</P>
<P>
   Reno ultimately ordered federal marshals to seize Elian from
Lazaro Gonzalez's home on April 22 and return him to his father,
who had flown to the United States a few weeks earlier. Juan
Gonzalez, who was divorced from Elian's mother, stayed with his
son, his new wife and their baby in a suburb of Washington, D.C.,
from that time until their departure Wednesday from Dulles
International Airport in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law has provided a process, and this little boy now knows
that he can remain with his father,'' Reno said in a statement
after Wednesday's final judicial ruling clearing the way for Elian
to leave the United States. ``All involved have had an opportunity
to make their case _ all the way to the highest court in the land.
I hope that everyone will accept the Supreme Court's decision and
join me in wishing this family, and this special little boy,
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez was being observed by a television news crew
when he got word of the Supreme Court decision. He was looking out
at the ocean behind a church in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   He turned angrily to the journalists and appeared ready to rush
at them as he shouted that they should leave. His daughter
Marisleysis, who described herself as Elian's surrogate mother
while he lived with the Miami relatives, pulled at her father's arm
and held him back.
</P>
<P>
   A family spokesman, Armando Gutierrez, told a news conference
after Elian had left the country that Lazaro Gonzalez and his
family were ``devastated'' by the boy's departure. The family had
repeatedly asked to see him since he was taken from their home, but
Juan Gonzalez said he would permit that only if they dropped their
legal fight, which they refused to do.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, a different argument held sway: that a
surviving parent has the legal right to make decisions for a minor
child _ including applying for political asylum _ regardless of
where he or she might live, unless there is evidence of abuse or
neglect. Indeed, most analysts agreed that the Elian episode would
neither have lasted so long nor achieved its high level of
prominence were it not for lingering Cold War sensitivities in this
country toward Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``A child of any other nationality stumbling over our border or
washing up on our shores would have been summarily shipped back to
his or her homeland without so much as a blip on the radar
screen,'' said Bernard Perlmutter, director of the Children and
Youth Law Clinic in Miami. ``This case has always been about the
relationship between the US and Cuba and about the power wielded by
the Cuban-American community.''
</P>
<P>
   Perlmutter and others interviewed Wednesday asserted that the
Cuban-Americans had likely undermined their political influence in
the long term with their adamant stand on Elian, mainly because it
differs so sharply from the view of most other Americans that the
boy belonged with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Several lawmakers said they already detected that waning power
in the GOP leadership's expressed willingness this week to make
exceptions for food and medicine in the US embargo against Cuba.
``They still have a big voice, but their behavior on Elian . . . is
absolutely going to be seen as a turning point,'' said US
Representative Joe Moakley of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez and his family reportedly heard the news that they
could go home on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were elated, absolutely elated,'' said Christina Fitz, a
spokeswoman for Youth for Understanding International Exchange, the
student-exchange organization that provided a home to the
Gonzalezes during the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Fitz described the farewell message that Elian's father left to
his hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am leaving you with two Cuban flags,'' he wrote. ``One big
one and one little one as a token and the first step in the
direction of a human and beautiful relationship between our two
countries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
