<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS AILING AFTER DIFFICULT WIN OVER KUCERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A day punctuated by a parade of exclamation points
ended with a huge, ominous question mark hovering over the All
England Lawn Tennis &AMP; Croquet Club.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty involved Pete Sampras, who is trying to tie
Willie Renshaw's century-old mark for Wimbledon men's singles
titles (seven) and break the record he shares with Roy Emerson for
most Grand Slam singles crowns worn by a male (12).
</P>
<P>
   In a surprisingly arduous 7-6 (9-7), 3-6, 6-3, 6-4 second-round
victory Wednesday night over Karol Kucera, Sampras had his left
ankle taped and later took a tumble. Afterward, he was expected for
the customary postmatch press conference.
</P>
<P>
   But it was announced he would be unavailable because he was at a
hospital undergoing a magnetic resonance imaging of his inflamed
left foot, a condition that will be reevaluated Thursday. The
injury could jeopardize Sampras's scheduled match with Justin
Gimelstob Friday _ and halt his march toward history.
</P>
<P>
   The silence from Sampras resonated throughout the Wimbledon
grounds, which had been reverberating from the shock waves of the
day's earlier activities.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest jolt was the departure of Magnus Norman, who is
ranked second in the world and third in this field. The
hardest-working man in tennis _ he's played more singles matches
than any of his colleagues this year _ Norman got a most unwelcome
breather because of a suffocating 6-4, 2-6, 6-7, 6-1 loss to
Belgian qualifier Olivier Rochus.
</P>
<P>
   The indefatigable Swede led an exodus of seeds that included the
No. 4 woman (Conchita Martinez) and the No. 6 and No. 11 men
(Cedric Pioline and Richard Krajicek, respectively).
</P>
<P>
   If that wasn't enough, there were also two notable breaches of
etiquette by nonentities apparently intent on horning in on the
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Tempestuous Jeff Tarango, who earned everlasting infamy when his
wife slapped an umpire here five years ago, this time avoided
contact. He refused the traditional postmatch handshake with his
opponent and fellow Stanford alumnus, Paul Goldstein, whom he
accused of dirty tricks at the end of their four-hour, five-set
grinder. The fact that Goldstein won the match was undoubtedly
coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   And Anna Smashnova provided a unique twist on spousal disputes.
Nagged from the stands by her opponent's husband during her
three-set win over Katalin Marosi-Aracama, Smashnova fired a ball
at him _ but instead skulled a female spectator.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras's situation superseded all that, much to his dismay. The
top seed already had a gimpy back when he launched his Wimbledon
defense, and he was clearly struggling against Kucera, whom he had
beaten in five of six previous meetings. As dusk descended on
Centre Court, there were doubts Sampras would have time to dispose
of Kucera. After the third set, there were doubts he would have
enough healthy body parts to survive Kucera.
</P>
<P>
   Leading, 5-2, in the third set, Sampras called an injury timeout
while a trainer treated his ankle. Then while making a lunging
volley for set point, he slipped and fell to the turf. He rolled
over and winced but quickly regained his footing, then finished the
job against Kucera. It remains to be seen whether he'll be on the
job against Gimelstob.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Sampras went to the emergency room, Norman was
nursing a severely bruised ego. Two weeks after finishing as
runner-up in the French Open, he couldn't handle an occupant of the
rankings netherworld (No. 179) who needed to win a qualifying
tournament in Portugal last week just to get on the grounds here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my first win with a Top 100,'' said Rochus after causing
the ruckus. ``Today I beat the No. 2. It's great, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman would disagree. Often dismissed as a dull workaholic, he
entertained the Court 1 crowd with quite a demonstration of
self-disgust.
</P>
<P>
   After being broken to 5-5 in the third set, he made a
ferociously authoritative bounce pass toward the stands. It would
have gone over great in the NBA Finals, but unfortunately for
Norman, he was abusing the tennis racket that was betraying him.
</P>
<P>
   After surviving the set by taking five straight tiebreaker
points for a 7-4 verdict, Norman was hapless in the finale. But at
least he wasn't humorless.
</P>
<P>
   Called for a foot fault while serving at 5-0, Norman, who had
disputed several rulings, plaintively walked over to ball girl
Lauren Graham, handed her his racket and three tennis balls, and
implored her to take his place at the service line. Flustered, she
nonetheless fulfilled his request, lofting two soft underhand lobs
to Rochus's side of the court before dumping the third into the
net. Then Norman reluctantly reclaimed the racket. He won that
game, then netted a return of serve on Rochus's second match point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing so poorly, so I thought, `Hey, she's going to do
better than me,' '' said Norman. ``She actually did.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Norman had company among those who did badly.
</P>
<P>
   Poetic justice prevailed when Krajicek didn't. The 1996
Wimbledon king was evicted from Centre Court by Wayne Ferreira,
5-7, 6-3, 6-3, 7-6. Ferreira had expressed sympathy for the three
highly ranked Spaniards who had withdrawn from the tournament
because of Wimbledon's abitrary pecking order, which had
disregarded their world standings and deprived them of any of the
16 seeds. Ferreira's protest was more tangible because his victim,
Krajicek, had been one of the prime beneficiaries of Wimbledon's
whims, elevated from his No. 27 world ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Pioline, the 1993 US Open and 1997 Wimbledon runner-up, lost a
heartbreaker to Vladimir Voltchkov, 6-3, 6-3, 2-6, 3-6, 6-4.
Pioline just turned 31 but dismissed the notion age had done more
damage to him than Voltchkov had.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose form, whatever, if you are 15 years old or 50
years old, it's the same,'' he said. ``Doesn't matter which age you
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was another casualty on a terrible afternoon for French
Open runners-up. Like Norman, her male counterpart in Paris,
Martinez _ who won here in 1994 _ was ambushed by an unknown,
Canada's Sonya Jeyaseelan, 6-4, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't . . . it hasn't sunk in yet,'' said Jeyaseelan.
</P>
<P>
   That, in fact, was Wimbledon's theme of the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
