<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The boyfriends: Where my daughters go, boys follow
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I've reached a new stage in my relationship with
my now-grown daughters. The oldest is a college graduate now
looking for a job making mega-bucks but willing to settle for
enough to pay her rent and car note, now that she's been downsized
from the patriarchal payroll. The youngest is a sophomore who is
only tangentially aware of the real world of bills and financial
obligations and has no intention of delving further into this
sphere until it's absolutely necessary. They live together in
Austin, a four-hour drive from here, which I believe to be an ideal
distance from one's grown children. It's close enough to make
weekend visits possible but not so close they're showing up every
weekend to cadge your food and use your washing machine and
gasoline card.
</P>
<P>
   I have survived dealing with my daughters' numerous car wrecks
and other late-night crises. It now appears altogether likely that
neither child will be sentenced to a lengthy prison term _
certainly always a victory for a parent and never a sure thing. The
youngest plans on being a famous writer of movie scripts and plays,
and I would not be surprised if she accomplished her goal. The
oldest has more modest but no less-worthy goals, to be a speech
therapist. Life is good. Now I must learn to adjust to the constant
presence of:
</P>
<P>
   THE BOYFRIENDS.
</P>
<P>
   I am possibly looking at my future sons-in-law _ at least one
and maybe both. Who knows? Jason and Matt are nice-looking, polite
kids with whom I have a decent relationship, meaning that I haven't
threatened them with bodily harm if they lay a hand on my
daughters. I have come a long way since my girls first started
dating, and I interrogated each beau while maintaining a cool,
gruff demeanor at all times and a shotgun in the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's... whatever. You're grown, you're gone. I am no longer
in control, not that I ever was to any degree.
</P>
<P>
   The key change in the past year or so is that the daughters do
not return to East Texas without the boyfriends. When I visit
Austin and invite them out to eat, guess who else is coming to
dinner? The boyfriends, of course. The boyfriends are ever-present,
both members of the UT band who live in the same apartment complex
as my daughters. I have no interest in further information and
details.
</P>
<P>
   I am not complaining, understand. As I said, both are pleasant
young men who like golf and music and willingly carry on
intelligent conversations with people twice their age, which puts
them a cut above most previous beaus. My mother thinks the
boyfriends are adorable and keeps pushing my daughters to get
married and presumably have babies so she can be a
great-grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what that would make me, besides even more broke after
paying for a wedding? ``Grampa Gary'' does not have a pleasant ring
to it, at least at the moment. I would like to at least reach the
half-century mark before that happens, though I have remarkably
little say into all this.
</P>
<P>
   The constant presence of the boyfriend is preparation for the
Next Big Change, which is taking on the title of father-in-law. At
the least, I hope there is a decent interval between receipt of
that appellation and that Grampa Gary thing.
</P>
<P>
   I'm resigned to it. From now on, a visit from the girls will
include boyfriends and later husbands, who may or may not be the
same young men sitting on my back porch last weekend, drinking my
soda waters and waxing poetically over my grilled burgers.
</P>
<P>
   Then a crop of babies will appear. I will be Grampa Gary for the
rest of my life.
</P>
<P>
   I've already warned the boyfriends: Don't even think about
calling me Dad. My given name will do just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
