<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Democrats may come to regret decision to leave 2000 ballot open
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ralph Nader's formal designation last weekend as
the presidential nominee of the pro-environment, anti-corporate
Green Party has the chance to be a real problem for the Democratic
nominee, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But for Texas Democrats, 2000 is just the beginning of the
problem. Fast-forward to 2002, which Democrats, who once ruled
Texas, have earmarked as a rebuilding year. They plan to field a
full ballot and hope to recapture some of the statewide offices
they have lost to the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party could be the Texas Democrats' worst nightmare _
and the Democrats don't seem to realize it yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats did not field candidates against incumbent
Republicans for several statewide offices. The Greens plan to field
candidates for some of them, including two seats on the Texas
Railroad Commission and a slot on the Texas Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if they get on the ballot. The Greens this spring
launched a signature-collecting campaign to do so. They had to
collect 37,380 signatures of registered voters who did not vote in
either the Republican or Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   To be on the safe side, the Greens presented 75,911 signatures
to the Texas secretary of state's office, which oversees Texas
elections. Those signatures have been sent back to counties where
the voters reside to be sure they're eligible to be counted.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Hanshaw, director of the legal division for the
secretary of state, says that accounting should be finished by late
July _ and the Greens should learn by Aug. 1 whether they've
achieved ballot status.
</P>
<P>
   If they do, they've got candidates poised to run for the
statewide positions the Democrats chose not to contest: Gary
Dugger, an Austin United Parcel Service driver and son of Texas
Observer founder Ronnie Dugger, for the Railroad Commission seat
held by Charles Matthews; Charlie Mauch, an environmental engineer
from Houston, for the Railroad Commission seat held by Michael
Williams; and Ben Levy, a Houston lawyer, for the Supreme Court
seat held by Nathan Hecht.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where the problem clicks in for the Democrats: If the
Greens get 5 percent in just one statewide race, they're
automatically qualified for the ballot in 2002, without having to
gather petition signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the past performance of third-party candidates in races
where only one major-party candidate is on the ballot, the Greens
will get at least 5 percent in one of those races _ if not in all
three. The Libertarian Party candidates have done so in election
after election since 1986 in races for seats where either Democrats
or Republicans failed to run.
</P>
<P>
   In several statewide races over the years _ including
gubernatorial wins by Democrat Ann Richards in 1990 and Republican
Bill Clements in 1978 _ the victor got less than a majority. That
was because of third-party candidates drawing some of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   So in 2002, presume that the Greens field candidates for
governor, lieutenant governor, the U.S. Senate and other offices
down the ballot. Again, if the past is a predictor, even in races
where both parties are represented, third-party efforts can draw of
2, 3, even 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And they're more like to come off the Democrats' tallies, given
that the Greens are represented by folks such as populist Dugger,
who ran for the Railroad Commission as a Democrat in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats Paul Hobby for comptroller and John Sharp for
lieutenant governor lost their races by less than 1 percent in
1998. In 2002, a left-leaning Green candidate could make things
even tougher for Democrats in close races.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic Party Chair Molly Beth Malcolm predicts the
Greens won't bother the Democrats in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always welcome an open honest debate on issues, because
that's a healthy part of democracy,'' Malcolm said. ``But I don't
think it's going to have an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Texas voters ``will see that we're supporting issues
that are important to Texans _ public education, health care and a
balance between a cleaner environment and moving this economy
forward. But we sure do want to have clean air to breathe and clean
water to drink _ that's important for the economy as well. And that
can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Malcolm's optimism, if the Democrats lose a few points
to the Greens in 2002, they're going to wish they'd run a full
ballot in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
