r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN30-COX     06-29 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sacrificing student safety, performance on UIL altar
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Someone refresh me why Waco High School needs that
5A by its name.
</P>
<P>
   So it can compete with Temple in football once a year, and
Odessa Permian once every other decade, that's why.
</P>
<P>
   Is that enough to put a pinch on student performance and to hand
administrators untenable crowd-control issues?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently. Apparently Waco needs to show how big it is.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Waco school trustees discussed the so-called
importance of 5A was over the question of magnet A.J. Moore Academy
offering University Interscholastic League sports and other
activities. It has no UIL sports, and Waco High's potential loss of
5A designation was the biggest reason why any such option was
scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the size of Waco High, roughly 2,000 students, became
an issue with concerns that halls were hard to monitor, classes
were way too large, and several teachers had to float without their
own classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers also cited an odd modern-day condition: a few students
who played hooky but didn't leave the building, shuffling from
restroom to restroom to cafeteria to cubby-hole, anywhere but
class.
</P>
<P>
   Things should be better this year, space- and numbers-wise. The
completion of the new performing arts building will create limited
classroom space. Additionally, A.J. Moore will welcome its fourth
freshman class, its final complement, siphoning additional students
away.
</P>
<P>
   We can hope that these two ingredients are the vents that allow
people to breathe at Waco High. But we should not be satisfied just
to breathe in and out.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is indisputable that smaller groupings of students
produce better conditions, whether in a classroom or in a student
body. That coin has two sides, of course. At some point ``smaller''
means sacrificing class options. A median can be found between too
large and too small.
</P>
<P>
   A two-year study out of Chicago urges the pursuit of that median
_ a shift away from bigger schools _ something Waco voters
essentially did this year at the middle school level by approving a
new middle school to relieve overcrowding at University Middle.
</P>
<P>
   But even within a large campus like Waco High there are ways to
make things more intimate. One of the best ways is with
subgroupings.
</P>
<P>
   Many have observed that the addition of freshmen two years ago
brought challenges not experienced when numbers were close to the
same and the school had only three grades.
</P>
<P>
   One approach seems obvious, then: Create a largely
self-contained ninth-grade wing. Do everything possible to make
ninth-graders feel part of a group, rather than grains of sand
sprinkled on a vast beach. Administrators discussed this last year.
They must follow through. Middle schools do this routinely,
insulating sixth-graders to the extent possible from, say,
eighth-graders who are growing facial hair. It helps. It matters.
</P>
<P>
   That certainly is one thing Waco High needs, some
community-building among newcomers who otherwise get lost in the
shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, though, Waco High would have even fewer students. Yes,
that might mean sacrificing 5A status. A.J. Moore should be the
outlet. A modest increase in its capacity, roughly to 900 (capacity
now is 680, which it will come close to meeting), would benefit
both schools. A student body of 900 would merit more program
options. Ideally, A.J. Moore would have UIL sports, making it easy
to attract enough students and to cement itself as a full-fledged,
full-service magnet high school.
</P>
<P>
   A question, Waco: Any problem with ideal? If pitting Waco High
vs. Permian every other decade is your idea of ideal, question your
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the Opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
