<HEADER>
A8151 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GARCIA-COLUMN30-COX     06-29 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An honest election in Mexico? It could happen
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY -- If Mexico's ruling party wins the July 2
presidential election, who would believe the results? Certainly not
the army of critics of the Party of the Institutional Revolution
(known by its Spanish acronym of PRI). The PRI has held power in
Mexico for seven decades, but in the last couple its stranglehold
on the Congress is weakened considerably. The PRI has lost its
monopoly on governorships and local offices to the point where some
PRI-istas are quick to note that they are an opposition party, not
a dominant one.
</P>
<P>
   ``One half of Mexico is governed by parties other than the
PRI,'' Rosario Green, Mexico's foreign minister, noted during a
conversation with a delegation representing the American Society of
Newspaper Editors. It was her way of saying that there is political
competition in Mexico and has been, contrary to the stereotype that
clings to the country.
</P>
<P>
   In days past, the PRI was pretty shameless in the way it
manipulated elections. The culmination was 1988 when Carlos Salinas
de Gortari was locked in a close race with challenger Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas. During the vote count, the computers went down
mysteriously and when they came back up, Salinas and PRI had won.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky guy, no? Actually no. Later, there were widespread reports
of electoral fraud, but Salinas kept the presidential sash.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office, Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo has
pushed and prodded -- often over howls of protest from his own
party -- for what Mexicans call transparent elections. His critics
note that Zedillo may have had little choice in the matter and
credit a persistent opposition for electoral reform.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever gets the credit, there is little doubt that the process
is a clean one.
</P>
<P>
   Voters are issued registration cards with their photo and a
computer bar code on them to prevent individuals from voting early
and often. Moreover, the thumbs of people who vote are dipped in
black ink that is impossible to remove for a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Carrillo, an official of the independent federal election
commission, also explained that representatives of each party are
present when election judges open ballot boxes to count votes.
</P>
<P>
   He described intricate security on the electoral computer
system. There is not a system that can't be beaten, but you have to
go a long way to scam this one.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's going to happen if Francisco Labastida, the PRI
candidate, wins July 2 in a squeaker ?
</P>
<P>
   No doubt you'll hear accusations of fraud. And those will have a
receptive audience given the long history of chicanery in Mexican
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the fact that there is a question about the outcome
reflects a sea change in Mexican politics.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that the contest between Labastida and Vicente Fox,
the nominee of the National Action Party (PAN) is tight. The
country is ready for change, it is thought, and change is what Fox
pitches. In retort, Labastida claims his candidacy represents
change with a purpose -- a jab at Fox, who can be quite
unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Lund, who has been conducting polling in Mexico for many
years, cautions against jumping to too many conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Women, a growing influence in Mexican politics, are attracted to
Fox's message but are wary of the messenger, Lund said.
Furthermore, Mexicans are conservative by nature and wary of rapid
change, Lund observed. That might work in the PRI's favor.
</P>
<P>
   Those are but a couple of logical reasons that indicate that the
PRI could win legitimately . Mexicans love irony, and there is
nothing more ironic than the PRI's past casting a shadow, long and
deep, over an election the party could well win honestly.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at (512) 445-3667 or
agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
