<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION (Leon, Mexico) _ In the final phase of Mexico's
presidential election, candidates must keep a low profile and
cannot air television campaign ads. On Saturday, alcohol sales will
be barred throughout the country until the Sunday election is over.
By SUSANNA HAYWARD and BONNIE PFISTER.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WILLIE-BROWN (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie
Brown's administration is moving to cut off city funding to a
nonprofit group whose executive director cooperated in the FBI's
criminal probe of public works contracting in San Francisco. By
CHUCK FINNIE and LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMISSIONER-RESIGN (Sacramento, Calif.) _ At the heart of
California Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush's resignation
sits the central dilemma of every elected official: how to legally
separate politics from your public work. Where Gov. Gray Davis has
become a master of the so-called ``perpetual campaign'' _ an
independent political workshop that includes pollsters, consultants
and fund-raisers _ Quackenbush utterly failed to keep the two
rivers divided. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCOUTS-GAYS (San Francisco) _ A U.S. Supreme Court decision
allowing the Boy Scouts of America to bar gay troop leaders from
the organization will force youths into an impossible predicament,
say critics of the ruling. ``Gay youths are put in a Catch-22
situation _ they are told by the scouts to be open and honest and,
yet, if they are, they are told they will be kicked out,'' said Jon
Davidson, supervising attorney in the Los Angeles office of Lambda
Legal Defense and Education Fund. By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BRAIN-APPETITE (San Antonio) _ Scientists at the University of
Texas Health Science Center are a little closer to understanding
how the brain responds to food, devising a way to keep track of how
quickly and how strongly the appetite control center responds after
eating. By CINDY TUMIEL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ Lawyers hired by the Hearst
Corp. have started closed-door questioning of Examiner reporters in
an investigation into suspended Publisher Timothy O. White's
testimony that he offered Mayor Willie Brown favorable editorials
in exchange for support of Hearst's purchase of the San Francisco
Chronicle. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND-ECONOMY (Oakland, Calif.) _ It's a familiar tune that
has already been heard elsewhere in the Bay Area: corporate wealth,
fueled by the pesky dot-coms, is pushing out nonprofit
organizations that serve the poor. The same problem that has been
noted in San Francisco and Silicon Valley is now knocking on
downtown Oakland's door. By MATTHEW YI.
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ A television special this month
on the musical highlights from ``The Ed Sullivan Show'' had a great
workplace anecdote about what happened when two egos collided:
those of Sullivan and Jim Morrison, lead singer of The Doors. In
1967, Sullivan got so mad at Morrison's performance that The Doors
group was never invited to return to the show. What happened
between Sullivan and Morrison is the same sort of thing that can
happen between talented bosses and talented employees. By DAVE
MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WEDDING-ATTIRE (Undated) _ Selecting wedding attire can be
stressful, but Ilene Beckerman's new book finds humor in the
situation for at least one member of the bridal party _ the mother
of the bride. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
