<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8171 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-OPRAH-COLUMN-N     06-29 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-OPRAH-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHENOMENALLY, PHENOMENAL OPRAH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Thursday, June 29, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Phenomenally, phenomenal woman, that's me.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Oprah Winfrey at her ``Personal Growth Summit'' in Detroit on
June 23.
</P>
<P>
   Mark your personal growth calendars, people, for we have reached
the moment when Oprah Winfrey has officially crossed the transom
from world's largest ego to flat-out having a messiah complex.
</P>
<P>
   This is the conclusion I've come to after immersing myself in
all things Oprah for an entire day.
</P>
<P>
   First I checked out some newspaper clippings, notably an
excellent story in the Ottawa Citizen about Oprah's ``Personal
Growth Summit'' in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Upon entering the arena, each member of the audience received a
tote bag containing a nightshirt, inspirational candles, skin
cream, mascara, lipstick and two chocolates, along with a green
journal embossed with a gold ``O'' and a courtesy-of-Microsoft
silver pen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Write this down,'' Oprah reportedly commanded her flock. ``You
become what you believe. You. Become. What. You. Believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Segments from Oprah's show were played, including the testimony
of a woman who bought a pair of Oprah's shoes at a charity sale:
``I bought her shoes and kept them under my bed, and when I got
really, really depressed, times when I didn't have anybody to talk
to, I took out the shoes and I ...''
</P>
<P>
   At this point the woman breaks down and cries.
</P>
<P>
   Now then. You'd think that any mere mortal would cringe and say,
``I'm sorry, but that's so misguided of you, to use my shoes as
inspiration. Only Jesus should be worshipped that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Oprah. She tears up and says, ``Stood in my shoes. To make
herself better she would stand in my shoes. And now she doesn't
have to stand in the shoes as much because she's ... standing on
her own.''
</P>
<P>
   Good God. How can a human being, even one who has accomplished
so much, get to a place where she could believe such tripe about
herself?
</P>
<P>
   I turned from the clippings to the ``Oprah'' show on TV, just as
she was introducing the ``Spirit'' segment, featuring author Denise
Linn, who explained how a bedroom can ``feed one's soul'' if you
can believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My bedroom is my sanctuary,'' she said. ``It's the place where
I can connect with my spirit ... It's important to have space
underneath the bed, to have a sense of clarity, even if it can't be
seen. Our subconscious mind is aware that directly beneath our body
is a lot of disorganization.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the April issue of Playboy and a dust bunny the
size of a catcher's mitt.
</P>
<P>
   Next I turned to the latest issue of O magazine, with Oprah on
the cover in a $920 pantsuit ensemble and Bach platinum earrings.
</P>
<P>
   She's on a sailboat. Looking like she doesn't spend a lot of
time on a sailboat.
</P>
<P>
   The first issue of O had 14 pictures of O. This one has 12. Not
counting the five pictures of Oprah on O subscription cards.
</P>
<P>
   I flipped past the ``Live in the Moment'' calendar (July 28:
``This day, have no regrets'') and read Oprah's article about the
``Spa Girls,'' a group of friends who gathered at Oprah's farm for
a week of exercising, dieting and beauty treatments, augmented by
in-person counseling from Oprah's chef, Oprah's personal trainer,
one of Oprah's favorite motivational speakers, etc. In other words,
just the sort of thing a working mom can relate to.
</P>
<P>
   From there I turned to Oprah's web site and read this posting:
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest way for me to connect to my spirit, to connect
with the capital WHO of who I am _ not Oprah Winfrey talk show
host, not Oprah Winfrey actress, not Oprah Winfrey whatever the
image, is through meditation ...''
</P>
<P>
   Wow. You have to be dazzled by such unapologetic
self-absorption.
</P>
<P>
   And now I'm starting to dive into Barbara Kingsolver's ``The
Poisonwood Bible,'' the latest selection of Oprah's Book Club. All
I can say for sure is I don't think Jim Carrey will be optioning
it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact I could spend the rest of the week reading
Oprah-recommended materials, trying Oprah-recommended diets and
workouts, lighting Oprah-recommended candles, listening to
Oprah-recommended speakers, purchasing Oprah-recommended items _
but we all know I'm never going to join the Church of Oprah.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what some have claimed, I don't ``hate'' Oprah. I don't
hate anybody. There is much to be admired in this woman. She has
used her monumental wealth and power to help thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
   But she's a contradiction with every breath she takes in public
_ basking without humility in her own glory while also trying so
desperately hard to find inner peace through meditation and diet
and candles and quotes and resolutions and workouts and, and, and
... it never stops.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could take her out for a couple of beers and a load of
laughs with some regular people, I really do. I wish she could see
that you don't have to be the center of attention and you don't
have to strain so much to find a few hours of happiness in this
world.
</P>
<P>
   And yeah, I wish people wouldn't find spiritual inspiration from
her shoes.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
