<P>
   EDITORIAL-RXINSURANCE _ Should a 65-year-old Bill Gates only be
required to pay $25 a month for prescription drug insurance? Should
drug costs for senior citizens be left to the profit motives of the
insurance and drug industries? (The Atlanta Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ I've reached a new stage in my
relationship with my now-grown daughters. The oldest is a college
graduate now looking for a job making mega-bucks but willing to
settle for enough to pay her rent and car note, now that she's been
downsized from the patriarchal payroll. The youngest is a sophomore
who is only tangentially aware of the real world of bills and
financial obligations and has no intention of delving further into
this sphere until it's absolutely necessary. (Gary Borders is
editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel.) EMBARGOED
for Sunday. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GARCIA-COLUMN _ MEXICO CITY -- If Mexico's ruling party wins the
July 2 presidential election, who would believe the results?
Certainly not the army of critics of the Party of the Institutional
Revolution (known by its Spanish acronym of PRI). The PRI has held
power in Mexico for seven decades, but in the last couple its
stranglehold on the Congress is weakened considerably. (Arnold
Garcia is editorial page editor of the Austin American-Statesman)
MOVEDMCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Ralph Nader's formal
designation last weekend as the presidential nominee of the
pro-environment, anti-corporate Green Party has the chance to be a
real problem for the Democratic nominee, Vice President Al Gore.
(McNeely, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ Last year the size of Waco High, roughly 2,000
students, became an issue with concerns that halls were hard to
monitor, classes were way too large, and several teachers had to
float without their own classrooms. The evidence is indisputable
that smaller groupings of students produce better conditions,
whether in a classroom or in a student body. That coin has two
sides, of course. At some point ``smaller'' means sacrificing class
options. A median can be found between too large and too small.
(John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald)
MOVED.
</P>
