u l BC-BRITAIN-DOME-$ADV01-C     06-29 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-DOME-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PANNING BRITAIN'S MILLENNIUM DOME: Expensive attraction's slow
start confuses some, angers others
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENWICH, England _ Emerging from the Body Zone on a recent
afternoon, David Owens said he had seen enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right then, that's it,'' fumed Owens, whose annoyance was
stimulating a powerful desire for a cigarette. ``I'm embarrassed as
an Englishman, as a European and as a human being. They spent
untold millions on this and at the end of the day it's money down
the pipe, isn't it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Body Zone is perhaps the best known of the 14 themed sectors
in the Millennium Dome, the US$1.2 billion attraction intended to
make an important statement about modern Britain at the dawn of the
new century.
</P>
<P>
   However, at the midpoint of the Dome's troubled life, the
statement being delivered is not exactly what its backers had in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, who paid about US$100 for a family ticket, waited 30
minutes with his wife and twin 5-year-olds to enter the colossal
peach-colored, androgynous body. The journey began with a view of a
giant naval _ pierced stylishly with a huge ring _ continued with a
ride up an arm past the thunderous pounding of a giant heart, a
talking brain, a Volkswagen-sized eyeball and then down the stairs
and out the leg.
</P>
<P>
   After finally lighting up and taking a thoughtful puff, the best
thing Owens could say about the experience was that it was brief.
</P>
<P>
   ``What, five minutes?'' he asked his speechless wife. ``I can
withstand anything for five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Britain must withstand six months more of the misery
generated by the ill-fated Dome since its inauguration on New
Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Dome quietly welcomed its 3 millionth visitor.
That's the good news. The bad news is that the attraction's
managers last year projected that the Dome would have 12 million
visitors for the year that is now half over.
</P>
<P>
   After a disappointing opening in January the projections were
slashed to 7 million _ a figure that may still be elusive.
</P>
<P>
   Slow ticket sales have had the predictable effect on the bottom
line. Losses are reported in the British media to be already more
than US$150 million. In May, the government had to come up with a
nearly US$50 million emergency cash injection to keep the doors
open. The government intends to sell the Dome in July to a private
bidder. At the end of the year, it is to be reconfigured into some
other use.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun, Britain's largest selling tabloid, reported earlier
this week that the Dome would run out of money in September and
close four months early _ an assertion that the Dome's management
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the most recent group of managers, headed by
EuroDisney veteran Pierre-Yves Gerbeau, acknowledges that the
earlier attendance estimates were wildly optimistic and that the
Dome has been slow to work its way into the public's heart.
</P>
<P>
   Gerbeau, a Frenchman who speaks with an American accent, blames
much of the problem on the British press, which has been gleefully
merciless in its attacks on the Dome.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gerbeau used an appearance at Parliament to appeal
for less vitriolic coverage. ``Why don't you stand behind us for a
change and let us prove ourselves to the general public,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dome's new advertising campaign urges the public to ignore
the press. A new television spot casts Dome critics as sheep and
ends with the line, ``You've got a mind of your own _ take it to
the Millennium Dome.''
</P>
<P>
   However, people seem to be taking their minds elsewhere. In a
nagging coincidence, the new and much acclaimed Tate Modern museum
also marked a milestone Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Open just seven weeks a few miles up the River Thames, the Tate
welcomed its millionth visitor and is on a pace to become London's
surprise top attraction for the year.
</P>
<P>
   This can be explained by two important factors: the Tate is free
and in central London. A ticket to the Dome is more than US$30 and
the structure is set in a car-free zone on former industrial land
about 15 miles east of London.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, many observers believe the Tate provides the smart
and funky experience promised but not delivered by the Dome.
Stephen Bayley, who resigned as creative director of the Dome
before its opening, believes that the Tate has been well-received
because it appeals to the public's intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``People so wanted something intelligent, smart and optimistic
and now it seems as though it is Tate Modern that has supplied
that,'' Bayley said. ``The Tate does not characterize the British
public as drooling morons, whereas the Dome insults with
patronizing rubbish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dome is a national disgrace, a catastrophically expensive
lesson and we should all be ashamed. The dimwits responsible should
be publicly stoned.''
</P>
<P>
   While there have been a number of resignations, no one has been
stoned _ so far.
</P>
<P>
   Dome designers say they meant to appeal to the masses and are
dismissive of complaints that they dumbed down the exhibits. ``We
have been accused of having low standards and pandering to the
lowest common denominator, but I don't apologize for that at all,''
Ben Evans, one of the Dome's four content editors, said in a recent
BBC radio interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted it to be family-orientated and to be inclusive, not
exclusive, and ensure that as many people as possible could come
and enjoy themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The 14 zones within the huge Teflon-roofed structure _ which is
twice the size of the Georgia Dome _ were intended to illustrate
human life, work and play as well as the social and environmental
challenges of the 21st century. Unlike Disney's Epcot Center, the
exhibits are not rides but rather strolls, climbs or meanderings
through the subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Body Zone, the Dome offers such attractions
as the Journey Zone, which chronicles the history of
transportation; the Money Zone, which invites visitors to spend
vast sums and watch the inflationary effects of their extravagance;
and the Faith Zone, which represents various forms of religious
worship.
</P>
<P>
   Some zones may seem peculiar at best to a visitor. Living
Island, which faithfully replicates the Spartan pleasures of a
British beach, offers a fine collection of what can be best
described as washed up garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Other sectors are more successful. The Play Zone has a variety
of entertaining family games, and the Self Portrait Zone, with its
thousands of photographs contributed by ordinary and famous
Britons, makes a fine national time capsule.
</P>
<P>
   The Dome also seems to fare better with conventional
entertainment. Each day, the Millennium Show provides a stunning
extravaganza of dance, acrobatics and high-wire theatrics in the
Dome's cavernous central arena.
</P>
<P>
   Impressively, the Dome also offers the largest McDonald's
restaurant in the world _ an odd feature in an attraction intended
to celebrate modern Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Dome's standing as favorite target for the city's
journalists, comedians and artsy class, it nevertheless does seem
to please many of its visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Loren Keene, who also exited the Body Zone on a recent
afternoon, said she was impressed. ``I'm quite weary with all the
comments in the press,'' she said. ``I think this is a bright and
cheerful place, and many of the exhibits are brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Dome's managers constantly remind everyone that
their studies show that people who actually see the Dome enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   Gerbeau, the Dome's chief executive, believes he will achieve
the revised target of 7 million visitors, which would place it
among Europe's most popular attractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``By any standards, the Dome is clearly an overwhelming success
both in terms of visitor numbers and the positive feedback from
those who visit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, many visitors may share the reaction of French
President Jacques Chirac, who had only one question after seeing a
model of the Dome in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's it for?'' asked a puzzled Chirac.
</P>
<P>
   The answer still isn't completely clear.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http//:london.millennium-dome-uk.com
</P>
<P>
   http//:www.londontown.com
</P>
<P>
   http//:www.tate.org.uk
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
