   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' news category)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-U.S. (Havana) _ On the future of U.S.-Cuban relations
following the return of Elian Gonzalez to Cuba and moves by the
United States to relax its embargo. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-KOHL (Berlin) _ With a swaggering contempt for his
accusers, former chancellor Helmut Kohl appeared Thursday before a
parliamentary committee investigating financial misdeeds under his
rule and said he was a victim of slander. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story will move by 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-VOTE (Kampala) _ A referendum Thursday will determine
whether to continue the government's ``no party'' system, which the
opposition sees as a one-party system. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-POLITICS (Dateline to come) _ Developments following
the parliamentary elections last weekend. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT-MIDEAST (Washington) _ Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright was scheduled to brief President Clinton on her talks with
Israeli and Palestinian officials and the prospects for an
Israeli-Palestinian summit meeting. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-DEVELOP (United Nations) _ The annual report of the U.N.
Development Program painted a grim picture for Africa and noted the
continuing information gaps between poor and rich countries. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES &LR;  _ General
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-RIGHTS (Undated) _ On possible further developments in
the battle over late-term abortion, following the Supreme Court
ruling on Thursday. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI (Miami) _ The scene in Miami's Cuban-American
community after Elian's return to Cuba. By Rick Bragg. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DECLARATION-AUCTION (New York) _ Sotheby's online auction of an
original copy of the Declaration of Independence may fetch upwards
of $4 million. By James Barron.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-AIRCRAFT (Lod, Israel) _ In the past 15 years, Israel
Aircraft Industries, a military contractor, has moved from
bankruptcy into an export-driven powerhouse. A major contract it
signed with China to convert an Ilyushin aircraft into a modern
radar plane showcased the company's strengths. But if the Pentagon
has its way, the converted Ilyushin will never get to China. By
William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-DAEWOO (Seoul, South Korea) _ Ford offered $6.9 billion,
much more than had been expected, for Daewoo Motor, the No. 2
Korean auto company, and was granted the exclusive right to
negotiate a final deal with the struggling company's credits. Ford
seems determined to acquire Daewoo, despite the opposition of
Korean workers. By Samuel Len.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   NY-TALL-SHIPS (New York) _ An estimated 5 million spectators are
expected to throng New York City's shores next week for what may be
the greatest nautical spectacle of all time _ an event drawing well
over 120 tall ships, some 42 warships from the United States and 25
other nations and 50,000 to 70,000 small pleasure craft. By Ralph
Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   ALICE-NEEL-PAINTINGS (Undated) _ Alice Neel made some of the
best paintings of the 20th century and added in particular to its
store of great portraiture, as demonstrated by the illuminating but
truncated retrospective of her work at the Whitney Museum of
American Art. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DAHESH-MUSEUM (New York) _ One of the virtues of the small
Dahesh Museum, young but with both feet planted in tradition, is
its mounting of academic shows by minor yet often contributory
artists that would be hard to come by elsewhere. By Grace Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   CHARDIN-RETROSPECTIVE (New York) _ According to the glacial
timetable on which big exhibitions at art museums operate these
days, it hasn't been especially long, 21 years, since the last
major traveling retrospective of the 18th-century French painter
Jean-Simeon Chardin. A new one arrives at the Met looking much less
cramped and more luxurious than it did at its last stop, in London,
on its European tour. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   KING-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ On the ``Burlesk King,'' directed
by Mel Chionglo, in Tagalog, with subtitles. Reviewed by A.O.
Scott.
</P>
<P>
   PRAISE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ On the Australian film
``Praise,'' an absorbing tale of sexual obsession. Reviewed Elvis
Mitchell.
</P>
