<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8225 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-PERFECTSTORM-TEX     06-29 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PERFECTSTORM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWERFUL RE-CREATION OF KILLER STORM COULD USE A COMPASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first half of ``The Perfect Storm'' doesn't resemble an
adaptation of a 1997 bestseller so much as it does a 1957 World War
II movie. We meet a sensitive but tough young man who's about to
leave his woman in port, promising her that this will be the last
time he goes out to sea on a dangerous mission; a jocular guy who's
leaving behind his adoring young son from a broken marriage; a
goofy dude who's on a romantic losing streak; and a taciturn,
reluctant seaman with a chip on his shoulder, especially when it
comes to the jocular guy. And they all respect their beloved
skipper, even if he is an arrogant cuss.
</P>
<P>
   These all sound like stock characters _ and they are _ but
they're based on real people, the ones so well-limned in Sebastian
Junger's acclaimed book about a swordfishing boat that gets lost at
sea as a hurricane, a tropical storm and a cold front converge in
the North Atlantic, creating ``the perfect storm.''
</P>
<P>
   The actors are, of course, part of the same shorthand that's
necessary when adapting a long, complex book into a two-hour movie.
If you need a charmingly arrogant determined-rebel sort to play
swordfish-boat skipper Billy Tyne, who better to turn to than
George Clooney? For the sensitive lovebird with a hard side, throw
in Mark Wahlberg, who is beginning to find his niche with this role
after similar turns in ``The Big Hit'' and ``Three Kings.'' For a
sad-souled joker, pull in John C. Reilly, ``Magnolia's'' lonely
police officer. William Fichtner, a familiar face but a
less-familiar name than Wahlberg or Clooney, plays the hardcase,
and Austin's John Hawkes steals what scenes he can as the
loser-at-love. Allen Payne has the most underwritten role as the
boat's lone Jamaican.
</P>
<P>
   This is the crew of the ill-fated Andrea Gail, but not only do
we get these courageous, likable men, we also get their women back
on the mainland, best exemplified by Diane Lane, who has the
thankless job of having crying jags and screaming fits as
Wahlberg's distraught lover. There's still more. The Coast Guard
sloop rescue, a key portion of the book, becomes a thrilling part
of the movie _ only to have director Wolfgang Petersen continually
cut away from it to go back to the Andrea Gail. Only the parallel
story of Tyne's more sensible fishing partner/rival Linda Greenlaw,
whose role is expanded from the book, has much flesh on it, and
that comes largely thanks to the solid performance of Mary
Elizabeth Mastrantonio, who must be yearning for a nice romantic
comedy after the grueling shoots for this and last year's
underrated ``Limbo.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an odd problem with the movie: It has a short attention
span, constantly jumping us from one subplot to another, but it
also wants us to be patient, waiting for more than an hour for the
storm of the title. But then, an even more curious thing happens:
The storm comes in, and virtually blows all the movie's flaws away.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``blows'' is too weak a word. The storm sequence,
which lasts a good 40 minutes or so, is the most bludgeoning,
mind-shattering, teeth-rattling, nerve-racking set piece since the
D-Day battle in ``Saving Private Ryan.'' It has glitches, but it
simply powers right by them, so that you don't think about them
till later. In fact, the storm doesn't give you much time to think
at all: You're too busy watching the towering, digitally enhanced
waves tossing around the poor Andrea Gail and its hapless crew, or
ducking from the screen as plywood, anchors and masts fly at you,
or cringing as a Coast Guard helicopter tries to rescue a misguided
sloop and then has to attempt to refuel in midair during gale-force
winds.
</P>
<P>
   The storm sequence is, indeed, near-perfect, another stellar
example of the almost preternatural knack for action that Petersen
has shown in movies as varied as ``Das Boot'' and ``Air Force
One.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm sequence is so overwhelming that the placid sea that
comes afterward is not enough to calm the nerves. Of course, it
also isn't enough to soothe any bristling toward the movie's often
overwrought sentimentality. Make no mistake, though _ if you're
going to ``The Perfect Storm,'' you're going for the storm, and
it's smashing in the literal and metaphorical senses. If only the
rest of the movie weren't so imperfect.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Perfect Storm''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Wolfgang Petersen
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg
</P>
<P>
   Length: 135 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ strong language and fishing- and storm-related
violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
