<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, June 30:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-U.S. (Havana) _ On the future of U.S.-Cuban relations
following the return of Elian Gonzalez to Cuba and moves by the
United States to relax its embargo. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-KOHL (Berlin) _ With a swaggering contempt for his
accusers, former chancellor Helmut Kohl appeared Thursday before a
parliamentary committee investigating financial misdeeds under his
rule and said he was a victim of slander. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-VOTE (Kampala) _ Uganda holds a referendum Thursday on
whether to continue the government's ``no party'' system, which
opposition sees as a one-party system. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-POITICS (Dateline to kum) _ Developments in Zimbabwe in
the aftermath of the parliamentary elections. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT-MIDEAST (Washington) _ Secretary of State Albright
returns and briefs President Clinton on her Middle East mission. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-BOAT (Jakarta) _ A boat carrying at least 270 refugees
fleeing sectarian violence in North Maluku province sank Thursday.
By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-DEVELOP (United Nations) _ The annual report of the U.N.
Development Program paints grim picture for Africa, and stresses
need for countries to be able to quantify their problems for them
to be dealt with in a big way. It is another instance of the
information gap between poor and rich countries. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The House is expected to pass a
bill giving doctors an exemption from federal antitrust law so they
can bargain collectively with insurance companies. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   HMO-MEDICARE (Washington) _ HMO's announce they'll drop 700,000
Medicare beneficiaries next year because the government doesn't pay
enough. Other Medicare developments, including Senate push for
prescription drug benefits. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   COMMERCE-MINETA (Washington) _ President Clinton announces the
nomination of Norman Mineta, a former California congressman, as
commerce secretary, making him the first Asian-American Cabinet
secretary. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ The Senate is to vote on a
campaign fianance bill. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House takes up the huge
supplemental spending bill. By Eric Schmitt and Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Chicago) _ Al Gore's campaign day. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   NADER (Washington) _ Ralph Nader blasts Al Gore as a
environmental hypocrite and lays plans for trade policies that
don't include Nafta or WTO. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-RIGHTS (Undated) _ What's next in the late-term
abortion battle? Are states planning to rewrite laws to meet the
Supreme Court decision? By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI (Miami) _ The aftermath of Elian for the
community.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-AIRCRAFT (Lod, Isrel) _ In the past 15 years, Israel
Aircraft Industries, a military contractor, has been built from
bankruptcy into an export-driven powerhouse. Its specialities
include refurbishing Soviet-era aircraft, and it has developed
electronic espionage devices for Israel's military that are
considered equal to any on the market. So a major contract it
signed with China to convert an Ilyushin into a modern radar plane
showcased the company's strengths. But if the Pentagon has its way,
the converted Ilyushin will never get to China. Since last fall,
Defense Secretary William Cohen has been demanding the deal's
cancellation, and he is backed by powerful members of Congress. By
By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CONSECO-APPOINT (Undated) _ Conseco Inc., the beleaguered
Indiana-based financial services company, named Gary C. Wendt as
its chief executive. During Wendt's 15-year tenure as head of GE
Capital Services, profits soared from about $300 million to nearly
$4 billion. The appointment of Wendt, who will forgo two years'
salary in favor of stock options, could restore some of Conseco's
credibility with investors. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly column. By Flody Norris.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-DAWEOO (Seoul) _ Ford offered $6.9 billion, much more than
had been expected, for Daewoo Motor, the No. 2 Korean auto company,
and was granted the exclusive right to negotiate a final deal wtih
the struggling company's credits. Ford's bid topped those submitted
by the team of GM and Fiat and the team of DaimlerChrysler and
Hyundai. The company is seen as determined to acquire Daewoo,
despite the opposition of Korean workers, to increase its capacity
in Asia and Eastern Europe. By Samuel Len.
</P>
