<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8227 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES30-CO     06-29 2013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At Daytona, turn on the lights!
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla _ The night NASCAR event at Daytona is
special for several reasons. Here are a few:
</P>
<P>
   1. Rare off day on Sunday. This race is one of four in the
Winston Cup Series held at night, and so it offers a welcome Sunday
off for everyone in the sport. An informal check with more than 20
drivers and owners has discovered near-unanimous support for more
Saturday-night races in future schedules. Getting that extra day
off becomes all the more important when NASCAR adds two more events
to the season in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   2. Beat the heat. Before lights were installed at Daytona
International Speedway, the Pepsi 400 was run in the morning,
initially with a 10 a.m. start and later an 11 a.m. green flag.
With the drivers raving about the lighting system in Charlotte,
officials at Daytona decided to make the move to night racing in
the summer of 1998. With the heat and humidity, every driver would
agree that an 8 p.m. start makes for much comfortable conditions
for the drivers, crews and fans.
</P>
<P>
   3. Better racing. When the Pepsi 400 was run in the middle of
the day in years past, many races would feature a two-car breakaway
for the lead. The problem was that, even though drafting was
critical at DIS, the intense heat made the track surface slippery,
which put a premium on handling. Unless caution flags flew at the
right time, the cars would string out along the 2.5-mile speedway.
At night, the racing surface is much more forgiving on a
less-than-perfect handling car, compared with the day-time
conditions. Also, some drivers have said they have better
visibility at night compared with day-time conditions.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bright paint schemes. In general, fans enjoy night racing
better than day-time action for reasons including the way the cars
shine and sparkle under the light. Most one-time paint schemes are
pulled out for The Winston at Lowe's Motor Speedway in Charlotte,
but several teams usually show up at Daytona in July with a
different look under the lights.
</P>
<P>
   Worst things about Daytona night-racing
</P>
<P>
   1. Brutal scheduling. The Winston Cup Series was delayed by rain
one day in Pocono last week. Teams had to scramble back to North
Carolina and immediately load to head to Sonoma, Calif. Then, they
turned around to face a short week, because they have to be in
Daytona for qualifying Thursday night. Those poor hauler drivers.
</P>
<P>
   2. Local tracks. With the Pepsi 400 schedule and with many race
fans staying home to watch it, a lot of local short tracks across
the country are forced to cancel their Saturday-night events this
weekend. It is sort of a ``Catch-22'' situation: Winston Cup night
races hurt attendance at local tracks, which develop the talent
that eventually ends up on the major-league circuit.
</P>
<P>
   3. Traffic and parking. This problem also is relevant to the
Daytona 500. For years, many fans had parked free at the Volusia
County mall across from the speedway, but the mall is going to
start charging next year. With the increased seating capacity,
ticket holders do not have enough parking on speedway property.
Vendors across the street behind the Winston Tower were charging
$50 for a parking spot on private property on the day of the
Daytona 500. Daytona Beach also is a popular destination for
vacationers on the fourth of July weekend, which adds to the
traffic tie-ups in front of the speedway.
</P>
<P>
   4. Hotels. The track is located just off I-95, while most motels
are located five to eight miles away on the beach. With the
vacationers, the demand for lodging is high, which translates into
big bucks for a place to stay. Also, with many young non-race fans
out cruising late at night, a glut of traffic is heading from the
speedway to the beach at 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   5. No support race. This event is the only one on the circuit
that does not feature a support race, such as Busch, Craftsman
Truck or ARCA. Many fans that attend races like to make a full
weekend out of the activities and attend Cup qualifying, the
support event and then the Winston Cup event. With Cup qualifying
Thursday night, Friday is pretty much a scratch, with all concerned
preparing for Saturday night. Perhaps NASCAR should consider
running a support race of some type on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Prime time, baby
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Pepsi 400 was the first Winston Cup event shown live
at night on network television from start to finish. The Pepsi 400
never will approach the importance of its sister event _ the
Daytona 500 in February _ but the excitement of night-racing in
front of a national television audience is intriguing for everyone
involved.
</P>
<P>
   With the new TV contract starting in 2001, this weekend's race
marks the end of CBS's affiliation with Winston Cup. CBS played a
vital role in the growth of the sport, most notably with its
memorable coverage of the 1979 Daytona 500, which captured the
fascination of the country with Cale Yarborough brawling against
the Allison brothers _ Donnie and Bobby.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise relief
</P>
<P>
   John Andretti and Tony Stewart proved that drivers have short
memories _ fortunately. The two sides have been at odds since last
year's Martinsville race, when Stewart was in the middle of his
infamous quarrel with Kenny Irwin and caused Andretti to wreck. As
a result, Richard Petty said, ``Tony needs to grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Stewart became frustrated when Andretti's lapped
car appeared to be slowing him down through traffic at the end of
the Pocono race. Guess who was the relief driver for Stewart at
Sears Point? Surprisingly, it was Andretti, who rescued the Home
Depot team by rallying to finish 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace shows class
</P>
<P>
   Fans can criticize Rusty Wallace for failing to capitalize on
six poles, but the veteran driver was a hero to many in the racing
community with his post-qualifying comments at Sears Point. Wallace
said he felt ``like an idiot'' for taking away the pole from Kyle
Petty, who is still mourning the death of his son, Adam. It was a
refreshing and touching moment for the sport.
</P>
<P>
   `DW' deservers more respect, says Waltrip's little brother
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Waltrip's farewell tour, dubbed ``Victory Tour 2000'',
has been a rough ride for the veteran driver.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip's initial goal for his 29th and final season on the
Winston Cup circuit was to win at least one race. Unfortunately for
Waltrip, it is considered a victory whenever he is able to qualify
for a race.
</P>
<P>
   In 16 races, Waltrip has had to use provisionals to make the
field five times and missed three races altogether. It has been an
embarrassment for the former three-time Winston Cup champion and
his team.
</P>
<P>
   Driver Michael Waltrip thinks his older brother deserves more
respect in his final season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching Pebble Beach the other day and Jack Nicklaus
was making what was maybe his final appearance in the U.S. Open,
and he was struggling home. He got in on an exemption, and they
said it could be his last one,'' Michael said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about our sport, and I say, why can't people be
talking about Darrell that way? Why can't they be saying, `Man,
this is going to be the last time we see Darrell Waltrip at
Daytona? Please just grasp this moment, he's meant so much to this
sport. He's going to be gone.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead we're saying, `Look at him. He had to use a
provisional again.' That's the kind of comments he's getting, and
that kind of gets on my nerves. It doesn't seem fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Nighttime is the right time for `Little E'
</P>
<P>
   If it were up to Winston Cup rookie sensation Dale Earnhardt
Jr., there would definitely be more night events on the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the our team has done pretty darn well at the night
races this year: we won at Richmond, we won The Winston and then we
finished fourth and led 175 laps at the Coca-Cola 600,'' Dale Jr.
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pepsi 400 will be Chevy No. 8 driver's first experience at
Daytona under the lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be awesome,'' Dale Jr. said. ``I mean, Daytona is
cool enough just being there anytime, but racing there under the
lights is gonna be great. If I had to say that I had a favorite
track, this place just might be it because of the history of the
track and the high speeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Dark horse at Daytona
</P>
<P>
   In the shadows of teammate Dale Jarrett, Ricky Rudd has been
flourishing over the last two months. The Ford No. 28 driver has
finished five of the last seven races in the top 5, including a
third at Pocono two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd has a strong chance at winning his first race this year
Saturday night at Daytona. Last February, Rudd won a Gatorade
Twin-125 qualifying race and started second in the Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my guys, `don't do anything different than your
doing,'''Rudd said. ``We're doing exactly what we need to do. The
communication keeps getting better and we keep progressing. With
consistent top-five finishes every week, sooner or later you're
going to win something.''
</P>
<P>
   Roush Racing's ``unofficial'' sixth team
</P>
<P>
   The Wood brothers have expanded their working relationship with
Roush Racing, which already has five drivers on the Winston Cup
circuit. The debut of this newly formed alliance takes begins today
at Daytona. Elliott Sadler, driver of the No. 21 Ford, will be
provided with motors, chassis, and bodies from Roush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tapping into stronger and deeper resources,'' said Eddie
Wood, co-owner of the Ford No. 21. ``Jack Roush has welcomed us
with open arms and he's giving us an opportunity to capitalize on
his technology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a single car team we've sometimes struggled searching
for the sweet spot on the chassis and body. Now we'll have our
notes and their notes to work from. It will also give Elliott the
opportunity to compare notes with some of the best drivers in the
business. We've been on the top before and we believe this is what
we need to do to rise to the top again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler gives a thumbs-up to the new program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first weekend where we are taking our single car
team and making a six car multi-car team out of it,'' Sadler said.
</P>
<P>
   Roush drivers include Mark Martin, Jeff Burton and rookie star
Matt Kenseth.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace hog wild over new paint
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace will be debuting a new Miller Lite/Harley Davidson
color scheme on the No. 2 Ford today Daytona. It will also be used
at the two other remaining night races this season, Bristol and
Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   The Harley Davidson people are all pumped,'' Wallace said.
``It's a sharp looking car with flames all down the sides. Heck,
even my driver's uniform has flames all over it. I try not to be
superstitious about any of this, but it might just be the little
extra shot we need to finally break on through.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace was referring to winning a circuit-leading six poles
this year, and failing to transform any of them to a trip to
victory lane.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR Q&AMP;A: MIKE BROWN
</P>
<P>
   Mike Brown is a classic example of someone who slowly and
patiently has worked his way to one of the top jobs in NASCAR.
Brown, 41, serves as the general manager for Bill Davis Racing,
which owns the Winston Cup teams of Ward Burton and Dave Blaney.
Here, Brown talks with Cox News Service writer Rick Minter:
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was your big break into the business?
</P>
<P>
   A: I got involved with changing tires for some Busch teams, as
sort of a weekend hobby (in 1991). I got invited to Nazareth, Pa.,
to work for an up-and-coming driver, Mike McLaughlin. Mike crashe
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you like so much about changing tires?
</P>
<P>
   A: It allows me to keep my competitive side, which you sometimes
lose when you're dealing with the headaches of the day-to-day
business entities. You know in the back of your mind you're still
going to be part of the show on Sunday. You still get to be part of
that competitive side, that when the team wins a race or finishes
in the top five, you feel like you had something to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
