<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES FEUD OVER STORAGE SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as it increased the target price for its initial public
offering, StorageNetworks Inc. of Waltham, Mass. has disclosed a
nasty dispute with one of its main hardware suppliers, EMC Corp.
</P>
<P>
   EMC, of Hopkinton, Mass., is the leading producer of disk-drive
assemblies for big computer databases. StorageNetworks buys
equipment from EMC and others, then leases out the capacity to
corporate customers like banks and e-commerce providers.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the two companies have insisted their operations are
complementary, although StorageNetworks has received investments
from such EMC competitors as Compaq Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But strains have emerged as StorageNetworks prepares to go
public, while EMC sorts out its relations with the company and
other startups known as ``storage service providers.''
</P>
<P>
   In filings to securities regulators this week, StorageNetworks
described a letter it received from EMC on June 21. The letter
accused StorageNetworks of pretending EMC has invested in the
company, misappropriating confidential EMC data and hiring away EMC
employees in violation of the contracts, according to the filing.
</P>
<P>
   EMC has threatened to sue, the companies said, though EMC
spokesman Mark Fredrickson wouldn't describe the basis of the
allegations. StorageNetworks executives called the charges false
but wouldn't say more, citing securities rules.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute may cause EMC to terminate contracts,
StorageNetworks said in its filings. Last year, its work as an EMC
subcontractor accounted for about 40 percent of StorageNetworks'
total revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Lost revenue could be disruptive to StorageNetworks, which plans
to spend $100 million this year, and $700 million by 2005, building
a fiber-optic network to its storage systems worldwide. Because of
those expenses, the company said that it expects to lose money
``for the foreseeable future.'' The company had an accumulated
deficit of $51.5 million as of March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that warning, StorageNetworks also increased the price
range for its initial public offering, usually an indication of
strong interest from investors. The new range is $23 to $25 a
share, according to a filing Wednesday, up from the $17 to $19 a
share range the company had previously targeted. StorageNetworks
wouldn't discuss its reasoning for the price increase.
</P>
<P>
   About 9 million shares in the company will be sold, according to
the filing, which would raise more than $200 million at the higher
share price. The company's officers and directors would still
control 68 percent of the company following its IPO,
StorageNetworks said. The IPO is expected in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   StorageNetworks is just one of a host of companies being created
to offer remote-storage services, challenging the business model
for EMC and others who have traditionally sold their gear directly
to users. In May, EMC said it will spend $1 billion over several
years to market and support its products to the new storage-service
providers. EMC has also made minority investments in some of the
companies aiming at consumer markets, including i-drive.com,
X:drive, and SkyDesk.
</P>
<P>
   In the industry, StorageNetworks is well known partly because
its management includes former EMC employees, among them Peter
Bell, the StorageNetworks chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst John Webster of the Illuminata Group, in Nashua, N.H.,
suggested the close ties may have fanned the competition between
the two companies, however. He noted a StorageNetworks' director
and shareholder, Harry Dixon, was previously a top EMC sales chief
before leaving in January for reasons neither side will discuss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
