<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8240 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     06-29 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY CHOICE REMAINING FOR THIS TEAM IS PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was 5:30 p.m. _ dinner time for some families _ and
Rick Pitino's Celtics family was already gathered around a long
table, preparing for what could be their Last (Basketball) Supper.
They were obviously panicking. Some relatives talk about selling
the house; these folks were ready to give the thing away.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Wednesday night, the family decided that it would
be best to trade three No. 1 draft picks along with a player or two
for 21-year-old Portland center Jermaine O'Neal. He is is not
related to the Diesel, Shaquille O'Neal, on the court or off. In
his best season, 1997-98, 6-foot-11-inch Jermaine O'Neal averaged
4.5 points and 3.3 rebounds in 60 games. He is the embodiment of
the ultimate basketball phrase (a player with potential), but the
numbers from last season, 3.9 points and 3.3 rebounds, indicate
that the potential has not been realized.
</P>
<P>
   Please, say a prayer for this troubled family.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said his staff agreed unanimously that O'Neal was the
center who could help the Celtics enter a land (The Playoffs) that
is foreign to them. If you are a Celtics fan, you should hope that
the organization's president and head coach was simply reciting a
sanitized public statement. You should hope that there was someone
at the table who pounded the wood a few times and asked, ``What the
hell are we doing? What are we thinking?''
</P>
<P>
   Since rumors are standard on draft night, it made one wonder how
accurate the rumored Organization-for-O'Neal swap was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fairly accurate,'' Pitino replied.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Pitino met with team owner Paul Gaston.
Later, the coach characterized the meeting as ``positive.''
According to Pitino, Gaston told him ``that the future is now'' and
that he wanted Pitino's staff to be ``very aggressive'' in an
attempt to turn the sad Celtics into winners. The Celtics haven't
won as many as 40 games since 1993, which makes them one of three
NBA teams, along with Vancouver and the LA Clippers, in that
category.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says the fans have been very patient the past six, seven
years,'' Pitino said of Gaston. ``We are going to be very active,
to try and bring the future a little closer to now. We're being
very active to try to bring our fans a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on their nearly destructive move for O'Neal, The Green
Family took the aggression advice literally. Next, Pitino said, he
will pack his bags and head for the road with general manager Chris
Wallace. They are allowed to speak with free agents beginning
Saturday. They can sign them Aug. 1, although it is not certain
what significant free agent will be willing to join this
dysfunctional family.
</P>
<P>
   As Pitino and Gaston hit the road trying to make the future
better, they will be reminded of their mistakes from the past.
Pitino will remember that he brought in Kenny Anderson to lead his
offense in 1998. By 1999, Anderson and shooting guard Ron Mercer
were at odds.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Anderson and Paul Pierce clashed constantly in
practice and sometimes during games. The men did not have
boys-will-be-boys disputes; there was genuine dislike between them.
One issue was the ball and how Anderson felt Pierce shot it too
much. At times, according to some Celtics, the point guard didn't
want to pass to Pierce for fear that he would heave it even if that
wasn't the wisest thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   So in consecutive seasons, Pitino's point guard _ the one he
brought in because rookie Chauncey Billups couldn't do the job _
didn't click with his shooting guard. There isn't a basketball team
in the NBA that will win with a combination like that.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that love affairs cannot always be explained logically,
Gaston has reportedly told his coach he sees good things in the
near future for this team. Pitino said he believes things are
close, too. He said that a few days after a story linked him with
the coaching vacancy at the University of Miami. He was said to
have lengthy (six hours) and harmless exploratory talks with the
school's athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   Six hours of exploration. Who searches that long? Lewis and
Clark?
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that the Celtics probably won't win next season,
either. They came out of draft night with intriguing big man Jerome
Moiso from UCLA. The 6-11 forward is fluent in French and fluid on
the court, so much of an athlete that ``he runs the floor like Ron
Mercer _ at 6-11,'' Pitino said. He also said Moiso can do things
that no one else on the team can do. That's frightening when you
consider that the draftee was selected 11th, hardly the place where
big men who make an impact are plucked.
</P>
<P>
   Even more chilling is what might happen before the season starts
in November. The most dangerous group or individual is one that
acts out of fear and desperation. The Celtics are that group. There
was talk that forward Antoine Walker might be used as a backup
point guard so mismatches can be created. A better tack, though,
would be to find a point guard who can create mismatches.
</P>
<P>
   When the Celtics begin shopping Saturday, they will be like
ambitious teenagers shopping at the mall. They will see a lot they
like, but won't be able to come up with enough cash to get what
they want. Anderson is a 170-pound weight on their salary cap. They
could trade Walker, although teams usually don't improve when they
trade their best players. They could deal Pierce, just as they
dealt Mercer the season before. That also would not help.
</P>
<P>
   So now they flail about, trying to be aggressive as the owner
requested. It is the kind of aggression that inspires parents to
install safety locks on windows. It's the kind of aggression that
inspires parents to put viewing blocks on televisions. They do it
because they are concerned about what their children will do with
free reign.
</P>
<P>
   As Pitino sat at the long table, a mural of Larry Bird was
draped behind him. The Celtics legend is one person who can change
the direction of this organization. Other than that? Prayer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
