<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8241 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-REPRODUCTIONS-2N     06-29 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-REPRODUCTIONS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... of furniture.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This history includes attendance at some of our country's most
significant events, including the signing of the Declaration of
Independence. Robert Pines's famous painting shows Continental
Congress delegates signing the Declaration in Philadelphia while
seated in Windsor side chairs.
</P>
<P>
   America's celebration of our centennial brought a renewed
interest in these chairs, and today there are hundreds of Windsor
chairmakers making them with the same careful craftsmanship as the
originals.
</P>
<P>
   Dunphy and Wakeman are two of these artisans. Manufacturer's
representatives with flexible schedules by day, the pair run their
small business, Classics in Wood, in their free time. Having bought
the business from Dunphy's brother in 1986, they moved it to
Ashford, Conn., where Dunphy, who had recently moved east from
California, had bought an 18th-century house. They built a barn to
house their new business on the property.
</P>
<P>
   Seasoned and passionate woodworkers, the two divided up the
furniture-making process. They hired Jim McMullan full time and
Erik Wohl part time to put the chairs together. Their duties
include cutting out the pine chair seats after tracing the
dimensions from metal and cardboard templates; hollowing and
smoothing the seat by hand and tapering the maple spindles and
stretchers to fit the appropriate grooves in the seat, bent oak
arms, and back. All dovetailing and joinery are done by hand _ no
machines, no nails, only glue.
</P>
<P>
   Dunphy does all the handwork, such as the delicate carving on
the ends of chair arms. He's also in charge of finishes _ the
paints and antiquing. (He will stain a chair only if the buyer is
insistent.) And he works with customers.
</P>
<P>
   Wakeman makes all the tables and large case pieces such as
huntboards, apothecary desks, and shoefoot hutch tables and
dressers. He does all the custom work. All his tabletops are made
from wood salvaged from 18th- and 19th-century structures such as
wainscotting and flooring. Such wood, says Dunphy, is becoming
increasingly difficult to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have copied the chairs of E. B. Tracy, who is considered
the patriarch of the Windsor chair,'' says Dunphy. ``He lived in
Norwich (Conn.) and was a high-volume producer of chairs. His
inventory has been published so we were able to study his chairs,
plus there's been a lot written about him and his work. To copy a
chair in a museum, for example, we measure all the angles _ top,
front, and back. The chair is such a complex structure, the way
it's formed and turned _ the spindles, stretchers, and legs. It's
very complicated to make everything fit.''
</P>
<P>
   But when everything fits, there's a visual harmony unsurpassed
by any other chair made for the masses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harley and Pam Savage
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Listed on the National Register of Historic Places, Frye's
Measure Mill of Wilton, N.H., is one of the few remaining
water-powered mills in the nation and the only measure mill still
active today. It's nestled at the end of a winding country road in
a breathtaking landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Round wooden measures were used by farmers and fishermen as
standard units before mechanical scales became the norm. They came
in five sizes _ one, two, and four quarts, a single peck, and a
half bushel. Measures were first made on this site in 1876,
followed by piggins or dippers, which were round wooden measures
with a wood handle attached.
</P>
<P>
   In 1909, Dr. Edmund Bailey Frye of Roxbury, Mass., bought the
mill for his son, Whitney, who added new products such as curry
cards (combs for cattle), wool cards, and pantry boxes to the
mill's product line and continually updated the machinery. After
World War II, Harland Savage, a local boy, began working at the
mill and eventually became its owner. The highlight of his tenure
came with a visit from Shaker eldress Bertha Lindsey in the late
1960s. The last Shaker box maker had died in 1961, and Lindsey
asked Harland if he would be interested in carrying on the sect's
box making at Frye's. His answer, of course, was an unqualified
yes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, the mill was bought by Harland's son, Harley, and his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no intention of taking over the business,'' says Harley,
who had worked at the mill during his teenage years. ``I was an
oceanography major at UNH until I found out that I wouldn't be able
to dive for medical reasons. So I switched to woodworking.''
</P>
<P>
   And that led him and his artist wife to the proprietorship of
Frye's.
</P>
<P>
   Their goals, says Harley, were to make high-quality boxes that
would attract the museum-shop market, expand their product line and
retail store, and restore the mill and grounds to their original
beauty. They also moved on site into a house attached to the mill
with a view of the pond and the waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   The mill was included in ``America Restored,'' a book published
by the National Trust for Historical Preservation that took two
sites from every state as representative of private individuals'
maintaining and protecting historic landmarks. The Savages also
broadened their product line to include swing, spool, spice,
Colonial, wedding, courting, and tinder boxes _ all made by hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our best sellers are our carriers and especially our salt and
pepper carrier, mantel boxes, game boxes, and our tavern house
line,'' says Pam, who hand-paints several lines of boxes and does
all the buying for the seven-room store. The store not only
features Frye boxes but crafts by other artisans such as pottery,
period lighting, pewter, and hand-forged ironware and tinware.
``Our customers expect us to have new items every year. Coming up
with new pieces every year is one of our greatest challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ron Geering, 246 Woods Hole Road, Falmouth, 508-457-0841. Classics
in Wood, Ashford, Conn., 860-429-6020, www.classicwindsors.com.
Frye's Measure Mill, 12 Frye Mill Road, Wilton, N.H., 603 654-6581;
tours every Saturday through October at 2 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
