<HEADER>
A8243 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FASHION-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      06-29 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCEIVING SOME HIP, NEW DESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who can blame women for not wanting to spend money on maternity
clothes? The garments, after all, are temporary; the designs often
atrocious; and no designer seems willing to sacrifice his or her
chic image by dressing the pregnant. No wonder tunics and leggings
triumph in the third trimester.
</P>
<P>
   But that has begun to change.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, A Pea in the Pod president Rebecca Matthias
approached Lilly Pulitzer, a fellow Philadelphia company, to spin
out maternity wear for the 40-store chain's winter resort
collection. And a trend was born.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Matthias persuaded Vivienne Tam, Nicole Miller, and
Trina Turk to conceive lines for mothers-in-waiting. Turk and
Miller's small collections hit the stores in April and are
expanding for debut fall collections. Tam's clothing, which
Matthias calls a ``forward, body-conscious'' (read: clingy) look,
is also expanding into a fall line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That goes against the trend of what you think women want,''
she said of Tam's tight-fitting fashions. ``But they're keying off
celebrities who are showing off their bodies because they're in
such good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Come August, maternity wear by designer BCBG will be in the
stores, which are also stocking Bisou Bisou and Levi's jeans (the
zipper is replaced with a cotton stretch pouch). Then there's Three
Dot T-shirts, which are otherwise only available at Bergdorf
Goodman and Barney's.
</P>
<P>
   None of this comes cheaply, of course.
</P>
<P>
   At the Chestnut Hill, Boston, store, a chartreuse and gold weave
long stretch sheath with bolero jacket by Bisou Bisou cost $290. A
Trina Turk light cotton brown and blue swirl spread-collar blouse
is priced at $70, with $195 matching pants. A Lilly green and
yellow print number was $170. And one pair of Levi's, trimmed at
the hem in pink, burgundy, and red suede stripes, was priced at
$180.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is sensitivity to price in maternity clothes for the
reason you stated: short life,'' Matthias said. ``But women always
want to look good.'' And ``it's nice to see a familiar brand that
you've worn before'' in a maternity store.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Miller has found that to be true. When she was pregnant
five years ago, she realized there was a void in the market for
would-be moms who wanted to be stylish.
</P>
<P>
   She introduced a few pieces of a maternity line, which turned
out to be a short-lived venture. Because the market is relatively
small (with 4 million births a year), her time was better spent on
the overall collection.
</P>
<P>
   But A Pea in the Pod has its own distribution system and
provides maternity patterns for the designers, making Matthias's
pitch harder for Miller and others to turn down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we've tested out they've done well with,'' Miller
said. ``Everybody has been disgusted for years about maternity wear
. . . the same way they were disgusted with bridesmaid dresses.''
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of designer wear in A Pea in the Pod appears to
be paying off. Matthias said that same-store sales have increased
40 percent over last year. Specific sales figures are not available
for the chain, which is owned by Mothers Work Inc., also the parent
company for Mimi Maternity (Bloomingdale's-level contemporary
garments) and Motherhood Maternity (the Old Navy of pregnancy
clothing). But overall sales for the three stores have hit about
$400 million, she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While some pregnant women are flaunting their bodies, many
others want to hide theirs, especially when it comes to bathing
suits.
</P>
<P>
   Two Boston-based women, Faviana Olivier and Diane Wood, have
launched FlirtSkirt, a company that designs flouncy,
just-above-the-knee bathing suit wraps.
</P>
<P>
   The skirts are produced by a women-owned manufacturer in Western
Massachusetts that hires immigrants and single mothers to teach
them a trade and/or English. Some of the proceeds from the wraps _
which come in black, royal blue, or leopard print _ will go toward
scholarships for those workers. They're available only through the
Web (www.flirtskirt.com) or by calling 1-800-560-3849.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And while you're melting at the beach, imagine what's happening
to your makeup, especially if you brought it along or left it in
the car.
</P>
<P>
   At temperatures as low as 80 degrees, a compact of creme blusher
or a tube of lipstick can liquify, and worse, ooze.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new thermal insulated makeup bag on the market that
can withstand temperatures up to 140 degrees for at least two hours
without the contents melting.
</P>
<P>
   The Macqui bag (pronounced ma-KEE) is available at some spas and
specialty stores or through 1-877-8MACQUI. Prices range from $24.95
for an average-sized black model to $45.95 for a large box-case
with mirror.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8245 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-     06-29 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 THIS `CONNECTOR' SPOTS INTERNET GAPS AND BRIDGES THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Anita Brown is having one of her moments. The
founder of a nonprofit group called Black Geeks Online is at
Harvard to participate in a panel discussion about the digital
divide, and there are a few things she would like to discuss. What
is wrong, she wants to know, with all those caffeinated kids who
work 24 hours a day without stopping to call their mamas or take a
look at the world? What good, she asks, is a computer if you're
poor and hungry and can't get a job?
</P>
<P>
   And another thing. What is all this gee-whiz technology doing to
the thing called humanity? ``They call this online connectivity or
community, but it's not,'' she says. ``Community is when you have a
crisis at home: Who do you call to take care of your babies while
you run down to the hospital at 3 o'clock in the morning? That's
community.''
</P>
<P>
   She interrupts her stream-of-consciousness monologue to seek a
light for a cigarette, and within minutes, she's deep in a
discussion with a woman who represents a health-oriented Web site.
The next thing you know, Brown has the woman's business card. The
contact may come in handy some day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an Aquarius,'' she says. ``Humanity is my thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is one of those individuals that author Malcolm Gladwell
describes as a ``connector,'' a walking, talking Rolodex of sorts
who makes it her business to bring other people together. And for
the past five years, she's been doing her matchmaking on the
Internet. Using the online monikers of Sistah Geek and Miss D.C.,
Brown runs Black Geeks Online from her home in Washington. Founded
on a whim in 1996, the loose-knit organization has grown from 18
members to 25,000  &UR; today &LR; , and Brown has established herself as an
unofficial Internet griot who sends out missives to members all
over the world, from the South Bronx to South Africa. The
organization is a sort of digital grapevine for people of color
online, and Brown has made it her mission to encourage black
information technology professionals to volunteer in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a genius for knowing all the right people,'' says Adam
Fisher, senior associate editor of Wired magazine. ``She makes
things happen.'' Brown has adopted Fisher as her ``new best
friend;'' she feeds him tips about black high-tech entrepreneurs
who should be featured in the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The 57-year-old grandmother, however, is the first to admit that
she is an unlikely role model for budding geeks. A sixth-generation
Washingtonian, she dropped out of college after six months _ ``I
didn't like it. They told you to read the book and spit it out'' _
and spent several decades working as a secretary in the civil
service. Back in her day, the transistor radio was considered
high-tech. But her brother, a retired computer engineer, introduced
her to the Internet in 1994. She resisted at first _ ``I said, `Oh
no you don't. Big Brother will not get me!' '' _ but when she
discovered that she could exchange recipes with a chef in New
Orleans, she was hooked. ``I'm a communicator, an information
broker, and I saw the potential,'' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Since she founded Black Geeks in her living room four years ago,
she has organized an information technology workshop called
``Taking IT to the Streets,'' which introduced 200 newbies to
computers and the Internet. Earlier this year, she was tapped as
one of the Top 25 Women on the Web by SFWoW, a San Francisco-based
association of professional women involved in the Internet. Brown,
who is known for wearing red high tops and a Tweety Bird watch,
shared the honors with top CEOs and computer scientists. ``She
isn't your typical CEO, but she has made a difference by helping
other women get over their fear of the Internet,'' says Mary Choy,
who ran the committee that selected this year's winners. ``When she
accepted her award, she said, `They told me not to wear sneakers
and not to curse onstage, but here I am, wearing sneakers and
cursing onstage.' She fit in beautifully.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown chooses not to wear those red high tops for her appearance
at Harvard, though. ``A girl has to look her best,'' she says with
a coy smile. But she is going to speak her mind. She is frequently
asked to speak about the digital divide, the gap between the
technology haves and have-nots. The digital divide is usually
described as a gap between blacks and whites, but Brown isn't
convinced that the problem can easily be solved by throwing money
and computers at poor communities. ``My main concern, from (Vice
President Al) Gore to (Microsoft chairman Bill) Gates, is that all
this equipment and money is being handed out in a vacuum,'' she
says. ``They're putting computers in the schools without talking to
the parents or the community. None of this money is going to train
people. They're just creating new consumers, and the last thing
poor people need to do is to find a new electronic mall.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, like many other former Internet enthusiasts, no longer
thinks that computers in and of themselves can provide the answer
to society's ills. ``I'm a techno realist,'' she says. ``It's time
to stop and say, `Wait a minute.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And she is willing to stir up debate wherever she goes. At the
Harvard conference, which was called Internet and Society 2000, she
objects when a moderator wants to discuss the digital divide in the
Third World. ``I don't see how we can fix someone else's barn when
ours is falling to the ground,'' she says. When she goes through
her spiel about the Internet dehumanizing society, including the
bit about the coffee, the crowd applauds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anita is a '60s revolutionary who uses the Internet as a new
tool to kind of continue the philosophy and ideology of changing
things and not accepting the status quo,'' says Kenny Granderson, a
fellow panelist and the founder of Inner City Software in
Dorchester. Granderson is a kindred spirit. He founded Boston
Blacks Online, a group of 650 members who communicate on the
Internet. ``We both deal with people on a grassroots level, dealing
with the regular Joes and Janes,'' Granderson says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, after a few days in Cambridge, Brown connects with many
Joes and Janes and counts a number of ``new best friends.'' After
her appearance on the panel, she launches an animated conversation
with Jose Orlando Lopez, vice-president for academic affairs and
innovations at the American University of Puerto Rico. She takes
his card, one more for her Rolodex. You never know when Sistah Geek
might need a best friend in Puerto Rico.
</P>
</TEXT>
