<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-DRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETIC FORWARD MOISO IS CELTICS' CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As the first hour of the NBA draft ended Wednesday
night, the Celtics pondered their options with the No. 11 pick.
They saw a talent with size and shot-blocking ability still
available. They saw a player who had impressed them in two workouts
at HealthPoint. The saw someone with athleticism to spare. They saw
a young man targeted from the start as a good fit for the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Bienvenue, Jerome Moiso.
</P>
<P>
   Boston chose Moiso, a bilingual product of Guadeloupe, Paris,
Milford (Conn.) Academy, and UCLA. The Celtics expect their first
and only pick of the 2000 draft to play power forward. But the
brain trust would not rule out Moiso playing center in some
alignments and possibly small forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good about (being drafted by the Celtics) right
now,'' said Moiso, who spoke with a lilting French accent. ``I'm
really very excited. I knew they had some interest in me after my
first workout . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the skills and what it takes to (play against strong
players). It's up to me to bring it every night and I think I can
do that because I want to be the best against the best. I play good
against the best, and I play good defense.''
</P>
<P>
   While Moiso was happy to learn he would start his NBA career in
the Hub, Boston was surprised that the 6-foot-10-inch forward found
his way here. Coach Rick Pitino did not expect Moiso to be around
at No. 11, but the early selection of two point guards changed the
complexion of the draft. As a result, the Celtics got the player
they desired and shored up a front court that might be without the
services of soon-to-be free agent Danny Fortson. Even if 7-1 center
Joel Pryzbilla of Minnesota was available, Pitino said, the Celtics
``were going with Moiso.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we wanted to do was get more athletic,'' said
Pitino. ``Probably last year was the least amount of pressing I've
ever done since I've been in diapers at Boston University. So, we
really didn't play like we did the first year because we weren't as
athletic as we'd like to be. This young man is a great athlete. He
did some things in workouts that we didn't notice on film. He's
very, very talented, a very gifted athlete, as well as being a good
basketball player.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Wallace: ``We're very happy to have (Moiso) for this ball
club . . . He's one of the most skilled players at his size
available in this draft.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who watched Moiso perform at UCLA, the assessments of
Pitino and Wallace were not revelations. During his freshman year,
he averaged 10.8 points and 5.8 rebounds per game. He was the
Bruins' leading rebounder in 11 games and leading scorer in five.
As a sophomore, he posted even more impressive statistics. His
scoring average jumped to 13 points, along with 7.6 rebounds per
game and 1.7 blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a great time for me (to leave college),'' said
Moiso of his decision to go pro after two years in Southern
California. ``I had kind of planned that before I got to UCLA I
would play for two years and I would see what it is after two
years.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Celtics' praise-filled evaluation of Moiso came mostly
from workouts at their training site.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was playing a very tough guy,'' said Pitino. ``We brought
him in twice and he would turn, wheel around someone, and get to
the rim and just dunk it. He was a lot more aggressive than we
heard. He has great hands, blocks shots. We do a couple of drills
where you have to go high on the glass five times, jog down to the
other end, and go high on the glass. All the guys we brought in
could not do what he could do on the glass. Besides being
6-foot-11, he's very long. So, he's what we need.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino declined to answer whether Moiso, who starting playing at
age 6, stopped at 9, and resumed playing at 13, would make an
immediate impact or need time to develop. The Celtics' pick,
however, was quick to point out areas of his game that need
improvement and the skills that made him stand out. On the positive
side, Moiso called himself, ``pretty quick, pretty offensively
oriented, and athletic on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he believes he can handle the press, Moiso said it
would take time to adjust to the Celtics' favored defensive scheme.
He also mentioned the need to ``get bigger and stronger'' and hoped
to add about 10 pounds to his slim 235-pound frame.
</P>
<P>
   The newest Celtic will also need to spend time brushing up
Celtic Pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was starting following about the NBA when I was about 13,''
said Moiso. ``That's when I really started to know about it. And
the Celtics, I've been reading magazines and seeing a few games I
could catch in France. I didn't really know much about it, just
Larry Bird, Kevin McHale, and Robert Parish. (With the current
team), I just practically know the two main players, Paul Pierce
and Antoine Walker.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before midnight, the Celtics pulled off a trade,
acquiring Josip Sesar, a 6-6 guard from Croatia. Sesar was selected
by Seattle with the 47th pick. In return, Boston gave Seattle its
two second-round picks in 2001. (Boston had previously acquired
Denver's second-round pick.)
</P>
<P>
   Sesar played for Cibona Zagreb in the Euroleague last season,
averaging 14.2 points per game. Prior to the 1999-2000 season, he
was one of the top scorers in the Croatian League with a 20.4
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in Europe told us about him,'' said Wallace.
``He's a tremendous shooter. He's the best shooter of all the
dozen-plus players we had come through here in the workout process.
He didn't actually come here, but we saw the workout process. He
handles the ball, he's got good size at the 2-guard position. We
need outside shooting, so we made that move.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
