<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO BASIS TO JUICED BASEBALL SUSPICIONS, RESEARCHERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM KALEC  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several theories exist to explain the high number of baseballs
leaving major league parks this season. But a study conducted by
Dr. Jim Sherwood and Lawrence Fallon of UMass-Lowell has dismissed
one of the more popular notions: the baseball is not juiced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baseball is not the problem, because there really isn't
any difference between this year's baseball and last year's
baseball,'' said Sherwood, who runs the Baseball Research Center at
the school, upon the report's release Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The study only tested balls made since 1998, which raises the
question, were all the baseballs tested juiced?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are planning to continue this research,'' Sherwood said.
``We were unable to run tests on some of the older balls, but are
planning to and will see how they compare.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball presented the project to Sherwood and
Fallon in April. For six weeks, the same type of baseballs used
each day were tested. Some tests, such as comparing the weights of
this year's balls with their counterparts from the past two
seasons, were simple. Other tests were a bit more complicated, like
the one using a BAUM machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it does is simulate a batter hitting a pitch at speeds
pitchers throw at,'' Sherwood said. ``The machine spins a bat with
the same speed a hitter would when he swings at a pitch. At the
other end the ball is thrown by a device that looks similiar to a
tuning fork.''
</P>
<P>
   When contact is made, the machine measures the incoming velocity
of the ball to the rebound velocity when hit. The machine showed
the speed ratio has been consistent from 1998-2000.
</P>
<P>
   But with all respect to modern science, Orioles veteran Will
Clark could have saved everyone time and money. Clark suggested
those trying to find a connection between the balls and the
increase in power are more likely to find ``a needle in a
haystack.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since pitchers don't pitch inside anymore, like a (Don)
Drysdale or a Juan Marichal or like Bob Gibson _ knocking people
down all the time _ since they are not allowed to do that, hitters
stay more on top of the plate and are swinging out of there butts
trying to hit the ball out of the ballpark,'' Clark said. ``If you
look at some of the stats, you'll find out that strikeouts have
gone up quite a bit too because guys don't care about striking out.
They care about going up there and dippin' and rippin'.''
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, young talent are spending just as much time in
the weight room as the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys you see now coming into the game are much bigger and
stronger,'' Clark said. ``When I first started in the league if you
saw a couple of opposite-field home runs, that was a bunch. Now
everybody and their grandma is hitting them. Even itty-bitty
shortstops are hitting the ball out the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the major league level, we'll see what happens with
the run production. If it continues then they are going to have to
do something to make it just as fair for the pitcher as the
hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Batters hit 2,875 homers in the first 1,122 games this season,
an average of 2.56 per game through Wednesday. That's up 12 percent
from the 2.28 hit in a comparable period to start the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the results of the study,'' said Sandy Alderson,
executive vice president of baseball operations. ``(We are)
confident that the baseballs being used in major league games are
consistent with 1999 baseballs in terms of both quality and
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball officials and researchers went to the Rawlings plant in
Costa Rica, its testing facility in Missouri, the factory in
Mississippi where they make the ball's cork center and the mill in
Vermont where they spin the yarn that is wound around the
compressed cork core.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that the 2000 baseballs and the 1999
baseballs are essentially the same,'' Sherwood said. ``The
difference between their batted-ball distance is negligible.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, this year's ball actually traveled 1.4
feet shorter than last year's in batted-ball simulations. This is
well within the range baseball deems acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
