<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8258 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     06-29 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE PLACEMENTS TO THE RESCUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marty Fahey traveled from city to city on a schedule that
started in May and stretched into June, stuck all the way with a
dismal stock price that only got worse as the miles piled up.
</P>
<P>
   Fahey was something we see alot of these days, the chief
executive of a Internet company burning through cash with no
opportunity to sell more stock to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Fahey's travels comes with a qualified happy
ending. His company, Webhire Inc. of Lexington, Mass., locked up a
$16 million private placement managed by Piper Jaffray and priced
at $2.35 per share Wednesday. The catch: existing Webhire
stockholders were diluted by nearly a third to raise what would
have been considered short money just six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   There are scores of Internet companies like Webhire, caught
between a financial rock and a hard place. Some go out of business,
or merge, or just cut their spending to the bone hoping to ride out
the storm. Private placements, the sale of company stock to a few
selected buyers with deep pockets, are one of the more attractive
options if you can pull one off.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other companies, Webhire had interesting potential but
no bottom line results to show for it. The company works the
recruiting business from the Web but unlike better-known sites like
Monster.com, it targets recruiters instead of employees.
</P>
<P>
   Webhire had a big advantage in its search for cash that most
other Internet companies don't enjoy. Softbank Capital Partners,
the giant Internet venture group, had already sunk $20 million into
another Webhire private placement last summer and wasn't going to
walk away from its investment.
</P>
<P>
   As Fahey traveled from Boston to New York, Philadephia and
Minneapolis, he knew full well that Webhire was on course to burn
through the last of its cash by late July. But he also knew
Softbank general partner Charles Lax would write a check by himself
to keep Webhire afloat if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Even that was unlikely to be necessary. Webhire had been talking
to Korn/Ferry International, the big executive search company,
since early this year.
</P>
<P>
   Korn/Ferry proved to be the ideal strategic investor for
Webhire, agreeing to buy half the private placement. Softbank
ponied up another $4 million. That left just a few million more and
Webhire found two investors to buy the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no point when we were worried about closing the
doors,'' said Fahey. ``It's a luxury many companies don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   There may have been a safety net, and eventual success, but
Webhire's journey was no joy ride. The company's stock was getting
pummeled, down to $6 per share when Fahey started on the roadshow
and just barely above $2 by the time he made his last pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The tumble this year is actually far worse. Webhire shares were
approaching $19 per share early this year. Even with a bounce from
the announcement, Webhire's 77 percent loss so far this year ranks
as one of the 10 worst among all public companies based in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood of investors is dramatically different,'' said Fahey.
</P>
<P>
   Webhire is actually an older company that adopted the Internet
later in life. For years it served recruiters via computer but
worked in the older ``client-server'' computer world.
</P>
<P>
   The company saw its industry moving to the Web and went with it,
changing from the old name Restrac Inc. to Webhire last year.
Attracting a big Internet investor like Softbank and creating an
online relationship with Yahoo! Inc. was another big strategic
step.
</P>
<P>
   The company embraced the Web and its big-spending ways. It saw a
potential market share landgrab as the recruiting business moved to
the Web and took its best shot.
</P>
<P>
   That suited Softbank just fine and Lax urged the company to
build fast. But Webhire's old venture capital backer, TA
Associates, had different idea. TA had invested in the old Restrac
as a software company years earlier and didn't plan to remain a
long-term investor in the new Internet strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charley Lax's desire is go, go, go, this is a long term
play,'' said Fahey. ``TA is saying, when are you going to get to
profitability. These are two very different views of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Lax discovered TA Associates wanted to get out just after
Softbank invested $20 million in Webhire last summer and wasn't
happy. But by Dec. 22, TA Associates distributed its stock to
limited partners and was out of the investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie Lax and Softbank came in thinking they could help the
company complete that transition,'' said TA Associates chief
executive Kevin Landry. ``They're a great investor and they know
that space. It's a more appropriate deal for them than TA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, all these (Internet) stocks got a bit over-priced
last winter and we didn't want to stay in for three or four years.
When the stock ran up, we decided to distribute it. In hindsight,
I'm damn glad I did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Webhire has a new crop of investors and a bit of financial
breathing room. A sign of the times: ask Fahey when Webhire will
make a profit and he has a ready answer. Toward the end of next
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's a common profit timetable among Web companies that have a
new lease on life. By then, they will likely be back on their feet
or flat on their face for good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
