<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE IS NO POINT IN CAULKING THE GAP IN ATTIC SHEATHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. At both ends of my attic, there are boards that run across
the frame of the house. They all have gaps about 3/4-inch wide.
Would there be any problem if I caulked the gaps? These are the
boards that the shingles and tar paper are nailed onto. The house
was built about 1939.
</P>
<P>
   W.J.R., Wollaston, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is no need to caulk between those boards that are a
part of the sheathing of your house. The tarpaper and shingles
cover the wall on the outside, and that is all you need. There is
nothing you have to do. Frankly, it would be a waste of time and
caulking to do so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house is about 20 years old and I would like to replace
some tarnished door knobs. The opening in the door for the knob is
1 3/4 inches. All replacement door knobs I have seen require a 2
1/8-inch opening. How can I make those holes bigger?
</P>
<P>
   ALEX KOREN, New Bedford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Before doing anything, check to see if your knobs are solid
brass, which I think they are, since most knobs are. Put a magnet
on the knob; if it sticks, the knob is not brass. If it doesn't
stick, it is solid brass. If solid brass, the knobs were probably
lacquered, and eventually the lacquer wore off, and the brass
tarnished. You could take off any remaining lacquer with lacquer
thinner, then polish the brass with Noxon or other metal polish.
The knobs will tarnish again, but tarnished brass really does not
look too bad. If you like you can spray them with a clear spray
plastic, which will last a few years.
</P>
<P>
   OK, if you have to replace the knobs, you can enlarge the small
holes with a hole saw, a device that comes in all sizes, including
2 1/8 inch, and attaches to a power drill. While it is a little
difficult to make the hole bigger with one of these hole saws than
to make it from scratch, you should be able to do it with care. To
make it easier, clamp a scrap piece of wood on the door over the
existing hole so the bit of the hole saw will start drilling in the
right position.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house is built over a 4-foot crawl space with a sand
floor. My question is about preventing moisture under the house. I
live about a quarter-mile from the beach. The floor of the crawl
space appears to be dry. There is 3 inches of faced insulation
between the floor joists. The space is vented with four 12- by
6-inch vents. I read articles that say 6-mil plastic sheets shoud
be laid on the sand floor to seal out moisture. One of the articles
also mentions leaving a 6-inch gap between the plastic sheet and
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Is this something I should do? What is the correct way to
install the plastic sheet? Where can I buy it?
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD CONRON, Bourne, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Even though the sand floor appears dry, water vapor is
constantly coming up through it. Your crawl space is not damp
because of those vents, which are doing their job of venting the
water vapor away before it condenses into water.
</P>
<P>
   While it is not urgent, I think it is a good idea to put down
the plastic to stop that water-vapor migration. Six-mil plastic may
be hard to find; if you cannot, 4-mil plastic, widely available,
will do. Put it on the entire floor of the crawl space, so that it
folds up the foundation for 6 to 12 inches, and overlap sections by
at least 2 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Weight it with stones or bricks if you like. Keep the vents open
all year long, although you can close them from November to April,
because there is less moisture in the air in winter. But keeping
them open all year long will not hurt.
</P>
<P>
   I have never heard of leaving a 6-inch gap between plastic and
foundation; it does not make sense and will defeat the purpose of
the plastic completely, as if you never bothered with it in the
first place. Leave no gaps.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You have helped me soundproof my apartment, but in
soundproofing I did not figure in the windows, and my daughter's
dogs are in a pen 5 feet away. Will acoustic drapes help, if there
is such a thing, or perhaps acoustic blinds? What would be better
for dulling the sounds of barking.
</P>
<P>
   TIM ILINITCH, Templeton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Don't get me started on barking mutts. It is a very sore
subject. It is not the dogs who are fault; it is their masters.
</P>
<P>
   But there are things you can do: If your windows are double
glazed (two layers of glass), or are single-glazed with a storm and
well weatherstripped, that is a good start. Adding a layer is your
next priority, and will make a big difference. Any kind of a solid
layer will help reduce sound. Thermal draperies will work as
acoustic barriers, but they must be attached to the casing on all
four sides; otherwise they are not going to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Window Quilts are good thermal/acoustical draperies; they are
sold in energy stores, stove and fireplace shops, and other shops.
They come opaque or translucent.
</P>
<P>
   Or, try an inside storm window. Not only will you save heat but
you will reduce sound considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Then put the dog pen 100 feet _ 1,000 feet _ away!
</P>
<P>
   You can buy inside storms from: Zip Storm, which provides
plastic strips for installing acrylic sheets; you buy the acrylic
separately: TryWindow Saver Co., Carlisle, Mass., 800-321-9276, or
Innerglass, Simsbury, Conn., 800-743-6207, 860-651-3951.
</P>
<P>
   These are real glass, and in the handyman's opinion, better than
acrylic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house is less than a year old, and already some of the
doors do not close properly: The latches do not fit into their
keepers snugly; you have to lift the doors to make the latches
engage. The contractor nailed into the hinge-side jambs to try to
make the doors and doorways vertical. Is there an easier way to
make the doors latch properly?
</P>
<P>
   KAREN SMITH, Canton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, and nailing into the hinge-side jamb is not one of them.
The jambs are not vertical because of shoddy workmanship. Making
them vertical requires taking everything apart and rebuilding the
jambs.
</P>
<P>
   Short of that, here's the quick fix: First, make sure the doors
are tight in their openings. Then, if the jambs are not too far out
of vertical, you can adjust the keeper (also called latch plate) so
the latch will fit. Since you have to lift the door to get it to
latch, it means the opening in the keeper (the hole in the jamb) is
too high. Relocating the keeper is impossible because the screws
cannot be moved that short a distance.
</P>
<P>
   So remove the keeper and file the bottom of the opening, enough
so the latch will fit, about 1/8 inch.
</P>
<P>
   But since the house is less than a year old, the builder should
rebuild all those jambs so they are vertical and correct. And don't
take no for an answer; some builders will delay the work until the
homeowner gives up, and until the warranty (normally one year)
expires. But if you ask the builder to correct substandard work
before the warranty expires, then he is obliged to do so promptly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
