<HEADLINE>
WORDS TO BE REMEMBERED BY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I am on my deathbed, I think I will feel most proud of my
support network of family, friends, and members of my
Unitarian-Universalist church. Because we could count on one
another, every one of us has been able to take risks and be guided
in our actions by our dreams of a more just and caring world. I've
been able to make hard decisions, like the one not to sign what I
consider an unfair contract in order to continue writing for the
Globe, because I do not feel I stand alone.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, a group of my friends formed a study group to
discuss Wayne Muller's book, ``How, Then, Shall We Live? Four
Simple Questions That Reveal the Beauty and Meaning of Our Lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Muller's first question is, ``Who Am I?'' Are we merely the
offspring of certain parents, or could a few ordinary women
actually think of themselves as ``the light of the world?'' Did we
dare to believe, with Nelson Mandela, that our ``playing small''
was a disservice to the world?
</P>
<P>
   Muller's second question is ``What Do I Love?'' We came to see
that what we love shapes our souls as a magnet molds filings, that
every choice we make either strengthens or deforms our deepest
being.
</P>
<P>
   His third question is ``How Shall I Live, Knowing I Will Die?''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about our deaths dispelled the illusion that tomorrow
was ours to dispose of as we pleased. We discussed what changes are
required when you realize you can't be unafraid, or make amends, or
do what is right at some later date. If this moment is in fact the
only moment we can count on, what did we want to do with our lives,
starting now?
</P>
<P>
   We decided to write our obituaries so that we might
imaginatively encounter the ending that is always only one breath
away.
</P>
<P>
   This is what I wrote:
</P>
<P>
   Linda Weltner passed away today, leaving behind her grieving
family and a troubled earth, whose cause she championed all her
life.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weltner, who strove with all her might to leave the world a
better place, was a spokesperson for caring and authenticity. In
her weekly Globe column, and later as an inspiring public speaker,
she urged others to see the beauty of their lives and the value of
their relationships, despite the imperfection inherent in all human
endeavors. She was aligned in her social activism with like-minded
and beloved colleagues who did not shrink from taking on powerful
enemies, including massive power companies like Pacific Gas &AMP;
Electric, the multibillion-dollar telecommunications industry, and
media conglomerates such as The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weltner was an impassioned wife and a loving parent, a
caring sibling, and a faithful friend, roles that she held sacred.
She was a stranger to halfhearted involvement and threw herself
into life with unrestrained enthusiasm, often to the dismay of
others. Having grown up poor, she felt that her good fortune was a
debt to be repaid. She was burdened all her life by an
overdeveloped sense of responsibility, which _ from necessity _ she
finally learned to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weltner's grandchildren will remember the many hours they
spent with her building volcanoes, dollhouses, train layouts, and
other projects, as well as her dramatic reading of the entire
``Harry Potter'' series. Her children will remember her as an
indefatigable parent. Despite their protests to the contrary, as
their embarrassment recedes into the past they will come to view
her outrageousness as a great loss in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weltner, who found herself facing the end with a surprising
degree of equanimity, spent her last hours writing a long letter of
affection to those she loved. It is hoped that her spirit will live
on in the memories of those whose lives she touched.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Linda Weltner is a freelance writer. Her Web site is
http://www.shore.net/weltner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
