<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8262 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS &LR;      06-29 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILD NEW STORAGE SPACE TO HOLD THE LEFTOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
(poetry style) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the world of mules
</P>
<P>
   There are no rules.
</P>
<P>
   Ogden Nash &QL; 
 &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No rules for mules?
</P>
<P>
   That's a great idea, but a better one would be to establish
rules _ for packrats.
</P>
<P>
   Picture this: Mr. and Mrs. Bookworm decide that it is time to
clean out the bookcases. There are books on the floor, on tables,
on chairs, under tables, on the toilet (hey, I know someone who
stores books that way).
</P>
<P>
   So, Mrs. Bookworm takes all the books she wants to give away and
stacks them in a neat pile, maybe 2 feet high. Pretty good. Mr.
Bookworm does the same with his.
</P>
<P>
   Then they make check each other's throw-aways. Oh, no, each
says, you can't dump that book. It is signed by the author. You
can't do this, and you can't do that, until most of each pile goes
back into the bookcases. And they go out to get another bookcase.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there should be a rule.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same with any possession: Cards, bicycles, old boards,
new boards, fuses, a mouse skeleton (It was a Colonial mouse,
Pop!), rocks, 78 r.p.m. records, pants too big, pants too small,
wind-up toys, broken toys, Grandma's old sheets and pillowcases
(might be worth something some day). Everything needs winnowing.
</P>
<P>
   We are a nation of packrats, saving everything we ever owned.
``Might use it some day,'' goes the philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be worth a lot someday,'' goes another philosophy.
Yes, it's worth keeping some items, especially linens, dresses, and
accessories, which can bring good money. But how many people find
an old item and sell it for $25,000, even $2,500?
</P>
<P>
   Can we break this habit? Maybe. It involves storage space, space
that you have to make or find at your house.
</P>
<P>
   The space must be right: the right size and the right shape.
With such space, you can sort material and keep some of it, having
done the most important thing: get rid of unnecessary, superfluous,
redundant, useless, and worthless things.
</P>
<P>
   The basement is not always good storage space. It is often damp
and not good for storing clothing (it will decay) or metal items
(they will rust). Attics are OK; the more they are ventilated, the
better.
</P>
<P>
   There may be space in the house for storage that you never
realized was there: under stairs, in a corner of an overly large
bedroom, the basement stairs (if they are wide enough, you can
build shelves along the empty walls).
</P>
<P>
   Even an empty wall in a kitchen, where nothing else will go, can
hold a shallow cabinet to contain bottles, glassware, and mugs.
Sometimes you can cut into the wall and build a shallow cabinet in
that interior space. This is best done with interior walls; an
exterior wall will not work to hold storage because it is
insulated, or should be.
</P>
<P>
   If you build a closet, make sure it is at least 2 feet deep.
Such a closet will be deep enough to accommodate jackets hung
sideways. It will also hold most storage boxes, which you can buy
at home goods stores.
</P>
<P>
   Old houses have closets, but they were usually only about 12
inches deep, way too small to store things easily. And really old
houses had no closets at all, but portable closets called armoires.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy new and antique armoires. Or you can build one, to
hold entertainment equipment or, or of all things, clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Finding storage space for our collective stuff is all well and
good, but it will not solve the original problem: how to weed out
useless and worthless things.
</P>
<P>
   Here is where a rule is needed, a rule that says you must clean
everything out once every five yaars.
</P>
<P>
   One way to weed out your stuff is to tear down the tool house,
to make room for a bigger one or a garage, which will be a great
place to store everything but cars.
</P>
<P>
   To tear down the tool house, you have to empty it. And if there
is no room to store things temporarily, you have to get rid of
them. It is amazing how much junk you can chuck when you have to.
</P>
<P>
   Another way is to throw away anything that you have not seen,
used or thought about in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Have a hard heart, and try not to do it by committee; other
members of the family are impossible to work with. Let them do
their own with their hard hearts and your high hopes.
</P>
<P>
   When you're all done, do it all over again.
</P>
<P>
   It can work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0124 </DOCNO>
