<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8263 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-REPRODUCTIONS-2T     06-29 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-REPRODUCTIONS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 USING OLD TECHNIQUES, ARTISANS REVIVE AMERICAN CRAFTS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Folks who visit recreated colonial villages such as Sturbridge
(Mass.) Village or Strawbery Banke in Portsmouth, N.H. often relish
thoughts of buying a falling-down Colonial house with good bones,
restoring it to its former grandeur, and furnishing it with period
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they may have to win the lottery first. How else to
afford a set of Windsor chairs when a single chair with its
original paint costs around $10,000, and even the smallest Shaker
box sells for $400? And forget about ceramics _ most slipware, or
redware, resides in museums or private collections.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a way to get that 18th-century look for your home,
and for affordable prices _ reproductions.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a new idea, of course. But we're talking genu-
</P>
<P>
   ine reproductions. Not those mass-produced retreads seen in
chain stores but handcrafted, one-of-a-kind pieces, produced by
skilled craftspeople.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been such an information explosion in the past 10
years along with so many advances in technology,'' says Mimi
Handler, editor and publisher of Early American Homes magazine,
``that craftspeople making traditional reproductions today know as
much about how they were made as the old guys. . . . And each piece
is signed. This does make them fairly expensive, but the
craftsmanship is worth the price tag.''
</P>
<P>
   The demand for these high-quality pieces means that there are
more artisans making more and better reproductions because
``craftsmen can now make a pretty good living making quality
traditional pieces,'' says Handler. ``The Internet has also helped
educate buyers who are interested in American decorative arts.''
</P>
<P>
   For both addicts and those with a new interest in Americana, the
backroads of New England could not be a better classroom. Five of
the most talented traditional craftspeople among the region's
growing number are Ron Geering, a potter and blacksmith who lives
in Falmouth, Mass. and makes decorative English and American
slipware, or redware; Gerry Dunphy and Terry Wakeman, woodworkers,
who own Classics in Wood in Ashford, Conn., makers of Windsor
chairs and other furniture; and Pam and Harley Savage, a painter
and woodworker, respectively, owners of Frye's Measure Mill in
Wilton, N.H., where measures, piggins, and other woodenware have
been made since 1876.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ron Geering
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Geering has been reproducing museum-quality pieces of early
American earthenware, stoneware, and metalwork since graduating
from Wayne State University, in Detroit, in 1971. He came east in
1985 to help Plimoth Plantation set up its 17th-century forge and
to supervise the museum's craftspeople. He developed the line of
pottery that's sold in the museum's shop. A stint as director of
exhibits at the Children's Museum of Rhode Island came next, before
Geering became a freelance product designer and illustrator. He's
presently in the process of turning his Falmouth garage into a
small combination studio/shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been drawn to slipware because it's easy pottery
to live with,'' says Geering. ``It's earthy and not real precious,
even though it's expensive because it's so labor intensive to make.
Traditionally, in England and then here, large slipware plates were
made to commemorate special occasions like birthdays or weddings.''
</P>
<P>
   A wedding plate often included a colorful, primitive drawing of
the couple in the middle of the plate with their first names and
the date of their wedding printed around the rim. Others boasted
sayings around the rim: ``Love in the spring is for the maiden'';
``As a ring is round and hath no end, so is my love unto my
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The charm of this type of pottery is in the technique,'' says
Geering, ``what happens while you're working with the clay. That's
what makes it interesting for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Slipware is lead-glazed earthenware made from red clay and then
decorated with colored slip (clay mixed with water) before it is
fired in a kiln. It is not to be confused with other earthenware _
majolica, faience, or delftware _ where the decoration is painted
on glaze after the first firing. The most unfortunate thing about
slipware is that it is often confused with the mud-brown,
mass-produced pottery that lines the shelves in tourist shops. To
be sure, slipware looks primitive with its folksy designs,
lettering, and squiggly lines, but this simplicity belies a
challenging technique.
</P>
<P>
   To begin a piece, Geering throws the red clay on his wheel into
the shape of a plate _ he also makes cups, bowls, and two- or
three-handled tygs , or mugs. He then lets the plate dry a little
before adding the slip, which is the consistency of cream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pour the slip on a plate and then scratch through it for a
design,'' says Geering. ``I use a little wooden or metal tool to do
the scratching. This is called sgraffito, a technique that's been
around for hundreds and hundreds of years. Because it takes several
hours to complete a complicated design, I can control the hardening
of the clay by adding water.''
</P>
<P>
   For a technique called slip trailing, which Geering compares to
decorating a cake, he squeezes slip from a child's ear syringe and
places the end of a feather in the nozzle, which acts like a
pencil. In the old days, he says, potters used an animal bladder or
clay cup with a cock feather or goose quill in the nozzle. There's
also feathering combing _ a technique in which a needle is dragged
across the slip in various directions, creating a geometric design.
</P>
<P>
   ``To ensure authenticity, I've done extensive research,'' says
Geering. ``I stay with the motifs of the 17th century but also
incorporate my own ideas into them. My large plates, because
they're so time consuming, sell for $500. Smaller, simpler plates
are $150, and the small vessels are $24.''
</P>
<P>
   His pieces are dishwasher and microwave safe and lead-free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Dunphy and Terry Wakeman
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to legend, King George I of England was fox-hunting
when it began to rain and he sought shelter in a subject's rustic
home. There he sat on a simple but comfortable chair, which he
liked so much that he immediately commissioned several for his more
palatial lodgings.
</P>
<P>
   This may indeed be myth, because when George took the throne in
1714, the Windsor-style chair was already being used as garden
seating at Windsor Castle.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their origins, the chairs, with their basic
stick-and-socket design of legs, arms, and back spindles anchored
by a solid plank seat, reached American shores in the 1730s. Here
they were copied and reinvented by Colonial furniture makers. But
their graceful form, sturdy construction, surprising comfort, and
versatility have ensured their popularity through the years.
Although some believe the chairs were painted to cover up the
different woods used for the various parts, most agree they were
originally painted to hold up outdoors and to accentuate their
lines. And according to Early American Homes magazine, the Windsor
chair is ``the greatest success story in the history of
furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8264 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CENTRA-NAVICKAS-ART-B     06-29 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTRA-NAVICKAS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 CENTRA TAKES EARLY LEAD IN WEB-BASED EDUCATION SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a New Year's Eve party on the last day of 1994, Lotus
Development Corp. executive Leon Navickas finally found someone
willing to listen to his idea for a new kind of software.
Unfortunately for Lotus, that someone wasn't Navickas's boss.
Instead, it was a venture capitalist with money to invest.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Navickas runs his own business, Lexington, Mass.-based
Centra Software Inc., which has taken an early lead in the market
for Internet-based education software. And despite last month's
announcement that Lotus's parent company, IBM Corp., is launching a
major drive to dominate the ``e-learning'' market, Navickas thinks
he can keep Centra on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that IBM-Lotus is fundamentally a services company,''
said Navickas. ``That's their DNA.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM's new Mindspan Solutions unit, headed by Lotus's new CEO Al
Zollar, offers a broad array of e-learning products and services,
with Lotus's LearningSpace software at its core. But the corporate
genome at Centra is tuned solely for the task of producing
educational software. Navickas thinks it's the best, and he's found
a goodly number of customers to agree with him.
</P>
<P>
   According to market research from Frost &AMP; Sullivan, Centra holds
over half the market for e-learning software, with IBM holding just
6 percent. And Microsoft Corp. has tapped Centra as a business
partner, with Microsoft salespeople pushing Centra software in all
their key accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Satisfied Centra customers include Ann Arbor, Mich.-based
Domino's Pizza LLC, which uses the software to upgrade the skills
of 1,000 administrative workers. Paul Messink, Domino's director of
intranet development, said he leaned toward buying Lotus
LearningSpace because the company already uses Lotus's popular
Notes collaborative software system. But workers found the Centra
software far easier to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really let this decision be driven by the users rather than
by IS (information services executives),'' Messink said, ``and
users certainly preferred the Centra solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Navickas didn't have e-learning specifically in mind when he
dreamed up Centra. He'd spent years working a variety of major
Lotus products, including an early palmtop computer that ran Lotus
software, and the ill-fated Jazz spreadsheet for the Apple
Macintosh computer.
</P>
<P>
   Navickas was impressed with the possibilies of Lotus Notes,
which allows teams of workers to share documents and collaborate on
projects. But Navickas thought it was missing something _ a way to
let people work together in real time. He wanted software that
would let workers send live messages to each other, or edit the
same document simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notes wasn't really built with real-time capabilities,'' said
Navickas. And back in 1994, with the Internet little more than a
gimmick, the company wasn't too interested in adding them in, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Along came New Year's Eve and a sympathetic investor.
</P>
<P>
   Navickas set up Centra and got busy producing software that
could let people work in real time over corporate networks or the
Internet. By late 1996, the company's first product was ready.
Symposium software let students work together on a single document;
it allowed them to talk to each other over the network, or even
over a slow telephone modem connection to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Centra also came up with Choreography, a program that enabled
e-learning instructors to coordinate the activities of class
members. With students scattered all over the Internet, and no
direct eye contact, an online classroom can collapse into chaos.
With Choreography, a teacher can seize control. For instance, the
teacher can force students to take turns speaking or tinkering with
a class project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies got incredibly excited about this, and they saw the
need immediately,'' said Navickas.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Sanregret, vice president of distance learning for Global
Knowledge Inc., a North Carolina technical training firm, has been
using Centra products for the past year. ``Centra is certainly the
easiest vendor to recommend to a Fortune 500 company,'' said
Sanregret. ``They've invested the most in technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanregret noted that IBM and Lotus, instead of focusing simply
on producing the best e-learning software, are more interested in
providing an entire set of educational services. Sanregret figures
that its superior software gives Centra the advantage for now; as
for the IBM approach, ``that'll be a good strategy in about a year
and a half,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   IBM has good reason to play catch up. According to International
Data Corp., companies in the Internet learning business took in
$1.1 billion last year, and will rake in $11.4 billion in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   With its software-only business, Centra will only get a sliver
of this market. But IDC analyst Cushing Alexander notes that IBM's
approach of offering complete solutions to the world's biggest
customers may actually offer an opportunity for Centra. At some of
their accounts, IBM Mindspan employees could decide that a client
is better off with Centra software rather than Lotus.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could recommend anybody's solution, theoretically, which
could give Centra an opportunity,'' said Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Navickas can even imagine a day when IBM gives up on Lotus
LearningSpace and sells Centra products to all its Mindspan
customers. ``I think that there may be another morphing of the
IBM-Lotus learning operation in the future,'' he said. ``It sort of
seems to me that they've tried this before . . . Lotus building
their own and then dropping it for best-of-breed products in that
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps IBM might even acquire closely held Centra, but Navickas
said he's not holding his breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a price for everything, but we're not angling to be
bought,'' he said. ``What we're doing now is we're building a large
and scalable stand-alone business, on the scale of Notes itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
