<HEADLINE>
ORLANDO'S MANY MANEUVERS SIMPLY MAGICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Everyone talks like a winner on draft night. The
Orlando Magic acted like one Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic went into the draft holding three of the first 13
picks. But everyone understood the draft was merely the undercard
for the Magic, who are ready to stage the basketball equivalent of
Operation Overlord Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   And they improved their already formidable chances in the free
agent market with three incredibly deft moves. By so doing, they
established themselves as a power-to-be, assuming their August
full-court press bears fruit. There doesn't seem to be any way it
won't. They have too much money and too many amenities.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic improved their team with the selection of versatile
forward Mike Miller of Florida with the fifth pick. True, they had
hoped to get the dynamic Darius Miles, but that plan fell through
when he went to the Clippers at No. 3. Miller may not be ready in
Rick Pitino's eyes, but most everyone else thinks he can play. (And
the Celtics would have taken him in a heartbeat at No. 11.)
</P>
<P>
   But Orlando still had two more picks. It exercised neither of
them. The 10th pick went to the Clippers along with cash, Corey
Maggette, and Derek Strong. In return, the Clippers sent a No. 1
pick, which, of course, means Future Lottery. The 13th pick went to
Dallas for another No. 1 (which, given Dallas's history, could also
be a lottery pick) and $3 million of Mark Cuban's pocket change.
(Some of that may have been routed to the Clippers.)
</P>
<P>
   What does this all mean? It means trouble for everyone else in
the Eastern Conference. Orlando cleared more than $4 million in
salaries _ Strong himself had three years and $11 million _ which
only enhances its already enviable position as free agency
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic now are in a position to spend more than $18 million
on the likes of Tim Duncan, Tracy McGrady, Eddie Jones, Grant Hill,
Maurice Taylor, or any other free agent they might ogle. Their game
plan was to get rid of at least one of their picks and maybe two.
But to do so while also jettisoning two salaries and getting two
No. 1s puts general manager John Gabriel in the Tiger Woods/Pebble
Beach category.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that with the Celtics' idiotic attempt to acquire
Jermaine O'Neal for three (3!) No. 1s and, well, that is why
Duncan, Hill, McGrady et al will be visiting Central Florida
starting Saturday. That's when the courtship legally can begin.
</P>
<P>
   Contracts cannot be signed until Aug. 1, but there's no such
deadline on public intentions.
</P>
<P>
   While the Magic were cleaning up, the Chicago Bulls, the other
team with picks and cap room, did some strange things. Like
Orlando, the Bulls wanted Miles, but were unable to get him. But
they then picked Marcus Fizer, which puzzled everyone since they
already have Elton Brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't understand what the Bulls are doing with Marcus
Fizer,'' Charles Barkley said on TNT.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Bulls drafted the Consensus Best Center in Chris Mihm,
which was a logical move considering they have no center. But they
then traded him to division rival Cleveland for a point guard,
Jamal Crawford, who was the hottest of the hot in the eyes of
draftniks over the last month.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford's resume: 17 games for Michigan. That's it. But he's
still an improvement over what Chicago had. Chicago GM Jerry Krause
still left ample room for small forwards (McGrady, Tim Thomas) who
might come his way during free agency. The Bulls still have a
considerable stash, but the Magic trumped them.
</P>
<P>
   We would like to think that the Clippers made out well, too.
But, well, they are the Clippers, which means, of course, that
they'll find a way to screw it all up. They picked up Maggette,
Strong, Keyon Dooling, Miles, and Quentin Richardson, as well as
cash.
</P>
<P>
   That's a good night for most teams. But the Clippers have a way
of turning gold into dross, as Barkley noted.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the Clippers' selection of the 18-year-old Miles,
Barkley said, ``I don't think this is a good fit. The Clippers are
a terrible organization. I hope that kid can get out there. There's
no excuse for what the Clippers have been doing for the last 15
years. It's a terrible organization.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right, of course. But that's old news. On the other side of
the country, the Magic were due for one long round of applause. The
real battle has yet to begin, but Orlando has put itself into the
best position to make a big hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic already had plenty going for them. Now, they have even
more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
