<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-FORESTS-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  Fees for using national forests likely to continue
</P>
<P>
   By Jen Miller
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 28 -- Despite widespread public opposition, the
federal government is likely to continue charging fees to visit
national forests.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year after legislation was introduced to end the
controversial fees, Congress has yet to vote on the measure.
Proponents of the fee charge say getting rid of it would harm the
timber industry, which relies on national forests for five percent
of its revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lois Capps, D-Ca., introduced legislation last June in part
because of public backlash to the fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't need to pay five dollars to watch a sunset or
hike a trail,'' said Capps spokesperson, Stacie Paxton. ``The fee
is a form of double taxation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bill has stalled in Congress because of worries of its
effect on the powerful timber industry. The legislation was
referred last June to the House Agricultural Committee, where it
has languished.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fee money is used for mapping roads and preparing to
harvest timbers,'' said Luci Willits, spokesperson for Rep. Mike
Simpson, R-Blackfoot. ``We want to continue the experiment to give
local forest managers time to see if the program works for them _
There are other ways to end the fee program without hurting the
timber industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government began charging fees at national forests
in 1997, aiming to improve national forests and increase timber
production. Originally slated to end this year, the program has
been extended until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the fee program is the Sawtooth National Recreation
Area. The park, which was once free to visitors, now charges five
dollars for a daily pass for park use or fifteen dollars for a
yearly pass.
</P>
<P>
   Since the program began in 1997, more than $260,000 has been
collected. This money has been used to improve recreation
facilities in Sawtooth and to add bathrooms and pave trails.
</P>
<P>
   Will Caldwell, co-founder of the Idaho Sporting Congress, said
he opposes the entry charge because he thinks it commercializes the
forest. ``[The government's] plan is to create major development:
new marinas, new hotels, new stores, new motorized vehicle trails _
They are going into business to create a theme-park atmosphere in
the national forest.''
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
