<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR OPPOSES NIEMAN CONTENDER  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Harvard University mulls a final decision on a new Nieman
Foundation curator, a heated lobbying campaign has been launched
against one of the reported leading candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In strongly worded letters to Harvard president Neil Rudenstine,
Metropolitan Detroit AFL-CIO president Donald W. Boggs and
Newspaper Guild president Linda Foley ask him to reject Freedom
Forum senior vice president Robert Giles for the prestigious Nieman
post.
</P>
<P>
   The source of their concern is Giles's former stint as publisher
and editor of The Detroit News and his role in Detroit's
still-festering newspaper labor dispute. According to Newspaper
Guild of Detroit president Lou Mleczko, there are still 600 union
workers who have not returned to their jobs five years after the
bitter strike began.
</P>
<P>
   Boggs's June 19 letter to Harvard accuses Giles of having been
``the symbol of a crippling labor dispute that has continued to
tear apart our community,'' and charges that he oversaw slanted
News coverage of the strike. ``Guild journalists across the country
. . . would see an appointment of Mr. Giles as a deep betrayal by
an institution they revere,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In her June 22 letter, Foley alleges that Giles ``condoned the
firing and replacement of some of the country's finest
journalists,'' during the early days of the strike and ``showed
himself to be committed, not to high journalistic standards, but
instead to the corporate agenda of the Gannett Co.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Mleczko said that ``our office has
not heard anything from Harvard,'' in response to the letters.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard officials declined to comment on the letters Wednesday.
And Giles did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, a study by the Pew Research Center revealed
that the Internet boom was significantly eroding the audience for
broadcast television news. Now, a new study released by the
National Arts Journalism Program (NAJP) at Columbia University
suggests that the Internet boom has significantly eroded the
coverage that broadcast television devotes to arts and culture.
</P>
<P>
   The survey _ of roughly 5,800 minutes of nightly network news
footage from 1990 to '99 _ found that a decade ago, more than 80
percent of coverage in the broad ``media'' category dealt with arts
and culture. But then cyberspace began dominating the headlines and
by 1999, arts and culture represented less than half of all network
``media'' coverage as the media business became a hotter story than
artistic media content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Media is elbowing out arts,'' says network news analyst Andrew
Tyndall, who helped produce the NAJP study. The Internet is
``obviously the story of the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the five top arts and culture stories of the
'90s _ measured in minutes of coverage _ have very little to do
with creativity and almost everything to do with our baser
impulses. The biggest story was television sex and violence (184
minutes), followed by the Academy Awards (140 minutes), Michael
Jackson's sex life (74 minutes), rebellious gangsta rap lyrics
(64), and Frank Sinatra's obituary (62 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   ``The arts aren't inherently newsworthy,'' sighs Tyndall.
``Stories that are important for the arts aren't important for
journalists, and this proves it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Monday to secondary school educators attending a Media
&AMP; American Democracy Conference sponsored by the Harvard School of
Graduate Education, Massachusetts Senator John Kerry _ an
oft-mentioned name in the Al Gore veepstakes _ took on the role of
media critic. He lamented the lowering of journalistic standards.
(``All of us in politics are dying to meet the person called
`source,' '' he joked.) And he blamed the blurring of news and
entertainment on competitive pressures ``driven by the bean
counters in the back office.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator also expressed the hope that a major media oulet
would rekindle a news renaissance _ and attract a big audience _ by
announcing its intention to eschew more sensationalistic coverage
for solid, substantiated reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's one of those things like `Field of Dreams,' ''
Kerry said. ``Build it and they will come.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One footnote to the Thomson Newspaper Co.'s decision to sell its
newspaper holdings is the fate of its intriguing experiment to
train regular citizens to become community reporters. The first
class of 15 midcareer hopefuls (average age 34) _ which included a
professional clown, a pizza delivery person and a minister _
finished a 16-week training program in late 1999 and took jobs at
Thomson papers. (Another $700,000 had been budgeted to train a
second class, but the divestiture plans intervened.)
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Thomson vice president and editorial director Jim
Jennings says the program is a solid success. What separated the
trainees ``from the 20-somethings that come out of `J-school' is
they were . . . a little bit broader in perspective,'' he says.
``They tend to write a lot less institutional material and a lot
more relevant material.''
</P>
<P>
   Most significant, 14 of the 15 initial graduates are still at
their jobs. The only exception was a staffer who left the Bucyrus
(Ohio) Telegraph-Forum because of her husband's job relocation _
but not before winning an award as best feature writer at a small
Thomson paper.
</P>
</TEXT>
