<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8292 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-OAKLAND-ECONOMY-HNS &LR;      06-29 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAKLAND-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OAKLAND'S GROWTH PUTS CRIMP ON AGENCIES FOR POOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATTHEW YI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ It is a familiar tune that has already been
heard elsewhere in the San Francisco Bay Area: corporate wealth,
fueled by the dot-coms, is pushing out nonprofit organizations that
serve the poor.
</P>
<P>
   What has been happening in San Francisco and the Silicon Valley
is now occurring in Oakland, a city that has been slower to attract
the economic growth than the rest of the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we don't want development,'' said James Thomas,
executive director of the Emergency Services Network of Alameda
County, ``it's that we don't want displacement.''
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old nonprofit organization that Thomas runs
coordinates service agencies in the East Bay. He led a group of
about 50 pickets outside Jerry Brown's home near Jack London Square
on Wednesday, asking the Oakland mayor to pay attention to their
plight.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is seeking policies to protect agencies serving the poor
and the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   He has two ideas:
</P>
<P>
   One would require landlords to give at least a year's notice
before raising rents. Typically, the agencies are on month-to-month
leases with no way to pay higher rent right away since their
budgets are fixed annually, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The second would either require commercial developments to
include space for nonprofit agencies, or have developers pay into a
trust fund, which will be used by the service providers to help pay
their costs.
</P>
<P>
   Brown acknowledged that it is a thorny problem, but one that
needs to be addressed more by the county, not the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key point is that social services are the function of the
county. We have serious responsibilities in police, fire, parks and
things like that. We have to be very careful that we don't
short-change our primary responsibilities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also pointed out that new development in Oakland is
relatively recent phenomena, so there are not great numbers of
builders or developers who would be willing to help subsidize the
nonprofit organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the city wanted to pitch in, it does not have the luxury
of significant budget surpluses like San Francisco and San Jose
have, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll work with (the agencies), but we don't have a bank with
unlimited funding. . . . We're in a very tight squeeze here,'' said
Brown, a former Democratic governor of California.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago, downtown was more ghost town than vibrant
business center. Landlords scrambled to find tenants, and office
space was given to nonprofit agencies for as little as 60 cents per
square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Those days are over.
</P>
<P>
   With the space crunch in San Francisco and the Silicon Valley,
more companies have been moving to Oakland, encouraging landlords
to fix up their units and rent them out at much higher prices: Some
increased by more than $3 per square foot.
</P>
<P>
   The vacancy rate in downtown Oakland has plummeted in recent
years, falling from 13 percent at the end of 1996 to a little over
2 percent now, according to the city's Community and Economic
Development Agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
