<HEADER>
A8293 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      06-29 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN FRANCISCO REPORTERS FACE QUESTIONS AS PART OF PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lawyers hired by the Hearst Corp. have started
closed-door questioning of San Francisco Examiner reporters in an
investigation into suspended Publisher Timothy O. White's testimony
that he offered Mayor Willie Brown favorable editorials in exchange
for support of Hearst's purchase of the rival San Francisco
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys assigned by Charles B. Renfrew, the retired federal
judge appointed by Hearst on May 10 to head the probe, conducted at
least three interviews Wednesday, starting with reporters who
covered Brown and his re-election last year. They plan to talk to
other reporters, editors, White and Hearst executives, said Sanford
Kingsley, a lawyer conducting the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to move as quickly as we can,'' said Kingsley, a
litigator at the San Francisco firm of LeBoeuf Lamb Greene &AMP;
MacRae, where Renfrew was formerly a partner. ``We don't have a
strict timetable.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, which was to have been the deadline for completion
of the Chronicle purchase, Hearst announced an extension to Aug. 31
to allow time for developments in federal court. A ruling is still
pending on an antitrust suit by Clint Reilly, a former mayoral
candidate and unsuccessful bidder for the Examiner, who contends
acquisition of the Chronicle would give Hearst an illegal monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Kingsley declined to discuss the scope of the investigation or
say how many Examiner employees would be questioned.
</P>
<P>
   The legal team, advised by a journalistic expert whose name has
not been announced, has spent weeks reviewing documents and is also
inspecting Examiner computer files, said James M. Asher, senior
vice president and legal and development officer at the Hearst
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   He said Hearst wants the investigation to remain confidential at
this stage, and has asked employees not to discuss the sessions
publicly.
</P>
<P>
   But knowledgeable sources said the questioning covered such
topics as whether articles about Brown were slanted at the
suggestion of White or other editors; whether stories were delayed
for questionable reasons, and whether the Examiner's coverage
changed after its editorial endorsement of Brown for re-election in
November 1999.
</P>
<P>
   There was also general questioning about how stories were
assigned and edited, but no questions that suggested the
investigation was focusing on a particular story, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   White, a veteran Hearst executive who had served as editor and
publisher of the Examiner since January 1999, testified May 1 that
he met Brown for lunch last August and offered editorial page
support in exchange for the mayor's backing of Hearst's $660
million purchase of the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony, in a federal court trial of an antitrust suit
challenging the sale, was denounced by staff members of both
newspapers, denied by Examiner officials and the mayor, and
repudiated by White himself in a statement released by Hearst
officials, which said he had been ``tired and confused by the
question.'' However, it turned out he had given similar testimony
to Justice Department investigators in a deposition in December
1999.
</P>
<P>
   White was placed on administrative leave May 2 and replaced as
publisher on an interim basis by George B. Irish, president of
Hearst Newspapers. Renfrew, who served on the federal bench from
1972 to 1980 before returning to law practice, was named by Hearst
on May 10 to conduct what he described as an ``open, independent
and unlimited review'' of White's testimony and the Examiner's
actions.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle sale, and Hearst's transfer of the Examiner to
local publisher Ted Fang along with a $66 million subsidy, are
being challenged in Reilly's antitrust suit.
</P>
<P>
   The trial ended May 31, but U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker is
delaying a ruling while he awaits a Justice Department reply, due
Thursday, to his invitation to enter the case or file papers
explaining its views. The department's Antitrust Division approved
the Chronicle purchase in March, but Walker wants to know whether
trial testimony about the sale process and the newspapers' value
might have changed the government's conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Renfrew's investigation is unrelated to the legal issues and is
instead addressed to the newspaper's reputation, which took a
public battering with White's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asher, Hearst's chief legal officer, said employees are being
asked to cooperate with the investigation and to keep the questions
and answers confidential so that Hearst remains free to decide
whether to make the results public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be able to preserve confidentiality of this
effort if individual employees are making public disclosures about
it that could be harmful,'' Asher said.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Editor Phil Bronstein said he also favored a
confidential investigation but added that staffers who choose to
speak publicly should not fear punishment. Bronstein, who attended
White's luncheon with Brown and has said he heard no offer of
favorable treatment, is arranging staff interviews with the
investigators and is awaiting his own interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact remains that the editorial integrity of the Examiner
was not compromised,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
