<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8295 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-CABBAGE-SALAD-HNS &LR;      06-29 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABBAGE-SALAD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAKING A BETTER-TASTING SLAW FOR THE HOLIDAY PICNIC 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARYELLEN DRISCOLL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It takes a name that sounds like an Eastern European folk dance
and a tight affiliation with picnics and cookouts for a salad of
shredded raw cabbage to wedge its way into a summer menu.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if there is any fault with coleslaw, fingers must point to
all too often a heavy ladling of mayonnaise or a lack of discretion
with the vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   The latter is most readily identified by the gag test. Take a
bite. If your throat constricts and a spastic cough follows, you've
too fallen victim to overly acidic coleslaw. One of the surest ways
to avoid this is by switching to a mildly acidic vinegar, such as
rice-wine vinegar. As for the mayonnaise, it just takes restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is a vast life beyond traditional coleslaw,
which comes from the Dutch word koolsla, meaning ``cool cabbage.''
Cabbage mates nicely with a wide combination of summer flavors to
give you a smorgasbord of ``cool cabbage'' salads to choose from on
July 4.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a food processor, shredding cabbage can take just
seconds. Cut the cabbage into wedges and feed through the mouth of
the food processor using the slicing disk attachment. For visual
variety, any of the recipes can be made with a combination of red
and green cabbage. If making a day in advance of serving, taste the
salad before serving. Its bright, gentle bite tends to dull with
time. So you might need to add an additional 1/2 to 1 teaspoon of
rice-wine vinegar or corresponding acid.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   CREAMY COLESLAW
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 6 servings)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons rice-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon celery seed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium head green cabbage, sliced into thin strips (about 8
cups)
</P>
<P>
   1 medium carrot, shredded
</P>
<P>
   1/2 small red onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   Ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl whisk lemon juice, vinegar, mayonnaise, sugar,
salt, and celery seed to blend. In a large bowl toss cabbage,
carrot, and onion with dressing to combine. Add black pepper to
taste.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN-STYLE COLESLAW
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 6 servings)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon toasted sesame oil or 2 teaspoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon honey
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced gingerroot
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon minced jalapeno, optional
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons rice-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 head Napa or green cabbage, sliced into thin strips (about 8
cups)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cucumber, quartered lengthwise and sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium orange, chopped into medium dice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   Ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl whisk oil, honey, gingerroot, jalapeno, vinegar,
and soy sauce to blend. In a large bowl toss cabbage, cucumber,
scallions, and cilantro with ginger-soy mixture to combine. Toss
with ground black pepper to taste. Before serving, sprinkle top of
salad with orange pieces and sesame seeds.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   COLE SLAW WITH BUTTERMILK-HORSERADISH DRESSING, DILL, BACON, AND
PECANS
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 6 servings)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon horseradish
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced dill
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 medium carrot, shredded
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cucumber, quartered lengthwise and sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 small red onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   3 slices bacon, cut into 1/2-inch pieces and fried crisp
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup pecans, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium head green cabbage, sliced into thin strips (about 8
cups)
</P>
<P>
   Ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl whisk horseradish, dill, vinegar, buttermilk,
sour cream, and salt to combine. In a large bowl toss carrot,
cucumber, onion, bacon, pecans, and cabbage with dressing to
combine.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   COLE SLAW WITH CURRIED MAYONNAISE, MANGO, CASHEWS, AND SCALLIONS
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 6 servings)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lime juice
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons Major Grey's mango chutney
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh cilantro, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup currants
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup roasted cashew halves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 mango, peeled and diced fine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium head green cabbage, sliced into thin strips (about 8
cups)
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   Salt Ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl whisk lime juice, chutney, mayonnaise and curry
powder to combine. In a medium bowl toss cilantro, currants,
cashews, mango, cabbage, and scallions with curried dressing to
combine. Add salt and black pepper to taste.
</P>
</TEXT>
