<HEADLINE>
$ADV04  
 IS DENNIS MILLER THE ANSWER FOR `MONDAY NIGHT FOOTBALL'? 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Due to the holiday, this column has moved in advance for use
Tuesday, July 4, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``What the hell happened to our formerly pastoral pastimes,
sports, in this country? Owners are rapacious and disloyal; players
are spoiled, ill-mannered lowlifes; coaches are abusive psychopaths
... If I see 
Neon-Deion-Prime-Time-'Do-Rag-Video-Game-Rap-Album-Krugerrand-neckla
ce-wearing-Pizza-Hut-Two-Sport-Sanders high-stepping into the end
zone like some kind of Bob Fosse-trained Nazi one more time, I
think I'm going to do the Ickey Shuffle right off a cliff.''
</P>
<P>
   _ From a 1996 rant by Comedian Dennis Miller, hired last week by
ABC-TV's ``Monday Night Football''
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 4, 2000. The St. Louis Rams host the Denver Broncos in the
regular-season opener of ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   AL MICHAELS: ``Welcome back to `Monday Night Football'
everybody, where the Denver Broncos are leading the St. Louis Rams
21-17 with one minute remaining in the game and the Rams taking
over on their own 14-yard-line, first and 10.''
</P>
<P>
   DAN FOUTS: ``That's a long way to go with only one timeout
remaining, but if anyone can do it, Kurt Warner is the man. He's a
can-do guy.''
</P>
<P>
   DENNIS MILLER: ``Did you just use the phrase can-do? Wow,
cha-cha, you're really cutting edge there! Let me do my Bette Davis
and fasten my ------- seatbelt so I can keep up with the lingo,
Fouts-meister.''
</P>
<P>
   MICHAELS: ``Warner drops back, he's looking over the middle but
now he just has to throw the ball away to avoid the sack as Nathan
Davis sends him sprawling. Not only was there a strong rush by
Davis, but the pass coverage by the Denver secondary was once again
impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   FOUTS: ``All night long, the Broncos have conceded the run and
have forced Kurt Warner to throw into deep zone coverage, and he
hasn't been able to make the necessary adjustments, and that's
coming back to haunt him now.''
</P>
<P>
   MILLER: ``I'll tell you what's haunting me, it's that beard Hank
Williams Jr. wears in the opening montage. Is he Amish now or
something? Memo to Hank: The 21st century stopped by and would like
you to return its call, babe. And if that's ------- country music
then I'm a Denver Broncos cheerleader _ and you don't see me in
midriff-baring outfits and high-heeled boots, unless you're
attending the Annual Miller Family Reunion and I've had a few too
many mimosas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Country music is more doomed than a Texas inmate awaiting a
mercy call from George W. Bush. Now I don't want to get off on a
rant here, but to me country music is Johnny Cash singing about
doing hard time or George Jones singing a love song in between SUV
wrecks and chugs of Jack Daniels _ it's not some doofus named
Bosephus doing an ersatz Daddy thing while a bunch of Carmen
Electra-looking cheerleaders jump around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, real country music scares the ---- out of radio
executives, who are nothing but Florsheim salesmen with better
haircuts. Faith Hill and Shania Twain aren't country singers,
they're midriff-baring masturbatory fantasies who look like the
daughters of one of the Golddiggers on the old `Dean Martin Show,'
babe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, that's just my opinion, I could be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   MICHAELS: ``By the way, Kurt Warner was injured on that last
play, it appears he twisted his ankle.''
</P>
<P>
   FOUTS: ``Take a look at the replay and you can see where Warner
just got tangled up in his own feet as Davis came in.''
</P>
<P>
   MICHAELS: ``So now here comes Trent Green, once considered to be
the future of this franchise before he was injured and Warner came
out of nowhere to have that magical season last year.''
</P>
<P>
   MILLER: ``Here's what gets me. Everyone on the Rams now accepts
Green as the quarterback; they just forget about the other guy! It
reminds me of when the second Darrin showed up on `Bewitched' and
he started nailing Sammy and bantering with Endora, and nobody
said, `Hey, you can't fool a bunch of witches, what the ---- did
you do with the other Darrin?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I don't want to get off on a rant here, but the substitute
is never as good as the real thing, whether we're talking about
Parkay masquerading as butter or George Lazenby trying to fill
Connery's tux as Bond or Peter Bogdanovich marrying Dorothy
Stratten's little sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, that's just my opinion, I could be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   MICHAELS: ``You might notice on your television set that the
entire Rams team is jumping around in the end zone. That's because
Trent Green just connected with Isaac Bruce on a 98-yard touchdown
pass with no time remaining, in one of the most astounding finishes
ever. Do you believe in miracles?''
</P>
<P>
   MILLER: ``Sure, I believe in miracles, because there's no other
way to explain why Matt LeBlanc makes more money blowing his nose
between takes on `Friends' than the entire Royal Shakespeare
Company earns in a good decade, cha-cha. Now I don't want to get
off on a rant here ...''
</P>
<P>
   FOUTS: ``Anybody got Rush Limbaugh's number?''
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'')
</P>
<P>
