<HEADER>
A8297 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-29 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHEN TOO MUCH PRIDE CAN SLAM THE DOORS ON SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A recent television special on the musical
highlights from ``The Ed Sullivan Show'' had a great workplace
anecdote about what happened when two egos collided: those of
Sullivan and Jim Morrison, lead singer of The Doors.
</P>
<P>
   Their clash happened in 1967, but the same principles of
arrogance and stubbornness are present today. And they are just as
self-destructive as they have always been.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what happened: The Doors were scheduled to perform their
huge hit, ``Light My Fire,'' on Sullivan's show. Because of
concerns that the song promoted drug use, the censors asked
Morrison to change one line _ ``Girl, we couldn't get much higher''
_ to something else, apparently, ``Girl, we couldn't get much
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison agreed. But then he sung the song his way.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan was furious. The Doors were never invited back to his
show.
</P>
<P>
   Now certainly their clash didn't destroy either career, but it
kept both men from being as successful as they could be. Sullivan
prided himself on attracting top musical talent, and it hurt his
show not to have The Doors on more than once. On the other hand, in
an era before the Internet or MTV, Sullivan's show was an
entertainer's best form of exposure, so the ban had to hurt The
Doors as well.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Morrison was wrong. He went back on his word,
sacrificing his credibility for the sake of one word in a lyric.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it wasn't as if network censorship was all that
unusual. Sullivan's show one time telecast Elvis Presley only from
the waist up because of his swiveling hips, and had the Rolling
Stones change their song ``Let's Spend the Night Together'' to
``Let's Spend Some Time Together.''
</P>
<P>
   (Those examples might sound ridiculous today, but censorship in
some form will always exist. I don't think you will hear Regis
Philbin asking, ``What's the street value of a kilo of cocaine in
New York City?'' anytime soon. Do you?)
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Sullivan and the censors were also wrong.
Although ``Let's Spend Some Time Together'' might make you cringe,
at least it doesn't sound like it was written by someone with a tin
ear. But the change in ``Light My Fire'' would have been horrible.
</P>
<P>
   The last word of the line needs to rhyme with ``liar'' and
``fire''; higher does, but better doesn't. It also needs to pass
for a single-syllable word; higher can, better can't. The
songwriter would have sounded like a hack.
</P>
<P>
   What happened between Sullivan and Morrison is the same sort of
thing that can happen between talented bosses and talented
employees. Both have achieved so much success that they are
determined to see things their way, without pausing to consider the
other person's point of view or whether there would be an
acceptable compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming for a minute that both men were coherent at the time of
their dispute, Morrison should have known that singing ``higher''
would embarrass Sullivan, and Sullivan should have known that
changing the word would embarrass Morrison. Yet apparently neither
managed to suggest that it would be better if The Doors simply
performed another song, or if the show just bleeped that word.
</P>
<P>
   Before you ask co-workers to make a crucial concession, think
about whether your gain is worth their sacrifice. Is there a
compromise that would allow both of you to win? Just because you
have the firepower to win a war doesn't mean you should start one.
</P>
<P>
   It is wonderful to have pride in your work, but you need to
appreciate that others have pride in their work, too. If you try to
take that away from them, you will never be able to break on
through to the other side.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
