<HEADER>
A8300 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-HARRY-POTTER-HNS &LR;      06-29 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRY-POTTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DON'T SPOIL HARRY POTTER WITH BLEEPS AND BATTERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LYSSA FRIEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mattel Inc. has secured the right to market toys
based on the hot-selling Harry Potter children's books. The fourth
title about the British wizard is scheduled for release July 8.
</P>
<P>
   Author J.K. Rowling's stories have shattered sales records at
Scholastic Press Inc. They have been translated into 28 languages.
Warner Bros. bought the film rights for a sum well into the seven
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter dominates the youth market, but adults love him,
too. The debut volume, ``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone,''
topped the New York Times bestseller list for well over a year.
``Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' and ``Harry Potter and
the Prisoner of Azkaban'' occupied the first and second slots for
months. All three remain among the nation's top eleven hardcover
sellers.
</P>
<P>
   So it was only a matter of time before a toy manufacturer cashed
in on the phenomenon. Toys 'R' Us will stock Harry Potter dolls,
games and high-tech toys in time for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The books are a fantasy wonderland. Harry's magical parents were
murdered during his infancy by Lord Voldemort, so evil he is known
as ``He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry spent his first 10 years living with his cranky relatives,
the Dursleys, in a nondescript floral British suburb. The Dursleys
are muggles _ mortals without magical skills _ and they keep
Harry's heritage a secret.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Harry's powers are revealed. He leaves for Hogwarts
School of Witchcraft and Wizardry. There owls, not postal carriers,
deliver mail. On the walls hang paintings whose characters speak
and move about, often into adjacent frames. Harry enrolls in
classes like ``Care of Magical Creatures'' and competes at
Quidditch, an aerial soccer-like game in which players dart around
on broomsticks.
</P>
<P>
   At Hogwarts, Harry meets best mates Ron Weasley, a redhead from
a family of seven wizards, and Hermione Granger, a straight-A
student and the first witch among her relations.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the books so popular?
</P>
<P>
   Rowling's rich parallel world suspends the reader's disbelief
from the first page. A good-versus-evil plot arcs through each
book. But alongside skip adventures and subplots with quick
resolutions that make the stories page-turners. Think Narnia's
magic combined with Star Wars' pacing.
</P>
<P>
   Although the escapades of Harry, Ron and Hermione involve
dragons and poltergeists, the children suffer age-appropriate
growing pains. Bullies attend Hogwarts. Fights erupt. Jealousies
percolate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I fit in?'' the witches worry. ``Will I pass the Reading
Tea Leaves test?'' ``Why doesn't she like me?''
</P>
<P>
   The Potter books have earned parental praise by encouraging a
generation of children raised on Nintendo to abandon the joystick
and pick up a book. Even slow readers and children with learning
difficulties can't put the stories down.
</P>
<P>
   Harry engages the imagination. No one has seen a Quidditch game,
but anyone who has read a Potter book can picture it played between
the golden goalposts 50 feet skyward.
</P>
<P>
   But why read about a Quidditch match when you can watch special
effects on a screen? Why fantasize about Harry catching the winged
ball that wins the game when you can switch on the computer and
beat the opposition with a click of the mouse? Why imagine what
Harry's high-speed broomstick looks like when you can unwrap a toy
facsimile on Christmas morning? Batteries not included.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter is a phenomenon because he has encouraged children
to activate their minds. And it is the marketing of Harry Potter _
the Hermione dolls, magic wands and video games _ that will dim the
light that Harry has lighted.
</P>
<P>
   By that I mean the light in the eyes of a child curled up with a
book.
</P>
<P>
   Although Harry and his friends live in a modern world, they
practice ancient divining arts. Their schoolrooms are heated by
fireplaces, the hallways lighted by candle. Harry gave children a
gift: magic and excitement that don't require the flip of a switch
or the bleep of a modem.
</P>
<P>
   So I say we return Harry's gift. Ignore the toys. Keep the
computer screens dark. Stay out of the movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   And head to the library when Harry Potter IV arrives.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Lyssa Friedman is a nursing administrator for a cancer research
program in Marin County, Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1412EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
