<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8301 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-INTERSTATE-HIGHWAYS-H     06-29 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERSTATE-HIGHWAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IKE'S HIGHWAYS, PAVED WITH GOOD INTENTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CYNTHIA BASS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANVILLE, Calif. _ President Dwight Eisenhower was still in
Walter Reed Army Hospital recovering from a heart attack when he
signed the 1956 Federal Aid Highway Act, the largest public works
project in the history of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The fruits of the 44-year-old law have been both sweet _ free
movement of people and commerce over 43,000 mapped, paved and
interconnected miles _ and bitter _ urban sprawl, rush hours and
smog. The interstate highway system stitches the country together:
Virtually everywhere is accessible. At the same time, virtually
everyone is subject to traffic, pollution and road rage.
</P>
<P>
   The history of the interstate (and of government-sponsored
highway expansion in general) offers a valuable insight into the
capacity of the state to solve long-term problems. For highways are
a classic example of how government officials grapple with the
issues of their own generation, sometimes quite successfully. The
catch is that one generation's visionary program may become the
next generation's headache.
</P>
<P>
   Federal interest in road-building began in the late 1800s, in
response to a new invention, not the car, as is widely assumed, but
the bicycle. By the 1890s, bikes were so popular that cycling
looked like a serious alternative to the far more expensive (and
environmentally harsh) railroads.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, outside of big cities, most roads were just dirt,
a complaint of the time described them as ``wholly unclassable,
almost impassable, scarcely jackassable.'' In 1893, a federal
Office of Road Inquiry was set up to research the problem of rural
transit. For the next two decades, this forefather of the
Department of Transportation preached, to whoever would listen, the
gospel of road improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Just how such improvement would be funded was decided in 1916,
when the Bankhead Bill (presented by actress Tallulah Bankhead's
senator-father) established the principle of federal-state
partnerships for the funding of roads _ a principle which, with
various tweakings, still exists today. By then, however, the car,
not the bike, was America's vehicle of choice.
</P>
<P>
   Road building blossomed during the 1920s, as the economy boomed
and the trucking industry convinced Congress of the commercial
benefits of paved highways. The '20s saw, among other things, the
first numbered highways, as well as plans for the Pan-American
Highway (Alaska to Argentina). As in the 1890s, however, the
emphasis remained on rural roads.
</P>
<P>
   During the Depression, rural road improvement, seen as a
job-source for the unemployed, continued. In 1938, President
Franklin Delano Roosevelt proposed a federally-funded toll-road
system which, unlike most New Deal programs, was supposed to be
profitable enough to actually pay for itself. His transport experts
replied that a national road system was a great idea, but argued
that since most existing roads were free, people would never pay
tolls. Instead they proposed an interstate system of ``Free
Highways'' _ freeways.
</P>
<P>
   Although World War II held up freeway construction, interest in
an interstate system remained. But a serious financial commitment
to such a project remained vague until Eisenhower's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Ike was a major proponent of the interstate. He had been
impressed by Adolf Hitler's autobahns, and believed a national road
system vital for civil defense. His 1956 Federal Aid Highway Act,
which committed both the states and the federal government to the
National System of Interstate and Defense Highways, moved the focus
from rural roads to all roads.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, costs skyrocketed (Reader's Digest, in 1960,
called the Federal Highway Program a ``rat hole'') and
dissatisfaction set in, with many Americans complaining about both
the social and environmental impacts of highways. Yet highway
construction pushed on; soon the gas tax became permanent, and the
entire look of the nation started to change.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping malls ``just off the interstate'' began to appear.
Workers began to commute by car, instead of by train, and distance
became something any American with a full tank of gas could easily
conquer. Suburbs and commerce flourished, while many urban areas
were left behind, and the skies over Los Angeles and other large
cities turned brown.
</P>
<P>
   The history of the Interstate Highway System illustrates how
democratically elected governments often operate. Politicians, in
the end, must try to please voters. This means they must respond to
the issues of the day, whether it's cycling (1890s), cars (1910s),
trucks (1920s), unemployment (1930s) or civil defense (1950s).
</P>
<P>
   In all these instances, the future took a back seat to the
present. Government, in the end, is about short-term thinking. In
the long term, it is possible that government may not be the best
agent for solving the greatest problems of a vibrant and changing
nation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cynthia Bass is a historian and columnist for the San Francisco
Examiner.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
