A8302 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-29 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE: LOST IN GREEN SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Adios, Elian. Unhappy trails, Boy Scouts. Hello
again, abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has done us all some big favors. The court
rejected appeals by Elian Gonzalez's Miami relatives and sent that
over-publicized little boy home _ right, it's his home, as
unbearable as the Leninist landlord is.
</P>
<P>
   Elian go home. It was as satisfying as watching an unworthy
contestant kicked off ``Survivor,'' except in this case, it was
back onto an island.
</P>
<P>
   The court also gave thinking kids another reason not to join the
Boy Scouts, besides having to rub sticks together and wear funny
bandannas. The Boy Scouts always were a weird bunch.
</P>
<P>
   By a 5 to 4 vote, the justices allowed the Scouts to ban gays
from serving as troop leaders, raising the question of whether the
Scouts will be giving out merit badges for finding closets in
tents.
</P>
<P>
   As a gay friend once told me, ``The Boy Scouts was where many of
us found out we were gay.''
</P>
<P>
   In their attempt to interpret their pledge to be ``morally
straight'' according to current vernacular, the Scouts are being
morally dishonest with themselves and everyone else. Does anyone
want to join an organization that purports to uphold the American
way, yet discriminates against a sizable group of Americans?
</P>
<P>
   The Boy Scouts shouldn't be that much like the Army. And neither
should the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but the Supremes made two rulings sure to invigorate our
democracy, one overturning a state ban on late-term abortions, and
another giving states more room to restrict demonstrations outside
abortion clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Those decisions have flushed George W. Bush from his catbird
seat, and forced him to talk about the one issue that could keep
him from being elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Now the amiable, inarticulate W. is appeasing right-wingers
angered by a decision that could negate some 30 states' laws
against late-pregnancy abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``States should have the right to enact reasonable laws and
restrictions, particularly concerning the brutal practice of
partial-birth abortion,'' Bush said on Wednesday. ``Unlike Al Gore,
I pledge to fight for a ban on partial-birth abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   The right wing invented that phrase for a procedure that is
rarely used, and then generally to save a woman's life.
</P>
<P>
   What Al Gore must do is play the women's card, and change the
terms of debate as surely as that phrase ``partial-birth abortion''
did. He has to talk about the right of women to save their own
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Gore isn't going to beat Bush with energy plans or by talking
about cars that don't run on gasoline. Americans love cars that run
on gasoline, and lots of it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore isn't going to beat Bush by trying to pin high gas prices
on him. Bush is playing the same game, and we know both are running
on empty on that issue.
</P>
<P>
   Gore isn't going to win on gun control or crime issues, or by
displaying his high-mindedness through the uncertain trumpet of his
voice. Watch some Regis and some MTV. This is the decade of the
amiable ignoramus, and Bush is a leader in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Women are going to carry this election. Gore and the Democrats
have to convince women that Bush and the Republicans are willing to
let them die in service of their ideology. Gore has to portray Bush
and the Republicans as goons trying to wrest control of women's
bodies as brazenly as any drunken jerks in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Women know that deep in the male brainpan is an antediluvian ape
telling them that women's bodies are not their own. Most men manage
to ignore the inner ape, but not all.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Gore's army of advisers can make a subtle connection
between rowdies who grope women's private parts, and politicians
who won't even let women have parts that are private.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this connection has to be made more gently than that.
That's the trick, and a tough one for the blaring Gore.
</P>
<P>
   He lost weight and buffed up. He learned to wear earth tones. He
can learn that when you hold a straight flush of women's cards, you
don't have to shout or wave your hand.
</P>
<P>
   He also should learn he has to play it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
