<HEADER>
A8303 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-WEDDING-ATTIRE-HNS &LR;      06-29 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEDDING-ATTIRE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOR MOTHER OF THE BRIDE, WEDDING BELLS CAN BE CACOPHONY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Selecting wedding attire can be stressful, but
Ilene Beckerman's new book finds humor in the situation for at
least one member of the bridal party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother of the Bride: The Dream, the Reality, the Search for a
Perfect Dress'' (Algonquin Books of Chapel Hill, $17.95) offers an
offbeat look at putting together a wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Beckerman, an author and illustrator who travels the country
imparting funny and sage advice to audiences, has judged People
magazine's Best and Worst Dressed issue and writes frequently on
the Oscars for the Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Her wit on mother-of-the-bride dresses comes from having three
married daughters. She also has two unmarried sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, childbirth was easier than being the
mother of the bride,'' quipped Beckerman in a recent phone
interview from her home in Connecticut. ``But I've found that, with
humor, the forgotten woman of the wedding can get through this. As
mother of the bride, don't lose your sense of humor. Remember, you
got through toilet training your daughter, you'll get through
this.''
</P>
<P>
   As mother of the bride, the pressure is also on you and how you
will look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Planning a wedding is similar to producing a show at a dinner
theater,'' Beckerman writes in her book. ``Both events have a
script, stars, a supporting cast, a budget that's too small and
critics to please.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckerman found that every bridal fashion show that she went to
featured models who were tall, thin and flat. They all looked like
bread sticks, whereas Beckerman describes her figure as more akin
to a Kaiser roll.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the prospect of finding the right dress, Beckerman
wondered what Jackie O would wear, even though she was built like
an ironing board and Beckerman is shaped more like an upholstered
chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, everybody remembers Princess Diana's wedding
dress,'' added Beckerman. ``But who remembers what her mother wore?
It's true the bride is supposed to look the best, but the mother of
the bride doesn't have to wear something that looks like something
that Mrs. Khrushchev would have worn.''
</P>
<P>
   Mother-of-the-bride selections can be dowdy. But, on the other
hand, the mother doesn't want to be in competition with her
daughter or look like one of the attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Rob McNamara, assistant store manager of David's Bridal in
suburban Albany, said that mother-of-the-bride dresses have been
updated with a more youthful look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fabrics are softer,'' McNamara said. ``You are now seeing a
lot of georgette and shear fabric for the jacket and lots of
fashionable colors to choose from. Before, you saw a lot of heavy
beading or satin with beading and the only colors to choose from
were either beige, navy or black.''
</P>
<P>
   McNamara added that mothers of the bride are also now selecting
their dresses from the bridesmaids collections for a more youthful
look. Mother-of-the-bride dresses and gowns cost $165 to $300 and
up.
</P>
<P>
   McNamara said that mothers of the bride are also buying informal
wedding gowns in ivory, but without the train, to wear for summer
wedding in a garden or on an island.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what style they choose, they usually try to buy
something with style, so that it can be cut to a tea or cocktail
length for future events.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the wedding calls for cocktail length, be careful how short
you go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of many brides who want their mother to look like
Tina Turner, even if she does have great legs,'' mused Beckerman,
who began her writing career at age 60. ``I remember trying on a
pale pink-and-violet, Monet-inspired chiffon print that Ladybird
Johnson would have loved, but I felt like I looked like a field of
wildflowers.''
</P>
<P>
   A blue sequined gown resembled the aurora borealis, and white
made her look like the Pillsbury Doughboy. Green velvet was the
twin of a pool table. Then Beckerman found a low-cut gown.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you show a little cleavage, nobody ever looks anywhere
else,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, mother-of-the-bride dresses are a lot more chic than
they were a decade ago. Many of the fashions have a fresh, young
and flattering look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the wedding party, you want to like what you are going to
wear,'' Beckerman said. ``But remember, you are not going to be
presenting an Oscar that night. Just remember that you are `in'
somebody's wedding and not the main event.''
</P>
<P>
   The best way to look for a dress, whether you are a bridesmaid
or mother of the bride, is to shop with the bride-to-be, advised
Beckerman.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, pick out a dress or gown that looks good on
you, no matter what the theme of the wedding, and go to the fitting
sessions (even if you don't like your dress). It should look like
it was tailor-made for you.
</P>
<P>
   As for color, always check with the bride before you buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sole thing to remember when buying your dress is to never
come out looking better than the bride,'' warned Beckerman. ``Yes,
get something flattering, but remember, your main job is to create
a flattering still-life backdrop for the bride's photo album of her
wedding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1414EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8306 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-SALMONELLA-OUTBREAK-D     06-29 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMONELLA-OUTBREAK-DISCOVER-$ADV20-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY IS EVERYONE SICK? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tue., June 20, 2000, or anytime thereafter.) 
 &HT;    
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (One color slide is included.) 
 By DANIEL C. WEAVER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    At 4 a.m. on a still-black Monday morning, 76-year-old Robert
Kilgalen came to the emergency room gripping his stomach. His wife
said he'd been alternating between explosive diarrhea and vomiting
for two hours.
 &HT;    He was so dizzy from loss of fluid that he could hardly stand,
and his temperature was 101.5 degrees.
 &HT;    The staff started him on fluids intravenously, then began to
examine him for clues. Toxic chemicals, viruses and pathogenic
bacteria such as shigella, E. coli and salmonella can cause
debilitating diarrhea. But sometimes chronic intestinal
inflammation can provoke it too.
 &HT;    The first step was to examine blood and stool cultures for
infection. The following day, Ellie, the lab technician, came up
from the microbiology lab. She held a small glass vial of stool
culture up to the light. ``Look. There's nothing, not even normal
flora.''
 &HT;    The antibiotics the patient had taken on the way to the hospital
had wiped out any telltale signs. The other lab results indicated
only dehydration and a slightly elevated white blood cell count. We
hadn't a clue what was wrong.
 &HT;    But before long, a feverish 8-year-old girl arrived, sick from
vomiting and diarrhea. Then an 81-year-old woman and a 3-month-old
boy came in with the same symptoms.
 &HT;    Was this the start of an epidemic? None of the new patients had
taken antibiotics, so I hoped one of the cultures would be
positive.
 &HT;    The following morning Ellie showed me the tubes. I could see
that the samples teemed with bacterial colonies. She took small
samples of the fluid and spread it out on agar plates specially
prepared to promote the growth of pathogenic bacteria and suppress
normal gut flora.
 &HT;    The next morning I went into the lab and Ellie opened the
incubator containing the cultures. She held the agar plate under
the light. There were hundreds of shiny black colonies _
salmonella. All three cultures, she said, were positive.
 &HT;    As many as 4 million salmonella cases break out in the United
States each year, making it the country's most common food
poisoning. More than 2,000 varieties of the bacterium live in the
guts of such animals as pigs, cows and chickens, without causing
them harm. (The infection can also pass from a hen to her eggs.)
 &HT;    One type _ Salmonella typhi _ lives only in humans. It causes
typhoid fever, which can be deadly. While typhoid fever is not
uncommon in countries with poor sewage treatment, it is rare in the
United States.
 &HT;    To thrive in a human, salmonellae must survive the acidic
conditions in the stomach, reach the small intestine and attach to
its lining. If enough live salmonellae get to the intestine,
diarrhea and vomiting _ the host's effort to expel the pathogen _
will follow within six to 48 hours.
 &HT;    In severe cases, the bacteria can slip into the bloodstream and
cause systemic infections. And in rare instances, mostly occurring
in the very young, weak or old, salmonella infection can lead to
death from dehydration or septic shock.
 &HT;    Given the timing of their illnesses, I guessed that all four
patients must have had a common source of infection. I talked with
each patient's doctor and learned that all but the 3-month-old had
recently eaten tapioca at a local restaurant. The 3-month-old,
whose parents were turkey farmers, proved to be infected with a
different type of salmonella.
 &HT;    Next I notified the state board of health. An inspector found
the problem: The restaurant's tapioca cooker wasn't heating the
pudding enough to kill bacteria. Instead it was warming the pudding
just enough to help bacteria grow. In the end, 13 diners at the
restaurant were diagnosed with salmonella food poisoning.
 &HT;    The key to controlling salmonella is understanding its rapid
growth. Bacterial colonies can double every 20 minutes, a rate of
growth so exponential that a single colony bred under perfect
conditions could reach the size of Earth in less than 48 hours.
 &HT;    Salmonellae grow best at about 100 degrees, making the human
body a great host. Keeping food colder than 40 degrees or hotter
than 140 degrees reins in bacterial growth remarkably.
 &HT;    Although restaurant outbreaks make the news, most food
poisonings probably occur at home. I know just how this can happen.
Some 20 years ago, to save money during my residency, I dialed my
refrigerator thermostat up to 45 degrees (my first mistake). Then I
made meat loaf with eggs, failing to cook it long enough (second
mistake), left it overnight on the counter (third mistake), put it
back in the refrigerator (fourth mistake), reheated it in a
microwave oven (fifth mistake) and ate it.
 &HT;    Six hours later I discovered firsthand salmonella's incubation
period.
 &HT;    This week I went back to the restaurant for a fine traditional
meal: mashed potatoes, fresh bread and fried chicken. Tapioca
pudding wasn't on the menu.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Pathologist Daniel Weaver trained at Washington University in
St. Louis and began his career as a research scientist. He lives in
Jasper, Ind., with his wife and two children.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
