<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8310 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-HNS &LR;      06-29 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IN THE CALM AFTER CAMPAIGN STORM, MEXICO WAITS OUTCOME OF
PRESIDENTIAL RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BONNIE PFISTER and SUSANA HAYWARD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEON, Mexico _ After months of mutual accusations and
bitterness, the heated race for the Mexican presidency is over. As
of Thursday, and until balloting ends Sunday night, candidates must
keep a low profile and cannot air television campaign ads.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, alcohol sales will be barred throughout the country
until the election is over.
</P>
<P>
   After a ride on horseback in Loma Blanca, outside Mexico City,
rancher Vicente Fox flew to his home state of Guanajuato, where
thousands of residents of the state capital, Leon, cheerfully
awaited the presidential candidate of the National Action Party
(PAN).
</P>
<P>
   ``Not one more minute!'' the former governor of Guanajuato said,
referring to the 71-year rule of the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   PRI candidate Francisco Labastida flew from Mexico City to his
native state of Sinaloa. He once served as governor of the western
state. About 50,000 Labastida supporters, waving the PRI's green,
red and white colors, gathered at the city's plaza as the candidate
addressed the crowd shortly after 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a great emotion, with my heart in my hand, with women,
men, farmers and workers at my side, we will have the victory next
Sunday,'' said Labastida, dressed in his usual khaki pants and blue
shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be the first president who was born in Sinaloa and the
first who was secretary of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will support the countryside, I will work for all but I
won't forget my friends,'' Labastida said, referring to his mostly
rural state.
</P>
<P>
   He said his would be a ``popular government, not a populist
one,'' in a reference to what pundits call Fox's populist
tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   He also promised a ``strong arm'' against crime, a worry in
Sinaloa, where drug crime has been on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Labastida called for conciliation and peace once final
election results are known.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is for there not to be rancor or hatred
among Mexicans,'' he said Tuesday in Cuernavaca, state of Morelos.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent polls show Labastida and Fox in a virtual dead
heat, making this the closest presidential race in the country's
history.
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo appeared live on television Wednesday
and praised the candidates for running spirited campaigns. He also
told voters they could count on a fair and legal election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can trust that each one of us will vote in liberty, secrecy
and that each vote will count,'' Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
   In Leon, a city of 950,000, thousands gathered at the municipal
stadium to celebrate the man they believe will end PRI's
seven-decade control of the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just hours away from a new history for Mexico,'' Fox
told the crowd of 60,000. ``I will be a president of all the
people. I will extend my hand to everybody regardless of their
electoral preferences.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said that if elected he would ask congress to form a
committee to confront Mexico's narcotics trafficking problems, one
of the sore points in its relations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Along the main Lopez Mateos Boulevard late Wednesday, families
in station wagons and workmen in trucks honked their horns in
support of Fox. Blue-and-white PAN flags fluttered from car
windows.
</P>
<P>
   On a more somber note, Fox's national campaign manager, in Leon
for the festivities, denounced alleged coercion tactics by the PRI
in four states.
</P>
<P>
   Some skeptics here believe the PRI will eke out yet another
presidential victory with its extensive social programs and
insinuations that a Fox win would cost poor farmers.
</P>
<P>
   But the thousands of people crowding Leon's streets were
confident of a Fox victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enthusiasm here: it's like a soccer match, only more
important. Mexico's future will be decided,'' said Humberto
Bonilla, holding a cardboard image of the V-for-Victory salute that
Fox has used throughout his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old operator of a leather shop and his nephew Ivan
Hernandez Bonilla, walking to the stadium, were undaunted by
streaks of lightening and threatening clouds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rain would be a blessing. The heavens are crying tears of
happiness!'' said Hernandez, 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viva Mexico! Viva Vicente Fox!''
</P>
<P>
   Former Mexico City Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of the leftist
Democratic Revolutionary Party is running a distant third in the
race.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, he rejected a plea from Fox to join his team,
which would assure the PAN the presidential win.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas, who many believe won the 1988 presidential election
only to have it stolen from him by PRI, charges that Fox, a former
Coca-Cola executive, caters to U.S. interests and would privatize
the oil monopoly Pemex, nationalized since 1938.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Cardenas spoke to a crowd in Ciudad del
Carmen, repeating his campaign message that the oil industry was a
metaphor for the country, a promising resource that has been
misused by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 70 million people are eligible to vote Sunday at 114,000
polling stations throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   The elections are being monitored by the independent Federal
Electoral Institute, which will send out 800,000 observers to
polling stations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1432EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8311 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-SMART-PILLS-DISCOVER-     06-29 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMART-PILLS-DISCOVER-$ADV20-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMART PILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tue., June 20, 2000, or anytime thereafter.) 
 &HT;    
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (One color illustration is included.) 
 By WILLIAM SPEED WEED 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    ``The world will little note, nor long remember, what we say
here, but it can never forget what they did here.'' Without reading
that sentence from Lincoln's Gettysburg Address again, you can
probably recite most of the words because they're stored in your
short-term memory, that bustling depot of the brain where fleeting
ideas come and go but never stay.
 &HT;    Long-term memory is another thing. Most people would have to
read the sentence out loud, write it down and test themselves
repeatedly to get it permanently down pat.
 &HT;    Repetition is the mother of all learning because our brains must
undergo a physical change in order to form a long-term memory:
Neurons have to grow new connections to one another to create a
structural basis for whatever it is we'll remember _ be it a fresh
idea, a telephone number or a famous speech. As anyone who's ever
been a student knows, memory construction takes work.
 &HT;    But what if you could swallow a little pill that gave you a
photographic memory, the ability to form long-term memories
instantly? With such a pill, the world as a whole would long
remember, for the first time in history, anything it wanted to.
 &HT;    Clinical trials for a memory-enhancing drug are just two to five
years away, say Jerry Yin and Tim Tully of Cold Spring Harbor
Laboratory on Long Island, N.Y.
 &HT;    At the center of their work is a protein that helps nerve cells
in the brain store memories. A sudden increase in the activity
levels of the protein sends the memory-making process into
overdrive and allows neurons to make long-lasting storage
structures immediately, without the slow work of repetition.
 &HT;    Yin and Tully first discovered the importance of this memory
protein (a form of CREB, for Cyclic AMP Response Element Binding
protein) while working with fruit flies.
 &HT;    They created two new, genetically altered strains of fruit fly:
one with extremely high levels of memory protein and one with
almost none of it. Then they conditioned the flies by placing them
in tubes and blowing in scented air currents. One scent ``smelled
like my tennis shoes in July,'' Tully says. The other smelled like
licorice and was accompanied by a small electric shock. A fly that
is zapped every time it smells licorice should eventually build a
set of neural connections that says, ``Avoid licorice!''
 &HT;    The question is: How much repetition does it take for that
long-term memory to form?
 &HT;    Yin and Tully tested the flies by placing them in the middle of
a double-ended tube and blowing tennis-shoe scent in one end and
licorice scent in the other.
 &HT;    Flies with normal levels of the memory protein needed to be
zapped 10 times before they stopped moving toward the licorice
scent. In other words, they could build the neural connections
needed for an ``Avoid licorice!'' memory, but it required spaced
repetition _ just as normal humans must say a sentence over and
over again to memorize it.
 &HT;    Yin and Tully then tested a strain with low levels of memory
protein and found that those poor flies never made the structural
changes necessary for lasting memory. No matter how many shocks
they received, they went for licorice scent as often as they went
for tennis-shoe scent.
 &HT;    The flies with an overabundance of memory protein formed
long-term memory instantly. After only one trial, they knew to
avoid licorice the rest of their lives.
 &HT;    Tully points out that these flies haven't gotten smarter _
they'll never solve quadratic equations. Extra memory protein
simply accelerates the pace of memorization by eliminating the need
for repetition.
 &HT;    Yin and Tully suspect that the memory protein is a sort of
construction-crew foreman in the brain that turns on the genes
neurons need to grow new connections, a process that normally
occurs bit by bit with repetition. When a brain is awash in memory
protein, the building process occurs all at once.
 &HT;    ``You require less training to initiate memory,'' Tully says.
``That's a dramatic switch.''
 &HT;    The finding could ultimately have dramatic implications for all
of us because it is overwhelmingly likely that memory protein has
essentially the same role in human brains as it does in fly brains.
 &HT;    The pharmaceutical challenge Yin and Tully must solve _ and they
say they're close _ is to find a compact chemical that can
infiltrate neurons, stimulate an overproduction of the protein and
thereby give the human brain a hurry-up, neural-connection
construction crew.
 &HT;    This pop-a-pill enhancement is expected to last only a few hours
before memory protein levels return to normal, but while levels are
up, we'll be like the one-zap flies, with supercharged
memory-making.
 &HT;    What great news! Wash down a pill, read one of Shakespeare's
plays, and you'll know it by heart! Learn a new language in a month
_ without flash cards! Get a law degree in one semester!
 &HT;    The possibilities are endless _ which is itself a problem.
Perhaps the reason evolution made repetition the mother of learning
is that repetition ensures that you remember only what you try to
remember.
 &HT;    On memory pills, you take the chance of memorizing the
ingredients on your cereal box, the disclaimer at the end of the
movie and every word of that annoying conversation you heard on the
bus. The minutiae that once flitted lightly through your short-term
memory will lodge in your brain forever, like it or not.
 &HT;    ``We're not sure society is ready for this,'' Yin admits.
 &HT;    It might be best, he says, to administer the pill only to people
with certain types of mental retardation that compromise memory.
 &HT;    ``But,'' he adds, ``if we really have something that's the
neuronal equivalent of Viagra, it's going to get out.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (William Speed Weed is a contributing editor to Discover
magazine.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 c.2000 Discover magazine 
