 HAITIAN SCHOOL HOPES FOR MUSICAL REVIVAL  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ Along a narrow concrete alley, where
people live jammed together under tin roofs, a skinny young girl in
pigtails sat in her front entryway and tucked a viola under her
chin.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, Debora Tatgrin, played the instrument as if it were an
extension of herself, the long fingers of her left hand skipping
over its neck, performing Bach for the neighborhood dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   Children on tiptoes appeared. They listened, eyes wide open.
Beneath them, trickles of filthy water flowed unnoticed past their
feet.
</P>
<P>
   When she finished, no one clapped. They only stared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so good when I play,'' said Debora, 11, holding the
viola to her chest. ``In my mind, nothing else matters when I'm
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the gift of music, handed to Debora when she turned 7, may
run out for other Haitians.
</P>
<P>
   Her school, Haiti's only school of music, which has had a long
relationship with the Boston Symphony Orchestra, is going through
extraordinarily hard times. Its decay is emblematic of the decline
of institutions throughout Haiti that withered to nearly nothing
during the 1991-94 military coup government and have yet to find
new life in a barely functioning democracy. Nationwide
demonstrations this week have done little to reassure overseas
supporters that the nation can be poised for better times.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is hard to give up hope in certain corners of this
country, such as the alleyway outside Debora's home or the halls of
Holy Trinity School, which resound every day with scratchy bows on
violins and the bellowing of horns _ most of the instruments
stamped with the insignia of the school's chief benefactor, BSO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music to Haitians is a real necessity,'' said David Cesar, the
school's director, walking in a hallway. ``We play music all the
time. When we're happy. When we're sad. It doesn't matter. But
people in the United States see little of this part of Haiti. They
never hear about our music. They rarely hear about our art. They
hear only bad things about Haiti, about violence and lawlessness.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is not the case for the school's donors, many of whom are
from the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship began with a knock on the symphony's door in
1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a nun to see me,'' said Bill Moyer, then BSO's
personnel director, referring to Holy Trinity's founder, Sister
Anne Marie. ``She came in with her black robes and said, `I wonder
if you'd like to give any instruments to our school in Haiti.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After learning about the school, Moyer liked the idea, and
suggested setting up a partnership. Perhaps, he said, the Boston
orchestra could send teachers to Port-au-Prince for weeklong
tutorials _ as long as the school would feed them and provide beds.
Sister Anne Marie agreed, and the relationship was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of BSO players went down during their vacation weeks to
teach, and they came back totally turned on and refreshed by the
spirit this school gave, I guess, to tired musicians,'' said Moyer,
70, now retired.
</P>
<P>
   BSO invited Haitian musicians to its summer getaway at
Tanglewood. In 1976 and 1984, the 70-member Holy Trinity
Philarmonic Orchestra, Haiti's only orchestra, took up summer
residence at Tanglewood and played to appreciative crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a very uneven talent, but they had a beautiful
spirit,'' Moyer said. ``They played scratchy, but it was wonderful.
Many were kids. The assistant concert master, Romel Joseph, was
blind, and he played fantastic. Audiences loved them.''
</P>
<P>
   But beginning in 1986, when Haiti ushered out the Duvalier
dictatorship, and continuing for nearly a decade, the country
turned sporadically violent. The musicians' exchanges between
Boston and Port-au-Prince nearly stopped.
</P>
<P>
   When President Jean-Bertrand Aristide was restored to power in
1994, the friends of Holy Trinity began to raise money for the
school. During the next three years, they collected more than
$100,000, as well as dozens of instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Anne Marie died in 1996. Since then, the school has
struggled, Moyer said. The money was put into a New York bank,
where it remains.
</P>
<P>
   Some BSO musicians have gone to the school in the past few
years, but Moyer said most return ``discouraged. There isn't the
lively spirit the school used to have.''
</P>
<P>
   During the same period, donors have stopped giving. Teachers are
taking second and third jobs because of their low wages. Most
students, after spending days in overcrowded classrooms, must leave
their instruments at school because of rising rates of theft.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Haiti's Episcopal Bishop Zache Duracin, who oversees
the Port-au-Prince school, will meet with Moyer and other US
supporters in New York plan to chart Holy Trinity's future. The
bishop's goal is for the school to become autonomous and seek funds
from Haitian individuals and groups, instead of relying on
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   That, too, has become a theme for Haiti's organizations, which
are being forced to cope more and more without outside assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those beautiful efforts that has simply got to
succeed,'' Moyer said. ``There are too many great little kids down
there.''
</P>
<P>
   For Debora Tatgrin, the girl who plays the viola, and her mother
and two sisters, the troubles with the school might as well be a
world away. They believe music will transport them from Haiti, just
as it has a precious few of the school's thousands of graduates in
years past.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband liked music. He used to play the guitar,'' said
Guylene Charles Tatgrin, a widow whose husband died seven years ago
from a mysterious stomach illness. ``But I always wanted my kids to
play music. The school was my opportunity for them. That's why I
chose this school.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother took a job as sixth-grade teacher there to be closer
to them. She took a second job to be able to send them to music
camp in the summer. And she learned to read music, even though she
can't play, to better help them practice.
</P>
<P>
   Debora is the middle of three sisters. The oldest, Francoise,
15, plays the violin; the youngest, Rebecca, 10, plays the
clarinet. Each said she chose her instrument based on personal
preference, not to avoid possible competition with a sister.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Francoise achieved a breakthrough of sorts. She was
chosen to perform in Puerto Rico before a church group. ``When I
get in my 20s, I'll still be performing,'' Francoise said in the
family's 10-by-12-foot living room, which is crowded with a couch,
two chairs, and a refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Debora, Francoise said, is exceptionally talented, a judgment
echoed by instructors at school.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has the will, that's for sure,'' Francoise said. ``She's
not scared, not shy to say she doesn't understand something.''
</P>
<P>
   Debora allowed the slightest of smiles. Then she straightened
her back, composing herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I will open my own music school when I turn 21, and
I will travel to many countries to play. I know this,'' she said
matter-of-factly, as if she has seen her future. ``I only hope that
my music will be pleasing to people. God gave me the intelligence.
God gave me the passion to play music. And God gave me the
confidence to play.''
</P>
<P>
   When the sisters' skill levels begin to intersect, they hope to
play as a trio. As their visitors prepared to leave the home, the
youngest sister, Rebecca, said that the family already has started
singing together.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, the three stepped into the alleyway and, with
Francoise taking the lead, began singing ``Tell Me About Love'' in
Creole. They sang three-part harmony, their voices distinct and
loud and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   At the sound of music, an audience of children arrived on silent
feet. And they stared anew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
