<HEADLINE>
IN PETERSEN MUSEUM, LOS ANGELES IS THE CITY OF WHEELS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If there is a place where the automobile has been
inextricably woven into the culture, it is Southern California. It
has given racing, radical hot rods, cool custom jobs, drive-in food
joints, and a link between car, owner, and prestige not found
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   From burgers to Bugattis, lakesters to limousines, Southern
California has had it all.
</P>
<P>
   It is a history remarkably represented at The Petersen
Automotive Museum, 300,000 square feet of exhibition space on
Wilshire Boulevard in downtown (if this place has a downtown) Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Its exhibits are dedicated to the automobile and its influence
on American culture and our lives. On display at any time are more
than 100 race cars, classic cars, hot rods, motorcycles, cars from
television and the movies, and cars that belonged to celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   From re-created scenes in the streets of the early city to
rambles through the as-yet-undeveloped hills, an exhibit shows the
evolution of Los Angeles, from tight city center to nascent sprawl,
complete with one of the most advanced electric trolley
transportations in the world, to the present. It is a present where
the 101, the 405, and the 10 (where else do numbered routes get an
article before them?) define travel and place.
</P>
<P>
   Take a tour and see a 1911 American Underslung Model 50 Traveler
from the American Motor Car Co. stuck in the mud in the undeveloped
hills above Santa Monica.
</P>
<P>
   Check out early California racing by peering into the cockpit of
a 1915 Stutz White Squadron Racer, 130 horses of thunder once
driven on tracks by Earl Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   And beyond round-and-round racing, Southern California gave us
racing on the flats of dried lakebeds or in the desert. The
Southern California Speedshop exhibit gives us the history of the
lakester, highlighted by tank cars that were made from the
auxiliary fuel tanks of Lockheed P38 Lightnings. From sky to sandy
earth they helped define an era of straight-ahead speed, their Ford
flathead V-8s dominant in the early 1950s _ until the appearance of
the Chrysler Hemi.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most gorgeous _ and effective _ racers of the day is
here as well _ the famed Pierson Brothers Coupe. Radically chopped
so you wonder how the driver could even see, it ran under various
owners and with continually upgraded mechanics from 1949 to 1991,
increasing its top speeds from 153.06 mph to 227.33.
</P>
<P>
   It stands in cultural contrast to yet another highly
recognizable car here, the 1959 ``bucket'' of Ed ``Big Daddy''
Roth, cream-and-blue and sculpted with its engine exposed and
gleaming.
</P>
<P>
   There are dreams here as well: dreams failed and dreams
realized.
</P>
<P>
   You get the 1945 Tucker Torpedo that was the personal car of
Preston Tucker. That did not lead to any trends.
</P>
<P>
   And you get re-creations of early service stations and fast food
joints _ such as The Dog Cafi, shaped just like the name would
imply, or other drive-ups shaped like pumpkins or owls from the
1920s. They did signify a trend. Golden arches and white-bearded
colonels would one day take their place.
</P>
<P>
   The culture, of course, was replete with stars. The hoi polloi
were left wishing they could drive what the stars drove. So here we
find the 1960 Mercedes Benz 300 SL roadster of Robert Stack; Mel
Torme's 1937 Jaguar SS100 roadster; the 1953 Cadillac coupe by Ghia
of Rita Hayworth; Mel Blanc's 1958 Edsel; Fred Astaire's 1927 Rolls
Royce Phantom I Town Car; and for those moments when she wanted to
be alone in luxury on the road, Greta Garbo's 1925 Lincoln
limousine.
</P>
<P>
   Otis Chandler of publishing fame offers up his motorcycle
collection. It includes a 1953 Norton Dominator, a 1948 Vincent
HRD, a 1907 Indian, a 1929 Cleveland, and a 1941 Indian Dispatch
Tow. I'll give a printed tip of the hat to the first person who
e-mails me to say how the latter was used.
</P>
<P>
   With a recent donation of $25 million from automotive publishing
magnate Robert E. Petersen, the 6-year-old museum has retired its
debt and can now concentrate on a major goal: ensuring that the
exhibits do not become static.
</P>
<P>
   Street scenes may provide the spine of the museum, but all
around them, things change.
</P>
<P>
   For the next few months, cars from movies and television will be
featured. They follow exhibits such as the Duesenberg as a car for
powerful people; photographic images that reflect cars and culture;
pedal cars; postwar sports cars; woodies; early hot road
performance equipment; and the low-rider as art.
</P>
<P>
   With an ever-changing display, and a vault of treasures from
which to pluck cars and motorcycles, you won't get much static at
the Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
