<HEADLINE>
SMALLER, LIGHTER OLDS AURORA CHASES THE SPORTY NICHE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Two roads diverged in a wood . . . .''
</P>
<P>
   I know, somebody else already wrote that, but that's the
intersection at which General Motors found itself when it came time
for a redesign of the seven-year-old Oldsmobile Aurora.
</P>
<P>
   Go big or go smaller?
</P>
<P>
   Smaller and lighter was the answer, and aluminum was a key.
</P>
<P>
   The 2001 Aurora is 165 pounds lighter in the V-8 model tested
and 6 inches shorter. Aluminum is showing up increasingly all
through cars, and the Aurora is riding the wave: aluminum engine
components, suspension parts, hood and trunk panels.
</P>
<P>
   This is a car that might have stayed larger had the Buick
Riviera been continued and provided a larger platform. But the
Riviera was put to pasture, and the result is a more modern,
snappier car that has a better chance of catching on with the niche
for which it is intended: younger, more affluent drivers that
Oldsmobile is hoping to attract.
</P>
<P>
   The Riviera-based model might have been, as they say, your
father's Oldsmobile. This one is not.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Olds will be to sell this new image in a sales
zone that is ever more crowded and highly competitive: midrange
luxury cars. Priced in the mid-30s, it will have to run with cars
such as the Lincoln LS, Lexus ES300, Infiniti I30, and the Acura
RL. And if you want to comparison shop, I'd try a Nissan Maxima and
an Acura TL, both fully loaded, and cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   GM is making a move with the Aurora, trying to fit an American
car comfortably into this niche. They've got the comfort and
mechanics down here. Standard leather, walnut trim, lots of
driver-assist goodies. Now comes the selling.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the aggressive look.
</P>
<P>
   Stand at the front and gaze. It is very NASCAR-esque. No central
grille, that replaced by two grilled scoops at bumper line. A wide
stance and ridged flares leading back along the bulging front
fenders, through the doors and the back fenders. The rear is
chopped and sits high. The effect is one of a wedge when viewed
from the side.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, it is a study in comfort and good ergonomics. Front
leather buckets are firmly bolstered up the sides and along seat
edges. Support is good in all places. The dash drops sharply away,
giving good legroom. Rear seats are comfortable, even for three,
and firm as well. Legroom is OK, not great.
</P>
<P>
   Controls are well organized. The console at center dash is
slanted toward the driver, giving a good look at climate and audio
controls, all easily used because of large buttons and knobs.
</P>
<P>
   Climate and audio controls for the driver are repeated in the
steering wheel, and the driver's side door is a warehouse of
controls: seating memory, windows, mirrors, and, in a vast
improvement over the many cars that tuck these controls away on the
floor or beneath the seat, gas and trunk lid buttons are right
there where you can see them.
</P>
<P>
   The front-seat passenger gets to control climate over there with
a knob on the door.
</P>
<P>
   Interior storage space is only OK _ shallow pockets in the
doors, a shallow glove box, an ample bin between the seats.
Rear-seat passengers get pockets on the backs of the front seats.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider performance.
</P>
<P>
   You get a choice of two engines, both DOHC, one a 3.5-liter V-6,
the other a 4.0-liter V-8. The V-8 delivered a very nice 21.4 miles
per gallon in several days of round-the-town and commuter driving.
</P>
<P>
   It was peppy, throaty, and reminiscent of the Monte Carlo SS I'd
driven a few weeks back. The four-speed automatic let the engine
wind out properly before shifting up, an important touch in a car
whose audience may be looking for at least a modicum of
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension _ 4-wheel independent with struts, coil springs,
and anti-roll bars _ struck me as a bit soft. That meant a very
smooth ride cruising on the highway with some hints of body roll
while cornering. Vented disc brakes stopped it quickly though there
was a tendency, when braking hard, to understeer. Not to fear. ABS
and traction control were noticeable in quickly correcting any
tendencies that could lead to trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Aurora is sporty, powerful, and luxurious. Now it has to
make a name for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touch:
</P>
<P>
   --The through-box from trunk to cabin that is concealed between
the center-rear-seat armrest. Great for skis, fishing poles, other
toys.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance:
</P>
<P>
   --The outside mirrors are too narrow, which confines vision.
Fatter, aerodynamic mirrors are possible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
