<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOHL CRITICIZES HIS TREATMENT DURING INVESTIGATION OF PARTY
FINANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ With a swaggering contempt for his accusers, former
chancellor Helmut Kohl appeared Thursday before a parliamentary
committee investigating financial misdeeds under his rule and said
he was a victim of slander.
</P>
<P>
   In hours of rambling testimony and subsequent exchanges with
journalists, Kohl, who was chancellor from 1982 to 1998, said the
parliamentary investigation amounted to ``an attempt to drag 16
good years through the mud'' and an ``act of unprecedented
defamation.''
</P>
<P>
   His stance was consistent with the defiance he has shown since
his admission last December that he had taken about $1 million in
undeclared, and so illicit, payments from donors and used the money
to bolster his Christian Democratic party in the formerly communist
eastern Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl, who took the money between 1993 and 1998, has refused to
name the donors, and on Thursday he said that he had ``no intention
of naming them.'' Just as he had given his word that Germany would
give up the mark for the euro, so he had promised that the donors
would remain anonymous, he added.
</P>
<P>
   His attempt to draw an analogy between a promise that Germany
would adopt Europe's common currency and a promise that illegal
donations would remain secret was the latest of a series of odd
declarations from Kohl. Last week, he compared the ostracism he
believes he is suffering to that of the Jews under Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned about that much-criticized reference to the
persecution of Jews, Kohl, 70, shot back: ``I do not need any
private tuition on history. As far as the relationship with the
Jews is concerned, I suggest you go to Jerusalem or Tel Aviv. There
you will find out who among living German politicians is held in
highest regard.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unquestionable that Kohl's international reputation
remains high, a tribute above all to his deft handling of German
unification in 1990. But the hubris he has shown as his party has
reeled from a scandal involving the revelation that millions of
dollars were paid in secret to the Christian Democrats has hurt his
domestic standing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This had been an unprecedented attempt to defame me through
inaccurate reports, insinuations and twisting of the facts to
criminalize me,'' Kohl told the parliamentary committee. He singled
out reports in the Suddeutsche Zeitung newspaper and ``on that
e-mail thing _ whatever it's called _ I mean, the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, Kohl veered between anger and jocularity.
When the proceedings began a little late, the former chancellor
shouted: ``Mr. Chairman, when may we commence this zoological
event?''
</P>
<P>
   His testimony came the day after Burkhard Hirsch, a former vice
president of the parliament, told the committee that in the days
after Kohl's electoral defeat in September 1998, most of the files
in the chancellery were destroyed. ``This massive erasure of data
had no legal basis,'' Hirsch said.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl dismissed as ``stupid'' anyone who could believe that
millions of files had been destroyed, insisting that all the people
around him were ``honorable'' and that there was no motive for such
an act of destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch said Wednesday that computer experts had managed to
retrieve one file showing that letters ostensibly written by four
state premiers calling on the government not to investigate
privatizations in the former East Germany had in fact been prepared
in the chancellery.
</P>
<P>
   One of these privatizations, that of the Leuna oil refinery, has
been the object of particular scrutiny because of the apparently
inflated price paid for it by Elf Aquitaine of France and because
of evidence that kickbacks were paid to several agents.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl said accusations that the sale was corrupt and that his
party may have benefited from the kickbacks were ``a scandalous
distortion of reality.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``It became clear that it was going to be hard to
find an investor for Leuna. In the end, only Elf showed the
necessary commitment. I spoke to President Mitterrand and he agreed
that the involvement of a large French company in Leuna would have
great psychological significance in the former East Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement appeared to be the first time that Kohl had
acknowledged speaking to Mitterrand about the sale before it went
through. The French president had been wary of German unification;
the transaction became a symbol of restored political trust between
Europe's central allies.
</P>
<P>
   As for another suspect sale _ that of 36 German tanks to Saudi
Arabia in 1991 _ Kohl said it was made with the express blessing of
former U.S. Secretary of State James Baker after the United States
criticized Germany for not sending troops to help the Allied effort
to drive Iraq out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no knowledge of bribery in this deal,'' Kohl said. ``It
did not happen. I have never been corrupt.'' The former
second-ranking military official in his government, Ludwig-Holger
Pfahls, has disappeared after being accused of receiving $2 million
in a Swiss bank account for his role in facilitating the sale.
</P>
<P>
   The former chancellor, who has raised over $3 million to pay
back a fine imposed on the party for its actions under his rule,
said more than once that he had ``made mistakes.'' But he also said
more than once that he was not and had never been ``for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   The parliamentary investigation is expected to end later this
year. It will make recommendations on campaign financing and give a
detailed account of Kohl's actions. But the former chancellor is
very unlikely to face any formal sanction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
