<HEADER>
A8357 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WHALES-$ADV02-COX     06-29 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALES-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BIRTHS DECLINING AMONG RIGHT WHALES
 &HT;    760&AMP;add. For release Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    With photo.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Biologists who monitor the behavior of endangered
northern right whales spotted only one newborn calf this year in
aerial surveys of waters off the coasts of Florida, Georgia and
South Carolina, where females go to give birth.
</P>
<P>
   The single recorded birth followed three births last year and
six in 1998. The decline has prompted environmentalists to issue an
urgent appeal for action by the governments of the United States
and Canada to help ward off extinction.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, whale biologists have drawn up research plans that
will involve, among other things, collecting and analyzing whale
feces for clues about the declining birth rate.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 300 northern right whales are known to exist.
</P>
<P>
   This year's one-ton calf was spotted off Ossabaw Island on Jan.
22, swimming beside its mother, a female that biologists call ``Mom
1334.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The area between Brunswick, Ga., and Jacksonville is the only
calving ground for these animals, and we really don't know why,''
said Chris Slay, an Athens, Ga., biologist who recorded the birth
as part of an annual census compiled for the New England Aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   There are probably several reasons, he said, including shallow
water and relatively calm seas caused by the fact that the Atlantic
Coast swings sharply westward between Cape Hatteras, N.C. and Cape
Canaveral, Fla., creating a sort of embayment.
</P>
<P>
   The whales were prized in the 1700s and 1800s by whalers, who
gave them their name. Because they were easy, slow-swimming targets
and floated when they were killed, they became known as the ``right
whale'' to go for. They were hunted to the brink of extinction a
century ago, when only a few dozen were left.
</P>
<P>
   A larger population of right whales exists in southern oceans,
but biologists say genetic studies indicate it has been tens of
thousands of years since ancestors of the two groups interbred.
</P>
<P>
   Although northern right whales have slowly fought their way back
from near-extinction, the population has begun to decline again in
the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   The largest causes of right whale death are collisions with
ships and deadly encounters with nets and other fishing gear, said
Karen Baragona, a whale and dolphin specialist with the World
Wildlife Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a really tough problem, but we don't think it's
completely intractable,'' Baragona said.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen, the U.S. Navy and shipping companies all are eager to
cooperate in efforts to save the right whale, she said. The
organization is calling on the International Whaling Commission,
which meets this week (July 3) in Adelaide, Australia, to pass a
resolution urging countries whose waters are frequented by the
whales to set up habitat protection zones.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the International Maritime Organization passed a
reporting requirement that mariners report right whale sightings so
other ships can change course to avoid to ponderous, 100-ton
creatures.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Baragona said, shipping companies have indicated a
willingness to work with authorities in Canada to declare an area
of the Bay of Fundy between New Brunswick and Nova Scotia an ``area
to be avoided.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeding area for about two-thirds of northern right whales
is in the middle of a heavily traveled shipping lane in the Bay of
Fundy, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cruising near the surface of the bay, straining plankton from
the water, right whales swim too slowly to get out of the way of
ships. Larger vessels, such as oil tankers, can't change course
quickly enough to avoid a collision, even when a whale is spotted,
Baragona said.
</P>
<P>
   She said there is room to shift the lanes a few miles to the
southeast, a move that would allow ships to bypass whales.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 60 percent of all right whales photo-identified by
scientists show scars assumed to be caused by fishing gear and nets
or vessels, although most whales involved in collisions with ships
are believed to be killed.
</P>
<P>
   With shipping and fishing interests expressing eagerness to
cooperate in efforts to protect the whales, the low birth rates are
the most worrisome problem.
</P>
<P>
   So far, researchers have no idea why the birth rates have
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to fewer calves in recent years, the number of of
years between calves is lengthening for each cow, said Moira Brown,
a whale biologist with the Center for Coastal Studies in
Provincetown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, they have had calves about every three years,'' she
said. ``That seems to mean a year of gestation, a year of nursing
and a year to rest. But the mean period between calving is now over
five years.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   There are two groups of females, Brown said, one group known as
the ``Fundy females,'' because they take their calves to the Bay of
Fundy to feed during the summer, and ``non-Fundy females,'' whose
feeding area is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Both groups go to the Georgia-Florida coast to calve. Weather
permitting, Slay flies over the Georgia-Florida coastal waters
every day during calving season, which runs from December through
March. Only if a cow and her calf can be photographed is the new
whale officially added to the census.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the non-Fundy females have continued to produce
calves at the traditional rate. The Fundy females have not,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Slay's airborne surveys haven't spotted a Fundy calf in
three years, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   One theory is that pollution, possibly by hormone-mimicking
chemicals, has reached a threshold that has disrupted the cows'
reproductive rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it wouldn't seem likely that this would happen to all of
the cows at the same time, regardless of their ages,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory is that inbreeding has caused a genetic problem.
This also seems implausible, she said, because the population was
much smaller at the beginning of the 20th century than it is now,
and genetic weaknesses likely would have been purged decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still another possibility is that some natural variation in
plankton biology is taking place as a result of La Nina-El Nino
weather cycles or some other unknown factor, and this is disrupting
the food supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a cow does not have enough stored fat to support the fetus,
she cannot bring it to term,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Whale fecal samples may help solve the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``They typically defecate at the surface, so we can simply motor
over and collect a sample,'' she said. ``We will analyze it to see
if there are hormones that indicate she is pregnant while she's in
the Bay of Fundy during the summer. Then if she is not pregnant in
Georgia that winter, that will be an indication that she is not
getting enough to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``In our hearts, we hope this is some natural cycle
and they will cycle out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: whale.wheelock.edu/rightwhale, www.worldwildlife.org
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e.mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
