<SLUG> BC-SUPER-SAVINGS-FOR-SENIORS-TRAVEL-MATURE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: SAVE A LITTLE HERE, SAVE A LITTLE THERE ...  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By ADELE MALOTT 
 Condensed from The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Travel bargains come and go. To make the most of these elusive
deals, savvy travelers shop around and then act on those bargains _
even if it means booking way in advance. Here are some deals that
I've come across that will help you in planning your next vacation:
 &HT;    American Airlines AActive American Traveler Club, whose
offerings are available for those ages 62 or older, is once again
accepting enrollmentsuntil September _ or until the number of
available membership spots has been filled.
 &HT;    While membership rates have been increased to $45 for a single,
or $75 for you plus a companion of any age, the popular club still
offers bargain airfares to both domestic and international
destinations. Using zone-based pricing, fares start at $118 for a
domestic round-trip flight or $218 for international, not counting
taxes or other fees.
 &HT;    Additional benefits include alerting members to special offers
throughout the year as well as discounts on car rentals, hotels,
cruises and tours. Benefits begin upon enrollment and are valid
through Sept. 30, 2001.
 &HT;    There are certain restrictions, such as no travel on Fridays or
Sundays and blackout dates. For more information: (800) 421-5600.
 &HT;    
 VIA RAIL CANADA  
 &HT;    Via Rail Canada has two new promotions, including one for
travelers ages 60 or older. Seniors who purchase tickets at least
10 days in advance of their trip can bring along a companion of any
age for free.
 &HT;    The offer runs through Feb. 15, 2001 _ except for Oct. 6 and 9 _
and between Dec. 20, 2000, and Jan. 4, 2001. The offer does not
apply to charter seats, group tickets or pass holders. For more
information: (888) 842-7245; www.viarail.ca.
 &HT;    
 AMERICAN HISTORIC INNS  
 &HT;    American Historic Inns Inc. is offering a
Buy-One-Night-Get-One-Night-Free discount program, with some 1,700
inns participating. The book ``Bed &AMP; Breakfasts and Country Inns''
(11th edition) contains certificates that give travelers their free
night at establishments in certain areas. When ordering the
488-page book from the publisher, (800) 397-4667, mention The
Mature Traveler and you'll save $5 off the regular price of $21.95.
Shipping costs $2.25.
 &HT;    
 GARDEN SAMPLER  
 &HT;    The Country Comforts Bed &AMP; Breakfast, 2722 Highland Drive,
Cambridge, Wis., provides fresh flowers and vegetables along with a
20 percent discount to travelers ages 55 or older throughout 2000.
The 20 percent savings is valid on any stay longer than two nights,
from Monday through Thursday. When checking out, you'll be able to
take home a bag of fresh-picked vegetables and flowers. Prices
start at $68 (regularly $85) or $104 ($130) for the Nightingale
suite. For more information: (877) 771-1277;
www.country-comforts.com.
 &HT;    
 CHURCHILL MEMORIAL  
 &HT;    The Loganberry Inn in Fulton, Mo., just a half-block from the
Churchill Memorial, is offering a package for those ages 50 or
older which includes a special midweek rate _ available from
Sundays to Thursdays. Rooms rates range from $75 to $135, and a
gourmet breakfast and two tickets to the Churchill Memorial are
also included. For more information: (888) 866-6661;
www.loganberryinn.com.
 &HT;    
 BEACHCOMBER BONANZA  
 &HT;    Sandy Cove Inn in Inverness, Calif., offers a 10 percent
discount on room rates to AARP members, along with a bottle of
champagne and chocolates at check-in. The lure: The inn is
surrounded by Point Reyes National Seashore and is just 35 miles
from San Francisco. Room rates, with discount, range from about
$167 to $270, depending the day of the week and season. For more
information: (415) 669-2683; www.sandycove.com.
 &HT;    
 A GOLFER'S DREAM  
 &HT;    The Jekyll Island Club Hotel, 371 Riverview Drive, Jekyll
Island, Ga., is offering a Birdie Golf Package through Aug. 23. For
$135 per person/double, golf fanatics of any age get unlimited
daily green fees on any of the 18-hole courses, along with
breakfast and use of resort amenities. For more information: (800)
535-9547; www.jekyllclub.com.
 &HT;    
 GRANDFAMILY GETAWAY  
 &HT;    The Aruba Sonesta Resorts Grandfamily Getaway includes
five-night accommodations, an off-road vehicle for a day of
exploring, choice of a beach barbecue or theme dinner and tickets
to the Star Dust Theater _ all for $829 for four people. Note: At
least one grandparent must be age 55.
 &HT;    The package represents a 15 percent discount and is good through
Dec. 22, 2000. For more information: (800) 766-3782;
www.arubasonesta.com.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Here, a potpourri of special packages for mature travelers that
are categorized by state:
 &HT;    
 CALIFORNIA  
 &HT;    The Resort at Squaw Creek in North Lake Tahoe offers a 50
percent discount to AARP members Sundays through Thursdays. For
example, a valley-view room, which is regularly priced at $275
during spring months, is only $137.50 for an AARP member. For more
information: (800) 327-3353; www.squawcreek.com
 &HT;    Hennessey House, a Victorian Bed &AMP; Breakfast at 1727 Main St.,
Napa, Calif., offers guests ages 65 or older a 10 percent discount,
Sundays through Thursdays, from Nov. 10 to March 10, not counting
Christmas and New Year's. With the discount, Hennessey House's
rates range from about $95 to $171, and that includes breakfast,
afternoon refreshments and wine and cheese. For more information:
(707) 226-3774; www.hennesseyhouse.com.
 &HT;    
 TEXAS  
 &HT;    The Lamb's Rest Inn, 1385 Edwards Blvd., New Braunfels, Texas,
discounts its regular rates on a sliding scale _ the longer the
stay, the greater the discount _ for guests ages 60 or older. The
discount is available Mondays through Thursdays, from September
through May.
 &HT;    A one-night stay earns a 5 percent discount; two nights, 10
percent; three nights, 15 percent. Rooms start at $95, double. A
$15 per-person charge and hotel taxes are extra. For more
information: (888) 609-3932; www.bbhost.com/lambsrestbb.
 &HT;    Historic Menger Hotel in San Antonio gives AARP members and
other guests ages 55 or older $155 rooms for $90. For more
information: (800) 345-9285.
 &HT;    The Beauregard House, 215 Beauregard St., San Antonio, offers
free trolley passes and room discounts for those ages 60 or older.
A standard room of $99 goes for $89 during midweek _ and this price
includes breakfast. For more information: (210) 222-1198;
www.beauregardbandb.com.
 &HT;    
 MINNESOTA  
 &HT;    Two Inlets Resort, 32240 Country Highway 50 in Park Rapids,
Minn., just six miles from Itasca State Park, offers 10 percent
discounts on weeklong stays in cabins. Prices range from $560 to
$720 for up to four people ages 62 or older. The offer is good
after Sept. 9, 2000. For more information: (800) 843-7453.
 &HT;    Best Western Stillwater Inn, in the quaint St. Croix river town
just east of St. Paul, offers a 20 percent discount on rooms that
are booked in advance. Simply call (800) 647-4039 and say you are a
mature traveler. The offer is good through Oct. 31, 2000. Here,
room rates start at $58 midweek and $68 on weekends. 
 &HT;    
