<SLUG> BC-LATINO-OLYMPIANS-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATINO ATHLETES GO FOR SUMMER OLYMPIC GOLD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By VALERIE MENARD 
 &HT;    Four years have passed since the last summer Olympics, and once
more it's time to experience the thrill of victory and agony of
defeat. Fortunately, Hispanic Americans can look forward to plenty
of thrills at this year's games.
 &HT;    The Latino athletes traveling to Sidney, Australia, with Team
USA will likely excel in the sports you would expect _ boxing,
baseball and soccer. They will also participate and excel in events
in which Latinos aren't traditionally as strong, sports such as
canoeing, kayaking and taekwondo.
 &HT;    Broadcast on NBC Sept. 15 - Oct. 1, the summer games will
showcase several Latino athletes favored to take home gold medals.
Leading the pack is diver Mark Ruiz. A native of Puerto Rico, Ruiz
has already been described as the heir apparent to diving great
Greg Louganis. At age 17, Ruiz did not make the Olympic team in
1996, but has since matured _ and so has his diving.
 &HT;    In 1999, Ruiz became the first diver since Louganis to sweep the
U.S. National Diving Championships by finishing in first place in
the one-, three-, and ten-meter platform diving competitions. In
international competition, his best finish was in 1999 when he won
the gold medal in the three-meter event.
 &HT;    Another Latino diver to watch is Rioger ``Rio'' Ramirez, 26.
Ramirez emigrated from Cuba in 1993 and became a U.S. citizen last
year. There may be a glitch, however. Even if he makes the U.S.
team, according to international rules, he will need to get
permission from Cuba to dive for the United States.
 &HT;    Several Latinos are sure to end up on the baseball team, too.
For the first time, the team will not be made up exclusively of
college players, but that doesn't mean Sammy Sosa or Livan
Hernandez will play. The U.S. Olympic baseball team will be made up
of minor leaguers currently playing in major league farm teams. As
yet, no players have been chosen, but Dave Fanucchi of USA Baseball
says that a team made up of top minor-league players debuted at the
Pan Am Games last year and included Latino left-handed pitcher J.
C. Romero. The team lost to Cuba in the gold-medal round. Now a
member of the Minnesota Twins, Romero may decide not to join the
team.
 &HT;    In women's softball, Team USA will again feature veteran players
and members of the gold-medal team from 1996 such as pitcher Lisa
Fernandez. A double-threat, Fernandez, 29, has an earned-run
average as a pitcher _ at the Canada Cup last year she was 3-0 with
40 strikeouts and a 0.00 ERA. Her batting abilities are also
impressive; Fenandez's batting average was .348 at the Canada Cup.
 &HT;    There will also be some newcomers. Shortstop Crystal Bustos, 23,
makes her first appearance in an Olympic competition. She compiled
a batting average of .385 at the U.S. Olympic Cup last year, and
batted .439 at the Pan Am Games. This will be the second year that
softball is an Olympic sport, and Team USA is expected to repeat
its gold medal performance.
 &HT;    The two remaining top sports for Latinos, soccer and boxing,
will again include Latino competitors. In a show of strength,
Soccer USA earned a slot in this year's Olympics _ in which only
two teams per continent can participate _ by beating Guatemala
soundly in April. Look for Ramiro Corrales on the men's team and
Kate Sobrero on the women's team.
 &HT;    The members of this year's U.S. boxing team have been selected
and include two players _ featherweight Ricardo Juarez and
bantamweight Carlos Navarro. Three Latino players made the team in
1996, but none won a medal. Unbeaten in over 60 bouts and a world
champion in 1999, Juarez is a strong favorite. Navarro was a silver
medalist at the Pan Am games and should do well. According to U.S.
boxing team spokesman Kevin Neuemdorf, both players are medal
hopefuls.
 &HT;    Perhaps the most interesting story for Latino athletes in the
Olympics is that they have emerged in several nontraditional
sports. Lisa Arce hopes to make the beach volleyball team, Armando
Ayala is a strong contender for the shooting team. Jeanette Antoifn
may become the first Latina gymnast to earn a medal (Trent Dimas
was the first Latino in 1992), and Angel Perez and Julia Sorzano
may compete in sprint kayaking events.
 &HT;    The most surprising development is the number of Latinos who are
contending for the first taekwondo team to compete as an official
medal sport at the Olympics. A family of Lopezes is listed among
several contenders _ Diana, Steven and Mark. The others are Juan
Moreno, Sabrina Alaquinez, Guillermo Mosquera, Jason Torres and
Peter Lopez. Coached by their brother Jean, all three are strong
medal contenders. Steven leads the pack in the featherweight
division. Flyweight Torres is also favored to win a medal.
 &HT;    Other Latino contenders for Team USA in Sydney are: Celita Shutz
in judo (she also participated in the last summer games); Marcelo
Arrue, Johnathan Bairos, Tinker Judrez and Mariano Friedick in
cycling, Mary Joe Fernandez and Kristina Brandi in tennis,
returning player Gavin Arroyo, Tony Azevedo, Ellen Estes and Brenda
Villa in water polo, and David Zuniga in wrestling. Eric Albarricin
and Michael Santos are in the running to make the wrestling team.
 &HT;    It promises to be fun watching first-time Hispanic American
Olympians and former medalists converging in Sidney as part of Team
USA.
 &HT;    May they all make it to the podium.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Valerie Menard is a senior editor at Hispanic magazine.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 HISPANIC magazine 
