<SLUG> BC-PAPAL-SIN-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PAPAL SIN' OFFERS HOPE FOR GAYS, CATHOLIC CHURCH  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By CHUCK COLBERT  
 &HT;    Let's hope that a new book by a highly respected religious and
cultural conservative provides a wake-up call for Roman Catholics
in America, as well as for church officials in the Vatican.
 &HT;    Gary Wills, a devout Catholic, Pulitzer Prize-winning author and
adjunct professor of history at Northwestern University, has just
published ``Papal Sin,'' a blistering attack on the papacy and its
``structures of deceit.''
 &HT;    One does not have to be Catholic _ or gay for that matter _ to
be disgusted, if not infuriated, by the multiple webs of
intellectual dishonesty, distortions of ecclesiastical history,
theological arrogance and papal bullying that Wills exposes with
his no-holds-barred, stinging indictment of the modern papacy.
 &HT;    Wills' book suggests that John Paul II is an intellectual and
spiritual embarrassment, if not disgrace, to Catholics and the
church. His book challenges the pope on church doctrine, including
masturbation, contraception, women in the priesthood, homosexuality
and mandatory celibacy, among other teachings.
 &HT;    I met Mr. Wills recently when I attended a book reading at the
Brattle Theatre in Cambridge, Mass. _ not far from the Weston
Jesuit School of Theology, where I am a lay graduate student in
divinity.
 &HT;    ``Book reading'' is a misnomer. The author did not read from
``Papal Sin.'' Rather, Wills answered a series of questions from
the audience, explaining that he is not angry withor attackingthe
church. After all, Wills says, the church is the people of God.
 &HT;    In fact, Wills enjoys participating in the liturgical life of
the church and still upholds Catholicism's essential creeds and
saving truths, including the Trinity, the Incarnation and the
Resurrection.
 &HT;    I am as convinced that Wills has no quarrel with the people of
God as I am struck by his vigorous disagreements with this pope.
 &HT;    Wills writes: ``The pope alone, we are now asked to accept, is
competent to tell Christian people how to live. No one else can
have any say in the matter _ not a council, not the college of all
bishops, not the national synods of bishops, not the Christian
people. The Holy Spirit now speaks to only one person on earth, the
omnicompetent head of the church, a church that is all head and no
limbs. If that were so, then the body of Christ would be shamefully
reduced.''
 &HT;    During his recent visit to Cambridge, I asked Wills what hope he
saw for the church and someone like me _ an out gay Catholic with a
life partner. The church teaches that gay sex is sinful; therefore,
gay people must remain celibate for life, with no possibility of
intimate, loving, long-term, committed relationships.
 &HT;    I explained to Wills that while he may not be angry with church
officials, I am angered when priests and members of the hierarchy
hurl insults at me and inject misinformation into the public debate
about homosexuality and the gay civil-rights struggle.
 &HT;    I offered one example of insult that came from a Polish priest,
who said recently that ``homosexuals are rich, from rich families''
and they ``do nothing other than travel throughout the world,
flaunting their sickness.''
 &HT;    Closer to home, I offered the example of 16 Catholic bishops in
New England who issued a statement earlier this month slamming the
Vermont state legislature for passing a civil-union law for gay
couples. The law, set to take effect on July 1, grants the legal
benefits of marriage at the state level.
 &HT;    ``Such legislation will undermine cultural and religious respect
for marriage'' wrote the bishops in a statement issued by Bernard
Cardinal Law, Archbishop of Boston. The statement even accuses the
Vermont legislature of ``prepar(ing) the way for an attack on the
well-being of society itself.''
 &HT;    It also rankles me that few, if any, gay priests _ not an
insignificant number _ speak out against such blatant slander and
insolence. Wills said that today, the priesthood is between 40
percent to 80 percent gay. ``If that's not true, it's trending that
way,'' he added.
 &HT;    Despite Wills' criticism of the papacy, he holds out hope for
the future. To be honest, I don't fully share his optimism. I
don't, for example, hold much hopein the near future for honesty
and truth telling about homosexuality and gay people in the public
sphere _ at least from priests and bishops, let alone officials in
the Vatican.
 &HT;    But Wills' courageous truth-telling does give me hope. Although
he didn't answer my questions directly, his words were inspiring _
just what the Catholic Church needs to hear. ``I credit you, an
open gay Catholic,'' he said.
 &HT;    For this sort of honesty we don't have to wait for a new pope.
``Start telling the truth,'' he added.
 &HT;    Now there's a hopeful call to action.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Chuck Colbert serves on the board of directors of the National
Lesbian and Gay Journalists Association.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Chuck Colbert 
