<TEXT>
<P>
   Weekend Section stories from The New York Times News Service for
Friday, June 30.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-TALL-SHIPS (New York) _ An estimated 5 million spectators are
expected to throng New York City's shores next week for what may be
the greatest nautical spectacle of all time _ an event drawing well
over 120 tall ships, some 42 warships from the United States and 25
other nations and 50,000 to 70,000 small pleasure craft. By Ralph
Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   CHARDIN-RETROSPECTIVE (New York) _ According to the glacial
timetable on which big exhibitions at art museums operate these
days, it hasn't been especially long, 21 years, since the last
major traveling retrospective of the 18th-century French painter
Jean-Simeon Chardin. A new one arrives at the Met looking much less
cramped and more luxurious than it did at its last stop, in London,
on its European tour. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ALICE-NEEL-PAINTINGS (Undated) _ Alice Neel made some of the
best paintings of the 20th century and added in particular to its
store of great portraiture, as demonstrated by the illuminating but
truncated retrospective of her work at the Whitney Museum of
American Art. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DAHESH-MUSEUM (New York) _ One of the virtues of the small
Dahesh Museum, young but with both feet planted in tradition, is
its mounting of academic shows by minor yet often contributory
artists that would be hard to come by elsewhere. By Grace Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   BENNINGTON-TRAVEL (Bennington, Vt.) _ Beyond providing an excuse
to indulge in hot dogs and fireworks, the Fourth of July weekend
can still call to mind the struggle around the event the holiday
commemorates, the signing of the Declaration of Independence. So
perhaps a town like Bennington, whose ambience runs from the
workaday to the artsy, should count itself fortunate to have so
visible a reminder of Revolutionary valor. That would be the
Bennington Battle Monument, a limestone shaft that does double
duty, commemorating the Battle of Bennington in 1777 and providing
a perch to which visitors can ascend for impressive views of the
countryside. Reminders of revolutionary glory are only one
diversion in southwestern Vermont, a place rich in recreational
opportunities (the Appalachian Trail runs through the area) and in
its association with famous people, from poets to the kin of
presidents. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-INDY-FILMS (Hollywood) _ Every summer, as sure as the
snowbirds return from Miami Beach, the major Hollywood studios
unleash their biggest, loudest and most expensive and star-studded
films into a world of vacationing families and entertainment-hungry
teenagers. Tom Cruise hangs from impossible cliffs. Mel Gibson
skewers sneering Brits. Jim Carrey rides the wild highway. The
rules are simple: cars exist to be chased, guns to be fired,
affairs to be consummated, rockets to be launched. Special effects
blossom like wildflowers on the prairie. Have sequel, will travel.
But off to the side, clustered together, are a growing number of
smaller, less heralded movies _ independent features, foreign
language films, this year's quirky Shakespeare adaptations _ that
somehow find themselves battling it out in the nation's theaters
with the big Hollywood quarterbacks. In these movies, cars exist to
be driven, guns to be decried, affairs to be analyzed and rockets?
Well, there are no rockets. Have subtitles, will travel.
</P>
<P>
   KING-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Burlesk King'': Mel Chionglo,
director; with Rodel Velayo, Leonardo Litton. In Tagalog, with
English subtitles. Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   STORM-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Perfect Storm'': Wolfgang
Peterson, director; with George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg, Diane Lane.
Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   PRAISE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Praise'': John Curran,
director; with Peter Fenton, Sacha Horler, Marta Dusseldrop.
Reviewed by A.O. Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   FILMS4KIDS (Undated) _ Assessing the current cinema for children
of different ages.
</P>
<P>
   AT-THE-MOVIES (Hollywood) _ News of the silver screen. By
Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-IN-BRIEF (Undated) _ Capsule reviews by New York Times
critics.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEVIDEO (Undated) _ Short items on what's news in home video
and short reviews of what's new in home video. By Peter M. Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLOSE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``A Little Too Close To God,'' by
David Horovitz (Knopf). Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   TV-WEEKEND (Undated) _ Julie Salamon spotlights the weekend's
television fare: Sunday on the History Channel, part of a marathon
series of programs: ``Prisoners of War,'' featuring an interview
with Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-NOTES (Undated) _ News of The Great White Way. By Jesse
