<HEADER>
A8440 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BRAIN-APPETITE-HNS &LR;      06-29 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-APPETITE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RESEARCHERS STUDY LINK BETWEEN BRAIN, OBESITY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CINDY TUMIEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Scientists at the University of Texas Health
Science Center are a little closer to understanding how the brain
responds to food, devising a way to keep track of how quickly and
how strongly the appetite control center responds after eating.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the Research Imaging Center said the technique is
an important step in being able to monitor the brain for a period
of time as it reacts to stimulation or medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't have a strategy to do that kind of experiment
until now,'' said Dr. Peter Fox, a professor of medicine and the
director of the imaging center. ``This is an experimental strategy
that allows us to look at things that happen over the course of
time. Our hope is that it will open up a new kind of
pharmacological research that we haven't had an opportunity to
study before.''
</P>
<P>
   The study by Jia-Hong Gao, an associate professor of radiology
at the health science center, and Yijun Liu, now an assistant
professor at the University of Florida, used functional magnetic
resonance imaging to observe a portion of the brain called the
hypothalamus in 20 subjects who drank sugared water.
</P>
<P>
   They developed a mathematical model, called ``temporal
clustering analysis,'' to plot the course of brain activation as
the glucose was metabolized in the body.
</P>
<P>
   Their report was published Thursday in the letters section of
the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   This work is another step in understanding how the hypothalamus,
the brain region that contains the appetite control center,
functions in lean and obese people.
</P>
<P>
   It's a further refinement of an earlier study by Gao and Liu
that found the hypothalamus turned off more quickly in lean
subjects, sending out signals to stop eating sooner than it did in
obese subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge of this functional MRI study was to map not only
where but also when the brain responds following food ingestion,''
Gao said.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers are collaborating closely with diabetes experts
in their work. Obesity is a contributing factor to Type 2 diabetes,
in which the body is unable to use insulin to metabolize blood
sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Gao and Liu noted that blood insulin levels matched strongly
with brain activity in their experiments. As the blood insulin
level rose, the hypothalamus slowed in lean subjects. The brains of
obese subjects did not respond as effectively to the insulin
levels.
</P>
<P>
   The data suggest a relationship between the brain and insulin
that needs further study, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists noted none of their study subjects had diabetes.
The next step in this research, Fox said, will be to study people
who are developing a resistance to insulin and at risk for
developing diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
