<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8458 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-RXINSURANCE     06-29 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-RXINSURANCE0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORIAL: Find compromise on drug benefit plans
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Should a 65-year-old Bill Gates only be required to pay $25 a
month for prescription drug insurance? Should drug costs for senior
citizens be left to the profit motives of the insurance and drug
industries?
</P>
<P>
   This is an election year, and with seniors making up a quarter
of probable voters, the debate on providing prescription-drug
insurance for the nation's 39 million Medicare recipients has
become a political show with little hope of reaching a bipartisan
settlement. During debate in the U.S. House of Representatives on
the issue, Democrats walked out and the Republicans sang songs at
the mike.
</P>
<P>
   Election-year politics and the influence of big money have
resulted in a Democratic plan that costs too much and a Republican
plan that would mostly benefit the pharmaceutical industry.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP approach, with a $40 billion price tag over five years,
would offer financial incentives to private insurers in hopes of
enticing them to offer drug insurance to Medicare recipients.
However, White House health policy analyst Chris Jennings says the
incentives would encourage insurers to bilk the government for more
money.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Kahn III, president of the Health Insurance Association
of America, concurs with Jennings. Few private insurers would offer
such drug policies, Kahn says, since the seniors most likely to
sign up for the benefit are those in need of a regimen of expensive
prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP plan has a $250 deductible, would cost an estimated $37
a month, and would pay half of a person's annual drug costs up to
$2,100. Any additional costs would then be borne by the patient.
However, the GOP plan would pay 100 percent of any cost above
$6,000.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to trump the GOP benefits, Democrats proposed a
program costing $100 billion over five years. Seniors would pay $25
a month for protection offered through Medicare, with no
deductible, and no one would pay more than $4,000 annually for
prescription drugs. To top it off, President Clinton wants the
program to roll in 2002, a year earlier than the GOP proposes.
</P>
<P>
   While the price tag of the Democratic approach is troubling, its
basic structure is clearly superior to that offered by the
Republicans. Its main advantage lies in running the program through
the existing Medicare system, instead of relying on private
insurance companies to decide whether or not they'll even offer the
coverage. Under that system, Medicare would also have the market
power needed to force pharmaceutical companies to lower the prices
they're charging for prescription medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, that has inspired a vicious and well-funded
response from the pharmaceutical lobby, which is paying for
television ads critical of several Democrats who co-sponsored a
bill to require discounts on drug sales to Medicare recipients. The
industry coalition, ``Citizens for Better Medical Care,'' is
spending hundreds of thousands of dollars on negative TV ads in the
home states of the bill's co-sponsors, claiming the representatives
favor ``government-controlled prescription medications.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans have a chance to shape the debate as the election
rolls around. A drug benefit for Medicare recipients is needed. It
should be voluntary and cost-efficient, which can only happen with
Medicare negotiating reasonable discounts with drug companies and
insurers.
</P>
<P>
   And in the name of fairness, even with today's budget surpluses,
we ought to remember that our children still face the depletion of
Medicare and Social Security trust funds within 30 years. There are
twice as many young families as seniors in poverty today,
especially single mothers with children. Millions of them lack any
health insurance whatsoever. Any new health benefit should be
balanced with the situation of truly needy Americans in mind,
whether young or old.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
