A8460 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-STORM-SPI &LR;      06-29 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STORM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS AND HIGH-TECH CAN'T BAIL OUT WATERLOGGED `STORM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The film version of Sebastian Junger's best seller, ``The
Perfect Storm,'' should have been the perfect summer adventure.
Alas, it's turned out to be considerably less than that _ not
terrible, but distinctly disappointing, not nearly as engaging or
thrilling as its premise seems to promise.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, it has everything going for it. A top-notch cast, a
respected screenwriter, a director who's already proved his mettle
with a classic seagoing adventure (``Das Boot'') and tens of
millions of dollars worth of computer-generated and other special
visual effects bent on creating the ultimate in movie bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, however, none of these virtues pans out: The
performances are ponderous, Bill Wittliff's script is weak and
cliched, Wolfgang Petersen's direction is uncharacteristically
heavy-handed and the various computer-generated portions of the
storm look so artificial that it's hard to suspend disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Junger's book is, of course, a slightly fictionalized account of
a true 1961 story about a Gloucester, Mass., swordfishing boat
caught in the grip of a giant storm in the North Atlantic created
by the collision of three raging weather fronts _ a storm Warner
Bros.' publicity department claims is ``the fiercest in modern
history.''
</P>
<P>
   This film version opens very slowly, with a tedious, pre-storm
prologue which introduces the not-especially-interesting crew
members of the ill-fated Andrea Gail _ a sequence which is so long
(45 minutes), overblown with James Horner's brassy score and filled
with portentous dialogue that they could well be astronauts
departing on a one-way mission to Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   Then the daddy of all storms finally hits, and the rest of the
movie is a blur of flying water, rolling waves the size of Idaho,
and an ultra-macho, bearded George Clooney steering his little boat
in the big, angry sea with a goofy smile on his face and laughing _
yes, laughing _ in the face of certain death.
</P>
<P>
   It should be the white-knuckle ride of all time, but, boy, is it
not:
</P>
<P>
   _The characters are unappealing and the storytelling is so
sloppy we never quite know (or care) what any particular one of
them is doing at any time as part of the group survival effort.
</P>
<P>
   _The narrative keeps cross-cutting to other characters caught in
the storm _ yachties, Coast Guardsmen _ which is pretty much dead
time because we don't know them and have absolutely no emotional
investment in their survival.
</P>
<P>
   _The script keeps taking us back to the Gloucester Home Front,
where Diane Lane (for some reason, the only character in the movie
with a thick Massachusetts accent) overacts her grief to the point
that we start looking for the hook.
</P>
<P>
   But, for me, the largest of the film's many problems are its
computer-generated effects. The recreation of a reasonably
realistic tempest may represent an advance in the science of
CGI-animation, but the key word here is ``reasonably.'' In fact,
the animated portions of the storm never look quite real.
</P>
<P>
   Stood up against the storm sequences in John Ford's 1937 ``The
Hurricane,'' Cecil B. DeMille's 1942 ``Reap the Wild Wind'' or even
Carol Reed's 1962 ``Mutiny On the Bounty'' _ this one pales in
believability. The digital technology that Hollywood is betting its
future on may be getting better all the time, but it still has a
long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Perfect Storm. Directed by Wolfgang Petersen. Screenplay by
Bill Wittliff. Cast: George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg, Diane Lane,
John C. Reilly, Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio. Warner Bros. 132
minutes. Rated PG-13 for natural violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
