<HEADER>
A8475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TALL-SHIPS-NYT &LR;      06-29 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TALL-SHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MILLENNIUM ARRIVES IN THE HARBOR BY SAIL AND STEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAYSON BLAIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The transportation and logistics battalions began
arriving several months ago. Sailors have been brought from as far
away as the Middle East. Dozens of American warships are preparing
to take position in line with several aircraft carriers, destroyers
and cruisers from across the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Battle stations, New York. OpSail is coming.
</P>
<P>
   In what the planners say will be the biggest maritime operation
in history, more than 300 military ships from nations across the
world will be sailing into the waterways around New York City for
the millennium's July 4th.
</P>
<P>
   The parade of tall ships, review of military vessels and a
fireworks display will close out a series of events in a big show
beginning this weekend that will include concerts, receptions and
tours of ships.
</P>
<P>
   The last time there were so many military ships in New York
Harbor, naval officers joked, the British were about to invade.
</P>
<P>
   But managing the logistics and security is no joke. Officials
from the Navy, Coast Guard, Secret Service and the Port Authority
of New York and New Jersey have long been preparing for visits from
300 ships participating in the events, somewhere between 40,000 and
70,000 private boats carrying spectators, more than 12,000 military
personnel, more than 5,200 invited guests, hundreds of Secret
Service agents and the president of the United States in an area
that appears _ to the nonboater _ to be without traffic lights,
marked lanes or enforceable speed limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Son, it is going to be crazy,'' said one naval officer, who
did not want his name used because, of course, the official
military line is: ``It's all under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimate responsibility for the operation, which was ordered by
Congress as a millennium celebration, falls to Rear Adm. John B.
Padgett III, the commander of the Navy's Northeast Region, and Rear
Adm. H.G. Ulrich III, the commander of Cruiser-Destroyer Group 12.
But more than 1,500 people have been working for months to pull
together the operation.
</P>
<P>
   In February the Navy and Coast Guard began bringing in security
workers, housing them in New York City hotels. Early this month,
they moved them to a command center at Pier 94 near West 54th
Street, where they have been elbow-to-elbow with the Secret
Service, the Port Authority, other government agencies and the
``force protection'' units, which will be responsible for escorting
ferries carrying invited guests and enforcing the normal water
traffic laws, monitoring everything from litter to speed.
</P>
<P>
   There will even be space for the judge advocate general's
office, in the event that someone in the military needs to be
disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been working on planning this thing for almost two
years,'' said Chief Petty Officer William Messing, who is helping
coordinate the transportation and logistics for the events,
officially called International Naval Review 2000 and OpSail 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Navy and Coast Guard personnel will help enforce special
regulations: Pleasure craft cannot travel faster than 10 knots
(about 8 miles per hour); no seaplanes over the Hudson; boats must
stay away from the staging area on Governors Island, the command
center for the anti-terrorism forces.
</P>
<P>
   And there is to be nothing but water within 500 yards of the USS
Hue City, a guided-missile cruiser that will have President Clinton
aboard while he reviews the parade of ships.
</P>
<P>
   The first time Congress passed an enabling act to allow warships
of other countries to enter domestic U.S. waters was in 1890, when
President Benjamin Harrison was authorized to invite foreign
warships to a naval review in New York Harbor to commemorate the
400th anniversary of Columbus' landing in 1892. (The review was
held in 1893 because it took three years to plan the event.)
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed a similar enabling act in October 1996 to
commemorate the millennium, and this time, warships from 43 nations
are coming. The American contingent during the review will include
14 government ships _ one from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, three from the Coast Guard and 10 from the Navy _
and the Marine Corps is providing land-sea amphibious assault
vehicles for demonstrations around the city.
</P>
<P>
   At about 8 a.m. on July 4, the president, on the Hue City, will
pass the anchored warships lining the harbor and the river to the
George Washington Bridge. The review will be followed at 9:45 by a
parade of about 300 tall ships. In the evening, after the ships
have finished moving up the Hudson, 60,000 fireworks will be fired
from 13 barges anchored at five locations in the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The command center team at Pier 94 will be watching over all
that, as well as helping coordinate some side shows, including the
movements of New York Fire Department's three tugs, which will be
spouting arching lines of red, white and blue water.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most difficult tasks, according to those involved,
has been amassing the resources to transport guests from shore to
three Navy ships _ 2,500 to the aircraft carrier John F. Kennedy;
1,700 to the amphibious assault ship Nassau, a carrier-like craft
for helicopters; and 1,000 to the destroyer Mount Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   To get VIPs from the shore to the ships, the organizers turned
to NY Waterway, which normally ferries 32,000 commuters to and from
New York City each day.
</P>
<P>
   For several months, Arthur Imperatore Jr., the president of NY
Waterway, has been directing construction of landing barges that
will nestle against ships and docks that are too high or two low
for ferry boarding.
</P>
<P>
   In the days before the events, the Secret Service will conduct
security sweeps of the barges, ferries and docks to be used by the
guests (some of the facilities were rebuilt for the occasion).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest naval review of all time, and they want
things to go without a hitch,'' Kenneth Favara, a construction
superintendent at NY Waterway, said as he and Messing reviewed the
construction of two barges in a Weehawken, N.J., shipyard.
</P>
<P>
   Favara has worked on projects for the city before, like building
barges for an emergency evacuation of Rikers Island. But after
talking to a supervising Secret Service agent, he realized that he
had done nothing like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a guy who is doing a plumbing job next week over
there,'' he said, pointing to a Manhattan pier. Then he added with
a playful smile: ``But the Secret Service lady told me that I might
want to hold off on that, unless I want my guy to be starring down
the barrel of a couple of AK-47s.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1601EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
