<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8477 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-REVIEW-BULLWINKLE0630     06-29 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BULLWINKLE0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocky and Bullwinkle' delivers fun, puns
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Our tender heroine's name is Karen Sympathy.
Get it? Care and sympathy. And our hero was a star ``quarterbuck''
at Wossamotta U. He's a moose. Now do you get it?
</P>
<P>
   These are among the truckload of outrageous and delightful puns
in the long-awaited spectacular that has all Hollywood abuzz _
``The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the anticipation hasn't been that great, even among aging
fans of the old TV cartoon series that featured plucky Rocky J.
Squirrel and bumbly Bullwinkle J. Moose. But after another summer
of gross-out movies, are we ever glad this animated/live-action
film has come along. It may be a trifle, but it's gentle fun. While
not fall-off-the-chair hilarious, it has enough satire, wordplay
and pop cultural references to amuse the adults, and enough cartoon
schtick to please the kids.
</P>
<P>
   And did we mention the human stars are Robert De Niro, Rene
Russo, Jason Alexander and Randy Quaid, with cameos by Jonathan
Winters and Carl Reiner? Nothing trifling about that roster.
</P>
<P>
   The director is Des McAnuff, a Broadway veteran whose first film
was an adaptation of Honore Balzac's novel ``Cousin Bette.'' From
Balzac to Bullwinkle? Why not? In its way, this film is just as
much a comedy of contemporary manners. It's also a kind of ``road
movie,'' a la Hope and Crosby.
</P>
<P>
   After some clever shenanigans that bring Rocky and Bullwinkle
out of retirement into real life, the pair once again must battle
the evil Fearless Leader (De Niro). He plans to take over the world
through his RBTV network based in Rockefeller Center _ Really Bad
Television. (Got that, NBC?) His feckless, heavily accented
henchmen from Pottsylvania are Boris Badenov (Alexander) and
Natasha Fatale (Russo).
</P>
<P>
   Rocky and Bullwinkle's comrade-in-antlers is an FBI agent (a
likable Piper Perabo, who debuted in ``White Boys''). The good guys
are sweet, but they're nearly as incompetent as the baddies who
chase them across the country by chopper and Cheapo-Rent-A-Car.
Rocky, the Flying Squirrel, can't get airborne anymore. Bullwinkle
is as confused as ever. And agent Karen Sympathy may be just too
nice for the job, as she struggles with her inner child.
</P>
<P>
   The action is cartoon-frenetic, but the violence is
cartoon-friendly. And there's a seamless melding of animation,
computerization and live action, with emphasis on the latter.
(Roger Rabbit set the standard.)
</P>
<P>
   The actors have a fine time hamming it up. Co-producer De Niro,
sporting a wicked scar, appears as if he might laugh at himself at
any moment, especially when he breaks into his ``Taxi Driver''
routine: ``Are you talking to me? Are you talking to me?''
Alexander and Russo make a good comedy team, with impeccable timing
and amusing little gestures, not to mention his abbreviated
moustache and her purple lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   As for Rocky and Bullwinkle, well, the Cold War may be over, but
America still needs them. So do adults looking for a flick they can
enjoy with their kids. The humor is broad, and the rule-the-world
plot familiar, but the film is still pun-derful.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
