<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8480 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      06-29 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE KEHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEING AN INDIE IN CHINA IS HARD
</P>
<P>
   One name stands out on the credits of ``Shower,'' a gentle
Chinese comedy that opens next week in New York. Among the Chinese
personnel _ the director Zhang Yang, the cinematographer Zhang
Jian, and Pu Cun Xin, a popular theater actor starring as a
prodigal son who comes home to run his father's outmoded
neighborhood bathhouse in Beijing _ there is the conspicuously
occidental moniker of the producer, Peter Loehr.
</P>
<P>
   A native New Yorker, Loehr, 33, is the founder of Imar Film Co.
Ltd. It is the first truly independent film company in China, where
production has been channeled through state-owned studios.
</P>
<P>
   Long fascinated by Asia, Loehr moved after law school to Japan,
where he found a job working for a large Japanese entertainment
firm. ``I had been traveling to China for a long time,'' Loehr said
on a recent visit to New York, ``when I rather naively decided that
it might be a good idea to go to Beijing and make independent
films.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took two years to get the company incorporated, because no
one had ever done this before. There was no precedent for me to
follow, so it was a very big struggle to get the company up and
running and legal. It was a very long process, so obviously I had a
lot of time to read scripts and a lot of time to meet with people
and learn about the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zhang Yang had a script that I thought was really, really
special. We got to know each other, and that lead to our first
feature, `Spicy Love Soup.''' The movie became the second highest
grossing film in China in 1998, right behind ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always thought that the Chinese audience comes first,''
said Loehr. ``We do have something to say about China and about
Chinese society. `Shower' is our third film, and we've just
finished our fourth, a violent road movie that takes place along
the Vietnam border.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the movies that have come out of China in recent
years, ``Shower'' was not originally designed for export. But when
it became a hit on the festival circuit, Sony Classics acquired it
for U.S. distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started,'' Loehr said, ``we wanted to lay down some
guidelines for ourselves: that we would make modern, urban films
for the Chinese audience, that we would work with first-time
directors and that we would try to do things differently than the
way they were being done, because nothing was working. We had to
find a way to compete with the U.S. blockbusters that were coming
in, because the market for Chinese films was dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't really barriers to foreigners, though at the
beginning, we did play it very low-key,'' continued Loehr, who used
the Chinese transliteration of his name in the initial publicity.
``The barrier is really that an entirely new system has to be
created. We couldn't find a national distributor, so we had to find
a way to market and distribute our films ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   For Loehr, that has meant making dozens of individual deals with
local exhibitors. In less populous regions like Mongolia, he sells
prints of his films on a cash basis, just as the pioneer producers
did. ``Playing percentage deals in bigger cities means having
agents on site to count the number of admissions,'' Loehr said,
``to make certain that the theater owner isn't underreporting the
gross.''
</P>
<P>
   Because state-financed Chinese films are always given glowing
reviews in the press, Loehr has found that the occasional negative
notice actually works in his favor. ``A bad review makes people
curious, because they've never seen one before.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSY HOLLY HUNTER
</P>
<P>
   ``I got offered opportunities last year that I couldn't turn
down,'' said Holly Hunter, by way of accounting for her
near-ubiquity this season. The Oscar-winning actress (for ``The
Piano'') can currently be seen starring in the Showtime feature
``Harlan County War'' and in supporting appearances in ``Jesus'
Son'' and ``Time Code.'' Coming up are roles in Rodrigo Garcia's
``Things You Can Tell Just by Looking at Her'' and Joel and Ethan
Coen's ``O Brother, Where Art Thou?'' And she can also be heard,
but not seen, in the Coens' 1984 ``Blood Simple,'' which is being
rereleased on July 7.
</P>
<P>
   Her role as a repressed recovering alcoholic in ``Jesus' Son''
came about when Hunter was appearing in New York in the play
``Impossible Marriage'' and saw a fellow cast member reading a
screenplay. ``I looked at the cover page and saw it was by Denis
Johnson, one of my favorite writers, period. So I read it that
night and I called the production office in Philadelphia the next
day and said, `I'd like to be in the movie.' And they said, `Hold
on, we'll let you talk to a producer.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the privileges that I have, of being able to help
smaller projects a little bit. It gave this project a little
nudge.''
</P>
<P>
   ADIEU TO MIRIMAX
</P>
<P>
   Miramax, the Manhattan-based production and distribution
company, has seen some significant executive turnover in the last
few weeks. Jason Blum and Amy Israel, both senior vice presidents
for acquisitions and co-productions for the company, a Disney-owned
mini-major, have left to form their own firm, Blum Israel
Productions.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, based in Los Angeles, has five features and two
television shows in active development. (``We promise they'll be
good,'' Blum said by telephone.) It has set up a nonexclusive,
two-year ``first look'' deal with Miramax, which means that Blum
and Israel will be pitching their projects first to their former
employers, Bob and Harvey Weinstein, co-chairmen of Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   Also departing is Cynthia Swartz, who has been with the
company's publicity department for 10 years, most recently as the
executive vice president in charge of special projects. Swartz has
been coordinating the studio's dauntingly efficient Oscar campaigns
for the last several years, racking up 122 nominations and 36 wins
for Miramax films, including best picture awards for ``The English
Patient'' and ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   In September she will become a senior vice president for
publicity at Columbia Pictures, directing the New York office.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Weinstein said: ``We loved working with Cynthia and wish
her nothing but success. With Jason and Amy we've given birth to
producers whose first-look deal will keep them part of the Miramax
family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
