<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8481 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-CRIME-0630-CO     06-29 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-CRIME-0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOVERNMENT MIFFED OVER CBS REPORT OF INCREASED CRIME IN BRITAIN
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDN _ A report on CBS News that crime in Britain has grown
worse than it is in the United States, has come under attack from
government and tourism officials here worried that fearful
Americans may take their vacation dollars elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which aired Tuesday evening, depicted Britain as
``one of the most violent urban societies in the Western world, a
place where a person's chances of being assaulted, burgled and
robbed are substantially greater than in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Rather, the veteran news anchor, introduced the story by
noting that it represents a substantial departure from conventional
images of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This summer, thousands of Americans will travel to Britain,
expecting a civilized island free from crime and ugliness and, in
many ways, it is that,'' Rather said. ``But now, like the U.S., the
UK has a crime problem and, believe it or not, except for murder,
theirs is worse than ours.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS reporter Tom Fenton cited an unpublished government report
that says violent crime has jumped 19 percent this year compared to
last year. Robberies in London have increased nearly 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by the story, Prime Minister Tony Blair's government moved
quickly to counter the report without denying the substance of it.
With national elections expected next year, the rising crime rate
is emerging as a key issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Home Office _ similar to the U.S. Attorney General _ issued
a statement saying the CBS report was ``simplistic'' and based on
flawed comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   The British government also went on the offensive, noting that
the murder rate in Britain is 1.43 per 100,000 residents compared
with 6.26 in the United States. The rate for London is 2.09 per
100,000 population, compared to 8.6 in New York and 49.15 in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average American is seven times more likely to be murdered
than a British citizen, and 60 times more likely to be shot dead,''
the Home Office said.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS report acknowledged that Britain still has one of the
lowest murder rates in Europe, but it noted that gun violence was
spreading.
</P>
<P>
   Handguns are still banned from Britain and very few police
officers are armed. ``This year there have already been hundreds of
shootings in British cities, dozens in London alone _ three of them
in one evening recently,'' Fenton reported.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the British Tourist Office expressed alarm over
the CBS report's description of British streets and shopping malls
as a ``battleground.'' About 4 million Americans visit Britain each
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that prospective visitors will not be deterred by
these sensationalist stories,'' the tourist office said.
</P>
<P>
   The government refuses to discuss the report upon which the CBS
story was based until it is made public, probably next month. The
report was leaked to the Times of London, which published details
on Sunday, however.
</P>
<P>
   But Home Secretary Jack Straw acknowledged in a recent TV
interview that crime was rising. Straw blamed much of the increase
on drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a general problem of drink-related violence in our
society, particularly amongst younger men, which we have got to
deal with,'' he said. ``It's one of the reasons why the violent
crime figures are going up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann Widdecombe, Straw's counterpart in the Conservative Party,
accused Blair's Labor Party of being soft on crime. ``I think there
are very obvious causes, first of all the huge drop in police,''
she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Policemen and particularly constables have dropped by about
2,600 since this government came to power.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton's E-mail address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.sunday-times.co.uk
</P>
<P>
   www.cbs.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
