<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8483 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-TOURISTS-SAFETY-TEX     06-29 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURISTS-SAFETY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL WRITER'S DISAPPEARANCE SCARY BUT NOT THE NORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The disappearance (and possible murder) of a U.S. tourist abroad
is extremely rare; in most popular tourist destinations, you're
probably as safe as you are at home, or safer. But for those of us
who travel abroad, especially alone, the story of Claudia
Kirschhoch ought to be a cautionary tale.
</P>
<P>
   Kirschhoch, a New York travel journalist described as an
experienced traveler, went missing in late May while on assignment
in Jamaica. She had been staying at a popular and well-known resort
with acquaintances but intended to spend the last few days of her
trip on her own. By the time friends and family realized she had
not made her return flight to the United States, she had not been
seen for several days. As of last week, she was still missing after
more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   Her disappearance is by far the exception, not the rule. During
the yearlong period ending Sept. 30, 1998, the Bureau of Consular
Affairs of the U.S. State Department investigated about 5,500 cases
of missing U.S. citizens abroad. The vast majority were located
without incident, a bureau spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   So, I bring up her case not as a scare tactic but as a reminder:
In a world that has grown so small, in which we've become so
accustomed to foreign travel that it seems like nothing to step on
an airplane in the morning and to be eating lunch in another
country that afternoon, it's sometimes easy to forget that when you
leave the United States, you also leave its laws and culture. And
at times, that makes it easy to overestimate your safety _ and
forget the common-sense precautions every traveler should take.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you finally get to where you're going, you want to have
this place as your oasis from work or whatever you're escaping, and
you don't want to think something could go wrong,'' says Kristina
Rundquist, a spokeswoman for the American Society of Travel Agents.
``I think it's easy to kind of shut down your defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   I am as guilty of that as anyone. I like to go off on my own,
renting a car or walking or taking a local bus rather than joining
an organized tour group. Though I always leave an itinerary for
friends and family, there are sometimes days when no one knows
exactly where I am; I rarely think to leave word of my day's plans
with the hotel staff or check in with anyone daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because you're traveling, you don't get a free pass,''
says Amy Hunter, publicity director at Lonely Planet, a guidebook
publisher. ``You don't want to become so paranoid that you miss out
on the things you went to see, but you're not immune to the kinds
of things that can happen anywhere. And if you're in some
less-established areas, you have to think about the kinds of things
that could get you into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Rundquist says, safe travel should start before you
ever leave the country. If you're going abroad, even to a popular
area like Mexico, a Caribbean island or Europe, you should check
with your travel agent or the federal government to see if there
are travel warnings about your destination, she says.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department publishes three types of travel documents
regarding foreign travel. First, there is a consular information
sheet published for every recognized foreign nation. These
documents list basic information about the country, including its
political, economic and legal system, driving regulations, and any
basic security information, such as high-crime areas or unusual
laws that might pertain to visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The department also publishes public announcements pertaining to
specific events or situations during a limited duration. For
instance, a public announcement would warn travelers when roads are
washed out after a flood or that demonstrations are likely because
of an upcoming election.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the department issues travel warnings for countries
that it urges Americans not to visit. These are typically strongly
worded documents listing problems such as civil war, terrorist
attacks or frequent kidnappings of tourists. Last week, there were
29 countries on that list, including Albania, Fiji, Nigeria and
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Even if going to a destination generally regarded to be safe,
there are a few precautions every traveler should take. Leave an
itinerary, complete with passport number, flight information, and
phone numbers for hotels and tour companies, with at least one
person at home. Take one with you as well.
</P>
<P>
   Especially if you're going to be gone for more than a week, set
up a system for keeping in touch with someone at home. You don't
have to make an expensive overseas phone call; you can just arrange
to send an e-mail or leave a message in a voice-mail box, says
Hunter of Lonely Planet.
</P>
<P>
   And when you're at your destination, relax but don't forget that
you are in unfamiliar surroundings, and don't lose sight of common
sense. Leave expensive jewelry or watches in the hotel safe (or
better yet, at home) and don't flash wads of cash or traveler's
checks. Book tours through your hotel or an established tour
agency, says Shirley Smith, a travel agent with Dan Dipert Tours in
Arlington, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   If you're traveling alone, try to hook up with groups of other
travelers when exploring, and ask for their advice about safe
areas. If you are driving, get clearly written directions, plus
helpful phrases such as ``Where is'' in the language of the country
you're in. Always carry a phrase book if you don't speak the
language.
</P>
<P>
   I also always try to carry something with the name and address
of my hotel. (Rundquist recommends a matchbook, as they're highly
portable.) This way, if I get wildly lost, as I've been known to
do, it's easy for passers-by to set me on my way. I watch what
other people are doing _ if there are no women in a restaurant or
club, I don't go in. And I pay attention to the locals _ if
children and families are walking around a neighborhood or plaza,
even if it's fairly late at night, I feel pretty comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, travelers should always listen to their
self-preservation instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be so paranoid that you don't meet people and you don't
enjoy yourself, but don't overlook your gut feelings,'' Rundquist
says. ``If you have a gut sense that something is wrong or someone
is following you, leave the area and go to somewhere you feel more
comfortable. At the worst, you'll feel a little silly later.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is a small price to pay for avoiding a potentially bad
situation.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FYI
</P>
<P>
   Get the latest information on foreign destinations from the U.S.
Department of State. Consular information sheets, travel
announcements and travel warnings can be obtained at
travel.state.gov or by calling (202) 647-5225.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society of Travel Agents publishes a brochure on
travel safety; call (800) ASK-ASTA or download it at
www.astanet.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
