<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8487 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GIRLGAMES0630-COX     06-29 1827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRLGAMES0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Girls are GEEKS too!
 &HT;    By Charlotte Moore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It takes a woman to tell this story, a woman who
was once a mid-teenager too old to play with dolls but not quite
old enough to drive. A woman who can relate to the inner workings
of a 15-year-old girl whose physical composition is 85 percent
gangly limbs, 10 percent braces and 5 percent stuff that's just
starting to make sense. A woman who would not be put off by a girl
who uses the word ``like'' 37 times in each of her tediously
unforgiving run-on sentences. A woman who would not be annoyed by a
girl with an earsplitting guffaw-screech-snort that follows every
one of her best friend's only mildly funny comments.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a woman to tell this story simply because she was this
very kind of girl at one point. And unlike teen-age boys _ whose
interests seem to oscillate timelessly between cars and the
sex-symbols of the era _ her well-being hinged on her capacity for
optimally uninhibited and uninterrupted communication. One wonders
what girls did before His Highness, Alexander Graham Bell,
contrived the blessed device that allowed for anytime conferencing
about fashion faux pas, cute teachers or the coordination of the
same kind of sandwich in tomorrow's lunch boxes. The teen girl's
telephone was as sacred and essential a prop as a Christian's cross
or a judge's gavel. Given the chance, teen girls might have
single-fingeredly dialed the contraption up as the most influential
invention of all time.
</P>
<P>
   But then along came ``Dad's'' computer; a big, clunky,
unimpressive machine that helped fathers with their work; a machine
toward which brothers and sons seemed to naturally gravitate _
clear-cut signs that it was nothing of value to her. Who knew that
it would eventually reshape human interaction on such a global
scale? Chances are, men didn't even realize its potential at the
time, but their early appreciation for the computer and its
offerings gave them an impressive head start.
</P>
<P>
   Women's uphill battle of playing technological catch-up at times
seems futile, at other times absolutely impossible. Nevertheless,
recent years have seen a slew of female leaders who are determined
to get girls thinking beyond the wonders of the telephone by
tapping into the double-X chromosomers and their computers _ that
market just waiting to be tapped.
</P>
<P>
   One such leader, Laura Groppe, president and chief executive
officer of Girl Games, Inc. _ a local research and product
development company that focuses on girls ages 8 to 18 _ is using
activities like focus groups and slumber parties to fill the
technological gap that still exists between boys and girls, all in
an effort to help realize her vision of living in a world where
women rival and often surpass men in areas of technology awareness.
</P>
<P>
   THE SLUMBER PARTY
</P>
<P>
   It's 7:15 p.m., a tepid evening in central Austin's bourgeois
Clarksville community. Bees swarm noisily at the front door of Dr.
Verlis Setne's house but the buzz inside is much more inviting. A
group of girls swarm around Kelly Green's Dell computer. Green, 16,
and her sister, Cyan, 14, are hosting a slumber party coordinated
by Girl Games, Inc. In attendance are Katharine Quintanilla, Alison
Colby, Jessica Sanders, Stephanie Wiggins, Kristen Schilt _ all
ranging in age from 13 to 26 _ and Laura Groppe. They are a trendy
collage of contemporary girlhood _ pinks, purples and other
pastels, baggy jeans, black nails, belly rings, tight T-shirts,
multi-colored hair and bare feet all swathed in the distinct sugary
aroma of bubble gum. They stand looking over Green's shoulder as
she adroitly uses her computer mouse and keyboard to pull up
various Web sites, which they critique. Chit-chat spurts in patches
of disjointed, almost alien, conversation. First there's the tech
talk:
</P>
<P>
   ``Pop-up ads annoy me. . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Animated banners are OK, but they're kind of irritating after
a while, though. . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Groovygames.com is, like, so cool. Oh my God, you can have a
tea party with Hello Kitty . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to nme.com every single day. They have a lot of, like. .
.in America nowadays it's really hard to get British music but this
site actually has a lot of it. . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Kelly, where's your printer?''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's fashion talk:
</P>
<P>
   ``So, are you really working at Sonic or did you just, like,
take the visor?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the visor from a friend of mine who got fired from
Sonic and so I kinda snagged it. . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's so funny, like, your friends who used to work
places and they'll just have, like, a random McDonald's uniform. .
.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to buy a postman's uniform from that Joseph's Men's
Shops on Congress but they would never let me buy one, you have to
be, like, an official mailman or something . . .''
</P>
<P>
   And talk of the arts:
</P>
<P>
   ``My all-time favorite musical is ``Guys and Dolls.'' I like
``West Side Story,'' too. . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, speaking of ``West Side Story,'' what do you guys think of
those Gap ads?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always get, like, totally addicted to the Gap commercials. I
mean, I don't go to Gap that much but those commercials are just so
good, and, like, the music is so totally good. . .''
</P>
<P>
   These topics are hit and hit again before 7:25 p.m. Sooner than
expected, the girls shut off the computer and migrate into the
living room where Gumby's cheese pizza awaits. Intimate verbal
chaos ensues among the eight people who somehow manage to
successfully carry on as many discussions. Here's some of what was
gleaned: The only good thing on MTV is the animated show,
``Daria;'' drugs and alcohol in our local high schools are
frighteningly prevalent; BET shows much more skin than MTV or VH1;
LBJ High School is merely a governmental experiment to study the
results of mixing virgin girls with mutant males; when Sisqo's
``Thong song'' comes on you gotta get up and dance; people who
enter chat rooms leave their grammar skills at the door; Britney
Spears (and, apparently, any other female celeb popular with the
boys) sucks; Hillary Swank's head is too big for her body; the Got
Milk ads are lame but Kibbles 'n' Bits ads are funny. Oh, and leave
two or more girls alone in a room with a Squier electric guitar and
amplifier and songs that only those girls can fully appreciate will
be composed.
</P>
<P>
   In short, what transpires is constant senseless gab and
activities that have seemingly little purpose, i.e. your typical
all-girl slumber party.
</P>
<P>
   Which this particular party is anything but.
</P>
<P>
   Groppe, assisted by her analysts, Schilt and Wiggins, are busy
collecting data. The three blend almost too perfectly: Groppe,
lying on the floor completely enthralled by one girl's soliloquy
about her premature angst; Wiggins in a cropped Girl Games T-shirt
and fashionable blue jeans, and Schilt with black and blond Pippi
Longstocking ponytails and stories of tongue piercings. They
expertly pose questions that instigate the type of uninhibited raw
conversation that will be analyzed later to determine how to
effectively appeal to the teen girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do a brain dump or download later at the office then
keep our information in a database,'' Groppe said. ``These girls
turn into the characters we're developing; we get that just by
hanging out with them.''
</P>
<P>
   While the girls display obvious tech skills, very little of the
discussion is directly related to technology. Only when specific
topics are brought up do these girls speak about computers, the
Internet or video games.
</P>
<P>
   ``My competition is friends, the mall and the telephone,''
Groppe said. ``I'm battling for time. Girls use technology as it's
relevant to their world. Content is a problem. There definitely
needs to be a bigger market with more variety so that there are
more opportunities and options for girls.''
</P>
<P>
   HOW THE PARTY STARTED
</P>
<P>
   Groppe was never really one to be intimidated by those things
deemed impossible. Towering at 5 feet 10 inches with a solid
physique, this 36-year-old credits her award-winning work as a
Hollywood movie and video producer as the impetus that led to the
success of her company. Groppe is confident that her background
validates her ability to outfit young women with the tools they'll
need to compete in an interactive future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transition (from producing to running her own company) was
not a frightening thing,'' Groppe said. ``What was a little unknown
was what on Earth I had a skill set for. As it turns out, it was
really a function of knowing how to manage creative people and I
knew how to think about a product and how all the money has to go
toward making it a good product.''
</P>
<P>
   So at 29, Groppe left the glitz and glamour of California and
moved back home to Houston. Soon, she was using the extra space in
her father's office as a corporate base. ``It was a tiny room with
a phone and it was like, 'Hello, Girl Games!' '' Groppe laughs,
holding a mock phone up to her ear.
</P>
<P>
   But the research she'd conducted would impress the National
Science Foundation at Rice University, Groppe's first backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to really build up our case,'' she said. ``Way back
when in '94 we were still dealing with girls saying 'I'm afraid of
the computer' and 'it's my dad's machine.' Yet, our research was
demonstrating 'but if you get me in front of a machine and if you
give me something interesting, by God I'll spend some time at it.'
''
</P>
<P>
   The funding from Rice afforded Groppe more space and analysts to
help produce. When she had a clear idea of her plan, she called
Simon and Schuster, the publishing company, ``because they
published Nancy Drew,'' she said. ``I thought, publishing company
with a weakness for women _ I'm bound to be able to convince
them.'' And convince them she did. ``They said, 'How much money do
you need to do this CD-ROM?' and I said, 'uh . . . $250,000.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That was not even close to what she really needed, and she
eventually was forced to go back to the publisher for more funding.
In any event, ``Let's Talk About Me!'' Girl Games' first CD-ROM
that Newsweek called a ``digital Kaboodles kit of activities,'' was
a successful endeavor and ``pretty aces for a first product out on
the market,'' Groppe said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost five years, five CD-ROMs, a powerhouse research lab and
an award-winning product development group later, Girl Games, Inc.,
he for itself. In August of last year it announced a new
subsidiary, Planetgirl.com, a Los Angeles-based online network for
teen girls covering topics ranging from music and fashion to
relationships and sports.
</P>
<P>
   The future of Girl Games is all about being No. 1 in researching
and understanding the teen-age female demographic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the leadership position,'' Groppe said. ``We've got a
five-year-old database; we recognize the trends. Now we've got to
take that to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
