<HEADLINE>
BRITISH GALLERY GETS A CIMABUE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROL VOGEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ After months of intense negotiations, the National
Gallery of Art in London will acquire its first painting by
Cimabue, the 13th-century Italian painter and mosaicist, who
predated Giotto and Duccio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Madonna and Child Enthroned With Two Angels'' (circa
1285), an 8-by-10-inch wood panel on gold ground, was discovered by
Sotheby's experts when they went to catalog old master paintings at
Benacre Hall, a Palladian villa near Lowestoft in Suffolk, England.
The painting was being sold by the estate of Sir John Gooch, who
died last year and whose family had lived at Benacre Hall since the
early 19th century. It is one of only seven or eight independent
panel paintings by Cimabue in existence and the only one in private
hands. It is the first work by the artist to be enter any museum
collection in England.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gallery tries to tell the story of Italian painting from
the Renaissance, and every history book begins with Cimabue,'' said
Neil MacGregor, director of the National Gallery. ``But we didn't
have one. We've waited 170 years to find this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cimabue was to be auctioned at Sotheby's sale of old master
paintings in London on Thursday but was withdrawn when Alan
Howarth, the arts minister, announced that the government had
accepted the Cimabue in lieu of estate taxes and would present it
to the Gallery. The Gooch estate will be given a tax break of $6.87
million, and Sir Paul Getty, a son of J. Paul Getty and a longtime
supporter of the Gallery, has paid an additional $1.05 million to
the Gooch family. Sir Timothy Gooch, an heir, said in a statement
issued by Sotheby's Thursday that he was ``delighted that the
painting had been acquired in this way for the national collection,
even though this represented a financial sacrifice'' on the part of
the family.
</P>
<P>
   In February, when Sotheby's announced it had discovered the
Cimabue, the National Gallery made it plain that it wanted the
painting. It was clear that if the panel had gone to auction and
been sold to an institution or collector outside Britain, probably
it would not have been given an export license without an effort to
find a British institution that could match the buyer's price.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say Sotheby's was at first reluctant to make a deal on
behalf of the estate, believing it could get a bigger price at
auction. But as news of the National Gallery's interest spread,
executives realized other institutions would be discouraged from
bidding.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between the National Gallery and the estate began in
February but were unsuccessful because at that point the estate did
not have such a large tax bill. But in May, Sotheby's sold the
contents of Benacre Hall in a three-day sale that grossed $12.5
million, a record for a country-house auction. The success of the
sale meant the estate had a larger tax bill than it had
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the Cimabue also escalated. In February, Sotheby's
experts said they thought it could bring $3 million. In March, they
revised the estimate to $7.5 million, and last month to $15.1
million. ``When we first announced the sale, we were testing the
waters,'' said Alexander Bell, head of Sotheby's old master
painting department in London. ``We didn't have anything to compare
it to.'' But as interest in the panel mounted, so did the price.
``There has been great institution and private interest outside the
U.K.,'' Bell added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Madonna and Child Enthroned With Two Angels'' is one of
Sotheby's greatest discoveries. It is part of a small tabernacle, a
portion of which is in the Frick Collection in New York. After
sophisticated tests to determine the age of the wood and pigments,
Sotheby's consulted Dillian Gordon, the curator of early Italian
paintings at the National Gallery in London, who, with Sotheby's
experts, concluded that it was by Cimabue. Sotheby's also took the
panel to New York to study it alongside the Frick's Cimabue. It was
then, Bell said, that experts had no doubt it was by the Italian
master. He added, ``It must be the most important early Italian
picture to have been on the market in a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   GUGGENHEIM FINALISTS
</P>
<P>
   The Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum has announced the international
finalists for its Hugo Boss Prize, a $50,000 award named for its
sponsor, a German men's wear company, and given every two years to
an artist whose work represents a significant development in
contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   The finalists, ranging from 29 to 60 in age, are interested in
work relating to public space. The winner is to be announced in
November.
</P>
<P>
   The finalists are Vito Acconci, 60, an American conceptual
artist; Maurizio Cattelan, 40, an Italian artist perhaps best
remembered for a performance piece at the 1999 Venice Biennale in
which he hired an Indian fakir to lie buried in sand for several
hours at a stretch with only his hands protruding; Michael
Elmgreen, 39, who is Danish, and Ingar Dragset, 31, who is
Norwegian, both of whom live and work in Berlin and create
sculptural installations; Tom Friedman, 35, an American sculptor;
Barry Le Va, 59, an American post-minimalist sculptor; Marjetica
Potrc, 47, a Slovenian artist known for architectural
installations, and Tunga, 48, a Brazilian sculptor and performance
artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the usual suspects,'' said Lisa Dennison, a deputy
director at the Guggenheim and its chief curator. ``These artists
span three generations.'' Unlike the Tate Gallery's prestigious
Turner Prize, given every year to a British artist under 50, the
Hugo Boss Prize sets no restrictions on age or nationality.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why no painters were among the finalists, Dennison said:
``There were plenty of painters nominated, but none were chosen.
What this list shows is an international group of contemporary
artists who reflect a trend we're seeing in art that engages public
spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of tight scheduling and a lack of space, Dennison said,
the Guggenheim will show only the winner's work rather than an
organizing an exhibition of the finalists' work, as in past years.
The show is to open in February. The museum plans to publish a
catalog of the finalists' work.
</P>
</TEXT>
