<P>
   SCOTUS-BIAS (Washington) _ Male collegiate wrestlers and soccer
players lose in a legal contest before the Supreme Court. The
Supreme Court, without comment, rejects their appeal of an Illinois
school's decision to eliminate their teams in an effort to equalize
athletic opportunities for male and female students. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-DONORS (Washington) _ The Senate passes and sends to
President Clinton legislation forcing so-called 527 groups to
reveal their lists of donors and how they spend money for
campaign-style television ads, radio spots and phone calls that are
being used to influence elections across the country. By LETITIA
STEIN.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-HMOS (Washington) _ Managed-care health plan officials
warn that low government reimbursements will result in 711,000
Medicare beneficiaries losing coverage next year. This is the HMOs'
latest campaign to get Congress to increase payments to plans that
offer health care and a prescription drug benefit to 6.3 million of
Medicare's 39 million beneficiaries. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-RENO (Washington) _ A day after 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez
returned to Cuba with his family, Attorney General Janet Reno calls
for a review of whether his case points out a need for new
regulations for dealing with children in political asylum cases.
Immigration and Naturalization Service regulations currently don't
address a minimum age for children to seek asylum against their
parents' wishes. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-FUNDING (Washington) _ Reps. Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., and
Tom Coburn, R-Okla., defend their decision to cut San Francisco's
share of federal AIDS funding by one-fourth over five years, saying
the city has been ``overcompensated'' in the past. Bipartisan
legislation introduced Thursday ``slowly gets rid of marked
discrepancies'' in funding for 51 cities ravaged by the epidemic,
said Waxman. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-GASOLINE (Chicago) _ Vice President Al Gore, hoping to
combat anger over high gasoline prices at the outset of the summer
travel season, details a long-term $25 billion package of
incentives to encourage urban centers such as Chicago to create
energy-efficient transportation systems relying on light rail and
buses, coupled with fostering attractive, safe neighborhoods around
transit stations. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ARCHBISHOP-HOSTAGE (San Antonio) _ With an open-door policy at
his chancery office, Roman Catholic Archbishop Patrick Flores has
always welcomed a steady stream of visitors _ the rich and powerful
and the poor and oppressed _ with the same gentle mixture of grace,
humility and respect. Flores, 70, was held captive for nine hours
at his chancery before being released unharmed Wednesday by a man
seeking help. By DAVID UHLER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ In reaffirming a woman's right to an
abortion by a 5-4 vote, Supreme Court Justice Stephen Breyer
acknowledged that the subject evokes ``virtually irreconcilable
points of view.'' He said the Constitution must govern such a
divided society in light of fundamental individual liberties. The
minority, however, was having none of that. The enraged justices
hurled personal insults at the majority. Their fury exposed the
fact that the case was really all about the politics of abortion,
not medical practices or even the law. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
