<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8496 &Cx1f; tad-z
s w BC-COX-NURSING-HOME-WORK     06-29 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-NURSING-HOME-WORKERS-0702 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AGENCY SAYS NO TO PLAN FOR ELDERLY HELPERS
 &HT;    For release Sunday, July 2
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Every day, two or three volunteers arrive at the
Joseph L. Morse Geriatric Center in West Palm Beach, Fla., to help
the nursing home residents there eat lunch.
</P>
<P>
   It's a program that has worked well for 17 years, but it's not
enough for the home's 280 residents, says Scott Boord, the center's
vice president and chief of operations.
</P>
<P>
   That's because there is little consistency from day to day with
volunteers. And because the volunteers are elderly and usually just
help at lunch time, they're not available to help at breakfast or
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   So Morse Geriatric, like many nursing homes across the country,
wants to hire workers to assist their residents at meal times _
and, in some places, to help push wheelchair-bound residents from
place to place within the home.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, says the federal government's Health Care Financing
Administration (HCFA), which oversees Medicare and Medicaid and
helps pay for many nursing home residents.
</P>
<P>
   HCFA officials say the law requires anyone providing nursing
services _ which include helping residents eat or be transported _
must be at least a certified nursing assistant (CNA) with 75 hours
of training.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law makes it clear that feeding is a nursing-related
service,'' said Chris Peacock, a HCFA spokesman who said the agency
is concerned with the problems of caring for residents at meal
times and is trying to devise a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is strike the right balance between
assuring residents of safe, quality care and increase flexibility
for nursing homes that are trying to do the right thing,'' Peacock
said.
</P>
<P>
   A bill filed in Congress in May by Rep. Paul Ryan, R-Wisc.,
would allow workers trained in a single task to provide services
such as feeding and pushing wheelchairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation is good for nursing home residents who
benefit from the extra personal assistance that these aides
provide,'' Ryan said. ``It's also good for busy nurses and CNAs who
work in nursing homes, freeing them up a bit so that they have more
time to use their extensive training to meet residents' other
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the legislation is a top priority of the American
Association of Homes and Services for the Aging, which represents
5,600 not-for-profit nursing homes and related senior facilities,
said spokesman Robert Greenwood.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for nursing home residents are skeptical of Ryan's
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't feel it solves the staffing crisis,'' said Janet
Wells, director of public policy for the National Citizens'
Coalition for Nursing Home Reform.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition is concerned that a shortage of nursing assistants
has led to a surge in health care problems such as dehydration,
pressure sores and painful muscle contractures among residents who
don't receive enough personal care and exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employment of single task workers is likely to exacerbate
conditions that make it difficult to retain nursing home
employees,'' the coalition said in a recent position paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure to improve wages and benefits will be reduced;
nursing assistants will be assigned more residents to care for
because of the perception that their workload has been lightened;
full-time nursing assistants will be given the heaviest, most
repetitive or least desirable task; and personal communication and
contact between residents and nursing assistants will be further
reduced,'' the coalition said.
</P>
<P>
   While the bill sits in two House committees _ Ways and Means and
Commerce _ several states have been stymied in their efforts to
allow single task employees to work in nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Florida and Illinois have both passed laws allowing the use of
single task workers in their states, but the laws have not been
implemented because of opposition from the federal government. Ohio
and Minnesota also have urged HCFA to allow them to use single task
workers. The requests have been denied.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin, which has been using single task employees since 1993
to help feed nursing home residents, has been the most active in
forcing the issue.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey showed that in roughly one-fourth of Wisconsin's
190 not-for-profit nursing homes, 244 single task workers were
helping feed 525 residents. Another 44 nursing homes had plans to
hire single task workers in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Wisconsin officials asked HCFA for a ruling
to allow them to continue using single task employees. HCFA denied
the request, touching off a letter from eight Wisconsin lawmakers _
including both senators _ asking the agency to clarify its position
on what services it considers ``nursing and nursing related.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the delegation has not received a response from HCFA
and Wisconsin's Bureau of Quality Assurance has not enforced the
ban on single task workers while waiting for further word from the
federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the single task workers are either high school students
or young retirees interested in working part-time, said John Sauer,
executive director of the Wisconsin Association of Homes and
Services for the Aging.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these workers are interested solely in helping residents
eat _ for which they receive a day or two of training _ and are not
interested in providing other nursing services such as assisting
residents in bathing, grooming or using the toilet, Sauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Having single task employees on hand allows the nursing
assistants to work with residents who need more extensive help,
Sauer said. It also provides a base for recruiting future nursing
personnel in a state that faces a severe labor shortage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a win-win situation,'' he said, noting that having
single task employees around at meal time makes eating a more
social experience and the interaction between residents and workers
benefits both.
</P>
<P>
   --STORY COULD TRIM HERE--
</P>
<P>
   Most nursing homes in Wisconsin are strapped for qualified
employees, Sauer said, noting the state has an unemployment rate
below 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every nursing home that I know of is out there actively trying
to recruit CNAs,'' he said. ``We have facilities that are looking
to contract with a company to bring in nurses from the
Philippines.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin's ombudsman for nursing homes, George F. Potaracke has
been lukewarm about single task employees.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Ryan last month, Potaracke said he was concerned
that ``implementation of a single task worker category will, in no
small measure, diminish the overall value, function and appeal of
the position of certified nursing assistant.''
</P>
<P>
   But Potaracke indicated he was aware of the labor shortage
problem and suggested that ``it may be possible that single task
workers, properly selected, trained, supervised and utilized''
could be a temporary solution.
</P>
<P>
   Potaracke suggested that Congress consider authorizing some
demonstration projects of 18 months to three years duration to see
how the single task concept works.
</P>
<P>
   On the web:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Health Care Financing Administration: www.hcfa.gov
</P>
<P>
   American Association of Homes and Services for the Aging:
www.aahsa.org
</P>
<P>
   Florida Association of Homes for the Aging: www.faha.org/
</P>
<P>
   Association of Ohio Philanthropic Homes, Housing and Services
for the
</P>
<P>
   Aging: www.aopha.org/
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin Association of Homes and Services for the Aging:
www.wahsa.org/
</P>
<P>
   www.house.gov/ryan/
</P>
