<HEADER>
A8498 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     06-29 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRUTH ABOUT BRADENTON, FLA. 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was alarmed to read that ``Money'' magazine selected Bradenton
as one of the nation's top five places to retire.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine called Bradenton a ``first-class Florida beach
town,'' which does not say much for Florida's other beach towns
since Bradenton is located several miles inland. Perhaps the
magazine's editors are taking this global warming thing more
seriously than the rest of us. (Book your reservations at the Blue
Boy motel today.)
</P>
<P>
   But let us not quibble. Bradenton is located close to the Gulf
of Mexico and you can drive there if the traffic is not too bad and
the bridges are not stuck open. Once there, you can indeed cavort
on 27 miles of white-sand beaches, as the magazine states, assuming
you can find a parking space.
</P>
<P>
   I am not saying these nasty things about Bradenton simply
because I live there and don't want 100,000 more elderly people
from Michigan competing with me for starting times or taking all
the good tables at Morrison's.
</P>
<P>
   No, I just think that people need to know that Bradenton isn't
nearly as nice as ``Money'' magazine makes it out to be and that
retirees might be better off relocating in other ``first-class
beach towns'' like Asheville, N.C., or Fort Collins, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money'' magazine contends that Bradenton is a good place to
retire to because the average home price is $126,100. A home of
that price would indeed be comfortable if you live alone and don't
plan on bringing any furniture with you. If you would like to live
in something more spacious than a walk-in closet, then you should
be prepared to spend more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money'' claims that Bradenton has 238 sunny days a year, and
says it as if that were a good thing. Spend one summer in Bradenton
and you will have a much less charitable opinion of our sun, which
is capable of melting cars into puddles of goo and causing people's
hair to spontaneously combust.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the alternatives to the sun, hurricanes and
wrath-of-God thunderstorms are not that appealing either. People
who live in Bradenton spend most of their time cowering in their
bathtubs under a mattress or pouring water on their smoking heads.
This is not my idea of carefree retirement living, but then again,
I suppose it all depends on what you're used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money'' also points out that Bradenton is located only 30
minutes from Tampa, and again makes it sound as if that were a good
thing. Tampa is the place to go if you enjoy getting lost in a maze
of one-way streets on your way to the adult-entertainment district.
Tampa also has an airport, but then again so does Bradenton, so I
wouldn't consider that any big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Bradenton gets high marks from ``Money'' magazine because
several professional sports teams are located within an hour's
drive. One of those ``professional'' teams is the Tampa Bay Devil
Rays which, thanks to strong pitching and clutch hitting in the
month of June, have improved to last place in the American League
East. The nice thing about being a fan of the Devil Rays is that
you don't have to contend with large crowds; the bad thing is that
you have to perform ``the wave'' all by yourself, which requires a
lot of running and jumping around.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, before you decide to retire to Bradenton on the basis
of ``Money'' magazine's recommendation, remember that the magazine
was also profoundly smitten last year with Punta Gorda, which,
cosmopolitan-wise, makes Bradenton seem like San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   This is not meant to disparage San Francisco, which I understand
is a very nice place, especially for retirees.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
