<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OLYMPICS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC PROMISES FEWER ADS IN SYDNEY OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This story also moved in the ``e'' entertainment news 
 file)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC assembled its Olympics talent for a satellite press
conference this week and behold, there was immediate good news.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Sports chairman Dick Ebersol said the network would devote
less time to commercials during the Sydney, Australia, Games than
it did in the Atlanta Games four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Not much, but some, bless their barnacled little hearts, and the
O.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said the allotted time would be 9 minutes an hour in
prime time, compared with 9 1/2 minutes during the Atlanta
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The figure doesn't include promo spots and other interruptions.
But the grand total should still fall short of normal prime-time
clutter. Given the trend toward commercial expansion, that's good
enough news to applaud NBC and give it 15 seconds back. On second
thought, nah.
</P>
<P>
   This will matter to you because come September, when you expect
to see the usual fusillade of new series on the networks, you'll be
seeing Olympics gymnastics, swimming and wrestling instead.
</P>
<P>
   The other networks apparently plan to hold their new wares until
after the Summer Olympics, which run September 15 to October 1.
</P>
<P>
   There's another holdover piece of good news, in case you haven't
heard. John Tesh won't be doing the gymnastics coverage. Al
Trautwig, and for two days Tom Hammond, will be in his place.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, Olympics gymnastics is the gig I wish Dennis Miller had
landed, rather than NFL football on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   NBC will of course gorge itself on the Olympics. The network is
expected to carry 162 1/2 hours of coverage, about the same as in
Atlanta. But that's just the broadcast network. The cable role will
be stepped up this time, with NBC corporate cousins CNBC and MSNBC
combining for an additional 279 hours.
</P>
<P>
   That's 441 1/2 hours of television coverage, none of it live _
another departure from Atlanta. Sydney is 15 hours ahead of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   So the NBC network, in particular, will package the greatest
event in sports into videotaped stories about perseverance and
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Storytelling, Olympics production chief David Neal said at the
press conference, ``is our mantra here at NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   The underlying meaning of ``storytelling'' is that NBC needs to
attract female viewers who otherwise wouldn't be caught dead
watching wrestlers and pole vaulters.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC and MSNBC are the designated outlets for sports in purer
terms. Generally, while gymnastics, swimming, diving and some
track-and-field events will be dominant on NBC, the two cable
channels will provide more extended coverage of ``lesser'' events.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing will be big on CNBC; women's soccer, spearheaded by the
powerful U.S. team, will be the top feature on MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Costas will be the main host on the broadcast network. His
cable counterparts will be Jim Lampley on MSNBC and Pat O'Brien on
CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Other points from the press conference:
</P>
<P>
   _ Supplementing its access to the TV feed from the Australian
host broadcasters, NBC will have 115 of its own cameras in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   _ The NBC production team is obviously infatuated with Sydney
and Australia; Neal, who's made 20 trips Down Under to prepare for
the Olympics, says NBC will pay ``keen attention'' to showcasing
Sydney with travelogue-type features.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ebersol said NBC is ``now certain to eke out a small profit on
these Games.'' The network is paying $3.5 billion for rights to
five consecutive Olympics, beginning with Sydney. These Olympics
account for $705 million of the total.
</P>
<P>
   _ The profit prediction comes despite the anticipation of lower
ratings than the 21.6 prime-time average in Atlanta. NBC projects a
17.5 to 18.5 rating average for Sydney. The difference is that four
years ago, the Games were on American soil and events were
televised live.
</P>
<P>
   _ The World Wide Web component will be vastly expanded. NBC and
its Web partner, Quokka Sports of San Francisco, are already up and
running with www.nbcolympics.com. It's full of data, athlete bios,
charts, video and audio elements and interactive features, and it's
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
