<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIKE A FEATURE, ONLY SHORTER
</P>
<P>
   Action and drama are in store as a young man in trouble drags
his family into a bad situation. Hand that general story line to a
major moviemaker, and a couple of years later one can plan on
spending at least 130 minutes at the multiplex. The Australian film
``Bloodlock,'' on the other hand, gets the entire tale told in 26
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting extras. ``Bloodlock'' is on DVD, one of 11 short
films on ``Short 9: Trust,'' to be released Wednesday by Quickband,
a Hollywood producer and distributor, and Warner. DVD usually
entails added features, and ``Bloodlock'' has a commentary track by
its directors, actors and producers, along with deleted scenes and
outtakes. In the miniworld of short film, nothing takes too long.
On ``Short 9,'' the ninth DVD in a series from Quickband, all 11
films and their extras are over in 160 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of feature films would benefit by being shorts,'' said
Milos Stehlik of Facets Multimedia, a Chicago video distributor and
mail order company that carries the first eight ``Short'' discs,
each with about 10 short films.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely seen except at film festivals and on cable, shorts
normally run up to 30 minutes. Many are products of young directors
on their way to feature filmmaking. Shorts obviously get to the
point quickly, but the curious thing about the best of them is that
they do a more effective job of storytelling than most full-length
features.
</P>
<P>
   Some films in the ``Short'' series have gone in the opposite
direction and been adapted into full-length movies. ``Short 1:
Invention'' includes George Hickenlooper's 25-minute ``Some Folks
Call It a Sling Blade,'' which was enlarged into an Oscar-winning
version by Billy Bob Thornton. ``La Jetee (The Leap),'' Chris
Marker's haunting 29-minute short about an emissary from a doomed
world sent to get help in the past and future, was the basis for
Terry Gilliam's ``12 Monkeys.'' Gilliam is a fine filmmaker, but
Marker's haunting little movie, made in 1962, got to the story
first and, it could be said, more inventively and compellingly.
</P>
<P>
   The shortest of the shorts, generally in the two-to-six-minute
range, are crazy enough to try anything. Charles Stone III's
``True'' was reworked into the ``Whassup'' Budweiser commercials.
``The Big Story,'' a five-minute Claymation film by Tim Watts and
David Stoten, stars five caricatures of Kirk Douglas working in a
newspaper office.
</P>
<P>
   Themes are recognizable but the treatments are never standard.
In the 20-minute ``Multi-Facial,'' the actor Vin Diesel
metamorphoses every which way in search of a role. Alain Resnais'
30-minute documentary ``Night and Fog'' documents the Holocaust in
far more gripping ways than many longer films.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the shorts have won or been nominated for Academy
Awards. ``There's always this hue and cry, `Why have this
category?''' said Sandra Neufeldt of Quickband. ``Nobody watches
these films; nobody can see them.''
</P>
<P>
   Instant access on DVD can help people get acquainted with a
large number of them and, in the spirit of the material, quickly.
``DVD makes short-watching comfortable,'' Neufeldt said.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   The Talented Mr. Ripley
</P>
<P>
   Posing as a Princeton graduate, Tom Ripley (Matt Damon, left)
goes abroad presumably to help convince the dilettante Dickie
Greenleaf (Jude Law) to return home. Once in Europe, though, Tom
finds a world that a young man on the make could easily get used
to. Ingratiating himself with Dickie, Tom becomes a part of his
circle, but it gradually it occurs to him that, given his talents
with impersonation, he could actually become Dickie. In a
homoerotic Faustian bargain played for keeps, Anthony Minghella's
film, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``offers
diabolically smart surprises wherever you care to look.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Paramount. $107.37; DVD, $29.99. 139 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging Up
</P>
<P>
   Three frazzled sisters do their best to keep up with their
elderly father's deteriorating medical condition while staying
connected to frantically busy lives via cordless telephone. Even
the old man (Walter Matthau) is a mean hand with a touch-tone
keypad, constantly harassing Eve (Meg Ryan), the dizziest of the
sisters, from his hospital bed. Maddy (Lisa Kudrow) has a slumping
soap opera career on her hands, while Georgia (Diane Keaton), a
famous magazine editor, has a new publication to get off the
ground. And with Dad to deal with, the film's ``very busyness
ensures that the characters' feelings stay on the surface''
(Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _ 2000. Columbia Tri-Star. $107.37; DVD, $24.95. 95 minutes.
Closed captioned. PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Scream 3
</P>
<P>
   When we left Wes Craven's ``Scream 2,'' all knife-wielding
maniacs supposedly had been sent to the sidelines. Now, though,
someone with those familiar concave cheeks is slicing up people on
a movie set. ``Ten more murders and we have a calendar,'' says a
detective. The killer really wants Sidney (Neve Campbell), the
combative student who gave him so much trouble in earlier
``Scream'' bloodbaths. Dewey (David Arquette), the sheriff's
deputy, is back, as is the scoop-driven newswoman Gale Weathers
(Courtney Cox Arquette), but Sidney is the one in a film that is
``as much a personality show as it is a slasher film'' (Elvis
Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   _ 2000. Dimension. $112..18; DVD, $32.99. 116 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Women
</P>
<P>
   It's a sorry excuse for cramming five personal stories into one
movie, but here we have a television personality (Carmen Maura)
preparing a documentary in which she asks her friends what they
would do if they had three wishes. Never mind that Maura is a Pedro
Almodovar favorite or that her friends include Miou-Miou, Marisa
Berenson, Marthe Keller and Guesch Patti and that the film was shot
in Portugal. Everybody has the 40-something jitters. Think ``Rohmer
crossed with Almodovar, but on a much lower artistic plane''
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998. Fox Lorber. $89.98; DVD, $29.98. 95 minutes. French with
English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   While the big films of summer rule the box office, video usually
makes more modest gains at this time of year. Here are some current
best-renters.
</P>
<P>
   THE GREEN MILE. A retired prison guard (Tom Hanks) recalls a
time of spiritual awakening in the '30s when he ran the security on
death row at a Southern prison. Frank Darabont's film is adapted
from Stephen King's novel. 1999. Warner. $109.99; DVD, $24.98. 188
minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   GIRL, INTERRUPTED. Sent to Claymoore psychiatric hospital,
Susanna (Winona Ryder) falls in with the house insurgent (Angelina
Jolie) and learns that her problems may have a fancy clinical label
but can be hung mainly on her neurotic peevishness and a need to
grow up. 1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $107.37; DVD, $24.95. 127
minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   BICENTENNIAL MAN. An industrial robot named Andrew (Robin
Williams) is made of metal but the emotions run gooey for several
generations while the gizmo with a heart finds the woman he loves.
1999. Touchstone. $104.16; DVD, $32.99. 131 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG.
</P>
<P>
   PLAY IT TO THE BONE. Two burned-out middleweights (Woody
Harrelson and Antonio Banderas) sign to fight in Las Vegas and
relive their botched title shots and other mainline chances while
being driven across the desert by a woman (Lolita Davidovich) who
was involved with them both. 1999. Touchstone. $104.16; DVD,
$32.99. 124 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   MAN ON THE MOON. Currently a schizophrenic state trooper in
``Me, Myself and Irene,'' Jim Carrey was the comedian Andy Kaufman
in Milos Forman's film. 1999. Universal. $107.37; DVD, $29.99. 118
minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
</TEXT>
