<SLUG> BC-NORTHTOALASKA-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEWARD, ALASKA, THE GLACIERS ARE BREATHTAKING AND THE TOWN IS
LAID-BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL GERST 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RESURRECTION BAY, Alaska _ The sky is a deep, cold, crystalline
blue. Off to port, the desolate northern Pacific stretches
endlessly into the distance. To the starboard, the howling wind
sweeps down a mammoth wall of ice, a thousand tiny needles stinging
already reddened cheeks and ears, the bone-deep chill exaggerated
by the speed of the excursion boat.
</P>
<P>
   As you see your breath condensing in the cool air, as you feel
the icy salt spray in your face, you have to keep telling yourself
that this really is August, and back home in the Lower 48, the heat
is unbearable and the land is parched. And then, sipping from a
steaming cup of cocoa, you smile and think to yourself:
``Perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer along the southern coast of Alaska is close to perfect.
Daytime temperatures are springlike, in the upper 60s; nights in
the 40s are tailor-made for cuddling with a comforter in front of
an open fire.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of August, the rainy season begins. Back home,
city officials squabble about water rationing. Here, long,
drenching showers soak the ground early in the day, a perfect time
to linger over a cup of coffee or stretch out in a comfortable
chair with a good book. By midmorning, the rain is gone, leaving
sparkling clear skies.
</P>
<P>
   But the weather isn't the only reason to head north. Alaska
truly is the last frontier, a glimpse at what the rest of the
country must have been like before it was covered with concrete and
asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   The adventurous get here by driving the grueling Alcan Highway,
the 1,500-mile road that snakes its way from Dawson Creek, British
Columbia, to Fairbanks. Once across the Alaskan border, you can
head southwesterly along Highway 1 to Anchorage, and from there
south to the rugged Kenai Peninsula, Seward and Resurrection Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Seward is a wonderful town of about 3,000 on the southern coast
of the peninsula, perfect for getting away _ but not too far away _
from civilization. And, although cruise ships disgorge hundreds of
voyagers each day, the town has relatively few tourist traps and
tacky T-shirt shops.
</P>
<P>
   If you're here to avoid hordes of cruise tourists, just steer
clear of the tiny business district and the waterfront during the
middle of the day. There's plenty of Alaska to enjoy without going
into town.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, thousands make the cruise northwest from Seattle or
Vancouver along the Inside Passage, stopping in Juneau, the
gold-rush town of Skagway or Sitka, a living ``matryoshka'' of
Russian heritage. Other lines dock daily in Seward, and ferries of
the Alaska Marine Highway System connect Juneau with Valdez,
Kodiak, Seward and Homer.
</P>
<P>
   The most convenient approach, however, is to fly into Anchorage,
pick up a car at the airport, then head south on the
well-maintained Seward Highway. If you plan on traveling some of
the peninsula's dirt and gravel roads, spend a few extra dollars
for a sport utility.
</P>
<P>
   Even though cruises are a wonderful way to sample several small
coastal towns, your time in each port is limited. It's not that you
can't see all there is to see in a town like Seward in a day. In
fact, you could see almost everything in an hour or two.
</P>
<P>
   But these are the sort of friendly little towns you'd like to
get to know, to call ``home'' for a few days. On top of that, the
125-mile drive from Anchorage down the Kenai Peninsula to Seward is
one of the most breathtaking in the country, full of majestic,
rocky vistas and lush green fields dotted with sweet-smelling
forget-me-nots. There are turnouts every few miles for
picture-taking and for relieving the traffic congestion caused by
the constant parade of awe-stricken motorists.
</P>
<P>
   For all the natural beauty that surrounds it, Seward is a town
that knows hardship. The little fishing village was nearly pounded
out of existence in the deadly 1964 Good Friday earthquake, a 9.2
on the Richter scale. The resultant tsunami demolished the
waterfront, leaving 13 dead.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the locals still tell tales of the quake, not just of the
devastation, but of the determination to rebound. In 1965, a
rebuilding Seward was named an All-America City by the National
Civic League.
</P>
<P>
   But the hardest part of life in Seward is the winter. Spring and
summer are glorious, but the town begins to pay for that as autumn
approaches. This past January, heavy rain and snow caused
avalanches that closed the Seward Highway, cutting the town and the
peninsula off from the rest of Alaska for a week. Only bush pilots
made it in and out.
</P>
<P>
   Why live like that? Spend a week in Seward, and you'll know.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   When you arrive in Alaska for the first time, you're in for a
cultural shock. First, you'll have to get used to ``Alaskan time,''
the quaint concept that nothing is ever so important that it's
worth rushing yourself to death. If New Yorkers have Type A
personalities, then Alaskans have Type Z.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest shock will come when you slow down enough to
enjoy the pristine beauty everywhere around you.
</P>
<P>
   There are several small hotels in Seward, but I rented a small
cabin just outside town, tucked away in a clearing surrounded by
towering trees and dense foliage. My first morning there, I awoke
to the sound of the owners' beagle pup yipping loudly. Stepping
outside, I found the 10-pound dog gamely trying to hold a
1,200-pound moose cow and her two calves at bay not a dozen yards
from my porch.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   The taciturn moose, not at all bothered by the noise _ or me _
simply continued to munch on the tall grass, plodding wherever she
wished. Overhead, oblivious to it all, hawks skimmed through the
trees looking for a meal. And next to the cabin was evidence that
the rustling outside last night had in fact been a hungry bear
hoping to find something scrumptious in my garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly you realize that nature is going on all around you,
literally in your front yard. You're little more than a tolerated
interloper. And just as suddenly, you know what makes this place so
special for adopted and native Alaskans alike.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every Alaska resident tells the same story, of how he or
she came for a brief vacation or to work for a summer and wound up
moving north. Call it a shared epiphany, but it seems no one who
witnesses the primeval wonders of Alaska ever feels the same again.
Few places on the planet are as untouched.
</P>
<P>
   You'll feel it, too, on a tour of Kenai's fjords and tidewater
glaciers. From the deck of your charter boat, you'll see orcas,
harbor seals, sea lions and the comical tufted puffins, ungainly
seabirds who find themselves too heavy to fly after a meal but who
try it anyway. Nothing, however, prepares you for the sight of a
soaring bald eagle or a pair of humpback whales breaching, then
sounding, the gentle behemoths flipping their tails in farewell as
they slip beneath the waves.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along your voyage, if you're lucky, you'll be
entertained by a school of playful porpoises tagging along next to
the boat. No one knows why they do it. The guide will tell you that
perhaps they're drawn to the thrum of the engines or maybe the
pressure waves peeling back from the bow. Perhaps they just like
the company.
</P>
<P>
   You'll come within a few hundred yards of mountainous, aqua-blue
walls of ice, glaciers spilling out into the sea from the massive
Harding Icefield just beyond. The sound of a glacier calving, of
huge chunks of it splitting off and falling to the water below,
echoes loudly through the fjord, sending the black bears that were
foraging for food near its base scrambling for safety.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like to get even closer to a glacier, drive a few miles
north of Seward to the ranger station at the Kenai Fjords National
Park. From there, it's a half-mile hike to Exit Glacier. You can
walk to its base and dip your hand in the icy runoff or take a
winding, steep trail to an overlook to peer deep into caves of ice.
For the hardy, there's a 7-mile hike that flanks the glacier and
looks out over the 300-square-mile ice field beyond from a vantage
spot 3,000 feet above the glacial valley floor.
</P>
<P>
   Keep those hiking boots on, because there are plenty of trails
to explore. Down at the waterfront, there's an easy, paved path
beginning at the original starting point of the Iditarod Trail,
where sled dogs and mushers began the arduous journey to Nome or
points north. If you're up to it, try the 3-mile trail up Mount
Marathon to the 3,000-foot level. Each July Fourth, 800 or more
runners scramble up the steep, muddy trail, and the town turns out
for a daylong party.
</P>
<P>
   The Chugach National Forest is right here, and it's full of
wooded trails and fishing holes. Maps are available in town, and
public-use cabins can be reserved for $35 a night. Camping is legal
anywhere you wish, but you'll need a $15 sport-fishing license if
you bring your rod and reel along.
</P>
<P>
   If you like your fishing a little more exciting than spending a
quiet afternoon by a mountain lake, catch a charter in Seward's
colorful Small Boat Harbor and head out into the bay in hunt of
silver and king salmon. If you manage to reel in the largest fish
during August's Silver Salmon Derby, you could go home with
$10,000. Or try your luck going after giant halibut, which grow up
to 300 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you do, don't miss out on a meal of that fresh halibut,
fried crispy and served with chips. Almost every restaurant has it
on the menu. And be forewarned: The portions are enormous wherever
you go.
</P>
<P>
   In a small town like Seward, most restaurants serve a variety of
cuisines. Christo's Palace features Mexican food, steaks, seafood
and pizza, although the pizza is better up the street at the
Apollo, which also specializes in Greek. Or try the spicy kung pao
halibut at the Peking. There's no haute cuisine here, just a lot of
it.
</P>
<P>
   The best home cooking _ and the best small-town gossip _ can be
found at the Marina, a little cafe downtown where the locals order
up their eggs with a side of reindeer sausage or dive into enormous
chili-burgers covered in cheese and onions and buried under a
mountain of shoestring fries. Don't forget to order an Alaskan
Amber or two with that.
</P>
<P>
   What you won't find is fast food, with the exception of a small
Burger King and two Subway locations. The transplanted yuppies like
them, though: no more monthly three-hour drives into Anchorage for
a burger and fries.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. It's really a nice drive.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
