<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, June 30. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-U.S. (Havana) _ ``At Last in the Fatherland!'' declared the
front page headline in Granma, above pictures of Elian Gonzalez
stepping off the plane and being swept up in a relative's arms in
an emotional end to the seven month custody battle that captivated
this nation. Despite the triumphal headline, the return of the
6-year-old rafter is only the beginning to a continuing campaign by
Cuban officials opposed to the American trade embargo and other
American policies that they say weaken their economy and encourage
people to risk their lives at sea hoping to obtain political
asylum. It is an attempt, foreign officials here said, to tap into
the Cuban public's overwhelming support for Elian's return in order
to rekindle an ardor for the revolution that had steadily cooled in
recent years, especially among the youth who were not even born
during the early glory days of the revolution. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-BOAT (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ An overloaded ferry
appears to have sunk in heavy seas Thursday and officials said they
feared the loss of nearly 500 people, many of whom were fleeing
religion-based killings in the remote Maluku islands. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-KOHL (Berlin) _ With a swaggering contempt for his
accusers, former Chancellor Helmut Kohl appeared Thursday before a
parliamentary committee investigating financial misdeeds under his
rule and said he was a victim of slander. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ The Senate approved a
bipartisan bill Thursday that would require a growing number of
secretive, tax-exempt groups that raise and spend money on
political activities to reveal their donors and spending. Only six
Senate Republicans voted against the measure, and the House
endorsed the same bill on Wednesday, 385-39. President Clinton said
he will sign the measure as soon as Congress sends it to him. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House was expected to approve
Thursday night an $11.2 billion spending bill that includes
emergency aid to battle drug traffickers in Colombia, as well as to
pay for the military's mission in Kosovo and relief for flood and
fire victims in this country. By Eric Schmitt and Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The House is expected Thursday
to pass a bill that would give doctors an exemption from antitrust
laws so they could bargain collectively with insurance companies
over fees and other issues. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   HMO-MEDICARE (Washington) _ More than 700,000 Medicare
beneficiaries will lose the insurance coverage they now receive
from health maintenance organizations because the HMOs are cutting
back their participation in Medicare next year, an industry trade
group announced Thursday. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   COMMERCE-MINETA (Washington) _ President Clinton announces the
nomination of Norman Mineta, a former California congressman, as
commerce secretary, making him the first Asian-American Cabinet
secretary. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DECLARATION-AUCTION (New York) _ In what could the most
expensive item ever sold on the Internet, a first printing of the
Declaration of Independence being sold online by Sotheby's could
fetch nearly $5 million. By James Barron.
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-AIR-CRASH (Undated) _ In a report on the Alaska Airlines
crash in January off the California coast, the FAA cites numerous
deficiencies at the airline but accepts its reform plan and will
not shut down its maintenance facilities; the FAA faults itself for
not spotting some of the problems in advance of the crash, and says
it will conduct special audits of the other nine major passenger
airlines in the next three months. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-RIGHTS (Undated) _ A day after the Supreme Court
effectively struck down ``partial birth abortion'' bans in some 30
states, people on both sides of the issue said the contentious
debate over the procedures is far from over. Across the country,
supporters and opponents of the bans said they expected a new
generation of laws around the country aimed at trying to prevent
what critics call partial-birth abortions while meeting the
requirements laid down by the justices on Wednesday. By William
Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-AIRCRAFT (Lod, Isrel) _ In the past 15 years, Israel
Aircraft Industries, a military contractor, has been built from
bankruptcy into an export-driven powerhouse. Its specialities
include refurbishing Soviet-era aircraft, and it has developed
electronic espionage devices for Israel's military that are
considered equal to any on the market. So a major contract it
signed with China to convert an Ilyushin into a modern radar plane
showcased the company's strengths. But if the Pentagon has its way,
the converted Ilyushin will never get to China. Since last fall,
Defense Secretary William Cohen has been demanding the deal's
cancellation, and he is backed by powerful members of Congress. By
William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
