<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEDISH MASTER OF DESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Sweden, Netherlands, Belgium, France and Italy)   By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The second-biggest decorating job in the 18th-century, after
Versailles, was the 608-room Royal Palace in Stockholm, Sweden.
This palace, which is now partly open to the public, is considered
the largest royal city residence still occupied by a king and
queen.
</P>
<P>
   The original Royal Palace suffered a disastrous fire in 1697 and
had to be rebuilt _ a process that took 54 years. Most of the
interiors were created by Carl Harleman, who, when hired, was a
27-year-old architect who had never built a thing. Harleman worked
on the palace for 26 years; in fact, until he died at age 53, the
year he completed it.
</P>
<P>
   Harleman, who is scarcely known in the United States, is
credited with introducing the rococo style to Sweden and giving it
a distinctly Swedish flavor. ``Harleman may have been trained by
the French, but he added something Swedish to the rococo that made
it his own,'' said Magnus Olausson, a curator at the National
Museum in Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   The National Museum has opened an exhibition of Harleman
drawings from its own collection to celebrate the 300th anniversary
of his birth (through Sept. 10). There are exquisite freehand
sketches as well as plans for villas, gardens, household goods like
silver tureens and textiles, even a sarcophagus for King Carl XII.
There are sketches of the many church towers he designed, and they
continue to give Stockholm its distinctive skyline.
</P>
<P>
   Lars Sjoberg, a senior curator at the museum for the last 26
years, explained the appeal of Harleman's work. ``French rococo is
ornate and elaborate, with arabesque elements, shells, scrolls,
branches and flowers seen in all kinds of ormolu mounts and
veneers,'' he said. ``In Sweden, our best architects, like
Harleman, refined the rococo style. He took away any decoration
that was not necessary and made the rococo functional. Even the
sinuous curves in his chairs were not designed only for the eye;
they were engineered to fit the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans who love the Swedish antiques they find at specialist
dealers like Eleish &AMP; Van Breems of Woodbury, Conn.
(www.evbantiques.com) and the reproductions made by Swedish Room
(973 644-4775), will find Harleman's work a revelation. Everything
admired about Swedish style _ the classical proportions, the pale
palette, the charming textiles _ can be traced back to him. He
created the forerunner of the Swedish Royal Academy of Fine Arts,
so his work was passed down to generations of architects and
craftsmen.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Palace, occupied in 1754 by King Adolf Fredrik and
Queen Lovisa Ulrika, has been redecorated over the centuries. But
Harleman's royal chapel is almost unchanged, as is the magnificent
lacy, gilded stucco work on the ceiling in the queen's antechamber.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a better way to see Harleman's work is to visit two of
his manor houses in the Stockholm area. Because of the exhibition,
the state has opened Svartsjo Palace, a small royal hunting castle
Harleman designed in 1731 on the shore of Lake Malaren, the largest
lake in Sweden. It can be visited this summer; in the fall it will
be rented.
</P>
<P>
   It looks a bit like a French chateau, albeit one with a clock
tower added to the roof. Its two-story great hall with trompe
l'oeil windows, faux marble walls and unpainted wide-plank pine
floors have all been restored to their initial style. The 10 rooms
on the ground floor have been furnished with 18th-century portraits
and antiques, including a rococo mirror Harleman designed, with his
signature gilded bird wings flying off the frame.
</P>
<P>
   As both the son and grandson of royal gardeners, Harleman was
initially trained as a garden designer. His Svartsjo garden is
gone, so it is impossible to see how he introduced vegetables into
a formal garden. As Olausson explained: ``In France, there was a
division between a pleasure garden and a potager. Harleman had the
idea to unite utility with pleasure, by converting the formal
garden into a kitchen garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Harleman's early houses were much emulated. ``Svartsjo was the
model for all the manor houses built in the 18th century,'' said
Sjoberg, who owns five of them and is the co-author, with his wife,
Ursula, of ``The Swedish Room,'' published in English by Frances
Lincoln in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Harleman's second manor house, the Svindersvik Pavilion, is now
an adjunct branch of the Nordic Museum in Stockholm. Built as a
summer retreat in about 1750 for Claes Grill, a director of
Sweden's East India Co., it is a small villa overlooking a bay of
the Saltsjon Sea on the eastern approach to Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   It is a one-story building with a pedimented two-story bay in
the center. This house, with only seven rooms, still has its apple
orchard, red barns, separate kitchen and a neo-Classical party
annex. With its high ceilings, large windows and symmetrical floor
plan, it is a study in refined simplicity. The blue and white tile
Swedish stove in the vestibule is paired with a blue and white
painted reproduction, which is a wooden cupboard. The salon is
decorated with handpainted 18th-century Chinese wallpaper and
gilded rococo mirrors. The master bedroom is furnished with pale
gray Gustavian chairs covered in green-and-white checked cotton,
very similar to the reproductions that Ikea once sold in its
Swedish collection. This charming villa would not be out of place
in most small towns in America.
</P>
<P>
   The genius of Harleman (1700-1753) evidenced itself early. His
father, the royal gardener, died when he was 7. ``His mother must
have been a brilliant woman with a strong will,'' Sjoberg said.
``Carl was one of six small children she was left with, but she
recognized his talents early on.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1721, on the recommendation of the royal architect Nicodemus
Tessin the Younger, Harleman received a stipend to study art and
architecture abroad. He visited the Netherlands, Belgium, France
and Italy before settling in Paris for four years. There, he won
the first prize for architecture in his class, at age 25.
</P>
<P>
   He was in Venice, Italy, in 1727 when Tessin summoned him to
decorate the royal palace. The rebuilding was about to resume after
a 20-year hiatus caused by the costly wars waged by the romantic
warrior King Carl XII. Harleman rushed home. Three months later,
Tessin died, and his son Carl Gustav was named commissioner of
public buildings. He kept Harleman, who then went to Paris to
recruit artisans to do fancy rococo masonry, stucco work and carved
paneling.
</P>
<P>
   ``No architect has ever been so gifted,'' Olausson said. ``He
did everything.'' The museum show includes his drawings for carved
trophies for the walls, huge wrought-iron lanterns and fanciful
rococo consoles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He oversaw everyone who had anything to do with art and
handicraft,'' Sjoberg said. ``Harleman has always been a name in
Sweden, but no one knew how much he did because he never told
anyone. Perhaps this exhibition will show how important he is in
Sweden's architectural tradition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
