<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8519 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHARDIN-RETROSPECTIVE     06-29 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARDIN-RETROSPECTIVE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARDIN MAKES THE SIMPLE RIVETING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ According to the glacial timetable on which big
exhibitions at art museums operate these days, it hasn't been
especially long, 21 years, since the last major traveling
retrospective of the 18th-century French painter Jean-Simeon
Chardin. Of course, if the world were a perfect place, a Chardin
show would be on view all the time.
</P>
<P>
   This one arrives at the Met looking much less cramped and more
luxurious than it did at its last stop, in London, on its European
tour. The unnecessary excuse is the tercentenary of Chardin's birth
in 1699. The show doesn't tell us much that was not already known,
but I can't see anything wrong with being reminded occasionally of
what great painting is.
</P>
<P>
   Every great painter is great by some terms or other, Watteau's
terms differing from Courbet's, Ingres' from Kandinsky's. Chardin
was as great as any artist by the terms he set for himself, which
were incredibly circumscribed: for almost his whole career,
spanning half a century, nearly every minute of it spent in Paris,
Chardin focused on what was not much farther than 3 or 4 feet in
front of his nose. He painted the same brown crockery, some fruit,
eggs and dead rabbits, sometimes mingled with French maids and
scrubbed children whose calm and immobility harmonized with the
inanimate things around them.
</P>
<P>
   These people seem arrested in motion, suspended, which can put
you in mind of the people in Vermeer's paintings except that
Chardin's people look more real than Vermeer's. They are absorbed
and inward turning, oblivious of us. When a little girl glances in
a mirror while her mother adjusts her bonnet, or when a nurse,
balancing a long-handled saucepan against her arm, peels a
hard-boiled egg, Chardin somehow makes these instants seem to
stretch toward infinity, assuming sudden gravity.
</P>
<P>
   In the process he conveys both the sensation of glimpsing
something unremarkable and the effect of having that glimpse
impressed on the mind as a memory. This memory, because it is
vivid, mysteriously takes a place in the imagination out of
proportion to its significance, like a smell or some notes of music
or a breeze that triggers the recollection of a childhood game or a
trip or a lost relative. It stays there, waiting.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Proust loved Chardin so much. ``You have already
experienced it subconsciously,'' he wrote, ``this pleasure one gets
from the sight of everyday scenes and inanimate objects, otherwise
it would not have risen in your heart when Chardin summoned it in
his ringing commanding accents. But your consciousness was too
sluggish to reach down to it. It had to wait for Chardin to come
and lay hold on it and hoist in to the level of your conscious
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   That's right (Proust is always right), although I'm not sure
Chardin exactly rings out with commanding accents, being moderate
and soft-spoken, and I would add that beyond just pointing out what
is already there, he uncovered a deeper truth in nature, one that
reveals itself slowly in his work. It has to do with the interplay
of color and rhyming form, which suggests a fundamental order in
the world, something immensely reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Smoker's Case,'' for example, it exists in the
right-facing L formed by the opened lid of the rosewood case next
to the left-facing L formed by the porcelain cup and pot. A third
and larger L is made by the thick horizontal slab of the table and
the corner of the wall behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Formal balance then becomes poetry with the abrupt diagonal of
the slender pipe, the picture's exclamation point, the point of
which is a tiny speck of red in the pipe's bowl, a flame from which
tendrils of wispy smoke drift up: movement within stillness. Added
to this are the corresponding reflections of silver cup, crystal
flask, silver cap and copper goblet, ovals doing a kind of call and
response across the picture plane, the image punctuated by delicate
blue and rose designs on the pasty white porcelain, fireworks in
Chardin's tamped-down context.
</P>
<P>
   Quietude and deliberation. These were essential ingredients for
Chardin, who didn't tell stories or anecdotes. There was no real
symbolism in his work, either, no fancy allusions, and above all no
sex. A scallion was a scallion was a scallion. This was chaste and
humble painting emerging from the most erotic, opulent and
rhetorically extravagant era in the history of European painting,
exemplified by the perfumed virtuosity of a compatriot and nearly
exact contemporary like Boucher.
</P>
<P>
   The art of Chardin, by contrast with so much Rococo art, was
about love, not sex, a big difference. The sheets stayed pressed in
his pictures. If an eroticism existed, we may sense it as dense
pigment: thick, painstakingly built-up paint, which can have a
sensual charge.
</P>
<P>
   Call it understatement. Chardin was the best still life painter
ever because he made the most of the least. Sometimes he achieved a
huge impact with empty space. ``Girl With Shuttlecock'' is a figure
silhouetted against a bare wall. Her outline is a triangle
complicated by a stray strand of ribbon and the feathers of the
shuttlecock, very spare.
</P>
<P>
   Even more minimalist is ``A Mallard Drake Hanging on a Wall and
a Seville Orange.'' The space behind the picture plane is shallow
and ambiguous, as it often seems with Chardin. The duck is head
down; the body is hung from the upper left of the picture, one wing
collapsed at a right angle from the body so that the whole thing
forms a kind of calligraphic sign against a plain backdrop. This
shape is offset by the orange in the lower right corner: painted
haiku. The trajectory that exists from Chardin to Cezanne and
Matisse, who both revered him, derives from this perfect mastery of
abstract form pared down.
</P>
<P>
   All writers about Chardin invariably point out that his
pictorial family consists of the cups and pans that reappear in one
painting after another, decade after decade. We recognize them
throughout the 66 works in this exhibition as friends sharing a
comforting universe where nothing ever changes and no one ever dies
_ except hares whose death in Chardin's hands becomes more a state
of grace than morbidity. We're given the signs of rigor mortis and
blood stains on the fur.
</P>
<P>
   Chardin's attendance to their condition and by extension our
attendance can be so loving and complete that it approaches
transference. We can fully believe this is what it's like to be a
rabbit, and the association, even though it's a little crazy,
elicits empathy.
</P>
<P>
   Dead rabbits and likewise dead fish: Cartier-Bresson, the
photographer, who draws copies of Chardins at the Louvre, has
pointed out about the famous dead ray hanging gutted from a hook
that it looks like it's crucified. This dovetails with Proust's
equally fantastic metaphor for the ray as ``the nave of a
polychrome cathedral.''
</P>
<P>
   What is it about Chardin that even his pictures of food make
people speculate about God?
</P>
<P>
   I suspect it has to do with the particular quality of his
silence. These are pictures of an extraordinary hushed reverence
for the dignity of modest things, for paint's ability to simulate
those things, and for a viewer's elevation through extended looking
at those things. With Chardin one loses track of time staring at a
bunch of cherries, wondering at their translucence, then counting
the cherries _ there are five _ and noticing that five matches the
sum of two peaches, a green apple and two sections of a split
apricot to create perfect symmetry.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny observation, but like many simple facts of life strangely
marvelous when it turns out to be a key to some greater truth.
Chardin's work is a compilation of these little facts that together
make as true a record of the value of seeing as exists in the
history of art.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
