r a BC-ARCHBISHOP-HOSTAGE-HN     06-29 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHBISHOP-HOSTAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ARCHBISHOP KNOWN FOR HIS OPENNESS, GRACE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVID UHLER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Roman Catholic Archbishop Patrick Flores' personal
philosophy, emblazoned on his episcopal coat of arms, offers one of
the best insights into why he was so easily taken hostage
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laborabo non mihi se omnibus,'' the motto reads in Latin. ``I
will not work for myself, but for others.''
</P>
<P>
   With an open-door policy at his chancery office, Flores
routinely welcomes a steady stream of visitors, receiving all of
them _ the rich and powerful and the poor and oppressed _ with the
same gentle mixture of grace, humility and respect.
</P>
<P>
   As the hostage drama played out over nine hours Wednesday at the
archbishop's office in San Antonio, friends, co-workers,
acquaintances and many people who did not even know Flores paused
to pray and reflect on the cleric fondly known as the ``Mariachi
Bishop.''
</P>
<P>
   Flores, 71, was not harmed during the ordeal. He was released
from a hospital Thursday and church officials said he was resting.
</P>
<P>
   The police charged Nelson Antonio Escolero, 40, an El Salvadoran
national who has lived in the United States for years, with
aggravated kidnapping. Escolero, whose wife and three children are
U.S. citizens, told the police he was distraught that a pending
charge of driving with a suspended license could get him deported.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first word you think of when you think of Patrick Flores
is kindness,'' said Tom Frost, senior chairman of Cullen/Frost
Bankers Inc., who has known the archbishop more than 30 years. ``I
think he's been one of the most significant forces for good in this
community that I've seen in my adult life.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Lyons, 16, met Flores five years ago when she and her
choir sang for him during a visit to her middle school. On
Wednesday, Lyons, now a high school junior, went to the San
Fernando Cathedral, the official seat of the diocese, to pray for
Flores.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me and my classmates a hug,'' Lyons recalled. ``I'll
never forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of migrant farm workers, a high school dropout who beat
the odds to become the first Mexican-American Catholic bishop,
Flores never lost his love for the people he vowed to serve. It was
a love forged from personal hardship.
</P>
<P>
   Patricio Flores was born on May 26, 1929, in the tiny South
Texas farming community of Ganado, one of 10 children. The family
migrated between Robstown and Amarillo every year, picking cotton
and rice. Lagging behind in school due to his family's frequent
moves, Flores dropped out in the tenth grade after his father fell
ill.
</P>
<P>
   The future archbishop sang in several Houston-area beer halls
until some soul searching put him on the path to the priesthood.
The pastor of Flores' church tried to discourage him, saying,
``Mexicans don't make it anyway.'' But a sympathetic nun, Sister
Mary Benetia Vermeersch, brought the 17-year-old to the attention
of Christopher Byrne, who was then bishop of the diocese of
Galveston and Houston. With Byrne's personal financial and
spiritual support, Flores completed three years of high school
coursework in two years and then entered St. Mary's Seminary in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Flores was ordained a priest in 1956. During the 1960s, he
served in several Houston parishes and became active in PADRES, a
group of Hispanic priests that pushed for the appointment of a
Hispanic bishop. They got their wish in 1970 when the Vatican, much
to Flores' surprise, made him its first Mexican-American bishop,
working as an auxiliary to then Archbishop Francis J. Furey.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, while attending a bishop's conference in Ecuador,
Flores and four other Mexican-American prelates were taken into
custody at gunpoint by the army. They were later released unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Flores was named bishop of El Paso, only to return to
San Antonio as archbishop 15 months later after Furey's death from
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Milestones of Flores' years in the top post include Pope John
Paul II's visit to the Alamo City in 1987. He also co-founded the
Mexican-American Cultural Center as a school for Hispanic pastoral
ministry, helped stanch declining enrollment in San Antonio's
Catholic schools and established the nation's first Catholic
diocesan television station.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers speculate that Flores could become the first
Hispanic cardinal, a theory Flores has dismissed. Flores plans to
stay in office until July 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Equally fluent in English and Spanish, Flores loves to tell
stories and jokes from the pulpit, but he never shies away from
controversy on behalf of poor people, unborn babies, undocumented
workers and death-row inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Well-wishes came from all over the world last year when Flores
celebrated his celebrated his 70th birthday. San Antonio auto and
real estate magnate B.J. ``Red'' McCombs served as the chairman of
Flores' birthday bash.
</P>
<P>
   ``His life, all of his life, is his service to others,'' McCombs
said Wednesday. ``There's not any question about that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact David Uhler by e-mail at duhler(at)express-news.net)
</P>
