<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ROCKY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UH, GEE, ROCKY, DE NIRO'S REMAKE OF KITSCHY CULT FAVE IS PRETTY
GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlikely as it may seem, Robert De Niro is said to be an
obsessive fan of the old Rocky and Bullwinkle television cartoon
show, and has apparently spent much of the '90s patiently trying to
secure the rights and put together his own big-screen version.
</P>
<P>
   The root of this obsession is not clear _ he's not been
forthcoming on the subject _ and no doubt his biographers will be
debating the matter for decades to come. Perhaps his ``rosebud'' as
an actor is buried within its absurdity. Perhaps it just tickles
his funny bone.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever has made the superstar spend nearly 10 years on the
project, his dedication has resulted in one of the better would-be
blockbusters of the summer of '00. It's often surprisingly clever,
dripping with respect for its model, and done with considerable wit
and style.
</P>
<P>
   The original animated series, ``Rocky and his Friends'' (later
retitled ``The Bullwinkle Show''), which ran between 1959 and 1964,
chronicled _ among numerous other characters _ the adventures of a
do-gooder flying squirrel, Rocky, and his ultra-dumb moose
sidekick, Bullwinkle: an undynamic duo that was often at odds with
an Eastern European spy couple named Boris and Natasha.
</P>
<P>
   It was drawn in the era's junkiest kind of ``limited'' TV
animation, but creator Jay Ward put much effort into the writing
and gradually developed a unique ``bad'' humor for the show that
went right over the heads of the kiddies to gather a large adult
following: groan-inducing puns, silly satiric gags, unbelievably
corny one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   This big-screen version generally succeeds in re-creating that
humor in a story that has the animated duo pressed into service
after a 35-year retirement. Their mission: to help the FBI stop the
post-Cold War Boris and Natasha from taking over America by means
of RB (``Really Bad'') TV, a network so unspeakably dumb that it
turns viewers into zombies.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that Boris, Natasha and their controller, Fearless
Leader, have _ through some esoteric computer glitch _ taken on
human form, while Rocky and Bullwinkle remain animated. So the
movie is very much a ``Roger Rabbit''-affair, with the
three-dimensional cartoon heroes operating in a live-action world.
</P>
<P>
   To make this difficult transition, producer De Niro has hired
Kenneth Lonergan, who wrote the hit 1999 De Niro-Billy Crystal
comedy, ``Analyze This.'' For the most part, the writer has risen
to the task with an occasionally very funny, shamelessly
pun-riddled script that plays off our affection for the old series
and constantly pokes fun at the nostalgic folly of the filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Director Des McAnuff _ a Tony-winning Broadway veteran whose
only previous movie was the 1998 adaptation of Balzac's ``Cousin
Bette'' _ is yet a third unlikely purveyor of baby-boomer kitsch,
but he also gets in the spirit, adds several inspired touches and
has resisted any pressure there might have been to upgrade the old
Jay Ward-style of animation with a Disneyesque lushness.
</P>
<P>
   De Niro gives himself the showiest part, Fearless Leader,
playing it as if he had understudied Laurence Olivier in ``The
Prince and the Showgirl.'' Jason Alexander and Rene Russo are also
suitably broad and silly as Boris and Natasha.
</P>
<P>
   In the final analysis, the movie ``Rocky and Bullwinkle''
manages to be a worthy tribute to the TV classic in every respect
except one: It lacks the original's brevity. While the Rocky and
Bullwinkle segments were only five or 10 minutes of a half-hour
show, this movie goes on for 88 minutes. Its first act is
delightful, but it just doesn't have the juice to sustain a feature
length and finally becomes redundant and tiresome.
</P>
<P>
   The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle. Directed by Des McAnuff.
Written by Kenneth Lonergan. Cast: Rene Russo, Jason Alexander,
Robert De Niro, Piper Perabo. Universal. 88 minutes. Rated PG-13
for no obvious reason.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
