<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENNINGTON-TRAVEL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATURAL BEAUTY, AND HISTORY TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT13 and 14 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BENNINGTON, Vt. _ Beyond providing an excuse to indulge in hot
dogs and fireworks, the Fourth of July weekend can still call to
mind the struggle around the event the holiday commemorates, the
signing of the Declaration of Independence. So perhaps a town like
Bennington, whose ambience runs from the workaday to the artsy,
should count itself fortunate to have so visible a reminder of
Revolutionary valor.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the Bennington Battle Monument, a limestone shaft
that does double duty, commemorating the Battle of Bennington in
1777 and providing a perch to which visitors can ascend for
impressive views of the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Reminders of revolutionary glory are only one diversion in
southwestern Vermont, a place rich in recreational opportunities
(the Appalachian Trail runs through the area) and in its
association with famous people, from poets to the kin of
presidents. Robert Frost is buried in Bennington. Mary Todd Lincoln
spent summers in nearby Manchester, which is also the site of a
mansion built by Robert Todd Lincoln, her son.
</P>
<P>
   I've felt the lure of the area since I lived in western
Massachusetts, where I worked for a local newspaper in the early
1980s. Driving up to Bennington seemed like a pleasant escape.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as then, there are two ways to get around. Those who value
speed can take Route 7, a highway connecting Bennington to
Manchester, 20 miles north. But why go fast when there is so much
to see?
</P>
<P>
   On a recent trip, my wife, Margaret, and I took the slow road,
Route 7A, a two-laner that rises and dips across the rural
landscape. We made our base in Arlington, a village that briefly
served as Vermont's capital after the Revolution. Fortunately, the
legislators have long since departed, leaving the place quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Because we liked the description in a guidebook, we booked a
room at the Arlington Inn, a mid-19th-century Greek Revival mansion
with a lawn fronting the main road. It turned out to be a very good
choice; the friendly and responsive staff treated us and our
toddler son with down-to-earth good cheer. From there we ambled
around the countryside, admiring its many shades of green, and even
found a couple of covered bridges, one not far from the inn.
</P>
<P>
   But we had some specific goals in mind, one being the Bennington
Battlefield State Historic Site. Visiting it brings a surprise, as
the site lies in New York, just across the Vermont line, on a small
but steep hill. The British forces involved in the fighting had
been heading for Bennington, on orders from Gen. John Burgoyne, to
seize American supplies. Burgoyne's subordinate, Lt. Col. Friedrich
Baum, made it only as far as a hill above the Walloomsac River,
where he dug in.
</P>
<P>
   The high ground did him little good. His troops were overwhelmed
on Aug. 16, 1777, by American forces under Gen. John Stark, a
veteran of Bunker Hill. Baum died in the battle, as did 200 of his
men. Vermont's militia, led by Seth Warner, saved the day by
chasing off British reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
   Burgoyne, leading an army south from Canada in an effort to
separate New England from the rest of the colonies, complained that
Vermonters were ``the most rebellious race on the continent.'' He
met his final defeat two months later, at Saratoga, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   As for Warner, he is honored by a statue in front of the battle
monument, built a century ago at the site of the supply house the
British had hoped to take. A mile west of Bennington's downtown, in
a community called Old Bennington, the 306-foot tower contains an
upper floor that visitors can reach by elevator. Narrow windows
offer views in all directions.
</P>
<P>
   Look south and you get a clear view of Mount Greylock, the
highest point in Massachusetts. In the same direction, virtually in
the tower's shadow, is the First Congregational Church, known
locally as Old First. Completed in 1806, it is every inch the
traditional white New England clapboard church-on-the-green.
</P>
<P>
   We first saw it illuminated by spotlights after nightfall _ a
stunning sight _ as we drove into Bennington on Route 9 from
Albany. The burial ground behind the church contains Robert Frost's
grave, as well as the resting places of Revolutionary soldiers and
several Vermont governors. The cemetery is one of several old
graveyards in the vicinity bearing headstones with elaborate
carvings of hourglasses and angels' heads and homespun couplets
that were common in 18th-century New England. One such cemetery
that is particularly worth seeing lies adjacent to Route 7A in the
village of Shaftsbury. The Green Mountains form its backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   The culture in which these stones were created favored epitaphs
that spoke of death with a bluntness now decidedly out of style. In
Shaftsbury, this inscription is carved onto the stone of one Israel
Cole, who died in 1787: ``You find the place where I am laid, To
moulder in the dust. As you must be tis only said, That I am here
the first.''
</P>
<P>
   From Shaftsbury it's a few miles to the busier streets of
Manchester, a resort of long standing. In August 1863, Mary Todd
Lincoln brought her sons there to stay in the Equinox Hotel, which
is still very much a part of the local scene.
</P>
<P>
   LAND OF A LINCOLN
</P>
<P>
   Robert Todd Lincoln, her oldest (and the only of the Lincolns'
children to reach adulthood) would later return to Manchester in a
very big way. In 1902, a successful corporate lawyer, he bought 500
acres southeast of town and built a grand summer home, which he
called Hildene. A Georgian Revival mansion, it sits atop high
ground, with formal gardens and a generous view of the valley
below.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   For the last two decades it has been owned and managed by the
Friends of Hildene, a nonprofit preservationist group that bought
it for $200,000 from the Christian Science Church, which had
acquired it as a bequest from the last of the Lincoln descendants
to live there, Mary ``Peggy'' Beckwith.
</P>
<P>
   These days it is open for tours from May to October, pretty much
the time of year that Robert Lincoln's family was in residence.
</P>
<P>
   Our guide told us that Mary Beckwith, an animal lover who kept
the mansion full of dogs and cats, was venturesome enough to learn
to fly but so reticent in public that it took Pat Nixon (then wife
of the vice president) several phone calls to persuade her to come
to Virginia in 1960 to christen a Navy submarine named for Abraham
Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the mansion strongly reflects the presence of
the younger Lincoln. Although he wore a beard in later life, he
looked little like his presidential father, to judge by a portrait
that hangs in the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   It could not have been easy being the son of the martyred savior
of the Union. And there does not seem to be much in Robert
Lincoln's public life to appeal to idealists. Twenty-two years old
when Abraham Lincoln was assassinated, he became a lawyer in
Chicago, establishing a base of corporate clients that included the
Pullman railroad car company; he became the company's president in
1897, only a few years after the concern had crushed its workers in
the great Pullman strike.
</P>
<P>
   He never sought elective office but twice served in Republican
administrations, as secretary of war and later as ambassador to
Great Britain. In Manchester, he played golf daily.
</P>
<P>
   What a visitor sees at Hildene is a life lived at very great
remove from the hardscrabble frontier existence Americans associate
with the young Abraham Lincoln. Robert Lincoln represented a
Republican Party leadership more privileged than populist, more
comfortable with William Howard Taft (who visited during his
unsuccessful re-election campaign in 1912) than with Teddy
Roosevelt. Robert Lincoln already owned a substantial house in
Chicago when he built Hildene, a mansion with 24 rooms. ``He was a
railroad baron, all right,'' our guide remarked.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the mansion has a homey rather than an imperial air. The
rooms are attractively designed but not grand. The library, from
which Robert Lincoln ran the Pullman company when he was at
Hildene, is small but inviting, decorated with portraits of Abraham
Lincoln. The parlor nearby is painted a rose red that Robert
Lincoln's wife, Mary, liked.
</P>
<P>
   After the visit we walked around Manchester, where a
neighborhood of stately homes leads up to the town's commercial
center, the Equinox Hotel on one side and the county courthouse,
with its gold-colored cupola, on the other. The Lure of Exploring
</P>
<P>
   It all seemed very busy and prosperous, the street humming with
cars and people bustling off to lunch, the golf course or upscale
outlet stores. One could probably settle in pretty comfortably and
perhaps not venture elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But if we had done that, we would have missed any number of
things _ like finding out just how cooling it is to be inside the
battle monument on a very hot day, or discovering that, upon
stopping in Shaftsbury, the loudest sound we heard was birdsong.
</P>
<P>
   And I would have been sorry to have missed the odd tree we found
outside our inn in Arlington, the one with a split trunk, an
opening just wide enough for a 2-year-old to squeeze through and
feel as if he was having an adventure. Our son liked that a lot,
and it made for some good pictures.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL AND TOURING
</P>
<P>
   Bennington, Vt., is 150 miles north of New York City. Here is a
sampling of attractions, along with travel information:
</P>
<P>
   ATTRACTIONS:
</P>
<P>
   BENNINGTON BATTLE MONUMENT, Bennington, (802) 447-0550. Hours:
Daily, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m., until Nov. 1. Admission: $1.50; 75 cents
for ages 6 to 12; free for children under 6.
</P>
<P>
   BENNINGTON BATTLEFIELD STATE HISTORIC SITE, Hoosick Falls, N.Y.,
(518) 279-1155. Hours: Daily, 10 a.m. to 7 p.m., until Labor Day;
weekends only, same hours, Labor Day to Nov. 1; closed Nov. 1 until
May 1. Free.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST CONGREGATIONAL CHURCH, Monument Avenue, Bennington, (802)
447-1223. Hours: Daily, 10 a.m to noon and 1 to 4 p.m., July 1
through Columbus Day. Free.
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT TODD LINCOLN'S HILDENE, Route 7A South, Manchester, (802)
362-1788. Hours: First tour begins at 9:30 a.m. and the last at 4
p.m., daily until Oct. 31. Admission: $8; $4 for children 6 to 14;
free for children 5 and under. Grounds are open until 5:30 p.m.;
grounds passes (no tour), $4.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO STAY:
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON INN, Route 7A, Arlington, (800) 443-9442 or (802)
375-6532. Double rooms: $115 to $265 a night.
</P>
<P>
   EQUINOX HOTEL, 3567 Main St., Manchester, (800) 362-4747 or
(802) 362-4700. Rooms: $189 to $339 a night.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO EAT:
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON INN, Route 7A, Arlington, (800) 443-9442 or (802)
375-6532. Continental-style cuisine, with a changing menu.
Appetizers, $3 to $9; entrees, $15 to $27. Reservations
recommended.
</P>
<P>
   DORMY GRILL, the golf clubhouse at the Equinox Hotel, 3567 Main
St., Manchester, (800) 362-4747 or (802) 362-4700. Soups, salads,
sandwiches; generous portions. Entrees, about $9. No reservations.
</P>
<P>
   RACHEL'S GOURMET FOODS, 4479 Route 7A, Manchester, (802)
362-3163. No seating. Take-out sandwiches, $4 to $6; soups, $1.75
to $2.50; salads, $4 to $7 a pound. Also fine wines, cheeses and
desserts.
</P>
