<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: You can lead a horse to water, but _
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the third in this week's grab-bag series of campaign
proposals, Al Gore, in Chicago today, proposed $25 billion in
mass-transit subsidies meant to clean up smog and traffic. He
underscored that his ``new-way-of-thinking'' environmental agenda
won't force drivers onto the bus or train: ``Don't tell me that
there's a great groundswell to get rid of cars and to push people
into mass transit whether they want it or not. That's the old,
tired way of thinking; the new way of thinking is, hey, give people
a choice.'' This proposal was dubbed ``Keep America Moving''
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   PUTTING OUT CONTRACTS?
</P>
<P>
   Two Republican congressmen _ Christopher Shays of Connecticut
and Peter Hoekstra of Michigan _ want Al Gore to answer allegations
that federal contracts went to the Teamsters to influence their
presidential endorsement. The New York Times had quoted anonymous
Gore advisers as saying projects were directed through federal
agencies that would use Teamsters in an effort to keep the union
from endorsing Green Party candidate Ralph Nader. ``This statement,
if true, is an illegal act,'' said Shays. The Gore campaign and
Teamsters spokesman Bret Caldwell denied the allegation.
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN ISSUE OFF THE FRONT BURNER
</P>
<P>
   With 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez back in Cuba, George W. Bush said
he was ``saddened'' and Al Gore said the Supreme Court's refusal to
intervene is ``entitled to respect.'' Gore had argued for the case
to be turned over to a family court. He also parted company with
the Clinton administration by supporting legislation to grant
permanent resident status to the boy, his father and other
relatives. That move was criticized as political pandering to
Cuban-Americans. Bush also favored a family court hearing, and had
wanted the administration to try to persuade the father and son to
stay in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL TO BACKERS: SEND MONEY
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is raising money for a final pre-convention TV ad
blitz. ``Please click on my Web site and contribute to my
campaign,'' he wrote in an e-mail to supporters. ``Every cent will
go to TV ads to let Americans know what I would do as president.''
Bush cannot spend privately raised money after he becomes the
official GOP presidential nominee at the July 31-Aug. 3 convention.
At that point, he will get $67.6 million in taxpayer money to run
his fall campaign. Al Gore will get the same. Bush has raised more
than $90 million, had $7.1 million left at the end of May, and
continues to raise more.
</P>
<P>
   NOW IT'S UP TO PEROT TO DECIDE
</P>
<P>
   A supporter of Ross Perot says he's gained enough signatures to
qualify the Texas billionaire for the Reform Party's presidential
primary ballot in an effort to block Pat Buchanan. But Perot, who
has until midnight Friday to accept or reject the ballot spot,
wasn't indicating what he'd do. With just over a day left until the
deadline, Ira Goodman of New Jersey said backers have received
qualifying signatures from enough states to satisfy party rules.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITAL CASES PILING UP ON BUSH
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of a swing to court minority voters, George W.
Bush is facing another clemency decision, this one in a death
penalty case marked by allegations of racial bias. The case of
Jessy San Miguel has not attracted as much mainstream media
attention as Gary Graham, who was executed last week. That's
because San Miguel, 28, has long admitted to the brutal slaying of
four people in a Taco Bell shop in 1991. Spanish-language media,
however, has focused on the role race may have played in San
Miguel's death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   GEE,THIS GUY'S REALLY ANGRY
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter (R-Pa.) sent a second letter to Al Gore
demanding an apology for a comment by his spokesman, Chris Lehane,
accusing Specter of using ``McCarthyite tactics.'' ``Since you have
not responded to my (first) letter and your surrogates are
repeating their outlandish, defamatory statements, if your campaign
intends to continue your character assassination of me, I think you
ought to be man enough to say it yourself.'' Specter had disclosed
a Justice Department official's recommendation of a special counsel
to probe Gore's statements in connection with 1996 fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   WHICH DIRECTION THE FEAR?
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton defended her two-week-long wave of attacks on
Rick Lazio, asserting that she was simply trying to highlight
contrasts between the two Senate candidates, and disputing Lazio's
contention that she was orchestrating a campaign based on fear. ``I
don't think the congressman has anything to fear from me; I think
the only thing he has to fear is his own record,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO `ARRIVE': USE MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Hosting a mostly black crowd of new and second-generation
immigrants from Africa at a $1,000-a-person fund-raiser in
Washington, Al Gore noted the event raised $350,000 for the
Democratic National Committee. ``That is a sign that this group has
really entered a brand new relationship to the national politics of
our country,'' he said. He added that ``as Irish-Americans have
been able to focus the attention of our policy makers,'' so, too,
would this group be able ``to play its proper role in helping to
focus the attention of our country on issues in Nigeria or Ethiopia
or Ghana or Cameroon or South Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   FIRING AN ANTI-GUN BARRAGE AT CONVENTION
</P>
<P>
   A national gun control organization that has displayed thousands
of gunshot victims' shoes around the country is planning an
advertising blitz and special shows of shoes during the Republican
convention in Philadelphia. The organization, Silent March, says
its ads against guns will appear on 100 city buses and 50 subway
trains from July 31 through Aug. 3, though convention managers
currently have no plans to make an issue of gun control. ``These
advertisements are a wake-up call to the Republican Party,'' said
Ellen Freudenheim of Silent March.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
