<SLUG> BC-NY-DAHESH-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOETHE AND THE LURE OF ITALIAN VISTAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Exhibition notes at end of review.) 
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the virtues of the small Dahesh Museum, young
but with both feet planted in tradition, is its mounting of
academic theme and individual shows involving minor yet sometimes
significant artists that would be hard to come by elsewhere. The
museum has grown (if not physically, at least in aesthetic stature)
since its rocky beginning in Manhattan five years ago when its
exhibition policy was based on the kitschy 19th-century academic
paintings acquired by its founding father, a Lebanese philosophical
writer and art collector (1909-1984) known by his adopted moniker,
Dr. Dahesh, which means ``inspiring wonder'' in Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   But after the first three shows of its own collection, the
museum decided to broaden its program. Under the direction of J.
David Farmer, an art historian, it began to bring in shows and
borrow works to complement its own. As its ambitions have
developed, the Dahesh _ maybe the only museum in America with a
wall-to-wall program of 19th-century traditional academic art
(eschewing Impressionism as too avant-garde) _ has gained in
credibility among its institutional colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally we really had to go out and find stuff, but now
it's coming to us,'' said Farmer. What's more, for the first time
in its short history, the museum earlier this year organized its
own show, ``Overcoming All Obstacles: The Women of the Academie
Julian,'' which celebrated the pioneering role of the Parisian art
school in training women. Breaking attendance records at the
Dahesh, the show was the first the museum was able to circulate.
</P>
<P>
   The Dahesh would like to spread its wings in the building at 2
Columbus Circle, erected by Huntington Hartford and most recently
occupied by the New York City Department of Cultural Affairs. It
has put in a bid for the building. But meanwhile, it is carrying on
in its cramped Midtown quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Its current show, ``In the Footsteps of Goethe: Paintings and
Drawings from German Collections'' is the first exhibition to focus
on 19th-century landscape painting in Italy by Germans affiliated
with the influential Duesseldorf Academy of Art _ an important
center for traditional academic art training _ during its golden
age, 1829-1865. It runs through Aug. 10.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 plein-air sketches _ done on site and concentrating
on Rome and its environs _ by teachers and students of the Academy
are on view, ranging from ink-and-pencil drawings to finished oils.
The show was organized last year by Dr. Martina Stitt, curator of
the Kunsthalle in Hamburg, to celebrate the 250th birthday of the
writer, art collector and polymath Johann Wolfgang von Goethe
(1749-1832). The Dahesh is its only United States stop.
</P>
<P>
   The lure of Italy for young German artists was much enhanced by
Goethe's widely read ``Italian Journey,'' an artistic-philosophical
diary of his sojourn there in the 1780s, first published in full in
1829. German artists had worked in Italy before, most notably the
Nazarenes, a group of early 19th-century painters in Rome keen on
reviving the purity of Christian expression in early Renaissance
art. The history of German painters in Rome usually ends with the
departure of the Nazarenes in the early 1830s. But new research has
tracked the German presence in Italy to the 1860s.
</P>
<P>
   Among the contributions of the first wave of Goethe-inspired
followers to the development of European landscape was the
proliferation of the plein-air sketch, done directly from nature.
Such sketches were regarded only as notes for finished work, but
they later came to be accepted as finished paintings in themselves
by more progressive artists, notably the Impressionists.
</P>
<P>
   The charismatic Friedrich Wilhelm von Schadow (1788-1862), a
history painter who was part of the Nazarene group, headed the
Duesseldorf Academy. It drew not only European but American
students, William Stanley Haseltine and Worthington Whittredge
among them, during its peak years, from 1826 to 1859. Von Schadow
revered Italy, made several lengthy visits to Rome and was joined
there by his students.
</P>
<P>
   What these northern artists loved about Italy besides its
centrality to classical civilization were the picturesque ruins;
beautiful vistas in the campagnas around Rome, Naples and Sicily;
the architecture of Roman houses and monuments, gardens, woods,
walls, hill towns; and above all the profusion of light that bathed
everything in a golden glow.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more talented and prolific of the Duesseldorf painters
was Johann Wilhelm Schirmer (1807-1863), who in 1839 became
professor of landscape painting at the Academy. He was known for
his offbeat perspectives and ability to register rapid changes of
light. The artist most represented in the show, his contributions
range from the beautifully lighted oil sketch ``At Tivoli, View
Below the Villa d'Este'' (1840), a peek through heavy foliage at a
grand structure, to the highly finished ``Italian Forest
Landscape'' (1842). Completed two years after his return from
Italy, it is a big, romantic close-up view of a forest through
which two travelers make their way toward an idyllic destination
that dazzles with its light.
</P>
<P>
   Schirmer's landscape students in Duesseldorf included the Swiss
symbolist Arnold Boecklin (1827-1901), who made Rome his base from
1850 to 1857. A low-key Boecklin view of the Roman Campagna from
that time is included in the show, ``Pontine Marshes'' (1851), a
clump of foliage on rocky ground backed by an idyllic cloudscape.
One of the few paintings with figures is a large, too-bright oil by
Caspar Scheuren (1810-1887), ``Monks at the Italian Sea'' (1846),
depicting men of the cloth on a balcony, looking out over a
campanile at a stretch of blue sea illuminated by a startling
pinkish-orange light.
</P>
<P>
   The show abounds in pencil sketches, too. Although most are
notes for landscape paintings or architectural studies, one
charming, undated work by Carl Andreae (1823-1904) depicts five
friends and colleagues at the German Archaeological Institute. A
strongly rendered lineup of profiles, it gives a lively character
reading for each face. A more exuberant sketch by a Nazarene, Peter
Cornelius (1783-1867), ``Festival of German Artists in Rome''
(1835) gives the rowdy flavor of life among the Duesseldorfers when
not at their easels.
</P>
<P>
   Fleshing out a little-known area of German art, ``In the
Footsteps of Goethe'' is a worthwhile show. The Dahesh is beginning
to prove that among its fast-stepping sister museums on the New
York scene, there is a place for one devoted to the arriere-garde.
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Footsteps of Goethe: Paintings and Drawings From German
Collections'' is at the Dahesh Museum, 601 Fifth Ave., at 48th
Street, (212) 759-0606, until Aug. 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
