<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8529 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-INTERNET-TAXES30-COX     06-29 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TAXES30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TAXING INTERNET SALES GAINING FAVOR IN CONGRESS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last month, the U.S. House overwhelmingly approved
a bill to block new taxes on the Internet for at least five years.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of moving smoothly through the Senate as expected,
the tax moratorium bill has stalled, and legislation intended to
help states collect taxes on online transactions is gaining
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sales tax is the backbone of most state budgets and the
foundation for the funding of education, police, fire and
transportation needs in our communities,'' Rep. Spencer Bachus,
R-Ala., said Thursday at a House subcommittee hearing on his bill.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Congress lets states tax out-of-state merchants who reach
customers in cyberspace, ``Internet retailers will continue to
enjoy a tax haven, while brick and mortar retailers will pay higher
and higher taxes to make up for the revenues lost,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many congressional staff members and lobbyists say the the
Bachus bill, and a similar measure in the Senate sponsored by Sen.
Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., probably won't have time to make it all the
way to President Clinton's desk this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the pro-tax bills may be gaining enough momentum to stymie
efforts in the Senate to pass a five-year extension of the current
moratorium on Internet access taxes, as the House did in May.
</P>
<P>
   The moratorium lasts until October 2001, and many lobbyists
expect Congress to put the matter off until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Sales taxes are in force in 45 states, but states cannot force a
company with no in-state store or warehouse to collect taxes. That
means online merchants and catalog companies generally collect
taxes only from in-state customers.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the University of Tennessee has projected that as
electronic commerce grows, states will eventually lose more than
$10 billion annually from untaxed transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-tax forces have been lobbying Congress heavily to
prevent such a loss. They include not only state and local
officials, but traditional retailers who say they are being put at
an unfair competitive disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   A new survey suggests tax policy does tend to shift business
away from Main Street. Fifty-seven percent of home Internet users
said they took sales taxes into consideration when making
purchases, according to a poll by PC Data Online.
</P>
<P>
   However, opponents of taxing online sales say merchants would be
unduly burdened by the maze of arcane rules in thousands of tax
jurisdictions coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   Sales tax advocates respond by saying states should be given the
time and encouragement to created simple and uniform tax policies.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bachus and Dorgan want Congress to help states form
compacts with common tax regimes. While state and local governments
impose sales taxes, Congress would have to give its blessing to
joint tax collection plans.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's hearing of the House Judiciary subcommittee on
commercial and administrative law, Bachus said his bill would
``provide a framework for simplification and allow states to
require (tax) collection when the simplification process has been
completed.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics say states will never be able to coordinate their tax
policies well enough to create a single compact, but the National
Governors Association says it needs only a couple of years to
develop a uniform tax system under which shoppers would pay the
same taxes, whether buying in stores, by mail or on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   e-Fairness Coalition, www.e-fairness.org
</P>
<P>
   Internet Tax Fairness Coalition, www.nettaxfairness.org
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
