<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8531 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY30-COLUMN     06-29 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY30-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: 3rd generation Rotarian fulfils
the American legacy
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Jayne A. McCurry was installed Thursday as
president of the Angelina County Rotary Club, the third generation
of her family to be so honored.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a generation ago such a thing wouldn't have been
possible _ a woman being a member of what was exclusively a male
organization. Best she could have hoped for was president of Rotary
Ann, the woman's auxiliary.
</P>
<P>
   But things change.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I attended installation ceremonies as guests of Elma
Alexander, proud mother of the new Rotary president.
</P>
<P>
   We knew her late husband, Lefty Alexander, president of the
Lufkin Rotary Club in 1973. I remember, too, Mrs. Alexander's
father, Al Cudlipp Sr., one of our leading industrialists, founding
president of Lufkin Rotary some 75 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For Thursday's luncheon meeting, Joe Byrd, himself a retired
industrialist-inventor who is known as Lufkin's ``Mr. Rotary,''
served as master of ceremonies. Joe was a founding member of the
Angelina Rotary, a spin-off of Lufkin Rotary, 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He can tell you most everything Rotary that's ever happened. A
lot of it he told at Thursday's installation.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite part -- and I had all but forgotten it -- was in
1953 when Lefty Alexander brought Western movie star Wild Bill
Elliott to Lufkin.
</P>
<P>
   Wild Bill was here to pick up a horse trailer he had ordered
from Lufkin Trailers. Lefty headed up the trailer plant. Next thing
you knew, Lefty had Wild Bill, all decked out in Western duds and
wearing his six-guns, speaking to the Rotary Club's noon luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   When word got out that Wild Bill was in town, the schools let
out early so that youngsters might catch a glimpse of one of their
film heroes.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if Wild Bill was a Rotarian himself, but he would
have fit right in, straight-shooter that he was, especially with
Rotary's Four-Way Test ``of the things we think, say or do.''
</P>
<P>
   1. Is it the truth?
</P>
<P>
   2. Is it fair to all concerned?
</P>
<P>
   3. Will it build goodwill and better friendships?
</P>
<P>
   4. Will it be beneficial to all concerned?
</P>
<P>
   The Rotary Club serves as a hero figure throughout much of the
world. It's good works, channeled through the Rotary Foundation,
are calculated in hundreds of millions of dollars aiding millions
of needy people each year, feeding the hungry and providing medical
help for the sick.
</P>
<P>
   Civic clubs throughout the country, whether in small towns or
big cities, are doing their share and more, with book drives, blood
drives, organ donor drives and all sorts of worthy causes _ all
driven by a conscientious effort for community improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Al Cudlipp, Lefty Alexander, Jayne McCurry . . . Some things
change, some things stay the same. In the process things get
better.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the American legacy, one generation to the next.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
