<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8540 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-BOAT-ART-50     06-29 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-BOAT-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERRY CARRYING RELIGIOUS REFUGEES CAPSIZES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ An overloaded ferry appears to have sunk in
heavy seas Thursday, and officials said they feared the loss of
nearly 500 people, many of whom were fleeing religion-based
killings in the remote Maluku Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Radio contact was lost after the wooden-hulled ship, the Cahaya
Bahari, reported that it was taking on water in heavy seas at about
1 p.m. The officials said that when rescue efforts were called off
at dark, about five hours later, no trace had been found of the
ship or of any survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The ferry was lost about 40 miles from land on its route from
Halmahera island, where as many as 200 Christian villagers were
killed a week earlier in continuing fighting between Christians and
Muslims. It was heading for Manado, the capital of the neighboring
province of North Sulawesi, about 1,500 miles northeast of the
capital, Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   The ship, which was licensed to carry about 250 passengers, had
492 people aboard, including 290 refugees from the massacre at
Halmahera, said an official with the National Search and Rescue
Agency. He said there were 186 other passengers and 16 crew
members.
</P>
<P>
   Port officials reached by telephone told news agencies that they
believed that the ferry had sunk. ``Of course, we are afraid many
people have died,'' said Ering Musa, a local maritime official.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that several vessels had reached the site
where the ship had apparently gone down, but that their search was
hampered by fog and six-foot waves.
</P>
<P>
   A sprawling archipelago of thousands of islands, Indonesia is
linked by a network of ferries, many of which are poorly maintained
and regularly carry far more than their legal load. Disasters are
common.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the Cahaya Bahari was particularly overloaded because
of the panic caused by the fighting, which has killed more than
2,500 people over the last 18 months and has driven thousands of
people to flee to neighboring provinces.
</P>
<P>
   In Ambon, the capital of the Maluku Islands, people reported
that the latest surge of terror continued Thursday despite a state
of emergency declared on Monday by President Abdurrahman Wahid.
</P>
<P>
   Although running street battles between Muslim and Christian
gangs appeared to have abated, they said, the continuing sounds of
gunfire and bomb blasts and the threat of sniper fire kept people
locked in their homes or in refugee centers.
</P>
<P>
   The French medical aid agency Doctors Without Borders, which has
been a mainstay of relief operations in Ambon, said seven
truckloads of urgent supplies were stranded at the port because it
was too dangerous to transport them. An official with the group,
Philip Havet, said supplies of food, medicine and drinking water
were running out for refugees and hospital patients.
</P>
<P>
   The situation appears especially desperate because elements of
the military, whose task is to restore order, appear to have taken
sides according to their religious affiliations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The state-run press agency Antara reported Thursday that
military armored cars shot volleys of gunfire at the majority
Christian suburb of Batugantung, forcing people to flee their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   At the Maranata Church in a Christian neighborhood, a priest
named Maksianaya said, ``I myself am afraid to go out because there
are still snipers everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the divided city, Malik Selang, an official
at a Muslim emergency center, said the fear of snipers had forced
residents to postpone the removal and burial of a man who had been
killed in an earlier round of shooting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
