<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8546 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN-ART     06-29 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTES TO CLOSE CAMPAIGN FINANCING LOOPHOLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: this story will be updated) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate approved a bipartisan bill Thursday that
would require a growing number of secretive, tax-exempt groups that
raise and spend money on political activities to reveal their
donors and spending.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 92-6, with the only votes against the measure cast
by Republicans. The House endorsed the same bill on Wednesday,
385-39. President Clinton said he would sign the measure as soon as
Congress sent it to him.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters hailed the outcome as a major victory over Senate and
House Republican leaders who had tried to block the measure, but
they acknowledged that the new law might have only limited impact
on the remaining four months of this campaign cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not pretending we don't have other loopholes to close, but
those groups that have found this an easy, painless way to go on
the attack are now going to have to scramble to figure out
different ways,'' said Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., one of the
bill's leading sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the shadowy groups formed under Section 527 of the
Internal Revenue Code will probably reorganize to avoid the new
disclosure requirements, tax lawyers said. And many donors may rush
big contributions to the groups, hoping to slip them in under the
wire before the new law takes effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the phones are ringing over on K Street to get their
money in before the 527's are eliminated,'' said Rep. Michael
Castle, R-Del., who supports the bill, referring to Washington's
center of high-powered lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, who heads the Senate
Republican re-election campaign and voted no Thursday, played down
the measure's significance, calling it a ``relatively benign
bill.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell urged fellow Republicans to vote yes, even though he
said the bill was a constitutional infringement on free speech,
``to insulate them against absurd charges that they are in favor of
secret campaign contributions or Chinese money or Mafia money.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who championed the Senate bill and
forced Thursday's vote by threatening to single-handedly bottle up
the chamber, said that whatever fallback positions the Section 527
groups take would be less beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill will not solve what is wrong with our campaign
finance system,'' McCain said. ``But it will give the public
information regarding one especially pernicious weapon used in
modern campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   A spectrum of political players, including conservative groups
aligned with Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the House majority whip;
liberal interest groups; and wealthy individuals, have created
Section 527 committees.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations use donations for polling, television and
radio advertising, phone banks and direct-mail appeals, but are not
subject to federal filing or reporting rules so long as they do not
advocate a candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
