<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, June 30, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Brighter weather will begin across the Northeast on Friday.
While high pressure remains over the Ohio Valley, a drier air flow
will become established over southern New England and the
Mid-Atlantic states. Residual clouds and light showers will persist
across northern New England.
</P>
<P>
   The boundary between an expanding area of pleasant early summer
weather and sultry conditions will stretch from the Southeast coast
to Texas. Cloudy skies will attend this front and thundershowers
will occur, mainly in the humid air mass.
</P>
<P>
   Hot air building over the Rockies will spread into the western
Plains. Along the advancing edge of warmer air, morning
thunderstorms will occur in parts of the Mississippi Valley. The
Northwest will turn cooler with higher humidity and clouds.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: RISK OF FIRE
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters battling the blaze near the nuclear waste
reservation in Hanford, Wash., will receive help from a change in
the weather Friday. The 100-degree temperatures that have recently
fanned the flames will drop into the '80s in much of interior
Washington as cooler air arrives from the Pacific. With the jet
stream's retreat into Canada, the Northwest often turns quite dry
in the summer, making the area a favored location for wildfires.
This is especially true east of the Cascades, where monthly summer
rainfall is often much less than summer rainfall in the East.
</P>
</TEXT>
