<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8552 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBESITY-BRAIN-NYTR &LR;      06-29 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBESITY-BRAIN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF FLORIDA STUDY LINKS OBESITY TO BRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Texas)   By TIM LOCKETTE   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Can't seem to lose those extra pounds? The
problem may be all in your head, according to one University of
Florida researcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``In normal subjects, the brain reacts to food intake in about
10 minutes,'' said Yijun Liu, a psychiatrist and associate
professor at the University of Florida's College of Medicine. ``In
obese people, the same reaction takes about 14 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Liu and three researchers from the University of Texas have been
using magnetic resonance imaging to study the human brain and its
reaction to food consumption. They found that the brains of obese
people work differently than the brains of thin people. Part of
their work appeared Thursday in the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   In the study featured in Nature, 18 volunteers fasted for 12
hours and were then subjected to a 48-minute brain scan. Ten
minutes into the scan, each subject was fed a sugar-and-water
solution.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that brain activity peaked around 10
minutes after each subject swallowed the solution. The peaks
corresponded with increased levels of glucose in each subject's
blood. The researchers believe that the peaks constitute the
``satiety signal'' that tells people when they've had enough to
eat.
</P>
<P>
   But in an earlier study, Liu and his colleagues found that the
brains of obese people take an average of 14 minutes to respond to
food intake. Four extra minutes might not seem like much, Liu said,
but the delay shows that in the brains of obese people, the
reaction to food intake is significantly diminished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can see that in obese subjects, there is some sort of
abnormal function,'' Liu said.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, according to Liu, lies in the hypothalamus, the
part of the brain that regulates body heat and other bodily
functions. When the subjects' brains responded to the intake of
food, Liu said, most of the changes occurred in the hypothalamus _
leading the researchers to believe that the hypothalamus regulates
the levels of glucose in the blood. In obese subjects, the
hypothalamus didn't respond as promptly or as strongly as in
thinner people.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean you can blame those few extra pounds on a
faulty hypothalamus. According to Liu, the delayed reaction may be
a result of obesity, rather than its cause.
</P>
<P>
   Liu intends to use MRI technology in the future to study the
brains of people who suffer from obsessive-compulsive disorder. He
said he came up with the idea of studying the brain's reaction to
food shortly after he came to the United States from Nanjing
University in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is a very wealthy country, and there is a very large
percentage of heavy people here,'' he said. ``This is a very hot
area for research.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sun in Gainesville, Fla, is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
