<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-DIVERSITY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEACHERS SEEK MORE MINORITY COLLEAGUES
 &HT;    620&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The gap between the number of minority teachers and
the number of minority students in the public schools is still
growing, officials of the National Education Association reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   They called for more use of new programs that have had some
success in attracting and keeping minorities as part of the current
drive to hire 2 million new teachers in this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unlikely that in the near future, the proportion of
minority teachers will come anywhere near the growing number of
minority students,'' said Segun Eubanks, the NEA's senior
professional associate for teaching and learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, due to the success of some of the recent
efforts at recruiting and retention, the decline in minority
teachers seems to have been stemmed, and has stabilized,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Government records analyzed by the NEA, which includes more than
half of the nation's public school teachers, show that all but 13.5
percent of public school teachers in 1991 and all but 9.3 percent
in 1996 were white. In 1996, about 4 percent of teachers of all
races were of Hispanic origin.
</P>
<P>
   Widely quoted projections indicate that before the end of this
decade, 40 percent of all students, but only 5 percent of the
teachers, will be minorities. ``The student projections are holding
up,'' said Eubanks, an African American.
</P>
<P>
   But limited studies indicate that today minorities among
teachers are slightly higher than projected, about 13 percent. He
said he expects that figure to stay steady or rise by a few
percentage points in the decade ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Though its membership reflects the heavily white nature of the
teaching work force, the NEA has long supported outreach to
minorities. Traditionally, 20 percent of the officers and board of
the association are non-Hispanic whites.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of NEA members from across the country attended two
days of workshops here Wednesday and Thursday to discuss various
methods of minority outreach prior to the NEA's annual convention,
known as the ``representative assembly,'' which opens Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The association deplores the current trend'' toward fewer
minority teachers, said NEA President Bob Chase. ``Our policies,
programs and varied activities encourage the development of a
teaching force that reflects the nation's population and changing
demographics. ``
</P>
<P>
   Seven out of 10 school superintendents, and nearly eight out of
10 superintendents in large urban districts, said in surveys this
year that they want to hire more teachers from diverse racial and
ethnic backgrounds because their student bodies are becoming more
diverse.
</P>
<P>
   But too few follow through effectively, according to Chase.
</P>
<P>
   A new edition issued this year of a national NEA directory lists
more than 100 examples of programs sponsored by nonprofit,
educational, business, community or other groups who claimed
success in increasing the number of minority teachers in their city
or region.
</P>
<P>
   Most followed one or more of these strategies:
</P>
<P>
   _ Using extra-curricular efforts like Future Educators of
America or curricular innovations like teaching career academies to
interest middle school and high school students in teaching.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stepping up financial aid for potential teachers, especially
those who already work as teaching aides or want to leave the
military and other professions, and conducting more recruiting
efforts in minority communities and schools of education.
</P>
<P>
   _ Offering extra help, such as courses in test-taking skills or
tutoring, to minorities who say they intend to teach.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mentoring new teachers so they won't join the one-fifth of
teachers of all races who leave the profession within their first
two years of teach.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But many teachers at the workshops suggested more down-to-earth
methods, such as increasing the salary and prestige of teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the young people get an education, and have a skill that
is marketable, they are going to go where the money is,'' said
Malcolm Bailey, a Sioux who taught art for 29 years in Billings,
Mont., and chairs the NEA's minority affairs committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just hope that love of their reservation or neighborhood or
wherever brings them back after they've made big bucks, because we
need role models, particularly for minority males,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those programs all sound fine and good, but if our college
graduates have an opportunity to obtain jobs in other fields that
are much more lucrative, how will we convince them to go into
teaching?'' asked a Filipina, Carmen Periquet of Waukesha, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son is just out of college, and he laughs at me, because he
makes $57,000, more than I do after nearly three decades of
teaching,'' said Rose Marie Gonzalez, a bilingual teacher in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make more from my pension as a county employee than my wife
does as a full-time teacher,'' said her husband Mauro. He recently
donated his computer to her first-grade classroom, because the
district didn't replace one stolen in a break-in.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   National Education Association: www.nea.org
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting New Teachers: www.rnt.org
</P>
<P>
   Recruitment and retention of minority teachers:
www.nea.org/recruit/minority
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison can be reached by e-mail at AndyM(at)Coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
