<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-FUNDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WAXMAN AND COBURN DEFEND PLAN TO CUT S.F. AIDS FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reps. Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., and Tom Coburn,
R-Okla., on Thursday defended their plan to cut San Francisco's
share of federal AIDS funding by 25 percent over five years, saying
the city has been ``overcompensated.''
</P>
<P>
   Waxman said bipartisan legislation they introduced Thursday
``slowly gets rid of marked discrepancies'' in AIDS funding to 51
cities ravaged by the epidemic, Waxman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some areas, San Francisco particularly, that will
not be able to maintain the same level of funding that they have
today,'' Waxman told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The AIDS program is named after Ryan White, a teenager from
Kokomo, Ind., and a hemophiliac who died of AIDS in 1990 after
contracting the disease through a blood transfusion. The program
pays for care and drugs for people with HIV and AIDS who don't have
private insurance but aren't poor or sick enough to receive
Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn said per capita Ryan White funding is nearly double in
San Francisco compared to other cities. He cited statistics from
the General Accounting Office, the research arm of Congress,
showing Ryan White funding for each AIDS case in San Francisco last
year was $5,958, compared to $2,509 in San Antonio, $2,892 in
Houston, $3,068 in Los Angeles and $3,090 in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody else feels that (San Francisco) is
overcompensated,'' Coburn said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Anna Eshoo, D-Calif., who represents a Northern California
district, vowed to fight the cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should know better than to be slicing up a community where
there is great need,'' Eshoo said.
</P>
<P>
   Waxman, the original sponsor of the Ryan White Care Act in 1991,
said lawmakers in both the House and Senate recognize
``inequities'' in the funding formula and want to reduce San
Francisco's share.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Waxman-Coburn plan, San Francisco's share of the AIDS
money couldn't drop below 75 percent of its current level, with
annual cuts of 2 percent, 2.3 percent, 4.6 percent, 6.9 percent and
9.2 percent. The House Commerce Committee, which oversees the Ryan
White care program, has scheduled a July 11th hearing on the plan.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate-passed version of the Ryan White program is less tough
on San Francisco and would freeze San Francisco's share of the
money at no less than 98 percent of the current $35.3 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Once the House passes its version of the Ryan White program, the
House and Senate bills will go to a joint House-Senate conference
committee where negotiators will come up with a compromise. The
House bill would decrease San Francisco's current share of Ryan
White money by $5 million over five years, compared to $1.7 million
for the Senate version, according to staffers for Rep. Nancy
Pelosi, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   When the federal program began in 1991, San Francisco's share of
the money was relatively large because the funding formula was
based on the density of AIDS cases in a city as well as its
cumulative number of AIDS cases, both living and dead. When
Congress in 1996 changed the formula to be based on the estimated
number of people living with AIDS in a city, San Francisco's share
would have been diminished because many people with AIDS had
already died. But Congress decided to limit any cuts to San
Francisco to avoid harming existing AIDS programs there.
</P>
<P>
   When lawmakers set about to update the five-year Ryan White
legislation this year, health officials in Los Angeles and other
cities complained that San Francisco was getting an unfair share.
The Waxman-Coburn bill would remove that special provision.
</P>
<P>
   Waxman and Coburn also said their bill focuses on reaching HIV
positive people who are not now receiving help under the Ryan White
program. By 2007, Ryan White money would be distributed to cities
based on the number of people with HIV, instead of the number of
people with AIDS, as is now the case.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn said the HIV is now spreading fastest among minority
women and children, adding that formula changes are needed ``to
make sure the dollars go where the disease is.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Waxman: ``What was once seen as a disease of gay white men
or of injection drug users is more than ever a terrible threat to
our communities of color, to women and adolescents, in short to all
of us.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
