<HEADER>
A8572 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-GASOLINE-HNS &LR;      06-29 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-GASOLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE SAYS GAS PRICES PROVE NEED FOR PUBLIC TRANSIT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Vice President Al Gore sought Thursday to convert
public ire about high gasoline prices into support for an ambitious
10-year $25 billion package of federal tax breaks to encourage
cities to expand their public transit systems.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the presumptive Democratic presidential nominee, portrayed
his proposal as an effort to offer Americans new choices for
commuting, rather than a federally mandated bid to oust commuters
from their cars and into crowded rail cars or urban buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be realistic: People want to drive their own cars and
they should have the right always to drive their own cars,'' Gore
told several hundred people gathered on a terrace of Chicago's Navy
Pier. ``Don't tell me that there's a great groundswell to get rid
of cars and push people into mass transit whether they want it or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore added: ``You deserve the independence to get in your car
and drive anywhere you want to go on your own schedule without
having to empty your wallet at every filling station. You should
also have the choice _ if you want it _ to park your car at the
light rail and be moved swiftly into the newly thriving downtown
without having to worry about gridlock or a parking lot or rush
hour traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore dubbed it an ``old, timid way of thinking'' for Americans
to believe that enhancing environmental protection means ``that to
help the earth you have to give up your own car for a crowded
subway car or turn down your air conditioning or swelter indoors.''
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices in the Midwest are the highest in the lower 48
states, nation,
</P>
<P>
   Gore tried to focus Midwest consumers' ire over skyrocketing
gasoline prices at large oil companies rather that Clinton-Gore
administration policies. He called for a Federal Trade Commission
inquiry into gasoline pricing to conduct public hearings to enable
Americans to hear first hand the explanations of oil executives for
the $2 a gallon cost of the reformulated low-pollution gasoline
that was required in 15 Midwestern urban areas including Chicago
beginning June 1.
</P>
<P>
   FTC spokesman Mitchell Katz said the FTC was conducting a
private investigation and would reports its results to Congress by
the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on here?'' Gore wondered aloud after citing
soaring profits for oil companies at the outset of this year
despite higher costs for crude oil. The vice president called
gasoline prices ``no less than outrageous,'' adding that the
federal government's quasi-independent FTC ought to ``pursue that
investigation vigorously.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said oil companies already are reducing the costs of
gasoline in the hard-hit Midwest now that the industry is faced
with the onslaught of the FTC's subpoena powers, its investigative
staff and the agency's ability to shine the public spotlight into
corporate decision-making at the highest level.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his proposal would encourage urban centers to convert
bus fleets to more energy efficient, cleaner engines; create new
light rail systems linking cities to suburbs; and encourage
creation of safe residential and retail communities adjacent to
transit stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there nothing as efficient as a steel wheel on a steel
rail,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Once consumers have alternative ways to commute to work, it will
reduce the oil industry's stranglehold on American commuters, Gore
said. With more rail links available, if ``big oil tries to take
advantage of whatever ability they have to manipulate the prices
and a lot of people say, `I'm not driving this week, I'm going to
make another choice,' then you'll see them start feeling the
pressure from consumers in a new way and they won't be as able to
get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address : stewart &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
