<HEADER>
A8574 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-IVOR-LOUIS-ARMSTRONG-     06-29 1404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-LOUIS-ARMSTRONG-CENTENNIAL-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CENTENNIAL FOR SATCHMO 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos of jazz musician Louis Armstrong. 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Some parties take a whole year to do them justice.
 &HT;    Louis ``Satchmo'' Armstrong, jazz trumpeter, singer and the man
Bing Crosby called ``the beginning and the end of music in
America,'' would have been 100 years old in August 2001. Or so it
is believed, at any rate, although this _ like many other aspects
of his life _ is in some dispute.
 &HT;    What is not contested is that Armstrong, who died on July 7,
1971, at his home in Queens, N.Y., was the most popular figure in
the history of jazz. The Los Angeles Times ran a memorial cartoon
depicting him in heaven, facing the angel Gabriel in a trumpet
contest _ and winning.
 &HT;    For such a larger-than-life figure, no ordinary birthday party
would suffice. A full year early, the festivities have already
begun, with the first glass being hoisted in New Orleans, city of
Armstrong's birth, and one with which he had a lifelong love-hate
relationship.
 &HT;    ``He had very ambivalent feelings about New Orleans,'' admits
Sean Cummings, owner of the city's chic International House hotel.
``He came back here only a very few times. But any black man who
grew up in the notorious Storyville district of this city would
have had difficulties with the past. We love him, and this will be
the biggest party we've ever thrown.''
 &HT;    It begins in the hotel's high-ceilinged lobby with a display by
veteran photographer Herman Leonard, who met Armstrong in Paris in
1950 and has recently published his photographs of Armstrong and
other jazz legends in a beautiful black-and-white coffee table
book, ``Jazz Memories,'' published in France.
 &HT;    ``Over 20 years I never saw him with a sober look on his face,''
Leonard recalls. ``He was always affable. He was always so
ebullient, an extraordinary human being.''
 &HT;    Further in the future, in fall 2002 the Louis Armstrong House
and Archives, housed in the Rosenthal Library on the campus of
Queens College in Flushing, N.Y., will open Armstrong's old home at
34-56 107th Street, where he lived with his fourth wife, Lucille,
from l943 until his death.
 &HT;    The house, a National Historic Landmark, has been completely
refurbished.
 &HT;    ``Not an ashtray has been moved,'' says archives director
Michael Cogswell. ``Nobody has lived there since the Armstrongs. It
will be like going to visit Louis and Lucille.''
 &HT;    Internet travelers can get a preview peek by logging onto
www.satchmo.com.
 &HT;    Last year 650 reels of tape-recorded conversations were made
available for the first time, capturing Armstrong and his cronies
in late-night, after-the-show bull sessions at home in Queens.
 &HT;    ``Anyone can listen to them,'' Cogswell says. ``You don't have
to be a professor or writing a book.''
 &HT;    But you do need a tolerance for the scatological. Armstrong had
an earthy sense of humor, and didn't hesitate to express it in
private _ as Cogswell realized when First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton visited the archives in 1998 and asked to hear some of the
recordings.
 &HT;    ``We wanted to play them for her,'' he recalls, ``but we had the
damnedest time finding clean ones.''
 &HT;    Armstrong comes across as a cheerful, down-to-earth man,
regardless of who he was with. On the tapes, he recalls a visit
with Princess Margaret, the Duke of Kent and other members of the
British royal family _ ``the royalty cats,'' he calls them.
 &HT;    ``They come over to Paris to catch us when we was at the Olympic
Theater,'' the musician says on the recording, ``and after the show
they wanted to take me to the big restaurants. I say, `I was just
on my way to scarf, man.'''
 &HT;    Dining with royalty was just another meal for Armstrong, who had
grown up in New Orleans surrounded by run-down tenements, brothels,
honkytonks, dance halls and churches. He was raised in a household
of women headed by his mother, his father having walked out on the
family when Armstrong was a baby, and got into his fair share of
trouble.
 &HT;    Music was his salvation, however. He sang for tips with three
other kids on the street corners of Storyville until a brush with
the law got him shipped off to the Colored Waifs Home. It might
have been a dead end, but there the young boy encountered
instrumental music and got his hands on his first trumpet. The rest
is literally history.
 &HT;    I met Armstrong only once, not long before his death. It was in
l969, on the set of the movie ``Hello Dolly'' at the Twentieth
Century Fox studios in Los Angeles.
 &HT;    As a foreign correspondent for the London Daily Express, I had
gone to interview a young British actor named Michael Crawford, who
was over the moon at having landed a key role in a lavish Hollywood
musical. Needless to say, he was still decades away from his
definitive performance as Broadway's ``Phantom of the Opera.''
 &HT;    Gene Kelly, as always preternaturally cheerful no matter how
frantic things got on the set, was directing the biggest scene in
the movie, the one in which Dolly Levi (Barbra Streisand), in a
dazzling outfit, marches into a nightclub as Armstrong leads
everyone in the movie's title song, his signature tune, ``Hello
Dolly.''
 &HT;    Afterward I was chatting with Crawford when, much to our
delight, Armstrong ambled over and introduced himself _ as if he
needed to _ and stopped to talk.
 &HT;    We discussed London, a city he said he had loved since his first
visit, way back in l932. He was given a new trumpet, which he used
onstage at the London Palladium. The critics raved and the
audiences cheered.
 &HT;    Later, however, a columnist for a London newspaper published a
particularly vicious, virulently racist attack on the great
musician, using terms that today would not be tolerated anywhere.
Nevertheless, Armstrong said, he could never wait to return to the
British capital, which he had grown to love almost as much as he
loved Paris.
 &HT;    I gave him my business card, and later he sent me a photo of
himself _ one which was somewhat unusual, to say the least. It
depicted Armstrong, pants over ankles, sitting on a toilet over the
slogan, ``Leave it all behind.''
 &HT;    It was his calling card _ a commercial, I later learned, for a
famous laxative to which he was devoted.
 &HT;    Alas, I lost track of that picture, which singer Tony Bennett
told me Armstrong had also passed out to members of the Royal
Family at a black-tie dinner following a royal command performance
in London.
 &HT;    ``That's Louis,'' someone at the studio told me. ``He's a
no-B.S. guy.''
 &HT;    He would have been equally frank, I was told, in discussing his
sex life or his firm belief in the salutary effects of marijuana.
 &HT;    Now, though he has been dead for almost three decades, and
though countless biographies have exhaustively documented his life,
there are those 650 reels of candid tape recordings to preserve his
conversational style.
 &HT;    In the end, however, the best way to get to know Louis Armstrong
is through his music, hundreds of recordings which constitute a
virtual panoramic history of jazz in the 20th century.
 &HT;    Through them emerges an American legend who will be with us well
into the next millennium. 
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood
Stars and other features. &QL; 
