<SLUG> BC-TREK-MAJANDRA-DELFINO-IN-ROSWELL-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALIEN RESURRECTION: MAJANDRA DELFINO CELEBRATES THE RETURN OF
`ROSWELL' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Majandra
Delfino with Brendan Fehr in a scene from ``Roswell.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    They said that ``Roswell'' was hanging by a thread, that the
powers that be at the WB network had the show ``on the bubble''
between renewal and cancellation.
 &HT;    Millions of fans worried, but somehow _ call it intuition, gut
instinct or simply wishful thinking _ Majandra Delfino wasn't one
of them. The actress, who stars in the show, says she wasn't all
that surprised when creator/producer/writer Jason Katims called
with the news that the network had renewed ``Roswell'' for a second
season.
 &HT;    ``I hoped. I knew,'' says Delfino, who plays Maria DeLuca on the
low-rated but critically lauded sci-fi series. ``I felt the WB was
saying, `Yeah, it might not' just to get us scared, to motivate us.
 &HT;    ``I just felt that we did so well once they changed our night,''
she adds, speaking of the show's shift from Wednesdays to Mondays.
``I thought, `How could they not pick us up?'
 &HT;    ``I was celebrating my best friend's birthday in Miami, and
Jason Katims called me from Jamaica to tell me the news. I was
like, `Oh, OK, so my suspicions were right.'''
 &HT;    Suspicions are the lifeblood of ``Roswell,'' of course. Who are
the benevolent aliens? Who are the rotten ones? Can our hero aliens
_ Max (Jason Behr), Isabel (Katherine Heigl) and Michael (Brendan
Fehr), who grew up on Earth in human form _ trust their human pals
Maria and Alex (Colin Hanks) to keep their secret?
 &HT;    Oh, and is shifty Sheriff Valenti (William Sadler) really a good
guy now?
 &HT;    As the first season unfolded, Maria evolved from a jittery ditz
into a formidable young woman. She stood up to her mother, devised
impromptu action plans to help her alien friends dodge the FBI and
threw herself hard into a volatile relationship with the often
emotionally remote Michael.
 &HT;    ``I liked that they explored all of that and didn't just make
her the dumb blond,'' Delfino says by cellular telephone,
breathless as she wends her way across Los Angeles to a dentist
appointment. ``They made Maria a free spirit with a brain.''
 &HT;    No dumb bunny herself, Delfino _ who plays piano, writes music
and is something of a mathematics wiz _ spent part of her
``Roswell'' hiatus in Cincinnati, acting in director Steven
Soderbergh's buzzed-about drama, ``Traffic.'' She plays a
drug-abusing high-schooler who's a bad influence on Michael
Douglas' daughter.
 &HT;    In only a couple of weeks, however, Delfino will be back on the
``Roswell'' set. The WB greenlit 13 new episodes, and the network
will decide whether or not to produce another nine soon after the
first few shows air.
 &HT;    Delfino reveals that season two will continue the sci-fi
emphasis that dominated last year's latter episodes. And, despite
unmistakable intimations that Isabel and Michael were meant to be
together, the actress believes fans will see more of Maria and
Michael.
 &HT;    ``Listen, that's all my fan mail is about,'' the actress says of
the fiery Maria-Michael relationship, which contrasts sharply with
the lovey-dovey, Romeo-and-Juliet bond between Liz and Max.
``Everyone was dying because Michael kissed Isabel. They were so
afraid that meant Michael and Isabel had to be together.
 &HT;    ``It was all, `Let's please keep Maria and Michael together,'''
she says, laughing. ``As if I write the stories. So there are some
really diehard fans of Michael and Maria.
 &HT;    ``But I'm sure they won't be separating us,'' she concludes.
``The fans need to relax.''
 &HT;    Delfino, however, can't relax. As she drives past a parking-lot
attendant and hurries into her dentist's office, the 19-year-old
can only marvel at her good fortune.
 &HT;    Beyond ``Roswell'' and ``Traffic,'' she has the independent
feature ``Learning Curve,'' which currently is navigating the
film-festival circuit in search of a distributor. Later this year,
she'll send up Neve Campbell and Jennifer Love Hewitt in the horror
spoof ``I Know What You Screamed Last Summer.''
 &HT;    ``My whole acting career _ the whole three years of it _ I've
never been out of work,'' Delfino says, cracking up. ``And the work
I've done I've been so happy with. I thought `Roswell' was such a
great thing _ and then I booked a Steven Soderbergh film on my time
off. I couldn't believe it _ I didn't do some cheesy teen movie,
but a quality, high-budget film where you read the script and go,
`Damn.'
 &HT;    ``It's a little too much,'' she says. ``It's all happening too
quickly. Pretty soon I'm expecting to get married and have kids!'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Roswell,'' consult the WB
network Web site at www.thewb.com. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
