<HEADER>
A8579 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT &LR;      06-29 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chicken Run
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of Julia Sawalha, Mel Gibson, Miranda
Richardson, Benjamin Whitrow, Tony Haygarth, Phil Daniels
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Peter Lord and Nick Park
</P>
<P>
   G 86 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Times are desperate for several dozen English hens at the Tweedy
farm. ``We lay day in and day out, and when we don't lay enough,
they kill us,'' one of them explains. Farmer Tweedy swings the
hatchet, but policy is set by his production-obsessed wife, who
runs the barnyard like a concentration camp, with barbed wire along
the fences and the number 17, as in Stalag 17, painted on one of
the barrackslike henhouses.
</P>
<P>
   The sole holiday is a stretch of solitary confinement in a coal
bin. If only the hens could escape. Led by the determined Ginger
(Sawalha), they dig and drill with an eggbeater. That gets them
nowhere. ``We haven't tried not trying to escape; that might
work,'' a hen suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger dreams of an air route, whether by wing, slingshot or
catapult. Then, literally out of the blue, comes Rocky, an actual
flying rooster, or so it would appear. Rocky (Gibson) says he is a
professionial. He is also an American, which draws some skepticism.
``Overpaid, oversexed and over here,'' one hen comments.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Ginger hails him as their one last hope and
persuades him to teach the hens to fly. Calisthenics ensue, but
early flight tests prove unpromising. Meanwhile, Mrs. Tweedy has
hit on a better way to make money: Grind up the birds for chicken
potpies.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tweedy puts together a ghastly portable potpie maker. The
hens' feed is increased, adding avoirdupois and taxing already
questionable aerodynamics. Would this have stopped the Wright
Brothers?
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ A hen's head is removed with a quiet chop, heard but
not seen. The pie-making machine graphically dismembers and
squashes all ingredients, and though no hens are caught in the
thing, the process could be mildly unsettling to very small
children. Otherwise the mishaps are plainly cartoon slapstick.
</P>
<P>
   SEX _ All the hens volunteer to share their nests with Rocky.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ None.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE _ In a process called Claymation, the figures are
modeled out of latex, not drawn. Generally, this gives them a more
lifelike appearance and movement.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-6 _ Park, a British animator, is known for his Wallace
and Gromit films, which are a good deal grittier than most animated
movies. Here, any lasting harm is carefully avoided, but the mood
is still a little darker than Disney.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 7 AND UP _ Fine.
</P>
<P>
   Me, Myself and Irene
</P>
<P>
   Jim Carrey, Renee Zellweger, Anthony Anderson, Mongo Brownlee,
Jerod Mixon, Michael Bowman, Robert Forster
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bobby Farrelly and Peter Farrelly
</P>
<P>
   R 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Behind those reflector sunglasses, Charlie Baileygates (Carrey),
a Rhode Island State Police motorcycle officer, looks like a
speeder's worst nightmare. But on patrol and especially at home,
Charlie is milquetoast. ``I get the feeling the whole town is
laughing at me,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The victim of a truly spectacular marital disaster, Charlie is
the father of three black sons who were but babes in the backyard
wading pool when their mother, a genius and Mensa chapter head,
took off with their biological father. Left to raise the children,
Charlie has three big, very bright and very obscene teen-agers on
his hands. ``A 1430 on the SATs? Must have an aneurysm,'' says
Shonte Jr. (Mixon).
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor regularly lets his dog defecate on Charlie's lawn.
While he is on the beat, a little girl screams him into submission.
But then something snaps. Suddenly, Charlie has another
personality, named Hank. As aggressive as Charlie is passive, Hank
picks fights with little children and anybody else. Hank himself,
not his dog, defecates on his neighbor's lawn. And those sons had
better get in line or Dad will have to ``bust a cap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Advanced hallucinatory schizophrenia,'' goes the diagnosis,
enlivened by ``involuntarily narcissistic rage.'' It's all very
confusing to Irene (Zellweger), the attractive golf course
groundskeeper who has befriended Charlie and might take up with him
romantically if the belligerent Hank didn't keep assaulting people.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ Some men are shot. So is a cow, which refuses to die
and then is strangled by Charlie, who thinks he's doing the animal
a good turn.
</P>
<P>
   SEX _ An oversized sex appliance plays a prominent role, as does
a chicken.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ A deep supply of the strongest obscenities and
expressions relating to the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE _ To attract the target audience (teen and young adult,
mostly male), the Farrelly brothers' movies (``There's Something
About Mary'') make all possible use of sexual crudity and bodily
fluids from wherever they may emanate. Deal with it _ or don't.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 12 _ Some will howl in protest, but no.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12-14 _ Are they ready for the Farrellys?
</P>
<P>
   AGES 15 AND UP _ Don't be silly.
</P>
<P>
   Titan A.E.
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of Matt Damon, Bill Pullman, John Leguizamo,
Nathan Lane, Janeane Garofalo, Drew Barrymore
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Don Bluth and Gary Goldman
</P>
<P>
   PG 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In the 31st century our trusty little planet has been blown up
by an electrostatic force called the Drej, and the few survivors
are hiding out on drifter colonies sailing around the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Out on Salvage Station Tau 14, the short-order cooks are
roaches, and a rocket jockey named Korso (Pullman) is on the
lookout for a 20-something slacker named Cale (Damon). Back when
Earth was destroyed, Cale's father, a professor, gave the boy a
ring that reveals the whereabouts of the Titan A.E. (``after
Earth''), a giant space station that contains all the basics to
help humans get going again on another planet.
</P>
<P>
   The Titan is a hot item. ``Position to destroy,'' wheezes a
Drej, which talks like a disconnected air hose. Korso wants the
Earth capsule to preserve the species, or so he says. Cale still
resents his father for leaving him at the time of the attack (duty
called), but overcomes some attitude problems to contribute plenty
of ``Star Wars''-style heroics. A new planet is found. They call it
Bob.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ Plenty of space pyrotechnics and annihilation,
usually viewed at a distance.
</P>
<P>
   SEX _ Cale takes to a good-looking fellow drifter named Akima
(Barrymore). No time at the moment, but maybe later.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ None.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-6 _ This is no simple, sunny animation for the littlest
ones. The theme and characters are too intense and complicated, and
some situations could be upsetting.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 7-10 _ Probably the best age for this film. The space war
razzle-dazzle will appeal, and youngsters won't be turned off by
simplistic characters who, for all the movie's visual
accomplishments, act and talk as if they belong in Saturday morning
cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11 AND UP _ Generally too sophisticated (the viewers, that
is).
</P>
</TEXT>
