   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   NOPOKER _ North Charleston, S.C. -Here on the outer fringe of
Charleston County, operators and players are preparing for midnight
Friday's shutdown of the $3 billion video gambling industry. This
stretch of highway dotted by video poker parlors illustrates what's
happening all over South Carolina - the industry's rapid rise and
even more rapid demise. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LABOR _ AFL-CIO President John Sweeney leads a town hall meeting
on George Bush's labor record in Philadelphia June 29. Rank and
file union members, who according to polls are split between Bush
and Al Gore, talk about who they will support in November.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS-DIVERSITY _ CHICAGO _ Teachers from across the country
discuss what to do about the failure of efforts over the past six
years by the National Education Association and others to halt the
decline of minorities and men in the teaching profession. The
two-day conference on race and gender precedes the NEA convention.
(Mollison, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category national, subcategory Education.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIAN-TRIAL30 _ WACO, Texas _ Davidian trial testimony
expected to shift soon to government defense. Developing.
(Witherspoon, Waco Tribune-Herald). 30.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-PRI _ Gov. George W. Bush touts his good relationship with
Mexican officials as proof of his international abilities. But the
governor's in is with officials from the ruling PRI party, which is
facing serious election challenges this year. What happens to Bush
if the PRI loses the July 2 election? (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CHARACTER _ Forget where candidates stand on a given issue. The
grueling horserace that is the presidential election comes down to
an assessment of a candidate's character. How would Bush or Gore
respond to the pressure-cooker job of president given what we know
of them now? Both are undergoing their own tests: Bush with his
response to the death penalty issue and Gore with his response to
the call for an independent counsel to investigate his fundraising.
How are both responding to their tests? What does it tell us about
the candidates? (Heath, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SECRETMONEY _ Congress sent President Clinton legislation
forcing secretive groups to say who is paying for campaign-style TV
ads, radio spots and phone calls that are being used to influence
elections across the country. The legislation would affect groups
that have seized on a once-obscure section of the tax code to
conduct unlimited political activity without reporting anything
about themselves to the public. It would require these newly
popular, tax-exempt groups to report most donors and spending to
the Internal Revenue Service. (Heath, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   NADER _ WASHINGTON _ Ralph Nader almost singlehandedly created
consumer advocacy. Now, he's bringing his reformist nature to the
political arena with a campaign for president as the Green Party
nominee. Although quixotic, Nader's campaign could cause some
problems for Vice President Al Gore, the likely Democratic nominee
and a longtime favorite of environmentalists. (Shepard, Cox News
Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Pegged to breakfast meeting with political reporters
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGIOUS-VISAS _ WASHINGTON _ The House immigration
subcommittee holds a hearing on the Immigration and Naturalization
Service's religious worker visa programs. (Garcia, Cox News
Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   WAN location Atlanta, category National, subcategory U.S.
Government.
</P>
<P>
   MAGLEV-RAIL _ ATLANTA _ Atlanta's magnetic levitation rail
project application will be postmarked and headed for Washington by
midnight tonight. The application will include the price tag for
the high tech railway _ and an explanation of how the metro region
will pay its share, about one-third of the total cost. The ARc will
learn later this summer if Atlanta was selected for the $1 billion
grant to build the project. (Simmons, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZILL _ State attorney releases interviews and other evidence
it's reviewed in the slaying of teacher Barry Grunow by his
student, Nate Brazill. Hoping it will include Brazill's handwritten
confession. (Spencer-Wendel, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   McCRAY _ Expecting state attorney to not charge Brazill's
surrogate grandfather with leaving handgun where Brazill could get
it and steal it. This is the gun used to kill Grunow.
(Spencer-Wendel, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
