<P>
   GIRLGAMES _ You hear so much these days about how girls are the
lost demographic when it comes to computers and the Web. That's
true. But Laura Groppe, founder of Girl Games _ a company that aims
to educate pre-teen and teenaged girls about computers and what
they can offer _ is determined to change that. Using management
skills she learned as a Hollywood producer, Groppe's company is
putting out the software to which girls can relate. One tool,
occasional slumber parties where girls can be girls and have the
fun they want to have. We crash one of these parties to see what
nightgowned girls doing each other's nails, giggling on the phone
and eating popcorn in their sleeping bags has to do with computer
education. (Moore, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
