<HEADER>
A8582 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-COMMISSIONER-RESIGN-H     06-29 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMISSIONER-RESIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     INSURANCE REGULATOR FACED TOUGH CHOICE: RESIGN OR BE
IMPEACHED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Behind the sudden resignation of California
Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush is the central dilemma of
every elected official: how to legally separate politics from
public work.
</P>
<P>
   Where Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat, has become a master of the
so-called ``perpetual campaign,'' Quackenbush utterly failed to
keep the two rivers divided.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush resigned Wednesday, a day before he was expected to
appear before the Assembly Insurance Committee, where he would have
faced, under oath, tough questions. The measured, relentless
committee had uncovered startling evidence that Quackenbush had
ordered his staff to fine a title insurance company $4 million
because he needed that precise amount to buy television and radio
time.
</P>
<P>
   This evidence convinced the Assembly it had no choice but to
impeach the two-term Republican commissioner for abuse of power.
Even members of his own party were eager to call for his
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1994 Northridge earthquake, where numerous insurance
companies were accused of bilking victims and low-balling claims,
Quackenbush began a ``deliberate effort to use those circumstances
to assemble and implement a perpetual political campaign,'' said
Assemblyman Fred Keeley, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than fine the insurance companies tens of millions of
dollars, Quackenbush is accused of coercing them into donating $19
million to nonprofit foundations controlled by his closest aides
and political operatives.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of using the money to help Northridge earthquake
victims, Quackenbush's consultants moved in. They produced
``consumer outreach'' television advertising featuring Quackenbush.
Money was donated to other groups that had nothing to do with
Northridge, like $500,000 to the Sacramento Urban League and
$246,000 to a football camp attended by Quackenbush's children.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers ultimately were appalled that Quackenbush had used the
power of his office to compel the companies he regulated to help
him and his political consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the commissioner was in a unique position to have
those two worlds collide because he was a regulator, and he could
impose fines,'' said Assembly Republican leader Scott Baugh.
</P>
<P>
   Baugh disagreed, however, with the assessment that Quackenbush
had tried to establish a perpetual campaign by directing money to
the nonprofit foundations. Not all of the money, Baugh said, went
to benefit Quackenbush politically, although his GOP political
consultants enriched themselves, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a system set up by a bunch of folks who stood to
profit,'' Baugh said. ``He was ill-served by his advisers and his
consultants, and they walked him down into a trap that he could not
escape from.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Quackenbush admitted mistakes had been made, he denied
any wrongdoing. By Wednesday, however, he was exhausted and still
under pursuit by two legislative committees, Attorney General Bill
Lockyer, the Fair Political Practices Commission, consumer groups,
the media and the Sacramento County district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush's attorney, former federal prosecutor Donald Heller,
heard in a telephone call with Keeley late Tuesday that Quackenbush
was in an untenable position no matter which way he moved: testify
truthfully at a hearing Thursday, and face impeachment. Refuse to
testify, and face impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve hours later, Quackenbush sent a two-line letter to
Secretary of State Bill Jones, now the last Republican in statewide
office, offering his resignation effective July 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly offered nothing in return, except to cancel its
Thursday hearing where a subpoenaed Quackenbush was scheduled to
testify under oath. In previous appearances before the Legislature,
Quackenbush could go from conciliatory to defiant to defeated in a
single sitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this has become such an emotional trauma for him that
he could no longer serve effectively as insurance commissioner,''
Heller said. ``I am satisfied he has done nothing illegal or
criminal or improper in any way. He made mistakes, which he readily
admitted.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first resignation of a statewide elected official
since Bill Honig resigned as superintendent of public instruction
in 1993. The situation was somewhat similar: Honig was convicted of
illegally directing public money to benefit a nonprofit education
group his wife founded and ran out of their Pacific Heights home.
</P>
<P>
   Davis must find a replacement to serve out the remainder of
Quackenbush's term, which ends in late 2002. The law requires the
Legislature to confirm the appointment, but both houses leave for a
summer recess July 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
