<HEADLINE>
`BURLESK KING': A SLICE OF LIFE FROM THE PHILIPPINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Burlesk King,'' a film by the Filipino director Mel Chionglo,
which opens Friday in New York after making the rounds on the
international festival circuit, is best described as a curious
blend of Italian neo-realism and soft-core pornography.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's grim, melodramatic slice-of-life view of Manila's
sexual demimonde is intercut with dreamy, slow-motion shots of
undulating, nearly naked male go-go dancers and with squirming,
heavy-breathing sex scenes in which various permutations of gender
and number are represented.
</P>
<P>
   Even more curiously, ``Burlesk King'' isn't especially tawdry or
prurient. Rather, Chionglo's attitude toward his characters, their
bodies and what they do with those bodies for love and money is
tolerant and affectionate.
</P>
<P>
   His hero, Harry (Rodel Velayo), is a pouty young hustler who
leaves his hometown, Olongapo, along with his best friend, James
(Leonardo Litton), for the seedy bustle of Manila, where he finds
work as a so-called macho dancer in a nightclub. He also moonlights
as a gigolo catering to clients of both sexes. He befriends a
lonely romance-novel writer (Raymond Bagatsing) and an upbeat
prostitute named Brenda (Nini Jacinto), who dispenses alms and
big-sisterly advice to the local street urchins.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything goes happily. Harry gets involved in drugs and
offends Brenda's sensitivities by proposing to pimp for her. For
reasons that are not very clear, Harry and James fall afoul of a
local harmonica-playing gangster, which leads to some pseudo-Hong
Kong fight scenes; really this is a movie with something for every
taste.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, these sequences are as haphazardly shot and
edited as the sex scenes, and the various plot lines are so
disjointed that the film never generates much emotional momentum.
Its central dramatic crisis involves Harry's memories of his
abusive American father, whose cruelty has soured the young man on
Americans altogether, and may, for all I know, be a metaphor for
the way the United States has treated the Philippines over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   But politics are the last thing on this movie's mind. Lithe
young bodies are its main concern. If all of the gyrations were
edited out, ``Burlesk King'' might just eke out an hour of
television melodrama. The story might even be easier to follow. But
of course no one would bother to watch.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BURLESK KING'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Mel Chionglo; written (in Tagalog, with English
subtitles) by Ricardo Lee; director of photography, George Tutanes;
music by Nonong Buencamino; production designer, Edgar Martin
Littaua; produced by Robbie Tan; released by Strand Releasing.
</P>
<P>
   With: Rodel Velayo (Harry), Nini Jacinto (Brenda), Leonardo
Litton (James), Raymond Bagatsing (Mario), Elizabeth Oropesa
(Betty), Cherrie Pie Picache (Aileen), Gino Ilustre (Michael),
Joonee Gamboa (Miong), Tonio Ortigas (Leo) and Joel Lamangan
(Odette).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 109 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burlesk King'' is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
