   FILM-PERFECT STORM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The storm sequence in ``The Perfect Storm,'' which
lasts a good 40 minutes or so, is the most bludgeoning,
mind-shattering, teeth-rattling, nerve-racking set piece since the
D-Day battle in ``Saving Private Ryan.'' It has glitches, but it
simply powers right by them, so that you don't think about them
till later. In fact, the storm doesn't give you much time to think
at all. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-JORDAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Fort Worth Museum of Science and
History's IMAX screen is usually reserved for the educational. You
go there to see films about butterflies and dolphins, earthquakes
and volcanoes. You don't go there expecting to celebrate sports
heroes to a jock-jams pop music beat. So the museum's newest IMAX
film, ``Michael Jordan to the Max'' _ added to a film rotation that
includes ``Dolphins'' and ``T-Rex: Back to the Cretaceous'' _ is an
unusual choice. But the 45-minute portrait of the basketball
superstar is also a good choice. Though not specifically
educational, the film is inspiring, entertaining and ideal for
summer viewing. By ALYSON WARD. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-EXTREME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Most of us feel pretty athletic if we run a few miles
or master in-line skating in the driveway. We talk about hitting a
runner's high or finding the zone as if we're really accomplishing
something extraordinary. All it takes is a movie like ``Extreme''
to wipe those notions away. The IMAX film features world-class
athletes who have conquered extreme sports _ surfing, windsurfing,
skiing, snowboarding, rock climbing and ice climbing. They're
risk-takers, top-of-their-sport champions who attempt the
impossible to prove that it's possible. By ALYSON WARD. Story has
moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
