<HEADER>
A8593 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS &LR;      06-29 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILMENTS PLAGUE SINGLES CHAMPIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Both Wimbledon singles champions were in sickly
condition Thursday. Pete Sampras was nursing acute tendinitis of
the left foot. Lindsay Davenport was suffering a severe case of
Elena Likhovtseva.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras used ice, electrical stimulation, and anti-inflammatory
medication to recuperate.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport followed a strict regimen of dynamic serves, radar
volleys, and relentless determination during a crisis to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras received his diagnosis late Wednesday night after the
tendon running from his shin to his foot became inflamed while he
was warming up for a second-round match against Karol Kucera, a
victory that required four sets and one tape job by the trainer.
The top men's seed was in seclusion being treated, but his coach,
Paul Annacone, promised that his star client will take the court
Friday for his third-round match against American compatriot Justin
Gimelstob.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport received her reprieve when she revived herself by
winning the last six games from Likhovtseva for a 3-6, 6-3, 6-3
escape. Davenport will be hoping her game is in more robust shape
Saturday, when she takes the court against Paola Suarez.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport is a mellow California girl who inconspicuously has
ascended to the tennis penthouse, but when she is cornered, she'll
respond with a bulldog's resolve.
</P>
<P>
   And that was her situation after she fell into an 0-3 chasm in
the deciding set, having looked alternately gassed and aghast in
splitting the first two. She readily recognized her peril _ and
shrugged it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I knew it was going to be tough,'' she said. ``But even
though it's two breaks, she still has to win three more games,
which is kind of a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But not as long as Davenport's route.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it wasn't on the tip of my racket, the victory,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But for the rest of the day, most of Davenport's shots were
beyond the grasp of Likhovtseva. Davenport was a model of menace as
she broke Likhovtseva to 3-1, 3-3, and 5-3. The Russian, ranked 23d
in the world, realized early in Davenport's surge that she wasn't
going to dethrone the queen. She shook her head in resignation when
Davenport, the No. 2 seed, drilled an ace that put her up, 40-0, in
the tying game. Likhovtseva's surrender was complete when she sent
a two-hand backhand of a Davenport service blast into the doubles
alley at 5-3, 40-15.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last six games, I thought I hit the ball great,'' said
Davenport. ``That's what I'm going to try and remember through the
next two days, just remember how I was hitting the ball at the end,
try to start my next match, try to get off to a quicker start, try
and win some games in the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of this match, she hardly looked ready to put
this title in her trophy case alongside her 1998 US Open, 1999
Wimbledon, and 2000 Australian Open mementos. Likhovtseva reeled
off the first four games, dropped the next three, then easily
wrapped up the opening set. Davenport, hampered by a bad back that
contributed to her first-round exit from the French Open, wore an
expression that was part wince, part scowl even as she was
rebounding in the second set. But it had nothing to with her
health, just that of her game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, I've been feeling really good again,'' she said.
``I just started off the match so poorly. I found that happening in
Eastbourne (a Wimbledon tuneup) also. For some reason, (I'm)
getting off to really slow starts.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least she averted a fast finish to her title defense.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, meanwhile, was a human ice pack as he tried to prolong
his defense, which, if successful, would provide him with a couple
of bonuses he covets _ a piece of the record for most Wimbledon
men's singles crowns (7), owned by Willie Renshaw; and sole
possession of the standard for most Grand Slam men's singles crowns
(12) he shares with Roy Emerson.
</P>
<P>
   His coach, who dubbed himself ``Dr. Paul Annacone'' when he met
the press as Sampras's proxy, said the injury was ``strange, just
kind of came on yesterday out of the blue.''
</P>
<P>
   That goes well with Sampras's prevailing body colors _ black and
blue. He, too, was victimized by back problems in Paris, where he
lasted one round, and he pulled a back muscle while hitting with
Tim Henman during a pre-Wimbledon warmup at the All England Lawn
Tennis &AMP; Croquet Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a rough go for a while with Pete with injuries,''
said Annacone, ``so I think, you know, this is just kind of another
injury thrown in front of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dropped on him, actually. Sampras had no warning about this
latest malady, which Annacone said developed ``at 5 minutes to 3
yesterday when he walked on the practice court. Can't figure it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Sampras grimaced throughout his gallant performance
against Kucera, Annacone doesn't think it will keep him out.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Sampras could have played, Annacone looked incredulous.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Wimbledon?'' he said. ``Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   So of course, he'll be back on public view Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the plan,'' said Annacone. ``As far as I know, he's
going to play, unless he tells me otherwise later.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the elixir for Sampras will be his cushy half of the
draw, which includes only one other seed _ No. 9 Thomas Enqvist,
who hardly is considered a viable threat.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, as Sampras and Davenport know, champions have to be
wary of every little thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
