<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8596 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-NADER30-COX     06-29 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NADER30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR RALPH NADER, PRESIDENTIAL QUEST IS ONE STEP IN A LONG
JOURNEY
 &HT;    820&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ralph Nader understands that he is not going to be
elected president of the United States this year. But then, winning
the White House is not exactly what his campaign for the presidency
is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victory is defined in many ways,'' Nader insisted Thursday at
a breakfast with political reporters from nearly every major
newspaper in the country.
</P>
<P>
   What he wants, as the nominee of the Green Party, is to do for
the fledgling political organization what Ross Perot did for the
Reform Party: win 5 percent of the vote in November to earn a share
of federal funding this year and in the 2004 election. That would
give the Greens a toehold in the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, we want to have a significant third
party that will draw thousands of local, state and national
candidacies in the coming years,'' said Nader, a legendary consumer
advocate and anti-corporate crusader.
</P>
<P>
   If that means siphoning off liberal-leaning voters who might
otherwise vote for Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive
Democratic nominee, well, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Nader wants to see Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the
likely GOP nominee, in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with George W. Bush is he's beyond satire,'' Nader
said. ``The challenge for me is: how do you satirize satire? This
guy is straight out of central casting.''
</P>
<P>
   He also described Bush as the ``corporate welfare king of all
presidential candidates,'' a reference to the governor's $14
million profit from the sale of the Texas Rangers after securing a
taxpayer-financed stadium for the professional baseball franchise.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Gore is the more infuriating, because he's such a
hypocrite,'' Nader added. ``He doesn't know who he is any more.
He's a plastic person.'' He also called Gore an ``environmental
imposter'' who supports trade treaties that subordinate the
environment and a ``gee-whiz techno-twit.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader's disdains Gore and Bush equally as ``indentured'' to the
corporate interests that hold sway over the political process in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But Nader is positioned to hurt Gore more in the fall election.
A favorite of liberal activists and union members, he is polling
between 5 and 9 percent in some states that are crucial to the vice
president's campaign. He is strongest in California, the linchpin
of Gore's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign is somewhat dismissive of Nader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The undeniable likelihood is one of two people is going to be
president, Al Gore or George W. Bush,'' said Gore spokesman Chris
Lehane. ``And if you care about progressive causes, you would be
supporting Al Gore. A vote for anyone else is tantamount to a vote
against progressive causes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, while trailing Bush and Gore by 40 points or more,
Nader is running third in most polls, ahead of staunch conservative
Pat Buchanan, who as the Reform Party nominee was expected to be
the wild card in the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   But Nader does not see himself as a ``spoiler'' in this year's
election. He sees himself as a reformer in the mold of movements
that challenged the corrupt political machines in the country's
major cities in the early 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they viewed themselves as spoilers,'' he said.
``They viewed themselves as reformers. You can't spoil a system
that's spoiled to the core.''
</P>
<P>
   The political system, he said, has moved from ``legalized
bribery'' of public officials to ``legalized extortion'' by
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party in the United States was organized in Minnesota
in 1984. It is an offshoot of the European Greens, which sprouted
in 1978 in West Germany as a pro-environmental, anti-nuclear
movement. Currently, 79 Greens hold elected offices in 18 states
and Washington, D.C. This year, 177 are running for state, local
and federal offices.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their political differences, Nader and Buchanan are
allies in trying to secure a place for themselves in the
presidential debates this fall. They have filed suit together
challenging the legality of the corporate-funded Commission on
Presidential Debates, which has set standards for inclusion in the
debates that could bar Nader and Buchanan _ specifically, a minimum
15 percent standing in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Nader has run for president, but it
is the most serious effort by the 66-year-old public interest
lawyer. In 1992, he briefly promoted a ``none-of-the-above''
candidacy in New Hampshire. And in 1996, he allowed his name to be
placed on the ballot in several states, but did not campaign.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, he has already visited all 50 states and is
trying to get on the ballots of at least 45. Since accepting the
Green Party's nomination last Sunday, he has begun assembling a
campaign headquarters staff of 21 people and a field staff of at
least 30 organizers.
</P>
<P>
   He also has set a fund-raising goal of $5 million. ``We get a
lot more out of $5 million than the other candidates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Nader's name recognition is helpful in some parts of the
country, he admitted. While he mostly depends on news coverage of
rallies and ``word of mouth'' for exposure, he also said he will
try to ``push the frontier'' with his campaign Web site, conducting
some live events on it.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he will try to advertise some this fall. He already
has hired Bill Hillsman, the advertising whiz whose television
spots helped put former pro wrestler Jesse Ventura in the
governor's mansion in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Nader's chief issues arise from his distrust
of corporations. He wants to end ``corporate welfare'' tax
loopholes, institute a system of public financing of political
campaigns, renegotiate international trade agreements and
strengthen labor laws and environmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
   But most of his campaign rhetoric flows from his advocacy of an
all-out effort by the federal government to end child poverty in
the United States. His solution involves universal health care and
a ``national minimum income'' for poor families.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't abolish child poverty now, we will never abolish
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nader, a 66-year-old bachelor, came to national prominence in
1965 with the publication of the book ``Unsafe at Any Speed,''
which criticized the safety standards of the auto industry. Since
then, he has established a number of public interest organizations,
helping to finance them by donating about 80 percent of his
earnings from royalties and fees.
</P>
<P>
   He lives austerely on $25,000 a year in a rented apartment in
Washington. But his anti-corporate image took a hit recently when
he disclosed that he has personal assets total close to $4 million,
much of it earned through investments.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.votenader.com, www.greenparty.org
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
