<HEADER>
A8598 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT     06-29 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIGHT FARE FOR THE FALL
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe it was the prospect of the long holiday weekend
or just the summer heat, but this has been a sizzling week for deal
makers on and off Broadway, giving shape to the coming season and a
sense of security to newly hired actors, playwrights and myriad
theater populi.
</P>
<P>
   First, some trend spotting. After several seasons packed with
serious fare, the fall is looking considerably lighter. The latest
indication is Neil Simon's ``Dinner Party,'' which opened last week
at the Kennedy Center in Washington. The Washington Post called the
play, which stars Henry Winkler, John Ritter and Len Cariou,
``laugh out-loud funny,'' adding that it was Simon's ``emotionally
richest play.''
</P>
<P>
   With reviews like that, producers don't have to be told twice.
Emanuel Azenberg, Simon's longtime producer, said he would bring
the play to Broadway in October, in association with Ira Pittelman
and Gordon Davidson, artistic director of Mark Taper Forum in Los
Angeles, where the play had its premiere last year.
</P>
<P>
   Industry gossip suggests that ``The Dinner Party'' will land at
the Walter Kerr Theater. That house, however, has also been
mentioned for ``Proof,'' David Auburn's drama, now at the Manhattan
Theater Club. There's no definite word on that play's future, but
this week brought word that Mary-Louise Parker, the star of
``Proof,'' has apparently opted out of the Roundabout Theater
Company's fall production of ``Desire Under the Elms.''
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Dinner Party,'' it joins another comedy, ``The Tale of
the Allergist's Wife'' by Charles Busch and a couple of revivals
that mix sugar and salt: Jane Wagner's ``Search for Signs of
Intelligent Life in the Universe'' from 1985 and Gore Vidal's 1960
political satire ``The Best Man.'' (More on that guy later.)
</P>
<P>
   Other transfers were in the works. From London via California is
``Lifegame,'' an improvisational piece from the Improbable Theater,
the British troupe behind mind-bending works like ``70 Hill Lane''
(a metaphysical magic show) and ``Shockheaded Peter'' (a morbidly
hilarious children's operetta).
</P>
<P>
   This time the work is even less predictable: Each night, an
audience member is picked at random (and in advance) to share his
or her life story, portions of which are then re-enacted by the
cast of eight.
</P>
<P>
   The show is currently at the La Jolla Playhouse in California.
David Stone, who has done very nicely with two unconventional
pieces, ``The Vagina Monologues'' and ``Fully Committed,'' heads a
four-member New York producing team.
</P>
<P>
   And after a brief run at Dance Theater Workshop in Chelsea,
producers of the Foundry Theater's ``And God Created Great Whales''
confirmed that that they would move even farther downtown. This
surreal exploration of ``Moby-Dick'' begins a monthlong run at the
Salon at 45 Bleecker Street in Greenwich Village on Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   SOMETHING NEW
</P>
<P>
   There was also action in the nonprofit realm, where the trend is
running headlong toward new plays. At the Drama Department the new
season will include three New York premieres: ``The Dazzle,'' a
play by Richard Greenberg; an untitled play ``about racism and
sweet potatoes,'' written by and starring the quirky comic siblings
Amy and David Sedaris; and ``The Big Time,'' the first musical by
the company's artistic director, Douglas Carter Beane.
</P>
<P>
   At the Signature Company, meanwhile, the next two seasons will
be filled by new works, each by one of the company's guest
playwrights from the last decade. (The company devotes each season
to a single playwright, often choosing lesser-known works from the
writer's canon.)
</P>
<P>
   For the fall the Signature plans to present ``A Lesson Before
Dying,'' a new adaptation of the Ernest Gaines novel by Romulus
Linney (1991-92 season), as well as the ``The Last of the
Thorntons,'' a premiere from Horton Foote (1994-95) that is already
cast with Mason Adams, Estelle Parsons and Hallie Foote, the
playwright's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The final entry of the season, ``Urban Zulu Mambo,'' is a
tribute to Adrienne Kennedy, who was the Signature's writer in
residence in 1995-96. ``Mambo'' was written by a quartet of
African-American women _ Regina Taylor, Ntozake Shange, Kia
Corthron and Suzan-Lori Parks _ and is performed by Taylor. Two of
the ``Mambo'' writers will also be represented elsewhere. Parks'
new play, ``Topdog/Underdog,'' is on next season's roster at the
Public Theater, along with ``Kit Marlowe,'' a new play by David
Grimm; ``Book of the Dead,'' a music theater piece by John Moran;
and ``Dog-eaters,'' a play about 1980s Manila by Jessica Hagedorn.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile a new play by Corthron, ``Force Continuum,'' is part
of the Atlantic Theater Company's 2000-01 season, along with Tom
Donaghy's ``Beginning of August,'' directed by Neil Pepe.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY CHOICE
</P>
<P>
   ``The Best Man'' has found its best man, and it's Mr. Big.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Chris Noth, best known for playing Mr. Big, Sarah
Jessica Parker's elusive paramour on HBO's ``Sex in the City,''
will be making his Broadway debut in September in ``The Best Man.''
Noth will play Joe Cantwell, a consummate politician (think RFK) in
the revival, which opens on Sept. 17 at the Virginia Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Noth, a Yale Drama graduate and a veteran of NBC's ``Law and
Order,'' said he was yearning to be back onstage but was surprised
by the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked that they're actually doing drama on Broadway,''
he said on the set of ``Sex and the City.'' ``I thought: `Wow,
they're doing this? I gotta be there.'''
</P>
<P>
   ALONG THE WAY
</P>
<P>
   _ Few details yet, but it looks as if the master magician Ricky
Jay will return to Broadway next spring in a new show directed by
David Mamet.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Moon for the Misbegotten,'' with Gabriel Byrne, Roy
Dotrice and Cherry Jones, closes on Broadway on Sunday, but there
is talk of a London run in late winter. There are a couple of
potential snags, however. Byrne and Dotrice have a new ABC series
in the works, ``Madigan Men.'' Byrne has also been entertaining
another Broadway engagement, for spring 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
