<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8600 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MEDICARE-HMOS-HNS &LR;      06-29 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-HMOS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HMOS IN SHOWDOWN WITH CONGRESS OVER MEDICARE FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The association representing managed-care health
plans warned Thursday that its members are likely to drop coverage
of more than 700,000 people on Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, the group said, is that the government pays the
plans too little per patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are staggering and tragic,'' said Karen Ignagni,
president of American Association of Health Plans, at a news
conference. ``For hundreds of thousands of Medicare beneficiaries,
today is the day Washington has failed them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ignagni released a survey conducted by the Washington-based
polling firm, Peter D. Hart Research Associates Inc. The study
showed that 18 of 37 health plans responding to the survey said
they will drop coverage of Medicare patients in at least one area
or region they serve. The 37 plans represent about 85 percent of
all Medicare beneficiaries enrolled in managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   All told, 711,055 beneficiaries will be affected, Ignagni said.
That's 11 percent of the 6.2 million Medicare beneficiaries who
have signed up with managed-care plans, or health maintenance
organizations (HMOs), and 1.8 percent of all 39 million people in
Medicare, the government's health system for the elderly and
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the survey was the latest salvo in the HMOs'
battle to get Congress to approve more Medicare funds for them. The
fight is likely to last until Congress adjourns this fall for the
November elections.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the HMOs' threat shows how pressure politics
works in Washington, with millions of dollars and health-care
options for thousands of senior citizens riding on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, the Clinton administration downplayed the managed
care industry's dire predictions. ``Medicare beneficiaries who are
affected by plans leaving Medicare should remember that no matter
what, they are still covered by a strong Medicare program,'' said
Nancy-Ann DeParle, administrator of the Health Care Financing
Administration (HCFA), which runs Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Although managed care has been available through Medicare since
the mid-1980s, Congress in 1997 set up a national payment structure
for reimbursing HMOs for covering Medicare patients. Congress named
it Medicare-Plus-Choice.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people now receiving health care through managed
care plans has doubled since the end of 1995. Managed care under
Medicare is similar to managed care in the private sector. Patients
are limited in terms of selecting doctors and hospitals but receive
treatment at a reduced cost.
</P>
<P>
   Senior citizens may select Medicare-Plus-Choice or retain
Medicare's traditional fee-for-service coverage. Under
fee-for-service, patients may choose the doctor or hospital they
want and Medicare pays a set rate. Patients pick up the balance
either through extra ``Medigap'' insurance or out of their own
pockets.
</P>
<P>
   For Medicare beneficiaries, the main attraction of
Medicare-Plus-Choice is drug coverage _ a benefit that greatly
reduces the skyrocketing cost of prescription medicines. About 63
percent of beneficiaries have such coverage.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Ignagni vowed to press Congress for
higher payment formulas. Under Medicare, plans are ``overregulated
and underfunded,'' she said. ``This day did not have to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The amount the government pays each plan for Medicare service
depends largely on geography. This year, in some sections of New
York (with a lot of wealth and competition between doctors and
hospitals), Medicare pays plans as much as $814 per patient per
month.
</P>
<P>
   But some rural areas of Minnesota receive the minimum _ $401 per
patient per month.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the plans succeeded in getting an extra $1.3 billion
from Congress for their Medicare services. HMOs now get about $45
billion a year from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ignagni said health plans need an extra $13 billion to $15
billion over five years to keep their Medicare patient programs
economically viable. The Republican Medicare prescription drug plan
that passed the House Wednesday contains $3.5 billion for health
plans serving Medicare patients. Ignagni said this drug funding
would not allow any boosts in the overall payment formula.
</P>
<P>
   Some major plans have already announced they are dropping
Medicare coverage. Cigna Corp. has said it will end its program
covering 104,000 Medicare beneficiaries in 11 states. Among the
areas hit are Los Angeles, Atlanta, New York City, Houston and
Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna U.S. Healthcare announced Thursday that it will drop
Medicare HMO coverage in 11 states: Connecticut, Florida, Georgia,
Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, Louisiana, Maine, Ohio, Texas and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Aetna said it will drop Medicare participants in
five counties north and east of New York City _ Nassau, Suffolk,
Orange, Putnam and Dutchess _ and seven counties in Northern
California _ Alameda, Contra Costa, El Dorado, Sacramento, San
Francisco, San Mateo and Santa Clara. In all, the Aetna withdrawals
will affect 355,000 Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Providence Health Plans of Portland, Ore.
announced it will discontinue its Medicare coverage in eight
counties in Oregon and southern Washington, affecting 6,000 of its
53,000 Medicare enrollees.
</P>
<P>
   But not all plans are abandoning Medicare. PacifiCare Health
Systems Inc. of Santa Ana, Calif. will announce next Wednesday only
``minimal changes'' in its coverage of nearly a million Medicare
patients in eight states _ Arizona, California, Colorado, Nevada,
Oregon, Oklahoma, Texas and Washington, according to spokeswoman
Cheryl Brady.
</P>
<P>
   The company has already decided it will not drop any of its
575,000 Medicare enrollees in California, its biggest market.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this time, health plans announced coverage cuts
that affected 327,000 Medicare beneficiaries. And in 1998, similar
cuts ended managed care for 407,000 beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   However, only 24 percent of the 327,000 and 12.5 percent of the
407,000 were left with no other Medicare managed care plan in their
area, according to the government's HCFA.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
