<SLUG> BC-TRAVELING-CAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 3,000-MILE JOURNEY, CAT'S NUMBER JUST WASN'T UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Colo.; i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Perhaps it was tragedy that caused Lapis to roam.
</P>
<P>
   On the day the black-and-white cat vanished from her home in
Boulder, Colo., Lapis's brother, Hoki, had been put down by a
veterinarian's needle because of an incurable kidney ailment. That
was April 19.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of the sweet-natured shorthair on top of the
other cat's death was devastating to owner Jennifer Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried and cried. I loved her so much,'' said Hill, 33, a
graduate student of social work at the University of Denver. ``I
posted signs, I placed ads, I called the animal shelters.''
</P>
<P>
   The signs yielded nothing but false leads, ditto the
classifieds. Animal shelter workers could offer only sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   But this kitty's tale has a happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   Lapis the cat is back purring on the lap of her owner, returned
earlier this week after an epic feline journey of nearly 3,000
miles to Canada's Far North _ all the way to Champagne Landing,
Yukon Territory, pop. 15, located nearer the Arctic Circle than the
United States border.
</P>
<P>
   How the pink-nosed wayfarer could wander so far is a mystery.
The best guess is she hopped into the back of a truck or camper,
and either leaped to freedom during a pit stop near Champagne
Landing _ or was pushed.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the discovery of Lapis is the biggest thing to happen
around Champagne Landing since the Alaska Highway was built through
in 1942. The former gold rush trading post and Indian burial site
hasn't lately even rated a place on the map _ it's too tiny to
qualify as a hamlet by Canadian government definition, so most
cartographers don't bother with it.
</P>
<P>
   Just about everyone noticed the five-pound furry stranger who
sashayed into the settlement last month, while Hill was still
futilely seeking kitty far, far to the south.
</P>
<P>
   There was Edward Chambers, 65, whose mutt, B.V., chased the
newcomer up a tree. ``Dog wouldn't stop barking, but I thought
nothing of it,'' said the retired businessman. ``Sure I figured the
cat was from away _ Whitehorse, maybe. Not the other side of the
Rockies.''
</P>
<P>
   A week or so later, the errant cat was spied again rooting after
field mice near the home of Chambers' mother-in-law. Then spotted
prowling the Indian burial ground. Chambers' son-in-law, David
Grant, remarked that it seemed odd a stray cat should have such a
pretty blue collar. Odder still that it hadn't been gobbled by
coyotes, wolves or other predators that make a cat's life in the
wild country a perilous one. Finally Grant's niece, Susan, checked
out the tag _ puzzling at the phone number with the unfamiliar area
code.
</P>
<P>
   Grant called Hill. The Colorado woman was incredulous,
wondering, just for starters, where the heck the Yukon was? But she
was delighted to learn that her runaway appeared to be faring just
fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``She survived up there because she's a real good mouser,'' Hill
said. ``She may be a little kitty, but she's tough and
resourceful.''
</P>
<P>
   The toughie's trials and travels weren't over. Grant drove the
cat to Whitehorse, the territorial capital, buying a cat cage at
the Canadian Tire store and trying to check her aboard the most
direct flight south. But because of a heat wave in Colorado, the
airline refused to carry an unaccompanied cat to Denver
International.
</P>
<P>
   So Lapis was flown to Hill's sister, Elizabeth, in San
Francisco. From where Hill retrieved her on Wednesday, 70 days
after the cat went missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she got home, she ate a can of tuna, then played with her
toys,'' Hill said. ``Then went to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky Lapis, for shuteye is something that Hill and the folk in
Champagne Landing are finding hard to come by these days, as the
phones ring and ring from media around the world. BBC calling.
People Magazine here. Australian radio on the line, mate. The New
York Post. Fox Network. Everyone loves a cat yarn.
</P>
<P>
   But is there a moral to it all? Any deeper lesson for us all?
</P>
<P>
   You betcha.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always put your cat's number on the collar,'' Hill advised.
``Because you just never know where she'll turn up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
