<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-POLITICS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UGANDANS VOTE ON HOW THEY WISH TO BE GOVERNED 
</HEADLINE>
   By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KABALE, Uganda _ Ugandans voted Thursday in an unusual
referendum on how they want to be governed, a question tied deeply
to the violence of the nation's past and the popularity of
President Yoweri Museveni, the man who has, in large measure, ended
that violence.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout among Uganda's 9.6 million voters appeared relatively
light _ which Museveni's opponents said showed the success of their
call for a boycott. But apart from trying to avoid the rain in many
parts of Uganda, voters also may have stayed home because the
election's result, in Museveni's favor, never seemed in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Museveni very much,'' said Sugra Khan, 69, after
casting her vote in a drizzle at a near-empty soccer field in this
southwestern town early Thursday morning. ``Now we have no
problems. I am sleeping well.''
</P>
<P>
   Khan said she cast her vote from her life: In the 1970s the
dictator Idi Amin _ responsible for as many as 500,000 deaths _
expelled some 70,000 Ugandans of Asian descent, among them her own
family.
</P>
<P>
   The choice in the referendum was whether to return to a
multi-party system or to continue the so-called ``Movement'' system
favored by Museveni, president since he won a five-year guerrilla
war in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Movement, political parties are permitted in name
only. Museveni's argument is that political parties have divided
Ugandans by tribe and religion, allowing men like Amin and Milton
Obote, whom Museveni overthrew, to take power.
</P>
<P>
   The question echoes the debate about whether African nations _
lacking a middle class that votes its economic interests rather
than its tribal or religious ties _ are politically mature enough
for the same kind of democracy practiced by rich nations.
</P>
<P>
   Museveni's opponents _ supporters of a multi-party system _
depict the Movement as a one-party state that he manipulates to
stay in power. The Movement bans party conventions and rallies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a kind of dictatorship,'' said Nasser Sebaggala, the
former mayor of the capital, Kampala, who plans to run for
president next year against Museveni. ``People want a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, opponents of Museveni called for a boycott of the
election: They have mounted a legal challenge against the
parliamentary vote that established the referendum and say that, at
any rate, the process is stacked against them. Proponents of many
parties were not permitted to appear on the ballot as separate
parties or personalities but rather as an idea, while Museveni has
been able to campaign as the public face of the Movement.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday, Sebaggala said people boycotted the
vote in huge numbers, though it was impossible to tell because the
results will not be known until Saturday at the earliest. By law,
results must be released within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Officials on all sides say the results will be significant
nonetheless, as an early indication for the more important
elections next year for both the parliament and the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In the last presidential elections, in 1996, Museveni won
three-quarters of the vote, with about three-quarters of the
electorate going to the polls. A similar result would give Museveni
a boost into next year's elections, while his opponents are certain
to capitalize on any weakening in his past high levels of support.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Movement officials have been bracing for a low turnout, saying
that Ugandans have voted often enough that they have begun to take
that right for granted. That explanation was echoed Thursday by the
assistant town clerk in Mbabara, who was also a local election
supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are educated are starting to talk about why
should they be bothered,'' he said. ``There is fatigue. I don't see
people getting excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Museveni has campaigned on his record _ what he says are huge
strides in economic growth, education and infrastructure, as well
as much more peace and stability than in the past. His opponents
say Ugandans are still poor, that 700,000 people have been
displaced by two rebellions and most Ugandans oppose Museveni's
involvement in the rebellion in neighboring Congo.
</P>
<P>
   But some voters are separating the candidates from the issues,
and in particular Museveni from the Movement. Allen Kyomugasho, a
65-year-old shopkeeper in Mbabara, said she likes Museveni but
voted Thursday to bring back political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame Museveni,'' said Kyomugasho. ``I just want a
change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
