<HEADER>
A8604 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-COX-RELIGIOUS-VISAS-0     06-29 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-RELIGIOUS-VISAS-0630 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUSTICE: STRICTER SUPERVISION OF RELIGIOUS VISAS NEEDED
 &HT;    By MIRIAM A. GARCIA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Citing reports where people fraudulently obtained
religious worker visas, the Justice Department told a House
committee Thursday that stricter supervision of the program is
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the House Judiciary Committee on Immigration and
Claims, however, said changes to the non-minister religious worker
immigrant visa program would violate the ethics of certain
religious sectors.
</P>
<P>
   The INS and the State Department identified several fraud
schemes where applicants lied to obtain visas and never worked for
a religious organization in the United States. The Justice
Department recommended toughening requirements for religious visas,
including requiring proof of previous religious experience and
documenting full-time, paid employment in a religious organization
upon arrival here.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 5,000 immigrants obtain visas every year to work
for U.S. religious groups, according to a March 1999 General
Accounting Office report. An INS investigation found a pastor who
filed 450 visa petitions that covered more than 900 people
falsified the number of years applicants were members of the
church. Another case involved 30 Fiji citizens living in the U.S.
who applied for religious worker visas because their visitors visas
had expired. As a result, INS now requires the sponsoring
organization to submit evidence regarding their ability to
financially support the applicant.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The visa program) was not intended to provide religious
denominations with the ability to obtain green cards for members of
their congregation, particularly on a revolving-door basis, without
a bona fide intention to employ them for religious work,'' said
Jess Ford who testified on behalf of the General Accounting Office.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the visa applications do not specify what type of
religious work is necessary to qualify. John Brennan, director for
visa services for the State Department, said sponsoring
organizations use that to their advantage and sometimes file
hundreds of petitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consular officers are presented with claims that a variety of
seemingly mundane jobs with no clear traditional religious function
are religious occupations because they are somehow related to the
overall work of a religious organization,'' Brennan said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Justice Department recommendation would discriminate
against religious groups like the Sisters of Charity, a
congregation of Catholic nuns started by Mother Teresa, said Rep.
Zoe Lofgren D-Calif. She cited a letter written by Mother Teresa
asking Congress to continue issuing visas to religious workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sisters of Charity are not paid, they serve the poor
without compensation,'' Zoe said. ``To request a pay stub would be
counterintuitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., echoed Zoe's concern and said, ``We
would end up excluding some religious groups because of their
religious beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Although fraud cases have been identified, ``much more serious''
cases exist in other segments of immigration applications, said
Mildred Patterson, the State Department's managing director. The
GAO report does not provide the number of fraud cases, but
Patterson said they are low.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Cook, a Justice Department acting assistox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
