<HEADER>
A8611 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-SECRET-MONEY0630-COX     06-29 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-MONEY0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate passes bill restricting political groupsBy Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. Rep. Lloyd Doggett scored a major victory
Thursday when the Senate approved a measure to limit the power of
secretive political groups like the one that bankrolled attack ads
against Arizona Sen. John McCain during his bruising Republican
presidential primary with Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would force the non-profit groups created under
section 527 of the Internal Revenue Code to tell the IRS when they
are formed and to file reports listing major contributors and
expenditures. The measure _ a compromise based on initiatives
pushed by Doggett and McCain _ passed the House earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton applauded the bill's passage and said he looks
forward to signing it, ``as a first step toward meaningful campaign
finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   That was good news for Doggett, who had hoped to make the
measure retroactive to the beginning of the tax year. The bill
becomes effective when Clinton signs it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This quick Senate action on modest reform is important, since
every day the bill goes without the president's signature is one
more day for disclosure opponents to fill their war chests with
secret money . . .,'' said Doggett, who also called the compromise
measure, ``far from perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Austin Democrat emerged as one of the chief proponents for
shining the light on so-called Stealth PACS. And though the measure
is narrower than some lawmakers had wanted, winning approval for
any campaign reform is difficult on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Frances R. Hill, a University of Miami law professor, said the
measure is, ``an enormous step forward.'' But she also said it is
too vague about when the IRS must make information from the groups
available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should say that they really mean to implement this and
there will be public disclosure before the 2000 elections,'' Hill
said. ``I don't think the American people should be deprived of
this information now that Congress has enacted this bill simply
because it would be a little inconvenient to the Internal Revenue
Service.''
</P>
<P>
   Groups of all political stripes have formed so-called 527s. The
Sierra Club formed one in 1996 and Scott Reed, manager of former
senator Bob Dole's 1996 White House bid, created one to help the
GOP reach out to Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, touts the Republican Majority
Issues Committee, whose mission is to keep the House in GOP hands.
DeLay was the sole member of the House Republican leadership to
oppose the measure. Republican Senators Kay Bailey Hutchison and
Phil Gramm voted for it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a $2.5 million ad campaign, paid for by a longtime Bush
backer, that sparked outcry on Capitol Hill. The group, Republicans
for Clean Air, launched the campaign slamming McCain's
environmental record in three critical states before the May 7
primaries. Media reports revealed that Sam Wyly and his brother,
Charles, were behind the group.
</P>
<P>
   Secrecy has been the hallmark of the non-profit groups formed
under section 527. They do not have to tell the IRS when they
organize or file tax returns or make public any information about
their contributors, spending or how they operate. Nonprofit groups
formed under other sections of the tax code are required to
disclose such information.
</P>
<P>
   The 527 groups run television and radio ads, send mailings and
make telephone calls to voters _ all legal so long as they do not
explicitly call for the election or defeat of a particular
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Under the measure that cleared Congress, section 527 groups that
``reasonably anticipate'' annual gross receipts of $25,000 or more
would be subject to federal campaign law. They would have to file
tax returns and identify contributors of $200 or more and
expenditures of $500 or more. They also would have to report
contributors and expenditures to the Internal Revenue Service every
three months during an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Violators could be subject to a 35 percent tax on contributions
and expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Common Cause President Scott Harshbarger applauded Doggett,
``for his persistence and determination in bringing this important
reform to the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
