<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-DAEWOO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR $6.9 BILLION, FORD WINS RIGHT TO BID FOR DAEWOO MOTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Ford Motor Co. on Thursday won exclusive
rights to negotiate the purchase of South Korea's ailing Daewoo
Motor Co. with a $6.9 billion offer that, if successful, would be
Ford's largest foreign acquisition and could significantly
strengthen its operations in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, the world's second largest automaker, outbid rivals
including No. 1 General Motors Corp. for the right to negotiate a
purchase of Daewoo from its creditors.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiating price, which was higher than had been expected,
does not include the assumption of any of Daewoo's estimated $18
billion in debt. Ford now has six weeks to conduct a so-called due
diligence review of Daewoo, and could conceivably decide to adjust
its offering price or withdraw from negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Yong-keun, chairman of South Korea's Financial Supervisory
Commission, which has been overseeing the auction process for
Daewoo Motor, said Ford ``offered the best terms and the Daewoo
Restructuring Committee and creditors chose it as the exclusive
negotiator after what I heard was a difficult selection process.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Ford seemed to be the weakest candidate, as it
competed against an alliance of GM and Fiat SpA and an alliance of
DaimlerChrysler AG and Hyundai Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   On top of its Mazda Corp. unit in Japan, Ford could use the
acquisition of Daewoo to make South Korea a new production base in
Asia, a region that is expected to lead the world incar sales over
the next two decades.
</P>
<P>
   An acquisition of Daewoo Motor would be just the latest in a
string of purchases for Ford. Earlier this year, Ford agreed to buy
the Land Rover sport-utility-vehicle unit from BMW AG for $3
billion, and last year it purchased Sweden's Volvo Car Corp. from
Volvo AB for more than $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after the announcement, David Snyder, head
of Ford's Asia-Pacific operation, sought to appease concerns by
South Koreans that there would be widespread layoffs at Daewoo
Motor factories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will seek the best way for all concerned-the employees, the
suppliers and the creditors and customers _ to normalize operations
at Daewoo at the earliest possible date,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Daewoo Motor is capable of producing 2 million vehicles annually
at plants in South Korea and abroad. But the carmaker, a showcase
subsidiary of the financially ailing Daewoo conglomerate, has
struggled with heavy debts and losses. Last year it lost $3.9
billion on revenue of $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Ford was a disappointment for GM, which had long
been considered the favored contender for Daewoo Motor. John
Mueller, a GM spokesman, declined to disclose what the GM-Fiat
alliance had bid for the company and did not rule out further
efforts to buy Daewoo Motor should Ford's negotiations falter.
</P>
<P>
   Although creditors and Daewoo officials said they did not expect
obstacles in the Ford negotiations, Oh Hogen, head of the Daewoo
Restructuring Committee, conceded that talks could be held again
with the DaimlerChrysler-Hyundai and GM-Fiat bidders if no
agreement were reached with Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Although DaimlerChrysler said it was not disappointed, its
partner, Hyundai Motor, could face a significant threat from a Ford
purchase of Daewoo. Hyundai Motor would face increasing competition
in a market where it holds a 65.7 percent stake. Daewoo's market
share is estimated at around 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means Hyundai Motor would have to expand its relationship
with DaimlerChrysler,'' said Joe Lee, an automotive industry
analyst at Daiwa Securities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1822EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
