<HEADER>
A8620 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-ALASKA-BOS &LR;      06-29 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ALASKA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLIPPERY SOLONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's nothing like a sense of gloom to pave the way for bad
ideas. The recent surge in gasoline prices has been seized on by
congressional Republicans as justification for opening Alaska's
Arctic National Wildlife Refuge, a unique natural asset, to oil
exploration. Doing so would squander one of the nation's last
untouched wildlife preserves without having any impact on the
current energy problem.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi has led the way
in the freshest attempt to assault the refuge by attaching an
energy package to an appropriations bill for the Labor Department
and the Department of Health and Human Services. The tactic of
turning contentious bills into riders on other pieces of
legislation presumed immune to veto is practiced by politicians of
all persuasions, but that does not keep it from being devious.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, senators with a sense of conscience should reject
the move on its merits in addition to the way in which it has been
introduced.
</P>
<P>
   The 1.5 million acres of northeastern Alaska, bordering the
Beaufort Sea, are home to a wide range of birds and land animals
that enjoy free movement. They are largely undisturbed by human
beings and wholly protected from the industrial-scale intrusions
that necessarily go with petroleum exploration and development.
</P>
<P>
   If the area were the answer to the nation's energy difficulties
the argument might be different. But the highest estimate of oil
that might be found there is about 3 billion barrels _ six months
of American consumption or about two months of global consumption.
Even if exploration started today it is highly unlikely that
production would begin before other factors had changed the
country's energy equation and the sense of emergency had passed.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative predators who play on the distress over gasoline
prices to carve out Alaska's pristine wildlife zone betray their
responsibility to protect national treasures. It is not a pretty
spectacle.
</P>
</TEXT>
