<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SYRIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SYRIAN VOTE THAT COUNTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a police state such as Syria, voting is the tribute tyranny
pays to democracy. This was the meaning of the unanimous vote
Tuesday by Syria's parliament to accept the ruling Baath Party's
nomination of the eye doctor Bashar Assad to succeed his father,
Hafez Assad, as the nation's president.
</P>
<P>
   Ballots were cast as if the dignitaries casting them had some
choice in the matter; the will of the people was invoked over and
over, as though it really played a role in the transfer of power.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after his father's death, Syria's make-believe
parliament removed a barrier to Bashar's succession in 15 minutes.
That's the time it took to amend Article 83 of the Baathist Party's
constitution, changing the minimum age of a Syrian president from
40 to 34, precisely the age of Bashar.
</P>
<P>
   The one nominal lawmaker who had the temerity _ or obtuseness _
to raise a procedural objection to the amendment was permitted to
apologize this week to his colleagues and express his wholehearted
support of Bashar's nomination. ``Your apology is a sign of respect
for this institution,'' the speaker of parliament told Monzir
Moussali, ``and a confession that you have erred.''
</P>
<P>
   Preposterous as it may seem to citizens of real democracies,
Syria's mimickry of democratic procedures may be seen as a tacit
recognition by Assad's inner circle of a yearning for
self-government that the Baathist regime, despite all its spies and
torturers, has never completely expunged from the population of
Syria _ and certainly not from the captive people of a colonized
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   That yearning is expressed in the Soviet-style jokes Syrians and
Lebanese tell about the referendum that will allow more than 99
percent of voters to elect Bashar the next president of Syria. The
real method of changing faces in the regime's ruling group is the
one perfected by the deceased Assad and practiced in the last few
years by his son. A dependent capo is placed in a sinecure where he
can reap the benefits of bribes, kickbacks, and partnerships. Then,
when it suits the supreme leader, a few such officials are purged
for being corrupt. This is the Syrian system of one man, one vote;
the Assad at the top is the one man with the one vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1829EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8624 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-APPETITE-SUPPRESSANT-     06-29 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPETITE-SUPPRESSANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG HAS POTENTIAL TO SUPPRESS APPETITE IN HUMANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEGAN SCOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of John Hopkins University scientists have produced what
seems to be a miracle diet drug capable of turning off appetite
with virtually zero side effects.
</P>
<P>
   For now, only mice have benefitted from the drug's weight loss
powers but doctors are hopeful the technique will one day work in
humans.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists said a non-toxic substance called C75, injected
into mice, wiped out the animals' interest in food within 20
minutes, tricking the brain into thinking it had been fed. The
result was a remarkably reduced appetite that led to weight loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not claiming to have found the fabled weight-loss
drug,'' said Dr. Frank Kuhajda, who led the research team at
Baltimore's Johns Hopkins University. ``What we have found, using
C75, is a major pathway in the brain that the body uses naturally
in regulating appetite _ at least in mice.''
</P>
<P>
   The C75 work, the results of which are published in the current
journal Science, comes out of the team's 14-year research on
abnormal fat metabolism that exists in cancer cells. Scientists
discovered cancer cells use ``fatty acid synthase'' or FAS, an
enyzme responsible for transforming carbohydrates into fat, to
produce fat.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, researchers injected mice with a single dose of
C75 and observed them for changes in behavior, weight and body
chemistry. The C75 substance killed the cancer cells without
harming the normal cells. In just 20 minutes, the mice lost their
appetite. Feeding was reduced by 90 percent the first day. It then
returned to normal over the next 48-72 hours as the drug's effects
dissipated.
</P>
<P>
   The injected mice resembled the fasting mice in the way they
lost body tissue, but the injected mice lost more weight than the
untreated mice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you try to lose weight by starving, your metabolism slows
down after a few days,'' Kuhajda. It's a survival mechanism that
sabotages many diets. We see this in fasting mice. Yet the
metabolic rate in the C75 treated mice doesn't slow at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuhajda said that this pathway is different from those found in
over the counter diet drugs like amphetamines, caffeine, and
phen-fen. The difference is that the pathway is found in brain
cells known to control appetite.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an entirely new discovery,'' said Hopkins researcher
Craig Townsend. ``Most weight loss drugs are essentially stimulants
that keep you going even though you're not moving. There's not much
out there that really works.''
</P>
<P>
   With 50 percent of the general population classified as
overweight, Americans are spending an increasing amount of money on
quick fix, weight loss drugs. But none of these seem to work.
According to government estimates, one-quarter of Americans are
obese.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obesity is a reality and associated with it are a lot of
health problems,'' Townsend said. If something can be done to help
people maintain their weight and control their eating there would
be a lot of benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Townsend recognizes C75 as a possible solution to what's become
a serious medical problem. But he emphasizes that the experiment
has only been performed on mice, and it will be many years before
such a product would become available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it worked, it could be a good thing,'' Kuhajda said. ``But
that's assuming that it goes through human safety and all the
trials that it has to go through. We'll just have to see what the
future will bring.''
</P>
<P>
   The study was funded by grants from the National Institutes of
Health, Department of Defense and the W.M. Keck Foundation and the
Steward and the Raynam Research Trusts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1831EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
