<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, June 30 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-RIGHTS (Undated) _ A day after the Supreme Court
effectively struck down ``partial birth abortion'' bans in some 30
states, people on both sides of the issue said the contentious
debate over the procedures is far from over. Across the country,
supporters and opponents of the bans said they expected a new
generation of laws around the country aimed at trying to prevent
what critics call partial-birth abortions while meeting the
requirements laid down by the justices on Wednesday. By William
Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ The Senate approved a
bipartisan bill Thursday that would require a growing number of
secretive, tax-exempt groups that raise and spend money on
political activities to reveal their donors and spending. Only six
Senate Republicans voted against the measure, and the House
endorsed the same bill on Wednesday, 385-39. President Clinton said
he will sign the measure as soon as Congress sends it to him. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: an early version has moved)
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Undated) _ For ages, nations have dreamed of
building invulnerable shields to protect themselves from hostile
forces. There was the Great Wall, the Maginot Line and, in America,
the Safeguard antimissile system and Star Wars. All fell short.
Now, the Clinton administration and its military advisers are
trying again, this time with a limited antimissile weapon they
think will go a long way toward immunizing the United States
against attack at least from missiles launched by adversaries like
North Korea, Iran and Iraq, which are known to be in various stages
of developing intercontinental missiles. Officials at the Pentagon
and experts outside of the government say this defense technology
has reached a new level of maturity. They argue that the
combination of miniaturized electronics and high speed rockets can
produce an agile, light-weight weapon that can find and ram an
incoming bomb at supersonic speed. But critics are skeptical that
it can work. A Special Report by William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-WOMEN (Mexico City) _ The macho, conservative world of
Mexican politics has taken on a decidedly feminine appeal to win
the votes of women. Male strippers were hired to perform at one
campaign rally. Television advertisements raised questions about
candidates' relationships with their ex-wives. And political wives
and daughters have opened themselves up to as much scrutiny as the
men running for office. The main reason is simple: women make up 52
percent of the electorate and could decide the race. By Ginger
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-JEWS (Hamadan) _ This is where Esther, the Jewish queen of
Persia, is reputed to be buried, a town once a center of Jewish
life. Now there are 35 Jews left. Here, as elsewhere in Iran, a
once-thriving community is worried. A verdict is expected Saturday
in the spy trial of 13 Jews in the Iranian city of Shiraz and,
according to Jewish leaders, the case has made life so unsettled
that up to half of the remaining Iranian Jews will emigrate in the
next year or so. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ENRON (Dallas) _ Enron, the Texas energy company, is George
W. Bush's biggest political benefactor, having donated $550,000 to
his campaigns. Bush, in turn, has gone to bat for the company in
Texas and Washington, where it has a growing list of legislative
interests. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTIONS-DOTCOMS (Undated) _ For a clear sign of the arrival
of e-politics, look to the skybox. This year, as always, household
names will adorn those familiar symbols of convention coverage, the
broadcast booths perched high above the floors of the Republican
and Democratic national conventions. But the old-line networks and
all-news cable channels will have new neighbors, New Media outposts
like Pseudo.com, America Online and USA Today.com that have all
been allotted the coveted booths. Down on the convention floor,
reporters for Voter.com and EVOTE will mingle with the delegates.
Around the hall, pool cameras operated by C-SPAN will send
convention images via streaming video to computer users. By Peter
Marks.
</P>
</TEXT>
