<HEADLINE>
HOW PORTABLE DEFIBRILLATORS WORK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use after July 3 by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Goes with Defibrillator story.) 
By ANGELA LEMIRE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest selling point for the automatic external
defibrillator has been its simplicity. Portable AEDs give clear,
concise voice prompts every step of the way, removing all guesswork
to guide trained laypeople in giving lifesaving shocks.
</P>
<P>
   First, electrodes placed on the victim's chest analyze heart
rhythms to determine if a defibrillating shock is needed.
</P>
<P>
   If defibrillation is needed, the device instructs the caregiver
and others to stand clear (to avoid shocking themselves), then
instructs the caregiver to deliver the shock by pressing a green
button.
</P>
<P>
   If no shock is needed, it instructs the caregiver to recheck the
victim's pulse and begin CPR if no pulse is found.
</P>
<P>
   After one minute of CPR, the AED analyzes the heart rhythm again
to determine the next steps. &QL; 
---For community class listings and class descriptions, log onto
the American Red Cross of Greater Los Angeles' Web site at
www.acrossla.org or call (800) 627-7000 or (213) 739-5220. The
American Heart Association Western States Affiliate, which also
offers classes throughout the San Fernando Valley, can be reached
at (213) 580-1408 and online at www.heartsource.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8641 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-DEFIBRILLATION-LADN &LR;      06-29 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFIBRILLATION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFIBRILLATE THE MASSES
</HEADLINE>
  Health-care professionals training people to save cardiac patients 
(For use after July 3 by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By ANGELA LEMIRE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you can perform basic CPR and push a button when told, you're
qualified to save the life of a co-worker, family member, customer
or even a golfing buddy in cardiac arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Once a method reserved for medical professionals, the use of
automatic external defibrillators by laypeople in private and
public workplaces is catching on. This development, touted by
experts as the most important adjunct to cardiopulmonary
resuscitation (CPR) within the past few decades, means it is more
likely the life-saving electric shocks can be administered in the
critical first 10 minutes of a cardiac arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller than laptop computers, programmable in most languages
and simple to use, the AED delivers a shock to the chest powerful
enough to temporarily stop some abnormal heart rhythms that cause
cardiac arrest, giving the heart a chance to return to a beat that
can pump blood again until trained medics arrive.
</P>
<P>
   El Caballero Country Club in Tarzana and Parsons Corporation in
Pasadena are two private business within Los Angeles County that
have formed their own AED response teams recently, according to the
American Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
   Employees at El Caballero have yet to be called to an actual
cardiac arrest emergency, but the AEDs bring general manager Tom
Bernsen some peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things that you hope you never have to
use,'' said Bernsen during a recent training demonstration. ``The
reason we have these defibs here is to stay ahead of the action,
not behind it. We would encourage all businesses to have AEDs. You
just never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout California, employees at stadiums, malls, airports,
beaches, restaurants and everyday workplaces also are getting
trained to use AEDs, due largely to legislation passed in January
that protects trained laypeople _ non-medical professionals _ from
getting sued after using AEDs to revive cardiac arrest victims.
</P>
<P>
   The City of Los Angeles plans to pilot AED response teams at
some police stations, Los Angeles Zoo, City Hall and at least one
municipal golf course. Six Flags Magic Mountain, Disneyland, Disney
Studios, San Diego Zoo and Universal Studios already have them
available to treat visitors or employees stricken by cardiac arrest
more quickly, according to the American Red Cross of Greater Los
Angeles, which now offers AED training with CPR instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``People die needlessly,'' said Gail Silverman, a cardiovascular
intensive care nurse and American Red Cross volunteer who pushes
for increased use of AEDs throughout Los Angeles. ``I defibrillate
patients almost every day. And it still gives me chills whenever I
use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sudden cardiac arrest can strike anybody, anywhere, without
warning.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 250,000 people die from cardiac arrest each year,
and most attacks occur among older men on Monday and Friday
mornings _ prime work hours. For children, the low-risk group,
cardiac arrest can occur in near drownings or severe electric
shocks.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a heart attack, in which blood flow to the heart muscle
temporarily is blocked, the primary cause of sudden cardiac arrest
is ventricular fibrillation _ a condition in which the heart's
electrical signals become disorganized and erratic.
</P>
<P>
   The heart quivers _ ``like a bag of worms,'' as one AED trainer
described it _ and cannot pump blood.
</P>
<P>
   CPR can keep a cardiac arrest victim's blood and oxygen flowing
to preserve vital organs for a short amount of time, but
defibrillation is the only way to reorganize abnormal electrical
signals into a steady heartbeat again.
</P>
<P>
   A victim's chance of survival decreases by 10 percent every
minute he or she goes without defibrillation following cardiac
arrest, according to American Red Cross statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Medical experts estimate that making AEDs as commonplace as fire
extinguishers could save 100,000 lives each year. The device costs
about $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross and American Heart Association have begun
training laypeople on AEDs in tandem with CPR lessons at 14
locations within the San Fernando Valley area.
</P>
<P>
   At El Caballero's 100-acre golf course, one device travels at
all times in the course marshal's cart, while another stays with
clubhouse doctors. Fourteen managers and supervisors across every
department and shift change know how to use them. And members _
especially regulars who golf with members with heart problems _ are
invited to get AED training through the club.
</P>
<P>
   The golfing industry has good cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
   Golfing typically corresponds with the likeliest hours for
cardiac arrest _ between 6 and 11 a.m. _ and expansive courses can
slow paramedics' response times in reaching victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is strengthen the chain of survival,''
said Dr. William K. Averil, a cardiologist and director for
American Heart Association's western state affiliates. ``There are
four basic links in the chain, and early defibrillation is the
third (link) and has been the weakest without AEDs.''
</P>
<P>
   The other ``links'' are early intervention such as a call to
911, early CPR, and advanced care by a medical professional who can
perform other analysis and more complicated lifesaving procedures.
</P>
<P>
   National survival rates for cardiac arrest are less than 5
percent, but experts predict that widespread AED distribution will
increase survival rates to 20 percent or more, said Averil.
</P>
<P>
   Jeannine Baugh, a Panorama City resident and tax accountant for
a private company, recently became an AED trainer for American Red
Cross because she believes more laypeople should get involved in
emergency response.
</P>
<P>
   ``The life you save could be my own,'' said Baugh, a diabetic
who has seen cardiac arrest claim the lives of two co-workers in
her career. She recalled, ``All the people knew how to do was call
911.''
</P>
<P>
   More complicated AED technology has been around for decades in
hospitals and ambulances.
</P>
<P>
   But about three years ago, simplified technology emerged to
create today's portable AEDs. Few professionals besides police,
firefighters, lifeguards and airline attendants used them until
recently, largely for fear of liability. Nationwide interest in AED
training rose within the last year, as states including California
passed laws extending ``Good Samaritan'' protection to laypeople.
</P>
<P>
   Both American Red Cross and American Heart Association officials
work closely with laypeople to determine how many AEDs are needed
in public and private workplaces, and how many employees, at a
minimum, should be trained to use them. They consider the layout
and expanse of each facility, number of levels, number of employees
and regular visitors, and the nature of the business. For example,
electric companies or concert venues would require more AEDs.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hare International Airport in Chicago often is cited as the
national model for AED effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The airport placed the devices a 90-second walk apart throughout
the airport six months ago, rigged them to alarms that
automatically dispatch emergency medics to that location and
trained 50,000 employees to use AEDs.
</P>
<P>
   In the first week alone, AEDs saved three lives at O'Hare. And
to date, nine of 11 people who suffered cardiac arrest at the
airport have been saved.
</P>
<P>
   Toni Hughes, who coordinates vocational services at an overnight
facility for troubled teens in North Hollywood and trains staff in
CPR, also took a recent American Red Cross class in Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   Her goal is to train staff and place AEDs at the facility's
three group homes and school, where high-pressure job situations
have prompted cardiac arrests among faculty in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone should have one of these in their office,'' said
Hughes, noting coaches and athletic trainers as prime examples.
``You have a lot of people hesitant about helping people in
emergencies, but this machine is self-explanatory. They're afraid
of doing something wrong. But this gives you confidence to help.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
