u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-29 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ABORTION IS SAFE, FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Make no mistake about it. The Supreme Court's 5-4
decision reaffirming a woman's basic right to choose an abortion
was a squeaker that alarms both those who are pro-choice and those
who care more about a fetus than a pregnant female.
</P>
<P>
   The high court decided correctly that it was essential to
protect the constitutional guarantee of individual liberty against
a ban on a late-term procedure under vague, sweeping laws that had
become an excuse for abolishing other abortions as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Nebraska law at issue was so loosely worded that it could
encompass second-trimester abortions more commonly used than the
rare so-called ``partial birth'' procedure technically targeted.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the law provided no exception _ from criminal
penalties that carried up to 20 years in prison _ to protect the
health and life of the pregnant woman.
</P>
<P>
   The enraged reaction of the court's minority made it perfectly
clear that this case was about chipping away at the basic right to
choose an abortion, not just about the brutal quality of the
rarely-used procedure in question.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four justices in the minority disgraced their black
robes by abandoning all pretence of judicial dignity, hurling
insults at the majority and resorting to hysterical accusations
grounded in emotion rather than law. They threw a collective hissy
fit more appropriate for a political rally than the high bench.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia wildly accused the majority of
practically condoning infanticide. ``It is a value judgment,'' he
thundered, pressing his own fetus-obsession as the only value that
matters in a society of diverse and sometimes conflicting values.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Clarence Thomas complained about court-mandated
``abortion on demand,'' a crude pejorative that anti-abortion
activists prefer instead of the more civilized ``request.'' Thomas
also protested the majority's ``philosophical views'' without
admitting his own ideological bent.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony Kennedy groused that the decision failed to
outlaw a procedure that ``many decent and civilized people find so
abhorrent as to be among the most serious of crimes against human
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist joined two dissenters but did
not pour further fuel on the fire by adding a separate intemperate
opinion. He must preside over this divided court, and a little
restraint was probably wise on his part.
</P>
<P>
   None of the dissenters acknowledged that millions of Americans
do not believe as they do that life begins at conception, which
would make abortion at any time the killing of a child. A Supreme
Court majority did not buy that theological theory in its original
1973 decision legalizing limited abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   The dissenters also barely nodded in the direction of the woman
involved, embracing Nebraska's transparent argument that an
exception to protect a woman's life or health is not ``necessary''
because unspecified alternative procedures might be available. If
they were troubled by any health problems a woman might suffer from
bearing an unwanted child, they did not indicate it.
</P>
<P>
   The dissenters are determined to force their own ideological
views on the whole country under cover of judicial power, even
though they are jeopardizing the credibility and authority of the
court they serve by turning it into an advocate for one religious
doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Justice Stephen Breyer, writing for the majority,
kept the tone of his opinion rational and noted carefully that on
this subject there are ``virtually irreconcilable points of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Breyer and the majority pointed out that ``millions fear that a
law that forbids abortion would condemn many American women to
lives that lack dignity, depriving them of equal liberty and
leading those with least resources to undergo illegal abortions
with the attendant risks of death and suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Breyer continued, ``Constitutional law must govern a society
whose different members sincerely hold directly opposing views.''
Right on.
</P>
<P>
   But the narrow one-vote margin by which sanity prevailed means
that the next Supreme Court appointments are likely to be crucial
for the future of female independence.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush predictably criticized the ruling, and
Vice President Al Gore predictably praised it. Gore has promised to
name pro-choice jurists to the high court and although Bush does
not admit it, everyone believes that he would name anti-abortion
folks like Scalia.
</P>
<P>
   Several justices are getting along in years and could retire in
the next four years. The philosophical makeup of the court could
flip with just one new justice, depending on circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides of the abortion issue may now be galvanized into
renewed political action, although so far most voters do not seem
to grasp the significance of the pending court appointments.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate consequences will be to throw the problem back to
the states. If they sincerely wish to abolish only the ``partial
birth'' procedure, they can draft laws that specifically target
only that one while leaving a loophole to guard the health and life
of the pregnant woman.
</P>
<P>
   Siding with the majority, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor said such
a narrow law would meet her own constitutional standard.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some abortion foes responded by saying that they could not
go for such a narrow statute. No doubt they feel it would be too
limited to achieve their real goal _ gutting abortion rights
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
