<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT TO SETTLE DISPUTE BETWEEN NEW HAMPSHIRE, MAINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., Maine, Colo., N.J., Neb., Ill., Wis., Iowa)   By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a final day of housekeeping after concluding its
term, the Supreme Court Thursday agreed to settle a longstanding
and increasingly bitter boundary dispute between New Hampshire and
Maine about which state includes the Portsmouth Naval Shipyard.
</P>
<P>
   The federal installation sits on islands in the Piscataqua
River, which flows into Portsmouth Harbor and forms the state
boundary between Portsmouth, N.H., and Kittery, Maine. According to
Maine, the state boundary is in the middle of the channel, placing
the shipyard on the Maine side. Consequently, Maine has been
imposing its income tax on the people who work at the shipyard.
</P>
<P>
   But New Hampshire, asserting a historical claim to all the river
up to the shoreline on the Maine side, says the shipyard is in New
Hampshire, which has no income tax.
</P>
<P>
   The United States owns the property in dispute, having begun in
1800 to acquire the five islands that make up the shipyard. For
years, however, the Navy regarded the island as within New
Hampshire's political jurisdiction. More recently, it has moved to
an official position of neutrality, though the federal government
has been withholding Maine income tax from the workers' paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   In March, New Hampshire filed its case against Maine directly in
the Supreme Court, invoking the court's constitutional ``original''
jurisdiction to hear suits between states. In agreeing Thursday to
take jurisdiction of the case, the justices instructed the federal
government to file a brief and make its views known.
</P>
<P>
   The case, New Hampshire vs. Maine, No. 130 Original, is
reminiscent of the ``original'' case the court heard two years ago
between New York and New Jersey about which could claim Ellis
Island. New Jersey emerged the winner.
</P>
<P>
   The competing claims of New Hampshire and Maine date to the
colonial period. New Hampshire says it is significant that the Port
of Piscataqua, now Portsmouth Harbor, was excluded from the
Massachusetts Bay colony in 1691. What is now Maine was originally
part of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Maine cites a decree signed in 1740 by King George
II, setting the boundary as a line that ``shall pass up thro' the
mouth of Piscataqua Harbour and up the Middle of the River.''
</P>
<P>
   In its brief asking the court to hear its case, New Hampshire
said that the shipyard ``has always been culturally, economically
and politically connected to New Hampshire.'' The state ``is not
able to maintain its historic connections to the shipyard without
judicial assistance,'' New Hampshire said.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are likely to appoint a special master to hear
evidence in the case and make a recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   As the court began its summer recess, it took these other
actions Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   Drug Sentencing
</P>
<P>
   The court vacated a Denver man's 30-year sentence for
distributing cocaine, and instructed the federal appeals court
there to reconsider the sentence in light of the Supreme Court
ruling this week that the sentencing provision of New Jersey's hate
crime law was unconstitutional. The court's action Thursday in
Jones vs. United States, No. 99-8176, could portend a major
upheaval in federal drug sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling Monday in the New Jersey case, Apprendi vs. New
Jersey, the court held that any fact that increases the penalty for
a crime beyond the statutory maximum had to be found by the jury
beyond a reasonable doubt. The New Jersey law was unconstitutional
because the judge, not the jury, determined after the defendant's
conviction whether the crime had been motivated by bias, a finding
that under the hate crime law then resulted in an increased
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The drug sentence the court vacated Thursday in light of that
ruling was typical of the way drug sentencing works in the federal
system. Carless Jones was indicted on and convicted by a jury of
two counts of distributing cocaine, a crime that carries a
statutory penalty of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment did not specify a particular amount of cocaine,
and the jury made no finding on that question. The pre-sentence
report informed the judge that the quantity of the drug, 165.5
grams, was enough for a life sentence. Over the defendant's
objection, the judge imposed a sentence of 30 years on each count,
to run concurrently. The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld
the sentence, ruling that the jury had found all the necessary
elements of the offense, and that the judge could make the findings
necessary to determine the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion
</P>
<P>
   Following its invalidation on Wednesday of a Nebraska abortion
law, the court vacated rulings by the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Chicago that upheld similar laws in Illinois (Hope
Clinic vs. Ryan, No. 99-1152) and Wisconsin (Planned Parenthood vs.
Doyle, No. 99-1156). The court also turned down an appeal by Iowa
from a ruling by the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which
struck down that state's so-called partial-birth abortion law last
year at the same time it invalidated the Nebraska law (Miller vs.
Planned Parenthood, No. 99-1112).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
