<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-PRI0630-COX     06-29 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PRI0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, aware he might have to
forge relations with a new ruling party in Mexico, is working hard
to stay out of Sunday's presidential election there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If elected, I look forward to working with whomever the good
people of Mexico choose to serve them as president,'' Bush said
Thursday, five weeks from receiving the GOP presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also offered a carefully crafted comment about Mexico's
reputation as something less than a full-fledged democracy, a
reputation built in part on the fact that one party has been in
control since 1929.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe a free and fair presidential election in Mexico will
be an affirmation of Mexico's continuing political progress,'' he
said of the nation that his given him his largest dose of foreign
policy experience.
</P>
<P>
   For some, one solid measure of that progress will be if the
National Action Party (PAN), headed by presidential nominee Vicente
Fox, can end the Institutional Revolutionary Party's 71-year hold
on control of the national government.
</P>
<P>
   Current polls show a tight race between Fox and PRI nominee
Francisco Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office in 1995, Bush has met with Fox and
Labastida. But like most American politicians, Bush's links to
Mexico are skewed heavily toward PRI officials, including current
President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't recall any meetings that the governor had with folks
outside of the PRI,'' said former Texas Secretary of State Al
Gonzales, now a state Supreme Court justice. ``Most of our meetings
dealt with substantive issues ongoing between Mexico and Texas that
required us to meet with PRI officials .'' Bush has met with PAN
members who are governors of Mexican states. That included a March
1996 session with Fox, then the governor of Guanajuato. Former
Secretary of State Tony Garza, now a state railroad commissioner,
and former U.S. Ambassador Jim Jones, who also was at the meeting,
on Thursday could not recall details about it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush met with Labastida, then Mexico's interior secretary, in
May 1998 in Mexico City. Gonzales said the major topic was American
business officials' concern about the safety of their employees in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida said the problem would be addressed, according to
Gonzales, who said Bush was pleased with the plan that came out of
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the deeper links to PRI officials, Gonzales believes
Bush can quickly make ties to PAN officials, if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I don't believe he has the same kind of
relationship,'' Gonzales said of Bush and PAN officials.
``Relationships take time to develop. I have every confidence in
the world that would develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Ambassador Jones agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, Governor Bush and other political leaders in the
United States with whom Mexico has a feeling of simpatico will be
very valuable because Governor Fox, if he wins, will need as much
advice on how to form a government at a national level, and I think
people who had those experiences will be very valuable to him,''
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also believes there are no inherent obstacles to forging
ties with PAN leaders if Fox prevails Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the U.S. point of view, we should really not care because
the amount of difference among the candidates concerning
fundamental U.S.-Mexico issues is minuscule,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Garces, who has helped coordinate Texas relations with
Mexico under three governors, also sees a smooth transition _
regardless of who is president of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``You handle it the same way you would handle everything when
there is a change of government in a different nation,'' said
Garces, Mexico and border affairs liaison in the secretary of
state's office. ``You accept whoever is elected as being the will
of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Garces believes Bush's hands-off approach to the Sunday election
is the only way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to Mexico and meeting with people from other parties
would be sending a political signal, and we try to stay out of
being political,'' Garces said. ``You just don't want to interfere
with the political process in another country.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, after he clinched the presidential nomination, Bush
ruled out a pre-election trip to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a complicating factor there,'' he said. ``The Mexican
presidential election is taking place, and I certainly don't want
to get involved in that.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, who will continue to have ties to Mexico whether he is
president or governor, forging links with a new ruling party will
not be a major obstacle, according to Secretary of State Elton
Bomer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In dealing with Mexico, it's all about personal relationships
more than anything else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
