<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-BOND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOND PRICES RISE IN A SIGH OF RELIEF, FOR NOW, ON INTEREST RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond yields fell sharply Thursday amid weakness in
stocks and investor relief that the Federal Reserve left interest
rates unchanged on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the currency market, the dollar was off against the euro and
the yen, making dollar-denominated investments, like Treasury
securities, more attractive to foreign investors because of
exchange rate advantages.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 10-year Treasury note, which many market
participants are using as the benchmark, rose 16/32, to 10 14/32.
Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the price,
fell to 6.02 percent from 6.10 percent. The price of the 30-year
bond rose 1 5/32, to 105 10/32. Its yield dropped to 5.87 percent
from 5.95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pugliese, director of the fixed-income department at J.W.
Genesis Financial Corp., said the moves had been exaggerated by low
liquidity and volume in the market.
</P>
<P>
   He said Treasury prices were too lofty, with the price of a
10-year note having run up too fast, and more interest rate
increases by the Fed were in the offing. ``I don't see prices
remaining at these high levels,'' he said. ``Prices in bonds and
equities will decline. The economic slowdown is a head fake, so
there are more tightenings in the wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald J. Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management,
said the Federal Open Market Committee, at its meeting on
Wednesday, refrained from tightening again ``as more moderate
economic and inflation data suggested that the previous tightenings
instituted over the past year may finally be starting to lower the
trend rate of economic growth to a more sustainable level, while at
the same time keeping a lid on rising price pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the issues of sustainability and extent of any slowdown
are open questions at this juncture,'' he added, ``and further Fed
tightening at the August FOMC meeting seems probable in light of
the economy's still-buoyant forward momentum, tight labor markets
and continued upcreep in inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   The government securities market was bolstered by the Treasury's
buyback program, some end-of-the-quarter buying and softer new-home
sales data that ran counter to sales figures released earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The release Thursday of updated figures for first-quarter gross
domestic product caused few surprises. Some bond market
participants think that coming figures on consumer prices could
prove unnerving, particularly if components of the price index
outside of energy go up more than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Fine is among those paying closer heed to other coming reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bond market's next major hurdle,'' Fine said, ``will be
the June labor market report, which should correct any misleading
perceptions resulting from last month's presumably questionable
information, which showed extraordinary weakness in the midst of a
very tight labor market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
