<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8671 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w BC-STATES-LUM-PA     06-29 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-LUM-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;   &QL;  &UR; Feds Say Plum Pox Money on the Way &QL;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Melissa Vogt &QL;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   C. 2000 States News Service &QL;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (June 29) -- Up to $13.2 million in federal money is
on its way to Pennsylvania fruit farmers hit by the plum pox virus,
Vice President Al Gore and Department of Agriculture officials
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. William Goodling, R-Seven Valleys, whose district includes
many of the counties affected by the virus, says the cash will be
nice, but late. Department of Agriculture officials identified the
virus officially in October. Goodling said he believed Gore was
using Thursday's announcement for political advancement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice-president's taking credit for releasing this funding
represents the height of political arrogance,'' Goodling said. ``It
was his administration's Office of Management and Budget that
prevented Secretary Glickman -- who is to be commended for issuing
an emergency declaration -- from honoring my request for plum pox
compensation all these months.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodling backed by a handful of Pennsylvania lawmakers convinced
Congress to release $5.1 million in aid to fruit farmers in May.
Those funds were lumped into the sum announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania Department of Agriculture has also spent $3.1
million to compensate farmers who have been forced to rip up and
burn their orchards. Officials have promised fruit farmers up to
$1,000 per affected acre.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore said in a statement, ``These growers
deserve support because they have helped to shield the rest of the
industry from this devastating disease.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States stone fruit industry is estimated to be worth
$1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   USDA spokeswoman Susan McAvoy said the virus has been found in
600 acres of Pennsylvania orchards. More than 1,000 acres are still
quarantined.
</P>
<P>
   The virus, known as sharka, affects stone fruits, such as
peaches, apricots, plums, nectarines, apricots and almonds. The
disease can be transmitted through by aphids and grafting. While
infected trees do not die, their fruit may drop prematurely, be
deformed or covered with spots and rings. The virus does not affect
people, but it does leave the fruit unmarketable.
</P>
<P>
   Sharka was found in European orchards as early as 1910 in
Macedonia. Orchards in Turkey, Syria, India and Chile throughout
the last century have also suffered from it. The United States
seemed to have remained immune until it was discovered last year in
Adams County, Penn.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Department of Agriculture, the virus appears to
be contained to west-central Pennsylvania. The department has spent
about $3.6 million for surveys and research to determine to the
extent of the virus' spread.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state agency officials continued to take leaf
samples from Adams, Cumberland and York county orchards this week.
They tested commercial orchards in Adams, Cumberland, Erie,
Lancaster and York counties last week.
</P>
<P>
   The optimal time to sample trees for the virus will end with the
onslaught of the summer heat.
</P>
<P>
   Of samples processed at the state Department of Agriculture's
laboratory last week, six tested positive for plum pox. All the
positive samples came from quarantined areas in Adams and
Cumberland counties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AFRICA-DEVELOP-NYT &LR;      06-29 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-DEVELOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. REPORTS WIDESPREAD DEPRIVATION IN SUB-SAHARAN AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Africans south of the Sahara, an area convulsed
in wars and weakened by natural disasters, also suffer the broadest
range of social and economic disadvantages, the United Nations
says.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, the Human Development Report, examines the
availability of schools, clean water and medical care, and whether
people can play a political role. It began 10 years ago as an
experiment to measure a nation's growth not by economic figures but
by statistical profiles of its people and what they could expect
from life.
</P>
<P>
   This year the report found that 30 of the 35 countries at the
bottom of the index were in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In that region, where the spread of AIDS and other diseases has
begun to shorten life spans after decades of slow improvement,
people can no longer expect to live beyond their 40s or 50s. Fewer
than half go to school and less than half _ sometimes 25 percent or
fewer _ can read, the survey shows. It also shows a large
proportion of people _ as high as 66 percent in the case of Sierra
Leone _ without access to clean water, and even larger majorities
lacking basic sanitation.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from Sierra Leone, which is ranked last, the other most
disadvantaged nations, in rising order, are Niger, Burkina Faso,
Ethiopia, Burundi, Guinea Bissau, Mozambique, Chad, the Central
African Republic and Mali.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme, the countries with the highest human
development indicators are, from the top, Canada, Norway, the
United States, Australia, Iceland, Sweden, Belgium, the
Netherlands, Japan and Britain. In the Western Hemisphere, only
Haiti ranks in the bottom 35 nations.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, the report, produced by the U.N. Development
Program, focuses on new themes that experts say should be factored
into studying why some countries remain poor and others grow in
economic and human terms. This year the report tried to connect the
importance of human rights and political freedoms with economic and
social conditions, saying the two could no longer be separated. It
challenges the view of some political leaders that people are not
``ready'' for democracy until there has been economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human rights are not, as has sometimes been argued, a reward
of development,'' said Mark Malloch Brown, the development
program's administrator, in an introduction to the report.
``Rather, they are critical to achieving it. Only with political
freedoms _ the right for all men and women to participate equally
in society _ can people genuinely take advantage of economic
freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   In another departure, this year's report calls for the increased
collection and more effective use of statistics to aid in promoting
human rights by quantifying more effectively the conditions under
which many people live.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statistical indicators are a powerful tool in the struggle for
human rights,'' the report says. Among other benefits even the
simple collection of information can provide is help in monitoring
the actions of government and curbing corruption, it adds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1922EDT &QL; 
