<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI-NYT &LR;      06-29 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MIAMI CUBANS, HIGH POLITICAL AND SOCIAL COSTS OF ELIAN AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CUBA-LOBBY, CUBA-U.S.) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ She was 19 when she came here from Colombia 43 years
ago, but even working with a mop in her hand, Maria Hernandez
believed she had found paradise. Then Elian Gonzalez came, and in
the seven months of speeches, marches and conflict that followed,
her Miami changed.
</P>
<P>
   She was driving to work recently when a pickup flying American
flags pulled up beside her. ``I looked over, in that way people
glance over at each other at stoplights,'' said Hernandez, who now
owns a cleaning service.
</P>
<P>
   The man in the truck rolled down a window and made an obscene
gesture at her, because he thought she was Cuban-American, she
believes. She was not flying the American flag upside-down, the way
angry Cuban-Americans had, in protest. She was just going to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked at me with these mean eyes,'' she said, and she knew
her paradise was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Eckerd's to buy some things, and two cashiers were
fighting about Elian right in front of their customers,'' said
Hernandez, who is married to a Cuban-American and wanted Elian to
stay here.
</P>
<P>
   But the cost has been high. ``This is not the city I grew to
love. I have neighbors who do not speak to each other. People's
personalities have completely changed. I never knew there was so
much hate in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian _ the battle to keep him, the armed federal raid that took
him from Miami, and the courtroom decisions that sent him home to
Cuba _ widened racial and ethnic divisions that are part of Miami's
history.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps the saddest legacy of Elian, say experts on Cuban
exile history, immigration, international politics, but it is
hardly the only one.
</P>
<P>
   The fight to keep Elian in the United States became an
all-or-nothing battle for many Cuban-Americans, the dominant
culture in Miami, and it has cost them prestige and power. It has
changed the way that others around the country see them and their
cause, say experts on the community, and may even lead to an
improvement in U.S. relations with Cuban president Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not handled intelligently,'' said Lisandro Perez,
director of the Cuban Research Institute at Florida International
University. ``It was driven by emotions and passions, and you don't
act intelligently when you are driven by emotions and passions.''
</P>
<P>
   But leaders of the exiles said the fight was necessary, and
moral. And while it may have colored the way people view the
exiles, it drew younger people to an old cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has united the exile community,'' said Jose Basulto, the
president of Brothers to the Rescue, a group of Cuban-American
pilots who search the Florida Straits for rafters.
</P>
<P>
   As for its cost: ``I could care less what the American people
think about the Cuban exile community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it does matter, said political experts.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's saga ``has weakened the Cuban-American position'' in
many ways, said Perez. ``The anti-embargo position has been
strengthened and it's not because Americans suddenly realized Fidel
Castro is a good guy. It's because the Elian case has made
Cuban-Americans lose a lot of credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   As most of the nation seemed to believe that a 6-year-old boy
should be with his father, and the courts said that he should, too,
Cuban-Americans could not see beyond their hatred of Castro, say
political and immigration experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This became a bizarre experience where family, flag and police
_ all parts of the Republican trinity _ were attacked by
Cuban-Americans,'' said David Abraham, a professor of immigration
law at the University of Miami. ``There was the firing of the
police chief because he kept public order, and the desecration of
the flag, and it was very disconcerting to middle Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, it has ruined friendships and brought a strained
politeness to relationships.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Ann-Sofi Truby and a Cuban-American who does
maintenance at her house in South Miami had talked, ``about our
families, different things,'' said Truby, who has lived here nearly
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   They stopped talking during the Elian crisis. ``I would stay
inside while he was here,'' she said, because talk would end in
argument.
</P>
<P>
   During the demonstrations, Truby, who is in her 60s, bought an
American flag. She waved it from her Volvo whenever she saw
pro-Elian protesters. ``I would tell my grandson to roll down the
window and I would show them a `bird.'''
</P>
<P>
   There are no apologies being offered on either side.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us should feel extremely satisfied,'' said Ninoska
Perez, a spokeswoman for the Cuban American National Foundation, by
far the most powerful of the exile groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Castro had to wait until the judicial process came to an end''
to claim Elian, she said. ``For someone who has not respected any
laws during the last 41 years, that should be a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   But the way the Cuban-American power structure conducted itself
left many in Miami feeling alienated.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Alex Penelas of Miami-Dade County and Mayor Joe Carollo of
Miami made it clear that they sided with the exiles against the
federal government, drawing a backlash from around the country.
Then, Carollo fired his city manager and forced the resignation of
his police chief _ both Anglos _ and both vacancies were filled by
Cuban-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cuban exiles have shown such arrogance,'' said Garth
Reeves, the publisher emeritus of the city's black newspaper, The
Miami Times. ``They're saying, `This is our town now, and dammit,
we run it. We make the decisions''' to the exclusion of everyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   To Reeves, and to many black Miamians, the Cuban-Americans are a
pampered minority that became a pampered majority, and now _ at the
first major setback for them in recent history _ they denigrate the
country that gave them a haven.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush, who has enjoyed the support of Miami's Cuban
exiles, who vote mostly Republican, blamed the media for what he
called a misunderstanding of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's damaged _ incorrectly so _ the nature of
Cuban-Americans in Miami,'' said Bush. ``It breaks my heart to see
the national press depict people who have been lovers of freedom
the way that this has all played out.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Bush defended his constituency in Tallahassee, Miami's
Cuban exiles continued to vent their anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am never going to vote again,'' said Magaly Lima, 58, who
came to Miami 38 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some Cuban-Americans said that what happened with Elian is what
has always happened here, that the hard-liners who control the
city's politics painted all Cuban-Americans as closed-minded.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term impact may be economic. Social instability, said
economics experts, seldom leads to a strong economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These recent events have made Miami less attractive,'' said
Michael Connolly, chairman of the Economics Department at the
University of Miami School of Business. ``People are moving away if
they live here and aren't coming down here if they don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
