<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8685 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBA-LOBBY-NYT &LR;      06-29 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-LOBBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITS CAUSE HURT BY ELIAN AFFAIR, CUBAN-AMERICAN LOBBY TRIES TO
ADJUST 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CUBA-U.S., CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI) 
 By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After dominating the U.S. policy debate over Cuba
for nearly two decades, Cuban-American advocates of a hardline
stance toward Havana find themselves on the defensive, increasingly
estranged from other Americans, according to supporters and
critics.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Cuban American National Foundation, the
preeminent exile lobby, is reorganizing its leadership to include
younger faces and Thursday appointed a non-Cuban former State
Department expert on Cuba to head its Washington office.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami-based group is also targeting the districts of
congressional adversaries for television ads and pledging to spend
``whatever it takes'' to protect the unyielding U.S. policy it
helped to craft.
</P>
<P>
   With the return home this week of Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old
Cuban refugee, and an agreement in Congress to lift the ban on
sales of food and medicine to the island, Cuban exiles are
adjusting to a political landscape that increasingly favors
accommodation with President Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   The travails of the foundation, widely viewed as one of the most
effective ethnic lobbies in America, are emblematic of exiles' lost
political ground. The lobby's leaders this week portrayed their
remarkably prosperous community as an underdog, locked in a bitter,
moral struggle against Goliath: American farmers and corporations
bent on doing business with Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really have no choice but to respond in a very aggressive
way,'' said Jose Cardenas, the foundation's Washington director.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Garcia, the foundation's executive director, complained that
the Cuban lobby and its supporters have been bruised at the hands
of ``very good players'' in the public relations arena: Attorney
General Janet Reno, President Clinton and Castro himself.
</P>
<P>
   For some Cuba-watchers, such shifts mark a stark reversal from
the foundation's heyday under the iron-fisted stewardship of Jorge
Mas Canosa, a multimillionaire businessman who breezed through the
halls of Washington with the aura and the entourage of a head of
state.
</P>
<P>
   Under Mas Canosa's leadership, the well-financed lobby mustered
a stable of loyal congressional allies, drafted Cuba legislation,
established anti-Castro radio and television stations with federal
funds and kept U.S.-Cuban relations in a deep freeze despite the
end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   But since Mas Canosa's death in 1997, the exile community has
yet to put forth a national figure who commands both respect and
fear in Washington. Without such leadership, the foundation has
invited challengers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of Mas Canosa's son, who is also named
Jorge, the foundation ran into a public relations fiasco with the
Elian Gonzalez case. To an extent, it was self-inflicted. Within
hours of the boy's rescue from Florida waters last Thanksgiving,
the lobby was the first to convert Elian, literally, into a poster
child, distributing thousands of leaflets of him at the World Trade
Organization meeting in Seattle beneath the headline: ``Another
child victim of Fidel Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro quickly responded, portraying Elian as a kidnap victim,
being kept from a devoted father by an exile band of political
extremists. Americans who had paid little attention to the Cuba
policy debate tended to support the father's claim over exile
relatives in Miami, who insisted the boy be granted political
asylum.
</P>
<P>
   ``They showed what they were really all about,'' said Rep. Jim
McDermott, D-Wash., said of the Cuban-American hardliners. ``They
were ready to sacrifice one of their own kids, and they didn't
really care about separating him from his father.''
</P>
<P>
   Exile hardliners acknowledge missteps in handling the case. But
they deny it had any impact in what came next: a concerted drive by
U.S. business _ led by the Farm Bureau and the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce _ to open Cuba for business after 38 years of embargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that if there was any negativity surrounding the Elian
Gonzalez situation, it was pretty much self-contained,'' Cardenas
said. ``I think that basically people saw it as the equivalent of
the O.J. situation _ they just wanted it to be over, and out of
their living rooms,'' in a reference to the long saga surrounding
O.J. Simpson's murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Max Castro, a sociologist at the University of Miami's
North-South Center, disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   During the seven-month struggle over Elian, Castro said, people
who had paid little attention to U.S. policy toward Cuba began to
ask questions about the hardline policy. ``Americans have basically
said it's a policy that hasn't worked, and it's inconsistent with
the rest of our foreign policy,'' Castro said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by lawmakers representing wheat and rice growers,
congressional Republicans agreed this week to lift the ban on sales
of food to Cuba, a move that has already been approved by the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation officials portrayed the deal as merely symbolic,
noting that Congress' three Cuban-American lawmakers and other
allies had inserted language to deny cash-strapped Cuba any
financing by the federal government or U.S. banks.
</P>
<P>
   The lobby hurried efforts to regain its footing.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference Thursday, the foundation introduced a new
addition to its Washington office. Dennis Hays, a former U.S.
ambassador in Suriname, is slated to become executive vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Hays, who is not Cuban-American, endeared himself to many exiles
in 1995, when he asked to be reassigned from his post as director
of the State Department's office of Cuban affairs. Hays was
protesting an accord secretly negotiated between the Clinton
administration and the Castro government that allowed the forced
repatriation of Cuban refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has also sought to renovate its image in its
Miami headquarters, which has long been dominated by
Cuban-Americans from Mas Canosa's generation, who recall the trauma
of exile.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Garcia, an energetic 35-year-old former chairman of
Florida's Public Service Commission, recently took over day-to-day
responsibilities as the foundation's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Like the foundation's chairman, the 36-year-old Mas, Garcia has
never been to Cuba. He promises to update the foundation's image,
including ``more sophisticated'' media efforts to educate the
American people about Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``You certainly are going to see a reinvigorated foundation,''
said Garcia. He eschews the familiar ``bearded tyrant'' references
to President Castro, calling him instead ``this old goofball.''
</P>
<P>
   As a start, the foundation plans to run television
advertisements that highlight Castro's abuses. Beginning this
weekend, the foundation plans to air ads denouncing the safe haven
provided by Cuba to scores of fugitives from U.S. justice,
including Joanne Chesimard, who escaped from prison in 1979 after
being convicted for the murder of a New Jersey state trooper.
</P>
<P>
   The ads will air first in Washington, Cardenas said, but the
foundation plans to target the districts of key lawmakers who have
advocated an easing of sanctions, including Reps. George
Nethercutt, R- Wash., Republican, Jay Dickey, R-Ark., and Sens.
Blanche Lambert Lincoln, D-Ark., and Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott said foundation officials risk further isolating
themselves with such tactics. ``Threatening people is not going to
help them,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
