<HEADER>
A8690 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MENINGITIS0630-COX     06-29 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENINGITIS0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CDC: Students should know meningitis risk
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For Alan and Lynn Bozof, a new federal recommendation
released today that suggests some college students should get a
meningitis vaccine is a bittersweet victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Bozofs' 20-year-old son, Evan, died from bacterial
meningitis in 1998, after struggling with liver and lung failure
and undergoing amputations of his legs and arms in an attempt to
stop gangrene. An honor student and baseball pitcher, Evan first
became ill over spring break.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Bozofs were not even aware there was a vaccine
against the killer. But since Evan's death, they have pushed health
and college officials to educate students and their parents about
the benefits of vaccination.
</P>
<P>
   They have succeeded. In its Morbidity and Mortality Weekly
Report, the CDC states that colleges and health care providers
should make sure that college students _ especially incoming or
current freshman who plan to live in dorms _ are informed about the
disease and the vaccination.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation is based on research that found college
students, particularly freshman living in dorms, have an increased
risk for the disease compared with the general population. The
research indicates that meningococcal meningitis may be linked with
campus behavior, such as alcohol consumption, active and passive
smoking, intimate contact, shared utensils and irregular sleeping
and eating patterns.
</P>
<P>
   However, the federal agency stopped short of recommending that
all college students get vaccinated. The reason: Bacterial
meningitis is still primarily a stalker of the very young _ almost
40 percent of the 3,000 cases nationally involve children uounger
than 2. In contrast, about 100 cases annually involve college
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple fact is the risk is not so great (for the college
population) and we think that a blanket recommendation simply isn't
warranted,'' said Dr. Bradley Perkins, chief of the CDC's
Meningitis and Special Pathogens branch. ``But we do want people to
make an informed decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, the vaccine, which costs between $55 and $75, does not
protect against all strains of the meningitis. It protects against
four types of bacteria that cause meningitis in the United States,
which account for nearly two-thirds of the cases. Researchers hope
to see a more effective second-generation vaccine licensed soon.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, the state health department has no plans to
recommend widespread vaccination of college students. In the past
three years, two Georgia college students have died from the
illness. One was Bozof, a pre-med student at Georgia Southwestern
University in Americus, Ga.; the other was Charles Trevor Copp, 19,
a mechanical engineering major at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Copp, of suburban Atlanta, died last year shortly after
complaining of a headache. Another Georgia Tech student, Kevin
Moore, 22, of Columbus, Ga., also was diagnosed with the illness
within three days of Copp. He survived.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths helped spur an advisory panel to the state's Board of
Regents to issue a recommendation that college students should
consider the vaccine and schools should keep the vaccine in stock.
And according to the American College Health Association, more than
70 colleges and universities have policies recommending the
vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for the Bozofs, who organize programs to
immunize seniors at Georgia high schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day is long and hard without (Evan),'' said Lynn Bozof.
``But we're happy that we might help save another life somewhere
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
