<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-HAWKS-JOHNSON0630     06-29 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-JOHNSON0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks will have time for Johnson
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He's representative of those prodigies Miss Jones
talks about in the Nike TV spots, the kids who decide when they're
18, 19, 20 that they're ready for the grown-up world of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Why, Miss Jones asks, is it such a big deal when kids such as
DerMarr Johnson decide to turn pro, when we have grown to fully
accept teens playing pro golf, tennis, and baseball _ not to
mention 12-year-old figure skaters and gymnasts.
</P>
<P>
   Lon Kruger, in his second month as a pro coach, says its
cultural conditioning. ``We have traditional values for our
children,'' Kruger said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the world of the NBA, only No. 1 pick Kenyon Martin,
among the first 11 taken, actually played four years of college
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Johnson and the Hawks' staff made a symbolic climb to
the Hawks Nest in the upper reaches of Philips Arena, where Johnson
said, in a very matter of fact way, ``I was ready. I did what I
needed to achieve in college.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a year. One season. When the season ended in March, Johnson
stopped going to class. He knew where he was going. There was no
further need for math or English or social studies. He was still 19
when he made that decision.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing more that the college experience had to offer,
he says. ``I won't miss it. This is where I've been headed for a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   He actually looked into coming out after his junior year in high
school. But in that instance, there are rules that require a young
man to finish four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about coming our after my senior year in high
school,'' he said, guessing he might have gone top 15. He said he
is glad he waited. He moved up nine spots to six.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for my year in college,'' he said. ``I don't regret
it. There are a lot of values that I learned. I got a lot of
experience. I played with great players and I played for a great
coach.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the season was over, Johnson decided he was ready for
the next stop. ``I knew I was ready,'' he said. ``I did the things
I needed to do. I needed to improve my defense and I did that. Just
playing for Coach (Bob Huggins, a screamer) I got a lot done.''
</P>
<P>
   He played 32 games for a Cincinnati team ranked No. 1 until
Kenyon Martin broke his ankle in the second round of the Conference
USA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, someone asked Johnson how it felt to be
young and wealthy and on his own in a major city like Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the money (contract) yet,'' he said. ``I didn't
come out for the money. I came out because I was ready for the
NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ready'' is a matter of perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I spoke to D.J., I tried to talk to him about
staying in school,'' general manager Pete Babcock said, palms up in
a gesture of surrender. He recalled having the same conversation
last year with the less-accomplished Dion Glover, determined to
bolt Georgia Tech after a season. Babcock lost that argument and
took Glover with the 20th pick.
</P>
<P>
   Now Glover is a veteran of sorts, going one-on-one in the arena
practice gym against new assistant coach Rick Mahorn. Known for his
dedication to physical play, Mahorn will not allow Glover to call a
foul against him. Johnson, at 6-foot-9, 201 pounds, is four inches
taller and 30 pounds lighter than Glover. He will either get
stronger or Mahorn may break him in two.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will get stronger. He's got a great work ethic,'' Kruger
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Babcock recalled that Kevin Garnett grew over two summers after
being drafted out of high school by Minnesota. ``We think it's
great to have a 6-9 guard and, who knows, we could end up with a
6-10 guard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do whatever they want me to do,'' Johnson said,
maintaining a poker face under a long-brimmed Hawks cap that looked
absurd on a young giant wearing a suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bring whatever Coach Kruger wants me to bring to the
game,'' Johnson said, but his game will do the talking. It will
make the statements that he is too shy to verbalize.
</P>
<P>
   But he knows he can play. ``Oh, yeah, there's a lot I haven't
shown. I didn't show my whole game last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing with Martin and another senior, Pete Mickeal, Johnson's
game at Cincinnati was catch and shoot, block some shots, pass the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   One night against Louisville he broke a 2-3-2 zone with five
straight 3-pointers. In back-to-back games against Marquette and
South Florida, he took the defensive assignment against their best
scorers and held them to a combined 4-for-15.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got great athleticism, great talent, great work ethic,''
Kruger said. ``All he needs is time.''
</P>
<P>
   Time? He's 20 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
