<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMERCE-MINETA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PICKS FORMER CONGRESSMAN TO BE COMMERCE SECRETARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Thursday nominated a former
congressman, Norman Mineta, as secretary of commerce for the final
six months of his presidency, laying the groundwork for Mineta to
become the first Asian-American to hold a Cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta, a Democrat, retired from the House in 1995 after 21
years representing the area of San Jose, Calif. He had been
chairman of the Public Works and Transportation Committee, and
resigned in 1995 to become a senior vice president at Lockheed
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   If confirmed by the Senate, Mineta would replace William Daley,
who will formally step down on July 15 to become campaign chairman
for Vice President Al Gore's presidential bid. He would be
Clinton's fourth commerce secretary, following Mickey Kantor and
the late Ron Brown, as well as Daley.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta is 68. During World War II, when he was 10, his family
was loaded onto a train and taken to an internment camp in Wyoming
for Americans of Japanese descent. Years later, as a lawmaker,
Mineta helped pass legislation granting $20,000 in compensation to
every Japanese-American who had been interned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norm Mineta's family story tells a lot about the promise of
the American dream and the power of one person's devotion to
opportunity and to justice,'' Clinton said in announcing the
selection Thursday morning in the Oval Office. Along with Mineta,
the president was joined by Daley and Robert Mallett, the deputy
commerce secretary, who had been a finalist for the top job.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination brought immediate praise from Asian-American
organizations. One side benefit of the selection, in the view of
administration officials, is that it may help blunt criticism from
Asian-Americans that followed the firing of Wen Ho Lee, the
government scientist accused of mishandling secrets at the Los
Alamos National Laboratory. Some Asian-Americans have also
expressed unhappiness over the scrutiny people of Asian descent
have faced during the investigations of campaign fund-raising
abuses in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will go a long way toward bridging the divide,''
Mineta said in an interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta acknowledged that, even with a quick confirmation, his
time in Clinton's Cabinet would be short. But he said that he was
not taking the job as a caretaker, and that he believed the
Commerce Department would remain active until the very end of the
president's term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some might say that the months remaining in this
administration is not a lot of time to make a difference in the
life of our nation,'' Mineta said. ``But I disagree. Six months is
a virtual eternity in the new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mineta's decision to leave the House to go into private business
with a year to go in his term, and just 10 months after Republicans
seized control of Congress, rankled some of his Democratic
colleagues at the time. A Republican, Rep. Tom Campbell, won
Mineta's seat in a special election. Key Republican senators and
supporters predicted a quick confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a guy who will do very well in the sprint to the
end,'' said Tom Donahue, president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
``He knows Congress well, and they know him.''
</P>
<P>
   Some union leaders also praised Mineta, saying their main
concern with him was his support for the Clinton Administration's
free trade agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody, however, was enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If his congressional voting record is any measure, he's
clearly out of touch with small business,'' said Nelson Litterst, a
spokesman for the National Federation for Independent Business.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a considerable salary increase when he went into the
private sector, Mineta had clearly not turned his back entirely on
politics. He served as an informal adviser to Gore's presidential
effort and had recently considered a run for his old seat in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second time Mineta had been offered a Cabinet post,
he said. In 1992, President-elect Clinton considered Mineta for
transportation secretary, and Mineta said Thursday that he had been
offered the job but turned it down. He was about to become a
committee chairman, and thought he could assist his party more in
that capacity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly eight years later, when another Cabinet offer came,
Mineta jumped at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   John Podesta, the president's chief of staff, called Mineta last
Friday to gauge his availability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you interested?'' Podesta asked.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta said he responded without hesitation: ``Do you want me to
crawl through the telephone line to your office right now?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
