<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8699 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-SENIORS-COLUMN-$ADV &LR; 0     06-29 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIORS-COLUMN-$ADV </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MADISON AVENUE FANTASY 
</HEADLINE>
 0 2-NYT   (For release Sunday, July 2)  
 (Editors: Double dashes beginning in 3rd graf are substituting for
bullets.)  
 By   FRED BROCK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hit television show ``Survivor'' is credited with
rejuvenating CBS, attracting loads of those coveted viewers between
18 and 49. That means the network, which mature Americans have long
called their own, can now sell more ads at higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   What remains difficult to understand is why Network Row and
Madison Avenue think young eyeballs are worth more to them than
older ones.
</P>
<P>
   Consider these statistics:
</P>
<P>
   __ Seven baby boomers will turn 50 every minute until 2014,
according to American Demographics magazine.
</P>
<P>
   __ People over 50 have half the nation's disposable income, and
those over 65 enjoy twice the discretionary income of people 25 to
34, according to Theodore Roszak, the author of ``America the Wise:
The Longevity Revolution and the True Wealth of Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The net worth of households headed by people over 60 grew by
30 percent over the last decade, double the national average,
according to a recent survey by the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   So what's going on? Why are advertisers acting like a bunch of
anti-Willie Suttons, aiming where the money increasingly isn't?
</P>
<P>
   Roszak suggests that corporate America and its media are at war
with the Census Bureau. In a 1998 article in Civilization, the
magazine of the Library of Congress, he put it succinctly: ``The
young are a vanishing breed. The future lies with the old.''
</P>
<P>
   While war may be too strong a metaphor, and the young aren't
really about to vanish, there is little doubt that the advertising
industry is generally well behind the curve of America's changing
demographic landscape. The reason may lie in the demographics of
the advertising business, where many decisions are made by people
in their 20s and 30s who have only the vaguest notion of, or
interest in, life past 50.
</P>
<P>
   Ann A. Fishman, 58, the president of the Generational-Targeted
Marketing Corp. in New Orleans, recalls a meeting she once had at
an ad agency in New York. ``I was struck by the fact that every
person I met except one was young,'' she said. ``But you can't have
one age group watching the store. You wind up not being sensitive
to the various generational groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the disconnect between Madison Avenue and demographic
reality more obvious than inside the covers of Modern Maturity,
published every other month by AARP. The magazine has two versions,
for working and retired subscribers, and a total circulation of
20.5 million, the largest of any magazine and almost double each of
its two closest competitors, Reader's Digest and TV Guide,
according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations. By further
comparison, Ladies' Home Journal and Good Housekeeping have a
circulation of 4.5 million each; Time magazine's is 4.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   But you would never guess the circulation of Modern Maturity
from its advertising volume. Publications aimed at younger people _
like women's fashion magazines, or Maxim for young men, or Fast
Company or Red Herring, which focus on technology, business and the
Internet _ attract so much advertising that they can be as fat as
phone books. But not Modern Maturity.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this youth-market myopia, however, is likely to fade as
the 80 million baby boomers and their money decamp into the golden
years.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Novelli, associate executive director of public affairs for
AARP, says Modern Maturity is trying to position itself to rise
with the boomer tide. In 1998, the organization ditched its old
name, the American Association of Retired Persons. Surveys and
focus groups show that boomers hate words like ``retired'' that
remind them of ``old.'' A lot of people in their 60s and 70s don't
think of themselves as old, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are big changes coming in the magazine,'' he said.
``It's going to become more of a lifestyle magazine, more vibrant
and youthful in its aim. We think we have enough elasticity to
appeal to both the 55-year-olds and the 75-year-olds.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent covers, featuring celebrities like Paul Newman, Judge
Judy and Cheryl Tiegs, are signals of the changes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said executives are considering a switch to monthly
publication, the addition of newsstand sales and, perhaps, a change
in name.
</P>
<P>
   The repositioning will make the magazine more boomer-friendly
just as the advertising industry is about to be jerked into reality
by that aging group and its buying power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Media buyers and media planners are young,'' Novelli said. ``A
mind change has to take place. But they are awakening.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet: Modern Maturity, which already charges advertisers about
one-third as much per subscriber as Time does, is considering
cutting its ad rates.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
