<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8708 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MAGLEV-RAIL0630-COX     06-29 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGLEV-RAIL0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    $1 billion in federal funds would help build high-speed rail
line from airport.
 &HT;    By Kelly Simmons
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's all over but the waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Regional Commission today will mail in its
application for $1 billion in federal money to begin building the
country's first magnetic levitation rail line.
</P>
<P>
   By Sept. 30, Atlanta _ and six other U.S. cities _ will find out
which of them has been selected to receive the money and the
economic development windfall expected to accompany it.
</P>
<P>
   ARC planner Bob McCord, who led the maglev study, said Thursday
that while Federal Railroad Administration officials won't say how
Atlanta stacks up against other cities competing for the project,
they have been encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `You guys in Atlanta have come a long way.' They're
very complimentary,'' McCord said. ``That tells me we've gotten
their attention, that we're competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed maglev project in Atlanta would run 32 miles
between Hartsfield International Airport in Clayton County to Town
Center in Kennesaw. Eventually, the line would be extended to
Chattanooga.
</P>
<P>
   Maglev lines use powerful magnetic fields to lift train cars
above the rail, propelling them with electricity at speeds of up to
300 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is seeking to build the first demonstration leg of a
rail line. The elevated track would roughly follow I-75. Four
stations are proposed: at the airport; near the Vine City MARTA
station; at Cumberland/Galleria; and at Town Center near Kennesaw
State University. The train would travel at 80 mph to 120 mph
through Atlanta, reaching a top speed of 240 mph. Fares would range
from $4.75 to $27.25 to travel the full length of the route.
</P>
<P>
   The initial 32-mile rail line is expected to cost about $2.2
billion. That cost _ about $57 million per mile _ is not out of
line with other rail projects in the region. New MARTA rail lines
cost about $100 million per mile, according to the ARC.
</P>
<P>
   About one-third of the maglev cost must come from local sources.
McCord said the ARC, Georgia Department of Transportation and the
Georgia Regional Transportation Authority have pledged to come up
with $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   In-kind contributions from private companies are included in the
local match. Companies that are interested in taking part in the
project include Georgia Power Co., which would provide electricity
to operate the rail line; and Lockheed Martin, which could assemble
rail cars and possibly operate the system, McCord said. The ARC
estimates the project could generate 6,000 new jobs for the region.
</P>
<P>
   The other areas vying to build the maglev line are Los Angeles,
Pittsburgh, New Orleans, Las Vegas, Washington-Baltimore and
Florida's Cape Canaveral.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
