<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-UNHAPPY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE MOVES BY HMOS, DOCTORS SAY THEY'RE STILL UNHAPPY 
</HEADLINE>
 DOCTORS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LIZ KOWALCZYK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Despite the promise that HMOs would take care of the
details and let doctors be doctors, Massachusetts physicians are
complaining that they are more miserable than ever.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of 1,400 physicians released Thursday, one-quarter
said they are ``very dissatisfied'' with managed care, five times
the number who were unhappy four years ago. The dissatisfaction has
grown even though health insurance companies say they've worked
hard to improve life in the exam room since the first statewide
survey in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors' most persistent complaints were that managed care
companies took too long to pay their bills and to approve referrals
to psychologists and psychiatrists. Physicians rated the different
health plans more similarly this year, but were overall more
negative about them as a group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spend an hour a day on the phone trying to get referrals,''
said Dr. Virginia Latham, an internist and president of the
Massachusetts Medical Society, as she announced the results.
``That's 12 patients I could have spent five more minutes with.
These problems aren't just hassles that bother doctors personally.
They prevent them from caring for patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Few professionals have their happiness on the job monitored and
measured the way doctors do. But when managed care _ the movement
to control health care costs _ began sweeping through the state in
the early 1990s, doctors began to feel beleaguered. So the medical
society decided to try and figure out the specific problems and
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   But as is typical in Boston health care, where the players have
known each for years and politeness is valued, the medical society
invited the health plans to join them in the study. And Thursday,
as doctors ran down their list of gripes at a news conference, HMO
executives patiently listened and then had their chance to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians are very unhappy and much more unhappy than the
last time around,'' said Paul D. Cleary of Harvard Medical School,
a researcher who helped conduct the study for the medical society
and the HMOs. ``The thing is, we don't understand why. The specific
things we looked at don't seem to account for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Physicians were asked to rate five different health plans: Blue
Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts, Harvard Pilgrim Health
Care, Tufts Health Plan, Fallon Community Health Plan and Health of
New England. They rated the availability of behavioral health
services as poor, with Fallon receiving the lowest score.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors scored claims processing as fair to good and the ease of
appealing denied claims as fair, with Harvard Pilgrim fairing the
worst on both counts. For all the plans _ except for Health of New
England, which was not part of the 1996 survey _ doctors said they
are less likely to recommend them to their families now than they
were four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robin S. Richman, medical director for Tufts, said that when
the HMOs received results from the first survey in 1996, they tried
to fix the complaints with a host of new programs. Tufts reduced
turnaround time for paying claims by 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim substantially reduced the number of procedures
requiring pre-authorization from the health plan. And HMO Blue, the
HMO run by Blue Cross Blue Shield of Massachusetts, adopted an
electronic referral system. Together, the HMOs instituted a joint
credentialing procedure for physicians joining their networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite that, when we look at the dissatisfaction it didn't
seem to be enough,'' Richman said. ``This may reflect more
discontent with the general health care environment. We will
certainly do our part _ as much of it as is in our control.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph L. Dorsey, medical director for Harvard Pilgrim, said
that even though his employer drew the worst scores on paying
claims, the survey was conducted during the health plan's most
chaotic period: last June to November. Harvard Pilgrim was forced
into state receivership in January and just released this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Claims are going through like greased lightening now,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The medical directors said that most doctors still submit their
claims, or bills, on paper through the mail _ although the rate
varies by health plan. Blue Cross receives 85 percent of claims
electronically while Tufts receives less than 40 percent
electronically.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic transactions ``are the direction we all need to go
in. But that requires significant investment,'' said Blue Cross
Chief Medical Officer Dr. Kurt Sligar.
</P>
<P>
   ``And right now we're all broke,'' added Dr. Thomas Ebert of
Health of New England in western Massachusetts.
</P>
</TEXT>
