<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8719 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALICE-NEEL-PAINTINGS-     06-29 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALICE-NEEL-PAINTINGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKING OF PAINTERS, ALICE NEEL'S PAINTINGS SPEAK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Colo., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alice Neel could be witheringly blunt. ``Art is not
as stupid as human conversation,'' she was once quoted as saying. I
wrote it down and pinned it up at my desk, struck by its weirdness.
In its unequivocal dismissal of daily discourse, Neel's remark
gives one a glimpse of a certain darkness: the misanthropy and
self-protective brutality that, along with more positive instincts,
may be part of the commitment to being an artist.
</P>
<P>
   Neel, who died in 1984 at the age of 84, acted on that
commitment for nearly 60 years, making some of the 20th century's
best paintings, especially portraits, as demonstrated by the
illuminating but insufficient retrospective of her work that opened
Thursday at the Whitney Museum of American Art and remains through
Sept. 17. It has been organized by Ann Temkin, the curator of
modern and contemporary art at the Philadelphia Museum of Art, and
will make four more stops over the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, Neel also knew how to use her mouth. She
negotiated the bureaucracies of the WPA and public assistance and
was active in artists' political groups throughout her life. She
gave pithy interviews as interest in her work grew.
</P>
<P>
   Neel was known for talking almost nonstop as she painted her
subject, often detailing the amazing ups and downs of her colorful
life, with its poverty, many love affairs, radical politics and
children born out of wedlock. She lived her life exactly as she
pleased and said so. A round-table discussion about the experience
of sitting for Neel appears in the catalog, and the painter Benny
Andrews recalls that she told him: ``I'm cursed to be in this
Mother Hubbard body. I am a real sexy person.''
</P>
<P>
   You can almost hear Neel talking at the Whitney. Talking to her
friends, lovers, children and grandchildren as she painted them.
Talking strangers into sitting for her, like the lean, nattily
dressed Fuller Brush man whom she painted in 1965, learning in the
process that he was a Holocaust survivor. Talking people who had
already agreed to pose into doing so nude.
</P>
<P>
   An innate egalitarian, Neel had to be voluble and gregarious to
have painted so many people unlike herself. From her Greenwich
Village bohemia phase of the 1930s, there is a demonic portrait of
Joe Gould, the slightly-crazed, Harvard-educated street person
immortalized in Joseph Mitchell's famous New Yorker article, whom
she depicted with three sets of genitals.
</P>
<P>
   From her days in Spanish Harlem, where she lived in the 1940s
and '50s, first with a singer named Jose Santiago and then with the
photographer and filmmaker Sam Brody, there is something of a
rainbow coalition of faces: from 1959, twin black girls, no older
than 4 or 5, stare up at the artist with quiet curiosity; from
1955, Georgie Arce, a friendly Hispanic youth, is seen against a
lush pink background; from 1946, a dark-haired young woman in a
red-striped blouse leans against a wall of arabesque-patterned
wallpaper, looking like a Semitic princess.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1960s and '70s, when Neel finally began to get the
critical attention she deserved, there are portraits of art-world
figures: the dealer Elinor Poindexter looking almost as loony as
Joe Gould; a withdrawn Andy Warhol stripped to the waist, the awful
scars of Valerie Solanas' assassination attempt mapping his sunken
chest; and the art critics (and at the time lovers) Gregory
Battcock and David Bourdon, their differences signaled by the first
being in his underwear and the other in a suit and tie.
</P>
<P>
   It seems fitting that Neel's distinctive expressionistic
realism, as some critics called it, can be described as extremely
loquacious. In her mature work all the parts of each painting have
their say: colors carry on one conversation, textures and brushwork
another, her oddly distorted bodies, limbs and facial features a
third. The avid expressions on most of Neel's subjects, which
contribute greatly to her work's intensity, show that they were
listening to her, often riveted.
</P>
<P>
   If Neel's life was a big subject, her art is too, and this
exhibition indicates that without doing it justice. The timing
could not have been better. Portraiture and figurative painting are
abundant; the body continues to be a consuming subject; and art
about identity, sexuality and orientation is increasingly nonverbal
and representational.
</P>
<P>
   But the show feels cramped. It is top-heavy with the portraits
of her last 25 years, when she mostly painted members of the art
world or her family. These include many strong pictures, one being
the portrait of a young, nervous Robert Smithson surrounded by
agitated brushwork from 1962, when Smithson was an unknown painter
of Expressionistic, cartoony canvases, not yet a bad-boy earth
artist.
</P>
<P>
   The show's smallness and imbalance short-change the first 35
years of Neel's career and also her work in landscape, genre and
still life. A few exceptions include a wonderful early still life,
``Symbols'' from 1933, with its sweet yet subtly sexual arrangement
of doll and apples, and a powerful later one, ``Thanksgiving'' from
1967. This work, in which Neel depicts the dead fowl of traditional
still-life painting plucked and draining in a kitchen sink, is one
of several instances in which she brings an art-historical subject
down to earth with a specifically feminist thud.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition perpetuates the picture of Neel as a late bloomer
when in fact she was also precocious, creating original work true
to herself and her time at nearly every stage of her career. In
this regard she is very much like Stuart Davis, six years her
senior. Like Davis, Neel in her early work operates fruitfully in
the gap between the pioneering American modernists of the Stieglitz
circle and the Abstract Expressionists.
</P>
<P>
   While Davis translated Cubism into an American vernacular, Neel
was drawn to the Expressionism of Munch and van Gogh. Her
translation incorporated elements of the Ash Can School and
American Scene painting and Social Realism. It also drew from the
straightforward evocation of American faces in the photographs of
Lewis W. Hine, Walker Evans and Helen Levitt (a point that Susan
Rosenberg, the assistant curator in Philadelphia, develops in her
catalog essay), the emotionally resonant simplifications of
American folk art and at times the hallucinatory strangeness of
Charles Burchfield. In the end, Neel, like Davis, benefited from
the bolder tactics of Abstract Expressionism and Pop, making her
work an indelible part of postwar American art.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great story, as is Neel's life, but it exceeds the limits
of this often rewarding show. This failure is partly architectural,
a reflection of the Whitney's constricting ``one floor one artist''
approach. Neel should not be a one-floor artist. Her six-decade
career deserves to be examined chapter and verse, on paper and
canvas, which would require at least one-and-a-half if not two of
the Whitney's floors. It's all the more galling that downstairs
from Neel, a dozen large recent works by Robert Rauschenberg loll
about in oceans of space. Maybe this show will grow a bit as it
proceeds on its tour. At present, it keeps Neel in her modest,
somewhat marginalized place, a position that the Whitney was
created to subvert.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
