<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8721 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-LAND-AND-HOLD-BOS &LR;      06-29 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAND-AND-HOLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT DELAYS LINKED TO CONTROVERSIAL RUNWAY PROCEDURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Ill., Fla.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Passengers flying in and out of Logan International
Airport this summer should be prepared for long delays, up to two
hours for some arriving flights, and the cause has nothing to do
with weather or antiquated air-traffic control equipment.
</P>
<P>
   A widespread pilot boycott of a landing procedure used on
intersecting runways is causing numerous lengthy delays at Logan as
well as Chicago's O'Hare and Miami International airports. Pilots
say they were forced into the action because of recent government
changes to the procedure, known as land and hold short operations,
or LAHSO, have not been adequately tested for safety by the Federal
Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is causing a lot of pain to this airport, mainly with the
arrival rate,'' said Massport aviation director Thomas J. Kinton.
</P>
<P>
   Under the procedure, which is designed to increase capacity at
airports, a landing plane is directed to stop and hold short of an
intersecting runway used by departing planes or other landing
planes. When pilots use the procedure, Logan can accept 58 to 60
arriving airplanes an hour. Without it, that rate drops to 38 and
hour. The procedure is used at Logan when there is a southwest wind
_ the prevailing wind in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA says the boycott is affecting air travel throughout the
nation during the busy summer season, which has also been plagued
by weather-related delays. From June 1 through June 19, 514 flights
were delayed at O'Hare International Airport because of the
boycott, 242 flights in Boston were held up, and 101 at Miami
International Airport did not arrive or depart on time. The agency
would not provide updated figures.
</P>
<P>
   The boycott is also causing frustration for controllers
confronted with rebellious pilots who have refused requests to use
the landing procedure _ an action virtually unheard of in the
crisp, precise relationship between pilots and air-traffic control.
</P>
<P>
   Several sources said controllers in Boston have had to deal with
planes that agreed to use the procedure when they departed for
Boston but refused to perform it on final approach to Logan. In
Chicago, some pilots have refused controllers' requests to exit
onto a high-speed taxiway to make way for other planes and instead
have continued down an active runway.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure has been used for nearly 30 years, and Logan was
involved in testing it in the 1970s. But the number of planes,
passengers and flights have jumped dramatically since then _ along
with delays. As a result, about two years ago, the FAA proposed
augmenting the procedure to increase capacity at airports like
Logan where runways intersect.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA changes included asking foreign pilots and some general
aviation pilots to use the procedure and formalizing rules under
which a pilot can abort a LAHSO landing. The changes were set to be
adopted last month, but pilot protests prompted the FAA not to
include foreign and general aviation pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Line Pilots Association, which represents some 58,000
pilots in the United States and Canada, said the final order still
raised safety concerns, however, and urged all pilots not to
perform the landing procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``In layman's terms, the essence of a LAHSO procedure is that it
takes two airplanes that are on, or are approaching, two
intersecting runways, aims them at each other, and trusts the
system will keep them from actually colliding,'' Duane Woerth, the
association's president, said last month in announcing the union's
boycott.
</P>
<P>
   Runway incursions have been increasing in recent years, despite
efforts by the FAA to reduce them. More than 45 people were killed
in runway collisions in the last decade and the world's worst
commercial aviation accident occurred in Tenerife when two 747s
collided, killing 583 people.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot's union is still concerned that the FAA's land and
hold short system is not completely safe because the agency has not
adequately tested the ramifications of a pilot aborting the landing
procedure just as another plane is taking off.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stay in the air because you rejected a landing and the
guy taking off may or may not be aware of it, so his options are
limited and your options are limited,'' said a union official, who
requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The union has said that once issue of aborted landings is
resolved, it would advise pilots to accept requests to use the
landing procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't afford to have even one pilot miss the message that
the safety of rejected landing procedures in the LAHSO environment
is questionable,'' said Woerth. ``The best way to ensure universal
understanding is to keep the message simple: We recommend that
pilots not participate in any LAHSO at any airport until all safey
questions are answered.''
</P>
<P>
   FAA spokesman William Shumann said the agency is working closely
with the union, air-traffic controllers and the airlines on
computer modeling of rejected landing procedures. But those talks
have been going on for more than a year, and Shumann said there is
no timetable for settling the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Until there is a resolution, airline passengers and air traffic
controllers are caught in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly appreciate the safety concerns being raised by
pilots, but my plea is why can't we at least go back to what was
acceptable for the pilot community before and practiced for nearly
30 years,'' said Massport's Kinton. ``This has knocked capacity at
some airports back to the mid-1970s.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinton said delays at Logan are typically 15 to 30 mintues for
outbound flights and one to two hours inbound. The inbound delays
are so significant that planes are held on the ground in other
cities by air traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA was giving pilots who agreed to use the landing
procedure an earlier release time from their departure airports,
but pilots accepting the early release then changed their minds
when they were cleared to land at Logan, Kinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Planes from the southern airports bound for Boston are sequenced
into a pattern that begins over North Carolina. To have a plane
cleared for landing and then reject a LAHSO landing can result in
its being pulled out of the sequence at the last minute and put
into a holding pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, controllers are scrambling around,'' said
William Blackmer, director of safety and technology for the
National Air Traffic Controllers Association.
</P>
<P>
   And controllers are certain that once planes are circled around
back into the landing pattern, the pilot tells passengers the delay
is due to air traffic, not on the decision to refuse to implent the
landing procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The frustration level in Boston is very high,'' said Wade
Stanfield, safety committee chairman for the controllers' union.
For the airlines, the boycott is yet another headache in a season
of delays, many of which are weather-related. ``We are already in
an awful delay season and it is unfortunate that pilots are
refusing the procedure,'' said David Fuscus, a spokesman for the
Air Transport Association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
