A8723 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PRAISE-FILM-REVIEW-NY     06-29 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAISE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRAISE': SQUALID WORLD OF 2 LOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes at end of review)  
 By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gordon is the epitome of slacker, a slender string of a
do-nothing whose passivity is part of his charm. As played by Peter
Fenton in the Australian film ``Praise,'' an absorbing tale of
sexual obsession, Gordon has a wasted charisma. He's the kind of
guy who sits alone at the end of the bar and still radiates a
forlorn arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   He has the look of a poet, if not exactly the soul of one, which
is probably what attracts Cynthia (Sacha Horler). She sizes up this
Slim Jim, peels away the wrapper and goes to work, and her appetite
pulls him into an affair. He is dragged into it by her neediness
and her fury, and Cynthia's robust fearlessness is the crucial
element in this romantic melodrama, which is so vivid you can smell
the anxiety pouring off the lovers' flesh.
</P>
<P>
   You can see it on hers, as she suffers from eczema so severe
that her skin has huge patches that are mottled and raw; her nerve
endings cry out for attention. And if Gordon isn't just the man to
give it, then she'll take it from him. (He has physical problems,
too, among them asthma and heroin addiction.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Praise'' has been burning up the track on the film festival
circuit for two years. I have yet to see it with an audience that
hasn't stood outside the theater caught up in conversation
afterward. It's Tennessee Williams with the ragged heedlessness of
post-punk; it could be more haunted only if the soundtrack included
the dolorous moan of the underground rock band Low. (The soundtrack
itself, by Dirty Three, is quite good and worth seeking out, though
very hard to find.)
</P>
<P>
   And that glint of trouble is probably what has scared
distributors away. As Gordon and Cynthia tumble into a squalid
world where they focus more and more on each other, things get
worse. Essentially the movie is plotless. The director, John
Curran, working with the writer Andrew McGahan, doesn't linger on
unrelenting unpleasantness. There are jolts of humor in the big,
empty room littered with beer bottles where Cynthia spends most of
her time falling all over Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Praise'' is uncanny and sizzling because it has the apparently
aimless feel of a bad love affair of youth, the kind of story you
would overhear the thoughtless Gordon telling somebody; you would
move your chair closer to catch every seamy, and often hilarious,
detail. That seemingly floating quality, as the relationship slumps
into one bad incident after another, is precisely what Curran
wants. For him the film's explicit detail spells out the
compulsiveness of his characters, something that keeps them
together.
</P>
<P>
   Horler's frank performance is something else that keeps
``Praise'' together. With all the predictable bad taste in films,
it's quite something to be startled not by mean-spirited jokes, but
by an actress' openness. And her Cynthia, who is given to wearing
sleeveless dresses to expose the eruptions on her skin and her soft
fleshiness, is utterly aware that she and Gordon are wrong for each
other and determined to stay the course anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Pungent, poignant and full of honest sentiment, ``Praise'' has a
complicated emotional intelligence that is hard to come by in
movies these days. Some viewers may find the dissipation
self-conscious or arty; the meticulousness of Curran's direction
and Dion Beebe's cinematography, as well as the carefully appointed
mess of Cynthia and Gordon's living quarters, are hard to miss.
Then again, there are always those who look for reasons that a
movie that affects them isn't worth their time, even as the picture
sticks with them. And ``Praise'' will stick with you. It's more
than worthy of its title. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PRAISE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by John Curran; written by Andrew McGahan, based on his
novel; director of photography, Dion Beebe; edited by Alexandre de
Franceschi; music by Dirty Three; production designer, Michael
Philips; produced by Martha Coleman; released by Strand Releasing.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Peter Fenton (Gordon), Sacha Horler (Cynthia), Marta
Dusseldorp (Rachel), Joel Edgerton (Leo), Yvette Duncan (Molly),
Ray Bull (Vass), Gregory Perkins (Raymond) and Loene Carmen
(Cathy).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 98 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Praise'' is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
