<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-AFTERMATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION FOES TO CONTINUE PUSH FOR FEDERAL PARTIAL-BIRTH BAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wounded but unbowed by a blow from the US Supreme
Court, antiabortion leaders Thursday vowed to press on for a
federal ban on so-called partial-birth abortions, to insist the GOP
not waver on a human-life amendment in its platform, and to defeat
Al Gore in the presidential election in November.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Wednesday's ruling that struck down Nebraska's ban
on certain abortion procedures energized the activists to demand
that Texas Governor George W. Bush make abortion politics a more
prominent part of his presidential campaign _ a commitment he has
been trying to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Governor Bush is where he needs to be on
abortion, and we have a responsibility to get him there,'' said
Judie Brown, president of the American Life League, an antiabortion
advocacy group. Brown said her phones have been ``ringing off the
hook'' since the ruling. ``Our people want to know what it means,
why did it happen, and what can they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who opposes abortion rights and Wednesday pledged to fight
for a ban on what he called ``the brutal practice of partial-birth
abortion,'' has been criticized by social conservatives for
refusing to apply an antiabortion litmus test to his choice of a
running mate and any prospective nominees for the Supreme Court. To
prove he is a ``compassionate conservative'' and to woo women who
support the right to choose, Bush rarely brings up the abortion
issue as he campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has tried to be open and down the middle about abortion,
but now it is going to be much more diffcult to be in the middle,''
said Susan Cullman, who co-chairs the Republican Pro-Choice
Coalition. ``The Supreme Court decision will arouse the right wing
and encourage them to be stronger. That is good news for the
prochoice people, but it is not good news for our candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Reed, a consultant to Bush and a former executive director
of the Christian Coalition schooled in grass-roots abortion
politics, said he did not expect the Supreme Court's ruling to have
much impact on the centrist course of the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for Bush to remain true to his conservative
principles, but you win elections by talking about the issues on
which voters in the middle are turning, and that's education,
expanding the circle of prosperity, and Social Security,'' Reed
said. ``Those are the issues that will decide this election.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who supports abortion rights and frequently talks about it
in campaign speeches, praised the court's decision, while his
campaign delighted in the news that the high court was stirring up
passions over abortion again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision brings the issue closer to home for more voters,
and by virtue of that, it will loom larger in our campaign,'' said
Douglas Hattaway, a Gore spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   There was no disagreement between advocates and foes on the
stakes in this election: The Supreme Court, which ruled 5-4 that
certain abortion procedures are unconstitutional, is more closely
divided than ever on the issue that continues to polarize the
country. With three of the justices at least 70 years old, the
probability is high that the next president will get one or more
nominees and the opportunity to tip the court's balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When two candidates are absolutely and diametrically opposed
to each other on a woman's right to choose, it is our challenge to
repeat over and over again to American voters that the Supreme
Court is at risk,'' said Alice Germond, executive vice president of
the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League.
</P>
<P>
   NARAL officials have told Warren Christopher, the former
secretary of state who is leading Gore's search for a running mate,
that the choice of Indiana Senator Evan Bayh would be ``very
problematic'' because last year he voted in favor of legislation to
ban what opponents call partial-birth abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there is a clear difference between Bush and Gore,
and to confuse that in any way would make it more difficult to
mobilize activists and voters,'' Germond said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, who opposed Bush in the GOP primaries, said Bush has
to learn from Democrats that you need to secure your core
supporters, in his case, conservatives, before veering to the
center. ``Prolife people are pretty depressed and are looking for
more reassurance that a Bush presidency would matter,'' Bauer said.
``In the wake of the Supreme Court decision, it would be a
political mistake for him to pick a prochoice running mate, water
down the GOP platform, or avoid the abortion issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer and representatives of a number of conservative groups
were on Capitol Hill Thursday pressing the GOP to keep a strong
antiabortion plank in its platform. Others in the Capitol were
poring over the Supreme Court's ruling, trying to determine how a
partial-birth abortion bill that has passed the House and awaits
Senate action could be modified to pass constitutional muster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawmakers are going to want to study the opinion carefully and
decide how to respond,'' Douglas Johnson, legislative director for
the National Right to Life Committee, said, predicting the bill
would pass and be sent to President Clinton, who has twice vetoed
similar measures.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of its ruling, the Supreme Court Thursday ordered
lower courts to review their decisions upholding bans on certain
abortion procedures in Illinois and Washington state. The court
also let stand a ruling that struck down Iowa's ban.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8726 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-SECURITY-HEALTH-BOS &LR;      06-29 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECURITY-HEALTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISEASES POSE SECURITY RISK, CIA SPECIALST TELLS LAWMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They ride on the wings of mosquitoes. They cling to
microscopic droplets when you cough. They pass in sex.
</P>
<P>
   They are the newest national security threat: infectious
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   A senior CIA analyst, in the first congressional airing on the
issue, told a House committee Thursday that emerging infectious
diseases will pose a ``rising and in the worst case catastrophic''
global health threat that could seriously undermine US national
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``These diseases will endanger US citizens at home and abroad,
threaten US armed forced deployed overseas, and exacerbate social
and political instability in key countries and regions in which the
United States has significant interests,'' said David F. Gordon,
national intelligence officer for economics and global issues at
the CIA's National Intelligence Council.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing called by the House International Relations
Committee, lawmakers and top health officials grappled with the
difficulties in trying to contain the spread of the lethal microbes
in an age of globalization.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony underlined the increasing threat from infectious
diseases, many of which have steadily become more drug-resistant
due to underuse of antibiotics in poor countries and overuse in
wealthier ones.
</P>
<P>
   In an unprecedented act earlier this year that linked global
health and security, President Clinton declared HIV/AIDS a national
security threat. It stemmed from a declassified National
Intelligence Estimate coordinated by Gordon that explored the
implications of the spread of infectious disease for the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon told the panel Thursday of an ``increasing possibility''
of a biological terrorist attack against the United States and that
the attack could be spread through an infectious disease. He also
addressed the potential impact on US troops abroad, saying that
those deployed to support humanitarian operations ``in developing
and former communist countries will be at highest risk.''
</P>
<P>
   In the developing world, nearly half of all deaths are
attributed to treatable infectious diseases. The National
Intelligence Estimate found that four of the ``deadly seven''
infectious diseases _ AIDS, tuberculosis, malaria and hepatitis B
and C _ were ``either spreading or becoming more drug-resistant.''
The other three _ lower respiratory infections, diarrheal diseases
and measles _ appear to have ``at least temporarily peaked.''
</P>
<P>
   AIDS is passed through sex or dirty syringes, tuberculosis
through droplets often when coughing or sneezing, malaria through
the bite of a mosquito. Many others are transmitted through water
or food.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony given by Gordon and others Thursday, examples were
used again and again showing that national borders did nothing to
keep out infectious diseases. They cited several examples in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Last's year outbreak in New York of West Nile virus, which was
carried by migratory birds, killed seven people. In the last six
months of 1999, 56 people in South Texas were found to have dengue
fever, a tropical disease. Also last year, two Boy Scouts acquired
malaria at a summer camp in rural New York. And just last Sunday, a
Rochester, N.Y., man died of bacterial meningitis on a flight from
Tel Aviv to New York; New York health authorities now are concerned
that others on the flight may have been infected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot put a fence around America and hope to keep the
diseases out,'' said Representative Sam Gejdenson of Connecticut,
the committee's ranking Democrat. ``We cannot stop Americans from
traveling overseas for business or vacation; we cannot stop
protecting our interests abroad and just keep our armed forces
locked in their barracks for fear of catching a deadly disease.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If this were a military invasion, it would be easier
to galvanize the public and policy makers. ... For humanitarian and
self-survival reasons, we need to face this challenge as if it were
an invading army.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Brad Sherman, a California Democrat, took the
thought another step, saying, ``Historians will wonder why in our
defense budget we spent so much defending ourselves from missiles,
and so little from diseases. Perhaps the NIH (National Institutes
of Health) will be the next Pentagon.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization has estimated that it would cost
$1.5 billion a year for the next decade for medicines and
prevention to stop the spread of the major infectious diseases.
Numerous bills in Congress propose trust funds to stem the spread
of diseases, including legislation passed by the House to spend
$500 million over five years for a World Bank AIDS fund.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeon General David Satcher delivered a sobering statistical
look at AIDS, especially in the sub-Saharan region of Africa, which
has, he noted, ``5,500 funerals occurring each day in the region''
from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Due to AIDS, he said, demographers have projected that life
expectancy by the year 2010 will fall from 66 to 33 years in Zambia
and from 70 to 40 years in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, CIA analyst Gordon said that while AIDS was
the only disease formally named a national security threat, other
infectious diseases also posed a threat.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he said that US officials were closely watching
the spread of multi-drug resistant TB, especially in Russia and
other former Soviet states. ``Drug-resistant TB is going to be one
of the very large strategic problems in the next few years,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He made the point that an outbreak far from home still will be
felt here.
</P>
<P>
   The worst infectious diseases are ``likely to slow economic
development and undermine the social structures in some
countries,'' posing major complications to US foreign policy, he
said. ``This will challenge democratic development and transitions,
and possibly contribute to humanitarian emergencies and military
conflicts to which the United States might expect to respond.''
</P>
</TEXT>
