<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8727 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ELECTRONIC-BILLPAYING     06-29 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-BILLPAYING-$ADV2-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU PAID THAT BILL WITH A CLICK. OR DID YOU? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 2)  
 (Editors: Double dashes beginning in 10th graf are substitutes for
bullets.)  
 By NANCY LLOYD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He did not seem the problem-credit type when he sat down across
the desk from Kathy Egan, a mortgage loan officer in Boston, to
talk about refinancing a $200,000 mortgage on a $330,000 home. He
was a financial services executive making more than $1 million a
year; approval seemed certain, Egan recalled.
</P>
<P>
   When a routine credit check turned up three late mortgage
payments, Egan said, her client was floored. He had been using his
bank's electronic payment service and had a stack of statements
showing debits to his checking account a few days before each
payment was due.
</P>
<P>
   What the statements did not show, and the executive did not
realize, was that he had stumbled into a significant pitfall of
electronic bill payment _ one of a several attracting concern from
consumer groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Electronic bill-paying is being oversold to consumers,'' said
Ken McEldowney, executive director of Consumer Action, an advocacy
organization based in San Francisco. In some cases, McEldowney and
others say, the systems may deliver the opposite of what they
promise: more delayed payments, more late fees, and more
hard-to-spot, hard-to-correct problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston executive's stained credit is a case in point. He
mistakenly thought that his mortgage lender received his payments
as soon as the money left his account.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ads make it sound like all of your bills will be paid
electronically,'' McEldowney said of electronic services in
general. ``But only some creditors have such arrangements. If not,
your bank has to write a check and mail it to your creditor.''
Because such checks are not accompanied by the original payment
stub, posting can be delayed even further.
</P>
<P>
   In the executive's case, Egan said, accumulating late fees meant
that his payments never caught up with the problem. ``He thought he
was getting convenience with online payments,'' she said.
``Instead, his credit report got damaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Electronic bill-paying is growing in popularity. According to
Avivah Litan, a research director at Gartner, a research firm based
in Stamford, Conn., 2.5 million households regularly paid bills
last year using a personal computer; 4 million are expected to do
so this year. And perhaps a million more households go to systems
by telephone or other means.
</P>
<P>
   There are many ways to make payments electronically, with or
without a personal computer and with or without bills arriving in
the mail. Most fall into four categories:
</P>
<P>
   __ Pre-authorized direct debit. Creditors automatically obtain
payment from your bank account on a schedule you authorize in
advance. Creditors may offer discounts for paying this way. This
method is suitable for fixed payments like those on a loan, but
risky for bills that fluctuate and may contain errors or
unauthorized charges.
</P>
<P>
   __ Consumer-initiated payments. You continue to receive bills in
the mail and must instruct the bill-payment service by computer
link or by phone to pay each one. The service mails checks to any
creditors that are not equipped to receive payment electronically.
</P>
<P>
   __ Creditors' Web sites. Some utilities, phone companies, credit
card issuers and others let you view bills online and then
authorize the company to debit your bank account. This can be
cumbersome for more than a few bills a month.
</P>
<P>
   __ Third-party consolidators. Instead of receiving bills at
home, you arrange to have them sent, electronically or by mail, to
the consolidator, which stores them in its computers. Typically,
you then receive e-mail notification that they are ready to be
viewed and paid online.
</P>
<P>
   All four methods offer some measure of what a recent Gartner
survey found to be the main attraction of electronic bill-paying:
convenience. But for many people who use the services, there are
also drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   George Barto, another research director at Gartner, said 37
percent of respondents who use online banking services said they
disliked losing control and not knowing exactly when a bill would
be paid, while 14 percent cited trouble coordinating deposits with
payments and 11 percent worried that bills would not be paid on
time.
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, electronic payment services can claim some
cost savings over checking accounts _ no check printing or postage
costs, for example. Most services charge a monthly fee, though
banks may waive the fee for good customers, and other providers may
waive the fee for a few months as an introductory offer.
</P>
<P>
   When payments are not immediate, however, there can be a hidden
cost to consumers: loss of the ``float.'' With traditional checks,
the money remains in your account until they clear. With electronic
payments, the money may leave your account immediately, though it
may not reach your creditor for a week or more. Unable to know the
exact payment date, many consumers try to avoid late payment
problems by authorizing electronic payments a few days earlier than
they might have mailed paper checks.
</P>
<P>
   Payments that are too early present another pitfall, as Holly
Anderson, 29, a public relations executive in Washington, learned
when she took the electronic route to paying off a credit-card
balance. She chose to pay $100 a month, much more than the minimum
due. As is often the case, finance charges on Anderson's account
are calculated on the average daily balance, so to save some
interest she wanted to pay as early in each billing cycle as she
could.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'd pay before I got the next bill, something I
would not have done if I were writing a check,'' she said. ``But
instead of crediting the early payment for the next month, they
would credit it as a second payment in the current month. Then I'd
get hit with a $29 fee for not making my minimum'' for the next
month. She now waits an extra week, undermining her strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Security can be a big issue, especially with services not run by
banks. ``Anyone can claim to be a bill-paying service,'' McEldowney
said. ``We're already seeing some prepaid-phone-card companies
becoming cash-strapped and leaving consumers with worthless prepaid
cards. It could conceivably happen with bill-paying services that
aren't FDIC-insured.''
</P>
<P>
   Privacy is another concern. A consumer who uses a consolidator,
especially, is trusting the company _ and the Internet at large _
with an extraordinary amount of sensitive personal information that
could be misappropriated by a rogue employee, a hacker or a con
artist. Cary Whaley, a spokesman for Nacha, an electronic payments
trade association, said the industry takes the concerns seriously.
``Consolidators who do not hold information private will go out of
business in a heartbeat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McEldowney warned that ``small mistakes in keying in the
Web address can send you to a `spoofer' site that looks legitimate
but is run by criminals to get you to reveal your account number
and password.'' He advised bookmarking the genuine Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Even a secure transmission to the correct Web address can
contain small, unnoticed errors that later prove troublesome.
Deborah Thornton, a fund-raiser in Wellesley, Mass., recalled her
surprise when she received a cutoff notice from a utility. She
checked her records, which showed timely electronic payments _ but
to an account number that was one digit off. ``Someone else had
been receiving my payments and never said a word,'' she said.
(MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   Payments that go astray or are accidentally duplicated can be
difficult to retrieve. Noise on Thornton's phone line once broke
her computer connection before she received a confirmation of her
payment instructions. When she dialed back to finish the
transaction, she unwittingly paid all 15 bills a second time. She
spotted the error a few days later and rushed to the bank for help,
but was rebuffed. ``They told me, `this happens all the time,'''
she said, but that it was up to her to get refunds on her own. Most
ultimately cooperated, she said, ``but I was on the verge of firing
the guy who was cutting my grass, so he never refunded the extra
$100.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If a bank makes a mistake, absolutely, they will be responsive
and work to resolve it,'' said Charlotte Birch, a spokeswoman for
the American Bankers Association. ``But if the customer authorized
it, the bank may not be in a position to retrieve the extra
payment, any more than if the customer wrote a second check for the
same bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she said, she appreciates the speed and convenience of
the system when it works properly, and her bank has made
improvements. She is now shown a summary of her latest online
payment session when she logs off, and she can print paper records
of all her transactions. ``Without a good paper trail, resolving an
electronic bill-paying dispute would be a nightmare,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Far from clear, though, is whether a consumer's home computer
printouts can ever match the probative power of a canceled check in
a court dispute or, worse, a tussle with the tax collector.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internal Revenue Service has no official position on
electronic transfers,'' a spokeswoman for the agency said, ``but
the burden of proof is still on the taxpayer to keep records and
show evidence that an invoice has been paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton is taking no chances. ``For charitable contributions or
other things where I might need a canceled check as proof of
payment, I write the check myself, just in case.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
