<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8736 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT &LR;      06-29 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS TRIES TO HEAL AS WIMBLEDON SEARCHES FOR CALM 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ At least Pete Sampras was safe. With his
sore left shin packed like a champagne bottle in ice, he spent his
off day on the schedule healing in a villa well outside the
vine-covered walls of the All England Club.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, chaos was exploding with the rapid-fire of popcorn. The
father of Jelena Dokic was hustled away by a policeman for unruly
behavior, Alexandra Stevenson was starting a firestorm after
accusing a fellow player of hurling a racial slur at her during a
recent tournament, and French Open champion Mary Pierce's powerful
game was short-circuiting during a surprise second-round exit.
</P>
<P>
   And on Centre Court, as the parting distress signal of the day,
Andre Agassi was throwing up his arms in anger when referee Alan
Mills waited until after he slipped on the buttery grass to suspend
his intense match with Mark Martin due to rain. On Friday, the
second-seeded Agassi will pick up his up match ahead two sets to
one, but down a break after the first game of the fourth set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you wait for a fall?'' an incredulous Agassi yelled at
Mills. ``It's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi gathered his things in a huff, and stalked out of the
court to end a frantic fourth day of Wimbledon. It began with
Sampras' latest malady. With his 28-year old body already as
tortured as a voodoo doll, the results of a magnetic resonance
imaging test he underwent Wednesday night after his second-round
win were unveiled Thursday: acute tendinitis in the lower left
shin.
</P>
<P>
   The top-seeded player will be in pain, but is expected to play
his third-round match against 99th-ranked Justin Gimelstob on
Friday. Over the next 10 days, if Sampras can grit his teeth
through his half of the draw _ which is light on danger with only
No. 9 Thomas Enqvist remaining as a seeded player _ he will still
have his shot at breaking Roy Emerson's record of 12 Grand Slams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is resilient, so it's a matter of doing the best he can,''
said Sampras' coach Paul Annacone, who has watched Sampras endure
back and leg problems throughout the last couple of years. ``He
could sit around and say, `Why me? Why has it been like this
lately?' You just try to figure out what happened, and try to deal
with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he plays here, and he feels well, I think historically,
we've seen what happens. So it's a matter of trying to do it
another way.''
</P>
<P>
   As a six-time winner at Wimbledon, Sampras will press on, using
his serve as a peg leg to stand on. Sampras still has his trusty
howitzer. But Thursday proved that power players are vulnerable.
With her grounds trokes spraying the grass well outside the lines,
the third-seeded Pierce could not find enough control on the big
points to hold off 49th-ranked Magui Serna, losing 7-6 (5), 7-6 (4)
in her attempt at an encore to her French Open title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't meant to be,'' said Pierce, who came cruising into
Wimbledon with a 25-9 record this year. ``She played well, served
great. There were a few chances _ not very many _ in the first set
and the second set. It was just close. It just wasn't there all
together for me today.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of sorts, Lindsay Davenport could sympathize. Still trying
to find the compass to her swift strokes after a six-week absence
with a back injury in the spring, she gamely groped for a way to
finally slip by Elena Likhovtseva 3-6, 6-3, 6-3. It was a delicate
drop-shot, of all weapons, that turned what looked like an upset
into a relief. Down 0-3 in the third set, Likhovtseva was serving
for the game when Davenport slipped in a drop shot. From there,
Davenport ran off six straight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always tough when you have injuries,'' Davenport said.
``I was on such a roll before that I wasn't ... you don't really
think about things when you're playing well. All of a sudden when I
was out for almost two months, your tennis just starts to hurt a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   By avoiding the upset, Davenport ducked the mayhem Thursday.
After a boisterous romp around the grounds, Damir Dokic celebrated
his daughter Jelena's second-round win by popping off in the press
center and breaking the cell phone of a reporter. Two hours later,
Stevenson's attempt to re-create her trip fantastic through
Wimbledon last year _ during which she became the first woman
qualifier to land in the semifinals _ ended with a 7-6 (6), 6-3
loss to Patricia Wartusch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is my rookie year is over,'' said Stevenson,
whose biological father was also disclosed to be Julius Erving at
Wimbledon last year. ``There was a lot of hazing going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson said one incident occurred at a tournament last month
when a French player, Amelie Cocheteux, profanely referred to her
with a racial slur on the court. When questioned about the
accusation by a French reporter, Cocheteux denied making such a
remark.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, there were more barbs ricocheting around the
grounds than volleys. Out of harm's way, Sampras was recovering
quietly, icing his shin and taking anti-inflammatory drugs. In his
absence, Annacone was left to confront the prickly issues
concerning Sampras' increasing fragility. The question of toughness
was raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a subjective thing,'' Annacone said. ``I can tell you my
body feels awful 90 percent of the time when I wake up in the
morning. I played 10 years on the tour. I've had a herniated disk
in my back. I've got all kinds of things. I don't know what he
physically feels like.
</P>
<P>
   ``But compared to certain people, his tolerance is very high.
Probably compared to a football player, they're saying, `What's the
big deal?' I think everything is relative, but unfortunately for
people like Pete, I think things like that tend to make a lot of
news. But yeah, if you give me five minutes, I could probably argue
both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a strong return by Sampras could help bring peace to
the argument _ and, perhaps, to the grounds of Wimbledon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
