<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8740 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NOPOKER0630-COX     06-29 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOPOKER0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S.C. pulling plug on video poker
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Across a red-topped table cluttered by
cigarette packs and coffee-stained spoons, Eddie Lewis and four of
his friends were saying good-bye.
</P>
<P>
   Not to each other, but to the five Pot O Gold video poker
machines hugging the wall. As of midnight tonight, more than 22,000
machines will be outlawed in South Carolina in one of the largest
shutdowns of legalized gambling in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of South Carolina's once-powerful gambling industry
has unfolded so quickly that Lewis can't quite believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all seems like a dream,'' said the 53-year-old masseur, who
is going to miss gathering for dinner at Jackies Restaurant on
Wednesday and spending a few bucks on Superball Keno, Aces High and
other games. ``It's hard to believe they'll be unplugged.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands already have been disconnected, loaded on trucks and
shipped to warehouses in Georgia, North Carolina and other states
that allow some forms of video poker.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolinians might get another chance to gamble in the near
future if Gov. Jim Hodges succeeds in his push for a statewide
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   But lottery fever might be on the wane in the South. A
referendum backed by Alabama Gov. Don Siegelman, who, like Hodges,
rode the lottery promise to victory in 1998, was soundly defeated
by voters last year.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, video poker operators seem unwilling to
challenge state Attorney General Charlie Condon, who vowed police
would confiscate machines still in the state after midnight and
likened illegal machines to cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Operators fleeing South Carolina aren't likely to find Georgia
to be as profitable for video poker. Georgia law prevents
convenience stores, bars and other establishments where some 45,500
machines are located from paying game winners in cash, said Charles
Willey, spokesman for the Georgia Department of Revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Winnings are limited to free replays or merchandise prizes, such
as toys or novelties, with a wholesale value of less than $5,
according to Georgia law.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, South Carolina's loosely regulated industry
flourished over the past decade. The number of state-licensed
machines, which dispense tickets that are redeemed for cash, peaked
last year at nearly 37,000. They were collecting bets at an annual
rate of $3.3 billion in every corner of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The state's image suffered as industry opponents portrayed
operators as preying on poor people willing to spend paychecks on
the chance of hitting it big.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to curb the industry, the Legislature voted last year to
end video gambling July 1 unless voters in a referendum in November
1999 decided to keep the machines legal and enact new regulations.
A month before the vote, the state Supreme Court ruled the
referendum was unconstitutional but left the ban in place.
</P>
<P>
   Defending themselves against charges that they flaunted state
regulations, operators countered _ as they still do _ that adults
have a right to play legal games. Besides, they said, the industry
employs about 10,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only legitimate complaint against video poker is it hurts
some people,'' said Warren Holliday, owner of Holliday Amusement
Co. in Charleston. ``But for every person it hurts, hundreds of
others are helped.''
</P>
<P>
   In video poker's final hours, industry officials predicted that
mom-and-pop stores that depend on gaming revenues will go out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   That in turn will leave buildings unoccupied and hard to rent,
they said. Canadian Donald Frenette rented a closed laundry mat in
downtown Charleston 3 1/2 years ago and installed five video
gambling machines in an establishment he named Club Sante.
</P>
<P>
   As he was preparing Thursday to move the machines and close the
business, he said each of his machines netted a profit of more than
$400 a week. Now he faces a monthly rent of $6,300, with no revenue
coming in.
</P>
<P>
   Frenette, 39, asked, hopefully, ``Is my lease void since this
business is now illegal? This is a question everybody is going to
be asking. How do we pay our rent?'' Holliday said he figured state
legislators would give the industry ``three or four years'' to wind
down their businesses so they could repay debts from the industry's
rapid expansion in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were absolutely double-crossed,'' said Holliday, whose
family business started in 1933 renting pool tables and jukeboxes.
It now counts on video poker for 93 percent of its revenues. ``They
have destroyed my business.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
