<HEADER>
A8743 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-SPI &LR;      06-29 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS REQUIRES DISCLOSURE BY SECRETIVE ADVOCACY GROUPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES POPE and JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Taking its first significant step after 21 years of
futility, Congress Thursday approved legislation requiring greater
disclosure by secretive groups that are spending millions of
dollars to influence elections nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, approved by the Senate 92-6, now goes to President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect he'll sign the legislation when it comes down to
him,'' said Joe Lockhart, Clinton's spokesman. ``The public has a
right to know who groups like this are, who funds them. This is a
step in the right direction as far as campaign finance reform, but
we have a lot more to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which passed the House Tuesday, would affect a single
class of tax-exempt groups that, while small in number, are having
an increasing impact on elections nationwide. These groups have
exploited part of the tax code, Section 527, allowing them to raise
and spend an unlimited amount of money without reporting anything
about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, these Section 527 groups would be required to
report their donors and expenditures to the Internal Revenue
Service in return for keeping their tax-exempt status.
</P>
<P>
   Though the groups are generally not aligned with any specific
candidate, their money has been used to underwrite advertisements,
conduct polls, and launch voter registration drives in hopes of
influencing elections. Yet unlike spending by other tax-exempt
groups that are required to disclose where their money comes from,
527 organizations leave ``no fingerprints'' as to who is donating
and what their motivation is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's action is based on the principle of openness and
letting the people know who is behind the flurry of anonymous
campaign ads,'' said Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., who voted for the
bill. ``The American people should know the true source of groups
seeking to influence our elections,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., who also voted for the bill, said
she has been alarmed by ``a huge proliferation'' of such groups in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   So-called ``issue advocacy'' ads already have gained prominence
in Washington state, months ahead of the primary and general
elections.
</P>
<P>
   An insurance industry-backed group called Americans for Job
Security has praised Gorton's education proposals in ads on Western
Washington TV stations, while Eastern Washington stations have run
ads extolling Gorton's promise to block any plan to breach Snake
River Dams.
</P>
<P>
   A front group for the nation's drug makers, Citizens for Better
Medicare, has blanketed the airwaves with a TV spot showing elderly
Canadians (played by actors) being bused into the United States for
surgery. The ad warns against ``Canadian-style price controls.''
</P>
<P>
   But the earliest, most intense campaign has been waged by U.S.
Term Limits against Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash., for reneging
on his 1994 pledge to serve only three terms in Congress. It has
run TV and radio spots, erected billboards, bought bus signs and
even fielded an animal-costumed demonstrator, dubbed ``The Weasel
King,'' to harass Nethercutt as he seeks a fourth term.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of 527 groups gained national attention earlier
this year when a pair of Texas brothers ran $2.5 million in ads
praising Texas Gov. George W. Bush and attacking Sen. John McCain
in the days before a crucial GOP primary election.
</P>
<P>
   One of the oldest 527s is the Sierra Club, which is running an
$8 million campaign boosting Democrats running for Congress and
attacking Bush's record in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, the Arizona Republican who sponsored the bill and who
has made campaign reform his signature issue, said passing it would
help restore public faith in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today indeed marks a seminal day in our battle to reform our
electoral system and restore the faith of the American citizenry
that ours is a government of and for the people,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   The praise wasn't universal, however.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., was one of a handful of senators to
vote against the disclosure bill.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested groups affected by the bill will either disband or
fight the measure in court.
</P>
<P>
   The other five senators who voted against the bill also are
Republicans. They are Paul Coverdale of Georgia, Jesse Helms of
North Carolina, Jame Inhofe of Oklahoma, Connie Mack of Florida,
and Don Nickles of Oklahoma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
