u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-PEDRO-BOS &LR;      06-29 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PEDRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDRO MARTINEZ PLACED ON DISABLED LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Pedro Martinez won't pitch Saturday in Chicago, won't
pitch five days later in Minnesota, and exactly what day he will
return to the Red Sox roster after the July 10-12 All-Star break
remains in question.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, the reigning American League Cy Young Award winner,
was informed Thursday that he had been placed on the 15-day
disabled list, retroactive to his last start, June 25 in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The decision clearly did not sit well with the 28-year-old
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything to say,'' he said, quickly dismissing
reporters clustered around his locker not long before the Sox took
the field against Baltimore, looking to break a five-game losing
streak. ``I did what I could to pitch. I was tight last time. This
time, I feel fine.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does it all mean? Why are the Red Sox shelving the best
pitcher in the AL when the best pitcher in the AL says he is able
and ready to pitch as soon as Saturday afternoon?
</P>
<P>
   In the words of Sox skipper Jimy Williams, it comes down to his
opinion that Martinez is not physically able to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a couple of little medical things that we're going to
take care of,'' said Williams. The manager would not provide more
specific information regarding the ``medical things'', other than
to make reference to the history of problems Martinez has had with
an oblique muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at it as (going) on the 15-day disabled list
that take care of the little glitches he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said Martinez, who shagged fly balls and tossed in the
outfield after being placed on the DL, would not accompany the club
to Chicago for the upcoming three-game series against the White
Sox. According to the manager, the ace will be treated by the
club's medical staff over the weekend, then meet up with the club
next week in Minnesota. The Sox open a four-game series with the
Twins Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want to go on (the disabled list),'' said Williams.
``I accept that. It's my decision. It's my responsibility. I think
it's the right thing to do, and he doesn't. That's all right.''
</P>
<P>
   It began to become obvious that management would direct Martinez
toward a fortnight of rest and relaxation Tuesday night, when Sox
general manager Dan Duquette said during a pregame radio show that
such a move could be imminent. Duquette added Wednesday night that
Martinez was ``tight'' prior to making his last start, against the
Blue Jays, and the tightness also lingered after the start.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was obviously working in concert with the GM when he
met with Martinez in the clubhouse not longer after 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line for me is that I'm just trying to protect the
assets of the Red Sox,'' Williams said. ``I want the kid to be able
to pitch for a lot of years here. If I didn't put him on, to be
honest, and he went out and did something severe, it would be
difficult to handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams likewise would not provide details regarding what
course of action the club's medical staff would take with Martinez.
He emphasized however, that Martinez would be ``checked out by the
organization'' _ a clear reference that the righthander wouldn't be
expected to go looking for outside second and third opinions about
the need for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take care of it,'' said Williams, raising his right arm
as if lifting his hand to answer a question in a school room, ``in
the fashion we think is the best way to handle it. And he will join
us in Minnesota.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox return to action after the All-Star break when the Mets
come to Fenway July 13, the start of a three-game series. Martinez
would be available to return at that point, provided his medical
``glitches'' have been remedied.
</P>
<P>
   Williams's best pitcher is hurting, and by the sounds of it, he
is hurting in more than one place. The scenario is reminiscent of
the '99 postseason when Martinez exited Game 1 of the AL Division
Series against Cleveland with what was diagnosed as a back strain.
Martinez returned in Game 5 and pitched six innings of brilliant
no-hit relief. Williams now wants the pain to go away, and feels he
has no option other than to send pitcher and pain to the sideline
for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't my decision,'' emphasized Martinez. ``It was
(Williams's) decision _ the GM's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He can handle a lot of pain,'' said Williams. ``Now, there's
pain and there's injury. We are trying to prevent injury. When you
have pain, your body is trying to tell you something. Now, will
that pain go away? I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
