<HEADLINE>
EXIT, ALEXANDRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Barbara Walters asked her about her first kiss. Anybody
with a TV set heard interviewers grill her about her mystery dad,
who turned out to be none other than Dr. J, a person of some
athletic ability himself: Julius Erving, a resident of basketball's
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   She was The Story of Wimbledon 1999: Alexandra Winfield
Stevenson, a California teenager who set a record at the oldest
tennis tournament by scurrying to the semifinals as a back-door
entry, a qualifier ranked No. 88.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Alexandra was merely the sorry loser to a woman as
much of a nobody as she had been a year ago. An Austrian named
Patricia Wartusch, rated No. 74, beat Stevenson handily in the
second round, 7-6 (8-6), 6-3, concluding with an ace, the stroke
that had been Alexandra's signature only 12 months before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very saddened by my early exit, but the good thing is my
rookie year is over,'' said Stevenson, ever poised. Headed to UCLA
on a tennis scholarship when her flame ignited at the Big W, she
quickly declared herself a pro to collect $145,026 in prize money,
and was pointed in a different direction _ ``a year I wouldn't wish
on my worst enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   She left this year's tournament not with a bang or a whimper,
but by throwing a brick (and not the kind her father occasionally
launched). It was aimed at the women's tour and the ``hazing'' she
says she had received during the year by ``girls who didn't
appreciate the big splash I made last year. Because I've gotten a
lot of attention, and I have a personality, they don't like it.
That's too bad. That's me.''
</P>
<P>
   She singled out the French, particularly Amelie Cocheteux, whom
she beat by rebounding from the brink of defeat at Strasbourg.
Cocheteux called her ``a piece of black (expletive),'' said
Alexandra, who has a black father and white mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``She invented it; I never went near her,'' the 22-year-old
Cocheteux answered to the charge that she shouldered Stevenson in
the locker room. ``Her mother was coaching her from the sidelines,
which is against the rules, but the umpire did nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Whom can you believe?
</P>
<P>
   A respected French journalist said, ``I don't know who started
it but there's bad blood between our girls and Alexandra and her
mother (Samantha Stevenson).''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain, it's been a rocky 12 months for
19-year-old Alexandra, whose vivacious personality does leave most
of her contemporaries seeming withdrawn and vacuous. Even so, she's
a shaky 8-22 since Wimbledon last, a tournament in which she won
eight matches (including qualifying).
</P>
<P>
   She considers herself an actress, ``an entertainer'' on court,
smiling and curtsying to the crowd. Some call it gracious; others
call it hotdogging. Andre Agassi gets away with it because he's won
six major titles, and . . . well . . . he's Andre, who has worn
nail polish and has had more hairstyles than Charlie's Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Well-schooled by her single-parenting mom, a former TV and
newspaper journalist, Alexandra gives good press conference,
actually in English, a subject that so many of the ill-educated
child pros flunk. Mummy is a shrewd strategist. Bad match, good
quotes, much publicity regardless.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra says she thinks of herself as a variety of characters
and actresses _ Julia Roberts when she won her first-rounder. Maybe
it was Ma Kettle Thursday. She's had a rough time maintaining what
she achieved here. Her ranking rose to No. 36 post-Wimbledon,
skidded to No. 46 as she played this brief encore, and plummeted to
No. 95 since she couldn't cover the Wimbledon points she made last
year.
</P>
<P>
   It's back to the bushes, qualifying tourneys again. Few have
risen so high from nowhere or done a canyon dive so deep in the
space of 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, at 6 feet 1 inch with an attractive
serve-and-volley style, she remains a potent prospect, bright and
coachable with plenty of room for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Alexandra said, ``I learned that you really have to be
tough out here. I came out (a year ago) as kind of a Southern
California clueless girl. I was used to high school and people
being nice to you. But out here it's a job, your profession. You
don't make friends . . . you can get eaten alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other people don't want you to succeed, so you stay within
your inner circle and pray a lot to God. Take a lot of confidence
from the small group around you, be tough, keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra and Samantha are the core of the small group. Though
Samantha could be called a stage _ or court? _ mother, her kid is a
lot better off emotionally than Jelena Dokic, the 17-year-old
Aussie whiz Alexandra beat in the quarters last year.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Damir Dokic, the latest member of the tennis Bad
Dads Club, embarrassed his talented daughter again Thursday with
another disorderly performance, this time trying to assault a TV
news reporter. Cops cooled him out. Papa Dokic isn't likely to be
summoned by Barbara Walters, and it may be a while for Alexandra,
who has kissed Wimbledon goodbye for this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
