<SLUG> BC-STRATEGIES-COLUMN-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRATEGIES: THE WAYS OF ONE-YEAR WONDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 2) 
 By MARK HULBERT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you're hot, you're hot.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not talking about the weather, but about the attitude of
many investors when choosing an investment adviser. They're
surprisingly eager to follow an adviser with a poor long-term
record, provided that he or she has had recent success. They
believe that such advisers have so-called hot hands _ that just
because they have beaten the market or their peers in the short
term, they are likely to keep doing so for at least a while longer.
</P>
<P>
   These same investors, meanwhile, are quick to shun advisers with
splendid long-term returns if their recent performance hasn't
measured up.
</P>
<P>
   But can investment advisers really have hot hands? Statisticians
have researched the matter exhaustively, and the picture that has
emerged is somewhat mixed.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for hot-hand advocates is that investors will make
more money by investing in last year's top market-beaters than they
will by following advisers at the bottom of last year's list.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that this strategy probably won't help investors
beat the market.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Metrick, a finance professor at the Wharton School of the
University of Pennsylvania, conducted one of the most extensive
studies on the question. First he scrutinized every buy or sell
recommendation on an American stock by 153 investment newsletter
editors from 1980 to 1996. Then he constructed two hypothetical
portfolios _ the first designed to follow the stock-picking
recommendations of the 10 percent of advisers with the best
performance during the previous calender year, the second following
the recommendations of the 10 percent with the worst records. He
repeated the process every Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the winners' portfolio produced a 15.7 percent return,
annualized, from the end of 1980 through the end of 1996, versus
8.9 percent for the losers' portfolio. The overall stock market,
meanwhile, gained 14.9 percent a year, on average, over the period.
</P>
<P>
   Great. So it appears that some advisers indeed have hot hands.
</P>
<P>
   There is a problem, however. The winning managers' portfolio may
have beaten the overall market by 0.8 percentage points a year, but
the calculations did not take transaction costs into account. It is
likely that these costs would substantially reduce, if not
eliminate, that advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But how do we explain that the hot advisers still outperformed
Metrick's losers portfolio by nearly 7 percentage points a year? I
suspect that some advisers play an icy cold hand, either because of
poor stock-picking ability or high transaction costs. In any event,
the research suggests that while investors shouldn't necessarily
follow advisers with the best one-year performance, they should
certainly avoid those with the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Similar results have emerged from studies of mutual funds. Mark
Carhart, a former assistant finance professor at the University of
Southern California and now co-head of quantitative strategies at
Goldman Sachs Asset Management, examined the performance of U.S.
stock funds from 1962 through 1993. He initially found support for
the hot-hand idea. During any given year, the previous year's
top-performing funds have, on average, beaten the worst performers
from the year earlier. But he later found that the pattern was more
a function of the worst funds continuing their lackluster
performance than the best ones continuing to shine.
</P>
<P>
   So, it seems, hot hands don't really exist in the world of
investment advisers and newsletters. But cold ones do. Or to turn a
phrase, when you're hot, apparently, you merely aren't freezing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
