</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-CONTROVERSY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENSON, DOKIC AT THE CENTER OF CONTROVERSY ONCE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (With TEN-WIMBLEDON)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ The All England Club's genteel image was
shattered Thursday when Jelena Dokic's father was led away by a
policeman after unruly behavior on the grounds, and Alexandra
Stevenson ended her run at Wimbledon by describing the hazing she
endured during her rookie season, which, she said, included a
profane racial slur recently directed at her.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after losing to Patricia Wartusch in the second round,
Stevenson spoke about how tough it was to deal with the jealousy
she has encountered since gaining celebrity status last year. In
her Wimbledon debut, she was the object of attention. She was the
first female qualifier to reach the semifinals and it was disclosed
that Julius Erving was her biological father. An interview with
Barbara Walters quickly followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of made a big splash,'' Stevenson said. ``I don't think
a lot of girls appreciated it. They have to grow up and have bigger
minds, not be so petty.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson said that at a tournament in Strasbourg, France, last
month, a French player, Amelie Cocheteux, hurled a profane racial
slur at her during every changeover of their match. The next day,
she said, another French player, Anne-Gaelle Sidot, pushed her
mother, Samantha Stevenson, and pulled down her hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cocheteux called me the names, and Sidot hit my mom,''
Alexandra Stevenson said. ``In the French Open, Cocheteux came up
and hit me, kind of bumped into me in the locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidot was not available for comment early Thursday evening, but
Cocheteux was reached by a French reporter and denied all of
Stevenson's accusations.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive officer of the Women's Tennis Association,
Bart McGuire, said the allegations were investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was determined that Ms. Sidot did not physically strike Ms.
Stevenson but did tip her hat during a conversation regarding use
of a practice court,'' McGuire said, referring to Samantha
Stevenson. `` Ms. Sidot also alleged that Ms. Stevenson used
verbally abusive language. The Tour determined no disciplinary
action was warranted.''
</P>
<P>
   McGuire said no proof could be found of a racial slur directed
at Alexandra Stevenson by Amelie Cocheteux. Tour officials found no
witnesses to substantiate the allegation of the bumping in the
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Damir Dokic spun out of control. About 20 minutes
after Jelena Dokic defeated Gala-Leone Garcia on Court 5, he was
seen walking unsteadily through the grounds, waving the flag of St.
George. As he entered the third floor of the press center,
witnesses heard him ranting ``the Queen's side of the country is
beautiful, the other side is fascist.''
</P>
<P>
   He also began criticizing the WTA for its treatment of his
daughter, who was fined for being four hours late to an interview
at the Australian Open. Mark Saggers, a sports reporter for
Britain's Sky Sports, said that Dokic smashed his cell phone into
three pieces after that. A police officer led Dokic away. Saggers
gave a statement to the police, but said he would not press
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Inspector Andrew Freestone of the Metropolitan Police Service
said that Dokic came to the police room voluntarily, that the Dokic
family chose to leave the grounds and that no further action would
be taken.
</P>
<P>
   At a tune-up for Wimbledon in Birmingham last June, Dokic began
shouting at spectators during his daughter's match and was ejected.
Later, he was picked up by the police when he was spotted lying in
the middle of a road. They said he was was cautioned for drunken
and disorderly behavior and was released without being charged.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Damir Dokic's outburst coincided with a WTA statement
concerning a new policy to help eliminate distractions created by
parents, friends and coaches. The players' council voted to
restrict access to locker rooms at all tour events to players only.
Alexandra Stevenson said she believed the rule was ``silly'' and
that it was aimed at her mother and the mother of Martina Hingis.
The WTA denied that the rule was directed specifically at mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the rule is fair,'' said Chris Evert, who is at
Wimbledon as an analyst for NBC. ``Players need a place to be
alone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
