u e BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     06-29 0343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUG SAHM: `SAN ANTONIO ROCK: THE HARLEM RECORDINGS 1957-1961' 
</HEADLINE>
   By BEN RATLIFF    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOUG SAHM: ``San Antonio Rock: The Harlem Recordings 1957-1961''
(Norton).
</P>
<P>
   For a pop singer, ``crossing over,'' in the racial sense, almost
always means someone of color reaching a white audience; rarely is
the reverse even tried. But at 17, Doug Sahm, a white singer from
San Antonio, was doing a double twist: making records in a black
rhythm-and-blues style for a Chicano audience.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he would form the Sir Douglas Quintet, a great rock band
of the 1960s and 1970s that combined British Invasion pop, urban
blues, a touch of West Coast psychedelia and the two-step thump of
Tex-Mex conjunto music. But Sahm never forgot his hometown: in his
songs with the quintet, he left a trail of references to San
Antonio, enough to convince you that it was a magical place,
possibly overlooked among the important American towns of early
rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Antonio Rock'' explains it all. In San Antonio, a number
of things naturally came together: T-Bone Walker's blues, Gulf
Coast rhythm-and-blues, country music, an older generation's
accordion-driven conjunto. Sahm absorbed it all, a fiendishly
precocious singer and guitarist before he was legally old enough to
play in the bars where he plied his trade, with a hoarse, rugged
voice that he pushed into gothic swoops, shouts and trills.
</P>
<P>
   The CD collects the singles he recorded as a member of local
bands with swanky names like the Dell Kings, the Mar-Kays, the
Twisters and the Pharaohs. His manic version of Larry Williams'
``Slow Down'' is inspired by Little Richard; his own ``Why Why
Why'' and ``More and More'' are lovely, slow, tortured ballads,
with Fats Domino-style piano triplets and sweet harmonies from two
tenor saxophones, lining the song like fat fins on an old car.
Typical of Norton's rereleases, the CD is well annotated; the liner
notes are a full disquisition on the San Antonio scene of the late
'50s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8755 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MONEY-MEDICINE-COLUMN     06-29 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-MEDICINE-COLUMN-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY &AMP; MEDICINE: OFF THE MANAGED-CARE TREADMILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 2) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Haddad, a pediatric ear, nose and throat doctor in
Manhattan, said he realized how dropping out of managed care was
paying off for him as he sat watching his son's preschool
graduation. Haddad's workload has shrunk markedly _ 20 percent
fewer surgical cases, a similar decline in office visits _ since he
stopped abiding by the insurers' fee scales last year.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is home for dinner most nights and can attend his older
son's activities. ``You realize how important that is when your kid
keeps waving at you the whole time,'' he said, recalling the
graduation ceremony. Ditching managed care, he said, ``was really a
quality-of-life issue.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of doctors around the country have taken the same
calculated risk in the last few years, by deciding to stop settling
for what insurance would pay. They cite low reimbursement rates
that forced them to make up revenue in volume, crowding their
waiting rooms with patients and rushing their care. The pace and
the paperwork stole too much time from their personal lives, the
doctors say. And frankly, some just disliked making less money.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these rebel doctors practice in cities where there are
plenty of affluent patients who can pay cash or who have access to
old-fashioned indemnity insurance that simply reimburses the
patient for most of the bill. Doctors in suburbs where managed care
has all but cornered the health insurance market have less scope to
drop out.
</P>
<P>
   Barney Softness, a pediatrician on the Upper West Side of
Manhattan, decided last year to tell his managed-care patients _
who made up about one-third of his busy practice _ that he would no
longer accept their insurance. Half left immediately, and he
finished the year on a sour financial note. But he was happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great benefit was, it was much quieter,'' Softness said. He
and his partners were able to reduce the number of patients each
saw in an hour to just four, from five or six under managed care.
``We had time to do it right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then something happened: The lost patients started coming back.
``Some said, `It is worth it to us,''' Softness said, ``the
implication being that they were getting mill-like treatment.''
Now, he said, ``we are back to being as busy as we were.'' If it
gets too busy, he said, he may have to stop accepting new patients.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, I have firsthand experience of the changes in
Softness' practice: My own baby has been seen by his partners since
shortly after they dropped the plans. Care was great, service
speedy at first; lately, I've been kept waiting from 10 to 40
minutes, though once we get into an examination room, I still feel
that my child is the only one the doctor is seeing that day.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, my own primary-care doctor, who accepts many insurance
plans, never makes me wait, and never rushes me either.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, few patients feel that their doctors neglect their care
as a result of insurance company pressures, according to a new
survey by the Center for Studying Health System Change, an
independent research organization in Washington. The study, based
on interviews with 59,000 Americans, found that while 44 percent
thought that the companies do influence doctors' care decisions,
only 7 percent said they believed doctors put insurers' interests
ahead of patients' needs. The center got similar results in 1997,
before the backlash against managed care had gathered steam.
</P>
<P>
   The response may mean that patients are simply not aware of how
stressed-out their doctors are. Or it may signal that patients do
not agree with their doctors' view that quality erodes as revenues
rise. Even if they do agree, most patients have little choice: Few
earn enough to afford doctors' fees on their own, and doctors say
they have had to turn away patients for financial reasons. ``There
are a lot of interesting cases that I might want to do, but can't,
because the families are constrained by their choice of
insurance,'' Haddad said.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Sheldon, a family doctor in Denver who opened a
no-managed-care office after working for a managed-care company in
Vermont, said he has found a way around the problem. He charges
patients $4 a minute. If he sees them for 10 minutes, they pay $40,
which, he said, is cheaper than an office visit at most nearby
clinics. ``It is a win-win,'' he said. ``I have patients who are
rich and poor, and they come because they love the service.''
</P>
<P>
   At a clinic, a patient might pay $60 for a 10-minute visit _ or
the same for an hour, making it hard to say if Sheldon's approach
really optimizes care and cost for patients.
</P>
<P>
   Most doctors do not have the chance to test such theories. Peter
Shutkin, an internist in New Canaan, Conn., recently decided that
he had had enough of Aetna. But while he may fantasize about
extending the take-a-hike message to the other four plans he
accepts, he knows it's no use. ``Practically, I don't think it
would work,'' Shutkin said. ``I wouldn't have any patients left.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 2040EDT &QL; 
