A8757 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-29 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   UKRAINE: PRESIDENTIAL POWERS
</P>
<P>
   A constitutional court ruled that President Leonid Kuchma's plan
to strengthen his powers over Parliament does not violate the
constitution. The ruling paves the way for Kuchma to submit the
changes to Parliament, which must pass them by a two-thirds
majority. Some opposition leaders want to water down the proposals,
fearing that Kuchma's executive powers will too easily override the
legislature's. Ever since Kuchma won re-election in November, he
has been campaigning for stronger powers to break the many
deadlocks that have snarled economic reform plans.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA: RIGHTS MONITORS
</P>
<P>
   Austria said it was willing to cooperate with a panel of ``wise
men'' asked to examine its human rights records. The European Court
of Human Rights in Strasbourg, France, will appoint three monitors,
who will send their findings to the other 14 European Union
governments. Analysts say they believe that this could be a first
step toward ending Austria's political isolation within the
European Union, which froze political relations with Vienna on Feb.
4 after Joerg Haider's far-right Freedom Party joined Austria's
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: ARMENIANS EXPELLED
</P>
<P>
   Four Armenians invited to a meeting in the eastern city of Kars
were expelled by Turkish security agents. Local authorities had
invited the four as part of an effort to improve relations between
the two countries, which would greatly help the economy in Kars and
other border areas. But the Foreign Ministry said that since
Armenia was occupying territory that belongs to Azerbaijan,
Turkey's ally, and was promoting hostility toward Turkey, the
ministry was ``not promoting such contacts.''
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: PREMIER TESTIFIES
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bertie Ahern told a tribunal investigating
improper payments to politicians that he had no knowledge of a
missing $91,000 that disappeared from a donation in 1989. A Fianna
Fail party supporter donated $121,000 to Charles Haughey, then the
prime minister, of which only $30,000 reached the party account.
Ahern, who handled party finances at the time, said he was aware of
the $30,000 donation only, and he accepted blame for not sending a
receipt for that amount.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: SUING BRITAIN
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of more than 300 sailors who were killed when the
Belgrano battleship was sunk by the Royal Navy during the Falklands
war in 1982 announced that they plan to sue Britain for damages
next week in the European Court of Human Rights in Strasbourg,
France. Lawyers for the relatives, who have been preparing the case
for five years, plan to argue that since the site of the sinking
was outside the theater of operations, Britain violated
international wartime conventions.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: REBEL TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Delegations of Europeans and Latin Americans representing 21
nations began two days of meetings with the Revolutionary Armed
Forces of Colombia, the country's main left-wing guerrilla group,
in a demilitarized area controlled by the rebels. The topic of the
conference is drug trafficking; the guerrillas are heavily involved
in the cocaine trade but say they would favor crop-substitution
programs. The United States is not not taking part because of a ban
on official contacts with the group.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: JAILED AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   An upstate New York judge has ordered a Vancouver man jailed for
fleeing a prison work camp 29 years ago while serving up to four
years for selling $20 worth of LSD to an undercover agent. A cause
celebre in Canada, Allen Richardson told the Rochester judge that
he fled in 1971 because a guard told him that he was about to be
returned to Attica state prison, where a deadly riot had just
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: PALESTINIANS COMPLAIN
</P>
<P>
   Saeb Erekat, a senior peace negotiator, said the Palestinians
had lodged complaints with the Americans and the Europeans about
increasing Israeli reinforcements of settlements in Gaza and the
West Bank. Palestinians report seeing tanks moving into certain
settlement areas, which they say is creating panic among
Palestinians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
