<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT-MIDEAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT URGES DELAY IN SUMMIT BETWEEN PALESTINIANS AND ISRAELIS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Before heading to the White House to brief
President Clinton on her visit to the Middle East, Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright said Thursday that the administration did
not feel pressured to call a summit immediately between the
Israelis and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said there ``was plenty of time to do what needs to be
done'' and that ``our calculus is Jan. 20,'' the day President
Clinton leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the capital after meeting with Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak in Jerusalem and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat at Ramallah on the West Bank, Albright signaled that the
time was not right for a summit next week, a schedule that the
Israelis had been eager for.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have consistently said that the
president will determine after Albright's visit whether the time is
right for a summit or whether it will be preferable to continue
negotiations at a lower level to massage the issues that have riven
the two sides for five decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis have said they are ready for a three-way meeting
with Clinton and Arafat in the Washington area next week to settle
the final issues of the future of Jerusalem, the borders of a
Palestinian entity and the fate of the scattered Palestinian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright, speaking to reporters on her airplane after a
brief stop in Berlin, said that there needed to be thorough
preparation of the core issues before the leaders could be closeted
in an isolated retreat. Otherwise, there was the risk of
unnecessary failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain issues that are the type of issues where if
they are not properly prepared then you are asking for something to
be even more difficult,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of negotiations between senior negotiators,
solutions to the basic issues have been discussed in deep detail. A
senior administration official said that these subjects had been
`de-mythologized' and some gaps had been narrowed.
</P>
<P>
   On the West Bank after her visit with Arafat, a senior
Palestinian official, Saeb Ereket, said that teams would return to
Washington next week to talk for another two weeks and that a
summit was out of the question until after that.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that a summit at any time was a
gamble but that Clinton was prepared to take the risk.
</P>
<P>
   From the Israeli side, a broad brush stroke picture has emerged
for what a final deal may look like. According to these accounts,
it would include granting more than 90 percent of the West Bank for
what would make, with the Gaza strip, a Palestinian entity.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Arafat has stuck to his demands of a full
withdrawal by Israel to the borders before the 1967 Arab-Israeli
war. In private, however, Arafat was more flexible, realizing that
some Israeli settlements would remain in the West Bank,
administration officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
