A8761 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-GROOVE30-COX     06-29 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-GROOVE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rave on in search for `Groove'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching ``Groove'' is like listening to a friend tell you about
the awesome dream he had last night: the colors, the sounds, the
sights. You smile and nod and wonder how long you have to wait
before politely changing the subject. Then he notices your frozen
smile and glazed eyes and mumbles, ``I guess you had to be there.''
Exactly.
</P>
<P>
   The second rave movie of the year, this is a big step up from
the snide and empty-headed Welsh import ``Human Traffic.'' But the
problem with any movie about an altered state _ whether it's a
dream or, as in this case, a drug-and-sound-fueled dance party _ is
that it's very hard to capture on film the subjective highs of the
real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Groove'' struggles against two impulses. It wants to catch the
techno-exultance of dancing, driven by the up-till-dawn euphoria of
the ravers' drug of choice, Ecstasy. But it also settles into some
traditional dramatic, um, grooves as it tracks a handful of San
Franciscans through the all-night event in an abandoned warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   They include longtime ravers Colin (Denny Kirkwood) and his
girlfriend Harmony (Mackenzie Firgens), who coax Colin's uptight
would-be novelist brother David (Hamish Linklater) along.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to the warehouse is half the fun of ``Groove.''
Writer-director Greg Harrison shows a where-and-when e-mail making
its way round the city's hipper computer screens, and the partyers
prepping for fun _ strapping on their glitter platforms and lining
up their party pills. A girl at the laundry turns the sound of a
washing machine into a secret dance beat in her mind. A guy on the
subway proudly carries a mirrored disco-ball on his lap.
</P>
<P>
   You can see that the semi-secrecy is part of the thrill. The
partyers follow hush-hush directions to the chosen spot. Only the
cool ones get the invitation, so they're a self-proclaimed
in-crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Buttoned-up David definitely seems out of place, but soon he has
popped his X and is being shown the ropes by be-cool rave regular
Leyla (Lola Glaudini). They flirt, they dance, they talk. They talk
too much, really, in a long dialogue that has Leyla starting to
question what she's doing with her life. It's the only moment when
``Groove'' suggests that partying your brains out might not be the
best thing to do with your life.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a subplot about a character who starts to question
his sexuality, but this thread feels arbitrary and forced. What
never flags in the film is the music, played by a series of
celebrated DJs, culminating with John Digweed, who is treated by
the others as a god.
</P>
<P>
   You walk out of ``Groove'' admiring Harrison's enthusiasm and
his drive to convey this high-energy phenomenon on-screen. It's a
good try. But, yeah, you kinda have to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Groove''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Lola Glaudini and Hamish Linklater. Rated R for drug
use, language and brief sexuality. 1 hour, 26 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A long night's journey into day, with glo sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
