<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV highlights
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News ServiceTonight
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``UFOs Uncovered (8 p.m., The Learning Channel) _ How did TLC
know that one of the biggest sci-fi festivals in the country,
DragonCon, was gathered in Atlanta this weekend? The cable channel
goes into orbit with three hours of UFO ``documentaries,''
including ``Dark Secrets,'' ``Are Aliens Here?'' and ``Out of This
World.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Stargate SG-1'' (10 p.m., Showtime) _ Fourth season premiere
of the sci-fi series finds Col. O'Neill (Richard Dean Anderson)
battling a bunch of robot bugs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dennis Miller Live'' (11:30 p.m., HBO) _ I don't want to get
off on a rant here, but why are some people upset about comedian
Miller (right) joining ``Monday Night Football?'' He's not a real
sportscaster? God forbid television would adulterate a sporting
event with entertainment values. Anyone who complains about Miller
should be forced to take a cross-country trip in a Yugo with ESPN
``real sportscaster'' Dick Vitale. Anyway, Miller's guest tonight
is the amusing-in-small-doses MTV prankster Tom Green. Whatever it
is, it won't be quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Killer Storm'' (9 p.m. , The History Channel) _ For
copyright reasons, they couldn't call this ``The Perfect Storm''
but it's the same storm chronicled in Sebastian Junger's
best-seller and in the George Clooney movie opening today. This new
documentary covers the October 1991 collision of a hurricane and a
nor'easter.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``La Forza del Destino'' (2 p.m., GPTV) _ The rest of the
country got to see the Kirov Opera's new mounting of Verdi's
classic on Wednesday, but Georgia Public Television postponed it to
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sisqo's Shakedown Finals'' (7 p.m., MTV) _ A dance contest
to appear in Sisqo's (``The Thong Song'') next video. In other
words, it's a booty pageant.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Jesse Ventura: The E! True Hollywood Story'' (9 p.m., E!) _
Yet another reason why satire is almost impossible these days.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Hollywood Rocks the Movies: The Early Years (1955-1970)''
(10 p.m., American Movie Classics) _ Ringo Starr hosts this
special, which encompasses moves about rock (``Woodstock'') and
movies in which rock plays a big role (``The Girl Can't Help It'').
After the special, AMC launches ``Rockstock,'' three days of
rockin' flicks, starting with ``Rock Around the Clock'' at 12:30
a.m. On the schedule next week: Ken Russell's surreal-unreal
version of ``Tommy;'' the Monkees' inexplicable, drug-addled
``Head,'' and something the AMC web page lists as ``The Jimmy
Hendrix Experience.'' Uh, that would probably be Jimi.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Big Cat Diary'' (10:30 p.m., Animal Planet) _ Slept. Ate.
Went out. Came back in. Ignored people. Repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Movies
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A Christmas Story'' (8 p.m. Sunday, Turner Classic Movies)
</P>
<P>
   Build a nice roaring fire, make some hot chocolate and settle in
for this bit of bizarre scheduling. Maybe you can address your
Christmas cards while you watch _ this year's or last, depending on
how organized you are.
</P>
<P>
   Best Bet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Rocky and Bullwinkle Marathon'' (4-7 p.m. Saturday, Cartoon
Network)
</P>
<P>
   Hey Rocky, watch me pull a promotional tie-in outta my hat! With
the big-screen version of ``R&AMP;B'' opening in theaters today, Ted
Turner's Cartoon Network uncrates three hours of the classic
cartoons, which originally ran from 1959-61. Although the animation
was crude, creator Jay Ward had a sly subversive streak (spoofing
the Cold War with Boris, Natasha and Mr. Big when everyone else was
taking it very seriously) and a love of achingly bad puns (a
valuable small boat encrusted with jewels was the Ruby Yacht of
Omar Khayyam).
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
