<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8770 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-REAGAN-ULSTER-EXCLUSI     06-29 1981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAGAN-ULSTER-EXCLUSIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAGAN, O'NEILL URGED US PEACE ROLE IN ULSTER, DOCUMENTS SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ President Ronald Reagan and Speaker Thomas P.
``Tip'' O'Neill Jr. conspired to advance the cause of peace in
Northern Ireland at a key juncture in 1984, pressing British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher to recognize an American and Irish role
in the affairs of the troubled province, newly-released documents
show.
</P>
<P>
   According to Reagan White House papers, which were part of more
than 10,000 pages released to The Boston Globe by his presidential
library under the US Freedom of Information Act, the former
president was persuaded by a personal appeal by the late House
Speaker to make a private approach to Thatcher, the world leader
with whom Reagan had his closest personal and ideological ties.
</P>
<P>
   The documents also shed new light on Reagan's personality and
private sense of ethnic identity; offer tantalizing glimpses into
the hidden world of high-level diplomacy, and add detail and
texture to the former president's relationships with Thatcher and
O'Neill, his foremost domestic political foe.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the O'Neill-Reagan diplomatic maneuver, detailed in
public for the first time by the newly-released papers, has been
confirmed for the Globe in interviews with Reagan's top White House
aides; former staffers to O'Neill, and Irish diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to personally share with you my deep concern,'' O'Neill
wrote Reagan on Dec. 13, 1984. ``The best hope for a peaceful,
lawful and constitutional resolution to the tragedy of Northern
Ireland may be in serious jeopardy as a result of Mrs. Thatcher's
public statements.''
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Thatcher at the presidential retreat at Camp
David on Dec. 22, Reagan replied to the speaker on Jan. 9, 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a special effort to bring your letter to her personal
attention and to convey your message of concern,'' Reagan wrote.
``I also personally emphasized the need for progress in resolving
the complex situation in Northern Ireland, and the desirability for
flexibility on the part of all the involved parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Thatcher, who had lost close friends and been personally
targeted by Irish Republican Army terrorist attacks, bent to
Reagan's private appeals. In their Camp David discussions, she
promised to renew diplomatic talks with Irish Prime Minister Garret
FitzGerald, Reagan informed O'Neill. In November 1985, the Irish
and British leaders signed the landmark Anglo-Irish agreement,
recognizing an Irish role in the affairs of the troubled North.
</P>
<P>
   The library files demonstrate how Reagan _ fresh off a
sentimental trip to his ancestral home of Ballyporeen in Ireland in
the summer of 1984 _ chose to overcome the pro-British leanings of
the US State Department. They also reveal how _ in the never-ending
scheming for political advantage in Washington _ members of
Reagan's staff sought to mute O'Neill's opposition to US funding
for the Nicaraguan Contra armies by appeasing the speaker on
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hoped to use this as a lever against `Tip' in order to get
Contra aide moving,'' wrote one official from Reagan's National
Security Council, in a September 1986 memo.
</P>
<P>
   The Reagan papers show how O'Neill, at one point, sweetened the
deal by agreeing to give Thatcher a coveted opportunity to address
a joint session of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   And the documents also detail how O'Neill, along with Senators
Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts, Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New
York, and former New York governor Hugh Carey _ who were known as
``the Four Horsemen'' _ played a critical role at channeling
Irish-American sentiment toward constructive purposes, thus
undercutting support for the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Working with moderate political leaders in Ireland, Northern
Ireland, and the United States, and advised by Irish diplomats and
Northern Ireland's Nobel Prize recipient John Hume, O'Neill and his
colleagues helped establish the precedent for US involvement in
Anglo-Irish affairs that President Clinton and envoy George
Mitchell have employed in the current peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intervention by Reagan was vital, and it was made possible
by Tip,'' said Sean Donlon, the former Irish ambassador to the
United States. The speaker's efforts in the late 1970s and early
1980s were the beginning of a process that Clinton then ``advanced
. . . to a whole new phase,'' Donlon said.
</P>
<P>
   The Four Horsemen had their first success in the late 1970s when
they prevailed upon Reagan's predecessor, former president Jimmy
Carter, to proclaim an American interest in the affairs of Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   After Reagan was elected in November 1980, however, the US
foreign policy establishment reverted to its traditional stance:
that the United States should not anger Great Britain, its closest
Cold War ally, by meddling in its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy and O'Neill were rebuffed in their first approach to
Reagan, in the spring of 1981, when they asked the president to
press Thatcher to compromise with dying IRA hunger strikers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intense media coverage of the hunger strike in the United
States has dramatically improved the image of the Provisional IRA
among 35 million Irish-Americans and reversed a five-year trend of
declining financial support of the IRA,'' O'Neill wrote Reagan on
May 19, 1981. ``Members of the IRA are terrorists and should be
treated as such. But by refusing to negotiate regarding prison
rules, Mrs. Thatcher is permitting the terrorists to undo
significant political progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Making a promise that he kept to his death, O'Neill assured
Reagan that he would keep any informal negotiations a secret, and
asked the president to make ``a private and discreet expression of
concern'' to the prime minister. But Reagan declined to appeal to
Thatcher, and refused to meet with members of Congress on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little to be gained by such a meeting,'' his national
security adviser, Richard V. Allen, wrote to presidential aide Ed
Meese. Allen was more upset at the verbal ``harassment'' that
Irish-American demonstrators were giving British diplomats in the
United States. He demanded that Meese send letters to the top
police officials in Boston and New York, requesting better
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is intolerable that the representatives of our staunchest
ally in the world are subjected to this sort of treatment,'' Allen
wrote Meese, on Aug. 27, 1981.
</P>
<P>
   As the hunger strikers died, Reagan and O'Neill were waging
their historic tax and budget battle over the size and role of
American government. But despite their heated rhetorical volleys,
the two men, for both personal and practical political reasons,
never allowed their relationship to completely deteriorate. A
shared fondness for funny stories and other things Irish served as
an important bridge.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1981, Reagan gave a private birthday lunch for
O'Neill at the White House. Calling for a bottle of champagne, the
president toasted the speaker's health saying, ``Tip, if I had a
ticket to heaven and you didn't have one too, I would give mine
away and go to hell with you.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aide Michael Deaver recalled ``It was an old Irish
toast Reagan had heard somewhere. Tip's eyes were all filled up and
they left the dining room with their arms around each other's waist
and Reagan took him down to the elevator . . . and Tip went out to
the South Lawn and beat the hell out of Reagan with the press.''
</P>
<P>
   In public, O'Neill gave no quarter. Privately, he wrote Reagan
to thank him for ``a birthday I will never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan, meanwhile, was cultivating another friend in Thatcher,
who endorsed the president's arms buildup and muscular approach
toward the Soviet Union and was attempting to match Reagan's
attempts to trim back government with her own conservative
revolution in Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm with you on our girl Margaret,'' Reagan wrote the US
Ambassador to Great Britain, Charles H. Price, in his
characteristic squiggly handwriting. If the British public ``turn
away from her, they may well have thrown away their last chance,''
Reagan wrote.
</P>
<P>
   When Thatcher journeyed to Washington in 1983, Reagan rebuffed
O'Neill's requests to add Ireland to the agenda. And in May 1984,
when Hume and his Irish counterparts released the report of a
diplomatic effort called the New Irish Forum, which called for an
Anglo-Irish agreement, Reagan aide Peter Sommer wrote to his boss,
national security adviser Robert C. McFarlane that ``State and I
had earlier agreed that it would be inappropriate to draw the White
House into the middle of this complex, historical problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be very frank, I don't think we should allow ourselves to
be used by the Irish; particularly since the Irish have not been
especially supportive of our interests on such issues as Central
America,'' Sommer wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But by now O'Neill had an important ally in the administration:
former judge William Clark, who served as national security adviser
and then Secretary of the Interior, and took a personal interest in
Irish affairs. Clark worked with Kennedy and O'Neill and their
staffs, and provided an important countervoice to the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Thatcher agreed to discuss the findings of the New Irish Forum
with FitzGerald, but then she narrowly escaped death when the IRA
bombed her Conservative Party's conference in October 1984. At a
famous press conference following talks with FitzGerald that
November, she curtly dismissed three compromise proposals to give
the Irish a greater a voice in Northern Ireland's affairs as ``out
. . . out . . .out.''
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's adamant stand set the stage for O'Neill's
Dec. 13 letter, which was followed by one or more private
conversations between the speaker and Reagan, and the
Reagan-Thatcher Camp David talks.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving office, Thatcher expressed disappointment in the
results of the subsequent Anglo-Irish Agreement, which she signed
in November 1985, on a day when a beaming Reagan and O'Neill
appeared together at the White House to hail the deal. American,
Irish, and Northern Irish leaders have since credited the agreement
as a crucial stage-setter for Clinton's involvement and the current
peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Why did Reagan and Thatcher bend to O'Neill's request?
</P>
<P>
   Reagan's rediscovery of his Irish roots, and his years of
swapping stories with the Speaker, certainly played a role, said
Deaver. Nor could Reagan and Thatcher fail to appreciate that
O'Neill was taking a political risk. The Irish-American community
in Boston and New York and other large cities was split between
moderates and militants. The British recognized the difficult role
O'Neill and the other Horsemen had taken.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in an extraordinary 12-page letter to Reagan, the
indefatigable advocate for the Irish republican cause, Paul O'Dwyer
of New York, condemned O'Neill for making ``politically-motivated
pronouncements'' which ``transferred the blame for the violence in
Northern Ireland from the British occupation forces and placed it
squarely on the shoulders of the Northern Ireland victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Thatcher's own political instincts and advisers told her she had
gone too far with her ``out . . . out . . . out'' remarks. And,
hoping to follow in the footsteps of her Conservative Party hero,
Winston Churchill, she coveted something O'Neill could convey: the
honor of addressing the US Congress in joint session.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such an occasion would be the highlight of her visit,''
British ambassador Oliver Wright wrote the speaker. Thatcher
addressed the Congress on her next trip to Washington, on Feb. 20,
1985, and met with O'Neill for an hour that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Farrell's e-mail address is J_Farrell(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
