<HEADLINE>
WEST IMPRESSED WITH CLIPPERS' MOVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jerry West phoned Elgin Baylor Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Not to set up a golfing date. Not to kibitz about the good old
days when they dispensed heroics together with the Lakers. Not even
to commiserate with Baylor over his brave choice to continue
working for Donald T Sterling all these years.
</P>
<P>
   What Jerry West had to say to Elgin Baylor had to be comforting
words for the long-beleaguered general manager of the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to congratulate Elgin for what a great job he
did on draft day,'' said West, referring to Baylor's dramatic
makeover of the Clippers during Wednesday's NBA draft in which he
(a) acquired the top high school player in the country, Darius
Miles, (b) acquired a talented point guard from Missouri, Keyon
Dooling, (c) acquired a talented shooting guard from DePaul,
Quentin Richardson, (d) acquired still another talented shooting
guard from Yugoslavia, Marko Jaric, (e) acquired a talented
swingman from Orlando, Corey Maggett, (f) acquired a veteran
forward from Orlando, Derek Strong and (g) acquired a new
reputation for himself as being a (h) shrewd and (i) innovative
basketball executive.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Clippers, those widely disparaged, cruelly demeaned,
savagely ridiculed Staples Center co-tenants with the Lakers,
actually seemed to have pulled off a major coup.
</P>
<P>
   Honestly!
</P>
<P>
   ``Darius Miles has tremendous potential, and I think the L.A.
fans will like him,'' says West. ``What the Clippers did was get a
lot of young players who figure to be together for a long time
because of the five-year rookie cap. Lamar Odom and Darius Miles
one day could be quite a force.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not comparable to the heralded combo on West's team,
Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, but, well, at least the Clippers
for a change are being discussed without people poking fun at them.
. .
</P>
<P>
   bullet With so many youngsters now on their roster, the Clippers
figure to struggle mightily again next season, but figure to lose
in a more entertaining manner because these youngsters are all so
athletically gifted. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet Gosh, I'm embarrassed. Here I write about sports for a
living, and can't even recall the name of the Clipper coach. Am I
suffering the from puglistic dementia, or the first signs of
Alzheimer's Disease? Maybe so because I simply have no idea who's
coaching the team at the moment. Perhaps I will by the start of the
season, or will I? . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet If the Lakers didn't so desperately need a power
forward---and A.C. Green's lame work during the playoffs showed
that they did---the Lakers might have taken Jaric with their first
round pick instead of Stanford's rugged Mark Madsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jaric is a tremendous shooter,'' says West. ``I'm very high on
him.''
</P>
<P>
   West also is high on Mark Madsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fearless banger who will provide us with some inside
muscle,'' says West. ``I think he's going to turn out to be a good
player.''. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet Like so many modern athletes unable to resist million
dollar salaries, Orel Hershiser understandably continued his
pitching career far past his prime. I'm not surprised the Dodgers
finally waived him the other day. What surprised me was that the
Dodgers signed him in the first place. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet The only heavyweight fight that followers of the sweet
science want to see these days is Mike Tyson against Lennox Lewis,
and I doubt it will happen because Tyson is aligned with Showtime
and Lewis with HBO.
</P>
<P>
   And that's ridiculous!
</P>
<P>
   If two bitter rivals like Don King and Bob Arum can put aside
their differences to co-promote shows---and they've several---then
why can't Showtime and HBO come together with some sort of
pay-per-view alliance?
</P>
<P>
   A Tyson-Lewis match would be the richest in fight history, and
everyone affiliated with it would make a ton of money. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet Mike Tyson's weird behavior during and after his
38-second devastation of Lou Savarese last Saturday evening in
Scotland overshadowed the fact that Tyson looked impressive during
the brief exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Savarese wasn't an imposing challenge, but Tyson
flashed quickness, power and savage aggressiveness in disposing of
him.
</P>
<P>
   I still think Tyson's skills have deteriorated too much for him
to beat Lewis, but I do think he will making matters interesting
for the reigning heavyweight champion whose suspect heart would be
severely tested by Tyson. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet Yes, Mike Tyson did beat up his promoter, Frank Warren,
before the fight, and his latest temper tantrum cost him dearly. To
keep Warren from pressing charges, Tyson reportedly had to sign
over almost half of his $8 million purse---sources say $3
million---to Warren. Gee, I wouldn't mind getting my eyes bruised,
jaw broken, and ribs cracked for such an immense sum. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet No doubt that Mike Tyson is a sociopath whose strange
post-fight, I'm-going-to-eat-Lennox Lewis'-children,
I'm-going-to-eat-Lennox Lewis'-heart ravings was proof that he must
be off his anti-depressant pills. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet Every time I jog at El Dorado Park I'm thankful that Les
Robbins didn't get an opportunity to disrupt it by sticking an
athletic center in it. If he had, I and a lot of other folks would
have stopped visiting the most tranquil and serene place in Long
Beach. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet The old football player and television actor, Fred Dryer,
could run for public office, or become a sports talk radio host,
based on his animated performance on my and Joe McDonnell's show
last Sunday evening on KABC (790 AM). The guy was refreshingly
outspoken on a variety of hot-button political issues, and is
definitely not politically correct. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet Wow, I can't hardly endure the agonizing wait for the
first Monday Night Football telecast so I can be enlightened by
Dennis Miller's gibberish. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet If Anna Kournikova could play tennis as well as she
photographs, she'd never lose a match. Alas, she now has gone 68
tournaments without a championship after getting eliminated the
other day at Wimbledon by one Gaelle Sidot. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet Who has the longest-running sports talk radio show in
L.A.? You guessed it, that two-fisted, tell-it-like-it-is one-time
publicist for the Angels and New York Yankees, the incomparable Irv
Kaze, who does his weekly bit on Saturday evening at 6 o'clock on
KIEV (870 AM). His guests this week will be Jerry Buss and Michael
Andretti. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet The Yankees might have won three of the past four World
Series, but they don't figure to win one this autumn because
they've made two terrible miscalculations in recent times---trading
David Wells for Roger Clemens and turning down a trade with the
Angels for Jim Edmonds. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet Where would the Angels be now had they only been willing
to spend their money and retained Chuck Finley and Edmonds, who was
their best player, even though no one on the team ever seemed to
realize it. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet The recent death of the Seal Beach used book guru, Nathan
Cohen, saddens me. . .
</P>
<P>
   The McDonell-Douglas Show, featuring Press Telegram columnist
Doug Krikorian and radio personality Joe McDonnell, can be heard on
Sunday night between 9 p.m. and midnight on KABC (790 AM). (this
paragraph all italics)
</P>
</TEXT>
