<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      06-29 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRISONERS OF WAR': A THOUSAND ACTS OF COURAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes appear at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This weekend on the History Channel, Sen. John McCain discusses
his imprisonment in a North Vietnamese prison. ``I was not a
hero,'' says McCain, heroically, ``I was witness to a hundred,
thousands of acts of courage, compassion and love by men who remain
my heroes to this day.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's recollections appear in ``Prisoners of War: Code of
Conduct,'' part of a ``Sworn to Secrecy Marathon'' featuring
prisoners and clandestine warfare, the History Channel's 12-hour
alternative to the holiday barbecue. In fact, in observance of the
long weekend, the network will be providing four such
morning-to-evening marathons, from Saturday through Tuesday, July
4. There will be lots of Nazis marching, as is usual on this
network, and tales of the American Revolution, but also programs
about cannibalism, King Tut and Dracula. Clearly, History Channel
programming executives aren't slaves to thematic coherence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Code of Conduct,'' a speedy survey of the treatment of
prisoners of war from the Korean conflict through the Persian Gulf
War, celebrates American heroism. It also helps explain why McCain,
during his brief presidential campaign, appealed even to people who
didn't share his political beliefs. He presents an image of
authority but also humbleness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing for me was to choose an attitude of defiance
and an attitude that they would be unable to break my spirit and my
will,'' he says in the documentary.
</P>
<P>
   The program aims to honor McCain and other American prisoners of
war without delving into historical complexity or political nuance.
Without being artful or even particularly insightful, ``Code of
Conduct'' capitalizes on mesmerizing old film footage (a History
Channel specialty) and compelling stories of capture and torture.
Endurance is recognized as one kind of heroism, with the message
subliminally reinforced by having a movie hero (Charlton Heston)
narrate.
</P>
<P>
   A retired brigadier general, Kenneth North, also a prisoner of
war in Vietnam, describes the introductory method of torture used
by the North Vietnamese: pulling a prisoner's arms behind his back
and tying them together at the elbows, then yanking them higher
until bones were dislocated. ``Trying to get your attention,''
comments North, wryly.
</P>
<P>
   It's attention-getting, and sad and terrible, to hear about such
cruelty. So the program provides some balm by explaining the
inventive ways the POWs managed to communicate with one another (in
solitary confinement) and with the outside world. One American
captive, dragged in front of cameras for propaganda purposes,
blinked a message in Morse code. U.S. intelligence officers
implanted messages into letters from the prisoners' loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   McCain tells of a prisoner who gathered bits of thread and sewed
an American flag inside his shirt. Every night his fellow prisoners
saluted his shirt and said the Pledge of Allegiance. When the
Vietcong discovered the flag, they beat the prisoner badly and
threw him back in the cell. McCain remembers watching this man take
his revenge by sewing another flag, almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   These cinematic moments are placed in context, but only briefly.
We see film of diplomats scurrying and hear about the two Geneva
Conventions (1929 and 1949), in which the signing countries laid
out the rules governing prisoners of war. The program mentions a
crucial paradox: North Vietnam said it didn't have to comply with
the rules because the U.S. government had failed to call the war a
war. Therefore, the North Vietnamese argued, the POWs were pirates
and criminals, not entitled even to the meager niceties provided by
the Geneva Convention.
</P>
<P>
   But with dawn-to-dusk holiday programming ahead, there's no time
to linger on complexities _ and there are many wars to relive, over
and over again.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `PRISONERS OF WAR'
</P>
<P>
   Code of Conduct
</P>
<P>
   3 p.m. ET Sunday on the History Channel
</P>
<P>
   A co-production of Documedia and the History Channel. For
Documedia: Alan Beattie, executive producer; Charles Proser, John
Corry and Robert Beemer, supervising producers; Deborah Blum,
writer/producer; Robert C. Doyle, consultant; Andrea Scharf and
Lisa Hartjens, researchers; Charlton Heston, narrator. Charlie
Maday, executive producer, and Joe LaPolla, supervising producer,
for the History Channel.
</P>
</TEXT>
