<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-RENO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO WILL LOOK AT NEW RULES FOR CHILD ASYLUM CASES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A day after 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez returned to
Cuba with his family, Attorney General Janet Reno said she will
review whether there should be new regulations for dealing with
children in political asylum cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're following up ... and one of the questions I want to ask
is what, if anything, should be done,'' Reno said Thursday. ``Where
do you draw the line between a 6-year-old and a 12-year-old? How do
you make these judgments?''
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Naturalization Service regulations don't address
a minimum age for children to seek asylum against their parents'
wishes. But immigration officials have been firm, and the courts
have backed them up, in deciding that for very young children, a
parent is the best and only person who can speak for the child in
immigration matters.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Elian, whose mother drowned en route to Florida
last year, his father made the decision to take him back to their
communist homeland. Despite a seven-month legal battle, Elian's
distant relatives in Miami were unsuccessful in convincing the
courts that the child should be allowed to speak for himself and
make his own decision.
</P>
<P>
   The only similar case was one involving Walter Polovchak, who
sought asylum against his parents' wishes in the 1970s to avoid
being returned to the Soviet Union. In that case, an appellate
court ruled in Polovchak's favor, saying age 12 was the lower limit
of when a child's wishes should be recognized as independent from
those of his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Reno indicated Thursday that she would not favor writing a
specific age into the regulations, saying, ``I think it's going to
depend on the child.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Elian, Reno said, ``in the end, he is with his father,
and I am glad of that. I just wish he were with his father in a
democratic, free country.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she had held out some hope throughout the long ordeal
that Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, would decide to remain
in the United States, Reno said, ``One can always hope.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was adamant that Gonzalez was given every opportunity to
stay. ``He was sitting right there, and he said he wanted to go
home,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is wonderful that they can now move on with their life, and
his father has made the decision, as I think he must have, under
the law,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, a native of Miami who has repeatedly expressed her
devotion to the city and its Cuban-American community, also voiced
an appeal to those who feel wounded by her decisions in the case,
and by her call to remove the child from his Miami relatives' home
by force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to talk to you. I would like to let you know just
how much I care about you and care about the community and what it
has done for a city I love,'' she said. ``This hurt may go too
deep, which I will regret, but I still have to do what I think is
right under the law, and I think that this little boy's father
should speak for him, and I think he should be with his father.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general recalled visiting her hometown last
Thanksgiving and reading a story in the newspaper about Elian's
survival of the boat sinking that killed his mother and 10 other
Cuban refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I thought, what a remarkable little boy and what a sad
situation, a tragedy. And it's a mixture of so many different
things: a little boy who lost his mother, a country that is not
free. It's a story of families that have disagreements,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a story of so much of human life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF FILE
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
