<HEADER>
A8785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SISTER-HAZEL-NYTR &LR;      06-29 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SISTER-HAZEL-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW `FORTRESS' FOR SISTER HAZEL 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL DeYOUNG   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Life is good for Sister Hazel, Gainesville's
platinum-selling rock 'n' roll group. ``Fortress,'' the band's
first album in more than four years, was released Tuesday by
Universal Records, and the band began a national tour Thursday in
St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Written entirely by the band members, ``Fortress'' shows a
muscular, confident Sister Hazel.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen years of nearly nonstop roadwork have toughened
them up; it's a much stronger album than 1996's ``Somewhere More
Familiar,'' which they recorded independently and then sold to
Universal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of bands go in and try and get their live
sound on a disc, and it didn't happen,'' the singer and guitarist
Andrew Copeland said as the band members relaxed recently in a
Gainesville restaurant after a long day of rehearsal before their
tour. ``We got lucky this time, and were able to capture that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Fortress'' wasn't an easy delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere More Familiar'' was so successful that they stayed
on the road a little longer than they probably should have.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, last summer, Sister Hazel convened in a Los Angeles
studio with the Guns N' Roses producer Mike Clink. ``We wanted
somebody that had made some big-sounding records to capture the
energy that our indie record didn't have,'' said Ken Block, singer,
guitarist and chief songwriter. ``We were hungry to make a real
record.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Clink and Ritchie Zito, who co-produced, helped the
band make an album's worth of hard-rocking songs, they all knew
something was missing. ``We could've put a record out, and it
would've been a damn good record,'' said Ryan Newell, whose slide
guitar work is one of Sister Hazel's secret weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't saying everything we wanted to say, and we were
feeling creatively like we weren't all on the same page,'' Block
said. ``I remember literally sitting around the pool and saying,
`Let's stop this.' The tracks were very one-dimensional to me. I
felt like we were beating our heads against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   What was missing? Well, frankly, it was a song to match the
group's breakthrough hit, ``All for You,'' a Top 20 single in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, everyone who's in this business knows you have to
have one song that you can really be confident will succeed at
radio,'' Block said, ``or your run will be over very quickly. And
we weren't sure we had that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Clink understood and bowed out. ``When we were talking about
stopping,'' Copeland said, ``I was scared and thinking, `Man, this
is it. We're crumpling right here. Something's going wrong.'
Luckily, it was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The band _ which also includes the drummer Mark Trojanowski and
the bassist Jeff Beres _ took Zito to a studio in Atlanta, where he
went to work with Paul Ebersold, who had produced ``Somewhere.'' He
was someone more familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came back to our support system,'' Block said, ``played a
couple shows, tested out a couple songs live before we met Paul and
Ritchie in the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, we needed that balance. Because we
wanted someone who remembered where we came from, who'd helped us
shape songs that were hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a couple of days, Block had written three new songs,
including ``Change Your Mind,'' the first single from ``Fortress''
and currently one of the most frequently played songs on radio
playlists.
</P>
<P>
   The new material was recorded quickly. ``We said, `Now we have
something that feels right,' and then everything else just started
falling into place,'' Block said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every song right behind it, we just found our groove again,''
he said. ``We remembered what it is we do and why we do it, and it
was great. `Change Your Mind,' ironically, changed the pace of the
whole record.''
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Sister Hazel will fly to London to shoot a ``Change
Your Mind'' video with Elizabeth Hurley, who's using the song in
her next movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortress'' is no mere rehash of early Sister Hazel _ there's a
string quartet on ``Your Winter,'' and Emily Saliers of the Indigo
Girls adds vocals to Block's ``Champagne High.'' Copeland wrote
``Strange Cup of Tea,'' Beres contributed ``Surreal,'' and
Trojanowski and Newell are credited as co-writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just something we felt was right at this point in
time, and we stand by it,'' Newell said. ``We plan on doing many
different types of records.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want somebody to put in a disc and say, `That's the
way Sister Hazel will always sound. That's the stamp,' because we
want to experiment and take our fans on that journey with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Information on the band's tour and selections from ``Fortress''
are available at www.sisterhazel.com.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sun in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8787 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN-1ST     06-29 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTES TO CLOSE CAMPAIGN FINANCING LOOPHOLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: subs for complete writethru, expands throughout; note double
byline) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   with JOHN M. BRODER   c.2000 N.Y. Times News
Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate approved a bipartisan bill Thursday that
requires a growing number of secretive tax-exempt groups that raise
and spend money on political activities to reveal their donors and
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said he would sign the measure into law, the
first important change in the nation's campaign finance law in
nearly a quarter-century. Only six Senate Republicans voted against
the measure, which the House endorsed on Wednesday, 385-39.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passage of this bill proves that public interest can triumph
over special interests,'' Clinton said in a statement, urging
lawmakers to keep pressing for a more comprehensive election law
overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers passed the campaign disclosure bill as Congress raced
to finish several spending bills and a measure on collective
bargaining for doctors before they adjourned for the July 4 recess
and a week of campaigning back home.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters hailed Thursday's outcome as a major victory over
Senate and House Republican leaders who had tried to block the
measure, but they acknowledged that the legislation may have only a
limited impact on the remaining four months of this campaign cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not pretending we don't have other loopholes to close, but
those groups that have found this an easy, painless way to go on
the attack are now going to have to scramble to figure out
different ways,'' said Sen. Russell D. Feingold, D-Wis.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid the new disclosure requirements, some of the groups
formed under Section 527 of the Internal Revenue Code may
reorganize as for-profit organizations and lose their tax
exemptions, or as other types of nonprofits, tax lawyers said. Some
donors may rush big contributions to the groups, hoping to slip
them in before the new law takes effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure that the phones are ringing over on K Street right
now about how to get money into the 527s before they are
eliminated,'' said Rep. Michael N. Castle, R-Del., who supports the
bill, referring to Washington's center of high-powered lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, who heads the Senate
Republican re-election campaign and voted no Thursday, played down
the measure's significance, calling it a ``relatively benign
bill.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell, an ardent opponent of the campaign finance overhaul
who is not up for re-election this year, urged fellow Republicans
who were facing re-election to vote yes ``to insulate them against
absurd charges that they are in favor of secret campaign
contributions or Chinese money or Mafia money.'' McConnell said he
voted against the bill because it was an infringement on free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas issued a statement applauding
passage of the disclosure bill. ``As I have previously stated, I
believe these third-party groups should have to disclose who is
funding their ads. As the only candidate to fully disclose
contributors on a daily basis, I have always been a strong believer
in sunshine and full disclosure.'' During the primary season, a
longtime political supporter of Bush's set up a Section 527 group
called Republicans for Clean Air, which spent $2.5 million on issue
advertisements criticizing the environmental record of a Bush
opponent for the Republican nomination, Sen. John McCain of
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The final vote on the measure Thursday was 92-6. The five other
Republicans who voted no were Paul Coverdell of Georgia, Jesse
Helms of North Carolina, James M. Inhofe of Oklahoma, Connie Mack
of Florida and Don Nickles of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who championed the Senate bill, said that whatever
fallback positions the Section 527 groups took would offer fewer
filing and reporting advantages than they have now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill will not solve what is wrong with our campaign
finance system,'' said McCain, promising to continue his fight to
eliminate the unlimited donations called soft money. ``But it will
give the public information regarding one especially pernicious
weapon used in modern campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   A spectrum of political players has created Section 527
committees, including liberal interest groups, wealthy individuals
and a conservative group aligned with Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the
House majority whip.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations use donations for polling, advertising, phone
banks and direct-mail appeals, but are not subject to federal
filing or reporting rules so long as they do not advocate the
election or defeat of a specific candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The bill approved by Congress would require Section 527
committees that raise more than $25,000 a year to comply with
federal campaign laws and file tax returns. They would have to
disclose any contributors who gave more than $200 and report any
expenditures above $500. These provisions would take effect as soon
as the legislation is signed by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Section 527 groups would have to report their donors and
spending to the Internal Revenue Service every three months during
an election year. The information would then be made public and
posted on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign disclosure measure would be the first alteration of
campaign finance law since technical changes were made in 1979 to
the Federal Election Campaign Act of 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Several groups operating under Section 527 said Thursday that
they would continue their fund raising and political activities
even as they reviewed their legal status.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Gallant, a DeLay ally who runs the Republican Majority
Issues Committee, said he intended to ``continue on our core
mission to give conservative voters a voice in the upcoming
elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee, which acts as DeLay's political action committee,
expects to spend as much as $25 million in closely contested House
races around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Gallant said he was uncertain about the practical impact on his
group. He said the committee would comply with the law, but ``we
are deeply concerned that Congress has placed the regulation of
free speech in the hands of the tax collectors.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We're not going anywhere. You will have RMIC to
amuse and delight you throughout the election cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the political spectrum, the Sierra Club has
conducted political activities under a Section 527 organization
called the Environmental Voter Education Campaign since 1995. Dan
Weiss, the Sierra Club's political director, said the group planned
to spend about $8 million in this year's campaign on political
advertising on environmental issues. He said the group supported
Republican and Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will eagerly comply with the new law as soon as it takes
effect,'' Weiss said. ``But it's important to note that while we
strongly support the passage of this reform, 527 money is just the
tip of the soft-money iceberg. Real reform would mean banning all
soft-money contributions to political parties.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most lavishly funded Section 527 organizations is
Citizens for Better Medicare, a group established a year ago by the
pharmaceutical industry to lobby against a government-run
prescription drug benefit under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The group has already spent more than $30 million on television,
radio, print and Internet advertising and has been active in more
than a dozen congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Zielinski, a spokesman for Citizens for Better Medicare,
said the group was reviewing its legal position in light of the
disclosure measure but had not decided whether it would abandon its
Section 527 status.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coalition is not going away,'' Zielinski said. ``We will
comply with whatever legal requirements are necessary. We'll do
whatever the lawyers say we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the financial scale from the drug industry
is the Peace Voter Fund, a modestly funded remnant of the peace
movement of the 1970s and 1980s. The fund, a Section 527 group,
plans to engage in voter education and issue advocacy on
disarmament in about a dozen congressional districts this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gosse, the group's executive director, said he would follow
the dictates of the new law and continue the group's political
activities as in the past. ``Disclosure of donors is not a major
issue for us,'' Gosse said. ``So we'll just say to donors in the
future that they will be subject to federal disclosure
requirements. It's no biggie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
