<SLUG> BC-ADVISORY-REAGAN-ULSTER-EXCLUSIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe, in a 2000-word story by staff reporter John
Aloysius Farrell, reveals that President Ronald Reagan and Speaker
Thomas P. ``Tip'' O'Neill Jr. conspired to advance the cause of
peace in Northern Ireland at a key juncture in 1984, pressing
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher to recognize an American
and Irish role in the affairs of the troubled province,
newly-released documents show.
</P>
<P>
   According to Reagan White House papers, which are part of more
than 10,000 pages released to The Boston Globe by his presidential
library under the US Freedom of Information Act, the former
president was persuaded by a personal appeal by the late House
Speaker to make a private approach to Thatcher, the world leader
with whom Reagan had his closest personal and ideological ties.
</P>
<P>
   The story BC-REAGAN-ULSTER-EXCLUSIVE-BOS has moved (a, i).
