<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8792 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-ABORTION-RIGHTS-560(2     06-29 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-RIGHTS-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION OPPONENTS PLAN NEW LAWS TO GET AROUND SUPREME COURT
DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb., S.D., Ind., Ohio)  (EDS: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A day after the Supreme Court effectively struck down bans on a
medical procedure its opponents call ``partial birth abortion,''
supporters of those bans said they were already planning a new
generation of laws that they hope will withstand further legal
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   In its 5-4 decision Wednesday, the Supreme Court majority said
that to be constitutionally acceptable, laws that ban the
procedures must specify the type of procedure barred. The court
also required that the laws must permit even the use of that
procedure if it is considered necessary to preserve the health of
the mother. The laws existed in some 30 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our state senators has already contacted our office to
get assistance to draft a new law that could withstand
constitutional scrutiny,'' said L. Steven Grasz, the chief deputy
attorney general of Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska's ban was the only one the Supreme Court considered in
the case decided on Wednesday. But legal experts said the court's
decision was likely to invalidate similar laws around the country,
and would spur efforts to pass new bans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a rush back to the drawing boards,'' said
Laurence Tribe, an expert on constitutional law at Harvard Law
School. Tribe and other legal experts said the court's majority
opinion had left little maneuvering room for the proponents of the
bans.
</P>
<P>
   But legislators and legal technicians on both sides of the
abortion issue said that, however the high court is composed,
battles over the procedure are likely to continue around the
country for years. Partial-birth abortion is the term opponents of
abortion use to describe one of several methods doctors use to
terminate pregnancies after about 16 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Hunt, the speaker of South Dakota's House of
Representatives, said Thursday that efforts were already underway
to analyze that state's ban and ``to see what, if anything, we may
need to do to amend our statute so that we meet constitutional
muster as far as the Supreme Court is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   In Indiana, State Sen. Patricia Miller, who sponsored the ban
there four years ago, said she would propose legislation if
necessary to meet the requirements of the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still very much believe that states have the right to
restrict partial-birth abortion,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the legal fight over Nebraska's ban, other states' bans
have been challenged in state and federal courts, and judges across
the country have permanently or temporarily barred the enforcement
of many of them, often using some of the same reasons cited in the
Supreme Court decision.
</P>
<P>
   So even before the court's ruling, supporters had been working
on strategies to rewrite the laws.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these revised bans are already on the books. Because of
court challenges, however, only eight of the bans are now in full
force across the country, according to the National Right to Life
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said those who want to ban the procedure might be
able to comply relatively easily with the requirement that the laws
describe what is banned more specifically. But they said that the
laws could falter concerning the requirement about the health of
the mother.
</P>
<P>
   Ban proponents said that such a broad exception permitting the
procedure would undercut the law since a physician could always say
it was needed to preserve the health of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, for example, an early ban was struck down by a federal
appeals court, and the Legislature enacted a new law that its
supporters say should meet some of the Supreme Court's new
requirements. That law is to take effect next month. The new Ohio
law is more specific in defining what is considered an illegal
partial-birth abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Heller, the litigation director of the Center for
Reproductive Law and Policy, which opposes the bans, called the
Ohio law an example of what he said would be new efforts to better
describe the prohibited abortion methods.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Supreme Court opinion, written by Justice Stephen G. Breyer,
said that the Nebraska law had been written too broadly.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer's decision said the Nebraska law, imposed an ``undue
burden'' on a woman's right to choose a D &AMP; E abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have said the legislation is often stated very generally
because its supporters are trying to discourage all abortions, not
just those they describe as partial birth abortions.
</P>
<P>
   In revised laws across the country, Heller said, ``they will now
try to come up with different language that they will claim is
limited to this one specific procedure, but that really isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   His group, which has challenged many bans nationally, is
preparing to challenge the Ohio law, which, he said, remains so
broadly worded that it could be read as banning more than the D &AMP; X
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bans denied they intended to limit women's
rights to other methods of abortion. Grasz, the Nebraska deputy
attorney general, said that abortion-rights groups make that claim
to motivate their supporters with the fear that the right to
abortion is at stake, not just a limitation on a particular method
of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing the states were trying to do,'' he said, ``was
ban partial birth abortion.'' Those efforts, he said, would
continue.
</P>
<P>
   People on both sides of the abortion issue were also divided
yesterday regarding the Supreme Court's requirement that any ban _
to be constitutional _ must permit the use of the D &AMP; X procedure
if it is deemed necessary to preserve the health of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the bans said that rule was needed to preserve a
meaningful right to choice guaranteed by the 1973 abortion
decision, Roe vs. Wade.
</P>
<P>
   But proponents of the bans said they regarded that part of the
opinion as a trap for them. On the one hand, they said, if new laws
are too narrow, they will be struck down like the Nebraska law that
did not include an exception to preserve the health the mother. All
existing laws permit the use of ``partial-birth'' procedures if
they are necessary to save the life of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, proponents of the bans contend, if the
``health of the mother'' exception is too broad, the bans would be
ineffective because doctors would invoke it routinely to use the
banned procedures.
</P>
<P>
   In a companion suit to the landmark Roe vs. Wade case in 1973,
the Supreme Court defined ``the health of the mother'' broadly to
include factors like a woman's age, and physical, psychological or
emotional condition.
</P>
<P>
   Dorinda C. Bordlee, a special assistant attorney general in
Louisiana who has defended the state's 1997 ``partial birth'' ban,
said she was considering advising the Louisiana legislature to
amend its law to define the mother's health as ``significant
long-term physical risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a law would surely be challenged in court.``That would
force the Supreme Court to reconsider what it considers `health,'
'' Bordlee said.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews yesterday, opponents and proponents of the bans
said their counterparts were unlikely to give up the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``If new statutes are passed that attempt to satisfy the court,
abortion providers will challenge those laws. That's been the
history,'' said Clay R. Smith, the solicitor for the State of
Montana, who has defended Montana's ban in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The abortion providers have very able lawyers,'' Smith said,
``and they're very persistent.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 2103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
