<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8794 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-BOS &LR;      06-29 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVILY GUARDED, ELIAN BEGINS LIFE AGAIN IN CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Cuba's most famous little boy began his life back home
Thursday much the way he lived it in the United States: in a
comfortable house, surrounded by loved ones and under heavy
security away from public view.
</P>
<P>
   But one major difference now for Elian Gonzalez is that the
agonizing, seven-month long custody battle that had him trapped
between two families and two countries is finally over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the homeland at last,'' a front-page headline
proclaimed in the Communist Party daily Granma.
</P>
<P>
   And while Cubans here expressed the same joy and relief that
their small hero was back for the first time since November, when
he survivied a migrant shipwreck off the coast of Florida that
killed his mother, there were no mass expressions of happiness or
demonstrations relishing victory _ by order of the Cuban
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fantastic to have Elian back where he belongs,'' said
Jacobo Ruiz, a 37-year-old Havana resident. ``But we're not going
to put on shows. The family needs to recover and we will respect
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian and his family, including his father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, who spent two months in the United States trying to bring
him home, spent Thursday reuniting with relatives and close friends
at a government-provided home, complete with swimming pool, in the
upscale neighborhood of Miramar.
</P>
<P>
   Security was tight around the freshly painted white dwelling.
Uniformed guards sealed off streets near the home to keep visitors
and journalists at a safe distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to get things back to normal as best we can
for the family and the country,'' said one government official.
</P>
<P>
   Around the capital, that's just how things appeared. Many of the
signs and billboards demanding Elian's return have been taken down
or replaced with traditional revolutionary images and slogans.
</P>
<P>
   The recently built protest plaza adjacent the US Interests
Section office, which had been the site of countless pro-government
and anti-US demonstrations by Cuban children, mothers, and workers,
was quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Even the welcoming ceremony for the boy on Wednesday evening at
Havana's international airport was brief and unusually low key for
a saga that has helped rekindle Cuba's revolutionary fervor and
strengthen President Fidel Castro's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   A shy and slightly awed Elian was lifted out of the private
plane by his father and waved stiffly to a small gathering of
classmates who had been quickly bused in from his hometown of
Cardenas, about 90 miles east of the capital. As he hugged teary
relatives, including the two grandmothers who tried unsuccessfully
to bring him back from the United States earlier this year, a band
played the Cuban national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   In less than ten minutes, the boy, his father, stepmother and
infant half-brother were placed into a small white Russian-made
sedan and driven away.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was allowed to return home Wednesday after the US Supreme
Court refused to intervene in the custody case between Miami
relatives and his Cuban father. The family left Washington shortly
after the final court order keeping Elian in the United States
expired at 4 p.m., ending one of the most dramatic and closely
watched legal sagas in US history.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, many of Elian's classmates returned to Cardenas, where
residents lined the streets, cheered and waved flags.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Castro _ who turned the custody battle into a
national crusade against exiled Cuban-Americans, who wanted Elian
to stay with relatives in Florida, and the US government _ did not
attend the arrival ceremony and refrained from making any public
statements Thursday, reluctant, perhaps, to further politicize the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no doubt that Elian's return to Cuba is a major
victory for Castro and his 40-year-old Communist regime and its
ongoing battle against its northern neighbor. Over the last three
years, the Castro government has used a variety of international
events _ from a papal visit to an exhibition baseball game with the
Baltimore Orioles and the struggle over Elian _ to keep hammering
away at US immigration policies and a Cold War-era economic
embargo.
</P>
<P>
   So now that the Elian drama is over, what's next?
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said Elian and his family would spend the
next two or three weeks at the Havana house, getting caught up on
missed schoolwork and readjusting to being back in Cuba. After
that, the family will be given a week's vacation and then return to
Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Castro government, the fight against US policies will
go on, although presumably without its young protagonist. A mass
rally of 200,000 demonstrators in the eastern city of Manzanillo is
scheduled for Saturday. And the nationally televised roundtables _
a Cuban version of the town hall meeting _ will continue, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   A government statement _ one of six published in Thursday's
Granma newspaper _ appeared to introduce the next stage for US-Cuba
relations, repeating the government's criticisms of US laws that
grant Cuban refugees asylum and prohibit economic trade.
</P>
<P>
   No one ``should forget for one second that the fight for Elian's
return . . . is nothing more than the first chapter of a larger
battle that we must keep fighting,'' the statement read. ``With
Elian, we have saved a marvelous boy, but thousands of innocent
creatures . . . run the risk of being shipwrecked, hurt or
drowned.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8795 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-ABORTION-RIGHTS-560(2     06-29 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-RIGHTS-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION OPPONENTS PLAN NEW LAWS TO GET AROUND SUPREME COURT
DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb., S.D., Ind., Ohio)  (EDS: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
