<SLUG> BC-WELDS-SEPARATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-MASS. GOVERNOR WELD, WIFE LIVING SEPARATELY, SOURCES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS AND SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Former Massachusetts Governor William F. Weld's move to
New York, where he has thrown himself into the city's legal and
social circles, appears to be taking a toll in at least one area of
his life: his marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the former governor said the Welds are
experiencing marital difficulties. Susan Roosevelt Weld, who
maintains the family home in Cambridge, has also taken an apartment
in New York separate from her husband's.
</P>
<P>
   Weld has told friends his marriage has suffered as a result of
his active social life, including his dating relationship with a
writer for a celebrity magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The former governor has said Mrs. Weld, a quiet academic who
specializes in ancient Chinese law, is uncomfortable with his New
York friends and his frequent dining out at chic Manhattan
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   While Weld, a managing partner for McDermott, Will, &AMP; Emery,
maintains an apartment on Carnegie Hill, on New York's upper East
Side, his wife rents a separate residence in midtown. Mrs. Weld is
also spending several days of the week in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Weld did not return phone calls Thursday. Mrs. Weld could not be
reached. In previous interviews with the Globe, Weld has not spoken
directly about their marital status, but has alluded to his wife's
lack of enthusiasm for his New York lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   During the past year, according to sources, the former governor
began dating Leslie Marshall, who lives in his apartment building.
Marshall is a contributing editor covering fashion, movies, and
celebrities for In Style Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of the Welds' marital strain, buzzed about in Boston
political circles for months, emerged publicly Thursday in a New
York Post gossip column, which reported that Weld was dating a
journalist in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The former governor has told associates he and his wife do not
plan to divorce. ``Nobody is talking to lawyers,'' he recently told
one source.
</P>
<P>
   Since moving to New York, Weld, who declared in a recent
interview that he was a mere ``carpetbagger'' while in
Massachusetts, has been a rumored potential candidate for governor
or for U.S. Senate from New York. Last month he told the Globe he
is ``having too much fun'' in the private sector to consider
political office right now.
</P>
<P>
   Weld has not kept in close touch with his friends in Boston,
including those in the political world who worked with him during
his years in office, from 1991 to 1997. But his career and musings
about future plans _ from writing novels to a possible return to
public office _ are closely followed.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Globe last week, however, Weld declined
direct comment when asked about the widespread reports of troubles
in his marriage.
</P>
<P>
   But he did say that while he lived full time in Manhattan, his
wife was in New York only about two-fifths of the time. He said he
is in Boston about every two weeks, but just for quick visits.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would comment on widespread reports of discord in
his marriage, Weld replied: ``No.'' Then, choosing his words with
care, he added: ``I think it has been harder for Sue-Sue to make
the switch to a New York base professionally than I had
anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   Weld has also spoken about his active social life in New York.
``It is true that I've become an inveterate lover of fine
restaurants,'' he said. ``I have an active social life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Welds, both New York natives, were married in 1975 in Oyster
Bay, on Long Island.
</P>
</TEXT>
