<SLUG> BC-HMO-MEDICARE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE HMOS CUTTING BACK PARTICIPATION IN MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., R.I.)  (EDS NOTE: This is now a story on the Times front page. In 12th
graf, replace (plus) with addition sign in name of health plan:
Medicare(plus)Choice) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Health maintenance organizations will cancel
insurance coverage for more than 700,000 Medicare beneficiaries
next year because the HMOs are cutting back their participation in
Medicare, an industry trade group announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Karen M. Ignagni, president of the trade group, the American
Association of Health Plans, said the H: :"were pulling out of
numerous counties because they had been ``over-regulated and
underps.
</P>
<P>
   Many elderly people joined HMOs to get outpatient drug benefits,
but they may lose those benefits when they are forced out of HMOs.
The beneficiaries can return to Medicare's original fee-for-service
program, or they can try to find another HMO. But there is no
guarantee that other health plans will be available or have the
capacity to take them.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna U.S. Healthcare, a unit of Aetna Inc., one of the largest
managed care companies, told the Clinton administration on Thursday
that it was dropping more than half of its 659,000 Medicare
beneficiaries in 14 states. The cutbacks will affect a total of
355,000 people, including 36,629 in New York state, 14,780 in
Connecticut, 134,324 in Texas, 52,331 in Ohio, 47,670 in Florida,
18,650 in Pennsylvania and 15,283 in California.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions by HMOs to withdraw from Medicare are relevant to
the debate in Congress over how to provide prescription drug
benefits to people on Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 217-214, the House on Wednesday passed a bill under
which the government would pay subsidies to insurance companies to
get them to offer drug benefits to the elderly. Democratic members
of Congress repeatedly said that private companies could not be
trusted to provide stable, reliable drug benefits, and they cited
the volatile Medicare HMO market to support their contention.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Weygand, D-R.I., said he had just received a letter
from United Healthcare, saying it would pull out of the Medicare
market in Bristol County, R.I. Weygand said he feared that
insurance companies would, in a similar way, stop offering drug
benefits, as proposed under the House Republican plan, if the
business became unprofitable.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chris John, D-La., said the last HMO in his district had
just announced that it was pulling out of the Medicare managed care
program, known as Medicare(plus)Choice. ``The Republican
prescription drug plan would privatize drug coverage in the same
manner that Medicare(plus)Choice privatized health care services''
for the elderly, John said. ``And this plan, too, is doomed to
fail.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans said Thursday that any legislation adding
drug benefits to Medicare should be tied to larger changes in the
program, intended to control costs and promote competition.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Finance Committee, Sen. William V. Roth Jr.,
R-Del., said he hoped the panel would approve a Medicare bill next
month.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats said they doubted that Roth could muster a
consensus. They said that a deal on drug benefits might be arranged
this fall through high-level negotiations between President
Clinton, House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois and Trent Lott of
Mississippi, the Senate Republican leader.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Jennings, the health policy coordinator at the White
House, said the administration was concerned to see HMOs again
dropping large numbers of Medicare beneficiaries. ``It is
regrettable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation Health Systems, based in Los Angeles, said on
Thursday that it would discontinue its Medicare HMO operations in
parts of New York, New Jersey, Connecticut, Arizona, California and
Pennsylvania. The cutbacks will affect 19,000 people, or 7 percent
of the 259,000 Medicare beneficiaries in the company's health
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Cigna Corp., said earlier this month that it would end
coverage for 104,000 Medicare beneficiaries in 11 states, including
New York, New Jersey, Connecticut, California and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Donaldson, the chairman of Aetna Inc., said, ``The
decision to exit certain Medicare markets was reached with great
reluctance.'' But, he said, ``inadequate government reimbursements
have made operating a number of our Medicare HMOs no longer
viable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
