<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8803 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ISRAEL-AIRCRAFT-2TAKE     06-29 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-AIRCRAFT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI AIRCRAFT MAKER RUNS AFOUL OF U.S. WITH CHINA RADAR
CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOD, Israel _ Behind a tarpaulin-covered fence at the far edge
of the Israel Aircraft Industries complex at Ben-Gurion
International Airport here sits a refurbished Russian transport,
its saucer-like radar pod temporarily removed for fine-tuning.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, company officials say, the pod will be back, the
radar switched on, and the distinctive droop-winged jet ready for
its final test flights. The plane, a transformed Ilyushin-76, will
be able to monitor air and telecommunications traffic more than 200
miles away _ the specifications ordered by the plane's owner, the
People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
   For Israel Aircraft Industries' president, Moshe Keret, who over
the last 15 years has built a virtually bankrupt military
contractor into Israel's biggest exporter, the sale was to have
been one his greatest achievements. The Phalcon early-warning radar
system installed on the Chinese plane showcased all the strengths
of IAI _ as the state-owned company is known _ its technological
prowess and its success in developing new markets abroad to help
pay for Israel's weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Pentagon has its way _ and the betting here is that
it will _ the converted Ilyushin will never reach China, which long
ago gave Israel Aircraft the down payment on the $250 million spy
plane.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, President Clinton reiterated Washington's concern that
China could use the radar system against U.S. forces in the Taiwan
Strait. Earlier in the week, the House Appropriations Committee
called on Israel to terminate the deal, with many members pledging
to cut Israel's aid if it does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We signed a contract,'' a top official of Israel Aircraft
said. ``We have their money. Now we say, `No, sorry?'''
</P>
<P>
   To foreign policy analysts, the Phalcon dispute is an
illustration of how Israeli-U.S. strategic ties are still often
frayed by miscommunication and mistrust on both sides _ as well as
by rare but deep divergences in each country's conception of its
national interest. The China contract has opened the first
significant rift between the Clinton administration and the
government of Prime Minister Ehud Barak, just as both governments
are trying to persuade the Palestinians to join them in Washington
for a conclusive round of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   But to Keret, 65, who has worked at Israel Aircraft his entire
adult life, the conflict is also a potential business catastrophe,
one that he thinks directly threatens his company's prospects for
survival in an increasingly competitive and consolidated global
arms industry.
</P>
<P>
   A threat to Israel Aircraft's future is seen by many Israeli
leaders as a threat to the nation, both militarily and
economically. The company, founded in 1953, is the centerpiece of a
domestic arms and aeronautics industry that Israel considers the
key to its defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about the Phalcon per se,'' said Keret,
who has been asked by the government not to comment on the deal, at
IAI headquarters here. ``But what is the environment in which we
are operating? It is very competitive. Although we are a
state-owned company, we get no subsidy, and no favoritism from the
defense ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Boeing and other behemoths of the global defense
trade, Israel Aircraft is no giant: Its $1 billion in foreign
military sales puts it about 30th among major arms sellers abroad,
according to independent assessments. Overall sales reached $2
billion last year, two-thirds from military contracts and the rest
from commercial aircraft production and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   But it is difficult to overstate the company's importance to
Israel. With 14,000 skilled workers, Israel Aircraft is by far the
country's biggest industrial employer, comparable in U.S. terms to
General Motors and General Electric combined. A further 15,000
Israeli jobs are indirectly dependent on the company. And its $1.6
billion in military and commercial sales abroad make it the biggest
exporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a disaster in IAI for one reason or another,''
Keret said, ``its effects would be felt throughout the country.''
</P>
<P>
   A certain disaster for the company would be any significant
erosion of U.S. aid. IAI has been the biggest beneficiary of U.S.
rules permitting a quarter of military assistance to be spent in
Israel _ for purchases of arms produced in this country. Yet Moshe
Arens, a three-time former defense minister, whose views are widely
shared here, said this week that $2 billion in annual military aid
is ``not sufficient to make us start accepting U.S. control over
defense industry exports.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials seem mystified that Israel would jeopardize its
critical international alliance by pursuing what appears to be a
marginal weapons deal. Last fall, as the China controversy broke
into the open, the same Israeli officials who were defending the
Phalcon sale were presenting Washington with a $17 billion wish
list of arms they said the country needed to compensate for the
then-expected turnover of the Golan Heights to Syria. Now the
Israelis are discussing a similar military aid package to safeguard
a peace pact with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have tried to explain to Israelis that Americans cannot
understand why Israel was refusing to give up $250 million when it
was asking the United States for $17 billion,'' said David
Makovsky, who has been an Israeli analyst at the Washington
Institute for Near East Policy.
</P>
<P>
   But far more than $250 million is at stake, say Israeli leaders.
``We'll do our utmost to act sensitively and to be attentive to
U.S. interests,'' Barak, who appoints Israel Aircraft's board,
said. ``At the same time, there's a contract with China, signed
during the incumbency of the previous government. The state doesn't
call off contracts to which it is a signatory just like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even seen narrowly, the contract with China is potentially a $2
billion deal, huge by Israel Aircraft standards. Under terms
negotiated three years ago, Beijing has options to buy seven more
Phalcon-equipped Ilyushins. Fulfilling such a contract would
catapult the company into an elite fraternity of major contractors
in bidding for such systems _ and it would subsidize further
technological advances at home. Though Israel Aircraft lost to
Boeing in a recent bid to supply early-warning planes to Australia,
it is competing for a $2 billion contract in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Worse, executives say, the cancellation of the contract would be
a signal to potential customers that no deal with Israel Aircraft
is final, as the United States could effectively veto a promised
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better to buy from the Europeans,'' a gloomy executive said.
Or perhaps from the Russians, who supplied destroyers, cruise
missiles and other heavy weaponry to the Chinese over the last
decade with few protests from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as others here cynically suggest, from the Americans
themselves. Israelis point to the continuing export of advanced
military technology to China by the United States in the last
decade: Since the ban by Congress in 1989 on military sales to
Beijing, after the crackdown on pro-democracy protests in Tiananmen
Square, the White House has issued waivers for some $300 million in
exports of satellite and encryption equipment to the country.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the United States did not renege on its own deals,
Israelis note, fulfilling $36 million in orders placed by China
before the ban, including anti-artillery radar systems.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial last week, the newspaper Maariv decried what it
called ``Washington's attempts to torpedo the deal and sabotage
Israel's defense exports, perhaps out of the desire to protect the
interests of giant U.S. corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Maariv, like other leading media voices here, concluded that
Israel would have little choice but to renege on the contract.
Until the dispute is resolved, another daily, Haaretz, said, ``The
Phalcon will continue to be a sword of Damocles hanging over
Israel's head.''
</P>
<P>
   Keret seems surprised by the furor in Washington over the
Phalcon deal. Until newspapers here published photos of the plane
late last year, setting off the American outcry, company executives
say they considered the contract old news.
</P>
<P>
   When the company bid for the contract in 1996, Israel officially
notified the United States that the Phalcon system did not
incorporate protected U.S. technology, a contention the Pentagon
has never challenged. Though Washington officials say they objected
to the sale on strategic and human rights grounds, there were no
public complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, calling for delivery beginning in 2000, was concluded
in highly publicized trips to Moscow and Beijing by then-Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai.
In April 1998, the Phalcon sale was reported to Congress in a
General Accounting Office review of recent Chinese arms purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Again, there were no public U.S. protests, though officials say
they tried to dissuade Israel from signing. ``As the deal went
forward, they weren't hearing us anymore,'' a senior State
Department official said.
</P>
<P>
   Though U.S. companies were prohibited from selling radar planes
to China after the events there in June 1989, Israel Aircraft
considered this a commercial opportunity. In the first foreign sale
of its airborne radar, it sent a Phalcon-equipped Boeing 767 to
Chile, which was then prohibited by Congressional strictures from
buying Boeing Awacs surveillance planes. Washington raised no
objections, Keret said.
</P>
<P>
   From Central America in the 1980s to Turkey in the 1990s, the
company provided other military equipment to countries where U.S.
exports were constrained by human rights considerations.
</P>
<P>
   And in China, Israel Aircraft was hardly alone. Competitors in
Italy and Britain were both offering advanced airborne radar
systems to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States has since become more worried by Beijing's
conflict with Taiwan, and officials are telling the Israeli
contractor that no company so dependent on U.S. trade and aid can
consider itself geopolitically autonomous.
</P>
<P>
   By design, Keret has made Israel Aircraft increasingly reliant
on the United States as a market, supplier and business partner,
creating joint ventures with all the major aerospace companies. And
through its own U.S. subsidiaries _ including its Galaxy corporate
jet business, based in Fort Worth _ the company says it spends
about $400 million yearly in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   With such partners, the company specializes in upgrading U.S.
aircraft for foreign air forces _ and even for the United States
Air Force, which recently awarded Israel Aircraft and Boeing a $400
million contract to revamp 450 of its T-38 Talon trainers. The
small unmanned planes, an IAI specialty, proved a key
reconnaissance weapon for the U.S. Army in Kosovo, prompting other
NATO orders.
</P>
<P>
   In its most ambitious U.S. joint venture, Israel Aircraft is the
principal contractor on the Arrow, a $2 billion
anti-ballistic-missile system deployed here this year.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. support has been critical to the company's turnaround.
After weathering a worldwide plunge in military sales in the
mid-1990s, it has stayed in the black for 14 consecutive quarters.
Net profit last year rose to $70 million.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Boeing and Lockheed Martin heed the Pentagon before
pursuing foreign arms deals, so now must Israel Aircraft, many
officials of this country reluctantly conclude.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Israel Aircraft tried to buck the Pentagon and its
military contractors, Keret painfully recalls, it almost destroyed
the company. The project was his baby: IAI's own jet fighter, the
Lavi, envisioned as a successor _ and competitor _ to the Air
Force's F-16. The increasingly expensive project was canceled under
pressure from Washington in 1987, just a year after the Lavi's
maiden flight. The move wiped out 5,000 jobs and nearly propelled
Israel Aircraft into receivership.
</P>
<P>
   Keret is credited with rescuing the company from the Lavi
debacle. The radar and navigation and missile-guidance systems
developed for the Lavi were refined into independent products, many
of them now installed on IAI-refurbished F-16s.
</P>
<P>
   But as he sits in his corporate offices in Lod, which are still
decorated with models and photographs of the extinct Israeli
fighter, Keret says he regrets the loss of corporate and national
independence that the Lavi symbolized. ``It was a good plane,'' he
said. ``I'm sure we could have sold a lot of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
