<SLUG> BC-MCCRAY0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No charges filed against owner of gun used to shoot Florida
teacher
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ No charges will be filed against the
75-year-old man who owned the gun used to shoot middle school
teacher Barry Grunow.
</P>
<P>
   The gun was not stored loaded and 13-year-old Nathaniel Brazill
stole the gun from a drawer in Elmore McCray's bedroom, police and
the Palm Beach County State Attorney's Office concluded. The boy
later used the gun to kill Grunow, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, which were released Thursday, mean that McCray
cannot be charged with either the misdemeanor or a felony version
of failing to keep a firearm secure from minors. To be charged with
either crime, Florida law requires that the gun be loaded. The law
also exempts gun owners whose weapon is stolen.
</P>
<P>
   McCray could not be reached for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Brazill, who is charged with first-degree murder in the May 26
shooting, as well as McCray and four people who live with McCray
gave similar accounts to police about the .25-caliber Raven
semi-automatic used to kill the English teacher at Lake Worth
Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   After his arrest, Brazill told police several times that he took
the gun from McCray's bedroom and loaded it himself.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe Brazill took the gun when he stayed
several days at McCray's home while his mother was in South
Carolina. McCray's daughter is Brazill's godmother. The teen
sometimes visited and called McCray by the name ``Grand.''
</P>
<P>
   McCray told police he kept the gun in a desk drawer in a holiday
Oreo cookie tin. The ammunition was in a box in the tin, according
to a transcript of the police interview with McCray.
</P>
<P>
   McCray said he was given the gun about seven years ago by a
woman whose husband had died. She didn't want the gun in the house
because her son was involved in drugs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCray kept the gun unloaded `` 'cause I didn't want no loaded
gun in my house,'' he told police.
</P>
<P>
   He took the gun out only on New Year's Eve. While kids were in
the front yard shooting off fireworks, he said he would fire two
rounds into pine trees in his back yard to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   He said Brazill and other family members may have known that he
owned the gun from the celebration. McCray's 7-year-old great
granddaughter knew he owned a gun but did not know where it was
kept, she told police.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Luvenia Corbin, said the gun was kept unloaded and
James McGill, a friend who also lived there, said he didn't know
where it was kept. McCray's son, Willie Mack McCray said he didn't
know his father had obtained a gun since another had been stolen in
the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
