<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8809 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SUMMER-INDIE-FILMS-2T     06-29 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-INDIE-FILMS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO GUNS BLAZING, JUST IDEAS ON FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Here it is, the biggest party of the year, and they
cluster together off to the side: the members of the chess team,
the guys from the audiovisual club, future physics majors with
thick glasses and pocket protectors. Just what are they doing in
this room full of quarterbacks and cheerleaders? Who invited them
to the party?
</P>
<P>
   Every summer, the major Hollywood studios unleash their biggest,
loudest and most expensive and star-studded films into a world of
vacationing families and entertainment-hungry teen-agers. Tom
Cruise hangs from impossible cliffs. Mel Gibson skewers sneering
Brits. Jim Carrey rides the wild highway. The rules are simple:
Cars exist to be chased, guns to be fired, affairs to be
consummated, rockets to be launched. Special effects blossom like
wildflowers on the prairie. Have sequel, will travel.
</P>
<P>
   But off to the side, clustered together, are a growing number of
smaller, less heralded movies _ independent features, foreign
films, this year's quirky Shakespeare adaptations _ that somehow
find themselves battling it out in the nation's theaters with the
big Hollywood quarterbacks. In these movies, cars exist to be
driven, guns to be deplored, affairs to be analyzed. And rockets?
Well, there are no rockets. Have subtitles, will travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be, five or six years ago, that the indies would
stay out of the summer because of the major studio films,'' said
Amir Malin, the chairman of Artisan Entertainment. ``But now, with
the success that we and others have had in recent years, that's no
longer true.''
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the independent films being released has shifted
as well. While still offering standard literary adaptations and
films by celebrated foreign directors, many distributors have tried
to use the summer as a springboard for darker and quirkier movies
aimed at a younger audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This summer we've got two comedies, both alternative, both
hip,'' Malin said. ``That's what we like to present to summer
audiences: counterprogramming to what exists from the major
studios.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just films for hipsters that the art houses are
offering this summer. They are screening foreign epics,
character-driven dramas, absurdist satires. ``The thing to
emphasize is that films like ours go up against Hollywood 52 weeks
of the year,'' said Mark Urman, a co-president of Lions Gate Films.
``In fact, the summer is for us a great time. It's the time when
Hollywood becomes more mindless than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   During the fall and holiday seasons, the Oscar-hungry Hollywood
studios put out their prestige films, and there are more movies in
the marketplace competing with specialized films from
independent-minded distributors like Lions Gate, Miramax, Sony
Pictures Classics, Artisan, Fine Line, Paramount Classics, Fox
Searchlight, USA Films and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the darker, colder months, films that reach more
sophisticated or more mature moviegoers simply stop selling tickets
at a certain hour,'' Urman said. ``Our audiences go home and watch
Charlie Rose and retire, or whatever they do. But in the summer,
there is such a vacuum of films of ideas, films of emotions, that
we have always looked upon summer as an extraordinary opportunity
to have a genuine impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some of the biggest hits released by independent
distributors in recent years have come out during the summer: ``Il
Postino'' in 1994, ``Trainspotting'' in 1996, ``The Full Monty'' in
1997 and, of course, ``The Blair Witch Project'' in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guiding principle on this is that my mother needs something
to see,'' said Mark Gill, the president of Miramax's Los Angeles
office. ``It's kind of a joke, but it's true as well. The art
audience is driven by educated women, middle-aged and up, who want
to see movies that do not have big explosions in them.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as four summers ago, Gill said, 26 films opened in
American theaters between mid-May and Labor Day that could be
classified as independent or foreign films _ movies given limited
releases, usually beginning in New York and Los Angeles and, if
they clicked, gradually appearing in an increasing number of cities
until no college town was left untouched. For the last two or three
years, though, the numbers have shot up to 70 or 75 such films.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was that there was an explosion of success at
the Academy Awards in 1996, when four of the five films nominated
for best picture were from independent distributors,'' Gill said.
``It was evident there was a marvelous business there, if you could
be successful at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The result, all distributors seem to agree, has been a glut. It
is not just your imagination: there are more movie reviews in the
paper because there are more and more of these small,
limited-release films. While many of the companies that began the
independent-film trend in the early 1990s have since given up the
ghost, victims of the pitiless economics of a fickle industry, a
few have hung on and prospered, and others have merged into larger
companies. At the same time, the major Hollywood studios have
gotten into the game, either by buying out the independent
companies (like Disney's acquisition of Miramax) or starting their
own in-house classics division (like Sony Pictures Classics, Fox
Searchlight and, most recently, Paramount Classics).
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that there has not been substantial growth in
the size of the audience,'' Gill said. ``Even films that are
successful must make do with less.''
</P>
<P>
   So while new companies enter the market, others are putting out
fewer films, and there is general agreement that the current pace _
70 or 75 small films coming out every summer _ won't keep up
forever. ``It can't last because so many of them are not
succeeding,'' Gill said.
</P>
<P>
   What keeps people going is that, first, a small film doesn't
have to be a mass-audience hit to turn a profit; it can make do
with less. ``We can make $1.5 million on a film, and it doesn't
sound like a lot of money, compared to the big studio movies, but
in our world, it's a success,'' said David Dinerstein, a
co-president of Paramount Classics. And if it somehow does click
and, like ``Full Monty'' or ``Blair Witch,'' cross over into a
mainstream audience, the profits are amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``With `Red Violin,' we had a movie that spoke to a certain
audience that is underserved in the summer,'' Urman said. ``It made
$10 million. I know that by certain standards, that can be one
Saturday for a Tom Cruise movie. But by independent film standards,
that's a breakout; that's a crossover success. And it's not
necessary for our kind of films to satisfy everyone. In fact, it is
intrinsic in their design that they won't.''
</P>
<P>
   The other factor in the success of a smaller film is that it is,
by definition, not released in the same way as a big summer movie.
For something like ``Dinosaur'' or ``The Perfect Storm,'' thousands
of prints are put into thousands of theaters all over the country,
and millions of dollars are spent on marketing campaigns to ensure
a huge opening weekend. Smaller films are released more gradually,
beginning in the largest markets, then spreading slowly. If the
film finds its audience, it can run through the entire summer. A
big Hollywood movie, even a substantial success, can substantially
burn out in less than a month.
</P>
<P>
   Marcy Granata, president for publicity and corporate
communications at Miramax, said that instead of spending a lot of
money to generate excitement over one huge opening, smaller
distributors must stage a series of small-scale openings, each week
trying to attract the attention of a new crop of local critics and
talk show hosts. ``We call it sticking to the knitting,'' Granata
said. ``You treat the opening in Boston as if it were a national
opening. The local, grass-roots effort becomes very, very
primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Miramax's ``Hamlet,'' for instance _ the version starring Ethan
Hawke and set in modern-day Manhattan _ opened on May 12 in New
York and Los Angeles. The next week, it expanded to the top 10
cities. On May 26, it went to the top 20 cities and, on June 9, to
the top 40. In recent weeks, it began to expand into the larger
college towns, like New Haven. ``You hope for 16 to 20 weeks in
theaters,'' Gill said. ``It used to be you could count on that. But
it's so much more competitive now. So few of these movies are
successful, it's just ridiculous.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of independent and foreign films currently in
theaters or scheduled to open this summer. Opening dates may
change.
</P>
<P>
   Currently in Theaters
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN PSYCHO.' Mary Harron, director of the 1996 ``I Shot
Andy Warhol,'' takes a satiric swing at Bret Easton Ellis' novel
about a killer yuppie.
</P>
<P>
   `BORICUA'S BOND.' Val Lik directs Frankie Negron in a story
about a young artist at work and play in the South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   `THE BUTTERFLY.' Jose Luis Cuerda directs Fernando Fernan Gomez
in this Spanish story of a man's friendship with a boy during the
Spanish Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   `CROUPIER.' Mike Hodges, who made the 1971 British thriller
``Get Carter,'' directs Clive Owen as a casino worker who falls
into the clutches of a femme fatale.
</P>
<P>
   `GROOVE.' The writer and director Greg Harrison takes an
all-night tour of the rave scene in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   `JESUS' SON.' Alison Maclean directs Billy Crudup and Samantha
Morton in a story about an addict trying to reform.
</P>
<P>
   `HAMLET.' The director Michael Almereyda takes a fresh swing at
Shakespeare's tragedy, setting it in modern-day Manhattan. The
prince becomes a downtown filmmaker in the form of Ethan Hawke.
Kyle MacLachlan and Bill Murray join in.
</P>
<P>
   `LOVE'S LABOUR'S LOST.' Kenneth Branagh turns Shakespeare's
comedy into a semi-musical with a Cole Porter flavor.
</P>
<P>
   `SUNSHINE.' Ralph Fiennes plays a member of three different
generations of a Jewish family in war-torn Europe in this sprawling
epic from the director Istvan Szabo, best known for 1981's
`Mephisto.''
</P>
<P>
   `TRIXIE.' Alan Rudolph brings an ensemble cast including Emily
Watson, Nick Nolte and Nathan Lane to this noirish comedy about a
female detective.
</P>
<P>
   `UP AT THE VILLA.' Philip Haas, who directed the 1995 ``Angels
and Insects,'' adapted this Somerset Maugham story with Kristin
Scott Thomas and Sean Penn.
</P>
<P>
   `THE VIRGIN SUICIDES.' Sofia Coppola directs Kirsten Dunst and
Kathleen Turner in an adaptation of Jeffrey Eugenides' novel about
suburban teen-age ennui.
</P>
<P>
   Opening July 7
</P>
<P>
   `ALL THE RAGE.' Before directing the recent IMAX hit ``Michael
Jordan: To the Max,'' James Stern made this film about the dangers
of guns, starring Joan Allen and Andre Braugher.
</P>
<P>
   `BUT I'M A CHEERLEADER.' Jamie Babbit directs Natasha Lyonne
(one of the romantic interests in last summer's ``American Pie'')
and Cathy Moriarty in a farce about a teen-ager sent to a camp
intended to ``cure'' lesbianism.
</P>
<P>
   `SHOWER.' A Chinese film, with subtitles, from the director Yang
Zhang about a man who runs a bathhouse in Beijing and his reunion
with his son. Opening July 14
</P>
<P>
   `CHUCK AND BUCK.' Miguel Arteta directs Mike White and Chris
Weitz in this comedy, shot on digital videotape, about a young,
immature man trying to re-establish a relationship with an old
friend.
</P>
<P>
   `THE FIVE SENSES.' The director Jeremy Podeswa's multicharacter
drama has intertwined stories involving the senses. (There is an
old man going deaf, a voyeur, a masseuse, etc.)
</P>
<P>
   `THE WISDOM OF CROCODILES.' Jude Law plays a vampire in London
in this English-language story from the Chinese director Po-Chih
Leong. Opening July 21
</P>
<P>
   `ALICE ET MARTIN.' Andre Techine, the director of `Les Voleurs''
in 1996, returns with this French romance starring Juliette Binoche
and Alexis Loret.
</P>
<P>
   `CRIMINAL LOVERS.' Francois Ozon directs Natacha Regnier as a
femme fatale on the prowl in this French drama.
</P>
<P>
   Opening July 28
</P>
<P>
   `THE GIRL ON THE BRIDGE.' Daniel Auteuil is a circus
knife-thrower who recruits his assistants from among those
attempting suicide. In French and black-and-white, from the
director Patrice Leconte.
</P>
<P>
   `THE EYES OF TAMMY FAYE.' A sly documentary from Fenton Bailey,
Randy Barbain and Randy Barbato about the former television
evangelist, including cameos by her ex-husband, Jim Bakker, Pat
Boone and Roseanne. RuPaul narrates.
</P>
<P>
   `WONDERLAND.' The British director Michael Winterbottom (the
1997 ``Welcome to Sarajevo'') directs a drama about three sisters
that tries to give a portrait of modern-day, multi-ethnic London.
</P>
<P>
   Opening Aug. 4
</P>
<P>
   `PSYCHO BEACH PARTY.' Robert Lee King directs an adaptation of
Charles Busch's campy play, which Busch adapted for the screen and
in which he also appears.
</P>
<P>
   `RESTLESS.' Set in modern-day Beijing among a group of
multinational friends. Jule Gilfillan directs.
</P>
<P>
   `SAVING GRACE.' Nigel Cole directs Brenda Blethyn in a comedy
about a middle-class British woman who is persuaded to grow and
sell marijuana to maintain her sprawling house.
</P>
<P>
   `THE TAO OF STEVE.' Three friends have dreamed up what they
think is a foolproof theory of dating, based on the teachings of
Laotzu, Heidegger and Groucho Marx. A first-timer, Jenniphr
Goodman, directs Donal Logue.
</P>
<P>
   `THE TIC CODE.' Gary Winick directs Gregory Hines and
Christopher George Marquette in the story of a musical prodigy
suffering from Tourette's syndrome. Opening Aug. 11
</P>
<P>
   `AIMEE AND JAGUAR.' The German director Max Ferberbock directs a
lesbian romance set during the Battle of Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   `CECIL B. DEMENTED.' John Waters returns with a film about a
filmmaker (Stephen Dorff) who kidnaps a famous actress (Melanie
Griffith) and forces her to perform in his underground films.
</P>
<P>
   `AN AFFAIR OF LOVE.' A Belgian-French film whose original title
(``Une Liaison Pornographique'') was originally translated as ``A
Pornographic Affair.' From the director Frederic Fonteyne and
starring Nathalie Baye and Sergi Lopez, it's about, well, a
pornographic affair.
</P>
<P>
   Opening Aug. 18
</P>
<P>
   `ABOUT ADAM.' Gerard Stembridge directs Stuart Townsend as a
young man in working-class Ireland who seems too perfect to three
sisters, and turns out to be just that.
</P>
<P>
   `LOVE AND SEX.' Valerie Breiman directs Famke Janssen as a
magazine writer assigned (along the lines of ``Sex and the City'')
to explain the difference between love and sex, a task that
reunites her with her long-lost boyfriend (Jon Favreau).
</P>
<P>
   Opening Aug. 25
</P>
<P>
   `THE BALLAD OF RAMBLIN' JACK.' Aiyana Elliott directs a
documentary about her estranged father, the musician Jack Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   `GOAT ON FIRE AND SMILING FISH.' A first-time director, Kevin
Jordan, directs two brothers, Derick and Steve Martini, who play
the American Indian characters of the title.
</P>
<P>
   `JUST ONE TIME.' Lane Janger directs Guillermo Diaz and Jennifer
Esposito in a story about a couple experimenting with menage a
trois.
</P>
<P>
   `MAD ABOUT MAMBO.' A high school student tries to improve his
soccer skills by studying mambo. Romance ensues. John Forte
directs.
</P>
<P>
   `SKIPPED PARTS.' Jennifer Jason Leigh escapes from her
dominating father to rural Wyoming. Tamara Davis directs.
</P>
<P>
   `SOLOMON AND GAENOR.' The story, in English and Welsh, of a
Jewish man's romance with a Welsh woman in 1911 Wales. Paul
Morrison directs Ioan Gruffudd and Nia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   `STEAL THIS MOVIE!' Vincent D'Onofrio plays the 1960s Yippie
leader Abbie Hoffman, and Janeane Garofalo plays his wife in this
biopic directed by Robert Greenwald.
</P>
</TEXT>
