<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-AIR-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA FAULTS ALASKA AIRLINES BUT LETS IT CONTINUE FLYING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alaska Airlines has allowed mechanics to perform
work for which they are not qualified, skipped maintenance on test
equipment and failed to tell pilots when equipment was inoperable,
the Federal Aviation Administration said Thursday. But the agency
said it had accepted the airline's remedial plan and would not shut
down its maintenance operation, as officials had threatened.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a top FAA official faulted his agency's
performance in overseeing Alaska Airlines in the period before the
crash of one of its MD-80 jets in January, and said FAA inspectors
would begin special audits of the nation's other nine large
passenger carriers in the next few days, to look for similar
management problems.
</P>
<P>
   The official, L. Nick Lacey, acting director of the Flight
Standards Service, said the problem at Alaska Airlines was not
simply the specific flaws found, but the pattern of errors and the
failure to correct them. ``Often there are lapses and oversights
and mistakes, that type of thing,'' Lacey said, shortly after
notifying the airline, which is based in Seattle, that it would be
allowed to continue operating.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're seeing here is going beyond that,'' Lacey said,
``is going to the heart of why are these things happening, why are
these noncompliances slipping through the system, why are these
continuing over a long period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines has promised to hire 130 more maintenance and
engineering workers, including many supervisors, and 28 more people
for its flight operations department. The airline has also filled
some long-vacant executive positions, including director of
maintenance, a post that was vacant for nearly two years. Lacey
criticized the failure to quickly fill that job, but said his
agency might be partly at fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is, did we allow them not to fill it?'' he said,
adding that he was ``disturbed'' by the agency's performance. He
hinted, though, that the FAA would seek a large fine against the
airline for its failings.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some of the findings were minor. The airline had
installed enhanced medical kits in the rear overhead bins of its
Boeing 737's but had not posted signs to show where the kits were.
Other findings were more serious. The investigation found, for
example, that the airline lacks enough instructors to train pilots.
</P>
<P>
   But, Lacey said Thursday, ``what I never found in that report
was unsafe airplanes in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash that set off the FAA's investigation took place on
Jan. 31, when an MD-80 jet trying to make an emergency landing in
Los Angeles plunged into the Pacific, killing all 88 people on
board. The investigation has focused on the horizontal stabilizer,
the movable portion of the horizontal tail that the pilots use to
make the nose point up or down, but the National Transportation
Safety Board, an independent agency, is still trying to determine
the cause of the crash. The FAA is assisting in that investigation,
but Lacey would not talk about it Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The flaws found at the airline have not been tied directly to
the crash. The situation is reminiscent of the aftermath of the
crash of a Valujet DC-9 in the Florida Everglades in May 1996.
After that crash, the FAA conducted an inspection of the airline
and then shut it down, but for reasons that were unrelated to the
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Such investigations often result, though, in criticism by the
NTSB of the FAA's program for monitoring airline safety.
</P>
<P>
   The inspection of the other airlines _ America West, American,
Continental, Delta, Northwest, Southwest, TWA, United and US
Airways _ is an unusual effort to identify management problems.
``This is not a traditional inspection when we're out there on the
ramp, running around and tire-kicking,'' Lacey said. It is also
intended to identify good practices that can be used at other
airlines, he said, including the use of statistical systems to find
troublesome parts that require more frequent maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Lacey said inspectors would repeatedly revisit Alaska Airlines
to see if it was carrying out its improvement plan. ``We'll come
back again and again and again and make appropriate decisions at
each point along the way,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
