<SLUG> BC-BOSS-HOSS-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST YOUR AVERAGE MOTORCYCLE WITH YOUR CORVETTE V-8 ENGINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 2) 
 By JIM McCRAW    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monte Warne is a down-home Renaissance man, a Michelangelo of
machinery: A licensed aircraft and airplane-engine mechanic, an
aircraft designer, a licensed private, commercial and crop-duster
pilot, a lifelong motorcyclist and a former motorcycle and car
racer. So what possessed him to build the outrageous Boss Hoss, a
motorcycle with a Corvette V-8 engine?
</P>
<P>
   It all began in 1998 when Warne picked up a new Harley-Davidson
Heritage Softail in Memphis. By the time he drove it 75 miles home
to Dyersburg, Tenn., he decided that it had too much vibration and
not enough power. He sold it with just 500 miles on the odometer.
</P>
<P>
   That winter, with time on his hands, $10,000 in his pocket and
an idea in his head, he decided to build his own motorcycle. He
took a modified Chevy engine out of his race car, put it on the
shop floor and tried to figure out how to build a motorcycle around
it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He used steel tubing for the frame, a widened Harley-Davidson
Fat Bob fuel tank, a Harley-Davidson front end and a right-angle
gearbox from a lawn mower to get the power to the rear wheel via a
foot-operated clutch and chain drive. He used a 12-inch-wide
Hoosier dirt-track racing tire at the rear, a modified Harley rear
suspension and the rear disc brake from a 1982 Dodge Colt.
</P>
<P>
   That first bike overheated, so he had a special radiator built.
It rode hard, so he reduced the tire's air pressure from 40 pounds
per square inch down to just 12. The Harley front forks flexed so
badly under the V-8's weight that he had to reinforce them. And
that was the beginning of the mechanical evolution that led to the
Boss Hoss. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Within days, bikers around Dyersburg started asking Warne to
build frame kits so they could create their own Chevy-powered
bikes. He built another V-8 bike during the crop-dusting off-season
in 1990, and took both his creations to Florida in 1991, to the
annual Daytona Bike Week.
</P>
<P>
   Warne says the presence of the loud, brawny V-8 bikes in Daytona
Beach caused a near-riot of spectators and photographers. But if
the Boss Hosses attracted the police, they also got the attention
of the motorcycle press. Warne sold the first two bikes, and
would-be customers started to call.
</P>
<P>
   In Dyersburg, he sold both his crop-dusting business and a local
racetrack that he and his wife, Meredith, operated. They started
Boss Hoss Motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   Warne and his employees (there are 22 now) have since built
2,000 Boss Hosses for well-heeled riders around the world.
Celebrity buyers include Jay Leno, the ``Tonight Show'' host; Mark
Martin, the Winston Cup racer (whose bike is painted like his red,
white and blue Valvoline Taurus race car); Sammy Swindell, the
World of Outlaws racer who modified his bike with his own engine;
Vince McMahon, the World Wrestling Federation impresario; and Stone
Cold Steve Austin, the wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   Riders must straddle the big engines, but Warne says the seating
position is similar to a Harley's, with the feet about 22 inches
apart. Nor is the weight a problem except when parking; once the
bike is in gear, the engine's torque melts the pounds away.
</P>
<P>
   The Boss Hoss has evolved through several generations. The 2000
model uses a 350-cubic-inch, 355-horsepower engine shipped from
General Motors ready to install. (By contrast, the world's most
powerful conventional motorcycle, Kawasaki's new ZX-12R Ninja,
makes 183 horsepower.) The production Boss Hoss uses a specially
built, foot-shifted two-speed automatic transmission with a reverse
gear _ it comes in handy if you're trying to get an 1,100-pound
motorcyle out of a parking space _ and a Gates belt drive similar
to those in Harleys.
</P>
<P>
   The Boss Hoss uses three gigantic Wilwood racing disc brakes,
two at the front and one at the rear, and Avon motorcycle tires.
Even with the V-8's power, the bike gets 30 miles to the gallon,
Warne said, and can go 300 miles on a tank of fuel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Boss Hoss meets federal regulations and is sold in 49
states, with California to be added as soon as the bike passes the
state's emissions test.
</P>
<P>
   For the truly power-hungry for whom 355 horsepower isn't enough
(or, some bikers might suggest, for the truly insane), the Boss
Hoss can be ordered with a 502-cubic-inch, 500-horsepower GM
engine. If either V-8 sounds like a bit much, you can order a bike
with a 4.3-liter V-6, also from GM, with a mere 200 horsepower. If
you'd like a more stable platform, there are three-wheeled Boss
Hoss ``trikes'' with rear ends that resemble either a '57 Chevy or
a '64 Corvette. Trikes, too, can be had with V-6, 350 V-8, or 502
V-8 engines. Prices start at $25,500 for the basic two-wheeled V-6
and go up to $38,000 for the 502 trike.
</P>
<P>
   Every Boss Hoss is custom-painted to the customer's
specifications, so no two are alike. There are 40 Boss Hoss dealers
in the United States, plus a network in several other countries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
