</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-JUSTICE-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET SOSA: YANKS TRADE FOR JUSTICE
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Refusing to make a high-priced trade for Sammy Sosa,
the New York Yankees instead acquired outfielder David Justice from
Cleveland Thursday night, the first move to bolster their sagging
team.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees swapped outfielder Ricky Ledee and two minor league
players to be named in return for the 34-year-old Justice, who has
21 homers and 58 runs batted in this season _ more homers than any
Yankee. Justice apparently was Plan C for the Yankees, who failed
to complete a conditional trade for Detroit's Juan Gonzalez last
week and then haggled without success for Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   After the Yankees informed the Cubs of their impending trade for
Justice, Chicago's general manager, Ed Lynch, passed on the word to
Sosa, who was playing in Pittsburgh Thursday night. ``Sammy was
disappointed,'' said Andy MacPhail, the president of the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and Indians have agreed on a list of minor leaguers
from which the two unnamed players will be selected by Aug. 1. By
rule, the teams cannot announce the players on the list, which
figures to include at least one good prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Justice will likely divide his time as the designated hitter,
left fielder and right fielder. Shane Spencer has been used as the
designated hitter, but will probably get more time in the outfield
now. It's possible that manager Joe Torre will shake up the lineup
in a big way. Tino Martinez, who has been the Yankees' No. 5 hitter
behind Bernie Williams, is having a bad year, batting .266 with
seven homers and 40 RBI. Justice could move into the No. 5 spot,
with catcher Jorge Posada hitting sixth and Martinez dropping to
seventh, ahead of Spencer and Scott Brosius in the last two spots.
</P>
<P>
   Justice will be a long-term investment for the Yankees: He is
making $7 million this year and each of the next two years, and has
an option for the 2003 season for $7 million. That's about $10
million to $13 million less than they might have had to pay Sosa in
a contract extension. It was the potential cost in salary and
prospects that made Yankees' executives extremely leery of dealing
for Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees offered Ledee, outfielder Jackson Melian, pitcher
Jake Westbrook and a choice of Alfonso Soriano or D'Angelo Jimenez
for Sosa; the Cubs insisted on five players, including Melian,
Westbrook, Ledee and two players from a group of three that
included Soriano, Jimenez and Alex Graman, a Single-A pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees also knew that when and if they agreed to a trade
for Sosa, they would then have to negotiate a contract extension _
an agreement that would revamp their salary structure and change
the dynamics of their forthcoming negotiations with Derek Jeter,
their 26-year-old shortstop, and Mariano Rivera, their closer.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, the team's principal owner, was enticed by
the idea of getting Sosa's power and marquee presence; his
executives were frightened by how such a trade would affect the
organization into the future.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs and Yankees reached a stalemate on Tuesday, and over
the last two days the Yankees reconsidered their stance. They spoke
again with the Baltimore Orioles about B.J. Surhoff, and exchanged
proposals for Oakland's John Jaha and San Diego's Ed Sprague. They
might still try to acquire Jaha or Sprague. And they talked about
Justice with the Indians, who, like the Yankees, are a struggling
American League power.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Justice had infuriated club officials by suggesting
that the Indians' best years might be behind them. ``There comes a
time when you say, `Hey, maybe the window of opportunity is closing
for them,''' Justice said.
</P>
<P>
   There were only three instances of brief contact between the
Yankees and Cubs on Wednesday and Thursday, and in all three
instances, it was MacPhail who made the call, reaching out to the
Yankees. But the response from Yankees' officials was that they
couldn't reach Steinbrenner and didn't know what they were going to
do.
</P>
<P>
   This evening, General Manager Brian Cashman began calling around
to all the teams with which he had been negotiating and informed
them he was about to make a significant trade. About a half-hour
before Thursday night's game, Torre summoned Ledee into his office
and told the outfielder _ who signed with the Yankees 10 years ago
_ that he was being traded.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee said goodbye to Jeter, Posada and a few others, but
couldn't face the rest of them, fearing he would be unable to
contain his emotions. His eyes were puffy and welled with tears
when he spoke to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad,'' he said. ``It's very, very sad. I'm just sad I
couldn't put it together with the Yankees, the team I wanted to be
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice was part of another shocking trade, in 1997, when
Atlanta swapped him to Cleveland in a deal that included Kenny
Lofton and Marquis Grissom. But Justice was still incredulous when
he was told Thursday evening that he was going to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm stunned,'' he said, ``but business is business. That's the
game we play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 2143EDT &QL; 
