<HEADER>
A8835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-ABORTION-DOCTO     06-29 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-ABORTION-DOCTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS EXPRESS RELIEF OVER HIGH COURT'S ABORTION DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (With ABORTION-RIGHTS) 
 By PHILIP J. HILTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doctors who do abortions as part of their regular medical
practice said Thursday that they were greatly relieved by the
decision of the Supreme Court that the government could not
prohibit doctors from performing a procedure that opponents call
partial-birth abortion.
</P>
<P>
   They said that laws trying to ban the procedure were so vague
that doctors performing almost any abortion could be prosecuted
under them.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors said that medically, there is no such procedure as a
partial-birth abortion, calling the term a political label. The
Nebraska law struck down by the court described a partial-birth
abortion as one in which part of the fetus was outside the woman's
body before the fetus was killed. The doctors said many types of
abortion could fit that description.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William F. Harrison of the Washington Medical Center in
Fayetteville, Ark., said that when the Arkansas Legislature banned
the procedure, he was not concerned because he did abortions only
up to 18 weeks of pregnancy after the woman's last period, or in
rare cases a few weeks after that. But on reading the law, Harrison
said, it became clear that the statute was so broadly written that
it could apply to many abortions he performed.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor said he talked to the local prosecutor, a friend,
about the problem. ``He said he'd never prosecute me under those
circumstances,'' Harrison said. ``I said, `Fine, I trust you, but
what about a few years from now when you are replaced by a
right-wing Republican prosecutor? Then what?' He couldn't answer
for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Feldt, head of the national Planned Parenthood, said that
``we are pleased with the court's affirmation'' of the right to
abortion, ``but we in no way believe this is the end.'' Feldt
added, ``We know there will be another generation of bills, in
which they will try over and over again to establish that
legislatures can outlaw specific medical procedures at any time
during pregnancy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frederick Hopkins, an obstetrician in San Diego who also
serves as an officer of Planned Parenthood there, said one of the
troubling aspects of the campaign against so-called partial-birth
abortion was that while it was a threat to any doctor who performed
abortions, it had no medical aspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no such thing as partial-birth abortion,'' Hopkins
said. ``It is not in any medical text and there is no medical
definition.'' Yet it is ``intimidating and frightening,'' he said,
``to think a doctor could have been prosecuted under such vague
language.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, ``doctors and patients are safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Johnson, legislative director of the National Right To
Life Committee, said he was disappointed with the court decision,
but that efforts would continue to get a law passed to ban
``partial-birth abortions,'' one that would meet the approval of
the Supreme Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
