<P>
   (NYT19) NEKOMA, N.D. -- June 29, 2000 -- MISSILE-DEFENSE -- For
ages, nations have dreamed of building invulnerable shields to
protect themselves from hostile forces. All fell short. Now, the
Clinton administration and its military advisers are trying again,
this time with a limited antimissile weapon they think will go a
long way toward immunizing America against attack at least from
missiles launched by adversaries like like North Korea, Iran and
Iraq, which are known to be in various stages of developing
intercontinental missiles. But critics are skeptical that it can
work. Empty silos which contained Spring interceptors, designed to
destroy incoming warheads, in the abandoned Safeguard antimissile
base. The structure in the background housed an early detection
radar site. (William J. Broad/The New York Times)
