<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- June 29, 2000 -- CHARDIN-RETROSPECTIVE -- ``A
Mallard Drake Hanging on a Wall and a Seville Orange'' (1728-30) by
Jean-Simeon Chardin on view in the Chardin exhibition at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art. Chardin was as great as any artist by
the terms he set for himself, which were incredibly circumscribed:
for almost his whole career, spanning half a century, nearly every
minute of it spent in Paris, Chardin focused on what was not much
farther than three or four feet in front of his nose. (The
Metropolitan Museum of Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) DINGLE, Ireland -- June 29, 2000 -- DINGLE-IRELAND-LADN
-- The Dingle Peninsula's verdant hills dotted with sheep,
turquoise water and white sands, combine to produce a compelling
array of colors. Dingle has 1,200 residents and 52 pubs. In Gaelic,
Dingle means ``fortress,'' appropriate enough given how the town is
sheltered by the mountains on one side and the Atlantic on the
other. (Glenn Whipp/The Los Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LOS ANGELES -- June 29, 2000 -- FORAY-SIDEBAR-LADN --
June Foray, the voice of Rocky in the upcoming movie ``The
Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle,'' is advocating a new category
for the Academy Awards: Best Animated Motion Picture. As a revered
veteran of animation, from its Golden Age to the present, Foray
feels a sense of duty in pushing this cause. Foray was also the
voice of Natashia in the original Bullwinkle cartoons. (David
