<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CONSECO-APPOINT-459&AMP;A     06-29 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSECO-APPOINT-459&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WENDT, WHO BUILT GE CAPITAL SERVICES, IS NAMED HEAD OF CONSECO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Minn.)   By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Gary Wendt, the man who built GE Capital Services into
a financial services powerhouse, was named Thursday as chairman and
chief executive of Conseco Inc., the beleaguered insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt's appointment, which had been rumored for more than a
week, was hailed by Wall Street analysts, who said that Wendt's
experience and track record made him Conseco's best hope for a
strong recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Conseco, which rose sharply on Monday, jumped 14
percent Thursday, or $1.25, to $9, in heavy trading on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Wendt comes two months after Stephen C.
Hilbert, who founded Conseco 21 years ago, resigned as chairman and
chief executive, along with Rollin M. Dick, who quit as the
company's longtime chief financial officer. Both said investors had
lost confidence in their credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Conseco, which is based in Carmel, Ind., was once a high-flying
insurance and financial services company that had grown profitable
under Hilbert through a series of acquisitions. But Conseco has
been struggling the last two years, partly because of its costly
and seemingly ill-fated acquisition of Green Tree Financial, which
finances purchases of mobile homes. The company is now trying to
sell the unit, which has been renamed Conseco Finance.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt succeeds David W. Harkins, a company director who served
as acting chief executive after the departure of Hilbert.
</P>
<P>
   The 58-year-old Wendt is now charged with trying to find a way
to sell Conseco Finance and restore confidence in a company whose
stock has lost about 82 percent of its value in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt said in a conference call with the media Thursday that it
was too early to outline a strategy or say exactly what course he
would take as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that he had accepted the job because he was familiar
with the financial services industry from his tenure at GE Capital
and that he relished the opportunity to turn around the company's
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears there's a challenge here,'' he said. ``There are
things that have to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said they were pleased with Wendt's
selection. But they cautioned that Conseco faces grave
difficulties. The company is trying to sell Conseco Finance at far
less than it paid in 1998. It is also facing a liquidity crunch
because of heavy borrowing of up $1 billion in bank debt. Profits
are declining.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said they expected the company to undertake a
restructuring effort in the next year. They say that days after the
First Union Corp. said it would close its Money Store operation, it
is not clear whether Conseco can find a viable buyer for its
finance unit.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``They certainly have gone out and hired the best guy to try and
turn around the business,'' said Colin Devine, an analyst at
Salomon Smith Barney. ``But investors need to temper that because
considerable issues with the finances remain unchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said earlier this year that the sale of its finance
unit would take place by the third quarter, but Wendt said Thursday
that he would explore all options.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Seifert, an analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's, said Wendt would
have to restore the confidence of big investors who lost confidence
in the last year of Hilbert's tenure, particularly after the
company reported disappointing first-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conseco lost a tremendous amount of institutional support,''
she said. ``It's going to take a long time to build that back up.''
</P>
<P>
   Seifert also said the company would have to draw up a game plan
to restructure its operations and create a financial structure to
allow investors to evaluate the company's value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to model this company is next to impossible,'' she
said, adding: ``For quite some time this has been a rudderless
ship. And Gary Wendt needs to get a game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   At GE Capital, which consists of about 29 businesses ranging
from credit cards to truck leasing, Wendt was known as a skillful
and visionary leader; over a dozen years, the unit's profits grew
to $4 billion from $300 million. By the late 1990s, GE Capital was
the most profitable division of General Electric, accounting for
about 40 percent of the company's profits in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He left in late 1998 in a management shakeup that some analysts
attribute in part strained relations with John F. Welch, the chief
executive of General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Wendt and other former GE Capital executives created
a buyout and private equity investment fund.
</P>
<P>
   Just days after Hilbert resigned from Conseco, however, Wendt
tried to get in touch with Conseco officials at about the same time
the company was trying to reach him to inquire about his interest
in running the insurance giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our letters crossed in the mail,'' Wendt said. ``They were
calling me at the same time we were calling them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported on Monday that the negotiations
had been delayed because of a non-compete agreement Wendt had
signed with General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffer, a spokesman at General Electric, said Thursday
that Wendt had been in talks with the company to get approval to
take the Conseco post.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a negotiation to let Wendt out of his non-compete
agreement,'' Sheffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffer said General Electric would not elaborate on the
negotiations or comment on reports that as part of the agreement
General Electric would have options to take a stake in Conseco.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt said he would not comment on whether there was a
non-compete agreement. He also declined to discuss his compensation
package at Conseco, saying that it would be contained in public
disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin L. Jacobs, the corporate financier who has been buying
shares of Conseco and hinting at a takeover of the company, said
Thursday that he was overjoyed with Wendt's appointment.
</P>
<P>
   After acquiring nearly $50 million worth of stock in Conseco,
most of it in the last few months, Jacobs said in an interview
Thursday that he would remain a ``passive investor'' for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know God can't come down here and do this,'' Jacobs said
from his office in Minneapolis. ``But the next best thing to God is
Gary Wendt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
