<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-U.S.-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW U.S. FARM SUBSIDY PLAN IS CONTRARY TO EUROPEAN POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The Clinton administration introduced a sweeping
proposal Thursday at the World Trade Organization to change the way
governments subsidize farmers, challenging the European Union's
extensive agricultural subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   The American plan would simplify financial support to farmers
and reduce or end disparities in tariffs to increase market
openings for agricultural goods from other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, disclosed Thursday in Geneva and Washington, will
be formally introduced Friday at a session of the WTO agricultural
talks, which began in March.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the current domestic subsidies system would be
revised to eliminate those agricultural subsidies not directly
linked to price and volume of output. There would also be a ceiling
on the level of domestic subsidies based on a percentage of the
country's total agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
   While the U.S. approach was welcomed by exporting countries, it
is likely to add to tension between the United States and the
European Union, which are already at odds over a number of
politically sensitive trade matters, including bananas and
corporate tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to begin a new global trade round in Seattle in
December was in large part attributed to serious differences in how
to tackle the issue of agriculture. The United States and an
18-country group of agriculture exporters argue that European
export subsidies hinder competition and drive up consumer prices.
The EU, Switzerland, Norway and Japan maintain that rural areas
need such financial protection to ensure their survival.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these differences, members of the WTO are bound to
negotiate farm subsidies because of commitments they have already
made.
</P>
<P>
   The new U.S. proposal is directly contrary to the position of
the European Union, which spends about half of its total budget on
agricultural subsidies and supports payments to farmers not to grow
crops.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-country trading bloc has criticized the U.S. government
for denouncing subsidies at the same time it supports what the
Europeans call a hidden subsidy, emergency aid, to farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Franz Fischler, the union's agricultural
commissioner, criticized American farm spending, saying the Clinton
administration had increased spending to record levels. Two weeks
ago, Congress passed a $15 billion relief bill to assist farmers
who are facing a fourth year of economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva, the American special negotiator for agriculture,
Gregory Frazier, defended emergency aid packages to American
farmers as falling within WTO rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
