u e BC-TALL-SHIPS-HISTORY-AR     06-29 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALL-SHIPS-HISTORY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN TO THE SEA AGAIN, IN SHIPS TALL AND FLEET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT8,9 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ We were heaving to and definitely not giving up the
ship as the U.S. brig Niagara weathered stormy skies in Long Island
Sound before mustering in New York Harbor for Operation Sail 2000
over the coming July 4 holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The spanker sail at the stern trailed a puff of patriotic color:
a 15-star Old Glory from the War of 1812. And atop the foremast
fluttered a replica of Commodore Oliver Hazard Perry's proud blue
banner, ``Don't Give Up the Ship.'' After vanquishing the British
in the original Niagara on Lake Erie in 1813, Perry retired to his
cabin and penned his eloquent report: ``We have met the enemy, and
they are ours.''
</P>
<P>
   The air rang with commands shouted and repeated: ``Avast!''
``Brace up three points!'' and _ my favorite _ ``OK, hear the news:
Port watch eats!'' Even a clueless landsman knew that spelled
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The Niagara has been assigned a leading spot in the parade of
sail on Tuesday, behind the flagship, the U.S. Coast Guard bark
Eagle; the full-rigged Danish training ship Danmark and the Pogoria
of Poland.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 5 million spectators are expected to throng New
York City's shores next week for what may be the greatest nautical
spectacle of all time _ an event drawing well over 120 tall ships,
some 42 warships from the United States and 25 other nations and
50,000 to 70,000 small pleasure craft.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will review the July 4 spectacle from the deck
of the aircraft carrier the John F. Kennedy, anchored near the
Statue of Liberty, as some 70 planes soar overhead in an
international flyover. The festivities will culminate at 9 p.m.
with what is being called the largest pyrotechnic display in
history: a Macy's fireworks bombardment shooting off more than
2,000 shells a minute _ more than 60,000 in all _ in New York
Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Between the arrival of the armada on Monday and its departure on
July 9 there will be gun salutes and a blessing of the fleet, a
national bell-ringing, military band concerts and a concert by the
New York Pops, with a guest appearance on the podium by Walter
Cronkite, the event's honorary chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Ships moored around Manhattan, Brooklyn, Staten Island, Liberty
State Park and Bayonne, N.J., will be open to visitors. Also
scheduled are demonstrations of military and sportive prowess by
many of the 28,000 or so visiting seamen. After the events in New
York, many of the ships will sail on to Boston for another
assemblage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is the most magnificent and important tall-ship
event in history anywhere in the world,'' said Charles Robertson,
chairman of Op Sail 2000. A longtime yachtsman and businessman,
Robertson was instrumental in the last Operation Sail, in 1992,
which commemorated the 500th anniversary of Columbus' landing in
the New World. Add the military component, said Capt. Woody
Berzins, the Navy spokesman for the ``gray hull'' or warship event,
officially called the International Naval Review, and you are
looking at ``the greatest maritime event in history,'' in the
unabashed words of the Op Sail 2000 slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Next week's extravaganza will be the fifth Operation Sail, a
tradition established in 1961 by another old salt, President John
F. Kennedy, who did not live to see its actual debut in celebration
of the New York World's Fair in 1964. Subsequent Op Sails
celebrated the nation's bicentennial (1976) and the centennial of
the Statue of Liberty (1986). Future Op Sails are already being
planned, Robertson said, for the West Coast in 2004 or 2005 and
back again on the East Coast in 2008 or 2009.
</P>
<P>
   The International Naval Reviews go back to 1893, when the
warships of 10 nations sailed from Hampton Roads, Va., into New
York Harbor past President Grover Cleveland to commemorate
Columbus' second voyage. In 1907 American and foreign warships
again convened in Hampton Roads to mark the tercentennial of the
Jamestown Colony, a salute reprised there in 1957 for Jamestown's
350th anniversary. A fourth naval review, the largest to date, drew
warships from more than 40 countries to New York for the 1976
bicentennial, and a smaller fleet converged in 1986 for the
relighting of the renovated Statue of Liberty's torch. Next week's
International Naval Review, the sixth, was mandated by Congress in
1996 as an observance of the millennium and the nation's 224th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   With the focus on anniversaries, the submarine service, in its
centennial this year (the inventor John Holland sold his prototype
submersible to the Navy for $150,000 in 1900), celebrates with a
visit by the Jacksonville, one of the nation's 50 nuclear-powered
fast-attack submarines.
</P>
<P>
   But once again it is the wind-powered craft, throwbacks to a
storied wooden world, that are likely to steal the show. They go
from the largest of the tall ships, 27 Class A vessels starting
with the Esmeralda, a four-masted Chilean barkentine of 371 feet,
to 25 Class B ships of 161 to 100 feet, to 61 Class C Vessels of 90
to 18 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Recreational craft that are not part of the official group with
assigned berths are also expected to swarm New York's waters in
record numbers, possibly as many as 70,000 by Coast Guard
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the windjammers, despite their antique look, are
actually modern-day re-creations, built as training vessels for
foreign navies. ``Sailing vessels like these teach them things they
wouldn't ordinarily know,'' said Paul Welling, a retired Coast
Guard Vice Admiral who skippered the Eagle for four years, training
600 cadets a summer. He now serves as chief operating officer of Op
Sail 2000. ``If you're on a screw-driven vessel you wouldn't be so
concerned about weather and wind-shifts.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Among the more authentic entries is the Wavertree, called the
world's oldest iron sailing ship, built in 1885. A pillar of the
British merchant fleet hauling jute from India to Scotland, it was
demasted in a storm off Cape Horn in 1910, faced junking for scrap
and was finally rediscovered in 1968 by the South Street Seaport
Museum, which is turning it into a floating museum and training
vessel.
</P>
<P>
   The Niagara, which I joined recently in New London, Conn., for a
sopping day sail before it headed off to Newport, R.I.;
Philadelphia, and New York for the festivities, is on the light
side for a Class A vessel and ranks about midway in length, at 198
feet. But it is surpassing in loftiness: its two masts top out at
118 and 113 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Both masts are square-rigged (the defining characteristics of a
brig), which means that the yards, the horizontal spars from which
the sails are set, can be set square to the centerline of the ship
as well as angled, or ``braced up sharp,'' to sail closer to the
wind. The 15 sails consume almost 13,000 square feet of canvas and
can propel the ship along at up to 13.5 knots, or more than 16
miles an hour, very speedy for a square-rigger of this size. Once
the Niagara bristled with 18 32-pounder carronades and two
12-pounder long guns that could hurl a cannonball more than a mile;
now only four replica 32-pounder Scottish cannons and two long guns
poke through the gun ports.
</P>
<P>
   The Niagara, which makes regular cruises out of the Erie
Maritime Museum in Erie, Pa., comes freighted with history,
although with the exception of a few precious original timbers, it
is a re-creation.
</P>
<P>
   With the immature young republic and its recently dislodged
British overlords having stumbled into war again in 1812 over
simmering resentments and insults, Perry, commanding nine ships,
confronted six of the enemy's at Put-in-Bay on Lake Erie on Sept.
10, 1813. The beginning of the battle went badly for the Americans.
Perry, aboard his flagship, the Lawrence, miraculously escaped when
80 percent of the crew was felled by British fire. Striking her
banner, ``Don't Give Up the Ship'' _ and then doing precisely that
_ Perry evacuated to the Niagara, hauled up the banner and went on
to capture the British fleet (``Two Ships, two Brigs, one Schooner,
&AMP; one Sloop''), a victory that prepared the way for peace in 1814
and the nation's westward expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The Niagara was ignominiously scuttled in 1820 and raised and
rebuilt nearly a century later, in 1913, for the centennial of the
battle. Renovation dragged on through the Depression and World War
II. But by the 1980s severe decay required its dismantling, with
some original timbers salvaged for a full reconstruction, completed
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The ship surely seemed authentic enough, though, as I stepped
aboard in a downpour, seeking shelter under the canvas-covered main
hatch and enviously eyeing the crew in waterproof orange and yellow
foul-weather gear. In 1813 a crew of 155 manned the ship, about 100
of them on the guns. Today it sails with 16 professionals,
including the master, Capt. Walter Rybka, plus 24 volunteers who
sign on for at least three weeks at a time. Visitors are encouraged
to pitch in on the two watches, port and starboard, and even, with
proper safety harnesses, high up on the sails.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give them tasks, belt them up if they want to play,'' Rybka
told the crew. But he cautioned, ``Do not belt up someone who
doesn't want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the special guests on board was Cmdr. William F. Foster
Jr. of the Constitution, the granddaddy of tall ships. Known as
``Old Ironsides,'' it was commissioned in 1797 as one of the
nation's first six warships and is now restored and permanently
berthed as a museum in Charlestown Navy Yard in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest revelation for a nonseaman was how much
brawn and know-how a tall ship requires to remain, well, shipshape.
There are sails to loose and set, halyards to haul away on and make
fast, line to coil, yards to brace up and brace in, watches to
stand and the tiller to steer. Below deck, where the clearance is
too low to stand upright, hot meals are cooked on a wood stove; the
crew is unceremoniously bunked in hammocks hanging like clusters of
cocooned caterpillars, and even the heads require manual pumping.
</P>
<P>
   That's all authentic, too (except that there are no more
floggings and no grog issue). ``They always kept them busy so they
wouldn't discover those sailorly vices,'' said John Beebe-Center,
the sun-bronzed Chief Mate, who learned sailing while growing up in
Salem, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   If the spaghetti tangle of rigging seemed impossibly intricate,
it was perhaps only the 19th-century equivalent of today's computer
innards: to the people whose business it was to sail the ship, it
all made perfect sense. So, too, the laboriously loaded and fired
guns, which Rybka and his crew demonstrated to thunderous effect.
</P>
<P>
   In the sudden silence after the concussive blast, somewhere on
deck a cell phone trilled. Clearly, we were back in the 21st
century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
