<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8846 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-ROCKER-SCENE0630-COX     06-29 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKER-SCENE0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker, Mets fans behave on first day
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The world's most infamous subway ride never happened,
the starting pitcher didn't show up, and the fellow everyone came
to heap abuse on didn't necessarily inspire the loudest boos.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one thing everyone at Shea Stadium was absolutely
certain of Thursday night: ``John Rocker sucks.''
</P>
<P>
   They all yelled it, even if they didn't all absolutely believe
it by the time Rocker and the rest of the Braves took the field for
the first game of their obsessively talked-about weekend series
against the Mets. Shouting it from the uppermost rows in the
right-field stands, sporting it on T-shirts they had purchased over
the Internet or outside Shea, 40,000-plus Mets fans made clear
their common view of the controversial reliever they had waited
half a season and shown up two hours early to jeer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to tell you, if someone had had a mike on John Rocker
for about a three-minute span when he was in the outfield a little
while ago, I think it would have changed a lot of people's minds in
this place about him,'' Ernie Bertothy, 21, said.
</P>
<P>
   What Rocker did, about an hour before game time, was walk over
and shake the hands of Bertothy and his friend, Mike Doran, who had
come to the game from nearby Naugatuck, Conn., to see a good game
and witness some even better insults being hurled at the big
left-hander as he loosened up in the outfield. Throw in the several
autographed balls he threw _ gently _ to fans in the field-level
seats and the apology he appeared on the giant scoreboard reading,
and it was a rather tame return to New York.
</P>
<P>
   From Rocker to the fans, nearly everyone was well-behaved. Yet
some of it was self-imposed, as many Mets fans said they were just
trying to keep things in the proper perspective. This series was
all about the Mets' big chance to take over first place, they said,
not Rocker's big mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, I don't even want to see John Rocker this weekend and
that's not because I'm so mad at him,'' said Tom Vitale, who was
sitting about five rows from the field near the visitors bullpen,
wearing a hard hat he'd jokingly decorated with an ``I Love New
York'' sticker. ``It's because if Rocker's in a game, that means
the Braves are probably leading.''
</P>
<P>
   To Vitale's friend, Matt Pacifico, Thursday was as much a chance
to disprove what Rocker had said about Mets fans' supposed bad
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   If, in fact, it was disprovable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's what I'm worried about,'' said Pacifico, who had
refused to bring along a hard hat and who now turned around to
study the upper decks where some fans were brandishing beer cans
and signs with Rocker-specific messages like ``Hey Rocker, Can I Be
Your Battery Mate?'' ``If anyone throwing batteries from up there
doesn't have a great arm, it's coming right at my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, from beginning to end, it was no lovefest in Queens.
Coming off the No. 7 subway line _ the same one Rocker had pledged
to ride Thursday, setting off citywide agita _ the first thing
anyone saw was a sign reading ``Dump John Rocker!'', part of a
protest organized by a consortium of groups representing Latinos,
gays, even Little Leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to denounce the hate language John Rocker used, but
also any hate language that might be used by fans in the stadium
tonight,'' said New York Police Sgt. Edgar Rodriguez, president of
the Gay Officers Action League.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't much better inside the stadium, where former Met Bobby
Bonilla got the loudest boos of the night during the pre-game
introductions. Ande where being from the Bronx couldn't save Jason
Vargas from becoming a target of fan vitriol, all because he wore a
Greg Maddux jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all I find out Maddux is sick and not pitching
tonight,'' Vargas sighed while nibbling a bit nervously on a piece
of red licorice. ``Then I'm getting a LOT of heckling about the
shirt. They yell `Take the jersey off,' `You shouldn't be here,'
and `Rocker sucks!'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's guilt by association,'' Vargas laughingly concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Even Rocker's pre-game schoomzing with fans made some of them
just hate him more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually you can go down near the field during batting practice
and get autographs, but because of all this Rocker stuff, they
weren't letting people down there,'' complained Mets season ticket
holder Michael Conslato, pointing to his disappointed 5-year-old
son. ``I wish he'd go to the minors and not ruin our whole
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   If only he'd been a little less cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
