<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8848 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SENATE-DONORS-HNS &LR;      06-29 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-DONORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PASSES DONOR DISCLOSURE BILL 
 
(INCL. TRIM INDICATORS) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LETITIA STEIN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Thursday overwhelmingly approved and
sent to President Clinton a bill to force tax-exempt organizations
to disclose their sources for money used for television and radio
advertisements to influence political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to sign the bill, the first restrictions on
campaign financing in 21 years. The legislation will become law
immediately, meaning the secretive groups would have to identify
their donors during the fall election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``To all those who believe in reform, today is only the first
step, but it is a great first step,'' said Sen. John McCain, the
Arizona Republican who led bipartisan efforts to overcome stalling
tactics by GOP leaders in the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which cleared the Senate 92-6, will no longer allow
groups organized under Section 527 of the tax code to raise
unlimited amounts of money for political purposes without
identifying the donors and how the money is spent.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 385-89 early Wednesday to approve the bill,
which requires disclosure only for donations made after Clinton
signs it into law.
</P>
<P>
   Other tax-exempt interest groups and companies _ which some
Republicans tried unsuccessfully to include in the bill _ will
remain free to run ads without disclosing their donors as long as
the groups stick to issues advocacy and do not directly advocate a
candidate's election or defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passage of this bill proves that public interest can triumph
over special interests,'' Clinton said in a statement urging
lawmakers to approve other election-law changes. The legislation
also was praised by Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club, a conservation organization that has conducted
political activities since 1995 under a Section 527 organization
called the Environmental Voter Education Campaign, ``will eagerly
comply with the new law,'' said Dan Weiss, the club's political
director.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents predicted that the legislation would have a ``chilling
effect'' on some groups' ability to raise money, and that when the
law is challenged in court, it will be thrown out as
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very nervous that this will make it much more difficult
for groups to make legitimate complaints about Congress and federal
agencies,'' said Stephen Moore, president of the Club for Growth, a
527 organization that promotes free-market policies. Moore said
donors doing business with the government could be punished if it
is known they oppose administration policy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``If the law changes, our lawyers will advise us on what the
best course of action will be, and we'll take that action,'' said
Dan Zielinski, spokesman for Citizens for Better Medicare, a 527
group criticized by Clinton this week for trying to derail a
Democratic plan for providing prescription drug benefits for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, a Kentucky Republican who led opposition
to the bill, predicted it would be struck down by the courts. ``It
will take us down the constitutionally questionable path of
requiring disclosure by advocacy groups,'' McConnell said.
</P>
<P>
   While he voted against the bill, McConnell urged his Republican
colleagues to support it as they wrapped up business before going
home for a week of campaigning over the July 4 holiday. Voting for
the bill ``will insulate them against charges that they are in
favor of secret campaign contributions,'' McConnell said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When McCain successfully pushed a similar measure through the
Senate earlier this month, eight Republicans who previously opposed
his efforts _ but this year face re-election _ sided with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are eight senators who never voted with us before who
found themselves on the road to Damascus,'' McCain said, referring
to a religious conversion described in the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tax-exempt 527 groups were targeted, campaign-finance reform
advocates said, because their ability to raise and spend unlimited
amounts of money from unidentified donors violates two principles
of campaign finance laws _ limits and disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation will enable voters to learn ``exactly who is
behind the last-minute smear campaigns and anonymous ads that
increasingly characterized our federal elections,'' said Common
Cause President Scott Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   From January through March, more than $114 million had been
spent by over 60 of the so-called 527 groups, acording to a report
by the Annenberg Public Policy Center at the University of
Pennsylvania. Only a handful of the groups' identifies are known.
</P>
<P>
   Although the legislation approved by Congress may shed some
light on these groups, cracking down on them is not likely to
reduce the amount of money or its influence in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it will do to the flow of money to the elections is
simply act as a router that will redirect the money to another
source,'' said Steven Weiss, spokesman for the Center for
Responsive Politics, a non-partisan organization that studies the
impact of money in the election process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a dam in the river of money that is flowing into
politics,'' he said. ``It is simply a levee that moves the money to
another place.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF FILE
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
