<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8853 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-ABORTION-RIGHTS-2NDTA     06-29 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-RIGHTS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 
UNDATED: abortion methods.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Publicly, supporters of the bans often say they want to ban a
procedure known as a D&AMP;X abortion, for intact dilation and
extraction.
</P>
<P>
   In that procedure, used starting at about 16 weeks of pregnancy
when the fetus' head has grown too big to pass safely through an
undilated cervix, doctors trying to keep the fetus as intact as
possible for various reasons extract it feet first and then use a
sharp instrument to collapse the fetal skull.
</P>
<P>
   But critics of the bans say they are often so broadly worded
that they seem to also ban so-called D&AMP;E abortions, for dilation
and evacuation. In this procedure, which is used much more commonly
for abortions after the first trimester of pregnancy, the fetus is
dismembered during the abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Supreme Court opinion, written by Justice Stephen G.
Breyer, agreed that that had been a flaw in the Nebraska law.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer's decision said that Nebraska, because of its broad
phrasing, imposed an ``undue burden'' on a woman's right to choose
a D&AMP;E abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have said that state legislation creating a ban was
often written in very general terms because its supporters are
trying to discourage all abortions, not just those they describe as
partial-birth abortions.
</P>
<P>
   In revised laws across the country, Heller said, ban proponents
``will now try to come up with different language that they will
claim is limited to this one specific procedure, but that really
isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   His group, which has challenged many bans nationally, is
preparing to challenge the Ohio law, which, he said, remains so
broadly worded that it could be read as banning more than the D&AMP;X
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bans denied they intended to limit women's
rights to other methods of abortion. Grasz, the Nebraska deputy
attorney general, said that abortion-rights groups make that claim
to motivate their supporters with the fear that all abortion rights
are at stake, not just a limitation on a particular method of
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing the states were trying to do,'' he said, ``was
ban partial-birth abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Those efforts, he said, would continue.
</P>
<P>
   People on both sides of the abortion issue were also divided
Thursday regarding the Supreme Court's requirement that any ban, to
be constitutional, must permit the use of the D&AMP;X procedure if it
is deemed necessary to preserve the health of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   The life of the woman is not at issue: all state laws banning
the procedure _ including Nebraska's _ made allowances for its use
should the pregnant woman's life be otherwise threatened.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday's ruling addressed the issue of the mother's
health, a lower medical threshold _ and one more open to broad
interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the bans said that rule was needed to preserve a
meaningful right to choice guaranteed by the landmark 1973 abortion
decision, Roe vs. Wade.
</P>
<P>
   But proponents of the bans said they regarded that part of
Wednesday's opinion as a trap for them.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, they said, if new laws are too narrow in
defining the health of the mother, they will be struck down like
the Nebraska law, which did not include a health exception.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, they continued, if the health exception
written into new laws is too broad, the bans would be ineffective
because doctors could invoke the exception routinely to use the
banned procedures.
</P>
<P>
   In a companion suit to Roe vs. Wade, the Supreme Court defined
``the health of the mother'' broadly, including factors like a
woman's age, and physical, psychological or emotional condition.
</P>
<P>
   Dorinda C. Bordlee, a special assistant attorney general in
Louisiana who has defended the state's 1997 ``partial birth'' ban,
said she was considering advising the Louisiana Legislature to
amend its law to define the mother's health strictly as
``significant long-term physical risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a law would surely be challenged in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would force the Supreme Court to reconsider what it
considers `health,''' Bordlee said.
</P>
</TEXT>
