<HEADER>
A8854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CELEBRITY-PHOTOGRAPHE     06-29 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELEBRITY-PHOTOGRAPHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGRAPHER OF STARS WILL NOMINATE THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   By GLENN COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So they gave one last decent Broadway gala to bid
farewell to the theatrical season, and Aubrey Reuben was there, as
ever, with his Canon Sure Shot 120, as ever, blasting cold flash
right into the eyes of celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Simon? Snap. Nathan Lane? Snap. Marsha Mason? Snap. Robert
Klein? Snap. Charles S. Dutton? Snap. Calista Flockhart? Snap.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, OK,'' Reuben said, eyeing the dinner crowd the
other night at the Broadway Cares/Equity Fights AIDS fund-raiser
honoring Simon. ``Now on to what's really important _ the food and
the wine!''
</P>
<P>
   Reuben, in his trademark gray Ralph Lauren suit and floral tie,
has been called a ``gentleman paparazzo'' but rejects that. ``I
don't take pictures of people without their permission,'' he said.
``I don't stake out homes or hotels. I don't shoot into people's
windows.''
</P>
<P>
   What then would be your job description, Reuben? ``Celebrity
photographer,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly Aubrey Reuben, observer, is the thing observed. Or
as Bill Evans, the press representative for the Neil Simon event,
put it: ``It's always been good to see Aubrey, but now we really
have to play up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that Reuben was recently named to the prestigious
nominating committee for next season's Tony Awards, one of only 30
chosen. ``I take it very seriously,'' Reuben said. ``It's a great
honor. The theater is literally my life.'' Pause. ``I even adore
the ushers.''
</P>
<P>
   True, some in the ever-treacherous theater business have reacted
to the news as if the scullery maid was named sous-chef. But his
new liege defends him. ``Aubrey is eminently qualified, as a lover
of the theater who has seen every show for years and years,'' said
Roy Somlyo, president of the American Theater Wing, which founded
the Tonys in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   But really, Somlyo _ a celebrity photographer? ``I don't think
that in any way demeans the Tony process,'' Somlyo said. ``It would
be wrong for the committee to be an elitist group.''
</P>
<P>
   Good enough. But how, oh how, to present Reuben in full? Is it
Reuben the gala-seeking missile, who has ``never been to a party I
didn't like,'' as he puts it? Is it Reuben the indefatigable, who
has snapped as many as eight events in an evening while consuming
untold merlots before having an Irish coffee at 2 a.m. at Rosie
O'Grady's, the saloon?
</P>
<P>
   Or is the real Reuben the avuncular Broadway historian, the
going-out guide who for decades has written about theater, opera
and ballet for Temas, the Spanish-language magazine _ the Reuben
who has for 20 years served on the executive committee of the
70-member Outer Critics Circle?
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the identity anomaly is the little-known
public-school thing. Reuben began as a teacher of Spanish in New
York City schools in 1957 and retired as assistant principal of
John Bowne High School in Queens, N.Y., in 1987. Along the way, he
arranged for discount Broadway tickets for his classes and invited
show-business luminaries to lecture in his schools.
</P>
<P>
   Reuben began his shutterbug career ``as a groupie with a box
camera,'' he said, flashing snaps backstage after seeing shows he
covered for Temas. But the early 1980s brought ``the revelation
that I could be paid for this'' when his first picture appeared in
The New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   When Reuben ``first showed up around the edges, he wasn't taken
all that seriously,'' Evans said. But now Reuben is absolutely
beset by what one might call event-faxation _ his number is on
press agents' automatic-send list. And his snaps appear, among many
other places, in The Post, where he is paid a retainer; an agency
also beams his pictures to newspapers and magazines around the
world. Reuben has had such world coups as the cover of People
magazine (Bess Myerson and Carl Capasso in a smoochy condition).
Giant scoops can earn him more than $20,000 a snap.
</P>
<P>
   Reuben steadfastly maintains that he is 33 years old. (He is
68.) ``I qualify for the Guinness Book of World Records because I'm
the only 33-year-old father whose son is 42 years old,'' he says
proudly. The son, David, teaches on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Reuben stubbornly inflicts his English accent on America though
he came to New York at age 15 from his native English city,
Manchester (to join his sister, a GI bride), and he is now a
citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Even without his photographic royalties, Reuben says he is
comfortably off, thanks to pensions and the investments he made
with his wife of 39 years, Maria Elena, who died five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He makes zero claim to photographic expertise. ``I have not the
slightest idea of how a camera works, and all I know about film is
that it has numbers on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then what is his definition of an artistically excellent photo?
``The picture editor likes it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What are the crucial aesthetic elements of composition? ``Deep
cleavage is a decided plus,'' he said. ``If it's the scandal of the
moment, that doesn't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Have his snaps ever attained the level of art?
</P>
<P>
   Reuben exploded in his life-of-the-party bray. ``Next
question!''
</P>
<P>
   And how many nights a year does he go out? Three hundred
sixty-five, he says. ``I love leap years, because then I'm out
366.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
