<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0439 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8864 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BRAZILL0630-COX     06-29 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZILL0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another side of shooter emerges
 &HT;    By Noah Bierman, William Cooper Jr. and Scott McCabe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Staring into the eyes of the girl who scorned
his puppy love, Nathaniel Brazill squeezed the trigger of a cheap
silver handgun and shot his teacher in the head.
</P>
<P>
   That girl, Dinora Rosales, and other close friends and
acquaintances of the 13-year-old student stood behind their English
teacher, Barry Grunow, as he fell dead from that bullet on the last
day of school.
</P>
<P>
   They, along with teachers, friends and relatives who knew the
seventh-grade student crafted an image of an angrier Nathaniel
Brazill than has been previously reported. He imagined killing,
bragged about how he would use a stolen gun and joked _ they
thought _ about inscribing hit lists with students' names,
according to witness statements culled from 799 pages of documents
released Thursday. Yet they all maintained that he'd been a
gentleman, a nice kid and a joker with a smile on his face. The
talk of violence almost always seemed in jest.
</P>
<P>
   The police evidence, released under the state's public records
laws, will be used by prosecutors and defense attorneys to define
the boy, once again, in preparation for his adult trial on a
first-degree murder charge, expected sometime next year. Brazill
has already admitted shooting Grunow May 26, hours after he had
been sent home by a guidance counselor for throwing water balloons.
</P>
<P>
   The Lake Worth Middle School surveillance tape, which police say
shows the shooting, has not been released. Brazill's defense
attorney, Bob Udell, has argued that it would inflame the public
and prevent his client from receiving a fair trial. A judge is
expected to rule today on whether to make the tape public.
</P>
<P>
   After shooting Grunow on the right side of his nose at 3:25
p.m., he told police he was angry at the teacher for laughing at
him when Brazill aimed the gun at his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a smile on his face and was laughing and that made me
mad,'' Brazill said.
</P>
<P>
   Udell said Thursday night he has not read the documents released
by the State Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``When is someone going to tell me what the motive for this
murder is?'' he asked. ``There's an old saying: You can believe
some of what you see but none of what you hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come to the trial. We'll see who's telling the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   He has previously indicated he will argue that Brazill fired
accidentally. He also is likely to question the credibility of the
police witnesses, most of whom are 13-years-old.
</P>
<P>
   Brazill's father, Nathaniel Brazill Sr., said he had not seen
the newly released documents and did not want to comment for this
story.
</P>
<P>
   UNREQUITED CRUSHES
</P>
<P>
   Brazill was apparently suffering from teenage heartache this
school year. He had a group of close-knit friends, but wanted more
than platonic relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Friends recounted numerous conversations in which he talked
about girls and he kept pictures of four of them by his home
computer. Brazill wanted to talk to two of those girls, Rosales and
Vonae Ware, when he ran into Grunow.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had asked me out like to be his girlfriend but I told him
no,'' Rosales told police.
</P>
<P>
   Brazill continued to bring her cards throughout the year, a
wooden heart he made in shop class and flowers and balloons on the
last day of class.
</P>
<P>
   Police took two of those cards, apparently written near the end
of school, as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This school year with you has been the best of my life...I
love you and I think I'm going to lose my mind. I love you, take
care,'' he wrote before signing ``Love Nate.''
</P>
<P>
   He had an earlier crush on Ware, but she returned the chocolates
he gave her. Although he was friends with Ware's boyfriend, Bobby
McRoy, he became jealous, students told police. He told students
he'd kill Bobby by the end of the year and he wrote about those
plans in one of his letters to Rosales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna kill Bobby. Bobby always lyin on me and stuff,'' he
told Suzy Fleureme, according to her statement.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the girls' rejections, Brazill remained close friends
with Ware and Rosales. He desperately sought them out when he
returned to school after being dismissed. On the way in, he told
his friend Jules Nole to go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him walking real fast cause and I thought it was strange
cause he had no classes right in the back there in the portables,''
Nole said.
</P>
<P>
   When Brazill arrived at Grunow's classroom, Rosales and Ware
were near the door, trying to leave a few minutes before dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Grunow saw Brazill at the door and told him to leave. As Brazill
held up the gun and racked the bullet into the chamber and ready to
fire, the girls told him, ``This isn't funny, this isn't funny.
This isn't a joke,'' according to Rosales' statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then he just looked at me and then he just shot Mr. Grunow
and left,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of middle school students told police they heard or saw
the gunshot. One said she smelled the smoke from the discharged
bullet.
</P>
<P>
   WRITTEN EVIDENCE
</P>
<P>
   When Brazill turned himself into police later that day, he had a
preprinted card for Safe Harbor, a teen runaway hotline _ something
Ware said he liked to hand out to other students as a joke.
</P>
<P>
   He told police that after he shot Grunow he thought he would
kill himself by riding his bike from school into a lake and
drowning himself.
</P>
<P>
   Later, police took an unsigned, unfinished letter from his room
that also mentioned suicide. Found in a notebook in his home, it's
dated April 15, 1988 and has an out of town address. But it's
addressed, ``Dear Grunow,'' and includes specific references to
many of Brazill's friends and teachers from the 1999-2000 school
year. The author of the letter, which contains several grammatical
errors, identifies himself as a seventh-grader: ``Their was nothing
about this school year that I liked. People were mean to me. The
were always beating on me. I think I might commit suicide,'' it
says in part. Some of the anger in the letter is directed at
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Brazill had shown anger earlier in the year. Geography teacher
Brett Packard recalled an incident in January when Brazill and
another student fought over a fruit drink. Packard took it and told
them if they were not going to share, then the soda was his.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got intensely mad when I would not give it back,'' Packard
said. ``I didn't back down on it and I poured it out onto the
grass. He was really mad. And he stewed on that for 2 or 3 weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   When Brazill confessed to police about shooting Grunow, he told
them he learned to load the gun, stolen the weekend before the
shooting from a family friend, by watching cop shows on television.
He kept pamphlets from gun manufacturers in his room, with prices
he jotted down in the margins.
</P>
<P>
   As far back as a year ago, before he even had a gun, he told his
cousin how he imagined he could use one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he wanted to rob a bank,'' said James Josey, a
12-year-old first cousin.
</P>
<P>
   He also talked about shooting police and ``sounded like he was
talking for real,'' Josey said.
</P>
<P>
   The idle bragging of a little boy? Perhaps, but hours before the
shooting, Brazill ran into a neighborhood kid, 18-year-old Brandon
Spann, and promised to ``(mess) up the teachers at the school.''
</P>
<P>
   And Tiffany Jenkins, 13, didn't know whether to believe him when
he showed her the gun a few days before and said it might be used
to kill her cousin Bobby McRoy.
</P>
<P>
   Kervin Dieujuste also saw the gun and heard Brazill brag. He
meant to tell the principal, but forgot, he told police.
</P>
<P>
   Students, even those who knew Brazill had a gun, didn't think he
was capable of shooting anyone. That's why talk of his ``hit list''
seemed like just that, talk. Many students heard Brazill mention
such a list, though, and police seized a sheet of paper from his
room with two names next to dates and a heading that said ``Add to
hit list Kervin.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days before the shooting, classmate Sandy Astain-Jules saw
Brazill writing down the names of ``people I hate'' while she was
talking to him in class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I looked at the paper and he put, 'People I wanna kill.'
So I thought . . . he was playing around. See he put my name on
there and some other people's name on there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Grunow, the 35-year-old father of two, was not on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
