<DOCNO> NYT20000629.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8865 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NISSAN-DESIGNER-NYT &LR;      06-29 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-DESIGNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGN A LAST CHORD FROM NISSAN'S ROCKER-DESIGNER-PITCHMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Mich., Calif.)   By PHIL PATTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nissan's television commercials have made Jerry Hirshberg the
most recognized auto designer in America. More than his Infiniti
J30 luxury sedan, his Nissan Xterra sport utility or even his
strange Gobi truck design, they are likely to be the images by
which he is remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Hirshberg's career at Nissan comes to an end Friday with his
voluntary retirement; he turns 60 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Hirshberg came to Nissan in 1980, when the Japanese company set
up a Southern California studio, Nissan Design International, or
NDI, to learn from the American market. Most automakers have
California studios now, but Nissan's was among the first. Hirshberg
was determined to design all kinds of products, which he believed
improved the quality of his automotive designs.
</P>
<P>
   His interest in other products has helped to make Hirshberg a
polarizing figure in auto design. The true car designer, tradition
holds, dreams of nothing else _ he has ``gasoline in his veins.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   He has also been one of the industry's most outspoken and
articulate practitioners; his explanations of his own work are
sometimes taken as glibness. Auto design is a hermetic world of
traditions and conventions, not unlike that of Paris couture or
Japanese anime.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   General Motors hired him in 1963 in a program aimed at enriching
the pool of ideas by bringing designers without automotive
backgrounds into the studio.
</P>
<P>
   His career had already taken an odd detour while he was earning
degrees in mechanical engineering from Ohio State University and in
industrial design from the Cleveland Institute of Art. He moved
from the classical music of his high school years into rock 'n'
roll and in 1959 had a hit song, ``Sparkling Blue.'' Using the name
Jerry Paul, he toured as an opening act for the likes of Fabian and
Frankie Avalon. ``Sparkling Blue,'' he proudly says, continued to
be played on oldies stations and produce residual payments into the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But he gave up music for automobile design, joining GM's Pontiac
Division in the '60s when its general manager, John Z. DeLorean,
was making waves. Hirshberg worked on the original Firebird of 1967
and the striking 1968 GTO muscle car, then moved on to Buick.
Through it all, he worked under the legendary (and tyrannical) Bill
Mitchell, who encouraged competition among GM's disparate design
studios. But Hirshberg thought the competition intimidated
designers and squelched new ideas. The very names of cars he worked
on _ LeSabre, Firebird _ summed up the aggressive ethos of the
place, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, he got a call from a headhunter. Nissan had decided to
establish a studio in California to adapt vehicle designs to the
increasingly important American market; would he set it up? Once he
got Nissan Design International going, in the LaJolla section of
San Diego, he worked to redesign the process of design. He laid out
some of his ideas in a 1998 book, ``The Creative Priority: Driving
Innovation in the Real World'' (HarperBusiness), whose pages are
full of phrases like ``mind mapping,'' ``porous planning'' and
``polarized thinking.'' California psychobabble, his Detroit
critics grumbled, though not on the record.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he calls the studio itself his most successful design.
But his style is unconventional. Once, to break a midafternoon
creative logjam, he took his entire staff to a screening of
``Silence of the Lambs.'' He administered a test to determine the
``colors'' of potential staffers' personalities, lest the
organizing greens be overwhelmed by innovative but helter-skelter
reds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To keep minds open and ideas fresh, NDI also took on a variety
of nonautomotive design work, from children's furniture to laptop
computers, yachts and golf clubs. (Its most commercially successful
project may be the best-selling Taylor Made Bubble Burner golf
clubs.)
</P>
<P>
   Another nonautomotive job was a commission to rethink the design
of The Los Angeles Times. Beginning with the basics, he concluded
that a person reading a newspaper ``appears to be smelling it.'' He
ground several metropolitan dailies into confetti and asked a panel
to evaluate their odors. The Los Angeles paper did very well;
testers called its smell ``sweet.'' (The New York Times rated less
well, due to a higher percentage of recycled paper.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His innovations have sometimes been small but significant. As
the studio set out to redesign the Quest minivan, word came back
that users wanted 3 inches of added space. The specific figure
puzzled him. Bringing in owners and their vehicles, Hirshberg found
that what they really wanted was room to accommodate objects, like
another row of grocery bags, without adding to the van's length. So
the studio added storage in the form of an adjustable shelf _ a
feature that has been widely imitated.
</P>
<P>
   Hirshberg is famous for the verbal spin he puts on his designs.
He called the Xterra, a small sport utility that has been a big hit
since its introduction last year, ``a garage tool that says, `Treat
me rough' _ it's designed to look better dirty than clean.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the Infiniti J30 made its premiere, he says, ``I presented
the car at the Waldorf-Astoria like a Hollywood director.'' The
sedan was conceived in the mid-'80s in an effort to create
``instant heritage'' for Nissan's new luxury division. The studio
came up with a series of round shapes that, in an era when most
cars were wedges, evoked the falling rear ends and rounded
coachlike bodies of old Jaguars and Delahayes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the J30s introduction, he presented the design theme as a
Zen-like drawing: a bold, calligraphic sketch of a line and an egg.
</P>
<P>
   New vehicles based on Hirshberg's designs will arrive in
showrooms until 2003, and he will continue to appear in ads. He
turned down a chance to become worldwide director for Nissan
design, he says. That job went to Shiro Nakamura, formerly of
Isuzu, whom Hirshberg recommended. Heading Nissan Design in
California will be Tom Semple, a longtime colleague.
</P>
<P>
   Hirshberg's last major design at Nissan Design International is
the American studio's entry in an intramural competition for the
design of Nissan's next ``Z'' sports car. It will compete with an
entry from Nissan's Japanese studio, and the winner will be
displayed at the Detroit auto show in January. Hirshberg promises
that the Z will be very different from a design shown in Detroit
two years ago. It will not be a ``retro'' version of the old Z car,
he says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Retro lost its edge when we crossed the millennial
threshold,'' he said. ``Now we run the danger of cars becoming
costumes on wheels.'' He considers it good for automotive design
``to become aware of its history _ for cars to begin referencing
other cars for a change, not rocket ships or airplanes.'' But he
says auto designers may ``squander this new credibility very
rapidly.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``How long can a wink last? The danger is that we will
visually giggle ourselves back into oblivion.'' He criticizes the
popular Chrysler PT Cruiser as a pastiche of retro references.
</P>
<P>
   Hirshberg will continue to work as an adviser to Nissan. But he
plans to spend most of his time painting. Not with a spray can, as
in a recent ad for the Sentra compact sedan, but with oils. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been this huge white canvas in my studio for 20
years,'' he said. Devoting himself to painting ``was a dream from
the days I first began working at General Motors.'' If that doesn't
work, he can always go back to rock 'n' roll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
