<SLUG> BC-LABOR0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will parties split labor vote this fall?
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Republicans descend on Philadelphia next month to
nominate Texas Gov. George W. Bush for president, but some
important Democrats are paying courtesy calls here this week.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton comes to town today. Vice President Al Gore
and House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt (D-Mo.) were here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   All three came to speak to the national convention of the
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees union,
whose 1.3 million members make it one of three largest in the 13
million member AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   That Clinton, Gore and Gephardt would come calling underscores
the pivotal role that organized labor will play for the Democrats
in the upcoming fall elections. Labor turnout, especially in key
battleground states such as Pennsylvania, will be critical to
Gore's chances of winning the White House and Gephardt's goal of
recapturing the House and becoming speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The visits from Clinton and Gore also point to the predicament
Gore faces just four months before the November elections. Both
Clinton and Gore are seeking to mend fences with organized labor _
a core constituency of the Democratic electorate _ after alienating
labor voters over their support of permanent trade relations with
China.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, meanwhile, appears to have solidified his support among
core Republican voters and is spending more of his time reaching
out to constituencies not normally allied with the Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Bush spoke to an important gathering of
Latinos in Washington, and in Cleveland two days later he made a
pitch to people with disabilities, proposing pilot programs to help
the disabled with transportation to and from work.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Voter.com Battleground 2000 poll, conducted by
Republican and Democratic pollsters, found union voters splitting
their support between Bush and Gore, an indication of the road Gore
still must travel to shore up support among labor voters.
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO President John Sweeney, who is committing vast union
resources toward Gore's election, spoke to the AFSCME convention
Thursday and delivered a passionate endorsement of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, the stakes have never been higher,'' Sweeney told the
4,000 delegates. ``We have to work harder than we have worked in
our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney then went off to lead a town hall meeting of labor
activists dubbed the ``Texas Truth Squad,'' featuring testimonials
from Texas workers on Bush's record on labor issues in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The town hall, with others to follow in other cities around the
country, was among the first public events of a huge AFL-CIO
campaign to turn out union voters against Bush and support Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past several months, the AFL-CIO has dispatched
hundreds of paid coordinators to 70 congressional districts around
the country. The field activists will be responsible for
registering union members to vote, developing accurate phone lists
of union voters, and distributing millions of mailings to union
households. Pennsylvania, with its 23 electoral votes, ranks among
the top five or six battleground states in the fall campaign. The
state is home to some one million union workers, and Gore enjoys
the support of most of the state's union leadership.
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO state President Bill George said the federation had
dispatched about 20 field staff this month to begin the
labor-intensive process of mobilizing the state's unionized
workers.
</P>
<P>
   George said Gore is still facing some skepticism among union
voters because of his support of the China trade legislation,
especially among the state's 85,000 steelworkers. ``But they look
at the other candidate and they see a complete disaster,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, ``I think it's going to go down to the wire.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
