<HEADER>
A8872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     06-29 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of new or
noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in New York
City. Ratings and running times are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `BIG MOMMA'S HOUSE,' starring Martin Lawrence. Directed by Raja
Gosnell (PG-13, 97 minutes). This fitfully amusing film, starring
the comic whirligig Lawrence, could best be described as
``Stakeout'' goes ghetto, with a touch of ``Tootsie'' for flava _
er, flavor. Lawrence plays Malcolm, an FBI agent with a penchant
for doing undercover work in full body makeup. Here he impersonates
Big Momma, a stubborn old Southern woman. Why? Big Momma's
granddaughter is on the run because her ex-boyfriend, Lester, a
murderous bank robber, has escaped from prison. Malcolm believes he
can use her to get to Lester. This isn't much of a movie; it looks
like a series of baseball card shots and may have the worst rhythms
ever in a film directed by a former editor. (Elvis Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `BUTTERFLY,' starring Fernando Fernan Gomez and Manuel Lozano.
Directed by Jose Luis Cuerda (R, 96 minutes). This gentle,
devastating new film, based on stories by the Spanish writer Manuel
Rivas, tells the story of Moncho (Lozano), a sensitive young boy
coming of age in the months before the outbreak of the Spanish
Civil War. The movie touches on the usual excitements and mysteries
of childhood, but Moncho's relationship with his teacher, the
proudly Republican Don Gregorio, beautifully played by Fernan
Gomez, gives the story an unusual degree of pathos and political
complexity (A.O. Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `CHICKEN RUN,' with the voices of Mel Gibson, Miranda Richardson
and Julia Sawalha. Directed by Peter Lord and Nick Park (G, 86
minutes). The first full-length feature from Aardman Animation is
immensely satisfying, a divinely relaxed and confident film that
credits youngsters' interest in a cartoon more substantial than the
standard bland musical. The movie employs modeled latex figures to
tell the story of a group of chickens desperate to escape from a
chicken farm before they are turned into pies. Nick Park, who also
directed the fabulous Wallace and Gromit shorts, transfers all of
the deftness and imagination of his shorter films into an artful
big-screen realization. And this briskly paced epic uses a
continuing satirical take on British modesty and balmy superiority.
``Chicken Run'' parodies cultural touchstones from ``Stalag 17'' to
``Star Trek'' to the loose-cannon heroics of Gibson, the voice of
Rocky, the matinee-idol flying rooster who is asked to teach the
hens to fly. Finally, it shows that the hens can save themselves
through the pluck of Ginger (Sawalha) and doesn't make a big deal
of this. (Mitchell)
</P>
<P>
   `DINOSAUR,' with the voices of D.B. Sweeney, Alfre Woodard and
Ossie Davis. Directed by Ralph Zondag and Eric Leighton (PG, 90
minutes). Reputedly the most expensive animated feature ever made,
Disney's showcase of computer animation technology begins with a
breathtaking sequence, a visual and sonic extravaganza that the
rest of the movie never quite lives up to. The story, of a young
dinosaur raised by lemurs who must lead a herd of his fellow
reptiles to safety after an asteroid strikes the earth, is cobbled
from other Disney plots. But the effects _ the dinosaur's movements
and their nearly seamless insertion into real locations _ will
impress skeptical grown-ups. Despite some potentially upsetting
scenes of carnivorous mayhem, the film will delight children. (A.O.
Scott)
</P>
<P>
   `FANTASIA/2000,' with James Levine and the Chicago Symphony
Orchestra. Various directors (G, 75 minutes). The millennial
version of Disney's 1940 groundbreaking fusion of animation and
classical music includes seven new segments and keeps one from the
original film (the wonderful ``Sorcerer's Apprentice,'' starring
Mickey Mouse). ``Fantasia/2000'' is more backward-looking than
futuristic. The two best segments are ``Rhapsody in Blue,'' a witty
Manhattan-in-the-Jazz-Age homage to the caricaturist Al Hirschfeld
set to the music of Gershwin, and the finale (set to Stravinsky's
``Firebird'' Suite), in which a cometlike sprite whooshes around
the globe explosively creating, destroying and renewing the
planet's life forms. (Stephen Holden)
</P>
<P>
   `FREQUENCY,' starring Dennis Quaid and Jim Caviezel. Directed by
Gregory Hoblit (PG-13, 100 minutes). ``Back to the Future'' meets
``Field of Dreams'' meets ``It's a Wonderful Life'' meets ``The
Sixth Sense'' in this entertaining but shamelessly sentimental
supernatural soap opera with a macho heart. Caviezel is a morose
young policeman who makes contact with his dead father, a
firefighter, on a ham radio and contrives to save him from the
accident that cost him his life. The two collaborate on changing
other aspects of the past and on catching a serial killer. There
are enough testosterone tears to soak Shea Stadium. (Holden)
</P>
<P>
   `GLADIATOR,' starring Russell Crowe, Joaquin Phoenix, Connie
Nielsen, Richard Harris and Oliver Reed. Directed by Ridley Scott
(R, 150 minutes). This movie is the answer to a question no one
bothered to ask: What would happen if someone decided to film the
imminent extreme football league as if it were a Chanel commercial?
Scott subjects action-packed bouts of mayhem and decapitation in
the Roman Colosseum to his glossy, inhuman directing style; it is
admirable but repellent. As the noble Roman general who ends up
fighting for his life, Crowe gives a performance with ball-of-fire
intensity suffused with a movie star's impatience. He holds the
movie together, such as it is. (Mitchell)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   `GONE IN 60 SECONDS,' starring Nicolas Cage, Giovanni Ribisi,
Angelina Jolie and Robert Duvall. Directed by Dominic Sena (PG-13,
119 minutes). A remake of a movie so insubstantial that its title
seems to refer to the length of time it would linger in memory.
Cage, who has gone prematurely blond, is the world's best car
thief, dragged out of his apparently lucrative go-cart business and
returns to auto theft to save the life of his brother ( Ribisi).
With a magnetic cast of crooks and cops, it's mindless hot-rodding
entertainment. (Mitchell)
</P>
<P>
   `HIGH FIDELITY,' starring John Cusack, Jill Peterson, Iben
Hjejle and Joan Cusack. Directed by Stephen Frears (R, 107
minutes). Although the setting has been moved from London to
Chicago, the screen adaptation of Nick Hornby's best-selling 1995
novel is wonderfully true to the spirit of the book. Cusack has one
of his juiciest roles in Rob, a 30-something record store manager
and vinyl fanatic sorting through the ``Top 5'' breakups in his
disastrous romantic history while trying to salvage his latest
relationship. The movie hilariously captures the mind-set of
not-so-young men for whom pop music is a kind of religion and hip
musical taste an ultimate measure of a person's worth. (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `ME, MYSELF AND IRENE,' starring Jim Carrey and Renee Zellweger.
Directed by Bobby Farrelly and Peter Farrelly (R, 100 minutes). If
``There's Something About Mary'' offended you with its callous
mockery of hair and pet care and its whimsical views of stalking
and serial killing, then this latest festival of vulgarity from the
Farrelly brothers will make you miserable. But ``Me Myself and
Irene'' shares with their earlier movies a kind of dopey, boyish
sincerity and a good-natured sympathy for the underdog that may
prove capable of winning over even the dourest spirits. Carrey, in
one _ or is it two? _ of his most charming and repellent
performances, plays a Rhode Island state trooper with a split
personality and a giant crush on Irene, played with winning moxie
and plausible bewilderment by Zellweger. (Scott)
</P>
<P>
   `M:I-2,' starring Tom Cruise, Thandie Newton and Sir Anthony
Hopkins. Directed by John Woo (PG-13, 120 minutes). Cruise returns
as the daredevil secret agent Ethan Hunt in Woo's loud, flashy,
incoherent new blockbuster. The film is jampacked with movie
references _ to Hitchcock, to the first ``Mission: Impossible''
movie and to Woo's superior Hong Kong action films _ but it's at
once overheated and flat. The plot, involving killer viruses, is
baffling rather than twisty. The introduction of a love interest
(Newton) who also happens to be the bad guy's ex-girlfriend adds an
element of melodrama that's more grating than affecting. Some good
car chases and explosions, though. (Scott)
</P>
<P>
   `SHAFT,' starring Samuel L. Jackson, Vanessa Williams, Jeffrey
Wright, Christian Bale, Toni Collette and Richard Roundtree A
sequel/remake to the 1971 semi-classic, starring the always
dependable Jackson. He's the nephew of the original Shaft
(Roundtree, who appears briefly), and this time, Shaft is a cop. He
leaves the force to track down a racist WASP murderer (Bale), who
joins forces with a drug dealer (the flamboyant and skillful
Wright) to eliminate the hero. This may be the least politically
correct movie in some time, and though it tries to convert
archetype into stereotype, it doesn't succeed. Watching the two
villains squabble for center stage is like watching Luciano
Pavarotti and Placido Domingo in a death match for the mike. But
Jackson comes out on top of this emptily entertaining hodgepodge of
retro and modern cliches. (Mitchell)
</P>
<P>
   `SHANGHAI NOON,' starring Jackie Chan and Owen Wilson. Directed
by Tom Dey (PG-13, 110 minutes). Chan is one of the great physical
comedians, and this martial arts western spoof is a high-spirited,
marvelously silly showcase for his talents. Chan plays an Imperial
Guard dispatched from Beijing to the Old West to rescue a princess
played by Lucy Liu. But the heart of the movie is the interplay
between Chan and Wilson, who depicts his inept outlaw sidekick with
goofy, spacey charm. (Scott)
</P>
<P>
   `SUNSHINE,' starring Ralph Fiennes, Rachel Weisz, Jennifer Ehle,
Rosemary Harris and James Frian. Directed by Istvan Szabo (R, 180
minutes). In Szabo's tale of 20th-century Hungarian history,
Fiennes plays three members of a wealthy Jewish Budapest family _
grandfather, father and son _ who endure the corruption of the
Austro-Hungarian empire, the viciousness of fascism and the
brutality of Communism. Fiennes' performances, and those of Ehle
and Harris (playing the same character at different stages of life)
help save the film from melodramatic excess. ``Sunshine'' is a
serious, humane and thought-provoking attempt to make sense of
complicated and painful historical experiences (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `TITAN A.E.,' with the voices of Matt Damon, Drew Barrymore and
Bill Pullman. Directed by Don Bluth and Gary Coleman (PG, 90
minutes). This animated sci-fi fantasy, set in the 31st century,
imagines that Earth has been destroyed by aliens and what is left
of humanity is scattered about the universe in drifter colonies.
Guided by a magic ring left to him by his father, Cale (Damon), a
teen-age space explorer, searches for the Titan, a hidden spaceship
with the key to humanity's future. The technology is innovative and
there are some gorgeous special effects. But the screenplay and
characters are too bland for the story to catch fire. (Holden)
</P>
<P>
   `U-571,' starring Matthew McConaughey, Bill Paxton, Jon Bon
Jovi, David Keith and Harvey Keitel. Directed by Jonathan Mostow
(PG-13, 120 minutes). Mostow, whose previous film, ``Breakdown,''
was a marvel of B-picture minimalism, shifts from the wide-open
spaces to the cramped interior of a World War II submarine movie.
McConaughey, whose knotted-with-unease face makes it look as if he
were cramming for finals, is part of a secret mission to capture a
Nazi code-encryption machine and get it back to the Allies. He and
his crew have to do so on a Nazi U-boat they have hijacked. Mostow
does a fine job of building tension, given that he is working in a
minor genre whose climactic notes you will know if you have ever
seen a movie set on a sub. (Mitchell)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
