<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTENFIELD CAN'T STOP MARINERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE -- When the Angels traded Jim Edmonds to the Cardinals
for Kent Bottenfield on March 23, they hoped they were getting the
same pitcher that won 18 games and was named to the National League
All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   So far the only noticeable similarity between Bottenfield in
1999 and Bottenfield in 2000 is the loss count -- Bottenfield had
seven losses all of last year, and Thursday afternoon he got his
seventh loss of 2000 in a 7-2 setback to the Seattle Mariners
before 44,387 at Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield (4-7) didn't pitch poorly -- he gave up four runs
and six hits in 5 2/3 innings. But two of the hits were home runs
by John Olerud, including a tie-breaking two-run homer in the sixth
inning that gave the Mariners the lead for good at 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield, who waved off reporters after the game, was so
upset after Olerud's homer, he told the next batter, Mike Cameron,
to hurry up and get in the batter's box. Cameron yelled back and
the benches from both teams stirred.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was telling him to get in the box, and Cameron got mad,''
Angels catcher Matt Walbeck said. ``They were jawing back and
forth. It was just gamesmanship. It was nothing dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottenfield was a little frustrated and wanted to get back to
pitching,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners hit two more homers off the Angels bullpen, giving
starter Gil Meche and the three relievers plenty to work with. The
win moved the Mariners past Oakland and into first place in the
A.L. West. The Angels are six behind the Mariners and 5{ behind
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield did start off the season pitching well, holding
opponents to three runs or fewer in seven of his first eight
starts. But since then, he's done it only once his seven starts.
Since beating the Mariners here on May 5, Bottenfield has won only
once -- June 2 vs. the Dodgers when the Angels scored 12 runs.
</P>
<P>
   A bout with shoulder tendinitis caused him trouble toward the
end of May and early June, but since returning from the disabled
list with a healthy shoulder, the results aren't any better -- he's
0-2 with an 8.44 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the numbers, Scioscia said Bottenfield's on the right
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he pitched a strong ballgame with the exception of a
couple pitches,'' Scioscia said. ``He made some strides today. I
think his confidence needs to get to the level it was last year and
early this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Walbeck said Bottenfield's performance Thursday was similar to
many of his starts early in the season when he was throwing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought his command was good and he hit all his spots,''
Walbeck said. ``He pitched well today. His rhythm was fine. He made
a couple mistakes and they made him pay. Sometimes you just have to
tip your hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure he's frustrated. Today was a big start for him. He's
disappointed in the outcome, but I hope it doesn't carry over to
his next start. He still made pitches and gave us a chance to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez's RBI single in the first inning gave the
Mariners a 1-0 lead, but the Angels tied it in the third inning.
Walbeck led off with a bunt single, took second on a walk to Benji
Gil, went to third on a sacrifice by Darin Erstad and scored on a
groundout by Orlando Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud gave the Mariners the lead back with the first of his
home runs, a solo shot in the fourth inning. The Angels tied it
again with a run in the sixth, the inning keyed by Garret
Anderson's double.
</P>
<P>
   But Olerud, who had only five homers all season going into the
game, got Bottenfield again with a two-run homer and a 4-2 lead in
the bottom of the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Javier added a two-run homer off Mark Petkovsek in the
seventh and Robert Machado hit a solo homer off Derrick Turnbow in
the eighth for the final margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels scored only eight runs the three-game series, and
Thursday it was Meche who kept the Angels hitters in check. Meche
gave up two runs and five hits in 5 2/3 innings. Reliever Jose
Paniagua (1-0) got the win.
</P>
</TEXT>
