u e BC-BULLWINKLE-FILM-REVIE     06-29 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLWINKLE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BULLWINKLE': A NOISY, BLOATED MESS WITH LAME ATTEMPTS AT SATIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the old ``Rocky and Bullwinkle'' cartoons? If you do,
either from their initial run in the early 1960s or their long
afterlife in syndication, you will recall that they were short,
clever (albeit in a stupid kind of way) and proudly
two-dimensional. The drawing and animation were defiantly crude,
cheap and fast. The show's low-rent look was as integral to its
aesthetic as the narrator's goofy modernist intrusions or the
moose's barrage of bad puns and loopy malapropisms.
</P>
<P>
   Why would anyone want to spin this slight, charming relic of the
pop culture past into a high-tech, expensive, effect-jammed feature
film like ``The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle''? As if
anxiously aware of its own pointlessness, Des McAnuff's hectic
blend of computer animation and live action raises this question
obsessively, hoping to distract a credulous audience with knowing
showbiz parody.
</P>
<P>
   The gambit works for about 10 minutes, an all-cartoon segment
during which the biographies of Rocky, Bullwinkle and their nemeses
over in Pottsylvania, whose escapades were unceremoniously canceled
in 1964, are rapidly brought up to date. The squirrel and the moose
live in the now deforested town of Frostbite Falls, Minn.,
supporting themselves with ever-shrinking residual checks, while
Boris, Natasha and their Fearless Leader are stymied by the fall of
the Iron Curtain, which falls, with appropriate sound effects, on
them. The narrator has moved back in with his mother and has been,
as he puts it ``reduced to narrating events in his own life.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good, but then the movie succumbs to its blockbuster
ambitions and turns into a noisy, bloated mess. Bloating, in fact,
is literally what happens to our heroes, who morph from line
drawings into computer-generated 3-D projections that look like
half-inflated floats from the Macy's Thanksgiving Day parade. Boris
and Natasha have slightly better luck: They turn into Jason
Alexander and Rene Russo, who do some spirited hamming on the way
to cashing their checks, which will be co-signed by Robert De Niro,
who plays Fearless Leader and whose company, TriBeCa Films, was
among the producers of this film.
</P>
<P>
   His mouth fixed in a rictus of evil glee, Fearless Leader has
apparently borrowed not only Regis Philbin's wardrobe of matching
shiny shirt-and-tie combos, but also Philbin's ambition to dominate
the airwaves. Fearless Leader concocts an elaborate plan to stupefy
the American public by making television even dumber than it
already is. The flagship of this scheme is RBTV _ Really Bad TV _
with headquarters in a New York skyscraper that looks a lot like
Rockefeller Center, home of the real-world NBC, the original Rocky
and Bullwinkle show's network.
</P>
<P>
   This is typical of the movie's lame, confused attempts at
satire, as is the movie studio called Phony Pictures. ``The
Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle'' cloaks its essential inanity
in warmed-over sub-``Simpsons'' facetiousness. The irreverent,
off-the-cuff spirit of Jay Ward's freewheeling original doesn't
really make it to the big screen. What should seem plucky,
inventive and charmingly silly _ improbable coincidences, elaborate
setups for trifling jokes _ feels at once panicky and stale.
</P>
<P>
   The script, by the playwright Kenneth Lonergan, desperately
tries to poke fun at its own ambitions, to signal to the audience
that there's nothing here to take seriously, but this feels like
cheating. When Fearless Leader proclaims that real and animated
characters have never before shared the screen, another says,
``What about that movie `Roger Rabbit'?'' ``This is completely
different,'' thunders the would-be ruler of the world, and you
can't help agreeing. That 1988 Robert Zemeckis extravaganza was a
good movie.
</P>
<P>
   The show biz references _ creaky plays on industry terms like
green lighting and hiatus _ will sail over the heads of most
children, as will De Niro's reprise of Travis Bickle's most famous
scene in ``Taxi Driver.'' But then again, ``The Adventures of Rocky
and Bullwinkle'' isn't really aimed at today's children. It's
another attempt to cash in on baby boomer nostalgia, and to exploit
that generation's bottomless appetite for nostalgic self-regard.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain the self-congratulatory cameos by John
Goodman, Billy Crystal, Jonathan Winters (in multiple roles) and
Whoopi Goldberg, whose character is named Judge Cameo? Why else
would the filmmakers tack on a syrupy moral about self-knowledge
and the inner child?
</P>
<P>
   It's uttered, with abashed conviction, by the hard-working Piper
Perabo, who plays the youngest-looking FBI agent in film history.
The original ``Rocky and Bullwinkle'' had sufficient ingenuity to
revel in its own dumbness and make an audience reared on Mad
magazine feel smart. Their new ``Adventures'' are made by people
who clearly think themselves much smarter than their audience. In
place of whimsy, it offers cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE ADVENTURES OF ROCKY AND BULLWINKLE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Des McAnuff; written by Kenneth Lonergan, based on
characters developed by Jay Ward; director of photography, Thomas
Ackerman; edited by Dennis Virkler; music by Mark Mothersbaugh;
production designer, Gavin Bocquet; produced by Jane Rosenthal and
Robert De Niro; released by Universal Pictures. With: Rene Russo
(Natasha), Jason Alexander (Boris), Randy Quaid (Cappy Von
Trapment), Kel Mitchell (Martin), Kenan Thompson (Lewis), Piper
Perabo (Karen Sympathy), Robert De Niro (Fearless Leader), Janeane
Garofalo (Minnie Mogul), Carl Reiner (P.G. Biggershot), Jonathan
Winters (Whoppa Chopper Pilot) and John Goodman (Oklahoma Cop). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of: June Foray (Rocky) and Keith Scott
(Bullwinkle/Narrator). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 88 minutes. This film is rated PG.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle'' is rated PG (Parental
guidance suggested). It includes some very mild profanity and some
real-life re-enactments of cartoon-style mayhem. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
