<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS FROM THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Calif.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEROT MAY FACE OFF WITH BUCHANAN
</P>
<P>
   If Ross Perot wants to run for president again, now he can. An
effort to collect the required number of signatures to qualify him
for the Reform Party primary has succeeded, said Ira Goodman, a
party official from New Jersey who has been leading a campaign to
draft Perot as an alternative to the two other candidates who are
seeking the party nomination _ Pat Buchanan, the former television
commentator, and John Hagelin, a physicist.
</P>
<P>
   Perot, the Reform Party founder and two-time presidential
nominee, now has until Saturday to notify party officials by letter
that he intends to run, if that is his decision. Russell Verney,
one his close associates, said Thursday that he would speak to
Perot as soon as possible to review the options. Verney added that
a decision on whether to try to undercut the other two candidates,
especially Buchanan, whom many Reform Party members consider too
conservative, could come as early as Friday. The balloting for the
primary, which is conducted by mail and over the Internet, begins
on July 5 and ends Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   CONCERNS ABOUT PROTESTS
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week after voting to set aside Pershing Square in
downtown Los Angeles as a gathering place for protesters at the
Democratic National Convention, the Los Angeles City Council is
reconsidering the move under pressure from the police and
merchants' groups worried about violence or disruptions at
convention hotels and the jewelry mart near the square.
</P>
<P>
   The police have proposed putting demonstrators in a fenced-off
parking lot near the convention site. The council approved the new
plan as part of a $4 million bailout of the convention's local
organizing committee, at the insistence of one member, Jackie
Goldberg, a liberal Democrat representing Hollywood. The Secret
Service has now decided not to have Vice President Al Gore stay at
the Royal Biltmore Hotel, opposite the square, citing safety
concerns. After a sometimes impassioned debate on Wednesday, the
council referred the matter to a committee; a final vote is
expected next week.
</P>
<P>
   REALITY-BASED ADS FOR BUSH
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign is searching for real people _ or at least
actors who look like them. In a casting notice sent to talent
agents this week, a company representing the campaign said it was
looking for ``a wide range of assorted, real-looking people'' to
appear in spots for Gov. George W. Bush that are to be filmed in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the spot as a ``nonunion commercial,'' the memorandum
asked for ``everyday people on the street'' with a ``strong
emphasis on Hispanic and Caucasian.'' The notice was a surprise to
officials of the Screen Actors Guild, which is on strike against
the advertising industry. Guild officials said Thursday that they
thought they had a signed agreement that gave the Bush campaign
permission to hire union actors during the strike.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark McKinnon, Bush's media consultant, said that while two
members of the campaign's advertising team who are partners in a
separate agency had signed such an agreement, the Bush campaign's
own advertising agency, Maverick Media, had not.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S IN THE MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's ``progress and prosperity'' tour
carries an implicit argument for four more years of the current
administration, and at a campaign event in Chicago Thursday, the
recorded music made the same case. It was by Fleetwood Mac, the
band that played at President Clinton's inauguration festivities in
1993, and it even included the song ``Don't Stop (Thinking About
Tomorrow),'' Clinton's theme.
</P>
<P>
   The other tunes had their own strange relevance. There was ``The
Chain,'' a plea for continuity that includes a declaration _ ``if
you don't love me now, you will never love me again'' _ with
disturbing implications for a candidate trailing in many polls. And
there was ``Tusk,'' which seemed to capture the uncertainty of
Gore's future in Washington with its opening lines: ``Why don't you
ask him if he's going to stay? Why don't you ask him if he's going
away?''
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: No public events scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Washington
</P>
</TEXT>
