<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-BIAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT REJECTS APPEAL BY MALE ATHLETES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Male collegiate athletes Thursday lost their
Supreme Court appeal of a university's decision to eliminate two
men's teams in an effort to balance athletic opportunities for male
and female students.
</P>
<P>
   The athletes had argued in vain that Illinois State University
violated the Constitution's ban on sex discrimination when school
officials canceled the wrestling and soccer programs.
</P>
<P>
   But a lower federal court accepted the university's counter
argument that cutting the men's teams was a valid effort by the
school to comply with a federal law prohibiting gender
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' refusal to hear the appeal sets no national
precedent regarding the legality of eliminating men's teams to
create equity between male and female athletic programs. Similar
lawsuits brought by other male college athletes are pending around
the country, potentially giving the high court an opportunity to
consider the issue fully in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The case arose in 1995 when the Illinois school cut its men's
wrestling and soccer programs in an effort to comply with Title IX
of the federal 1972 Education Amendments.
</P>
<P>
   The law bans schools receiving federal funds from discriminating
on the basis of gender in their athletic and other programs.
Because virtually all schools receive some federal money, every
educational facility can potentially be held liable for providing
greater resources to men's athletic programs than to women's.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen wrestlers and soccer players challenged the
university's action as violating the Constitution's Equal
Protection Clause, which generally prohibits states and their
schools from intentionally discriminating on that basis.
</P>
<P>
   But the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled for the
university, saying its controversial action was legitimate in light
of Title IX and financial realities.
</P>
<P>
   ``A holding that universities cannot achieve substantial
proportionality by cutting men's programs is tantamount to a
requirement that universities ... add women's sports programs,''
the 7th Circuit said. ``This result would ignore the financial and
budgetary constraints that universities face.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporting the men in their unsuccessful appeal was House
Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., a former high-school wrestling
coach in Illinois. He argued in a brief to the justices that Title
IX was intended to expand athletic programs for women, not
eliminate opportunities for male athletes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF FILE
</P>
<P>
   $$$
