<SLUG> BC-PERU-OAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAS MISSION TO PERU SAYS INTELLIGENCE BOSS MUST GO
</HEADLINE>
  By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ The foreign minister of Canada and the secretary
general of the Organization of American States urged President
Alberto Fujimori on Thursday to remove his chief of intelligence as
a crucial step in re-establishing a full democracy after last
month's much criticized presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was one of several offered by the two officials,
including ensuring the independence of the judiciary, guaranteeing
access of the opposition to the media, establishing an independent
human rights commission and returning a television network to an
owner who was stripped of his property by the courts after critical
news broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy of Canada and Secretary General
Cesar Gaviria of the OAS came as heads of a three-day mission sent
here by the regional organization following two rounds of
presidential elections in April and May that were characterized by
dirty tricks during the campaign and a questionable count of
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The two officials stopped short of satisfying the opposition's
demand for new elections, but its insistence that Fujimori limit
the powers of his intelligence services in the political process
created some friction in meetings with senior officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country has to put a limit on what the intelligence
services can do,'' said Gaviria in an interview Thursday night,
``and put into better balance security and the rights of
individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior officials, who spoke on condition that they not be
identified, said the two officials pressed Fujimori to remove
Vladimiro Montesinos, his intelligence chief, from power as a
necessary step to improve Peru's international standing. They said
they had the explicit support of the Clinton administration in
making the proposal, but they added that it was too early to gauge
the Peruvian government's reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Montesinos is believed to have been the mastermind of a smear
campaign of several presidential candidates in the tabloid press,
as well as a campaign of harassment of opposition candidates and
election observers. Though he was cashiered as an army officer for
alleged espionage in the 1970s, Montesinos has enormous influence
over the military. He handpicked top army commanders in the months
prior to the election and Fujimori recently said he retained close
communications with the CIA and Drug Enforcement Administration on
matters of security and the fight against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS mission told both the government and opposition that
they must enter a dialogue to rebuild the judiciary, Congress and
other democratic institutions. Alejandro Toledo, the opposition
presidential candidate who charged fraud and dropped out of the
race a week before the May 28 runoff, said he was ready to talk. A
presidential commission appointed by Fujimori put out a statement
Thursday saying, ``The government accepts discussion of these
themes with the political community and civil society.''
</P>
<P>
   Axworthy responded with cautious optimism Thursday night to the
responses of both sides. ``It's not bad for the first day,'' he
said in an interview. ``It took God seven days to create the world
and we've been here only two.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials said a permanent OAS mission would monitor and
facilitate talks between the government and opposition and attempt
to set timetables to guarantee results. One senior Canadian
official, for instance, said officials had a goal to overhaul the
government's election-counting apparatus by the 2002 municipal
elections.
</P>
<P>
   But Peruvian officials publicly rejected any timetables. ``We
are not going to establish a schedule, never,'' said Foreign
Minister Fernando de Trazegnies.
</P>
<P>
   There have been street demonstrations throughout the delegation
visit, several of which were broken up by police with tear gas.
Toledo led a march Wednesday night on the luxury hotel where the
delegation was staying. At least five people were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo urged the delegation to reject the legitimacy of the
presidential elections. ``I come to ask the OAS mission publicly,''
he told a rally, ``do not close your eyes to an illegitimate
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, a business professor, plans to lead a large march late
next month with the goal of blocking Fujimori's July 28
inauguration to a third term.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
