u f BC-AIRLINES-HOTWIRE-NYT &LR;      06-29 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-HOTWIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICELINE SHARES FALL AS AIRLINES PLAN TO INVEST IN A RIVAL WEB
SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares in Priceline.com dropped 8.4 percent Thursday after a
report that six major airlines planned to invest in a competing Web
site for customers looking for discounts on plane tickets online.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported Thursday that UAL's United
Airlines, AMR's American Airlines, Northwest Airlines, Continental
Airlines, US Airways and America West Airlines had invested in
Hotwire.com, a San Francisco start-up scheduled to begin operating
this fall. Hotwire has $75 million in financing, primarily from the
Texas Pacific Group, a private investment firm that has owned
stakes in Continental and America West.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline shares closed at $36.8125 each, down $3.375, in Nasdaq
trading. The stock is down 69 percent from its 52-week high of
$119.
</P>
<P>
   Isakowitz Tomas, an analyst with Janney Montgomery Scott, cut
the stock from a ``buy'' recommendation to ``accumulate,'' citing
continuing concern about the valuation as well as the impending
competition from Hotwire. Other analysts said the market had
overreacted. Eighteen of the 19 analysts following the stock still
rate it either a ``buy'' or ``strong buy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors still haven't learned that just having some cash,
some partners and a press release does not make a leader,'' said
Lauren Levitan, an analyst with Robertson Stephens. ``What makes a
leader is getting out there and executing on a business plan day
after day. Priceline is two years old, on the verge of break-even
or profitability, and we do have ample evidence of their
executional capability.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Priceline, Hotwire will sell so-called distressed
inventory, seats that would otherwise go empty and that are not
published on industry-wide sites like Travelocity.com and
Expedia.com. Unlike Priceline, which requires users to bid for
seats and accept the lowest fare offered, Hotwire will let them
select an actual fare for the desired route. As with Priceline, the
identity of the carrier, and the precise timing and routing,
whether nonstop, or connecting, will be concealed until purchase.
</P>
<P>
   One big risk for Hotwire is that if it makes the process too
easy, it could undercut the airlines' sales of full-fare tickets to
business travelers, which are the source of most of their profits.
Because Priceline makes the consumer go through various hurdles to
get a discounted seat, it has reduced that risk for the carriers.
Although only Delta Air Lines was on board when Priceline began,
United, American and US Airways all joined in December and have
minority equity stakes in the company.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines have already banded together in a fare site for
leisure travelers, Orbitz.com, which is also scheduled to begin
this fall. Delta, United, Northwest, Continental and American will
take part in Orbitz, which is expected to offer fares similar to
the deep discount tickets available on the airlines' own sites.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline said it expected no negative impact from Hotwire, and
noted that its airline service had grown sharply in recent weeks.
All eight major full-service U.S. airlines now work with Priceline,
as well as over 20 brand-name international carriers. Priceline now
sells more than 80,000 tickets a week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
