u i BC-U.N.-CRIMINAL-COURT-N     06-29 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-CRIMINAL-COURT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WINS A COMPROMISE ON WAR CRIMES TRIBUNAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United States won an agreement Thursday to
keep the door open to further talks on its demand that no American
official or soldier be surrendered to the world's first permanent
court for war crimes as long as Washington has not signed the
treaty creating the court.
</P>
<P>
   European and other nations are determined to keep the United
States from being frozen out of the biggest change in international
law in decades. With their help, the Clinton administration's
ambassador at large for war crimes, David Scheffer, won an
agreement letting his delegation return to the final round of
negotiations on the form and functions of the court, in November.
Without the deal Thursday, the United States' participation would
have ended.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was immediately criticized by many independent legal
experts and official delegates here, who say that no exceptions
should be made for the United States. Exempting Americans, they
argue, only opens the way for officials of other nations _ some of
them ruled by dictators _ to avoid prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The United States voted against the creation of the tribunal,
the International Criminal Court, two years ago because the
Pentagon and a Republican-controlled Congress had opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   The court will deal with war crimes, crimes against humanity and
genocide. In principle, the court will have universal jurisdiction,
regardless of which countries voted for the treaty to form it. That
power makes Washington nervous, believing that it would be
vulnerable to unfair or frivolous prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Scheffer said the United States would take the criticism into
account and try to devise safeguards as it prepares for further
negotiations. In the meantime, he said, it is important for the
United States to stay involved with the court as it comes into
operation over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world needs a permanent international criminal court,'' he
said in an interview with several reporters Thursday. ``We need it
because the perpetrators of these heinous crimes must be brought to
justice, and we need it as a deterrent over the generations that
follow. The international system simply cannot continue to deal
with these problems in an ad hoc manner indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This court has tremendous potential for being a vehicle for
international justice, and we want to be able to see that
potential,'' he said. ``We should be able to assist the court and
cooperate with it when it's in our national interest to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scheffer, who helped create war crimes tribunals for the
Balkans and Rwanda, is in danger of being hamstrung over the next
few months by a bill recently introduced in the Senate by Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., and John W. Warner, R-Va., that seeks to block any
American cooperation with the International Criminal Court as long
as the United States does not sign and ratify the treaty. Helms,
chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, has vowed never
to allow ratification.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clearly a locomotive coming down on us,'' Scheffer said
of the bill Thursday. ``But I would hope that the locomotive stops,
because it's recognized that we are making progress in these
negotiations to achieve the very objective that is behind this
legislation. It is a counterintuitive piece of legislation because
it is undermining the very negotiating efforts that we are
undertaking to achieve the objective that we all agree must be
achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, delegates from more than 100 nations who have been
meeting here for three weeks are expected to approve two main
components of the court's business, the rules of procedure and a
document called ``the elements of crimes.'' These elements are a
compendium of legal definitions that Scheffer called a checklist
for prosecutors considering indictments.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, which once spoke more forcefully for
membership in the court, was instrumental in calling for more
specific criteria for war crimes, genocide and crimes against
humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before have war crimes and crimes against humanity and
genocide been defined with such precision as we now have in the
elements of crimes,'' Scheffer said. ``This will be the document
that guides prosecutors not only in the ICC but also in national
and military courts for decades to come.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``And defense counsel will look at this document to
determine where exactly their rights are in the defense of their
clients with respect to any particular crime. It's a truly historic
document. We invested a tremendous amount of our talent in it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a November-December session, the last at which countries that
do not sign the treaty establishing the court will have the right
to participate in its affairs, the United States will argue for a
provision that allows specifically for an exemption from
prosecution. The accord reached Thursday generally paved the way
for that debate by raising the general question of international
agreements outside the court's treaty.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, another American official was more cautious than
Scheffer in welcoming the move. ``Proponents of the court are
certainly not speaking for the American people,'' the official
said. ``It is inconceivable that the American people would support
the hauling of an American official before a court that is not
accountable to the American government when we are not party to the
underlying treaty. Ultimately, we're going to have to address this
more fundamental question.''
</P>
</TEXT>
