<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES AND ROCKER TAKE THE FIRST ROUND AT SHEA
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He is 6 feet 4 inches, but he may as well have been
80 feet tall Thursday night, the way his presence loomed over the
field like the billboard snaking up the light tower behind the Shea
Stadium bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Braves relief pitcher John Rocker _ two years in the
majors, 25 on the planet _ was the reason a combined total of more
than 1,000 reporters and police officers showed up for a June ball
game. And he was the man 46,998 fans most wanted to see.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves took a four-run lead midway through the game _
perhaps too wide a lead for a late-inning specialist like Rocker.
When Braves manager Bobby Cox called for Jason Marquis as his first
reliever, the fans chanted, ``We Want Rocker!''
</P>
<P>
   They had seen him only on video before the game, when the Mets
replayed his pre-game statement in which he apologized for his
offensive ranting in a December magazine article. They booed then,
and they stood and shouted when Rocker bolted from the bullpen
before the bottom of the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   His assignment was to protect the Braves' 6-4 lead, and as
usual, Rocker sprinted in. He was leaving the sanctuary the Mets
and the city had created _ a roof over the bullpen bench and mound
_ and with debris pelting the field as he ran, Rocker looked like a
soldier on a suicide mission through enemy territory.
</P>
<P>
   But he reached his destination safely, and there he won his war.
As the crowd chanted at him profanely, Rocker fell behind in the
count to Robin Ventura. But he came back, heaving 94 mph fastballs
that Ventura could not hit. Strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Zeile grounded out. So did Jay Payton. And that was that.
Calmly _ and with no more objects flying toward him _ Rocker had
set down the Mets' 5-6-7 hitters in order in a crucial spot.
</P>
<P>
   He walked off the mound slowly and slapped high-fives with
several teammates as he descended the steps into the third base
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Ligtenberg came on to save the 6-4 victory for the Braves
in the ninth, and the Mets' seven-game winning streak ended. The
Braves increased their lead in the National League East to three
games.
</P>
<P>
   The drama of Rocker's inning notwithstanding, the opener of the
four-game series did not display the quality of baseball expected
from the teams with the two best records in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' starter, the right-hander Rick Reed, fractured his
left wrist on a line drive and also strained a calf muscle. The
Braves' scheduled starter, Greg Maddux, was ill and never left the
hotel. The winning team made three errors. The losing team's
All-Star catcher lost track of the outs.
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga tripled in a run in the first inning, the ball
eluding a charging Jay Payton, but Reed seemed in control after
retiring the first two Braves in the third. Then Andruw Jones came
up and smacked a liner off Reed's glove that went for an infield
single.
</P>
<P>
   It got worse. Chipper Jones tripled off the right field wall,
and Galarraga followed with a 414-foot, opposite-field home run off
a billboard in right. The Braves were up, 4-0, and after Reed got
the final out, he was through for the night _ and perhaps a while
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who missed a start in April when a line drive bruised his
glove hand, will have the wrist re-examined Friday. The severity of
the calf strain was not immediately known, but Mets starter Bobby
J. Jones missed a month with that injury earlier this season, and
Reed missed three weeks with it last year.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, the four-time Cy Young award winner, was replaced by
John Burkett, a journeyman released this spring by the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays. Maddux will start Saturday, when Burkett was scheduled
to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett faced a lineup that included seven .300 hitters, but he
held the Mets hitless his first time through the order. Melvin Mora
reached base on a two-out error in the third, and a walk and an
infield hit loaded the bases for Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza singled, bringing in two runs and giving him 12 games in
a row with at least one run batted in. The last National Leaguer
with a streak that long was the Cardinals' Rip Collins in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura came up next, but he struck out looking with runners at
first and third, ending the inning.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Reed had thrown his last pitch, and Pat Mahomes came on
to start the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's role was the one in which Mahomes is used most,
but if Mahomes can be used in a right-handed set-up role in tandem
with Turk Wendell, he could eliminate that need for the Mets as
they explore trades. If the Mets could count on Mahomes in the late
innings, they could then promote from within _ perhaps Grant
Roberts or Paul Wilson _ to fill the long-relief role.
</P>
<P>
   But Mahomes has been wild this year, and his one-out walk to
Chipper Jones put runners on first and second with one out in the
fifth. Mahomes then struck out Galarraga, but Piazza thought it was
the third out, and began to walk off with the ball. Mahomes shouted
at him, but Piazza could not hear him, perhaps because of a plane
taking off overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones took third and scored the Braves' fifth run when
Brain Jordan singled up the middle.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
