<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9034 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-NY     06-29 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACK AD PUTS CLINTON ON THE DEFENSE AS RIVAL ACCUSES HER OF
HYPOCRISY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the last two weeks, Hillary Rodham Clinton has
attacked Rep. Rick Lazio for missing a vote in Congress to create a
home-heating oil reserve so he could fly back home to campaign in
New York. The measure failed by two votes, a point Clinton has made
in speeches and television advertisements belittling her opponent
in the race for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign acknowledged Thursday that on the night of
the vote, she was at the side of another errant New York
representative, Eliot Engel, a Bronx Democrat who had left
Washington early to tend to his own political needs: a fund-raiser
in Westchester. And Lazio seized the information Thursday,
attacking Clinton as a ``hypocrite'' and demanding that she stop
running ads attacking him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just the height of political chutzpah to go on the
attack, air commercials, and pretend that she had a role other than
what she had,'' Lazio said in a telephone call from Washington.
``Obviously the entire attack on her part was disingenuous. I think
it goes back to the central question of truth and truthfulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge question of hypocrisy here,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers said the first lady had been unaware that the
vote was going on when she appeared at Engel's fund-raiser on June
15, and Engel said he, too, was unaware of the vote that night.
Clinton's spokesman, Howard Wolfson, said Clinton first learned
that the fund-raiser coincided with the vote from a campaign
briefing column that appeared in Newsday on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson, who declined to say when he learned of the confluence
of the Engel fund-raiser and the vote, said that the first lady had
no intention of ending her attacks or withdrawing the television
commercial in question. He scoffed at Lazio's labeling of Clinton
as a hypocrite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ad would have gone up and it is definitely staying up,''
Wolfson said. ``He still hasn't apologized for missing the vote.
He's a member of Congress. You're supposed to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview, Engel pointedly declined to back the
Clinton campaign's point of view. He said he did not believe Lazio
had done anything wrong, and that House Republican leaders were to
blame for changing the schedule without notifying members.
</P>
<P>
   Engel said he had left Washington in mid-afternoon after being
assured by the Republican leadership that Congress would adjourn by
6 p.m. As it turned out, the House stayed in session into the
night.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought Clinton's criticism of Lazio was fair, Engel
responded: ``I don't know _ you know, that's a Senate campaign;
they've got to resolve that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not critical of anyone for missing that vote,'' Engel
continued. ``I think any vote that comes up after 6 p.m., when they
tell you it's going to be over at 6 p.m. _ people set up
alternative things to do. I criticize the Republican leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio took the 9 p.m. shuttle back to New York that night in
order to be on the ground Friday morning for a day of campaigning.
The disclosure that he missed the vote has become an issue both
because of the closeness of the outcome and because he has been
attacking the Clinton administration for escalating fuel costs. The
missed vote has not only given Clinton a campaign issue, but will
also make it more difficult for Lazio to leave Washington while
Congress is in session so he can tend to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Lazio's aides reacted with relief upon learning
where Clinton had been that night, and moved quickly to try to
stoke media interest in the report. ``Scoop city!'' Mike Murphy,
Lazio's chief media adviser, said in a voice mail message left for
a reporter. ``This is a huge hypocrite thing. She's running a TV ad
on it. We demand that she pull it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Lazio said he could not recall whether he knew
the vote was about to happen when he left Washington. (An aide
later called to say that Lazio had been told it was possible, but
not certain, that it was going to come up.)
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he did not believe that Clinton was unaware of
Engel's missing the vote when she began attacking Lazio for being
absent. ``It's plain she knew about it before she was airing attack
ads.''
</P>
</TEXT>
