<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9036 &Cx1f; tth-z
U a BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-SPI &LR;      06-29 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA LIFTS THREAT OF STIFF SANCTION AGAINST ALASKA AIRLINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TRACY JOHNSON and PAUL NYHAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Satisfied with Alaska Airlines' plan to fix its maintenance
practices, federal officials Thursday lifted their threat of a
stiff sanction that could have forced the airline to ground planes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Federal Aviation Administration also vowed to scrutinize
each plane leaving Alaska's maintenance hangars in coming weeks,
and it will carefully monitor the airline's progress in coming
months.
</P>
<P>
   The agency earlier this month threatened to strip the airline's
authority to do heavy maintenance, a sanction never before imposed
on a major carrier. The FAA gave Alaska seven days prove it was
fixing problems, such as incomplete maintenance records and unclear
repair procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Word came Thursday that the Seattle-based airline had passed the
test.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska executives, pleased their plan got the FAA's nod, said
they were already looking ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge before us is to implement this plan, and we're
really well on our way to doing that,'' said Alaska President Bill
Ayer. ``It's now up to us to assure the FAA, ourselves and our
passengers.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA launched an intensive safety audit of Alaska Airlines in
April, five weeks after Alaska Flight 261 plummeted into the
Pacific Ocean off the southern California coast, killing all 88
people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Problems found during that audit spurred the agency to take a
closer look at the nation's nine other major carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The final report on Alaska Airlines, released Thursday, details
more than 50 findings. The shortcomings range from general to
specific, from management positions left vacant to ignored
maintenance manuals to missing signatures on paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   The report notes that Alaska has a fleet of fairly new planes
and a dedicated workforce, but said there ``seems to be a basic
lack of understanding regarding the complexity of operating (an)
airline of this size.''
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials say they found no instances where unsafe planes
were flown.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska has until July 12 to respond to the report. The FAA could
still sanction the airline in other ways, and Ayer acknowledged
there are ``very likely to be some fines.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline's chief executive officer, John Kelly, said Alaska
``tried to go above and beyond'' the FAA's expectation in
correcting flaws. One priority was to hire more people, and the
airline has already filled about 80 of 130 new slots in its
maintenance and engineering department.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska has also revamped its general maintenance manual, which
the FAA criticized for being unclear, incomplete and ignored by
workers.
</P>
<P>
   And the company has appointed a new vice president of safety,
leading an 11-member safety team, and tripled its staff of
quality-assurance auditors.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials said Alaska is headed in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, the plan looks good,'' said Nick Lacey, director of
the FAA's Flight Standards Service in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Lacey said FAA inspectors will keep a close eye on Alaska until
mid-July, inspecting the paperwork for each plane as it is released
for flight after heavy maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   FAA inspectors will return to Alaska maintenance facilities
three months later, and six months after that. The agency wants to
ensure Alaska's plan is working.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll come back and look again and again,'' Lacey said.
``Should we not like what we find, we will not hesitate to take
stronger action.''
</P>
<P>
   As teams of FAA inspectors begin conducting ``white glove''
safety inspections on other carriers beginning July 17, they will
also be looking at the way their own agency does business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audit in April found things that should have been found in
routine, day-to-day inspections,'' said FAA spokesman Paul
Takemoto.
</P>
<P>
   Although Alaska won a reprieve from the potentially crippling
sanction, its stock dropped in trading yesterday, falling $1.625,
to $26.56, or 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The stock took a tumble because the company is still battling
rising oil prices and because of a broader drop in the financial
markets, a financial analyst said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell roughly 1.2 percent
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally this (FAA announcement) would have given it a shot in
the arm,'' said Raymond Neidl, an analyst who tracks Alaska Air
Group Inc. for ING Barings. ``There are other things going on in
the short term.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock price _ near its 12-month low of $25.50 _
isn't likely to attract anyone hoping to buy the nation's
10th-largest carrier, Neidl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they (other airlines) have their thoughts in other
places right now,'' Neidl said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Alaska plans to add 19 new Boeing 737s to its fleet in
the next two years, Ayer says executives are more concerned with
fixing problems than with growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are, frankly, not going to grow the company very
aggressively until we feel like we have got a strong foundation
built,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And troubles still loom over the airline, which has been the
subject of federal scrutiny, criminal investigations and intense
publicity this year.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury in San Francisco is investigating whether
maintenance records were falsified in Alaska's Oakland hangar. No
indictments have been handed up, but the FAA investigated the same
allegations and recommended three maintenance supervisors lose
their licenses.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury recently broadened its investigation to the
handling of the plane that crashed, ordering Alaska to hand over
all of its maintenance paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board's crash investigation
is continuing, focusing on the MD-83's jackscrew assembly. The
plane's pilots reported a jammed horizontal stabilizer, which is
moved by the jackscrew to control the plane's angle of flight.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance workers in Oakland planned to replace the plane's
jackscrew assembly in 1997, then determined its parts, while worn,
were within allowable limits.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bright, often unflattering spotlight on the company,
Alaska officials say many passengers are standing by the airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airplanes are full,'' Ayer said. ``Looking at the numbers,
there's no evidence of an adverse impact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
