<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WATERPOLO-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYNN PLAYS THROUGH THE PAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The throbbing shoulders, particularly the right
one, with which he has fired a water polo ball for the past 27
years, don't waste many opportunities to explain to Robert Lynn
what toll the sport has taken on his body.
</P>
<P>
   And when the shoulders aren't complaining, maybe it's his aching
back or a knee which suffered cartilage damage that made hit
difficult for him to move his legs to keep himself above the water.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, stopping because of the pain doesn't seem to be an option
for the 33-year-old Lynn, a native of Long Beach, graduate of
Wilson High and USC, the second-oldest player currently on the U.S.
National team and longtime veteran of the professional leagues in
Greece, Italy, Croatia and France. Which begs the natural question
- why not let your body say it's time to quit?
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2, 200-pound Lynn likens the situation to a marriage.
Even a person who loves their spouse, Lynn reckons, is caused some
pain by their partner. But the anquish is not enough reason to end
the marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water polo, for me, is like a marriage,'' Lynn said. ``I love
playing too much to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   That logic shouldn't be surprising from a guy who learned to
swim at three and first played water polo at six. He was an
All-American and CIF Southern Section 4-A co-player of the year as
a senior in 1985 as a senior at Wilson and blossomed into one of
the country's best players as a four-time All-American at USC.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the U.S. national team in 1989 and, particularly
offensively, made an immediate impact. He had a team-leading 11
goals in the 1990 World Championships, trailed only teammate Chris
Humbert in goals during the 1991 French Open and was an integral
member of the FINA World Cup title team.
</P>
<P>
   The logical next step, Lynn figured, was to be one of 13 players
who traveled to Barcelona for the 1992 Olympic Games. That,
however, was a step that never came. When then-head coach Bill
Barnett selected his team, Lynn was not a member.
</P>
<P>
   ``It crushed me,'' said Lynn, who was 25 at the time. ``I can't
express the pain. I don't think he realized he changed an important
aspect of the team. I was a three-year starter. But how could I say
to him, you're wrong? When you're (25), how do you convince a
50-year-old man that he needs me?''
</P>
<P>
   Time hasn't answered those questions, but it has, at least
partially, healed old wounds. Lynn says he still doesn't understand
the decision but he's learned to accept it and respects Barnett,
who is serving as the video/scout coach currently for the U.S.
team.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the 1992 Olympics, Lynn began his professional
water polo life with a club team in France. That lasted two years
and included a pair of league championships. He left there to try
another shot at playing with the U.S. National team, but that
didn't work out and he moved to Italy.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly two years in Italy, he moved to the powerful
Croatian leagues, where the crowds are big and vocal and the
players are considered celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, that was the highest level,'' said Lynn, the Croatian
Cup MVP in 1996. ``At that level, there was at least 10 solid teams
you had to beat. The other leagues there were probably four or five
teams and the others we would kill.''
</P>
<P>
   From there he moved to Greece for a year and has spent the past
two years back in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the European lifestyle,'' said Lynn, who added that he
would like to live somewhere in Europe, probably coaching water
polo, when his playing days are over.
</P>
<P>
   However, he also missed climbing out of the pool after a game
and hugging his parents. Or looking up into the stands to see his
grandmother and friends in the crowd. And there was also the
Olympic dream still burning in his soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always joyful for me to play in front of my family,''
said Lynn, who comes home only for Christmas and in the summer. ``I
had gone so long playing away from home. It's funny, but there was
nowhere I felt more like a stranger than at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn approached U.S. National coach John Vargas about the chance
of joining the team. Vargas, who was a national teammate of Lynn's
from 1989-92, agreed to give him a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Robert came to the team in the late 1980's he was a great
offensive talent,'' Vargas said. ``He still is, but he has matured
and is much more of a complete and team player than he once was.''
</P>
<P>
   His former style as a player - which was to shoot first - was
born of necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches I had gave me a green light to do what I wanted,''
Lynn said. ``That was my role. I wasn't just that I was a ball hog.
I was told to shoot a lot and attack a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   His style as a person saw him grow mature with the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was young, hyper and out of control in a way,'' Lynn
admitted. ``I've done a lot of growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   With his new style, which is a two-meter defender with an
offensive threat, Lynn has fit well into the U.S. national team
system. He helped the team win a gold medal at the 1999 Pan
American Games and was on the third place squad in last year's UPS
Cup in Newport Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn, who is older than everyone on the prospective Olympic
squad but 34-year-old Kyle Kopp, is a good fit on a team full of
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has a lot of guys who have played together for a
long time,'' said Chris Humbert, a 30-year-old two-meter man, who
is perhaps the team's best player. ``We've all paid our dues but
its time to do something good.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn has been a solid contributor during the current UPS
International Cup, which began on Tuesday and concludes on Sunday
at the U.S. National Aquatics Center in Los Alamitos. He had the
final goal in a 7-7 tie with Australia in the opener and
contributed a key goal in a 11-9 victory over Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he'll see if his recent efforts are enough to land him on
the U.S. team which will represent the country in Sydney in
September. Vargas will announce the 13-man team in late July.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is a good coach and an honest man,'' Lynn said. ``I'm
grateful he's given me a chance. I've kept the Olympic dream in
place for the last 12 years. But, you know, it won't kill me if it
doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   With our without Sydney, Lynn will pack his bags and head back
to Europe to continue playing the sport that has been his life. He
would love to be able to take an Olympic experience home and it
would been even nicer to carry a medal with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wonderful to finish off the dream,'' Lynn said.
``When it's over, I still be playing. I'll probably still play
until my arm falls off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-00 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
