u k BC-EDIT-MEXICO-NYT &LR;      06-29 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MEXICO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WATCHING MEXICO'S ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, June 30:
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's presidential election Sunday will determine the outcome
of a very tight race between Francisco Labastida, of the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, and his center-right
rival, Vicente Fox. The vote will also be a test of how far Mexico
has progressed from the fraud-tainted elections of the recent past.
The close contest makes it imperative that all aspects of the
voting and ballot counting be scrupulously fair and transparent.
</P>
<P>
   The policy differences separating the two leading contenders are
relatively minor, particularly on issues concerning the United
States. Both Labastida and Fox are broadly pro-trade and
pro-business and would work comfortably with Washington on border
and drug issues. The third major candidate, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas,
from the center-left, is given no realistic chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   A victory by Fox would dislodge the PRI from the presidency for
the first time since the party was formed by the victorious
generals of the Mexican Revolution 71 years ago. Such change is
overdue and would be a healthy development for Mexican democracy.
But a Labastida victory can also serve democracy if it is achieved
fairly.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past dozen years Mexico has made important strides
toward cleaning up its elections. A new, independent electoral
institute has been created to oversee the campaigning and assure an
honest count. Lists of eligible voters have been compiled and photo
identification cards issued to all qualified voters. Opposition
parties now have a better chance to get out their messages and more
confidence that voter choices will be respected.
</P>
<P>
   But serious problems remain, including the PRI's unchecked
ability to use government spending to support Labastida's candidacy
and the pervasive pro-government bias of most local broadcast and
print media. Some local PRI operatives have been posing as
``independent'' poll monitors or have intimidated voters with fears
that they will lose jobs or benefits if they fail to vote for the
PRI. Such behavior tarnishes Labastida's campaign and will
undermine his legitimacy if he wins. He must make every effort to
bring it to a halt. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
