<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE AIDS EPIDEMIC IN AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, June 30:
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations' prediction this week that about half of all
15-year-olds in AIDS-plagued African countries will eventually die
of AIDS is the latest measure of the devastating impact of the
epidemic on the African continent. It is difficult to imagine what
kind of future may be in store for countries if half of their adult
populations will have died of the disease within coming decades.
</P>
<P>
   There are 16 African countries with critical infection levels.
This is a true emergency that requires vigorous action by the
countries affected and a greater flow of international aid and
expertise from the industrialized nations. Although American aid
has been increasing and some drug companies have slashed their
prices for AIDS drugs, more money is needed to buy medicine, build
up medical facilities and conduct research.
</P>
<P>
   But the most immediate need is education and prevention
programs, which are severely lacking in countries like Botswana
where stereotypes and misinformation about AIDS facilitate its
spread. UNAIDS has reported considerable success in Uganda and
Senegal, where advertising campaigns and educational efforts have
lowered infection rates. The key to such improvements is
recognition by the African governments that the AIDS crisis is a
priority. Domestic commitment and international support are
critical to saving Africa's next generation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
