<HEADER>
A9049 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-ROCKER-NYT &LR;      06-29 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE WATCH AS FANS JUST BOO ROCKER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Rocker walked out of a side entrance of the
Atlanta Braves' midtown hotel Thursday afternoon and was quickly
escorted into an unmarked police van that would take him first to
the players association headquarters and later to Shea Stadium. So
began the pitcher's first day in the city he so notoriously
insulted in a magazine article last December, a day that ended
without any ugly incidents and with Rocker contributing to the
Braves' 6-4 victory over the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The use of the police van was one of dozens of measures that New
York police officials and Mets management took Thursday in the
hopes of keeping Rocker's presence from leading to any incidents
outside the stadium or in it. Police officers were stationed
outside the Braves' hotel, the Grand Hyatt, on East 42nd Street in
Manhattan, from the moment the Braves arrived in a bus from the
airport early Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Those police were part of a contingent of more than 700 officers
deployed at the team hotel, along the Flushing subway line and at
Shea Stadium because of concerns about Rocker's safety, New York
officials said. City officials were relieved on Wednesday when
baseball officials sent assurances that Rocker would back down from
his vow to ride the No. 7 train _ the one Rocker had singled out
for verbal abuse in Sports Illustrated in December _ to Thursday
night's game against the Mets. But those assurances did not mute
the police presence.
</P>
<P>
   The department's bomb squad arrived at Shea about 2:30 p.m.,
followed by police officers carrying bags with sharp-shooting
rifles. Officers on horseback were in the stadium's parking lot,
while others in plainclothes mingled around the stadium. A unit of
officers with video cameras took positions in case of mayhem. It
seemed as if the Police Department was preparing for the arrival of
the president, and not the presence of a 25-year-old left-handed
reliever who has alienated many of his own teammates with the
uproar he has created with his derogatory comments toward gays and
immigrants and just about anyone not like Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy police presence seemed to work. Rocker was booed when
he first came on the field before the game and again when the Mets
played a videotape, on the scoreboard, of an apologetic statement
he made at a brief press gathering about 50 minutes before the game
started. But there were no incidents _ before the game or during
it. Rocker himself took part in the Braves' pre-game warm-up on the
field and even autographed a few baseballs. There were some insults
hurled his way, but nothing more. By 8 p.m., an hour into the game,
the police had sent 100 officers home.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as the game proceeded, the police made sure its presence
was known. Between half innings, about eight police officers stood
on each foul line, facing the crowd. Police officers were visible
in the back of the newly barricaded visitors' bullpen, where Rocker
was situated, and in the left-field bleachers adjacent to the
bullpen. There were fears the bullpen would be bombarded with
flying objects, but peace prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, in the eighth inning, Rocker entered the game, with
just one object _ a rubber ball _ apparently being thrown his way.
Amid derisive chants, but nothing more, he proceeded to strike out
Robin Ventura and retire Todd Zeile and Jay Payton on ground balls.
He walked off the field with his head up, seeming to fight the urge
to flash the smirk that was so familiar when he clashed with Mets
fans in last year's postseason.
</P>
<P>
   During his pre-game statement, Rocker seemed to make an effort
to be humble, flashed a grin or two, said that most New Yorkers
were ``extremely charismatic, although a bit spirited'' and
apologized several times for all the negative remarks he has made.
Braves officials said that Rocker had written the statement
himself, scribbling it on a piece of paper in his hotel room at 2
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, Rocker also said that he was ``happy to be
back in New York'' and that it was unfortunate that ``the situation
has continued to escalate.'' He asked reporters _ more than 300 are
here for the four-game series _ to refrain from asking questions
about anything other than baseball. Rocker spent the early part of
his day in the hotel. At about 12:30 p.m. he took an unmarked
police van to the players' union headquarters. Hours later, he
returned to the hotel, and at about 4:30 p.m. _ back in the van _
he arrived at Shea. Rocker is being shadowed by an Atlanta police
lieutenant, and the police want to limit his itinerary while he is
here.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they are successful remains to be seen. Before the game,
several dozen fans took part in an anti-Rocker rally outside Shea,
but hundreds of other fans walked right past, with any number
saying the whole Rocker situation had been blown out of proportion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
